<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-DRUNK-CAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: OVERKILL ON DRUKEN DRIVING 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesda, Feb. 24:
</P>
<P>
   New York City's mayor, Rudolph Giuliani, and the police
commissioner, Howard Safir, cannot be faulted for wanting to crack
down on drunken driving. In the hands of someone who is
intoxicated, a car is a deadly weapon aimed at members of the
public. Still, the sweeping new plan to confiscate the cars of
virtually everyone arrested for drunken driving within city limits
seems overly broad. It ought to be possible to have strict law
enforcement without one-size-fits-all justice.
</P>
<P>
   We would like to see stiffer punishments for drunken driving,
including more confiscations where appropriate. But there has to be
room for legislative and judicial input. Giuliani argues that
judges already have powers to overrule confiscations, and he
estimated that two or three out of every 10 seized cars would be
returned to their owners. He believes that the imposition of an
inflexible-looking basic policy has big advantages in public
education.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that New Yorkers are beginning to complain about
what looks like bullying law enforcement. Also, making officers
appear to be part of the punishment process threatens to undermine
public regard for a force that has done a good job of reducing
crime. Under the crackdown, which got under way this week, officers
will continue to seize the car of anyone arrested for driving while
intoxicated and found to have a blood alcohol level at or above the
legal limit of .10. Generally, the city will then hold the vehicle
while it initiates a forfeiture proceeding. The owner will have to
go to Civil Court to try to get it back, which may not happen even
if he is acquitted in the drunken-driving case.
</P>
<P>
   The constitutionality of such seizures is uncertain. For legal
authority the city cites a provision of its administrative code
that gives police the power to seize property that is the
``instrumentality'' of a crime. The city can plausibly argue that
the cars of drunken drivers fit that broad definition, since
driving with high blood alcohol levels is by definition a crime
that requires a vehicle in order to commit it. The plan would be
unlikely to offend the present forfeiture-friendly U.S. Supreme
Court. But New York's top court, the Court of Appeals, will
probably be more skeptical about pre-conviction forfeitures.
</P>
<P>
   In practice, the mayor's approach may turn out to be less rigid
than it appears. In the case of a repeat offender, or an egregious
case of a first-time offender involved in an accident or driving
with a blood alcohol level way above the state's already high
limit, loss of a vehicle can be a reasonable cost of protecting
public safety. But that approach seems too sweeping for first-time
offenders who were lucky enough not to have caused any injury or
are later acquitted of the criminal charges. In such cases, judges
will still have some general discretion to avoid inflicting
disproportionate punishment on the defendant. But their power to do
so is murky.
</P>
<P>
   The city says it wants to avoid hurting innocent third parties.
In some cases it may allow an innocent spouse who jointly owns a
vehicle to keep the car. In other cases, innocent co-owners may
petition for half the proceeds from the vehicle's sale. But that
may not be sufficient to avoid major hardship for some families,
including the loss of employment as a result of the vehicle's
confiscation.
</P>
<P>
   We are sympathetic to the hard line taken by those who have lost
loved ones to drunken drivers. But New York City and state have
legislative and judicial bodies that need to be brought in to
produce law-enforcement solutions that will enjoy broad public
support. Stern executive edicts are part of running a complex city
like New York, but they are not the answer to every problem.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
