<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-PREDATORS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODANO'S HAT TRICK KEYS STARS' VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ Stars coach Ken Hitchcock wanted to burn the
game tape. Stars centers Mike Modano and Joe Nieuwendyk wouldn't
mind using it as a training guide.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars last night threw away the shackles of the conservative
hockey endorsed by Hitchcock and defeated the Nashville Predators,
4-3. In their first trip to the NHL's newest expansion city, the
Stars rallied from a 3-1 third-period deficit _ the first time this
season they have come back in the third period to post a victory.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, Nieuwendyk scored his 800th career point and
Modano, who had a hat trick, scored his 300th career goal. It was
night of milestones as the Stars recorded a season-high 45 shots
and both teams combined for a season high of 77.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was good for us,'' Hitchcock confessed, his heart still
racing from the NASCAR-like pace of the game. ``Holy cow, it was
revved up. But we needed to find a way to beat a goalie who was
standing on his head, and we did that tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory moved the Stars' NHL-best record to 36-10-9, good
for 81 points. They lead the second-place Phoenix Coyotes by 13
points in the Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars outlasted Predators goalie Mike Dunham, who was
spectacular from the opening drop, robbing Tony Hrkac, stoning
Brent Severyn and frustrating Jere Lehtinen _ all in the first six
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars had an 11-2 advantage in shots when Modano scored in
the slot off a smooth feed from Brett Hull for a 1-0 lead at the
9:50 mark of the first period.
</P>
<P>
   After that, however, the Predators electrified their fans and
stunned the Stars, scoring the next three goals _ all against the
line which had the biggest mismatch of the night _ Modano, Hull and
Lehtinen.
</P>
<P>
   Blair Atcheynum scored off a slick feed from Robert Valicevic,
just up from the minors. Then Scott Walker punched in two goals,
the second a spin-o-rama move down the slot that literally had the
Stars shaking their heads with a 3-1 deficit just 37 seconds into
the second period.
</P>
<P>
   But that's when the reconstruction began. Instead of panicking,
Hitchcock and his troops stayed with the same lines and most of the
same pairings.
</P>
<P>
   The second period was a blur as the Stars outshot the Predators,
18-8, but couldn't get anything past Dunham.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' second line of Nieuwendyk, Pat Verbeek and Jamie
Langenbrunner was buzzing all night, finishing with 12 shots. But
they didn't score until Nieuwendyk set up Verbeek for a rebound
goal at the 7:50 mark of the third period, and that changed
everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew if we got the second one, we'd win,'' Modano said.
``Nieuwie's line had been all over it all night, and eventually
they got the one we needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk's assist gave him 391 to go with his 409 career goals
_ and a total of 800 points in 813 games. Modano worked free for
two goals, giving him 300 in his 689th career game. Modano has two
hat tricks in the past three games and three on the season. He had
only four career hat tricks entering the season.
</P>
<P>
   His second goal, to tie the game at the 9:01 mark of the third,
was a fantastic effort as he stole the puck from Jamie Heward,
faked a backhand and slipped a wrister around a fallen Dunham. The
game-winner then came off a perfect feed from Lehtinen, who had
worked his way free on a wraparound attempt and left an open net
for Modano.
</P>
<P>
   Goalie Ed Belfour made several strong stops to hold that lead,
and the Stars left Nashville with one of their most exciting
victories. Now, they get to try to duplicate the result tonight
when the two teams meet in a rematch at Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   So are you ready for another shootout, Brett Hull?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think our coach would be very happy if we did,'' Hull
said, referring to the defensive style that Hitchcock prefers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm burning the tape,'' Hitchcock joked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
