<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-HAWKS-TEX </SLUG>
 
Pack pushes pace, then Mavs hold on 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Aha, so that's how it's supposed to work.
</P>
<P>
   Coming off a 1-6 road trip, the weary Mavericks stumbled onto
their blueprint for victory last night at Reunion Arena, getting an
up-tempo spark from Robert Pack, rugged rebounding from Gary Trent,
shot-blocking intimidation from Shawn Bradley and the key baskets
from Michael Finley in an 89-85 victory over the Atlanta Hawks.
</P>
<P>
   Hold off on the championship parade for now, but the Mavericks
have their first victory over a winning team, two victories in
their past three games, and their first home victory since April
11.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think we can play better, but we found a way to
scratch out a win,'' coach Don Nelson said. ``It would've been
quite a downer to let this one get away.''
</P>
<P>
   They almost did.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks (3-9) saw a 70-53 lead dwindle to 76-75 midway
through the final quarter and to 83-81 with 2:40 remaining. But
Finley drilled a 15-foot jumper from the left baseline for a
four-point lead then made a 20-footer from the right baseline that
barely beat the shot clock and gave the Mavericks an 87-81 lead
with 45 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sooner or later I knew we'd knock down a couple of big
shots,'' said Finley, who scored 16 of his game-high 22 points in
the second half. ``The great thing is I didn't have to create those
shots; my teammates found me. It's a step in the right direction.
Hopefully it will be contagious.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks were coming off an 11-day road trip, but it was
the Hawks who appeared to run out of energy. Playing without
injured leading scorer Steve Smith, Atlanta trailed 47-38 at
halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Pack entered the game with Atlanta leading 15-7 and immediately
energized the Mavericks' offense, hitting two fast-break jumpers
and scoring off a steal from Mookie Blaylock to tie the score at
15. In the second quarter, Pack _ who scored 31 points in the
Mavericks' previous home game 12 days ago _ again raced past
Atlanta's transition defense. His drive-and-dish penetration set up
two Hubert Davis 3-pointers as the Mavericks took control of the
score and the tempo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Robert coming off the bench,'' Nelson said. ``He really
energizes us.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Pack: ``It's the role they've defined for me and if it
helps us win games, then fine. We're a better team when we play
up-tempo, and that's my game.''
</P>
<P>
   While Pack lit Dallas' fire with 15 points and eight assists,
Bradley (nine points, four blocks) occupied Hawks center Dikembe
Mutombo, Trent (12 points, 10 rebounds) did the dirty work and
Finley carried his offensive load by making six of his last seven
shots.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks finish a stretch of seven games in nine days with
three in a row vs. Denver tomorrow, at Utah on Friday and vs.
Sacramento on Saturday. /
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
