A6918 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOG-ATTACKS-LADN     02-24 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOG-ATTACKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIT BULLS ATTACK 2 RESIDENTS IN L.A. NEIGHBORHOOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY YVETTE CABRERA  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles Animal Services officers have captured
two free-roaming pit bull dogs suspected of vicious attacks on
several residents, and officers combed the neighborhood for others.
</P>
<P>
   One man was bitten Monday night as he changed a tire outside his
home in suburban Granada Hills. A second attack occurred in the
same neighorhood where Veronica Arce was walking out of her
mother-in-law's home with her 9-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   The two dogs were found roaming Robert Frost Middle School,
where maintenance workers confined them in a gated area until
Animal Services officers arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not uncommon,'' said Jackie David, spokeswoman for
Animal Services. ``It happens all the time. Dogs attack over food,
sex or territory. We're probably dealing with irresponsible pet
owners.''
</P>
<P>
   From her home, where she was recovering Tuesday, Arce described
how the dogs attacked without warning as she stepped onto the
sidewalk. One of the dogs clamped its teeth onto her arm and
wouldn't let go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, Oh my God, if I don't find a way to defend myself they
will kill me or destroy my arms,'' said Arce, 39, who was bitten
five times on her right arm, once on her left arm and several times
on her right leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I was about to faint,'' said 9-year-old Santiago
Arce, who stayed home from school because of the terrifying
incident.
</P>
<P>
   After Arce screamed for help, two friends inside her
mother-in-law's home came to her rescue, beating the dogs with a
pot to chase they off. She was treated at a hospital and released.
</P>
<P>
   Neither dog had a license, collar or name tag. One pit bull was
a neutered male, which leads officers to believe it has an owner,
said David. The other dog was a female pit bull.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to hold them for a week or two to see if the owner
comes in,'' David said. ``If they don't come in, we're going to
(euthanize) the dogs because they are dangerous and therefore (not
adoptable).''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the city dispatched its Special Enforcement Unit _
three officers devoted solely to capturing the city's estimated
44,000 stray dogs _ and one animal control officer to the
neighborhood to look for other pit bulls.
</P>
<P>
   A resident in the neighborhood said two dogs also attacked her
dog and pulled his head through a fence. Animal Services officers
believe the captured dogs attacked her pet, but they continued to
search for another set of dogs believed to have attacked the man.
</P>
<P>
   ``These dogs roam in packs so it's possible they separated,''
said David.
</P>
<P>
   Owners of the captured dogs could face vicious-animal
complaints, said Animal Services Officer Jesse Castillo.
</P>
<P>
   Residents will hold a meeting about the neighborhood's loose-dog
problem Thursday and Animal Services officers will answer
questions.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the stray dog population is concentrated in South
Central Los Angeles and the east and north San Fernando Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Animal Services General Manager Dan Knapp said ridding the
streets of stray and wandering animals is a top priority for the
city. He has asked for an additional $262,000 to hire seven
officers and one supervisor to battle the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Gini Barrett, president of the American Humane Association in
suburban Sherman Oaks and a member of the city's animal regulation
board, cited Monday's attacks as yet another reason to improve the
city's animal law enforcement tactics.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what happens when you dismantle your animal control
agency,'' said Barrett. ``The reason so many people let their dogs
run loose on the streets is because it's been 20 years since we
have had a substantial animal control presence to remind people
it's illegal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles County Health Department dismantled its dog bite
investigation unit in 1995, so dog bite statistics are not
available. In 1996, the city and county reported 878 animal bites _
dogs, cats and wild animals _ to state health officials, but many
consider this figure to be a low estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Animal Services currently operates on an $8.2 million annual
budget with 45 officers policing a city of 3.8 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the agency took in 33,000 stray dogs, of which animal
control officers caught 7,581.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
