<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROAD-WEARY MAVERICKS SHOW SOME UNEXPECTED SPUNK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Suffice to say, they didn't return home as conquering
heroes.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh from a dreadful 11-day, seven-game, NBA-forced march, the
Mavericks returned to Reunion Arena last night in the throes of an
identity crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks are (choose one, please):
</P>
<P>
   1. a young team in a desperate search for a winning combination,
</P>
<P>
   2. a young team on a suicide mission for a mad scientist of a
coach,
</P>
<P>
   3. a good waste of $24,
</P>
<P>
   4. Dennis Rodman's last choice.
</P>
<P>
   There are no answers here. Not yet.
</P>
<P>
   But, lo and behold, a victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been a kick in the teeth,'' coach Don Nelson
said of the alternative, after his Mavericks had knocked off the
equally discombobulated Atlanta Hawks, 89-85.
</P>
<P>
   Nellie's frequent fliers had arrived home from Monday night's
game in Phoenix sometime near 2 a.m., and after having played 48 of
their most listless minutes of the season.
</P>
<P>
   So how unexpected was this?
</P>
<P>
   This much: the Mavericks hadn't beaten a team over the .500 mark
since March of last year.
</P>
<P>
   That it happened last night may say more about the NBA's
vagabond schedule than it did about either the Hawks or Mavericks.
But after 11 nights of ordering room service, the Mavericks weren't
in the mood for labeling anything with an asterisk.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shows a lot of character to come off that road trip _ a
trip without a lot of wins (read: one) _ and come in here and
win,'' said guard Robert Pack, who scored 13 of his 15 points in
the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Pack is right. This was a game that they could have easily
mailed in. Having the finger-wagging Dikembe Mutombo in town will
do that to a struggling team.
</P>
<P>
   But with Pack, Gary Trent and Chris Anstey supplying a
second-period spark, the Mavericks asserted themselves as they had
never done this season. The strange brew continued in the second
half when Michael Finley suddenly started looking like the old
Finley, and Shawn Bradley again played like _ dare we say it? _ a
franchise cornerstone.
</P>
<P>
   OK, a franchise brick.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley finished with nine points in 35 minutes, but that stat
remained one of the most misleading of the young season. A better
line for Bradley was the one that said he blocked four shots, and
the hidden ones that said he hustled and frequently disrupted the
Hawks in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   The new-old Bradley isn't looking to shoot. It's been like
taking off his cap with the propeller on the top. He looks like a
real player out there.
</P>
<P>
   And this is with no practice to speak of. Unless somebody puts
in a court at the Denver airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurts,'' veteran A.C. Green said about the lack of practice
time. ``We're struggling with continuity, with chemistry, and it's
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Surely, it's been hard for Finley. Amid great expectations, the
third-year pro's season has been a blur of hotel lobbies and missed
jump shots. He came into last night's game as the team's leading
scorer, but battling an apparently flagging self-confidence and
shooting only 39 percent from the field.
</P>
<P>
   This is the same reportedly rising star who was handpicked by
Michael Jordan himself to wear His Airness' new style of Nikes.
They're sharp. They sparkle.
</P>
<P>
   Finley, alas, couldn't have been helping the sales.
</P>
<P>
   But in the second half against the Hawks, suddenly there was the
old Finley. He nailed five of six from the floor and scored 16 of
his game-high 22 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole demeanor of our team picked up in the second half,''
Finley said, deflecting the praise away from himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good I hit those shots, obviously. But that was more
because my teammates fed me.''
</P>
<P>
   So go figure. Mike, Mike, was it the shoes?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it was an excellent start \Rto the Mavs' next 10-day
stretch\S,'' Finley said. ``We were coming off a long, long, long,
long road trip. Hopefully, this will become a common thing for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, let's not get giddy, Mike. Somebody still has to explain
Nellie's mad scientist of a rotation, one that saw Green in the
middle at crunch time and Steve Nash, playing sick, getting most of
the second-half minutes instead of Pack.
</P>
<P>
   But that is another night's mystery in a season of intrigue for
the Mavericks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
