<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-WETTELAND-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WETTELAND EXPECTED TO BE READY FOR OPENER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Johnny Paul 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Rangers closer John Wetteland's injured
right ankle should heal in about two weeks and he is expected to be
available for Opening Day, the team's orthopedic consultant said
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland's ankle locked during a 10-minute bullpen session
Monday, but X-rays and a magnetic-resonance-imaging test revealed
no structural damage to the bone or tendons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely unlikely that John will have surgery during the
season for his ankle,'' Dr. John Conway said. ``He just has a
soft-tissue injury. In most cases, two weeks is enough for that to
heal.''
</P>
<P>
   If the ankle responds to treatment within two weeks and he
experiences no further setbacks, Wetteland will be available for
Opening Day, Conway said. The Rangers plan further tests if
Wetteland's condition doesn't improve by tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland, who limped noticeably through the clubhouse
yesterday, began his rehabilitation with range-of-motion exercises,
muscle stimulation, ice and heat therapy and anti-inflammatory
medication.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have more strength in it today, and that's encouraging,''
said Wetteland, 32.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland, though, acknowledged a decrease in the ankle's range
of motion and an increase in pain. X-rays Monday revealed one loose
body in the ankle, and Wetteland could undergo surgery after the
season to remove it.
</P>
<P>
   Wetteland, a one-inning specialist, doesn't as long to prepare
for the season as starting pitchers, who have to build strength and
endurance for 120-pitch appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spring training is for starting pitchers,'' Rangers manager
Johnny Oates said. ``Everyone else can be ready in two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates declined to discuss his contingency plan should Wetteland
be unavailable for Opening Day, but the manager mentioned three
possibilities. The Rangers could utilize Tim Crabtree or Danny
Patterson as their closer or adopt a closer-by-committee approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, it won't come to that,'' said Patterson, who
recorded two saves in two opportunities last year and yearns to
become a closer someday. ``This is not the way I would want to be
thrust into that role, but I definitely wouldn't shy away from
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Crabtree echoed Patterson's sentiments and said he would not be
intimidated by the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no different than pitching the seventh or eighth
innings,'' said Crabtree, who went 2-1 with a 2.30 earned-run
average in his final 22 appearances of 1998. ``You just happen to
be pitching the ninth inning protecting a one-, two- or three-run
lead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
