<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS ON SCHEDULE FOR CORYATT TOUR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Quentin Coryatt sweepstakes begins in
earnest Sunday, the free-agent linebacker's agent said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Zucker said the former Texas A&AMP;M star has visits scheduled
with four teams, including the Cowboys. Coryatt's tour starts
Sunday in Chicago and he plans to visit Philadelphia and Carolina.
An official tour of the Cowboys' facility is set for ``the week of
March 8.''
</P>
<P>
   Zucker said Coryatt has fully recovered from pectoral and
shoulder injuries that forced him to miss the 1998 season.
</P>
<P>
   Zucker reiterated that the Cowboys are Coryatt's first choice,
however, he said he expects a strong market for his client and
envisions adding a few more teams to the shopping list before a
decision is made.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys also are one of the teams Zucker plans to talk to
about a sign-and-trade deal for another client, Cincinnati
free-agent receiver Carl Pickens. The Bengals made Pickens their
franchise player so any team that signs him would have to give up
two first-round draft picks.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys also have expressed interest in Chargers restricted
free-agent receiver Charlie Jones, said his agent, Kendall Kremer.
Jones was the Chargers' second-leading receiver last season and
would only cost a fourth-round pick as compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Unrestricted free-agent receiver Raghib Ismail is considered to
be at the top of the Cowboys' list.
NFL EUROPE ASSIGNMENTS
</P>
<P>
   The six players the Cowboys allocated to NFL Europe for the
spring season were assigned to teams: Chris Brymer, Oliver Ross,
Jason Tucker and Robert Thomas to Rhein, Terry Billups to Scotland
and Brandon Noble to Barcelona.
</P>
</TEXT>
