<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 01:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6930 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-GOMEZ-COLUMN-D-BA     02-24 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GOMEZ-COLUMN-D-BACKS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GILKEY'S DECI SION DIFFICULT TO BELIEVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What is Bernard Gilkey thinking?
</P>
<P>
   By single-handedly blocking the trade that would have sent him
to Pittsburgh for Tony Womack and Al Martin, Gilkey has placed
himself in a perilous spot with the Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   If Gilkey's in this just for the money, then Arizona's as good a
place as any to collect it. But if he's a baseball player, then
competing in Pittsburgh was the way to go.
</P>
<P>
   This is a player who may find himself buried so deep on the
Diamondbacks roster that the club may need to send out a search
party to find him in its own dugout.
</P>
<P>
   The potential for this to turn into a nasty situation down the
road is great.
</P>
<P>
   As it stands, the Diamondbacks were exploring other ways Tuesday
to trade for Womack, which would further push Gilkey down their
depth chart.
</P>
<P>
   After rejecting the idea to change some language in his contract
(which would not have cost him a cent), Gilkey has basically forced
his will on the Diamondbacks, who badly wanted to add Womack's
speed to the top of their lineup.
</P>
<P>
   You don't need to be a genius to recognize that the Diamondbacks
spent most of the winter trying their darndest to trade Gilkey
anywhere. It's quite obvious Gilkey is not in the Diamondbacks'
plans, short- or long-term.
</P>
<P>
   To recap: The Diamondbacks agreed to send Gilkey to the Pirates
in exchange for Womack and Martin. In addition, Arizona was willing
to pick up Gilkey's $5 million in deferred payments and to split
the $1 million buyout of Gilkey's option year in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates, who need to dump some salary to meet their rigid
1999 budget, had agreed to every aspect of the deal. Even after
hitting a major snag _ one in which the commissioner's office
raised a red flag _ the clubs managed to work through that obstacle
and come to an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The final hurdle was getting Gilkey to OK a change in the
wording of his deal, which actually further guaranteed Gilkey's
deferred payments more than in his original contract.
</P>
<P>
   Done deal, right? Not on this one.
</P>
<P>
   Gilkey balked, saying he felt Pittsburgh's outfield was more
crowded and that after weighing all the factors, it was ``a choice
made totally for me and my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilkey looked and sounded sincere Tuesday as he spoke of his
desire to be a part of the Diamondbacks' high expectations this
season. He also spoke of being determined to turn himself into the
club's right fielder (he has been a left fielder throughout his
career).
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Gilkey may very well be given a chance to become the
everyday right fielder. The reality is that Gilkey is now tainted
in the eyes of the organization.
</P>
<P>
   Every player _ no matter who _ enjoys a clean slate whenever he
is welcomed into a new situation, and Gilkey was no different after
he was traded to Arizona from the New York Mets last July.
</P>
<P>
   But slowly he has diminished his standing within the club. After
undergoing corrective laser eye surgery in September, Gilkey agreed
with the club's advice to play winter ball.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks officials had to jump through a series of hoops to
secure Gilkey a spot on one of the Dominican winter teams. But when
it came time to leave, Gilkey decided against the idea and remained
at his St. Louis residence instead.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness to Gilkey, his wife was pregnant and delivered the
couple's second son last week. The Dominican regular season runs
from late November to mid-January. Even if Gilkey had gone for just
a few weeks, the club would have been satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   Another strike against Gilkey's case was his agent, Jim Bronner,
floating the idea that Gilkey would approve the trade if he could
receive a large portion of his deferred money now rather than
later, which tosses out the argument of wanting to play in Phoenix
over Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Gilkey will need to play near-flawless baseball if he is to be
among the club's contributing players. Several sources within the
organization said Gilkey basically has committed baseball suicide.
</P>
<P>
   There is still the chance that Gilkey could change his mind and
the deal could be pulled off. It's true Gilkey will collect his
money no matter how much or how little he plays.
</P>
<P>
   But unless he returns to his 1996 form, when he hit .317 with 30
home runs and 117 RBIs, expect Gilkey to decay at the end of the
bench all season. &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
