<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6933 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DIAMONDBACKS-GILK     02-24 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DIAMONDBACKS-GILKEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADE TALKS DIE AS GILKEY REJECTS CONTRACT TERMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ After all the phone calls, all the posturing, all the
legalese, all the words written in the newspapers over the past
week, we're back where we started.
</P>
<P>
   What a long, strange trip it's been.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Gilkey is still a Diamondback. Tony Womack and Al Martin
are still Pittsburgh Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   No deal.
</P>
<P>
   Gilkey's heart and mind told him to stay in Arizona, he said, so
he declined to approve language in his contract that would have
allowed him to be traded to the Pirates for Womack and Martin.
</P>
<P>
   There's no doubt Gilkey's decision frustrated Diamondbacks
officials. Now comes the period of time when Gilkey and the team
attempt to dance around the disappointment issue, Gilkey's at being
the subject of a trade and the team's at not getting the leadoff
man (Womack) that they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Gilkey arrived at Tucson Electric Park at 7:15 a.m. Tuesday to
inform Diamondbacks General Manager Joe Garagiola Jr. of his
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say that I`` didn't'' want to go to
Pittsburgh,'' Gilkey said. ``It's just that this team stepped out
and got some players (over the winter), and I want to be a part of
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I weighed all the factors, I did what I thought was best
for me and my family. Regardless of what people think, regardless
of what people say, I'm here to play baseball. I'm ready to put all
the riff-raff, put everything behind me.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who resides in Scottsdale, and Womack were divided on
their reaction to Gilkey's decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable. I don't know what else to say,'' Martin
told reporters at the Pirates' spring home in Bradenton, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Womack was happy to be staying put.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no desire to go anywhere else,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Garagiola left open the door for another attempt to acquire
Womack, saying he would call Pirates General Manager Cam Bonifay,
but was uncertain of the timetable. Gilkey obviously would not be
part of that, Garagiola said, nor would left-hander Brian Anderson,
who has been the subject of trade rumors over the winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Bernard that this was nothing personal, that it's my
job to analyze trade offers and do whatever it takes to help the
club,'' Garagiola said. ``You get calls, some are short, some are
longer and some are worth pursuing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Look, I want to make a contribution.' If he were
upset by the notion of the trade, he would say, `Hey, you don't
want me, I don't want to be here.' But it's not that way. We as an
organization always said that we were looking for players who``
wanted'' to play for us, and now, in this roundabout way, we have a
good example.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some people who say that the best trades sometimes
are the ones you don't make. If Bernard has a season like he did in
1996 (.317, 30 homers, 117 RBIs for the New York Mets), he can be a
factor for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilkey met briefly with Manager Buck Showalter in the morning,
went through the first full-squad workout of the spring with his
teammates and then met again with Showalter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buck and I are fine,'' Gilkey said. ``The best manager I ever
had is the one who puts my name in the lineup, and that's my goal
here, to make this club.''
</P>
<P>
   Showalter said the smoke is clearing. ``We'll put this behind us
and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilkey is expected to move from left field to right. He
anticipates a smooth transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach (Dwayne) Murphy will help me out a lot,'' Gilkey said of
the Diamondbacks' outfield coach, who was a six-time American
League Gold Glove winner with the Oakland Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   Said Murphy: ``There are a lot of different angles involved in
right as opposed to left and it can be a difficult adjustment, but
Bernard is very capable.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that Womack is out of the leadoff picture, Showalter will go
about the task of finding a man to fill the top spot. He said he
already has conducted preliminary inquiries of players to get a
sense of whether they would be willing to assume that role.
</P>
<P>
   One of those is Luis Gonzalez, acquired in a trade from Detroit,
who is expected to start in left field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done it five or six times, and I think I could do it,
yeah,'' Gonzalez said. ``The first time (at-bat) is really the only
one that matters. The only real thing that might affect you is
hitting behind the pitcher, but if they can move the runner over,
you've got a chance to drive them in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really no big deal because we have a lot of scrappy guys
who could do it, just so long as it helps us win.''
</P>
<P>
   Other candidates are center fielder Steve Finley, infielder Tony
Batista, outfielder Dante Powell and perhaps even Gilkey.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever Gilkey hits in the lineup, he is hopeful of rebounding
from a pair of slow seasons in 1997 and 1998 that followed his big
year with the New York Mets. He had corrective laser surgery on
both eyes in September during the last week of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The focus and the clarity . . . I can pick up the spin and the
threads on the ball,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As he enters his 15th spring in professional baseball, Gilkey
says he hasn't lost perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never take anything for granted,'' he said. ``I enjoy each
day out there, because one day, I might not have another
opportunity.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
