<HEADER>
A6934 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-BASEBALL_NOMADS-A     02-24 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALL_NOMADS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLVING DOOR SPINS AROUND BIG MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Depending on how you look at Major League Baseball in its
present state, the Diamondbacks represent everything that is either
great with the game, or all that is lousy with it.
</P>
<P>
   The mere fact that a club with little to look forward to in the
short-term future can open its checkbook and throw money at its
problems is perceived as one of the game's evils by many purists,
who recall a time when a well-run farm system was the only way to
build a top-notch organization.
</P>
<P>
   Others, who don't care how their favorite club is built, as long
as it wins, could care less about the old-school ways. They're just
interested in getting behind a winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's tough on the fans,'' Boston General Manager Dan
Duquette said. ``The challenge is to build up a team. These days
you build it up and the economic pressures are such that as soon as
you build it and have great success, it drives up the cost of your
labor. You end up breaking down what you spent all that time
building up. It's like an endless challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks have answered the challenge by investing
heavily in free agency, most notably pitchers Randy Johnson and
Todd Stottlemyre and center fielder Steve Finley. The result is a
roster loaded with new faces _ already 13 players who were on their
inaugural Opening Day roster are playing elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not just the Diamondbacks who have a revolving door to
their clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette and the Red Sox have seen two of that storied club's
biggest stars leave town in the past three years. All-Star pitcher
Roger Clemens left for Toronto after the 1996 season and has added
his fourth and fifth Cy Young Award since. Perennial All-Star and
former Most Valuable Player Mo Vaughn departed for Anaheim just a
few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The door continues to spin greater numbers of players in the
direction of new destinations each winter. It's getting to the
point where fans _ serious fans _ are having difficulty keeping up
with who plays where.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not just an off-season phenomenon. Johnson and
Stottlemyre both were involved in midseason trades last year,
filling the role of temporary hired guns to help Houston and Texas
secure playoff berths.
</P>
<P>
   The days of watching Los Angeles keep intact its infield of
Steve Garvey, Davey Lopes, Bill Russell and Ron Cey for 10
consecutive years (a major league record) are long gone, most
baseball officials agree.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the days of knowing your favorite player would remain
with the same club throughout his career.
</P>
<P>
   Cal Ripken, who has been with Baltimore since his rookie season
in 1982, and seems destined to stay there until his final at-bat,
may well be the last of his kind _ a superstar who spends his
entire career with the same organization.
</P>
<P>
   The financially stable teams have been able to withstand the
changing tide. It's the small-market teams that are hit hardest by
players seeking greener pastures each winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably good from a national standpoint because it
creates a lot of interest in a lot of cities,'' Oakland GM Billy
Beane said. ``But it's very tough on small-market teams. You get
someone who is, say, the rookie of the year and people are starting
to ask when is he going to leave? It's always the first question
when a guy has success in a small market. In a big market it's
``how do we keep him?' ''
</P>
<P>
   It's a question Beane hears often since his young and talented
right fielder, Ben Grieve, won the American League Rookie of the
Year honor last season.
</P>
<P>
   There is no better way to look at the current problem than to
put the Pittsburgh Pirates of the early 1990s and the Montreal
Expos of the mid-1990s under a microscope.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates won three straight National League East division
titles from 1990-92. But after winning the final of the three
titles, the Pirates saw the core of their team fall apart when
Barry Bonds left as a free agent to San Francisco and Cy Young
Award winner Doug Drabek left for Houston. The year before, Bobby
Bonilla and Sid Bream left.
</P>
<P>
   The Expos? They had a major league-best 74-40 record the day the
1994 season ended when the players went on strike.
</P>
<P>
   The Expos roster that season had outfielders Moises Alou, Larry
Walker and Marquis Grissom. The pitching rotation had Pedro
Martinez, Ken Hill, Jeff Fassero and Kirk Rueter. In the bullpen,
Montreal had closer John Wetteland being set up by Jeff Shaw and
Mel Rojas.
</P>
<P>
   There is little doubt that Manager Felipe Alou had a special
group. There is also little doubt that Alou doesn't stop to think
about what that club could have achieved if it had been able to
keep the players together.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a rule, I try never to look back at anything,'' Alou said.
``But with that team I can't help but do so. We had a team that, I
think, would have gone all the way to the World Series. And then,
to see it all taken apart simply because of the financial structure
of the game, well, it definitely hurts.''
</P>
<P>
   Because teams are in constant flux, today's general managers
must look beyond a player's skills and concentrate equally on what
type of person they are bringing into the mix.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that chemistry was created over five or 10
years,'' Beane said. ``Now, we're all trying to do the same on a
one-year basis. It's a roll of the dice whether those new
personalities will work together.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the small-market clubs that recognized potential problems
early was the Cleveland Indians, where GM John Hart has
orchestrated what is generally considered the model franchise.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, the Indians had yet to move into Jacobs
Field, which has become a virtual cash pump for a franchise on the
brink of bankruptcy 15 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Hart saw young players who were on their way toward stardom:
Kenny Lofton, Albert Belle, Sandy Alomar, Charles Nagy, Jose Mesa,
among others. Instead of risking the loss of those players to free
agency or being forced to trade them because of escalating
salaries, Hart gambled that they would remain healthy and
productive and signed them to long-term deals through their
arbitration years.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of having to go to an arbitration hearing against Belle,
who might have a 50-home run season under his belt, the Indians had
locked him up for several years. The contracts were a gamble, but
the payoff has been enormous. The club has used similar tactics
with Manny Ramirez, Jim Thome and Jaret Wright.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at it as two elements,'' Hart said. ``As an
executive or an operator, you have to scout well, trade well and
replace quality players. And two, you have to be creative with what
you do with contracts. That's the balancing act that is baseball
right now; one that, quite frankly, is more mobile than at any
point in the history of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still the game we all grew up with, but the rules are
completely different. We have a chance to be in the most exciting
era of baseball. It's the ability of fans to connect that worries
me. It really bothers me. Ultimately, the game is the only agenda
any of us _ owners, executives, players, unions _ should worry
about.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-99 0128EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
