<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 01:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6936 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NHRA-GWYNN-AZR &LR;      02-24 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NHRA-GWYNN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GWYNN HAS PRIDE OF OWNERSHIP  
 PARALYZED EX-DRIVER REMAINS IN RACING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his dreams, Darrell Gwynn is walking. In some of them, he
even is tucked inside the snug belly of the race car, shoulders
harnessed and hands tightly gripped around the steering wheel.
</P>
<P>
   They are good dreams.
</P>
<P>
   And they also are bad.
</P>
<P>
   When Gwynn wakes up, he can't move his feet or his hands.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn is paralyzed from the mid-chest down, the victim of a
horrible crash on Easter Sunday nine years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn was at England's Santa Pod Raceway making an exhibition
pass when the Top Fuel dragster he was driving at a speed of 240
mph suddenly veered left and smashed into a concrete wall.
</P>
<P>
   The car exploded upon impact, snapping Gwynn's neck.
</P>
<P>
   The mangled car skidded along the pavement with Gwynn's left arm
hanging out the driver's compartment. Later, massive infections
forced physicians to amputate Gwynn's arm at the elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn needed 23 pints of blood in the first two days after the
accident. He couldn't eat or drink for more than 10 days, yet his
waist ballooned from 32 to 38 inches because of kidneys and liver
failure.
</P>
<P>
   When Gwynn finally was able to return home to Miami about five
weeks later, 14 seats on a 747 were needed to accommodate medical
personnel, life-support equipment and a bed specially designed to
absorb the shock of landing and in-flight turbulence.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn was home, but home wasn't where his heart was.
</P>
<P>
   His heart still belonged to racing.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why during Friday's first-round qualifying in the
Checker Schuck's Kragen Nationals at Firebird International Raceway
Park, a wheelchair-bound Gwynn will be sitting a few feet from the
starting line, watching driver Mike Dunn try to put a Gwynn-owned
Top Fueler into the starting field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though racing took away Darrell's ability to walk, it
also has given him all the happiness he could ever want,'' said
Lisa Gwynn, Darrell's wife and mother of their nearly 8-month-old
baby girl. ``Thank God, he's made this a success story when it
could have devastated his life. For Darrell, it was like, `Hey,
this is terrible, but life goes on. Let's live life.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Racing really is all he knows. It gave him something to live
and strive for after the accident. It gave him purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   It gave Gwynn life, just a few months after it tried to snatch
it from him.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn, 36, was the sport's most promising driver before the
crash. Only a few days earlier, he had set NHRA elapsed-time record
of 4.909 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the uncertainties.
</P>
<P>
   But because Gwynn also was the team's car owner, duties still
had to be performed outside of driving. That is, if he was up to
it, mentally and physically.
</P>
<P>
   Mentally, Gwynn never struggled with the decision to return.
</P>
<P>
   Physically, it took a little time.
</P>
<P>
   Now he attends about half the circuit's 23 races.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had been just a driver and didn't have my own team, maybe
I could have walked away from the sport,'' Gwynn said. ``But I had
great sponsors behind me and a great team. We were on top of the
world at the time, and I wasn't going to let one bad day in England
destroy what I had had in mind for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   To get to the future, however, Gwynn needed some help.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Bernstein stepped forward almost immediately, raising
$35,000 from the Professional Racers &AMP; Owners Association to
finance Gwynn's flight home from England. Bernstein also arranged a
benefit softball game between NASCAR and NHRA drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt in my mind, Darrell would have been one of the stars
of the sport,'' Bernstein said, noting that he and Gwynn are among
nine drivers who share the record for most wins (six) in a single
season. ``That gives you an idea how he could have been a major
star.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it doesn't surprise me to see him out there today, even
after that accident. I knew if there was any way he could function
after that crash, he was going to come back out here. It's his
life.''
</P>
<P>
   But not his entire life.
</P>
<P>
   First, there's his wife, a former University of Miami
cheerleader who has known her husband since childhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our families were friends,'' Lisa said. ``We started seeing
each other seriously when I was in college.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until after the accident that they were married. She
graduated from medical school last year and is a pediatrician in
residency at Jackson Memorial Hospital in Miami, which is where her
husband spent some time when he returned from England.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of the Miami Project to Cure Paralysis, the Gwynns
celebrated the birth of their first child last summer, a 5-pound,
9-ounce baby girl named Katie Brianne Gwynn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got pictures of my little girl all over my office,''
Darrell said. ``She gives me more reasons to go home at night
instead of staying here until 8 p.m.''
</P>
<P>
   But with Dunn winning the season opener three weeks ago, which
was the team's first win in three seasons, Gwynn felt it necessary
to attend the Firebird event.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got momentum now,'' he said. ``I feel like I should be
here.''
</P>
<P>
   And Dunn will be happy to see his car owner on pit road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since I've been with Darrell, he's never complained once about
the cards he's been dealt,'' Dunn said. ``So when things are going
bad for me and I'm not winning races, I have no right to
complain.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the paralysis, Gwynn still must constantly contend
with possible urinary tract infections.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can potentially be a very bad thing,'' Gwynn said. ``I just
don't have the immune system that normal people do.''
</P>
<P>
   But who's complaining?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have dreams about walking and racing, and fans even come to
me and tell me they have dreams about me walking and racing,''
Gwynn said. ``But I'm realistic. Even if a cure is found, you're
not suddenly going to walk one day. It takes time.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I know a cure will be found and people will walk again.
When it happens, I'll be one of the first ones in line.
</P>
<P>
   ``But even if they just makes small strides to help guys like
me, maybe I'll be able to pick up a pen and maybe drive my van.
Maybe then I'll even be able to hold my baby.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
