<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 01:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6938 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      02-24 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ One day after Moises Alou was lost probably for
the year, the last thing the Astros' brass needed was Ken Caminiti
and Craig Biggio barreling through the training-camp gates on
sparkling new Harley-Davidsons.
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti and Biggio might have been the ones on bikes, but
general manager Gerry Hunsicker and skipper Larry Dierker were the
Uneasy Riders.
</P>
<P>
   There were Cammy and Bidge, decked out in their leather jackets,
dark shades and biker-dude helmets, looking like some sort of cross
between Peter Fonda and Colonel Klink. They weaved through cars and
gates. They energetically waved at fans.
</P>
<P>
   It was quite the show of unity. It was quite the bold,
determined entrance into the 1999 season by these longtime friends
now reunited under the Astros' star and sharing an old dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``Same goal, different team,'' Caminiti said. ``We had this goal
a few years ago here, and now we're back. It's the same thing we've
always wanted to reach.''
</P>
<P>
   So let it be known that the road to maybe the club's first NL
pennant began with a rumble through the gates, then a reverberation
off the walls of the Astros' clubhouse as Biggio and Caminiti
pulled their bikes up to the door.
</P>
<P>
   There was the deep, booming sputter of the twin Harleys and then
the flawless, if deathly slow, idle. Glub glub glub.
</P>
<P>
   There was Hunsicker _ no doubt holding his breath and watching
closely with visions of ACLs dancing through his head. OK, guys,
hit the kickstand. Kickstand!
</P>
<P>
   And there were Caminiti and Biggio, pulling off their biker
helmets, pulling on their Astros uniforms for the first time this
spring and never looking more imposing _ or important _ for this
team.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the noticeable absence of the injured Alou, the
spring began with many of the same sights and sounds as always:
</P>
<P>
   Jose Lima danced a sort of mambo in the outfield. Jeff Bagwell
stepped into the batter's box for the first time, fiddled with a
new swing and smashed pitch after pitch. Casey Candaele had them
laughing in the clubhouse. Derek Bell was late. Daryle Ward and
Russ Johnson looked like big-leaguers but probably had tickets to
New Orleans on the way. Biggio wore a clean uniform for all of two
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Not much has changed, except for the loss of Alou and the return
of Caminiti.
</P>
<P>
   Goodbye to one power-hitting, 100-RBI Most Valuable Player
candidate, hello to another. This isn't the way it was supposed to
be _ Caminiti's powerful presence and impressive numbers were
supposed to add to the lineup, not replace those numbers gone for
the year. But that is how it must be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Losing Alou certainly took some of the spirit away from the
first day of camp,'' Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   But seeing Caminiti rumble through the gate with Biggio lifted
spirits again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Caminiti's input may have been overstated in the beginning,
after we first got him,'' Dierker said. ``But now that we've lost
an RBI hitter, it makes getting Caminiti even bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   Without Alou, Dierker's batting lineup figures to take on all
sorts of different looks this year. He needs to find another player
who can get on base behind Biggio, so the likes of Bell, Bagwell
and Caminiti can work their RBI magic.
</P>
<P>
   Bell likely will bat in the No. 2 hole quite often, but any
number of players, from Richard Hidalgo to Glen Barker, Ricky
Gutierrez, Jack Howell, Bill Spiers and Tim Bogar also could get a
look.
</P>
<P>
   The luxury Dierker has in 1999 is Caminiti. He is confident and
comfortable. Without the signing of the popular Cammy, things could
have been much more complicated.
</P>
<P>
   But with him, the runs figure to keep coming. Caminiti reported
to camp in exceptional shape and, perhaps more important, was not
coming off offseason surgery for the first time since before the
1996 season. That's the year he was the NL's MVP, batting .326 with
40 home runs and 130 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see him, and you know he's ready to go,'' Bagwell said.
``To have him back, behind me with that lefthanded bat, it's great.
I wish it never had to happen when we didn't have him for three or
four years.''
</P>
<P>
   As he motored into camp with Biggio, it seemed like Caminiti
never left. The only difference was that back then, they usually
arrived quietly in a shared rental car.
</P>
<P>
   But the dream remains.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt a little weird pulling up here,'' Caminiti said.
``Things have changed, but some things haven't. They put me in the
same corner (locker) that I was at five years ago. I have the No.
11 back (a product of the Brad Ausmus trade). It's strange, but
it's good.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
