<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990224.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 01:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6940 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SONICS-ROCKETS-HN     02-24 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The Rockets' guards are just going to have to find some big men who
can give them some help.
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the Rockets were struggling though another third-quarter
collapse Tuesday night, they turned to _ who else? _ Brent Price
and Cuttino Mobley. Price kick-started the offense with a bomb from
just inside midcourt, and Mobley took it over, driving the Rockets
past the Seattle SuperSonics 98-86 at Compaq Center.
</P>
<P>
   After a brutal road trip in which they lost three of four games
and most of their confidence, it was a win the Rockets said they
had to have. That the victory came on the strength of their
backcourt made it that much more rewarding.
</P>
<P>
   ``It boosts our confidence,'' said Rockets forward Scottie
Pippen, who chipped in 19 points, 10 rebounds, five assists and
three steals. ``It gets our mindset back to where we can beat
anybody. It was a great win for us. We definitely needed this.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Pippen and Hakeem Olajuwon had their moments early and
Othella Harrington came on late, it was Mobley who went through a
few unstoppable minutes to key the win. He scored nine consecutive
points in just 90 seconds of the fourth quarter and 11 of 12 in a
three-minute stretch that took the Rockets into the final 4:50 with
a 10-point lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``To go from (playing against) Tim Hardaway to Penny Hardaway to
Gary Payton is like Disney World,'' said Mobley, who had 19 points,
five assists and six rebounds, all season highs. ``I was a little
nervous, but you've got to play basketball. I love one-on-one,
man-to-man. That's just basketball. Coach (Rudy Tomjanovich) had
confidence in me, and my teammates had confidence in me. And the
shots went.''
</P>
<P>
   Mobley became the answer when the SuperSonics disrupted the
Rockets' offense in the third quarter by trapping the ball-handler
and rotating defensively. With Payton's ballhawking threatening to
take over the game, Tomjanovich went away from Payton by calling on
Mobley, who promptly burned a succession of defenders _ Hersey
Hawkins, Dale Ellis and finally Moochie Norris.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the fourth quarter, I had a mismatch with Dale Ellis and
Hersey Hawkins switching on me, so I had to create,'' Mobley said.
``I love basketball, and I love pressure like in Golden State (when
he hit the game-winning 3-pointer in the first game of his
career).''
</P>
<P>
   That shot offered a clue to Mobley's nerve, but his role has
steadily increased to the point he has started the past two games,
exposing his bravado even more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cuttino is courageous, and he's talented,'' Tomjanovich said.
``Every game is a learning experience. He does have something
special _ not only his skills but the way he can see different
things out there. I'm amazed at how well he's doing at a different
position (point guard).''
</P>
<P>
   Before Mobley had his fourth-quarter run, the Rockets (7-4)
stared into the brink of another third-quarter fade. But contrary
to their lost weekend in Florida, they would not allow one bad
stretch to doom them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had control all of the game,'' Olajuwon said. ``When they
made their run, there was concern but there was no doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of a third-quarter meltdown, the Rockets abandoned
the scorers who had carried them in the first half and came up with
novel ways to turn the ball over, such as three-second violations.
After scoring nine points in Saturday's third quarter against Miami
and 10 in Sunday's vs. Orlando, the Rockets through nine minutes of
Tuesday's second half had scored six points, making three of 11
shots and committing seven turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen, who made his first six shots and had a 15-point first
half, went 21:46 between attempts. Olajuwon, who also had a
15-point half, took only two third-quarter shots. The SuperSonics
(7-3) rode that stretch to a 12-0 run and a 62-60 lead, their first
of the night.
</P>
<P>
   But before the Rockets would repeat the second-half fades of the
weekend, they scratched out a 9-0 run to end the quarter.
Harrington beat the shot clock with a hook in the lane, Olajuwon
made a pair of free throws, and Price sank a pair of foul shots
after an illegal defense and a technical on Seattle coach Paul
Westphal.
</P>
<P>
   Price added to the degree of difficulty, giving the Rockets a
69-62 lead with a shot so unexpected that it blew out the
scoreboard. He ended the third period with a running, falling
3-pointer over Payton from a step inside midcourt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Price's 3 really deflated us,'' Westphal said. ``It shouldn't
have affected us that much, but I think it did.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked when he knew his shot would fall, Price (10 points, six
assists in 26 minutes off the bench) said, ``When it was in the
net.''
</P>
<P>
   But the element of good fortune did not diminish the production
of the guards.
</P>
<P>
   Like Pippen, Olajuwon had 19 points and 10 rebounds, and
Harrington added 17 points on 7-of-10 shooting. But it was the
contributions out of the backcourt that put the Rockets over the
top.
</P>
<P>
   ``That style of play (when) the whole team, the whole offense is
moving, you don't know who is going to get the shot, and when, and
how,'' Olajuwon said. ``That's what I like about that.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big game, a big win for us. This is one of the top
teams in the league. To come back home and get a win like this, I
think, will boost the confidence of the whole team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
