<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 01:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6941 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HIDALGO-HN     02-24 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HIDALGO-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ An injury hurt Richard Hidalgo's chances of
becoming a regular Astros starter in 1998. A year later, an injury
has provided him a second chance.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hidalgo, long hailed as the Astros' No. 1 outfielder of the
future, arrived for workouts Tuesday morning and found opportunity
awaiting him.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a young player, you sometimes get frustrated because you
think you're being blocked by players ahead of you and not getting
the opportunities you feel entitled to,'' Hidalgo said. ``Then
there is a situation when you have to be ready to play at all
times. You never know what's around that corner. One day it looks
like you're being blocked, and the next day there is an
opportunity. Richard's time has come.''
</P>
<P>
   After splitting time in center field last year with Carl
Everett, Hidalgo will take over the duties in left for All-Star
Moises Alou, who is likely out for the season after suffering a
torn anterior cruciate ligament in his left knee when he fell
during a treadmill workout last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an unfortunate circumstance that has created this
opportunity,'' said general manager Gerry Hunsicker, ``but we're
going to find out some things about Richard this year.''
</P>
<P>
   There's one thing the Astros already know: The 23-year-old with
the solid bat and shotgun right arm belongs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should certainly reinforce in his mind that he belongs
here, he's capable of playing here, and he's primed to take on a
greater role,'' Hunsicker said. ``Richard has always been a kid
that has stood out. There are just some kids from an early age _
they have that can't-miss label. He was one of those kids. He was
somebody that everyone in the organization felt early on had a
chance to be a special player.''
</P>
<P>
   Hidalgo, constantly mentioned in trade talks involving Roger
Clemens and Randy Johnson during the past eight months, finally got
his chance last season by making the club's major-league roster out
of spring training and opening the season as the starting center
fielder. He started 30 of the first 53 games before a separated
right shoulder, the result of a collision with the center-field
wall at Denver's Coors Field, sidelined him for seven weeks. When
he returned in late July, Everett had won the job outright.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad for Alou. He's one of my good friends,'' Hidalgo
said. ``When something happens, you have to be prepared for that
time and just go out there and be relaxed. Right now, I have an
opportunity. I'm going to be working hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Hidalgo hit .303 with seven home runs and 35 RBIs in 211 at-bats
last season. He has only 93 major-league games to his credit but
said inexperience wouldn't be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not nervous,'' said Hidalgo, once rated the best
minor-league prospect in the Astros organization. ``I've been
waiting for a chance to play for so long. It's time. This year is
the time for me to play every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite last season's crowded outfield, which included Alou and
Derek Bell, the Astros decided to break camp with Hidalgo on the
roster. The thinking was it would be easier to slowly adjust
Hidalgo to the majors on a contending club.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way to break in a young player is on a part-time
basis,'' Hunsicker said. ``That's what happened last year. It was
the perfect opportunity for Richard to make his debut in the major
leagues without putting a lot of pressure on him to play a vital
role on the club.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Larry Dierker plans to use Hidalgo primarily in left
field during spring training and will occasionally shift him to
center, his natural position, to allow him to remain sharp there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't play left field, but if I have to, I'll do it,''
Hidalgo said.
</P>
<P>
   While offsetting the loss of Alou won't be easy, the Astros are
glad to get Hidalgo in the lineup. In their center-field platoon,
Hidalgo and Everett combined to hit .297 with 22 home runs and 111
RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Alou hit .312 with 38 homers and 124 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Carl and Richard) don't want Moises to be hurt. They just
want a chance to play and prove they are every-day players,''
Dierker said. ``I don't think Richard will feel any additional
pressure, because I think this is what he wanted all along. It's
what he wanted last year. He wanted to play more; so did Carl.''
</P>
<P>
   Said second baseman Craig Biggio: ``Somebody is going to have to
pull the weight that's gone. They are not necessarily going to do
what Moises can do, but they are going to go out and do the best
they can.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros don't want to fall into the pitfall of asking Hidalgo
to try to duplicate Alou's numbers. Hunsicker's advice to Hidalgo:
Be yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing we can't do, and it would be unfair for us to
do, is to label him as Moises Alou's replacement and try to compare
him,'' Hunsicker said. ``That's not realistic, and it's not fair.
He certainly has a chance to step in and be a very solid
major-league player for us this year.''
</P>
<P>
   It's up to Hidalgo to seize the opportunity.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
