r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUNS-NOTEBOOK-AZR     02-24 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIDD'S DURABILITY FACES STIFF TEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arguably, Jason Kidd of the Suns is playing as well as any point
guard in the NBA so far this season.
</P>
<P>
   He leads the NBA with an average of 10.7 assists per game. He
ranks 30th in scoring with 17.4 points a game, and he's the Suns'
leading rebounder with an average of 6.7 per game.
</P>
<P>
   But he also ranks third in the NBA in minutes played, averaging
more than 40 a game. With 50 games in 90 days, can Kidd hold up
under that kind of demand?
</P>
<P>
   The Suns don't have a true backup point guard. Rookie Gerald
Brown is on the injured list. Shawn Respert can play the position,
but he's more of a scorer than a distributor.
</P>
<P>
   When Kidd needs a break, Coach Danny Ainge has been running his
offense through forwards Danny Manning and George McCloud.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that I'm down on Gerald or Shawn,'' Ainge said. ``To
be honest, I'm trying to get more playing time for some of our
veteran guys like George, Danny, Cliff (Robinson).''
</P>
<P>
   The club has no immediate plans to go sign a veteran backup,
although the Suns have looked over the list of available players.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at the list of who's available, those guys would
be about the same as what we've got now,'' Ainge said.
</P>
<P>
   Trades aren't likely because the Suns have only two players they
can deal, Kidd and Manning. And the club isn't likely to give up a
draft pick of any value for a backup point guard.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Ainge said he's willing to go with what he's got, allow
Respert and Brown to grow into the job and hope Kidd doesn't suffer
an injury that would cause him to miss an extended period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those veteran guys can get us into our offense, and in some
situations they can even defend point guards,'' he said. ``If we go
get a backup point guard, it's going to cut into the other guys'
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jason is a guy who is going to play a lot of minutes. He's
going to get 38-40 minutes even if we have another backup.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is an injury, then yeah, we would look at doing
something and Shawn Respert would get a lot more minutes. He might
get more anyway depending on the type of game it is.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Three men &QL; 
 &QL; 
McCloud is off to a terrific start from three-point range, hitting
17 of his first 33 shots from behind the arc to rank fifth in the
NBA with a 51.5 percent average.
</P>
<P>
   But guess who's atop the three-point shooting chart?
</P>
<P>
   The Suns' Robinson has made 7 of 11, 63.6 percent, to lead the
league. But he's barely on a pace to qualify for the leaders. He'll
have to make at least 34 three-pointers this season to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson rates 16th in overall shooting percentage at 50.5.
Manning, who is shooting better than 55 percent, would rank fourth
but lacks enough attempts to qualify. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Kidd campaign &QL; 
 &QL; 
Suns President Jerry Colangelo said he's made calls to USA
Basketball to support Kidd for a berth on the U.S. Olympic team
that will compete in Sydney in 2000. Kidd isn't likely to be among
the first nine players picked. That group, which will include Tom
Gugliotta of the Suns, will compete in a qualifying tournament this
summer in Puerto Rico and then in the Olympics. But Colangelo said
he'll do what he can to help Kidd land one of the three remaining
spots.
</P>
<P>
   Ainge said he believes Kidd would excel in the wide-open style
of the Olympic tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jason definitely belongs on that team,'' Ainge said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
