<SLUG> BC-BBN-DIAMONDBACKS-NOTES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHEDULE BENDS FOR PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter is a stickler for
precision. He doesn't like anything interrupting his club's
schedule, particularly in the spring when he needs to get as many
opportunities to evaluate players as possible.
</P>
<P>
   He will have to bend for at least one day when President Clinton
visits the Diamondbacks' workout here Thursday afternoon after a
downtown speaking engagement.
</P>
<P>
   The club's two workouts, normally open to the public, will be
closed that day. Showalter will have his veteran players, who
normally practice in the morning, switch with the younger players
so they can visit with the president. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Good first impression
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Dante Powell wants to prove to the Diamondbacks that
they made a good decision when they acquired him in an off-season
trade with the San Francisco Giants for left-handed middle reliever
Alan Embree.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks vividly remember one occasion when Powell
tracked down a long drive to the left-center-field gap by Travis
Lee late last season at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Powell impressed outfield coach Dwayne Murphy during Wednesday's
first full-squad workout.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a great first step, a great first two steps,'' Murphy
said. ``Steve Finley (Arizona's new center fielder) has it, and
Devon (White, Arizona's former center fielder) had it, and Powell
has it. In fact, he may be the most explosive I've ever seen.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sveum's the name
</P>
<P>
   A handful of Diamondbacks live in the Phoenix area year-round,
some even before they joined the club, but one of the newest has
lived there the longest.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Dale Sveum, 35, has been in the Valley since 1985. He is
attempting to earn a role as a utility infielder. He played with
the New York Yankees in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Third base will be his primary assignment, ``but I can do a
little bit of everything,'' said Sveum (pronounced Swaim). ``I feel
this club is the best fit for me. It would be great to help it
become a contending team.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Tale of the tape
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks have their version of the 38th parallel in
their clubhouse at Tucson Electric Park.
</P>
<P>
   It is a piece of white medical tape that stretches on the carpet
between the dressing cubicles of third baseman Matt Williams and
jack-of-all-trades Andy Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Is there a problem here?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not if he stays on his side, and I stay on mine,'' Williams
said with a straight face. ``He's got size 14 feet, and the first
day he threw his shoes over here.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Tabloid teaser
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Randy Johnson had a few differences with the media
in Seattle but is getting along fine with the Arizona contingent.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he engaged in an amusing conversation with three
sportswriters the other day.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson walked past them and said, ``Well, there they are, the
three beat writers for the (National) Enquirer, the Star, and . . .
what's the other one, the Globe?''
</P>
<P>
   Careful, Randy, you know how the truth can sometimes be
stretched. Like, say, ``The pitcher with four arms.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I had four arms,'' he said. ``I'd renegotiate my
contract.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
