<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROAD-WEARY LAKERS BITTEN BY GRIZZLIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, B.C _ If this is what post-lockout,
three-games-in-three-nights basketball looks like, NBA games should
come with an NC-17 rating to protect the fragile psyches of
innocent children.
</P>
<P>
   The shock of seeing an endless string of botched layups,
rim-rattling jumpshots and, well, anything involving Bryant ``Very
Big Country'' Reeves, must be considered a danger to kids. And
Tuesday night's game at General Motors Place should have been
censored, if not canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Unless, that is, your idea of good, clean, wholesome fun is a
bunch of guys shooting 30 percent and tripping over themselves.
</P>
<P>
   There was precious little action resembling professional
basketball as the road-weary Lakers dropped a 93-83 decision to the
lowly Grizzlies and ended their road trip with an unsightly 0-3
mark. Not only that, the Lakers lost to the Grizzlies for the first
time in 13 meetings since Vancouver entered the league.
</P>
<P>
   This much damage, maybe even Dennis Rodman can't fix. The Lakers
better lure Michael out of retirement too.
</P>
<P>
   The last minute of the game was representative of how far the
Lakers have fallen and how ugly things got Tuesday. Trailing 87-81
with 1:05 left, the Lakers close enough to salvage a comeback,
Derek Harper tossed an inbounds pass that missed a cutting Eddie
Jones and went out of bounds. Turnover, game effectively over.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end, Bryant fouled Shareef Abdur-Rahim, who sank
two foul shots for an eight-point advantage. And the end to that
losing streak to the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Abdur-Rahim led Vancouver with 28 points and 14 rebounds.
Shaquille O'Neal led the Lakers with 26, and Eddie Jones scored 15.
The Lakers shot 35.9 percent and looked every bit like a team that
played three games in less than 60 hours.
</P>
<P>
   And every bit like a team that's .500 (6-6).
</P>
<P>
   So what does three games in three cities in three nights feel
like?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody in general is a little tired,'' Kobe Bryant
said before tipoff. ``Tired of the trip, tired of losing, a little
frustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Back-to-back losses in Seattle and Denver will do that to a
team. And even a fresh-faced 20-year-old can't avoid the effects of
so much basketball in so little time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know me, personally, I'm sore,'' Bryant said. ``Hamstring,
knee. I'm getting old, man.''
</P>
<P>
   How bad were things Tuesday night? The Grizzlies shot 29.7
percent in the first half and forged a 41-41 tie, thanks to 18
points on 26 foul shots. The two teams combined for 33 personal
fouls in the opening two quarters. Such ugly play could be expected
of Vancouver, a team that entered the game with only three wins to
its credit, and only because it beat up on the Clippers and
Mavericks. But for the Lakers, the only explanation was fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   How else to explain a second quarter in which they didn't make a
field goal until the 5:18 mark? But they were at least consistent _
shooting 37.5 percent in the first, 37.5 percent in the second and
36.2 in the third.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' only solace was a flight home, a day off to look
forward to and the knowledge that the next two games both involve
the Clippers. And even that matchup seems like less than a sure
thing.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the Lakers take the court again, though, they will
be a changed team. Dennis Rodman will see to that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a new face coming in, it's a change,'' Bryant said. ``He
definitely is gonna give us a burst of energy.''
</P>
<P>
   Right about now, the Lakers will take what they can get. Even if
it comes in a dress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
