<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DAY OF GIVE, AND NOT MUCH TAKE FOR A SMILING BONILLA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ On the morning of his 36th birthday,
Bobby Bonilla began what could be a long and difficult healing
process by trying to reinvent himself in the eyes of the New York
news media.
</P>
<P>
   He was funny. He was engaging. He was relaxed. And this time, he
did not challenge anybody to wipe the smile off his face.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the day, Bonilla, who often experienced stormy
times with the New York Mets from 1992 to 1995, had even created a
new role for himself, hitting instructor for the Mets' other new
corner outfielder, a 40-year-old left fielder named Rickey
Henderson.
</P>
<P>
   If Bonilla, never known for his defense, can reinvent himself as
an outfielder, the Mets' pitching staff might not need to worry so
much about balls hit to right field.
</P>
<P>
   More than once during a surprisingly humorous group interview on
his first day in a Mets uniform since 1995, Bonilla poked fun at
himself, the news media and a remark made by his new manager, Bobby
Valentine, on the day he was reacquired by the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 11, after the Mets had shipped the disgruntled reliever
Mel Rojas to Los Angeles for Bonilla, Valentine said that with
Bonilla in the outfield, the ``risk is whether he catches the ball
when it comes down.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Bonilla quipped more than once, ``There's a good
chance that if I'm under it, I'll catch it.'' The question, of
course, is whether Bonilla will be able to get to the ball. But
even Bonilla, who had a little trouble shagging balls here in the
morning sun, had to admit: ``I'm not here to do sprints. I'm here
to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   What began on one of the Mets' practice fields with Henderson
seeking advice from Bonilla on his leg kick after the two had taken
their first rusty, supervised swings of the spring, gradually
evolved into a give-and-take between two top hitters.
</P>
<P>
   And long after most of the other Mets had retreated to the
showers after the day's workout, Bonilla was working overtime with
Henderson in an otherwise deserted batting cage, soft-tossing him
balls from behind a screen, giving Henderson tips on his stride and
on the proper way to hit the inside pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not really being a hitting instructor,'' Bonilla said
after. ``It's just sharing what we've learned over the years. I'm
always up to talk about hitting with anybody who wants to. I just
don't know if the younger players do that as much anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it is just that, as Valentine said, ``A lot of guys
don't know enough about hitting to talk about it.'' Not Henderson
and Bonilla. Together, they have 32 seasons of major league
experience and three World Series rings. But both are coming off
down seasons, which may be one reason why they were both here
today, two days before the Mets' first scheduled full workout. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Henderson is legendary for not coming to camp on time. But
despite leading the American League in walks and stolen bases last
season, he batted a career-low .236. He feels he has become too
passive at the plate. And that was why Henderson decided to seek
Bonilla out for a little advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two or three years, I've been hesitant at bat, not as
aggressive as I had been in the past,'' Henderson said, attributing
the tendency to his first experience in the National League, with
the Padres in 1996 and 1997. ``I got away from my leg kick in San
Diego. And Bobby has it down pat.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, the two engaged in a hitters' discussion, much like
pitchers often do about their trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rickey was very receptive,'' Bonilla later said.
</P>
<P>
   Will the New York news media be the same?
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in 1992, Bonilla got off to a good start on Tuesday. When
asked what went wrong in his first go-around with the Mets, Bonilla
cracked: ``What year? There were four of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The first year was probably the most disappointing. The Mets had
made Bonilla the highest-paid player in the game. But he hit just
.249, and the Mets stumbled to fifth place, 24 games behind the
Pirates, the team Bonilla had left.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at '92, people will say I struggled,'' Bonilla
said. ``But at the All-Star break, I had the same numbers I usually
have. And apparently they just weren't good enough. I think there
was a longing for Darryl Strawberry. And saying stuff like you
wouldn't be able to knock the smile off my face didn't help. I
think they took it literally, and tried their best to do just
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla was referring to the comments he had made at his
introductory news conference in 1992. But this morning, the people
he talked to were smiling, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
