<SLUG> BC-BKL-WNBA-ABL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLER, WEBB DIFFER ON INFUSION OF ABL TALENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF METCALFE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Mercury coach wants the WNBA doors thrown open to all former
American Basketball League players, but one of her starters isn't
so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has to be some boundary where people who started the
league and stuck with it should be rewarded for it,'' small forward
Umeki Webb said. ``It's going to be good (having one U.S. pro
women's league) once it evolves and the number of teams increases.
Right now, it's not good for the people in the WNBA.''
</P>
<P>
   Webb and teammate Brandy Reed are among more than 30 WNBA
veterans who finish a five-day training camp today in Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Reed has missed most of the workouts because of a bruised
shoulder that will be examined when she comes to Phoenix to join
Webb, Jennifer Gillom, Toni Foster and Coach-General Manager Cheryl
Miller for Saturday's Mercury Madness fan festival.
</P>
<P>
   Miller admits her advocacy of no limit on the number of ABL
players allowed into the WNBA this season is not popular among WNBA
players, who are in negotiations for a collective bargaining
agreement with the third-year league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the best players possible,'' Miller said. ``Whatever it
takes to strengthen the Phoenix Mercury.''
</P>
<P>
   But Webb, who started every game last season as an undersized
5-foot-10 small forward because of her defensive intensity, is the
classic example of a player threatened by the 20 to 30 ABL
front-liners who are without U.S. jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Those familiar with the two meetings so far between the National
Basketball Players Association, the union representing WNBA
players, and the WNBA say they think an ABL limit is a given and
would stand up in court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Speaking to WNBA players, that's really important to them,''
said Evan Korth, vice president of business affairs for Bruce Levy
Associates, the agency representing the most WNBA players. ``My
understanding is there are certain categories you're not allowed to
discriminate against (age, race), but you can on other things.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Wasserman, NBPA director of communications, said: ``It goes
to the issue of job security. These players took less to help make
this league successful, and to turn around and replace them with
players who didn't make that sacrifice would be hypocritical and go
against the commitment they asked of these players in the first
place.''
</P>
<P>
   Options include limiting the number of ABL players leaguewide or
per team (two is the number most often suggested), combined with an
increased roster (from 11 to 12) and accelerated expansion. An
extra roster spot plus the new teams in Orlando and Minnesota would
create 34 more jobs for this season, which begins June 12.
</P>
<P>
   Webb, 23, was the Mercury's third-round draft pick out of North
Carolina State in 1997. She went overseas for the first time after
the Mercury's WNBA runner-up finish, playing point guard in Greece
for two months to improve her ballhandling. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
