<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990224.0036 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6977 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     02-24 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DALE ROBERTSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
FOR a rookie playing out of position, he's playing pretty solid.
Every day becomes an excellent new adventure for Cuttino Mobley,
whose Sicilian grandmother named him, molded him and now, he says,
smiles down upon him.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``She's been (gone) since I was, like, 9 years old,'' Mobley
says, ``but I'm still trying my best to make her proud of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Grandma, you should be. Houston says thank you.
</P>
<P>
   As an NBA player, the Cat is just a kitten, but his courage and
his chutzpah made the Rockets purr Tuesday night _ if not yet
perfect. Although he has no right to be lighting up a team of
Seattle's pedigree in the fourth quarter only three weeks into his
fledgling professional career, he simply doesn't know any better.
</P>
<P>
   Mobley sank a winning shot at the buzzer of his first game, a
fine omen. Now this: 13 points in 12 minutes of money time,
including nine in a row and 11 of the team's 12 over a crucial
stretch as the Rockets, having just staggered in off the road trip
from hell, pulled away down the stretch to defeat Seattle 98-86.
</P>
<P>
   For now, for at least another day, they have found their point
guard. So what if Mobley was a clearly defined two guard coming out
of college?
</P>
<P>
   ``His college coach (Jim Harrick at Rhode Island) told us
Cuttino was the biggest winner he'd ever been around,'' Rudy
Tomjanovich said of the second-round draft choice, who was only the
third pick of three rookie guards on the revamped Rockets roster.
</P>
<P>
   And to put such a statement in perspective, remember Harrick had
won a national championship at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Mobley is, to be sure, a work in progress. Most conspicuously,
he jacks up some really dumb shots. Tomjanovich had to call a
timeout in Miami to berate him for one particularly atrocious
decision. But he's not afraid to try to make things happen, and
that instinct can't be taught. Nor can the ability to create
opportunities for oneself, which he does remarkably well.
</P>
<P>
   He spent the full four seasons at Rhode Island and led the Rams
to the Elite Eight last spring. Sort of tells you the importance of
the maturity factor, doesn't it? He's young, but he's not that
young. At 24, he's spotting fellow rookie Rashard Lewis five years.
The Sonics' Lewis also started, but he lasted exactly four minutes.
His linescore was pure zeros, except for two fouls and a turnover.
</P>
<P>
   Mobley, for his part, was on the floor 39 minutes, launching 13
shots (he made five), snaring six rebounds and accumulating five
assists. He had three turnovers, five fewer than his eminently more
accomplished counterpart, Gary Payton. But Payton had seven steals,
too, vs. none for Cat.
</P>
<P>
   For the bulk of the last quarter, Payton and Mobley were the
respective go-to guys. One prominent spectator in the usual
sold-out crowd at Compaq Center this evening, a certain large round
man who answered to Chuck, admitted: ``I love the kid's talent. I
really do.''
</P>
<P>
   But Charles Barkley added: ``He's got to learn to harness it.''
</P>
<P>
   Another illustrious oldster who knows a little bit about great
guard play seemed to second the Chuckster's cautionary notion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to take away from his confidence,'' Scottie
Pippen said. ``But a lot of times, he feels like he has to take
advantage of every opportunity instead of controlling the game and
realizing those opportunities will be there throughout the game.''
</P>
<P>
   You suspect both stars remain suspicious of Mobley as a point
guard. And in a normal season, one featuring a normal training
camp, we might never have seen Mobley in there with Brent Price,
the veteran would-be point guard, occupying the two spot in a game
that counted in the standings.
</P>
<P>
   But Rudy is coaching by the seat of his pants these days and
experimenting on the run. There's no time to sort out the details
in practice. Uh, what practice?
</P>
<P>
   ``I like that lineup,'' Tomjanovich said of the
Mobley-Price-Pippen-Harrington-Olajuwon combo that finished against
the Sonics, who came in 7-2.
</P>
<P>
   But don't make the assumption it's cut in stone. Rudy wouldn't
guarantee that's how he'll go against Atlanta on Thursday, although
he's probably just being his usual coy self.
</P>
<P>
   Even after Mobley had a fine effort in Orlando on Sunday,
scoring 13 points on 5-of-7 shooting in an otherwise dismal Rockets
effort, Tomjanovich made no announcement of his encore start
against the Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   Mobley had assumed nothing, either. He's as amazed as the rest
of us by the sudden starring role he's in. Asked if, a few months
ago, he could have foreseen himself being a starting point man in
the NBA, he replied: ``I can laugh about that one. No way.''
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, stranger things have happened. Just none comes to
mind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
