<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6992 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     02-24 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DICTATING RULES OF BASEBALL NOT UMPIRES' CALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ (Begin italic) RULES OF BASEBALL: The strike zone is
that area over home plate the upper limit of which is a horizontal
line at the midpoint between the top of the shoulders and the top
of the uniform pants, and the lower level is a line at the hollow
beneath the knee cap. (end italic)
</P>
<P>
   Printed in black and white, right there in your Official Rules
of Baseball handbook, are the words describing the vertical
confines of baseball's strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   For any man, woman, child or major league umpire who still finds
this passage a bit too antiquated or too open to interpretation,
let's try a more elementary description: armpits to kneecaps.
</P>
<P>
   If this description sufficiently addresses the zone's vertical
limits, why does baseball's strike zone continue to float like a
butterfly and sting like a bee?
</P>
<P>
   Why does the strike zone shrink and expand more than a big
floppy sponge in the kitchen sink?
</P>
<P>
   Why is there one strike zone in the American League with its own
set of umpires and another in the National League, whose crew sees
things a little more generously in favor of the pitchers?
</P>
<P>
   And why does a major league umpire walk away from a game in the
1997 NL Championship Series after helping Marlins' pitcher Livan
Hernandez achieve a liberal 15 strikeouts and respond to criticism
by stating, ``Everyone should know my strike zone?''
</P>
<P>
   (It is not ``your'' strike zone, Mr. Eric Gregg. It is
baseball's strike zone. Or at least it should be.)
</P>
<P>
   The answers, my friends, are blowing in the hot wind emanating
from baseball's umpires' union: This is their game, they bluster.
</P>
<P>
   But something revolutionary is happening in the mad, mixed-up
world of major league baseball. With the 1999 season just a month
away, a higher authority from someplace called ``The Commissioner's
Office'' is making a bold attempt to wrest control back from a
radical splinter group, more commonly known as umpires.
</P>
<P>
   Incredible, really.
</P>
<P>
   In a memo to all 30 big-league teams, the new executive director
of baseball operations, Sandy Alderson, issued notice last Friday
that the official definition of the strike zone ``will be more
strictly enforced'' by umpires this season.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in a sport where the umpires' union could not be any
stronger if it were run by Che Guevera, Jimmy Hoffa and Norma Rae,
the new strike-zone enforcement edict has royally ticked off the
union chief, Richie Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see how anyone could say we're going to strictly
enforce a rule,'' Phillips was quoted by the Associated Press'
baseball guru, Ben Walker.
</P>
<P>
   ``The umpires enforce all of the rules. That's been their job
for more than 100 years. It is deplorable of the commissioner's
office to indicate that the umpires have not strictly enforced all
the rules,'' Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   Who made Phillips keeper of the game?
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Phillips did not venture an explanation about why
American League umpire ``Terrible'' Ted Hendry's strike zone has
more permutations than an episode of ``The X-Files.''
</P>
<P>
   The point is, umpires are unwilling to relinquish their
unrelenting grip on the game of baseball. They are by far the
strongest officiating union in the galaxy. They are overzealous and
so in need of being reined in that, miraculously, the players'
union and the owners are in agreement on this issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the union in baseball has much more influence than any
other officials in the NBA, the National Hockey League or the
NFL,'' NBA senior vice president of basketball operations Rod Thorn
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a lot of influence, though it looks like (baseball
is) trying to move'' toward placing control of the rules in the
commissioner's office.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball must go the way of the NBA and the other leagues when
it comes to seizing control of the most fundamental aspects of the
sport.
</P>
<P>
   The rules are the game. The rules are just as critical, if not
more so, than baseball's superstars, light shows and entertainment
elements.
</P>
<P>
   Enforcing them uniformly is tantamount to fair play. Just ask
tennis about its Cyclops machine, which is used to minimize human
error on line calls. Or ask the NFL about its need to reinstitute
instant replay. Or ask the NBA, which just fined Shaquille O'Neal
$10,000 for criticizing NBA refs for not calling fouls he feels
were committed against him.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the power for making sure the rules are interpreted
as uniformly as possible and that games are called as cleanly and
objectively as possible should not rest with a power-hungry bunch
of umpires, but with some higher authority, even if it is one as
historically slippery as baseball's office of the commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any decisions about rules comes under the aegis of the
commissioner's office ... and anytime we make a rules change, we
don't consult with the referees. We give the referees the
interpretations and their leaders make sure those are carried
out,'' Thorn said, adding, ``They better adhere to them or they'll
get themselves fired.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine baseball exerting that sort of control in its own house.
What a novel idea.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-99 0213EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
