<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 02:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6993 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI &LR;      02-24 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCKETS SOCK IT TO SONICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Because Sonics coach Paul Westphal readily admits to
being a huge Bob Dylan fan, it is safe to assume that he can endure
any Dylan melody over and over again.
</P>
<P>
   If only Westphal could say the same for his struggling offense.
</P>
<P>
   Just when the Sonics seemed to be in tune, they again skipped a
beat, losing Tuesday night to the Houston Rockets 98-86 at a
sold-out Compaq Center. After seemingly striking offensive accord
and balance with Sunday's win against the Los Angeles Lakers, the
Sonics (7-3) fell victim to their early season problems.
</P>
<P>
   They stood around, watched Gary Payton take over and got very
limited production from anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   It is to the point where Westphal can hardly stomach what is
becoming an annoying broken record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm starting to think it's less of an aberration and more of a
trend,'' Westphal said. ``We've got to execute better on offense.
We're not cashing in on our opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   The team's trials with the offense resulted in its third loss in
four games. And the Sonics play another tough Western Conference
opponent tonight in San Antonio at the Alamodome.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of Payton (11 of 22 for 26 points) and Detlef
Schrempf (9 of 16 for 20 points), no one shot better than 50
percent. The Sonics combined to shoot just 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   They haven't shot better than 45 percent this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate the guys weren't hitting shots,'' Payton
said. ``We're not making shots a lot. It's going to be up to me to
keep getting them the ball. All I can do is keep getting them the
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   At times, Payton seemed as though he was the only Sonic tuned
into the game. He nearly posted a quadruple double, finishing with
10 assists and seven steals to go with his game-high point total.
But Payton turned the ball over an unusually high eight times.
</P>
<P>
   That was more a product of his aggression than anything. If it
weren't for Payton, the Sonics would have never been in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Houston led the entire first half and most of the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics trailed 60-50 with 6:14 left in the third when Payton
made one of his mini-runs. He scored eight straight points and got
the Sonics within 60-58.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Olden Polynice split two free throws and Schrempf sank a
3-pointer that put the Sonic ahead 62-60. The 12-0 spurt was all
the Sonics had left.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets scored the final nine points of the quarter. Brent
Price's buzzer-beating 3-pointer at the end of the third gave the
Rockets a 69-62 advantage. The basket deflated the already wilted
Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were never able to recover,'' Polynice said.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics never got closer than six points the rest of the
game. They were stung in the fourth quarter by rookie Cuttino
Mobley, who made just his second NBA start. Mobley scored 11
straight points midway in the fourth and the Sonics trailed 85-74
with 4:50 left.
</P>
<P>
   Mobley's two free throws buried the Sonics 92-82 with 1:08 left.
He finished with a career-high 19 points, which tied Scottie Pippen
and Hakeem Olajuwon for the team high.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stood around and let them do whatever they wanted,''
Westphal said. ``We did a lot of good things defensively after we
let them get started. We just shouldn't have let them get
started.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first half, the Sonics had no answer for Rockets center
Olajuwon and forward Pippen. Olajuwon scored his first six points
within five feet of the basket. Pippen drilled his first six shots,
including three 3-pointers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came in a little soft defensively, and that gave them
confidence,'' Polynice said. ``We were confused.''
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, Polynice and Vin Baker were nonfactors.
</P>
<P>
   Polynice did not defend Olajuwon with the same energy he used
two days earlier against Shaquille O'Neal. He had nine rebounds,
but missed his three shots.
</P>
<P>
   Baker was worse. He shot 4 of 13, settling mostly for outside
shots.
</P>
<P>
   In typical fashion, the Sonics corrected their defensive
problems in the second half. Pippen and Olajuwon scored just four
points in the last two quarters.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics, though, were even more flat.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still lots of time,'' guard Hersey Hawkins said.
``We're still not executing the second and third options.
Everybody's struggling. When you have two or three guys struggling,
for some reason it becomes contagious.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
