A7012 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAVIS-VICEPRESIDENCY-     02-24 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAVIS-VICEPRESIDENCY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 DAVIS DENIES INTEREST IN VICE PRESIDENCY  &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ California Gov. Gray Davis sought Tuesday to
squelch speculation that he will use his recent victory as a
springboard for national office, saying he would refuse any offer
to be a vice presidential nominee even if Al Gore picked up the
phone and asked him directly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any national ambitions,'' said Davis, in town for
the National Governors Association meetings. ``I spent 23 years
preparing to be governor of California, and now that I have climbed
to the top of the hill, I don't want to leave it.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before Davis' big win in the vote-rich Golden State, his
name was being bandied about in national Democratic circles as a
possible running mate for Vice President Gore, the clear favorite
for the Democratic nomination in the 2000 presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be an honor, but I took an oath to serve four
years,'' said Davis at a lunch with reporters. ``I think it's very
important to keep your word in politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who spent Sunday night at the White House with his wife,
Sharon, and met privately with both Gore and President Clinton,
said Gore's experience in two national campaigns gives him an
advantage in California.
</P>
<P>
   Gore ``knows the difference between the Inland Empire and the
San Fernando Valley,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   The new governor also had kind words for the man he replaced,
Pete Wilson, who announced this week that he would not run again
for president for lack of money.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said he sent a note to Wilson saying he had a ``remarkable
career'' as a Marine, a mayor, and twice-elected senator and
California governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not too shabby,'' said Davis. Rather than being
disappointed by passing up another presidential bid, Davis said
Wilson ``should take time to reflect proudly on more than 30 years
of public service.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis called Wilson the ``toughest kind of Republican'' for a
Democrat to beat, given his centrist views on abortion, the
environment and other divisive issues, and he lamented that the
Republican Party's right wing appears hostile to moderates like
Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Davis characterized himself as ``a millimeter left of center''
and Wilson as ``a couple of millimeters right of center,'' and said
it is ``much harder to draw a contrast'' between Democrats and
Republicans who share moderate views.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would think there would be some place for a moderate (in
the GOP),'' Davis said, ``but maybe there isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis went on to describe views hardly distinguishable from
conservative on a host of issues, from his opposition to taxes on
Internet sales, to his insistence that states should be freed from
federal mandates, to his support for allowing individuals to invest
part of their Social Security payroll taxes in the stock market
``within certain guidelines.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis' opposition to Internet sales taxes puts him in league
with Wilson and at odds with the vast majority of his fellow
governors, who see the Internet draining states' chief source of
tax revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just not the time to be raising taxes,'' with states
running big budget surpluses, Davis said, adding that taxing
Internet sales ``sends the wrong signal'' about government's
attitude toward the Internet and high technology.
</P>
<P>
   Davis also said that while he would urge legislative action in
Sacramento to crack down on health maintenance organizations that
fail to provide adequate care to patients, he does not think the
ultimate solution lies in ``more lawsuits and regulations.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis said he favors a ``two-track approach'' that would
threaten regulation but also acknowledge that the government is in
no position to practice medicine by telling providers how to treat
patients.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding President Clinton's education proposals to reduce
class sizes for kindergarten through third grade, Davis said he had
already spoken to the president and four of his Cabinet secretaries
to ask for greater flexibility in using the money.
</P>
<P>
   California has already made a major effort, including passage of
a $9billion bond measure, to reduce class sizes in the primary
grades, Davis said, and the state should now focus on reducing
class sizes in the high schools. Davis wants to spend the money to
reduce high school class sizes instead, because the state had
already made a major effort in the primary grades.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
