 ENTERTAINMENT No. 422 - February 24, 1999  
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. ELTON JOHN RIDING HIGH WITH 'AIDA' SET When Elton John
expressed interest in working on a second project with Tim Rice for
Disney he made it clear that he wanted something more ``dangerous''
than the Oscar-winning soundtrack to the animated film ``The Lion
King'' that the pair created in 1994. Disney suggested that he
adapt the Verdi opera ``Aida'' into a musical stage production,
complete with an accompanying pop/R&AMP;B soundtrack that would bring
its music to the masses. ``It's such a great story,'' says Elton
John, ``and it was too interesting and too challenging to turn
down. I'd never done anything especially for the stage before, so
it was a first for me, something completely different.'' The result
is a multi-tiered musical journey that evokes a new level of
artistic mastery. By Chuck Taylor. Billboard. 1,700 words + photo.
2. THE ANALYTICAL WORLD OF BILLY CRYSTAL In his latest film,
``Analyze This,'' Billy Crystal plays a psychiatrist who finds
himself treating a troubled mob boss (played by Robert De Niro.)
The timing of the film's release is why he turned down an
invitation to handle this year's Oscar-hosting duties. ``I work so
hard to make the Oscars look easy, but it is a lot of work,'' he
says. De Niro - who's had an Oscar night or two himself - may seem
an unlikely co-star for the irreverent comedian, but Crystal
insists that the two actually worked well together. By Cindy
Pearlman. 1,300 words + photo. 3. MAKING FRIENDS WITH LISA KUDROW
Winner of New York Film Critics Circle's best supporting actress
prize for hr role in the hit film ``The Opposite of Sex,'' Lisa
Kudrow (who plays Phoebe on the TV show ``Friends,'') shares her
thoughts on motherhood, sit-com salaries and the price of playing a
long line of blonde dimwits. By Christopher Bagley. From W
magazine. 1,000 words + photos. 4. A PINCH OF SNUFF Of all the
gruesome urban legends, the snuff film is perhaps the most
chilling. Supposedly, these are movies in which people are actually
killed in front of the camera's cold eye. But do they actually
exist? ``I hope not,'' says filmmaker Joel Schumacher. And yet his
new thriller ``Eight Millimeter,'' starring Nicolas Cage, is based
on the premise that they are real. Despite the unrelenting grimness
of its subject matter, it is a film with a definite moral core that
deals with extremes of human behaviour. By Joshua Mooney. BPI.
1,100 words + photo. 
____________________________________________________________________
____________ 5. PAUL ROBESON : AN AMERICAN MASTER His life has
practically been erased from American history because of his
revolutionary and outspoken views during the 1930s and '40s. Who is
Paul Robeson? He was a Renaissance man : a successful actor,
singer, athlete, linguist, cultural scholar, author and political
activist. He was an African American dedicated to furthering human
rights all over the world. Now, 100 years after his birth, his life
is once again being celebrated. By Tamara Conniff. BPI. 900 words +
photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 6.
'INTENTIONAL' GROUNDING : SARAH MICHELLE GELLAR
</P>
<P>
   MOVES BEYOND 'BUFFY' Buffy the Vampire Slayer may need her mouth
washed out with soap after this. Sarah Michelle Gellar, who played
Buffy on the TV show, curses like a trooper in Roger Kumble's
``Cruel Intentions'' and she says she relished every scandalous
second of it. Audiences used to Gellar beating up vampires on
``Buffy'' are in for quite a shock when ``Cruel Intentions'' opens
(it's a modern version of the classic French work ``Les Liaisons
Dangereuses,'' set in Manhattan's ritzy Upper East Side.) By Ian
Spelling. 1,300 words + photo. 7. HOLLYWOOD OBSERVER : KIMBERLY
ELISE IS TAKING NOTES Kimberly Elise Trammel Oldham is an
up-and-coming star. She recently played Oprah Winfrey's daughter in
``Beloved'' (1998.) Her quiet but forceful performance is the
film's great revelation, a Newsweek review said. Today the actress
finds her race to be less of an obstacle, even in frequently
racially troubled Los Angeles. It's sexism that makes her angry.
``Maybe it's an industry thing, but you really have to fight for
your respect as a woman in this town,'' she says. ``And as a black
actress, there's the hurdle of having to fight for people to see
beyond your colour.'' She doesn't see herself as an overnight
success. ``It seems quick to other people, but I've known it as my
destiny since I was very young, and it's been years of learning, a
long process.'' By Jon Krampner. 1,300 words + photo. Please fax to
Paris 33.1.47.42.80.44 or 33.1.47.42.18.81
</P>
