<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7159 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISSGAMB25-COX     02-24 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSGAMB25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gulf towns wary of casinos' boom
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GULFPORT, Miss. _ A developer wants to take control of a city
park and the only public marina and build high-rise hotels,
condominiums and a casino.
</P>
<P>
   Down U.S. 90 in Biloxi, a casino company plans to fill in 54
acres of the Gulf of Mexico for a six-casino, 12-hotel, mega-resort
unlike anything now on the Mississippi Gulf Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another developer has proposed filling in more than 200
acres of water adjacent to small, forested Deer Island for a
casino-hotel project.
</P>
<P>
   As casinos eat up waterfront property in the two Gulf counties
where gambling is legal, and developers propose ever more creative
ways to squeeze in more slot machines and gambling tables, some
people, even some gambling supporters, are wondering: How much is
too much?
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the proposed ``Millennium'' resort in the Gulfport
park, local lawyer Virgil Gillespie said, ``I am 100 percent pro
casinos, but this is a project I am not personally for. I don't
think the city should give away its only public space on the water
just because a casino comes around waving money.''
</P>
<P>
   The resort would displace the marina, the White Cap Restaurant
and Burt Jones Park, given to the city in 1935 by the family of the
founders of Gulfport. The developer, Alfred Dana Jr. of Florida,
has said the project would include a new park and marina. Some City
Council members have voiced support for the development, which has
not come up for a final vote, but the mayor and at least one
councilman oppose the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the city gives away that property, it would discourage
other donors from ever giving property to the city,'' Councilman
Sam Albritton said. ``I'm not going to let anybody take control of
a park that's for the people.''
</P>
<P>
   At the White Cap, a seafood restaurant and local hangout for
almost 30 years, folks are against the project. ``Even if we could
stay, the casino would bring in an influx of out-of-towners and it
could drive the locals away,'' said Josh Dibble, a restaurant
manager whose uncles own the White Cap. ``This place and the marina
are part of the heritage here. Why change it?''
</P>
<P>
   Saying ``no'' to the gaming industry isn't easy for the poorest
state in the nation. Thirty casinos _ 11 on the coast, the rest
along the Mississippi River _ employ 33,000 people. They generate
more than $167 million in state tax revenues. On the Gulf Coast,
once a notoriously depressed region, there are now more jobs than
people to fill them, and the cities and counties there make
millions from a 4-percent tax the casinos pay to local governments.
More than 24 million people gambled on the Gulf Coast last year,
according to the Mississippi Gaming Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere on the coast have the casinos been more welcome than in
Biloxi. Seven out of 10 voters said ``yes'' to casinos in 1990, and
today, eight casinos cover nearly every available square foot of
shoreline.
</P>
<P>
   Two proposed casinos on Back Bay are tied up in litigation. And
the City Council last week approved plans by President Casino to
fill in 54 acres of the Gulf to build a massive $2.5 billion
complex of six casinos and 12 hotels around a marina.
</P>
<P>
   But the council had to override a veto by Mayor A.J. Holloway,
who says he thinks the project goes too far.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely for development and business, but this is
something I don't think the area is ready for,'' he said. ``If they
fill in 54 acres, then where does it stop? Another one might come
in and want to fill in 100 acres.''
</P>
<P>
   But John Aylsworth, president of President Casinos, said support
for the project has been ``unprecedented.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor-appointed Commission on Marine Resources voted 4-2
for the project. But Vernon Asper, a marine biologist on the
commission, voted against it, saying it would pave the way for more
casinos to ask to do the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This project would be of no benefit to the citizens of
Mississippi or to the coast,'' Asper said. ``It would be different
if our economy was really bad and we still had 13 percent
unemployment. We have more jobs than we have people. Every time we
get more jobs, we have to get more people, and more
infrastructure.''
</P>
<P>
   But for some residents, there is no such thing as too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since 1992, my business has doubled. Biloxi was six months in
the red, and now it is really financially sound. We have to be the
envy of every city in the United States,'' said Bobby Mahoney,
owner of Mary Mahoney's, a landmark Biloxi restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
