<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERGLADES-BIRDS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Birds wade back into Everglades
 &HT;    By Robert P. King
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The word on wading birds for 1999:
Better. But not great.
</P>
<P>
   For wood storks, herons, egrets and ibises looking to feather
their nests this spring, the Everglades is once again rolling out a
soggy welcome mat. Fewer birds than average are flocking to South
Florida's marshes, where rain has pushed water levels nearly to the
brim for yet another year.
</P>
<P>
   One consolation: Scientists have found more than three times as
many birds as they saw in February 1998, when a wet El Nin(tilde)o
and a glutted drainage system led to a disastrous nesting season.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists often use wading birds as a barometer of the
Everglades' health, because nesting is disrupted by the same flood
control system that has turned free-flowing marshes into
bathtub-like reservoirs. Bird populations today are a fraction of
the super-colonies, hundreds of thousands strong, that darkened the
skies in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   In aerial surveys early this month, the U.S. Army Corps of
Engineers estimated that 31,400 wading birds were flocking in the
state-owned Everglades marshes north of Everglades National Park.
That's more than triple the 9,000 they found a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The increase was even more notable in the Everglades'
northernmost remnant, the Arthur R. Marshall Loxahatchee National
Wildlife Refuge in Palm Beach County. There, the numbers more than
quadrupled to more than 12,100 from 2,880.
</P>
<P>
   The overall total was still less than half the number of birds
that arrived in 1997 and less than half the February average since
1985.
</P>
<P>
   ``There weren't any really great years in the 1990s,'' said John
Ogden, a biologist and bird expert at the South Florida Water
Management District. He said it's too soon to predict how this
nesting season will turn out, but he said he expects a better year
than last year.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said, two things will tend to keep birds away: Water
levels are still high, and a mild winter up north gives the birds
less incentive to fly to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   High water can make it hard for the birds to wade. It also
interferes with the winter dry spells that are supposed to make
waterways shrink, collecting the birds' prey into a concentrated
smorgasbord.
</P>
<P>
   Years of high water have also killed large stretches of trees
that serve as rookeries.
</P>
<P>
   Another disturbing sign: Some people are seeing the wading birds
in urban ponds, which could means the birds are finding the
Everglades less than homey.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
