<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7162 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KELSO-COLUMN25-COX     02-24 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Theory of everything + T-shirts   $
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ I'm not much at physics. When I took it in high
school, I thought they said psychics and sat around waiting for a
palm reading.
</P>
<P>
   But let me try to explain this to you anyway. A Texas A&AMP;M
physics professor is trying to develop a formula that is both short
enough to fit on a T-shirt and complicated enough to explain
everything _ or at least every physical thing _ in the universe.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Duff, who has been working on finding the ``theory of
everything'' since he got his Ph.D. in 1972, says finding the
theory could be years away. But he's looking.
</P>
<P>
   This is A&AMP;M we're talking about here. What's this got to do with
sheep, football or maroon carrots? Beats me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes people in other fields or nonscientists think we're
being arrogant by claiming to have a theory of everything,'' Duff
said. ``So it's important to make it clear that when a physicist
talks about a theory of everything, he's talking about the
universe, the fundamental constituents of matter, the laws of
nature.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, no matter what, you should still change the oil
every 3,000 miles.
</P>
<P>
   No, seriously, scientists really have been busting their noggins
to find a formula that will explain everything. But this has been
difficult, Duff says, because of the incompatibility of the two
pillars of physics.
</P>
<P>
   These are quantum theory, which describes tiny subatomic
phenomena, and Einstein's theory of relativity, which says
everybody in Arkansas is a relative of everybody else.
</P>
<P>
   Just joshing with you on that one. Einstein's theory of
relativity describes gravitational phenomena, Duff said.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Duff said, breakthroughs have been made in the
search for the theory of everything because scientists have
determined that the tiny stuff that makes up matter isn't
necessarily ``point-like particles,'' as previously thought. Why
this matters I have no clue, because in college I majored in beer,
with a minor in girls.
</P>
<P>
   But Duff says another theory is that matter is made up of
one-dimensional string-shaped objects called ``super strings.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like a violin string, these strings can vibrate, and each
different mode of vibration represents a different elementary
particle,'' Duff said.
</P>
<P>
   I think I saw that band on Austin City Limits.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, other scientists, including Duff, are leaning toward
the new ``M theory,'' which says matter is constructed of
``two-dimensional bubble-like objects.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're optimistic that this M theory may indeed provide the
long sought after theory of everything, because it will incorporate
not only quantum theory, but also Einstein's theory of
relativity,'' Duff said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of spending their time on this high-falutin' stuff, why
don't they do something practical and important, like make a better
cream gravy or figure out why a dog's leg twitches uncontrollably
when you scratch its belly.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the moment, I don't see any practical application,'' Duff
said of the everything formula. ``But history has taught us that
whenever we've had these major theoretical breakthroughs, in the
course of time they've been found to be of use in one way or
another.''
</P>
<P>
   One way or another, in this case, might be T-shirt sales. If
Duff could write the theory of everything short enough to stick on
a shirt, he might could sell the snot out of them.
</P>
<P>
   Let me know when they're ready. I'll take an extra large.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso's humor column appears on Sundays, Wednesdays and
Fridays. He can be reached at jkelso(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
