<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas, Alabama lawmakers pushing to take over bedroom
 &HT;    By Roland Nethaway
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Not that long ago, out-of-state visitors were
appalled to see Texans openly swigging from Jack Daniel's or Lone
Star bottles while driving down the road with an arsenal of weapons
within easy reach.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors went from appalled to flabbergasted if they reported
this behavior only to be told that drinking and driving with loaded
guns was perfectly legal in Texas as long as things didn't get out
of hand.
</P>
<P>
   When Texas lawmakers first started talking about the need to ban
drinking and driving, Texans from across the state urged their
elected representatives to vote against the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Editorials in major Texas newspapers said Texas already had a
law against driving while drunk. Another law was unneeded and would
punish Texans who simply wanted to drink a cold beer while driving
home after work.
</P>
<P>
   Texas lawmakers listened to their constituents and voted down
the repeated efforts to ban drinking and driving.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the increasing threats and pleas from the federal
government, Mothers Against Drunk Driving and traffic safety
organizations from across the nation won the day. Texas also banned
drinking and driving.
</P>
<P>
   That broke the dam. Texas lawmakers went from a reputation of
leaving people alone as long as they didn't frighten the horses to
a reputation for passing all manner of laws to control behavior.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, a lot of laws, rules and regulations have been
forced on Texans by federal lawmakers and bureaucrats who have made
it their life's work to uniformly regulate the behavior of
Americans from sea to shining sea.
</P>
<P>
   But Texas lawmakers became quite capable of passing silly,
intrusive laws on their own with absolutely no pressure from the
federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the Texas veggie libel law that allows citizens to be
hauled into court and punished financially if they insult a Texas
cow, chicken, carrot or other home-grown commodity.
</P>
<P>
   A group of Texas ranchers used their new law to try to punish TV
star Oprah Winfrey for saying she didn't like hamburgers. They
ended up looking like whining crybabies, which all but destroyed
the image of Texans as rugged individualists.
</P>
<P>
   Just the other day I learned that Texas lawmakers passed another
silly, intrusive law that makes it illegal for Texans to use sex
toys such as vibrators behind closed doors.
</P>
<P>
   The first I heard that Texas had such a law came from a news
story that reported a lawsuit filed by a group of Alabama women.
The women are asking a federal judge to block a new Alabama law
banning sales of such items, sometimes referred to as ``marital
aids.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers representing Alabama defended their law by arguing that
there is no fundamental right to a product used to produce an
orgasm. They also argued that Alabama's law is modeled after a
similar law in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   That's a slam-dunk legal argument if I ever heard one. ``Well,
your honor, they do it this way in Texas.'' Case dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Alabama's American Civil Liberties Union is solidly behind the
constitutional rights of vibrator users and sellers. ACLU lawyers
told the judge that sex therapists recommend vibrators for women
who cannot achieve orgasm.
</P>
<P>
   A Feb. 23 Chicago Tribune editorial defended vibrator use. ``As
long as they (the Alabama women) pursue their activities behind
closed doors, they aren't likely to hurt property values.'' That's
darn reasonable.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this silly, intrusive law started in Texas, but the fact
remains that Texas women didn't feel a need to sue to stop the law.
If the Alabama women can't find what they're looking for in the
courts, perhaps they should move to Texas. Just don't frighten the
horses or insult the veggies.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
His column appears Wednesdays and Fridays. E-mail:
RNethaway(at)mail.wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
