<HEADER>
A7165 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TELEMARKETERS25-COX     02-24 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELEMARKETERS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Telemarketers, I'm a horror of hang-ups
 &HT;    By Michael Browning
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Over and over again during the Civil
War, soldiers noticed a strange phenomenon that came to be known as
``acoustic shadow.'' An eerie zone of silence seemed to descend on
the periphery of a battle, muffling all sound.
</P>
<P>
   On the field itself, men could be screaming, cannons booming,
rifles popping. The noise might be heard for miles. But on some
occasions, when atmospheric conditions were right, the terrible
sound of war simply evaporated, and people a mile away heard
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   The Union army very nearly lost the Battle of Perryville in
Kentucky on Oct. 8, 1862, because of an acoustic shadow. The Union
commander, Gen. Don Carlos Buell, had his headquarters in a deep
valley and was blissfully unaware that his troops were fighting for
dear life.
</P>
<P>
   Since moving to Palm Beach County in December, I've been living
in my own little acoustic shadow, a delightful one, in this case.
</P>
<P>
   Telemarketers, the bane of suffering humankind in the closing
years of the millennium, have not found me yet, thanks to my new
phone number. I feel like a dog that has been dipped at the vet's
and is completely freed of fleas and ticks.
</P>
<P>
   Now, whenever the phone rings, it's somebody I know, somebody I
am often interested in hearing from, someone I enjoy talking to.
How long has it been since you could say the same?
</P>
<P>
   It amazed me how quickly the phone hucksters zeroed in on me in
1992, when I returned from nine years of living overseas. They
seemed so earnest, so polite. They must work very hard in the
daytime, I reasoned, because they always seemed to call me at
night.
</P>
<P>
   Innocent in those days, I actually gave $15 to a local
firefighter's auxiliary and received a little sticker in return.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put it on your children's bedroom window,'' the telemarketer
said knowingly. ``That way, if, God forbid, there should ever be a
fire, the firemen would know to break into that part of the house
first.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Really?'' I answered. Only after hanging up did I realize what
a numskull I'd been. I'm sure firemen carefully inspect a burning
house for Fire Fighters' Auxiliary stickers before deciding exactly
where to enter!
</P>
<P>
   Well, once burned, so to speak, twice shy. Skilled reporter that
I am, I soon learned to spot the telltale signs of a telemarketing
call: the uncanny timing, right in the middle of dinner; the
one-or-two-second pause between the time you pick up and say,
``Hello?'' and the click as the computer-autodialer passes the
latest bozo _ in this case, you _ to the pickpocket at the other
end; and the inevitable, cheery ``How are you?'' from the lips of
an utter stranger.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, when the firefighters called, I was ready: ``I
decided to play it safe and have the house completely sheathed in
asbestos,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh,'' the telemarketer said. There followed a satisfying,
nonplussed silence at the other end of the line.
</P>
<P>
   But they called back the next year, regular as clockwork.
</P>
<P>
   So began my Chameleon Period. Whoever called, I was the exact
opposite, the anti-person, the Bizarro thing they could never hope
to reach.
</P>
<P>
   If it was a religious organization, I was an agnostic. If it was
a political party, I was an anarchist. If it was a credit-card
company, I was Plastic Man, who owned so many credit cards he
rattled like a human castanet when he walked. If it was a hospital,
I was immortal and invulnerable. If it was the Police Benevolent
Association, I was _ well, not a criminal, but simply too poor to
help out.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a while, the word will get around,'' I thought. ``The
news will spread through the quays and marts, down the boulevards
and into the bistros and back alleys: `Don't bother with that
number. Dry well. Empty pockets. Bloodless turnip. Waste of time.'
Even hobos used to mark houses where it was useless to knock. My
fame as a miser will spread.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't spread. The telemarketers never quit. If anything,
they redoubled their efforts. To my chagrin, the number of calls
seemed to increase.
</P>
<P>
   I fought back with horrible, imaginary diseases. ``I have
cholera,'' I told one telemarketer. ``I will be dead within the
week. So you see, I don't need a second mortgage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I see,'' she answered brightly. ``Well, thank you for your
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Another mortgage company called the very next evening.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I moved. I had the old number disconnected and got a
new phone, in a new county: a fresh start, like the immigrants at
Ellis Island. It was like burning the house down to get rid of the
termites, but it has worked. At least until the next phone
directory is published.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
