<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 10:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7171 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS-1-COX     02-24 1801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS-1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDITORS: THIS IS PART ONE OF A TWO PART FILE)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've seen several references in the news to a program called
Character Counts. What is it, and how can I reach the sponsoring
organization?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Character Counts! coalition describes itself as a
diverse, nonpartisan alliance of human-service and educational
organizations working together to strengthen the character of young
people by advocating ethical values that transcend political,
religious, class and ethnic divisions. It stresses what it calls
``six pillars of character'': trustworthiness, respect,
responsibility, fairness, caring and citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   The Joseph and Edna Josephson Institute of Ethics, a nonprofit
teaching organization, helped organize the coalition in 1993.
Member organizations include 4-H, Little League, the National
Education Association, Boys and Girls Clubs, the YMCA and the
National Association of Secondary School Principals. Information:
Josephson Institute of Ethics, 4640 Admiralty Way, Suite 1001,
Marina del Rey, CA 90292-6610 (310-306-1868) or, on the Internet,
http://www.charactercounts.org
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who appointed Alan Greenspan chairman of the Federal Reserve
Board, and when?
</P>
<P>
   A: President Ronald Reagan, in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How much does it cost to operate Air Force One, the Boeing
747 President Clinton uses? Does he ever fly on any aircraft other
than Air Force One?
</P>
<P>
   A: Previously published reports have quoted the White House as
saying the VC-25 (in civilian use, a 747) costs $35,300 an hour to
operate. The president will fly on any one of several aircraft in
the inventory at the 89th Airlift Wing, Andrews Air Force Base, in
Maryland. It depends on the mission, said Andrea Bittner, Andrews
spokeswoman. For example, when President Clinton flew to West
Jefferson, N.C., last year, and to Martha's Vineyard, Mass., he
used smaller aircraft, such as a C-9, Bittner said. The designation
Air Force One, by the way, refers to any aircraft the president
happens to be using, not just the VC-25.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Several articles about Hillary Rodham Clinton's considering a
run for the Senate from New York, even though she isn't a resident,
have said Robert Kennedy did the same thing. Will you refresh my
memory about his circumstances?
</P>
<P>
   A: It started in June 1964 when some Democratic leaders in New
York urged Kennedy, then U.S. attorney general, to make the race.
At the time, Kennedy issued a statement saying, ``I will not be a
candidate.'' Just two months later, on Aug. 25, he announced his
candidacy for the seat held by Sen. Kenneth Keating (R-N.Y.). At
the time, Kennedy lived in Virginia but voted in Massachusetts. He
had resigned Aug. 23 as a member of the Massachusetts delegation to
the Democratic National Convention. On Sept. 1, Kennedy won the
nomination at the New York State Democratic convention in New York
City. In his acceptance speech, Kennedy, referring to criticism
that he lacked roots in New York, told the delegates that the
state's first senator, Rufus King, ``was from Massachusetts. And he
served this state well.'' Kennedy's candidacy was based, he said,
on his record of 13 years of public service. Kennedy returned to
Washington on Sept. 3 and resigned as attorney general, effective
that day. In the Nov. 3 election, he defeated Keating by a vote of
3,728,864 to 2,926,383.
</P>
<P>
   As Q&AMP;A has previously reported, New York has a very liberal
residency requirement for a candidate to run for the Senate. Such a
person needs only to have purchased or rented a residence by
election day. Q: Is any listing available of the most-stolen
vehicles?
</P>
<P>
   A: The National Insurance Crime Bureau says these are the five
most commonly stolen vehicles nationwide: Honda Accord, Oldsmobile
Cutlass, Toyota Camry, Honda Civic (and CRX) and Ford Mustang. For
comparison, these are some other ``top fives'' across the country:
Los Angeles, Honda Accord, Honda Civic (and CRX), Toyota Camry,
Toyota 4x2 pickup and Oldsmobile Cutlass; New York, Honda Accord,
Toyota Camry, Nissan Maxima, Toyota Corolla and Acura Legend;
Atlanta, Oldsmobile Cutlass, Chevrolet Caprice, Honda Civic,
Cadillac De Ville and Jeep Cherokee. Those with Internet access can
get information at this site:
http://www.giis.org/nicb-stolencars.htm
</P>
<P>
   Q: The man who won the $60 million Big Game jackpot in Georgia
recently actually got less than half that amount. Exactly where did
the rest of the money go?
</P>
<P>
   A: The winner had chosen a lump sum cash payment instead of an
annuity taken over 26 years. The $60 million was the estimated
annuitized payment amount, which would be the estimated cash value
of the jackpot and the interest earned over 26 years, based on
sales and current interest rates. The Feb. 2 winner, Jim Sheets of
Harrison, Tenn., selected the cash option when he bought his
ticket. So he received the cash value of the $60 million annuitized
jackpot, which worked out to $33,277,860. Because federal and state
income taxes were withheld, he received $21,963,387.60.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My wife and I recently returned from Maui, where we visited
Charles Lindbergh's grave. We were reminded of his wife, author
Anne Morrow Lindbergh, whom we haven't heard anything about for a
long time. Can you update us about her?
</P>
<P>
   A: The 92-year-old widow of the famed aviator is famous in her
own right for her books, diaries and letters, and honored for
surveying trans-Atlantic air routes and working as a co-pilot and
radio operator. She maintains the family residence in Maui.
</P>
<P>
   She was born June 22, 1906, in Englewood, N.J. Her father, a
lawyer, became a partner in J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co. and later served as
U.S. ambassador to Mexico and as a Republican senator from New
Jersey. She graduated in 1928 from Smith College, where she won
several prizes for writing.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Lindbergh became a worldwide hero in 1927 when he flew
solo from New York to Paris in the Spirit of St. Louis. Anne Morrow
met the aviator when he was invited by her father to Mexico as a
gesture of friendship toward that country. The two met while
Lindbergh spent two weeks at the U.S. Embassy in Mexico City. On
Feb. 12, 1929, Ambassador Morrow announced their engagement, and on
May 27, 1929, the couple were married in Englewood. Adopting her
husband's cause of aviation, she took flying lessons and in 1930
became the first woman in the United States to obtain a glider
pilot's license. She received her private pilot's license the next
year.
</P>
<P>
   The Lindberghs had six children. The kidnapping of their
first-born from his nursery in March 1932 created a worldwide
sensation, which continued long after his body was found two months
later. A daughter, Anne Spencer, also died. Her husband died of
cancer on Aug. 26, 1974, at their Hawaiian home.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I always thought of Mexico as sort of a man's country, and
was surprised to see that its foreign minister is a woman, Rosario
Green. What is her professional background?
</P>
<P>
   A: Green became the first woman in Mexican history to head the
Foreign Relations Ministry _ her country's equivalent to U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright _ when she replaced Jose
Angel Gurria in January 1998. Named to the post by President
Ernesto Zedillo, Green is the highest-ranking woman in his
government.
</P>
<P>
   She holds a degree in international relations from the National
Autonomous University of Mexico, with a master's in economics from
El Colegio de Mexico. She obtained a second master's in economics
and a certificate in Latin American studies from Columbia
University in New York, then studied at the Institute for Latin
American Integration in Buenos Aires, Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   After stints as a professor at several universities in Mexico,
she turned to government, serving as ambassador to the German
Democratic Republic, executive secretary of the National Commission
on Human Rights, undersecretary of the Ford Foundation's Commission
on the Future of Mexico-U.S. Relations, and Mexico's representative
at the World Bank, among other positions. In 1994 she went to the
United Nations, where she was a consultant, assistant secretary for
political affairs and coordinator for women's issues. She resigned
her U.N. post in January 1997, and was elected a senator six months
later. She gave up that seat to take her post with the Foreign
Relations Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is meant by the term ``right-to-work'' law?
</P>
<P>
   A: A right-to-work law is a state law making it illegal to
refuse employment to a person unless that person is, or becomes, a
union member.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What exactly is the national debt, and to whom is it owed?
</P>
<P>
   A: The national debt is the amount of money the government owes
because of money it has borrowed by selling bonds or other
securities. So the debt is owed to those who buy those government
bonds or other securities. Banks and private individuals are the
largest ``owners'' of the debt, but about one-fourth of it is held
by government agencies. Banks and insurance companies buy
government bonds as a safe investment and to earn interest on funds
not used for other purposes. Individuals also buy bonds for family
security and for patriotic reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the origin of the expression ``getting off
scot-free''?
</P>
<P>
   A: Like hopscotch, this term for ``absolutely free'' has no
connection with frugal Scotsmen. A scot or sceot was a municipal
tax in 12th-century England, and someone who went scot-free was one
who succeeded in dodging these taxes. The term later was given
wider currency when scot was used to mean the amount that one owed
for entertainment, including drinks, in a tavern _ anyone who had a
drink on the house went scot-free. The scot in this version was
reinforced by the fact that all drinks ordered in taverns were
scotched, or marked on a slate, enabling the landlord to make a
reckoning of how much a person owed.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was reported some time ago that independent counsels were
investigating Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt and Labor Secretary
Alexis Herman. I haven't seen anything in the news lately about
either case. Who are the independent counsels, and what is the
status of these cases?
</P>
<P>
   A: Both investigations are continuing, according to Justice
Deparment spokeswoman Michelle Bishop. The Babbitt inquiry was
assigned to prosecutor Carol Elder Bruce; the Herman case to Ralph
Lancaster. Both are in Washington. There's little else to report,
Bishop told Q&AMP;A.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
