<HEADER>
A7172 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS-2-COX     02-24 1880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS-2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    (EDITORS: THIS IS PART TWO OF A TWO PART FILE)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent newspaper article reported that members of the
Merchant Marine during World War II had been granted veterans
status. I would be in the group affected, so it seems an honor that
I am due. How do I go about obtaining this status?
</P>
<P>
   A: As the article indicated, it wasn't until 1988 that Congress
granted the merchant seamen of WW II the status of military
veterans. And then it applied only to those who sailed between Dec.
7, 1941, and Dec. 15, 1945. Last Veterans Day, President Clinton
signed a measure extending the cutoff date to Dec. 31, 1946, the
same as that for those in the armed services.
</P>
<P>
   For information, contact a regional office of the Department of
Veterans Affairs. When applying for medical care, seamen who
qualify must present their DD-214 discharge certificate from the
Defense Department to the VA medical facility. The VA regional
office can assist you in obtaining a certificate, if you don't
already have it.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read recently that four Boeing 757s were added to the fleet
of aircraft operated for the U.S. vice president. How many aircraft
in total are in his fleet?
</P>
<P>
   A: While the 757s _ designated C-32s by the Air Force _ are used
primarily by the vice president and congressional delegations, they
aren't specifically for the vice president, according to Andrea
Bittner of the 89th Airlift Wing at Andrews Air Force Base in
Maryland. And three, not four, have been delivered to date, she
added.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president and the congressional delegations also use
other aircraft. In addition to the three C-32s, the fleet is
composed of three C-9s, one VC-137 and seven C-20s, Bittner said.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I saw a Lyon College listed as being rated among the best
regional liberal arts institutions in the South. I'm not familiar
with Lyon College, and haven't been able to find any information
about it. What can you tell me?
</P>
<P>
   A: Founded as Arkansas College in 1872 in Batesville, Ark., the
name was changed in 1994 to Lyon College in honor of Frank Lyon
Sr., 84, a long-time member of the board of trustees. As reported
in 1994 at the time the college was renamed, Lyon's family had
donated more than $10 million to the school.
</P>
<P>
   The private, coed school is affiliated with the Presbyterian
Church USA. It has 43 full-time teaching faculty members and an
enrollment of 450 full-time and 100 part-time students, and its
library contains more than 140,000 volumes, said spokesman Bob
Qualls. It has consistently been rated _ under both names _ as
among the best in its category in the South by U.S. News &AMP; World
Report.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to its scholastic accomplishments, Lyon has another
distinction: It claims to be one of only two colleges in the nation
with its own specially designed tartan registered in Scotland. The
college offers scholarships for pipers, drummers and Highland
dancers as part of its Scottish Heritage Program. It also is the
site of the annual Arkansas Scottish Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Information: Lyon College, P.O. Box 2317, Batesville, AR 72503
(870-793-9813). Or, on the Internet, http://www.lyon.edu Q: How can
Hillary Rodham Clinton run for the Senate from New York when she
doesn't live there? Aren't there any residency requirements?
</P>
<P>
   A: You're right in thinking that the first lady has no roots in
New York. Here's the deal. Residency requirements vary among
states, but in most of them the requirement is 30 days or less. In
New York, a candidate need only have purchased or rented a
residence by election day to meet residency requirements for
running for office, according to Lee Daghlian, spokesman for the
New York Board of Elections.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My newspaper recently printed a short obituary for Ben
Margolis of Los Angeles, saying he was an activist lawyer connected
with the racially tinged Sleepy Lagoon murder case. I'm 65 and I've
never heard of that. Can you tell me about it?
</P>
<P>
   A: Sleepy Lagoon was one of two celebrated cases in the 1940s
and '50s in which Margolis was involved. The other concerned the
blacklisted ``Hollywood 10,'' screenwriters and directors accused
of being members of the Communist Party.
</P>
<P>
   The Sleepy Lagoon case took its name from a East Los Angeles
rock quarry and reservoir, which in turn took its name from a
popular song. On Aug. 2, 1942, 21-year-old Jose Diaz was found
beaten to death there. Fueled by a sensationalist press and
anti-Latino sentiment, some 600 youths were arrested in connection
with the crime; 24 were tried for murder and, despite no
eye-witnesses, 12 were convicted and sent to prison.
</P>
<P>
   In 1944, Margolis won a reversal of their convictions when an
appeals court overturned them because of lack of evidence, and
reprimanded the lower court judge for displaying prejudice and
hostility toward the defendants. The case later was dramatized in
Luis Valdez's play and movie, ``Zoot Suit,'' referring to press
accounts in the Sleepy Lagoon case calling the defendants ``zoot
suiters'' because of their long coats and wide pants.
</P>
<P>
   Margolis, 88, died on Jan. 28 in Portland, Ore. No one was ever
convicted in the Sleepy Lagoon case.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the composition of the Academy of Motion Picture Arts
and Sciences? How does one become a member?
</P>
<P>
   A: The honorary organization has more than 6,000 members
representing varied branches of the motion picture industry,
including actors, art directors, cinematographers, directors,
executives, film editors, musicians, producers, publicists, writers
and those who work in short films, feature animation, sound and
visual effects.
</P>
<P>
   A candidate for membership must be sponsored by at least two
members of the branch for which the person may qualify. Each
proposed member must first receive the favorable endorsement of the
appropriate branch executive committee before his or her name is
submitted to the board of governors for approval. The board also
may invite people to become members-at-large and associate members.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When did Bill Clinton change his name from that of his
biological father? I believe his father's last name was Blythe.
</P>
<P>
   A: According to the book Facts About the Presidents, William
Jefferson Blythe 4th was the only child of William Jefferson Blythe
3rd and Virginia Blythe. His father was killed in an auto accident
before his birth. In 1950, his mother married Roger Clinton, who
legally adopted her son, giving him his name.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In October, at the Wye River Mideast summit, Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu demanded the release of Jonathan
Pollard, who was convicted in the mid-1980s of spying against the
United States for Israel. In December, it was reported that
President Clinton would announce his decision on Netanyahu's appeal
in mid-January. It's now well past that. What's the status?
</P>
<P>
   A: The review process is ongoing, White House spokeswoman Julie
Goldberg told Q&AMP;A. There was never a deadline for its completion,
she added.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A reported recently that President Clinton's pension will
start at about $151,800 a year. That seems pretty steep for a guy
who had no prior federal service. How is that amount determined?
</P>
<P>
   A: Prior federal service doesn't figure into it. The
presidential pension benefit is called a pension by law, but it's
really more of an entitlement, stipend or system of payments, said
Pete Sepp of the National Taxpayers Union. To qualify for it, a
president doesn't have to have a certain length of service or a
certain salary level. The pay is for an active-duty member of the
Cabinet. All a president has to do is to qualify is to serve ``for
as little as one day,'' Sepp said, and not have been removed from
office by impeachment and conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent article reported that actor Hal Holbrook is married
to actress Dixie Carter. I always thought that was just an act they
carried over from their days on TV's ``Designing Women.'' Is that
where they met?
</P>
<P>
   A: They already were married when ``Designing Women'' first went
on the air on Sept. 29, 1986. Carter and the twice-divored Holbrook
were married on May 27, 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm curious about Duncan Hines, whose name is associated so
closely with cake mixes. Can you tell me anything about him?
</P>
<P>
   A: Hines was born in 1880 in Bowling Green, Ky. His mother died
when he was 4. Years later, he said in an interview that the family
cook prepared home-baked bread, wild turkey, venison, fried
chicken, biscuits and sausage for him, his sister and their four
brothers. ``We ate all the time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As an adult, he and his wife traveled constantly on business,
but Hines found a barrier to his complete enjoyment of traveling:
``The library paste served as gravy in short-order places was a
personal insult.'' So they began making notes, then lists, of
places where they found good food, and before long Hines was widely
known as an expert on good eating. He turned his hobby into a
business, writing and publishing books on cooking, carving and
lodging. In addition to his staff, Hines relied on a network of
more than 300 ``foodies'' who would find places to be included in
his ``Adventures in Good Eating'' _ something like a mid-1930s
version of today's Zagat Survey.
</P>
<P>
   After World War II, interest in convenience foods perked up, and
in 1948 Hines was approached by the director of a farmer's
cooperative who was entering the food marketing business. The
cooperative's first product was a cake mix that called for fresh
eggs instead of the dehydrated eggs usually included in box mixes.
Hines loaned his name to the product and Duncan Hines, the company,
was born. Procter &AMP; Gamble bought the cake maker in 1956, and in
1998 sold it to Aurora Foods, whose other lines include Aunt
Jemima, Log Cabin syrup, Mrs. Butterworth, Mrs. Paul's seafood and
Mama Celeste pizza.
</P>
<P>
   Hines, who was married twice, died in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A referred to Duncan Hines' book ``Adventures of Good
Eating'' as ``something like a mid-1930s version of today's Zagat
Survey.'' What is a Zagat Survey?
</P>
<P>
   A: They are best-selling books that began in 1979 with Nina and
Tim Zagat's New York City Restaurant Survey. Started as a hobby,
their concept became so popular, and gained such an intense
following, that it developed into a full-time publishing business.
In 1988, the Zagats extended their reporting empire to include U.S.
hotels, restaurants and spas, and in 1990 to the airline and car
rental industries.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to other guides, the Zagat Surveys don't rely on
paid staff or freelance writers for their judgments. The surveyors
are about 100,000 consumers _ ``real people'' _ who submit their
opinions on places, which then are organized into a rating system
ranging from 0 (``poor'') to 30 (``perfect''). The pocket-size
Zagat Surveys, featuring more than 40 and foreign cities (including
Atlanta), can be found at any bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
