<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ Dispatches from Dreamsville: When you've
grown up in Oklahoma's Tornado Alley, you're accustomed to
dangerous weather, and if you are forced to go without it, you
really miss it. (Clark, Cox News Service) MOVED TUESDAY
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ After passing a law against drinking and
driving, Texas lawmakers went from a reputation of leaving people
alone as long as they didn't frighten the horses to a reputation
for passing all manner of laws to control behavior. They became
quite capable of passing silly, intrusive laws on their own with
absolutely no pressure from the federal government. (Rowland
Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   KELSO-COLUMN _ I'm not much at physics. When I took it in high
school, I thought they said psychics and sat around waiting for a
palm reading. But let me try to explain this to you anyway. A Texas
A&AMP;M physics professor is trying to develop a formula that is both
short enough to fit on a T-shirt and complicated enough to explain
everything _ or at least every physical thing _ in the universe.
(Kelso, Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TELEMARKETERS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Since moving to Palm
Beach County in December, I've been living in my own little
acoustic shadow, a delightful one, in this case. Telemarketers, the
bane of suffering humankind in the closing years of the millennium,
have not found me yet, thanks to my new phone number. I feel like a
dog that has been dipped at the vet's and is completely freed of
fleas and ticks. (Browning, Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
