<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MARINE-INVASION (Oakland, Calif.) _ Peace activists are decrying
an East Bay mock military invasion endorsed by Oakland Mayor Jerry
Brown. Members of the Coalition Against Urban Warfare, a group of
more than 15 local anti-war organizations, said they were shocked
that Brown, who in recent years has disparaged U.S. military
spending and the ``weaponry of death,'' would endorse a practice
landing by the Marines they say promoted war and violence. By
ROBERT SELNA.
</P>
<P>
   HIV-DISCRIMINATION (Albany, N.Y.) _ Despite the U.S. Supreme
Court's decision last June to include HIV under the Americans with
Disabilities Act, a law that prohibits discrimination, many
workplaces still are hostile to people with HIV, advocates say. By
SYLVIA WOOD.
</P>
<P>
   CEMETERY-HISPANIC (San Antonio) _ Members of a cemetery
association in rural Bee County have voted to remove a chain- link
fence that divided the Anglo and Hispanic sections of the burial
ground and threatened to sour local ethnic harmony. By JOHN
MacCORMACK.
</P>
<P>
   TRYON-OBIT (San Francisco) _ Lorin H. Tryon Jr., one of the
world's most respected classic car aficionados and president of the
renowned Blackhawk Automotive Museum, is dead at the age of 71. By
MALCOLM GLOVER.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAMP-ART (Undated) _ Geometrically carved, layered, wood
accessories and furnishings, called Tramp Art, have gained in value
since they were made that were made between 1870 and 1940. These
whittled one-of-a-kind wooden objects were sometimes the decorative
works of immigrant artisans from Europe who used them to barter for
food as they traveled from town to town. By FRANCES INGRAHAM.
</P>
<P>
   GADGETS (Undated) _ A company in Clifton Park, N.Y., sells a set
of novelties that poke fun at Internet and computer paranoia
related to the year 2000 computer glitch. Among the choices: Bug
Spray and Virus Killer, which is actually an anti-static monitor
cleaner. By STEVE BARNES.
</P>
<P>
   T-SHIRT-ART (Albany, N.Y.) _ If you want to design your own
T-shirt or mouse pad, or apron, or drink coasters, or anything else
that might require a special name, logo, photograph, type face,
color and so on, there are computer programs that can help. Hanes
T-Shirt Maker 2.0 seems like an ideal tool to accomplish these
projects and more. By WILLIAM M. DOWD.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-DUKE (New York) _ With Kevan Hall of Halston and
Randolph Duke, formerly of Halston, showing their fashions a day
apart, there was a little compare-and-contrast exercise going on.
By CYNTHIA ROBINS.
</P>
<P>
   TV-GAY (San Francisco) _ What a drag it is being gay on
television. Not only can you not have sex _ or kiss without a
month's worth of hype preceding it _ you can't wear purple and you
have to be wary of ``purses'' and triangles. And now a group of
religious zealots wants ``gay warning labels'' on TV shows.
Apparently the hieroglyphics boom from a year ago _ the V, S, L, D
and MA thing, not to mention FV for fantasy violence on kids shows
_ just wasn't enough. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-COBURN-PROFILE (Undated) _ Nobody in the movies grins
bigger than James Coburn, and this month those wall-to-wall teeth
have reason to shine. Coburn is enjoying his best movie month in
years. He's in ``Payback'' with Mel Gibson, and he was received his
first Academy Award nomination, as best supporting actor in
``Affliction.'' By LOUIS B. PARKS.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Undated) _ Among the most common reader questions
is: What ship should I take for my first cruise? Here is a 10-step
approach for getting started. By HARRY SHATTUCK.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Yet another bad thing about that
impeachment trial: Strom Thurmond woke up. Now the 96-year-old
senator from South Carolina wants to triple the federal tax on
wine. Hypocrisy strikes again. The conservative who once opposed
the federal government when it came to integrating blacks and
whites wants to use the federal government to punish makers of reds
and whites. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-VALUES (San Francisco) _ Over the last year, pundits and
politicians have labored to explain the discrepancy between
President Clinton's high approval ratings and what House Minority
Leader Dick Gephardt has called his ``reprehensible'' behavior. By
DOUGLAS MACKINNON.
</P>
