<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKMAN-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Turner's genius, generosity don't excuse gaucherie
 &HT;    By Jay Bookman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Watching Ted Turner speak in public is like watching
some brave soul juggle four loaded pistols. It can be vastly
entertaining, but part of the fascination lies in wondering whether
he'll shoot himself in the foot.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, one of those guns did go off, and Turner is again
hobbling around on crutches. The occasion was a speech to the
National Family Planning and Reproductive Association in
Washington. Turner was asked what he would do if he ever met Pope
John Paul II, whom Turner has repeatedly criticized for his
opposition to birth control.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the question, Turner cracked an adolescent Polish
joke, suggesting that the pope's ethnic background made him less
than competent. In a mere half-dozen words, he managed the
impressive feat of insulting the leader of a major religion and the
intelligence of an entire nationality. A few days later, he
apologized.
</P>
<P>
   For longtime Ted-watchers, such incidents are nothing new. Among
those he has insulted over the years have been Chinese political
dissidents (they asked for it at Tiananmen Square), Christianity
(``a religion for losers''), media tycoon Rupert Murdoch (he
likened him to Adolf Hitler), and victims of mass suicide (``There
are too many people anyway; it's a good way to get rid of a few
nuts; you gotta look at it that way'').
</P>
<P>
   Ted's a funny, irreverent guy, and I do like to hear the man
talk. He's blunt and honest, and it's exhilarating to try to keep
up with him as he flits from topic to topic, his mind unfettered by
the structures and restraints that hamstring the rest of us. It's
more than a freak show; that ability to simply let the ideas flow
freely has been the cornerstone of Turner's phenomenal success,
allowing him to see opportunity where others saw only obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   At times, however, you get the eerie sense that Turner is still
just a little boy thrilled at the idea of saying something naughty
to get a laugh. And the louder the laughs, the bolder he gets. You
can see him get revved up by the response of his audience, his
energy rising and his mind racing. And before you know it, he's
gone off and said something really stupid.
</P>
<P>
   Turner's outbursts are perplexing because they so directly
contradict the causes he pursues. The same man who told the Polish
joke also banned the word ``foreign'' from the offices of CNN,
preferring the more neutral ``international.'' The same man who
spoke sympathetically about the Chinese government's violent
repression of student dissidents donated $1 billion to the United
Nations and contributes hundreds of millions more to social-justice
causes here at home.
</P>
<P>
   His accomplishments have undoubtedly made the world a better
place. His electronic brainchild, CNN, has reinforced the notion
that we share a planet and that our fates are interconnected. His
philanthropic mission, which is no doubt sincere, has provided the
financial seed money for many a progressive cause.
</P>
<P>
   But at root, the goals of world peace and social justice can be
addressed only through a basic and fundamental respect for one
another as individuals. Disagreements are not evidence of the other
party's stupidity; they cannot be resolved by ridicule or mockery.
The contribution of huge sums of money does not buy a change in the
rules of the game for anyone.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Ted Turner needs to put his mouth where his
money is.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Bookman is the assistant editorial page editor for the
Atlanta Constitution. His column appears occasionally. E-mail:
jbookman(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
