<HEADER>
A7241 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN25-COX     02-24 0676
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Take the money, run?
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ The taxpayers of Waco public schools have already
heard from young Kalvin Farrow. It's time the lawmakers of Texas
did, too.
</P>
<P>
   Kalvin, a fifth-grader, had the gumption to speak before the
local school board when his teacher at South Waco Elementary was
taken away. He didn't understand when the district explained,
``It's all in the numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened to Kalvin and his classmates ought to bear on the
minds of lawmakers in Austin flirting with the idea of school
vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   Kalvin is among the students who most concern lawmakers, those
who need extra help with basic skills. He started out the year in a
multi-age class for students like him. It had a 1-to-8
teacher-student ratio, a great chance for special attention.
</P>
<P>
   But when enrollment figures came down, the district had to
scramble. It suddenly found it couldn't afford Kalvin's small,
multi-age class.
</P>
<P>
   Why? It's pretty simple. Waco last year implemented one of the
state's strictest retention/promotion policies, basing it in large
part on passing the Texas Assessment of Academic Skills in every
grade it's offered or, in grades one and two, results on the Iowa
Test of Basic Skills.
</P>
<P>
   The stricter policy, plus the opening of Waco's second charter
school, undeniably was the major factor when 400 students left
WISD.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of this school year lost enrollment has resulted
in $2.5 million in budget cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Waco schools are taking the enrollment-budget hit in
part because they are a step ahead of the state on student
promotion. The Senate last week voted unanimously to make promotion
from grades three, five and eight contingent on passing TAAS.
</P>
<P>
   Fiscally neutral?
</P>
<P>
   The hits Waco schools have taken based on enrollment should make
one leery of vouchers, which are portrayed as fiscally neutral _
painless. With fewer students you need fewer dollars, right? Wrong.
Among policy mind-sets, that's called simpleton's dementia. It
disregards fixed costs.
</P>
<P>
   Take away a smattering of students and public schools still have
the same airspace to heat and cool, the same light bill. They also
are left with critical staffing decisions.
</P>
<P>
   It's as if the city were to cut funding to its fire department
when 400 scattered families were offered vouchers to have their
fire protection done by a private firm. Does anyone think the fire
department's costs would decline proportionally? Additionally, when
schools lose state dollars in this fashion they lose some of the
flexibility to group students based on ability and to tailor
programs to their needs, like Waco wanted to do with Kalvin's
classmates.
</P>
<P>
   Waco would not be one of the districts targeted by the pilot
voucher bill proposed by Rep. Mike Krusee, R-Taylor. It would
involve low-performing students in major metro school districts
with 60,000 or more students.
</P>
<P>
   Their magic bullet
</P>
<P>
   But proponents of vouchers aren't going to be satisfied very
long with a ``pilot'' program. They see vouchers _ ``free
enterprise'' in education _ as the solution to all problems. They
disregard the fact that public schools always will be needed to
handle the toughest, costliest problems, particularly educating
students no private school will touch.
</P>
<P>
   Reports from Austin indicate the voucher movement doesn't have
the steam some expected, though the pilot idea is supported by the
governor and lieutenant governor.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, one reason is that public schools are doing what the
legislature has required of them _ emphasizing basic skills and
improving TAAS scores at rates that are drawing attention
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Texas legislators should be offended to hear voucher proponents
denounce public schools as failed. They only fail if we allow them
to fail.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is the opinion page editor of the Waco (Texas)
Tribune-Herald. E-mail: jyoung(at)mail.wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
