<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 12:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7254 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-COUNTRY25-COX     02-24 0237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-COUNTRY25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    An undeserved dearth of emotion
 &HT;    By Russ DeVault
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first and last thing that grabs the ear when Kelly Willis'
fourth album is played is the voice. She may be diminutive, but the
pipes aren't. Willis can toss off a near-yodel, deploy classic
country twang, sing it low and slow or go for the
middle-of-the-road country-pop crossover sound _ and that's just on
virtually any one of the 13 songs on ``What I Deserve.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is what Willis deserves (and lacks): songs that
reach out and cleverly stir some emotion, whether it's sympathy for
a loser at love, scorn for a jilter or an understanding of the fact
that nothing lasts forever. ``Heaven Bound,'' ``Not Forgotten You''
and ``Not Long for This World'' score points for quality, as does
the music on which Willis' voice rides. But lackluster phrases _
such as the title cut's ``Now time has left me feeling old and
losing hope/Hell, I've walked a long way just to find the end of my
rope'' _ weaken others. So you take your pleasure where you find
it. Here, it's in the voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I Deserve''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Willis. Rykodisc. 13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: No mystery about what Kelly Willis deserves:
stronger songs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Russ DeVault writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
