<DOCNO> NYT19990224.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 12:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7255 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-MINIS25-COX     02-24 0484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini reviews of recently released CDs
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray, Doug Hamilton and Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  RAP
</P>
<P>
   ``A Prince Among Thieves''
</P>
<P>
   Prince Paul. Tommy Boy Music. 35 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Here's proof that the brain behind such early-'90s
thinking-man's rap acts as De La Soul can still come up with a
creative project. Too bad its individual parts aren't that
interesting. Producer Prince Paul's latest album is basically the
story of an aspiring rapper told over 35 tracks. Days before the
fictional Tariq (rapper Breeze) is supposed to meet with the
Wu-Tang Clan about a record deal, he promises to work a week for a
longtime friend/drug dealer to earn money for studio time. Along
the way, Tariq meets rapper Big Daddy Kane as the pimp, comedian
Chris Rock as the crack addict and rapper-turned-singer Everlast as
the crooked cop who busts him. The story line would actually be
easy to follow if it weren't for the only average rap singles
sandwiched in between.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sonia Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  POP
</P>
<P>
   ``No Exit''
</P>
<P>
   Blondie. Beyond/BMG. 14 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time _ OK, the late 1970s _ Blondie was arguably the
coolest band in the world. Fronted by Deborah Harry, the perfect
new wave pinup girl, this New York combo churned out a string of
chart-topping hits, including ``Heart of Glass'' and ``Call Me,''
which thrillingly fused downtown hipness and pop hooks. ``No
Exit,'' Blondie's first album in 17 years, shows how much times
have changed. Gamely bopping through cheesy new wavers such as
``Screaming Skin,'' the group sounds more quaint than cool. But
``Maria,'' a soaring pop track that showcases Harry's ice-princess
vocals, will have you slipping on a skinny tie and pogoing around
your living room.
</P>
<P>
   _ Doug Hamilton
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  TECHNO
</P>
<P>
   ``Mixed Emotional Features''
</P>
<P>
   Mocean Worker. Palm Pictures. 10 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Multi-threat DJ Mocean Worker _ a.k.a. Adam Dorn, son of
longtime jazz producer Joel Dorn _ inhabits a sonic wonderland
where the already blurry boundaries of electronic dance music blur
even more than usual. This debut release for Palm Pictures, Island
Records founder Chris Blackwell's new label, slams and shimmies all
over the map: hypnotic washes of ambient noir, imaginative
drum'n'bass workouts and jazz-influenced tracks that jump off of
plucked bass grooves and catchy vocal samples. What holds it all
together is Dorn's appealing sense of craft. He's got an ear for
accessible hooks and odd little twists _ recycling the Neville
Brothers' ``Fiyo on the Bayou,'' for instance, on ``Jello Dart'' _
that makes these quirky instrumentals warmly engaging.
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Dollar
</P>
<P>
   Sonia Murray, Doug Hamilton and Steve Dollar write for the
Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
