<HEADER>
A7256 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-ROCK25-COX     02-24 0322
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-ROCK25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Westerberg shows new maturity
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It can't be easy being Paul Westerberg. A Midwestern pop
classicist dressed down in garage-rock tatters, he brought heart
and soul to the sometimes heedless fury of the '80s post-punk,
pre-Nirvana scene as frontman for the Replacements. But while his
solo career has foundered for much of the '90s, the rough-hewn
sentimentality that was his trademark has worked wonders for
mall-rat avatars the Goo Goo Dolls, among others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suicaine Gratifaction'' _ who knows what the title means _
marks a subtle reversal of ill fortune. Co-produced by Don Was,
who's usually busy pumping musical Viagra into creatively stalled
geezers like Brian Wilson and Bob Dylan, the album sounds
refreshingly loose and unfussy, especially for an angst-ridden
perfectionist like Westerberg. Lyrically, he's still the clever,
self-deprecating poster child for chronic underachievement. ``I'm
past my prime, or was that just a pose?'' he asks on the opening
track, ``It's a Wonderful Lie.'' But when he stretches for
narrative mood, Westerberg escapes his own beautiful loser cliches.
``Self Defense,'' which features just piano and French horn, is a
moving vignette of adolescent anomie, and ``Born for Me,'' a duet
with Shawn Colvin, is romantic wimp-rock at its finest.
</P>
<P>
   If not exactly prime Westerberg, these dozen songs suggest he's
finally writing his way out of the paper sack of Replacements'
infamy and finding a mature voice with which his longtime fans can
happily identify. Even mall rats get older.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suicaine Gratifaction''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Westerberg. Capitol. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A near-gratifying solo effort from one of rock's
great songwriters.
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Dollar writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
