A7257 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP25-COX     02-24 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPESWAP25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Recipe for Corn Bread Salad proves elusive
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Since no one has responded with a corn bread salad
recipe like one requested in December by Sheila Richardson of
Dahlonega (Ga.), we thought we'd reprint one that ran here in 1995.
It doesn't call for cucumbers, like the one Richardson raved about
after having it at a restaurant in South Carolina, but you
certainly could toss some in if you like.
</P>
<P>
   SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Corn Bread Salad
</P>
<P>
   Makes 18 servings Preparation time: 30 minutes Chilling time: 2
to 3 hours
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: varies according to corn bread recipe used
</P>
<P>
   1package (1-ounce) dry ranch salad dressing mix
</P>
<P>
   1cup sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   19-inch pan Tex-Mex corn bread, crumbled (see note)
</P>
<P>
   215 1/2-ounce cans pinto beans, drained
</P>
<P>
   3large tomatoes, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup chopped green pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup chopped green onions
</P>
<P>
   2cups (8 ounces) grated cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   10slices bacon, cooked and crumbled
</P>
<P>
   216-ounce cans whole kernel corn
</P>
<P>
   Tomato wedges
</P>
<P>
   Green pepper rings
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, combine the salad dressing mix, sour cream and
mayonnaise. Set aside. Place half the crumbled corn bread in the
bottom of a large (at least 5 quarts) serving bowl. Top with half
the beans. In a medium bowl, combine the tomatoes, green pepper and
onions; layer half this mixture over the beans. Over the tomato
mixture, layer half the cheese, bacon, corn and salad dressing.
Repeat layers, using remaining ingredients. Cover and chill 2 to 3
hours. Before serving, garnish as desired with tomato wedges and
green pepper rings.
</P>
<P>
   Note: To prepare Tex-Mex corn bread, add one 4-ounce can chopped
green chiles and a pinch of sage to your favorite corn bread recipe
or a prepared mix that yields one 9-inch pan of corn bread.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 355 calories, 9 grams protein, 23 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 60), 28 grams carbohydrates, 53
milligrams cholesterol, 655 milligrams sodium, 2 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Requests
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``I had my first boiled custard this past Christmas but was
unable to purchase this product after the holiday,'' says Nina
Whitfield of Roswell (Ga.). ``Does anyone have a recipe for this
wonderful drink _ which I would imagine is very high in calories?''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Marietta Fields of Marietta asks for help finding ``an
old-fashioned tea cake like my grandmother made for me. It was a
big sugar cookie that had soda, buttermilk, flour, sugar, eggs and
vanilla and shortening or butter.''
</P>
<P>
   Where to write
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests for this column should be sent to Recipe
Swap, Food Department, The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box
4689, Atlanta, GA 30302. Include a daytime telephone number.
E-mail: mlanghenry(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Langhenry is a freelance writer for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
