<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-MINIS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini movie reviews of movies released on video
 &HT;    By Steve Murray and Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Your Friends and Neighbors'' (R) _ ``In the Company of Men''
writer-director Neil LaBute expands his canvas, dissecting the sex
lives, secrets and lies of several couples (including Ben Stiller,
Jason Patric, Aaron Eckhart, Catherine Keener and Nastassja
Kinski). It's a ruthlessly observed roundelay of bad relationships,
so keenly written and acted that you'll laugh uncomfortably with
recognition. Standout moment: the collision between the brusque
Keener and chauvinist Patric. It's like watching a pair of snakes
dance. Grade: A -
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Urban Legend'' (R) _ Some laughs, some scares, nothing
special. The latest spawn of ``Scream.'' The gimmick: What if a
serial killer decided to off college students by imitating urban
legends? You know, the baby sitter and the goon calling from
upstairs. The gang members driving without headlights. The
dog/cat/baby in the microwave. The movie is slick, amusing,
forgettable. Grade: C+ _ Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Pecker'' (R) _ Edward Furlong plays the title character, an
amateur Baltimore photographer whose documentary-style pictures
capture the eye of New York art dealer Lili Taylor. Writer-director
John Waters' jokes about the Manhattan gallery scene are about 10
years too old. The movie relies on shock gags (lesbian strippers)
and irreverence (Pecker's grandma plays ventriloquist with her
statue of the Virgin Mary). It's the usual mix of amiable poor
taste and ragged filmmaking that Waters has made his signature.
He's turned his own mediocrity into artistic self-justification.
Grade: C. +
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Permanent Midnight'' (R) _ This true-life story of a
successful sitcom writer (Ben Stiller) trying to kick his heroin
habit could use some time in movie rehab. Pretending to explore the
lower depths, Hollywood-style, it's actually a self-serving ego
trip that uses its shooting-up scenes as shock tactics and its
``insider'' Hollywood talk as an audience-flattering distraction.
Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   _ Eleanor Ringel
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Let's Talk About Sex'' (R) _ If Jerry Springer, Henry
Jaglom, a brain-dead Howard Stern wannabe and the folks who dreamed
up ``The Love Connection'' ever collaborated on a movie, it might
look a lot like this. Unfortunately, the film is actually the
creation of Troy Beyer _ an appealing actress who, like everyone
else in Hollywood, apparently really wants to direct. And write.
Before she tries it again, perhaps she should be locked up for a
week in a room with Don Simpson's corpse. Grade: D -
</P>
<P>
   _ Eleanor Ringel
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray and Eleanor Ringel write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
