<HEADER>
A7261 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE25-COX     02-24 1330
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A civilized tradition: Tea sites steeped in good taste
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the 13 original Colonies defied England and declared they
were no longer subjects of the king, they didn't chuck everything
British. Among other things, they kept the language, the literature
and much of English jurisprudence, all of which became part of the
fabric of the new country.
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, one very, very British tradition that never
caught on here that we might want to rethink: Teatime.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's a simple ``cuppa'' taken alone at the kitchen table
or formal high tea served from a 200-year-old silver service, from
battlefields to boardrooms in cottages and castles, generation
after generation of Brits have stopped their earthly pursuits
around 4 in the afternoon to reflect over a cup of tea.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, we Yanks have our varied pauses that refresh, and happy
hours abound, but they don't come close to equaling the civilizing,
meditative, revitalizing, reflective ambience of taking tea.
</P>
<P>
   We can only speculate what all that cozy, civilizing daily
reflection would have done for us. At best, it might have calmed
things down a bit; at worst it might have diluted some of America's
famed nervous energy, robbing the world of a great invention. It
was, after all, an American who invented the tea bag.
</P>
<P>
   For the British, however, taking tea is intricately woven into
their collective personality and psyche.
</P>
<P>
   The cup of tea on arrival at a country house is a thing which,
as a rule, I particularly enjoy. I like the crackling logs, the
shaded lights, the scent of buttered toast, the general atmosphere
of leisured coziness.
</P>
<P>
   P.G. Wodehouse, ``The Code of the Woosters''
</P>
<P>
   It is over tea that many of life's problems, big and small,
become solvable.
</P>
<P>
   They were sitting at one of the tables now, where Daphne had put
out tea things, a cuppa being the true Englishman's cure for
everything, from tired feet to mass murder.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Grimes, ``The Man With a Load of Mischief''
</P>
<P>
   Teatime is time to calmly reflect on the events of the day.
</P>
<P>
   At teatime they compared notes, and all agreed that it had been
a delightful, though unusually long day.
</P>
<P>
   Louisa May Alcott, ``Little Women''
</P>
<P>
   Taking tea helps one to gather one's wits _ to put things into
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   If you are cold, tea will warm you; If you are too heated, it
will cool you; If you are depressed, it will cheer you;
</P>
<P>
   If you are excited, it will calm you.
</P>
<P>
   William Gladstone
</P>
<P>
   There are at least 150 more tea quotes such as these at
http://www.teatime.com/, and if you read them all in one sitting,
you may want to jump up and sing ``God Save the Queen'' or at least
go have yourself a cup of Lipton's. This is a truly tea-riffic
site, though, to immerse yourself in all things having to do with
tea. Along with the quotes and a complete glossary of tea terms,
there is ``The Philosophy of Tea,'' tea reviews, a tea chat room,
tea and health information, recipes and more.
</P>
<P>
   At http://www.stashtea.com/facts.htm, you won't want to miss the
engrossing tale of tea through 5,000 years of civilization. There
are some enthralling, even pulse-pounding aspects to the story of
tea that will fascinate just about anyone, even if you are not a
history buff.
</P>
<P>
   If all this inspires you to have an English tea party, you must
stop at http://wwwiz.com/issue02/wizd04.html to learn about the
history and etiquette required for British high tea. You will learn
that the British Standards Institute has proclaimed that milk is
best poured before the tea, even though it's been reported that the
Queen herself recklessly enjoys her tea by adding the milk
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   And what about the crumpets? The English are as enamored of the
things that go with tea as they are the tea itself. Here, too,
there are finely honed traditions and rules to be followed. Visit
http://www.byerlys.com/bbag/bbag9804/recipes.html to learn the
proper English accompaniments to tea such as scones, tartlets,
petticoat tails, sandwiches, spreads and more.
</P>
<P>
   There are also recipes at the other sites.
</P>
<P>
   BREAD
</P>
<P>
   Flaky Buttermilk Scones
</P>
<P>
   Makes 24 Preparation time: 20 minutes Cooking time: 12 minutes
</P>
<P>
   3 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup cold butter, cut in pieces
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup currants, dried cherries or other dried fruit
</P>
<P>
   1 cup buttermilk, divided
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon buttermilk or cream
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 425 degrees. Lightly butter a cookie sheet and
set aside. In a large bowl, stir together flour, sugar, baking
powder, baking soda and salt. Cut in butter until the mixture
resembles oatmeal flakes. Add fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Add 3/4 cup buttermilk and stir in gently. Add the remainder as
necessary, stirring just to combine _ do not overwork the dough.
Gather dough into a ball and turn out onto a lightly floured
surface. Roll out dough into a 1/2-inch-thick circle and cut out
2-inch rounds. Place 1 inch apart on the cookie sheet and brush
tops with buttermilk or cream. Bake 12 minutes or until tops are
nicely browned.
</P>
<P>
   Serve warm with butter, homemade jam, lemon curd or Devonshire
cream.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 132 calories, 2 grams protein, 6 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 41), 18 grams carbohydrates, 16 milligrams
cholesterol, 204 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SANDWICHES
</P>
<P>
   Tea sandwiches
</P>
<P>
   Trim crusts from thinly sliced white and wheat sandwich bread.
Spread each slice lightly with soft butter. Spread about 1 1/2
teaspoons of one of the fillings below evenly to edges of half of
bread slices. Cover with buttered bread. Cut into squares,
triangles or cut with appropriate cookie cutters. Arrange on
serving trays; cover with wax paper, slightly dampened tea towel
and plastic wrap. Refrigerate several hours until ready to serve.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Egg salad: In small bowl, combine 6 chopped hard-cooked eggs,
6 tablespoons mayonnaise, 1/4 cup minced onion, 1 tablespoon
snipped fresh dill, 2 teaspoons prepared mustard and 1/4 teaspoon
salt. Mix well. Using 32 slices of bread, this will yield 64 tea
sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Red pepper-basil: Arrange peeled, thinly sliced English
cucumber on paper towels to drain. In medium bowl, combine one
8-ounce package softened cream cheese; 1/3 cup coarsely chopped
deli-roasted red pepper or marinated sun-dried tomatoes, drained; 1
tablespoon snipped fresh basil; and 1 teaspoon snipped fresh
chives. Mix well. Spread filling as directed, topping with one
layer of cucumber slices. Makes 48.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Chicken chutney: In medium bowl, combine 1 cup deli chicken
spread, finely chopped; 2 tablespoons chopped chutney; 2
tablespoons chopped toasted sliced almonds or cashews; and 1/4
teaspoon curry powder. Mix well. Makes 48.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Fruit and nut: Two 16-ounce cans of round New England-style
raisin brown bread, sliced 1/4-inch thick, may be used instead of
sandwich bread. In medium bowl, combine one 8-ounce package
softened cream cheese, one 8-ounce can drained crushed pineapple
and 1/4 cup chopped walnuts. Mix well. Spread brown bread with
honey butter ( 1/2 cup soft butter and 1 tablespoon honey) or
cinnamon butter ( 1/2 cup soft butter, 1/4 cup firmly packed brown
sugar and 1/2 teaspoon cinnamon). Makes 64.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Smoked salmon: In food processor bowl, combine 1/2 cup
softened unsalted butter; 4 ounces thinly sliced Norwegian smoked
salmon, chopped; and 1 tablespoon lemon juice. Mix well. Stir in 1
tablespoon drained capers. Makes 48.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Stilton-pear: In medium bowl, combine 7 or 8 ounces
room-temperature Stilton cheese, 3 ounces softened cream cheese and
2 tablespoons milk; mix well. Spread filling as directed, topping
with 1 cored and thinly sliced ripe pear. Makes 48.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
