<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With MEDICARE-FRAUD.
 &HT;    Eds: Restores dropped word ``fraud'' in 2nd graf of final
section.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AARP'S 'THREE-STEP PLAN TO FIGHT MEDICARE FRAUD'
</P>
<P>
   STEP ONE: Answer these three simple questions about your
Medicare bill.
</P>
<P>
   1. Did you receive the service or product for which Medicare is
being billed?
</P>
<P>
   2. Did your doctor order the service or product for you?
</P>
<P>
   3. To the best of your knowledge, is the service or product
relevant to your diagnosis or treatment? (If you have a question
about a procedure or test, ask your doctor to explain the need for
it.)
</P>
<P>
   STEP TWO: If you spot something questionable, get a second
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   If the answer to any of the questions is ``no''
</P>
<P>
   _ Report questionable charges to your Medicare carrier, whose
phone number is on your statement.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you are sure it's a fraudulent claim, call the Medicare
fraud hotline at 1-800-447-8477.
</P>
<P>
   STEP THREE: Keep Medicare costs down by staying up on fraud.
Common signs of fraud and abuse include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Charging more than once for the same service.
</P>
<P>
   _ Performing inappropriate or unnecessary services.
</P>
<P>
   _ Offering free services, equipment or supplies in exchange for
your Medicare, Medicaid or private insurance number.
</P>
<P>
   _ Providing lower-cost or used equipment while billing Medicare
for new.
</P>
<P>
   _ A supplier completing a Certificate of Medical Necessity for
the physician.
</P>
<P>
   _ Routinely waiving patient coinsurance.
</P>
<P>
   Source: AARP
</P>
<P>
   WHAT AMERICANS THINK ABOUT HEALTH CARE FRAUD
</P>
<P>
   How widespread do you think health care fraud is in general?
</P>
<P>
   Extremely widespread ... 29 percent
</P>
<P>
   Somewhat widespread .. 54 percent
</P>
<P>
   Not too widespread ...... 12 percent
</P>
<P>
   Not at all widespread ..... 2 percent
</P>
<P>
   Don't know/refused ....... 3 percent
</P>
<P>
   The percentage of people agreeing with each statement:
</P>
<P>
   92 percent. It's my personal responsibility to report suspected
cases of health care.
</P>
<P>
   92 percent. I would report my doctor if I thought he or she had
committed fraud.
</P>
<P>
   72 percent: The Medicare program would not go broke if fraud and
abuse were eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   63 percent. Insurance companies have no incentive to detect
health care fraud; they can always raise your premiums.
</P>
<P>
   fraud.
</P>
<P>
   49 percent. People to whom you report suspected health care
fraud don't really care enough to do anything about it.
</P>
<P>
   19 percent. Health care fraud is just built into the health care
system; there's nothing that can be done about it.
</P>
<P>
   Source: National survey of 2,000 adults in December 1998 by ICR
Survey Research Group for the AARP.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
