<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-ADVISORY-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   A human face for brain tumors ... New help for chronic fatigue
syndrome .... Vitamins and cancer treatment .... A wake-up call for
heart-disease prevention .... Ask the Doctor about sinusitis ...
Here are summaries of the daily MEDICAL TRIBUNE NEWS SERVICE
stories that moved to subscribers Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions about the content of a story, call Anne
Harding at the Medical Tribune News Service at 212-686-8584 x35.
</P>
<P>
   If you'd like sales information for your newspaper or Web site,
call The New York Times Syndicate at 800-535-4425 or e-mail
farnellb &LR; nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   --Magic Johnson put a human face on HIV, Ronald Reagan on
Alzheimer's disease and the late Princess of Wales on eating
disorders. But with the death of Chicago movie critic Gene Siskel
on Saturday, the National Brain Tumor Foundation (NBTF) in San
Francisco continues to wrestle with a central issue: who will
volunteer to be the organization's famous spokesperson?
(BRAIN-TUMOR-MED -- 900 words)
</P>
<P>
   --A dietary supplement may benefit people suffering from chronic
fatigue syndrome, researchers announced at a Washington press
conference Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A poorly understood ailment, CFS afflicts around 78,000 people
nationwide, by some estimates. Many more complain of its symptoms,
which include fatigue, body aches and poor concentration.
(CFS-SUPPLEMENT-MED -- 550 words)
</P>
<P>
   --While the role of antioxidants in disease prevention has
received much attention, some researchers think the vitamins may
also improve cancer treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Giving cancer patients high doses of vitamins A, C and E may
protect their healthy cells from the onslaught of tumor-killing
treatments like chemotherapy and radiation, say Denver researchers.
Further, they contend, the antioxidants may bolster the
effectiveness of standard therapy. (CANCER-VITAMINS-MED -- 600
words)
</P>
<P>
   --When it comes to preventing heart disease, there's no time to
waste, researchers report. Autopsies performed on 2,876 people ages
15 to 34 found that all of them had fatty deposits in their
arteries. Such fatty deposits are believed to contribute to heart
disease.
</P>
<P>
   The study should serve as a wake-up call on the need for early
reduction of heart-disease risk factors, such as high cholesterol,
smoking and obesity, the researchers said. (BC-HEART-DISEASE-MED --
550 words)
</P>
<P>
   --Dr. Eric Anderson answers health questions. This week: What
are the symptoms of sinusitis, and how should it be treated?
(HEALTH-ADVICE-MED -- 250 words)
</P>
<P>
   New York Times Syndicate
</P>
</TEXT>
