<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 12:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7288 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAYS-EPISCOPAL-AZR &LR;      02-24 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAYS-EPISCOPAL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BISHOP URGES ARIZONA FLOCK TO TAKE HIGH ROAD IN SEXUAL DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KELLY ETTENBOROUGH  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Jesus called people by name, not by their race or
profession or sexual orientation, and the leader of the Arizona
Episcopal Church is asking his flock to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   In his first public statement on human sexuality, Bishop Robert
Reed Shahan is calling on the state's 27,000 Episcopalians to be a
more inclusive, compassionate community that takes the high road in
the often-contentious debate on human sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Epistle,;; Shahan shares his views on the blessing of
same-sex unions, the ordination of homosexual priests and the
church's current debate on those issues.
</P>
<P>
   Shahan believes that the denomination should ordain qualified
people regardless of their sexual orientation and should develop
rites of blessings for same-sex relationships. But, he added, the
Arizona Episcopal Diocese will follow current denomination rules
that prohibit the ordination of non-celibate homosexual priests and
the blessing of same-sex unions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not going to be disobedient,'' he said. ``What I am going
to do is call the people to a higher road. It's about what it means
to be a church. It's when people engage one another by name and in
the spirit of Christian fellowship and they are not trying to draw
lines of distinction.''
</P>
<P>
   He is not sanctioning blessings of same-sex unions that resemble
wedding ceremonies, saying marriage is a male-female symbol. But it
would be appropriate to develop another kind of blessing for many
relationships, including same-sex partners seeking a blessing for
their lifelong commitment, in a church that already blesses cars,
buildings and animals, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Priests showed the videotaped statement to parishioners this
month, and the January-February issue of the diocese newsletter
contained the full text of the statement and a letter from the
bishop.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction from the Arizona diocese and the church nationally has
been mostly supportive, according to the diocese, parish priests
and parishioners.
</P>
<P>
   ``You all pray together, and you all worship together, and you
all take Communion together,'' said Daniel Richards, a parishioner
in Trinity Episcopal Cathedral in Phoenix. ``This speaks more to
the gospel and to integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Frank Clark expected a negative reaction among his
parishioners at All Saints of the Desert Episcopal Church in Sun
City, he said, but it didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   Clark does not favor the ordination of non-celibate gays as
priests, but he supports the bishop's call to be inclusive and his
rejection of the debate's extremes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of what I've seen is a lot of polemics on both sides of
the issue,'' Clark said. ``What Bishop Shahan has done is helpful
in encouraging people to discuss it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sun City parishioner Dodie Evans is 81 and doesn't agree with
the bishop on all things, she said. ``The Epistle,'' though, is
something she can support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was interested and really relieved to hear him explain that
a blessing is very appropriate for committed homosexuals but that a
marriage is between a man and a woman,'' said the retired
elementary-school principal.
</P>
<P>
   A Valley group for gay and lesbian Episcopalians and Catholics
found Shahan's ``Epistle'' a good step, said Cheak Yee, a member of
Dignity/Integrity and a parishioner in St. Mary's Episcopal Church
in Phoenix. ``Frankly, the Roman Catholics are a little envious,''
Yee said.
</P>
<P>
   Among other activities, Dignity/Integrity holds Episcopal and
Catholic worship services for its 30 Episcopal members and 150
Roman Catholic members.
</P>
<P>
   Many Episcopal parishes are wel coming, so fewer Episcopalians
feel the need to seek fellowship elsewhere, Yee said.
</P>
<P>
   Shahan had not taken a public stand on human sexuality in his
seven years as Arizona bishop until he voted against a resolution
on sexuality during August's Lambeth Conference, a worldwide
meeting of Anglican bishops in Canterbury.
</P>
<P>
   The non-binding resolution said, in part, that homosexual
practice is incompatible with Scripture, that practicing
homosexuals should not be ordained and that same-sex unions should
not be blessed.
</P>
<P>
   The vote for the resolution was 526 for and 70 against. There
was concern, Shahan said, that his vote signaled he would break
denomination rules. &UR; He said that he won't but that he wants to see
a denomination where ``faithful, healthy'' people are ordained and
being a homosexual in a committed relationship is not an automatic
disqualification for ordination.
</P>
<P>
   Issues of ordination and same-sex blessings have been a point of
contentious debate in the Episcopal Church nationally and in other
denominations. Resolutions to change current denomination policy
are expected to be introduced and hotly debated at the July 2000
national Episcopal convention.
</P>
<P>
   The Episcopal Church has about 2.5 million members in the United
States. Integrity, the organization of gay and lesbian
Episcopalians, has about 3,000 members. Episcopalians United, a
conservative organization in the denomination, has about 30,000
members.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Todd Wetzel, executive director of Episcopalians
United, said the majority of Episcopalians in the middle do not
support the proposed changes. Homosexual practice is a sin, and the
church should not condone it, Wetzel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Counseling someone to continue in a sin is a far greater sin
in itself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rev. Michael Hopkins, national president of Integrity
and vicar of St. George's Episcopal Church in Maryland, called
Shahan's statement courageous. Hopkins, who is in a same-sex
covenant relationship, sees the church becoming more accepting. ``I
think a lot of the moderate bishops are where he is,'' Hopkins
said. ``Maybe the harshness of what happened at Lambeth has helped
push some of them to be more vocal and more outwardly affirming.''
</P>
<P>
   Many gays and lesbians have been unwelcome in churches and have
left, said Lyle Miller, an ex-Christian who is executive director
for the Valley of the Sun Gay and Lesbian Community Center in
Phoenix. Miller found the bishop's comments warm and affirming, he
said. ``This letter opens that door again for those people who have
felt that they have not been welcome,'' Miller said. ``I hope the
bishop is true to his word and that he will continue to encourage
churches to be open to all members of their community.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Kelly Ettenborough can be reached at kelly.ettenborough(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
