<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 13:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7292 &Cx1f; ttd-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-HOMENET-SFCHRON &LR;      02-24 1267
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-HOMENET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Home Smart Home  
 By Deborah Solomon   
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you think it's tough sharing the remote control, imagine
trying to share a computer, modem, scanner and printer with others
in the house.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Cummins and his wife each have a PC at home. His has a
color printer and more memory, so they both store files on it. Hers
has a scanner and black-and-white laser printer attached.
</P>
<P>
   The couple found it a hassle when Cummins had to stop working on
his PC so his wife could access it for files or print something
from the color printer. And Cummins often had to interrupt his
wife's work to use the scanner or laser printer.
</P>
<P>
   So the Cincinnati couple decided to create a home network _
hardware and software that lets computers talk to each other _ so
they could share files and peripherals like printers, CD-ROM drives
and scanners.
</P>
<P>
   They were among the first users of Symphony Cordless Networking
Suite, a product developed by Proxim Inc., of Mountain View, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's made things so much easier. We no longer have to
interrupt each other or unhook and reconnect things to various
computers,'' Cummins said.
</P>
<P>
   Silicon Valley companies like 3Com Corp., Cisco Systems Inc.,
ShareWave and others are anticipating that as more homes add a
second or third PC, consumers will want a way to link them.
</P>
<P>
   Their quest is buoyed by the growth in the number of homes with
multiple PCs. Between 15 million and 20 million homes already have
more than one computer, according to Dataquest, and that number is
expected to rise as the cost of PCs continues to fall.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of this year, 1.9 million U.S. homes will have a home
network, according to International Data Corp. During the next few
years, IDC says, that number is expected to soar to 12 million or
almost 12 percent of all U.S. homes. Industry watchers anticipate
sales of home networking equipment will reach about $200 million
this year and $1 billion by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of a home network varies, but consumers should expect
to spend between $100 to $300 per computer.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers have gotten the attention of almost every
networking firm. Just last month, 3Com announced that it formed a
division devoted to home networking. And several startup companies
have staked their fortune on the concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sharing of resources is the key word,'' said Greg Naderi,
information technology market analyst for Frost and Sullivan in
Mountain View. ``The ability to share a printer, a fax, a scanner
or any other type of peripheral device is cost-saving.''
</P>
<P>
   Home networking can also do more sexier things _ like letting
computer users play games against one another on different
computers.
</P>
<P>
   And in the near future, home networks will be able to control
security systems, lights, entertainment systems and even microwave
ovens.
</P>
<P>
   But the main driver for home networking, industry watchers say,
is Internet access. As high-speed Internet services, such as cable
modems and digital subscriber lines, catch on, consumers will look
to home networking as a way to share those costly devices and
services among various PCs. Linking computers gives users the
ability to surf the Web at high speeds from any PC in the home.
</P>
<P>
   ``As cable modems and DSL become more widespread, that's going
to drive demand,'' said Roy Johnson, who heads 3Com's home
networking division. ``What makes sense is sharing that pipe. Not
many people are going to buy multiple cable modems.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of home networking is not new. Multibillionaire Bill
Gates and athlete Barry Bonds each networked his home, and several
developers have been building houses wired for home networks. But
the costs have been prohibitively expensive and time-consuming for
average folks.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, consumers who wanted to link their PCs needed to
drill holes and lay cable to make a connection. Today, companies
are either selling or getting ready to roll out home networking
kits that the average person can install and afford.
</P>
<P>
   The products work in three ways _ through existing phone lines,
over power lines or wirelessly via radio waves from an antenna.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless products work by attaching tiny antennas to every
computer a customer wants to include in the network. Using special
software installed on a PC, families can share a modem to surf the
Web from any PC in the house. With the use of set-top boxes, they
can also download video or music clips from the Internet to the TV
or the stereo. The speeds vary depending on the product and the
modem being used.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wireless is easy to use and install and it eliminates the
problem of not having a phone jack in the room where you want to
surf the Web,'' said Bob Bennett, a co-founder of ShareWave, an El
Dorado Hills, Calif., company that's developing wireless home
networking products.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett's company is selling its technology to manufacturers
like Phillips Electronics, and products should be available in the
second quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies, such as Sunnyvale's Epigram and Tut Systems of
Pleasant Hill, use existing phone lines to create home networks.
</P>
<P>
   With Epigram, customers buy a networking card at a retail store,
snap it into a slot on the computer and connect a traditional phone
wire between the computer and existing wall jack. The product is
about 200 times faster than a 56K modem. Tut's ``HomeRun`'
technology allows data to travel across phone wires at speeds up to
1 megabit per second, roughly 40 times faster than a standard
modem.
</P>
<P>
   The products, which are expected to retail for $100 to $200 per
computer, don't affect ordinary phone service.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the home networking products being developed will hit
the shelves within the next year. Some companies, such as Proxim
and Sunnyvale's ActionTec, are already selling wireless networking
kits in retail stores.
</P>
<P>
   Are Networks Mainstream?
</P>
<P>
   While company officials predict the home networking market will
soon explode, some industry watchers are skeptical. The benefits of
home networking are clear for people like Cummins, whose wife runs
two businesses out of their home. But whether home networking has
broad market appeal remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a mainstream product,'' said Paul Johnson, an
industry analyst with BancAmerica Robertson Stephens in New York.
``A lot of money is being thrown here, but not that many homes are
ready for a home network.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who installed his own home network, said while the
products are easier to set up than in the past, they still require
a good deal of time. And once up and running, they are often clunky
and unreliable, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so hard to put one of these things in place,'' Johnson
said. ``Early adopters may put this in, but until these things get
easier to set up at home and people see a need for it, the market
won't take off.''
</P>
<P>
   But some in the industry argue that the popularity of the
Internet will drive home networking into the mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we didn't have the Internet out there I would be much more
pessimistic about what this market could be,'' said Jeffrey
Thermond, president of Epigram and a founder of the Home Phone
Networking Alliance, a trade group. ``But there's a lot of
bandwidth in the home for people to share. It's hard for me to
imagine that a home that has the discretionary income to pay $50 a
month for cable (Internet access) has less than two PCs. They are
going to want to share that pipe through a home network.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-02-17-99 2120EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
