<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOODYKOONTZ-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AND NOW, A FEW WORDS FROM ABOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Even if you're not particularly religious, you've got
to admit the sign announcing the Sunday sermon at Memorial
Presbyterian Church was intriguing:
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesus and the three-toed sloth.''
</P>
<P>
   Not a member of the church, I still found myself wanting to know
what on Earth (or above) the sermon was about.
</P>
<P>
   When told this, the Rev. David Hicks, who came up with the
title, laughed. ``That's good,'' he said of the sign. ``It did what
it was supposed to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is: engage you, catch your eye. Make you think. And, just
maybe, entice you to go to church. (Hicks' sermon, by the way, was
not a religious version of ``Wild Kingdom''; it discussed how
people want Jesus to be as unchanging as the three-toed sloth.)
</P>
<P>
   Church signs are a funny business _ sometimes literally. One
side of the sign in front of the East Mesa Christian Church
recently said, ``Keep using my name in vain and I'll make rush hour
longer _ God.''
</P>
<P>
   But more often, signs are the only means of regular
communication a church has with a community. It's doubtless unfair
to judge a congregation on something so shallow as the couple of
lines you read on a sign out front when you're driving past at 45
mph. But it's also inevitable. First impressions are lasting. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Fire of faith
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For instance, it's impossible to think of St. Theresa Catholic
Church as a frumpy, formal place after having seen the sign out
front during the ugliest, brain-melting heat of August: ``If you
think it's hot here . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Can't imagine many Latin Masses at that church.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that was done when I was away on vacation,'' the Rev.
Charles Kieffer, the pastor at St. Theresa, said with a chuckle.
``I'll sidestep that.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Theresa's sign is used mostly for announcements for its
school, Kieffer said. But he occasionally ventures to try something
different.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's nothing particular happening, I'll put a little
scripture out there, or a little thought of the day, just to tickle
people's minds,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's more challenging than it sounds. Most churches change
their signs weekly; the need for new messages never ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm always on the lookout for something, even just listening
to a sermon or a speech or whatever,'' said Dru Paine, chairwoman
for communications at Scottsdale United Methodist Church. ``All of
a sudden, it's, `Aha! I can use that on my sign.' '' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Tight fit
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are other challenges as well. Space limitations, for
instance. Paine has only two lines on one side and one on the
other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I can pick out an `and' or throw in a dash, but
sometimes it's hard to pare things down and keep the meaning,''
Paine said. A favorite she managed to fit: ``Ch_ch _ what's
missing? U-r.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, churches aren't just looking to entertain you.
They're looking to get you inside their doors. A sign's
effectiveness in that regard is debatable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gotten calls from people who say they appreciate the
message,'' Kieffer said. ``Having the school sign has definitely
brought people in.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not been the case for Hicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``A church sign, I believe, is not really going to do much in
the sense of pulling a non-member into the church,'' he said. ``To
my mind, that's a very small part of church life. Church life is to
be part of a community.''
</P>
<P>
   Paine doesn't worry about it either way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who knows if somebody's going to come to the church and join
it because of the sign,'' she said. ``But at least it's there?''
</P>
<P>
   And will be next week, and the week after that.
</P>
<P>
   Which is a good thing. You don't have to be religious to
appreciate a well-done church sign; in between underwear ads and
fast-food billboards, something to actually think about is a nice
break, even for atheists.
</P>
<P>
   And if they can throw in a three-toed sloth every now and then,
all the better. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
