<SLUG> BC-TRAMP-ART-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ART OF WAYFARERS GOES CHIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By FRANCES INGRAHAM  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Geometrically carved, layered, wood accessories and furnishings,
called Tramp Art, have gained in value since they were made between
1870 and 1940.
</P>
<P>
   These whittled one-of-a-kind wooden objects, often made from
inexpensive cigar boxes or orange-crates, were sometimes the
decorative works of immigrant artisans from Europe who used them to
barter for food and/or shelter as they traveled from town to town.
</P>
<P>
   The construction was humble, sometimes created by those with no
artistic skills. Wooden strips were notched out into a series of
geometric shapes with a pocket knife and applied layer upon layer
with tiny nails, or glue when available, until an eye-catching
design was created.
</P>
<P>
   Some were grooved together, without nails or glue. This
technique was used to create small pieces of furniture, such as
plant stands, chests, clock cases, birdhouses, dollhouses, mirrors,
jewelry boxes, frames and boxes. Many of the pieces were coated
with a dark stain.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the larger pieces took several months or even years to
notch and construct. Because of this, most of the pieces that are
considered to be authentic Tramp Art today may put to rest the
notion that this craft was only practiced by drifters and hobos.
</P>
<P>
   Tramp Art was not always made from scrap wood. In some cases
items were ornamented with other salvaged materials, such as broken
pieces of glass, mirror and tacks.
</P>
<P>
   Tramp Art is considered a worthy form of Folk Art today and in
demand by collectors. It can be found at flea markets, antiques
shops, estate and yard sales. Depending of the size, condition,
intricacy and uniqueness of the object, authentic Tramp Art pieces
can cost anywhere from $100 to more than $1,000, particularly
pieces that are signed and dated.
</P>
<P>
   Excellent contemporary examples of Tramp Art can also be
purchased or commissioned today.
</P>
<P>
   The 7-year-old Hermitage des Artistes in Troy, N.Y., makes some
2,000 pieces of Tramp Art a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We make a product line and one-of-a-kind pieces to
commissions,'' said Andy Stutter, president of the company. ``Most
of our work is made from scrap wood and grape crates from local
supermarkets.''
</P>
<P>
   Prices begin at $20 for a 2-inch-by-4-inch frame to $500 for a
four-shelf bookcase. All of the pieces are wood and dowel
construction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
