<HEADLINE>
COMPANY MAKES LIGHT OF YEAR 2000 BUG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE BARNES  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A company in Clifton Park, N.Y., called COBIS sells a set of
novelties that poke fun at Internet and computer paranoia related
to the year 2000 computer glitch.
</P>
<P>
   The package includes five types of products, among them rubber
critters bearing cute and jokey names. The Bug Spray and Virus
Killer is actually an anti-static monitor cleaner, on the back of
which is the note, ``Unlike users, contents not under pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   There's an Analog Bug Eliminator, otherwise known as a
flyswatter, and a mouse pad. The 4-inch-long rubber bugs resemble a
spider and a scorpion (arachnids), as well as a fly (insect), with
names like Millie the Millennium Bug and Vinny the Internet Virus.
</P>
<P>
   Stick 'em to your computer or populate the desk. A complete set
costs $19.99, or $12.99 for a smaller collection. Order for your
favorite computer nerd by visiting http://www.bugoff2000.com or
calling 518-371-4069.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOVINE BALM: A few years after horse shampoo became a hit among
humans, at least a certain subset of humans, here's information
that another product aimed at animals has crossed the species
boundary. This time it's Udderly Smooth, an udder cream from a
company called Redex.
</P>
<P>
   The directions on the back of the tube say ``Wash udder and teat
parts thoroughly. ... Apply to the udder after each milking,
massaging into the skin.''
</P>
<P>
   The cream also apparently works well even if you don't have an
udder; our colleague says quilters of her acquaintance swear by
Udderly Smooth because it's utterly ungreasy. We tried it, and now
we can't keep our hands off our hands, so supple are they.
</P>
<P>
   The cream is available at stores such as Kmart, Wal-Mart and
Rite Aid, where it retails for $4 to $6 for 10 ounces.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   POP FICTION: Drink enough Diet Coke by the end of March and you
will be able to have read the first chapters of six new books.
Included for free in 12-packs of the soft drink will be booklets
containing the opening segments of Elmore Leonard's ``Be Cool'';
Maeve Binchy's ``Tara Road''; ``Chicken Soup for the Couple's
Soul,'' by Jack Canfield and Mark Victor Hansen; Barbara Taylor
Bradford's ``A Sudden Change of Heart''; Nora Roberts' ``River's
End''; and, by Lisa Scottoline, ``Mistaken Identity.''
</P>
<P>
   Publishers are printing 45 million of the booklets, about 20
times more than the first print run of even the biggest
best-sellers, such as John Grisham's new one, ``The Testament.''
About 30 million people drink Diet Coke, split 60/40 between,
respectively, women and men.
</P>
<P>
   Those drinkers also, according to Coca-Cola, buy seven hardcover
books per year, compared to one or two for those with allegiance to
other brands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
