<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7313 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-COMPUTER-QUAKE3-H     02-24 3048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTER-QUAKE3-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUAKE III: ID SOFTWARE HOPES TO SHAKE UP REALM OF SHOOTERS WITH
MULTIPLAYER MASS APPEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   By DWIGHT SILVERMAN  
 
 c.1999 Houston Chronicle   
 &HT;    MESQUITE, Texas _ From high above, you can spy your enemy
approaching through the fog.
 &HT;    He moves quickly, but through the red mist he is only a vague
outline. You can make out the spines on his back, so you know he
cannot be human.
 &HT;    You also know that he's hunting you just as intensely as you are
tracking him.
 &HT;    He pauses to peer through the fog. As you get him in the sights
of your plasma gun _ and you wonder consider whether if your rocket
launcher might not be more effective _ you can hear the sounds of
other battles, in other rooms. There are explosions, grunts of
pain, even screams.
 &HT;    You're about to pull the trigger, adding another kill to your
count, when you hear footsteps from behind. You try to turn, but
it's too late.
 &HT;    Someone gives you a quick push and suddenly you are
somersaulting through open space, past the bridge, where your enemy
stands and watches you fall through the fog.
 &HT;    You plummet into nothingness. All you see is blackness and now
the screams you hear, well, they are your own.
 &HT;    But don't worry. Click your left mouse button, and you're back
in the game.
 &HT;     
QUAKE III: ARENA &HT;    The game is Quake III Arena from id Software, and it's the next
iteration in the kill-it-if-it-moves genre of first-person
shooters.
 &HT;    But there's a big difference between this title, due about
midyear, and the previous computer games that have borne the Quake
name. There will be no slavering monsters to kill, no endangered
worlds for individual players to save _ the hallmarks that have
characterized id's games since its early titles, such as
Wolfenstein 3D and Doom.
 &HT;    Instead, id is creating a game that focuses on what's known as
death-match play, in which the only fiend a player stalks is
another player, usually connected via the Internet. Doom, Quake and
Quake II _ along with a host of imitators _ all have this
multiplayer capability, but until now it's been secondary to the
single-player part of those games.
 &HT;    ``We think that ultimately, the most addictive form of game play
is death-match,'' said Todd Hollenshead, the chief executive at id.
``But, I believe that the majority of our customers have yet to
play death-match. The majority have never gotten online.''
 &HT;    Quake III Arena is a calculated risk for id, but not by much.
Game experts say that although the numbers of dedicated death-match
players are relatively few, it's this multiplayer aspect that keeps
id's titles on gamers' hard drives longer than most other games.
 &HT;    ``Anyone who still plays Quake II is not playing the
single-player game; they're playing death-match,'' said Gary
Whitta, editor in chief of PC Gamer magazine.
 &HT;    With Quake III Arena, the company hopes to create a breakthrough
title that entices a whole new audience to get online and play.
 &HT;    ``When you play against other people, it's like a different game
every time,'' said Whitta.
 &HT;    The new game will take advantage of several developments in the
home personal computer market:
 &HT;    _ More powerful video cards. Most personal computers sold in the
last 18 months have graphics cards with the ability to accelerate
3-D images, which Quake III Arena will require. The market also is
flooded with aftermarket add-on and replacement cards.
 &HT;    _ More people using the Internet. Online usage continues to grow
exponentially, and the No. 1 reason given for home PC purchases is
to connect to the Internet.
 &HT;    _ A move toward home networking. With the dramatic drop in PC
prices, many homes how have two or three machines, and their owners
are starting to link them into home networks.
 &HT;    _ Growing awareness of multiplayer gaming. Most games sold today
have multiplayer capabilities. Sometimes that features Internet
play, though occasionally it is confined to a computer network.
Game owners are used to seeing multiplay touted on the box, even
though they may have never tried it.
 &HT;    Quake III Arena will include features aimed at both veteran
death-match players, as well as those who've never tried playing
online. Newcomers will be able to hone their death-match skills
against computer-generated opponents _ called ``bots,'' as in
software robots _ that will have varying degrees of skill.
 &HT;    This will be the primary single-player aspect of the game.
Players can progress through ever-tougher opponents until they've
beaten the best of the bots. Hollenshead likens it to games such as
Mortal Kombat.
 &HT;    Once novices feel comfortable with death-match play, they'll be
able to use a simple Web page to find a server on which to compete
against others. Click on the server of choice, and the game
automatically launches and connects.
 &HT;    ``Our goal is three clicks, and you're online,'' said John
Carmack, the lead programmer on the game and one of id's
co-founders.
 &HT;    Carmack, working with fellow programmers John Cash and Brian
Hook, designed and programmed the game's engine, which controls the
overall look and behavior of the game. Designers Christian Antkow,
Tim Willits, Paul Jaquays and Brandon James built the levels in
which players wander. Paul Steed built and animated the models _
weapons, power-ups and players _ that populate the game. Artists
Adrian Carmack (no relation to John), Kevin Cloud and Kenneth Scott
designed the characters and created textures that are used to give
them a realistic look.
 &HT;    John Carmack, who is considered the best 3-D games programmer in
the world, has given Quake III Arena a new look.
 &HT;    The game is now capable of displaying curved surfaces, something
not possible in the previous Quake titles. As a result, Quake III
Arena is full of arched doorways, curving hallways, bridges and
circular windows.
 &HT;    The program also is better at displaying the textures that cover
surfaces, so they don't turn into a mishmash of pixels when viewed
up close.
 &HT;    The onscreen representations of players _ called player models _
are much more realistic. Rather than the cartoon-like characters in
Quake II, the models in Quake III Arena look almost like moving,
3-D photographs of real people. In fact, many of id's employees
have had their images digitized, and players may be able to pick
from ``skins'' that make them look like John Carmack, Steed or
Willits. The models also have an expanded number of moves. They can
nod their heads, bow from the waist and even do backflips.
 &HT;    The game also will have fog effects that can be controlled by
the designers of each level. For example, fog can be tinted a
color, can be a certain height and have variable thickness. This
adds a new strategy to the game because players can now use the fog
to hide, then pop up and start blasting away.
 &HT;    There are other graphic tricks, such as reflective surfaces and
even mirrors that move. One level features a maze with a mirrored
ceiling, allowing players a view of their opponents' location.
Walls pulsate, as though they were living.
 &HT;    But veteran players will recognize that this is definitely a
game from the Quake lineage. As with Quakes I and II, it's dark and
violent. The action is fast and furious. When players shoot each
other with a variety of weapons _ a shotgun, Gatling gun, rocket
launcher, even a railgun that fires plutonium slugs _ their
opponents don't just fall over. They explode into flying chunks of
pixellated flesh known as ``gibs'' _ as in giblets.
 &HT;     
 &HT;    As with Quakes I and II, anyone will be able to set up and run a
Quake III Arena server on the Internet. And id will once again
publish enough information about the game so that amateurs can
build their own levels.
 &HT;    The decision to do a game that focuses on multiplayer
competition came at a time when id had finished Quake II and was
looking for its next project. Like a rock star who only puts out an
album every couple of years or so, id does one game at a time,
working slowly and methodically. It then licenses its technology to
other companies, gaining revenues from sales of its own titles
along with those of others.
 &HT;    ``Originally, we were going to do a true sequel to Quake II _
the press release had even gone out,'' said Hollenshead. But at a
meeting to determine the company's next direction, the idea of a
multiplayer-focused game arose and captured imaginations.
 &HT;    ``Instead of concentrating on a story line, we said, `What if we
focused on game play, on the death-match game, the thing that gives
our games longevity?''' Hollenshead said.
 &HT;    Carmack said the decision made designing the game easier. Rather
than concentrating on what amounts to two different games _
single-player and multiplayer _ the id staff was able to focus on
just one component.
 &HT;    ``There's a lot of duplicate code in there. If it's a
single-player game, do this; if it's a multiplayer game, do that,''
Carmack said.
 &HT;    Even though Quake III Arena is not due out until mid-year, the
game already is stable.
 &HT;    ``We could ship this today if we wanted to _ it's been playable
for months,'' said model designer Steed. ``We're just polishing and
polishing. We want to get it right.''
 &HT;    Tiny id _ only 14 people work at its offices in this northeast
Dallas suburb _ made its initial multiplayer game with Doom in
1993. The title, now considered a milestone in the PC game
industry, featured a lone space marine doing battle on a Martian
moon against creatures from Hell.
 &HT;    The single-player game, with its three-dimensional graphics,
realistic sound and lightning-quick gameplay, was impressive enough
to make it an instant best seller.
 &HT;    But the game made national news soon after its release because
college students were playing death-match Doom across campus
networks. A bug in the code caused some networks to bog down
dramatically, and as a result the game was banned at some
universities and businesses.
 &HT;    With Doom, death-match could only be played on a local area
network, or one-on-one via a modem connection. A company in
Houston, Dwango, figured out how to simulate a network, letting
players use modems to connect to file servers.
 &HT;    With its next game, Quake, id expanded the multiplayer
abilities. Like Doom, the single-player story featured a lone hero
battling a horde of monsters _ this time in a dimension that was a
strange mix of medieval and science-fiction themes _ with more
intricate graphics and a true 3-D perspective. Players had a
360-degree, free-motion view of the dark, dank and dangerous world
that id had created.
 &HT;    But the multiplayer part of the game added a new wrinkle _ play
over the Internet. No longer did players need a local area network
to play death-match with more than two people, because anyone who
had a copy of the game could set up his or her own server on the
Internet. Others could then sign on to the server to play _ for
free.
 &HT;    This aspect, along with the fact that id openly published the
design specifications for Quake _ allowing anyone to make new
levels for the game _ created an explosion of growth in an online
community that had already coalesced around Doom.
 &HT;    Fans of Quake used the World Wide Web to spread news about the
game, find opponents and propagate home-brew levels. Sites such as
Stomped (www.stomped.com), PlanetQuake (www.planetquake.com) and
Blue's News (www.bluesnews.com) quickly evolved from hobbies into
serious businesses. Jupiter Communications, a New York-based market
research firm, estimates game-related Web sites will earn more than
$58 million in ad revenues this year, and as much as $464 million
by 2002.
 &HT;    The game also allowed for group play. Almost immediately teams
formed _ calling themselves Quake ``clans'' and using the Web to
challenge each other.
 &HT;    But playing over the Internet required a level of computer
knowledge that the casual home PC user didn't possess. Those who
wanted to jump onto Quake servers had to find them first.
Quake-related Web sites offered lists of servers, but many who
bought the game weren't even aware that the sites existed.
 &HT;    In late 1997, id released Quake II, with even better graphics
and more advanced 3-D physics. It further improved on death-match
play by allowing players to keep a list of favorite servers in an
address book. But still, the game did not offer much help in
finding them.
 &HT;    The number of people playing Quake death-match games in their
various forms is hard to pin down. John Carmack said most market
research firms estimate there are around 50,000 dedicated players.
 &HT;    ``We think that's a low estimate,'' Carmack said. ``We think
there are a couple hundred thousand playing, and that's without any
direct pointers to the servers that are out there.''
 &HT;    Estimates of player numbers are hard to come by, but Jupiter
believes that consumer spending on online gaming will reach $110
million this year and rise to $622 million by 2002.
 &HT;    Fans of id's games will get their first taste of Quake III when
a technology test is released on the Internet in March. Tentatively
dubbed Q3Test, it will be used to test the game's networking
capabilities. As bugs are found and problems arise, the software
will be updated.
 &HT;    Shortly afterward, a larger demo version will be released, and
that will be followed by the full game, available for computers
running the Windows, Macintosh and Linux operating systems.
 &HT;    When it ships, Quake III Arena will not be the only game on the
shelves with a multiplayer emphasis.
 &HT;    _ Shortly after id announced Quake III Arena, Epic Megagames
said it would do a similar follow-up to its best-selling 3-D
shooter, Unreal. That game, Unreal Tournament, could ship as early
as this spring.
 &HT;    _ Valve Software is working on a version of its hit Half-Life
game called Team Fortress 2. The game takes its name from an
amateur-designed modification for Quake I called Team Fortress, in
which teams defend and attack each other's castles.
 &HT;    _ StarSiege Tribes from the Dynamix division of Sierra On-Line
is a multiplayer-only title in which teams or tribes defend their
land against invaders.
 &HT;    _ Ultima Online, an online-only version of the popular series of
role-playing games from Austin-based Origin, is now in its third
year and an update, The Second Age, was recently released.
 &HT;    Even if Quake III Arena's death-match focus means it doesn't
sell as much as Quake I or II, that's fine with id. Hollenshead
estimated that, because the company is so small, it need sell only
10,000 copies to break even.
 &HT;    By contrast, Quake II has just gone over the 1 million-copy
sales mark.
 &HT;    ``My expected-case scenario is that it will not sell as well as
Quake II, but maybe about 70 to 75 percent of what Quake II sold,''
Carmack said.
 &HT;    If it does flop, id likely will go back to making single-player
titles.
 &HT;    ``We've been toying with the name `Doom 2000,''' said
Hollenshead. ``What do you think?''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;     BC-COMPUTER-QUAKER3-SIDER-HNS 
 &HT;    ONCE-RAUCOUS GAME MAKER TONES DOWN CORPORATE CULTURE
 &HT;    By DWIGHT SILVERMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   MESQUITE, Texas _ In 1994, id Software's office in this suburb
northeast of Dallas was not a place for the faint of heart.
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoons, the game company's employees and owners would
fire up the latest version of Doom for a game of death-match,
supposedly to test the latest round of code. In the heat of virtual
battle, they'd scream epithets that would make a sailor blush.
</P>
<P>
   A large open space had room for pool and ping-pong tables. Level
designers' stereos blared heavy metal music. And co-founder John
Romero's door had a hole hacked in it, the result of an encounter
with a medieval battle-ax.
</P>
<P>
   It was, in short, a work space only twenty-something computer
game developers could love.
</P>
<P>
   Today, id Software still occupies the same offices _ though
they've expanded to take up more of the sixth floor in the Town
East Tower office building _ but it's a different environment.
</P>
<P>
   The offices where its employees work are almost hushed. Gone are
the pool and ping-pong tables, replaced by a set of free weights
and a boxer's punching bag.
</P>
<P>
   A visitor can still hear music, but it's muted.
</P>
<P>
   And when it's time for a round of death-match to test the
upcoming Quake III Arena, there's a lot less profanity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone's just grown up,'' said Katherine Anna Kang,
id's director of business development and an ace death-match
player.
</P>
<P>
   The company's corporate culture now mirrors the personality of
John Carmack, the genius 3-D programmer who co-founded id and who
remains the soul of its creative efforts.
</P>
<P>
   After Quake I was completed in 1996, id saw an exodus of some of
its original team, including co-founders Romero and Jay Wilbur, the
company's original ``Biz Guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Romero, known as much for his waist-length hair and rock-star
style as for his ability to design killer game levels, left the
company after Quake was released. He now co-owns Ion Storm, a
Dallas game company that aggressively seeks publicity.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1994, Romero had the most powerful personality in the
company, and id was viewed by the public through Romero's
persona,'' said Todd Hollenshead, id's chief executive and Wilbur's
replacement. ``But John Carmack is not that sort of a person. When
the people changed, the dominating personalities changed. As a
result, id became more reserved, and that took over the apparent
culture of the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, where the old id sought publicity, the company now
avoids it. In-person interviews are rarely granted, photographers
are seldom allowed in id's offices and Carmack doesn't release his
photo for publication.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one here is interested is being the poster boy for the
company,'' said Carmack, adding that he intensely dislikes what's
necessary to promote a game. He concedes that getting out in front
of the public is going to be more important with Quake III Arena,
because it represents a departure from id's past titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wish this was the kind of a world where I just do my
work, we'd put out the game and everyone would just get it,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-02-19-99 1445EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
