<HEADLINE>
T-SHIRTS ARE A SURE FIT WITH NEW COMPUTER PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM M. DOWD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ If you want to design your own T-shirt, mouse
pad, apron, drink coasters, or anything else with a special name,
logo, photograph, type face, color and so on, there is a computer
program that can help.
</P>
<P>
   Hanes T-Shirt Maker 2.0 seems like an ideal tool to accomplish
just about any T-shirt project. Apple users and some PC users are
left out, however. This version of the software program was
designed to work only with Windows 95 and 98.
</P>
<P>
   The 2.0 version (with a suggested retail price of $49.95) works
in a very simple way, using a combination of items in the software
package and some artwork imported from your own files.
</P>
<P>
   To create designs, you select the product you want it to appear
on _ T-shirt, apron, mouse pad, tote bag, pennant, cloth portfolio
and so on _ and work through a series of type faces, colors and
images offered by the program. You can import your own photos and
logos or other artwork rather than use the Hanes library of images,
or play mix and match.
</P>
<P>
   It is virtually impossible to foul up the creative process. The
program guides you step by step, and you can't go in the wrong
order or place things in the wrong place.
</P>
<P>
   You can view the finished product on the screen, make any
modifications you want, then print out a color proof on regular
printer paper. Or, you can go directly to the special transfer
paper that comes with the program. That transfer paper is used to
iron the image onto whatever product it is you're creating.
</P>
<P>
   Replacement packs of paper are available at most computer,
office supply and art stores. Once you get the hang of proper
placement of text and graphics, you can alter the placement of the
printed image: that is, you can shift the print image in different
directions, which can be helpful depending on the size, shape and
detail of the object on which you're going to finally place your
design.
</P>
<P>
   If you have an older version of the program and want to use
designs made with it in the new version, you can do so by
purchasing an Expansion Pack that will convert your old files to
2.0. Then you no longer can use them in a 1.x version unless you've
saved a copy of the original. Transfer paper can be used just once,
but you can maximize efficiency nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   As the Hanes folks note, ``During the ironing process, the ink
and the transfer film separate from the paper backing and stick to
the fabric. So you can only make one full-size transfer per page.
However, if you are making small designs, you can design them on
the same page. Then you can print all the designs onto a single
sheet of transfer paper and cut around each one.''
</P>
<P>
   If you want larger versions of your designs than you can print
at home, Hanes offers a ``Made To Order'' service from Austin-James
custom apparel manufacturing. You upload the design file to company
by Internet and receive the finished garment or embellishable gift
back by mail or overnight express.
</P>
<P>
   Hanes has wisely found as way to keep making its product useful.
It offers a forum for users to post questions, answers and
suggestions about how to use the product. Some people have found
ingenious ways to turn the hobby into a small business. Some have
found interesting artwork to accommodate interests the built-in
Hanes art library does not address. Others simply like telling
people how they use the product, and thus spur a little more
creativity among the pool of users.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-99 1314EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
