<DOCNO> NYT19990224.0093 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 13:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7317 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-DUKE-HNS &LR;      02-24 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-DUKE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUKE CUTS LOOSE WITH CLASSY COLLECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Note optional trim.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA ROBINS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With Kevan Hall of Halston and Randolph Duke,
formerly of Halston, showing their fashions a day apart, there was
a little compare-and-contrast exercise going on.
</P>
<P>
   Was Duke the brains behind the Halston brand's revival or was it
his design assistant, Hall? What would Duke do if he didn't have to
cleave to the Halston tradition? And could Kevan Hall design within
the Halston structure of super-linear, architectural shapes and a
minimum of glitz and still be original?
</P>
<P>
   All was revealed as Duke paraded a succession of tall,
pony-tailed models down the catwalk in an amazing array of
extravagant dresses, skirts and sweaters in both cashmere and
mohair, and proved, once and for all, that his design talent is not
a fluke. Freed from the Halston strictures, Duke created a
collection for the modern woman, not necessarily a glamour queen,
who wants to look special, classy and classic.
</P>
<P>
   I loved the sportswear direction of about a fourth of the
clothes, particularly the ``ice'' cashmere fleece skirt paired with
a flashy pave silver T-shirt worn with a mink-lined, double-faced
satin parka. Your basic vavoom without having to work too hard.
(And that was the just first ensemble!)
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the collections, designers have been using knits like
cashmere and mohair in unusual places. Duke's extravagantly beaded
mohair and cashmere gowns, done up in tones of hematite or ivory,
were spectacular. So were the gauzy, cloud-like mohair sweaters
over satin-faced organza skirts and beaded tulle tanks.
</P>
<P>
   But for the Cinematic Siren stuff that gets Duke on the front
pages of celebrity mags: Look out, Minnie Driver. Your stylist is
going to have a field day with Duke! Especially if you like a
little fur garnish, which Driver sported at last year's Oscars in
her red Halston.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dress'' in this collection? A Prussian blue tulle dance
dress sparkled with a psychedelic pattern of pailettes, modeled by
Kimora, rap impresario Russell Simmons' wife. Come Oscar time, it
will be photographed.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Kevan Hall's second full collection for Halston was
hit and miss, although when he stuck to the formula _ clothes that
worship the body _ he scored. The sportswear/daywear in suede and
cashmere that opened the show was major and dramatic, particularly
a long, brown suede skirt sprinkled with studs in vertical lines,
worn with a black cowl-necked cashmere top. Hall is still doing
slip dresses, which are beginning to outlive their usefulness,
although women are as reluctant to give them up as they were their
Alexis-Carrington-on-``Dallas'' shoulder pads.
</P>
<P>
   But the prettiest clothes were the entrance-making gowns like
the signature columns of pailettes, which look like molten metal
with movement; the floaty chiffons, (one with a mink bodice in
copper will be very popular) or the ombre velvets, where amazing
colors have been dyed together on fabrics that move sensually and
change tonality in the light. Preferably candlelight.
</P>
<P>
   Hall turned out a group of ombres in shades of green or opal.
His piece de resistance was a garnet velvet column dress worn under
a huge and stagy opera coat trimmed with a massive self-dyed fox
collar and cuffs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The opera and symphony mob will also have a field day with the
rest of the designers who specialize in evening clothes. And,
happily to say, glamour does come in all price points:
</P>
<P>
   _ Badgley Mischka _ The Bead Boys are branching out into
full-skirted opera gowns with beaded bodices that are far less
``body-iest'' than their patented slip dresses. And it's about
time.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the collection is typically B-M with mysterious,
undefinable colors; body-loving velvets that have been cut a little
more generously and fall away from the body instead of strangling
it; exquisite bead and embroideries done in India that are almost
works of art.
</P>
<P>
   _ Carmen Marc Valvo _ If you can't see your way clear to shell
out the six grand that Duke or Halston cost, set your sights a
little lower (under $2,000) and opt for Valvo's high-voltage
glitter gowns. They're a lot of plastique for your pennies. Valvo
showed sparkled-up mohair or cashmere shells and sweaters with
satin skirts like an incredible Irish fisherman's tunic in mocha
with a matching satin skirt.
</P>
<P>
   The Hollywood goddess glitter dresses were sumptuous. A number
of them were slips in computer-generated bead patterns with solid
silver chain straps, or gunmetal ``Jackson Pollack'' lace patterns,
again with metal chain-link straps.
</P>
<P>
   My favorite gowns, however, were sexy black velvets, one a bias
pane, off-the-shoulder gown with a deep, face-framing decolletage
and the other was a sterling silver pane velvet set with glass and
Swarovski crystals that looked like liquid silver. Valvo is just
getting better and better all the time.
</P>
<P>
   _ Donald Deal _ Count on Deal to come though with great MOB
(Mother of the Bride) stuff. You know: conservative, always
lady-like, proper, and not too exciting.
</P>
<P>
   With this new fall collection, Deal has gone for shape, color
and fullness, particularly with a selection of full- skirted
entrance-makers that are not only quite regal, but girlish and
quite pretty. My favorite: A navy, silk taffeta ball gown with a
huge skirt, with Jackson Pollack-like splatters of abstract color
around the hem and a velvet tank top.
</P>
<P>
   _ Vera Wang _ Her fall palette is greens, browns and wheaten
gold and the clothes are, in a word, quite a departure from her
architectural and exacting wedding gowns. There are unfinished
tulle hems and selvages; fur like broadtail and squirrel, the
latter worked up into a T-shirt with a hem so chopped up, it looked
like something larger than a squirrel had been chewing on it.
</P>
<P>
   Beading is held to a minimum and usually tracing the numerous
images of palm leaves. Her major pattern: An Asian-themed print of
pagodas and other Eastern images. Very strange.
</P>
<P>
   _ Marian Clayden _ She is known for her sumptuous fabrics and
this collection is not disappointing, particularly in the Egyptian
hieroglyphic burn-out black on black velvet in three-quarter
jackets and cocoon and slouch coats worn over camis and satin
pants.
</P>
<P>
   The collection was small, but mighty, with Clayden's timeless
designs _ fashions that harken back to Clayden's hippie roots.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
