<SLUG> BC-TV-GAY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAY WARNING LABELS: JUST THE TIP OF THE ICEBERG? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM GOODMAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ What a drag it is being gay on television. Not
only can you not have sex, or kiss without a month's worth of hype
preceding it, you can't wear purple and you have to be wary of
purses and triangles.
</P>
<P>
   Now a group of religious zealots wants ``gay warning labels'' on
television shows. Apparently the hieroglyphics boom from a year ago
_ the V, S, L, D and MA thing, not to mention FV for fantasy
violence on shows for children _ just wasn't enough.
</P>
<P>
   Now we need a G, for gay. Or maybe SG, for super gay, if someone
is clearly over the top.
</P>
<P>
   This idea comes from the Christian Action Network which, on the
surface, sounds like one of those must-carry channels you never
watch. It is based in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Action Network isn't really a channel on digital
cable, it's a pack of people out to protect us all from gays and
their influence on television. Of course, if you're a fan of
``Ellen'' you may be thinking that the bottom-line minefield of
network television has already done enough weeding out, thank you
very much.
</P>
<P>
   If CAN _ the acronym the organization likes _ wants gay warning
labels, let's at least open the floor to some other suggestions,
such as:
</P>
<P>
   _ HP: Hackneyed plot. With this in place, we never would have
had to suffer through ``Murder, She Wrote.'' Not to mention most
made-for-TV movies, particularly those in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   _ WN!: Wacky neighbor. The ubiquitous sitcom guest is not always
a bad thing, even if they never knock. Lenny, Squiggy, Kramer _ all
good. But much of the time this is a lazy cast concept and we
should be told if one's coming.
</P>
<P>
   _ MFF: Moralizing father figure. A TV staple from the ``Father
Knows Best'' and ``My Three Sons'' glory days right through
``Cosby,'' ``Home Improvement'' and ``7th Heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   _ NRA: Nebulous religious angels. ``Touched by an Angel,''
``Promised Land'' and anything on Pax TV.
</P>
<P>
   _ GT: Groin thwack. For those of us who find a great deal of
enjoyment from ``inadvertent'' shots to the groin, such as those
seen on ``America's Funniest Home Videos''; this could be a real
ratings plus.
</P>
<P>
   _ BP: Bad premise. Sometimes a show can be good but you just
can't get past the idea of it. Like ``Two Guys, a Girl and a Pizza
Place'' or ``Early Edition.''
</P>
<P>
   _ MNL: May not last. Perfect for a show like ``EZ Streets'' or
``Cupid,'' ``Profit,'' ``My So Called Life'' _ an endless list,
really. This stops viewers from getting involved and then being
disappointed later.
</P>
<P>
   _ ABOWPSAT: A bunch of white people sitting around talking. For
those who would rather not encounter the people from ``Friends,''
``Seinfeld'' or ``Felicity,'' this would be a valuable service.
</P>
<P>
   _ SD: Sweetheart deal. This alerts those people who don't read
industry trade magazines to bad ideas, like when a network gives
the green light to a show _ sight unseen _ from people who have
delivered hits in the past. This way viewers would know why
``Jesse,'' ``Encore! Encore!'' and ``Veronica's Closet'' got on the
air.
</P>
<P>
   _ CNM: Cheesy news magazine. Very important for people who are
channel surfing.
</P>
<P>
   _ MSRP: Money-saving reality program. ``World's scariest''
anything qualifies, as do home videos from neighbors and the local
police department. Of course, it could be MSRP/GT _ if someone's
groin is injured.
</P>
<P>
   _ ISC: Illogical sweeps cameo. We've all seen it. The celebrity
guest in February or May who has nothing to do with the show and
only hinders the ongoing plot for quick ratings.
</P>
<P>
   _ TD: Tony Danza. Absolutely mandatory. We should be warned!
</P>
<P>
   _ ARD: Angst-riddled drama. Fairly essential for the likes of
``L.A. Doctors,'' ``Party of Five,'' ``ER,'' ``Chicago Hope,''
``Dawson's Creek'' and ``Felicity.''
</P>
<P>
   _ GEC: Gratuitous eye candy. We're going to see this a lot. A
staple of shows like ``Melrose Place,'' ``Ally McBeal,''
``Charmed,'' ``Magnificent Seven,'' ``Pacific Blue,'' ``NYPD
Blue,'' and others where low-cut blouses, men without shirts and
butt shots are the norm. Whoops, forgot ``Providence.'' How many
times can they show that doctor in her underwear?
</P>
<P>
   _ ORS: Obvious racial stereotypes. Sure, this will pop up a lot
for African-American shows on the WB and UPN, but let's not forget
the Irish and Italians _ TV's favorite ethnic whipping posts _ and
all those bad Asian accents across the dial.
</P>
<P>
   _ WAPOD: Wild animals procreating or dying. How many times have
you been sucked into some nature or pet show only to find the bunny
gets eaten by a lion, or two sea lions are in nauseating heat?
</P>
<P>
   _ CC: Cop cliches. This one's too tiring.
</P>
<P>
   This is just the start, of course. Why stop with warning labels
for gay content?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Tim Goodman is the television critic for the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is goodman(at)examiner.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
