<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTER-ONLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTERS: WHAT'S ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By DWIGHT SILVERMAN   
 c.1999 Houston Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Disintegration: Microsoft Corp. is spending a lot of money
defending itself against antitrust allegations in federal court.
The government contends that, among other things, Microsoft went
out of its way to do harm to Netscape Communications by giving its
Internet Explorer browser away and including it as part of Windows.
Microsoft has insisted that pulling its browser out of the Windows
98 operating system _ which uses the browser as a desktop interface
_ would cripple the system. But someone had better show Microsoft's
legal team the 98lite Web site at www.98lite.net. Here you can
download a program that purports to strip Internet Explorer 4 and
its components from Windows 98, then replace it with the original
Explorer from Windows 95. Programmer Shane Brooks has written some
software that removes IE4's files, folders and Registry entries,
then asks users to insert a Windows 95 CD, from which the necessary
Windows 95 components are extracted. 98lite lets you remove IE4
altogether, or just remove the desktop integration and keep IE4 as
a browser. He claims _ and user comments on an included message
board back him up _ that the result is a faster, more responsive
operating system that still has all the other benefits of Windows
98, including its improved stability. There are some known problems
in doing this, and Brooks is upfront about it on the site.
</P>
<P>
   _ Find the fun: The number of specialized search engines that
focus on one particular topic is growing by leaps and bounds. As
the Internet and its World Wide Web become a part of everyday life,
it makes sense to seek out a specialist when you're looking for
specific information. GameSpyder at www.gamespyder.com is one of
this new breed of search engine, devoted entirely to computer
games. Although it's a product of GameSpy Industries _ the company
that brought you GameSpy, which helps find 3-D, multiplayer game
servers on the Net _ it deals with all kinds of game sites,
including sports, simulation, strategy, adventure, classic games,
role-playing and, of course, first-person shooters. You can browse
the listings Yahoo-style, with a directory, or use the search
feature. It's a great place to find cheat codes, walkthroughs,
reviews and screen shots.
</P>
<P>
   _ All politics are local: A ``wonk'' is defined as someone who
takes great joy out of analyzing and possibly even crafting
government policy. What doubles as Sominex for most of us turns
these folks on with a vengeance. Chances are, serious wonks are
going to love Stateline.org at www.stateline.org, a Web site
devoted to politics and government at the state level. Billed as
``your source for news on state policy innovation,'' it looks at
breaking government news in individual states that normally doesn't
receive national publicity. For example, did you know that
Michigan's legislature is on the verge of passing a law mandating
drug tests for all welfare recipients? Or that Florida's governor
has berated the state's graduation rate as ``lousy''? Or that the
Milwaukee school board has approved a plan to give free laptop
computers to 24,000 high school students? The site generates its
own stories, as well as providing links to government-related
articles in daily newspapers and journals.
</P>
<P>
   _ A thousand words: Cheese Magazine at www.cheesemagazine.com
has nothing to do with dairy products or Wisconsin residents.
Despite its name, this is a showcase for amateur photographers. In
the intro, site operator Tim Kitchen explains why it's for amateurs
only: ``We believe that you don't have to be a photographer to be a
photographer and that sharing pictures bonds people together.''
Cheese takes the pictures it receives and then groups them to make
statements about life. It's very tastefully done. Prospective Web
site developers should check it out as an example of clean,
tasteful page layout.
</P>
<P>
   _ Morning toons: Saturday morning cartoons have been an American
cultural fixture since the 1950s, and millions of adults have fond
memories of the hours spent in front of the TV watching them. At
Yesterdayland at www.yesterdayland.com, you can literally browse
through your childhood, as one visitor to the site put it. Remember
``Roger Ramjet,'' circa 1965? Or ``Fireball XL-5,'' from the
mid-1960s? The ``Dudley Do-Right'' show, from 1969-70? Or ``The
Electric Company,'' from the early 1970s? You can search for
specific shows, or browse through individual decades, then call up
a synopsis and information about the show's production.
</P>
<P>
   _ Better mail: CompuServe has updated its mail capabilities to
allow for new features and a better display of mail. The new mail
client features better file attachment handling, including the
ability to exchange messages in sizes up to 10 megabytes. The new
client will place header information at the bottom of each message,
America Online-style, instead of at the top. To sign up for the new
mail setup, go NEWMAIL.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY
</P>
