<HEADLINE>
`SYSTEM ON A CHIP' AT HIGHER SPEED FROM IBM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   IBM plans on Monday to announce its entry into the market for
technology used in making so-called system-on-a-chip
semiconductors. In recent years, as it has become possible to
squeeze more and more transistors onto silicon chips, designers
have gradually begun putting all the key components of a computer
system on a single chip _ sharply lowering the cost while
increasing the performance of computing devices.
</P>
<P>
   Although by no means the first company to create such systems,
IBM will enter the market with transistor technology that computes
more quickly than current system-on-a-chip products, company
executives said.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, computers deal with information in two ways: as
memory (or storage) and as logic (or processing). Previous
system-on-a-chip designs have been based on the circuitry of memory
transistors, which tend to handle information more slowly than
logic transistors. IBM's new approach will be based on the
circuitry of logic transistors, which the company said should
create higher-speed processors.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, IBM's new technology will be capable of creating
chips with as many as 24 million transistors, by using the
company's semiconductor process that can etch circuits only 0.15
micron apart _ less than one-six-hundredth the width of a human
hair. The company said that such circuit densities could yield
computers with up to eight times the performance and as much as two
to four times the memory of the typical personal computer today.
</P>
<P>
   IBM executives expect that the first application for the new
technology will be in data communications, but that it could be
rapidly applied to consumer products ranging from computers to
smart appliances.
</P>
<P>
   IBM would use the technology for its own chip-making operations
or sell it as a tool kit for other chip designers. The company
plans to make the first tool kits available in April and predicts
that the first commercial products containing the new chips will
reach the market next year.
</P>
<P>
   By John Markoff
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE BIG CORPORATION, 24-HOUR LINUX SUPPORT
</P>
<P>
   Is it time for Bill Gates to worry? This Linux thing seems to be
getting serious.
</P>
<P>
   Linux, of course, is a Unix-based computer operating system that
is widely available free and is rapidly gaining at least symbolic
value as an alternative to Microsoft's Windows and Windows NT
programs. Last Thursday, IBM announced it would preload Linux on
certain of its network server machines, alongside Windows NT.
</P>
<P>
   And as of Monday a small San Francisco-based start-up, Linuxcare
Inc., will be offering large corporations an around-the-clock Linux
support service.
</P>
<P>
   ``An uninformed user is a bad thing,'' said Arther Tyde III,
chief executive of Linuxcare. The company's customers will be able
to call for help at any hour, paying annual service rates up to
$150,000, depending on what options they sign up for.
</P>
<P>
   As word of Linux's reliability spreads and more corporations
adopt it, ``a technical support service like Linuxcare is
absolutely needed now,'' said Sandra Potter, a senior analyst at
the Aberdeen Group of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Linuxcare (www.linuxcare.com) does not sell Linux itself, but
supports a variety of commercial versions, including ones sold by
Red Hat and Caldera. Caldera is expected to announce this week that
it has been selected by several big hardware and software companies
to train and certify Linux engineers. As part of its new service,
Linuxcare has set up a Web-based system it calls Caretracker to let
customers trace the handling of their cases on line, much as
Federal Express enables users to track packages.
</P>
<P>
   And starting next month, Linuxcare intends to make its
``knowledge base'' of technical information freely available to the
public over the Web. That data base will be continually updated,
the company said, as new information pours in from its experience
providing technical support.
</P>
<P>
   By Deborah Branscum
</P>
<P>
   THE ROAD PROVED DAUNTINGTO MAKER OF GAMES FOR GIRLS
</P>
<P>
   Brenda Laurel spent the last two and a half years creating
software for girls, a product intended to ``comfort while it
entertains.'' But competitive pressure and shrinking profit margins
in the computer game market made business anything but comfortable
for her company, Purple Moon LLC, which closed its doors last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to save the situation until the last possible
moment,'' Ms. Laurel, a 48-year-old executive who has spent much of
her computer career involved in game design and research into the
people who play them, said in an interview. ``Now we'll all try to
take what we learned and apply it elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Laurel, elsewhere might be another software start-up or
a job developing games software for another company.
</P>
<P>
   Purple Moon, whose backers included the Microsoft co-founder
Paul Allen, had a staff of 40. The company considered its games for
preadolescent girls, like ``Rockett's New School,'' a way of
addressing what Ms. Laurel sees as a gender gap between the action
games that prevail for boys and the fashion-oriented Barbie titles
from Mattel Inc. that are aimed at girls.
</P>
<P>
   Purple Moon's games were designed for girls 8 to 12, and
addressed friendships, families and the pressures of growing up,
with the intention of increasing self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   Next time, Ms. Laurel plans to tackle gender stereotypes by
developing software for boys. ``I care about both boys and girls,''
she said. Before founding Purple Moon, she spent four years at
Interval Research in Silicon Valley studying the differences
between the ways girls and boys play. She says boys are interested
in more than the ``military metaphors'' that many computer games
offer. ``I'm going to spend some time looking at that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Ms. Laurel was optimistic that Purple Moon, whose
first products came out in autumn 1997 and sold relatively well,
could hold its own in a market dominated by Barbie. But the
competition intensified. The number of titles in the girls'
software market doubled _ Mattel alone released more than a dozen
Barbie games _ while shelf space in computer stores dwindled as a
result of mergers and consolidations. At the same time, the average
retail price of computer games dropped $6.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be a big company to absorb a hit like that,'' she
said. Purple Moon was not yet a big company.
</P>
<P>
   By Laurie J. Flynn
</P>
<P>
