<HEADLINE>
WHERE DR. SPOCK MEETS `E.R.' ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By LISA NAPOLI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Denton A. Cooley, the pioneering heart surgeon, is
accustomed to having an audience when he wields his scalpel. Since
he performed the first successful human heart transplant in the
nation more than 30 years ago, a steady stream of medical
professionals and students have watched him at work in the
operating room.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 19, Cooley appeared in front of a a wider audience than
he had ever had before. He performed a 3 hour 40 minute coronary
bypass procedure in Houston that was transmitted live over the
Internet. More than 150,000 people tuned in to the Webcast over the
course of the day. In the months since, tens of thousands more have
reportedly logged on for information about the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   The surgery was one of nine medical procedures put on the Web in
recent months by AHN.com, the World Wide Web companion to the cable
channel America's Health Network.
</P>
<P>
   Since AHN.com made headlines last June with its Webcast of the
birth of a baby, the site has made a signature _ and a multimedia
educational experience _ of these live medical dramas.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of attracting attention and audience, Victoria's Secret
fashion shows they are not. But they do generate publicity for the
network. They also help overcome one of the primary difficulties
faced by independent ventures: getting carried on cable systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Distribution is the most obviously challenging part of the
cable network business these days.'' said Webster Golinkin,
president and co-founder of America's Health Network, which is
based at Universal Studios in Orlando, Fla. ``While people talk
about the 500-channel environment, it's not here yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the network started the site to extend its reach,
and, Golinkin said, to respond to a growing public interest in
health information on the Web. ``Most other media businesses kind
of have their priorities in one place rather than the other,''
Golinkin said. ``It's either an Internet company or a cable
network, and if they have the other thing it's a stepchild.''
</P>
<P>
   America's Health Network is available in 9.5 million American
homes, and an average of 2 million people around the world visit
the Web site each month, where a live signal of the television
channel is available, said J. Tod Fetherling, president of the Web
venture. Its potential to reach a wider audience is limited only by
the availability of Internet connections. Twenty-two percent of its
users come from overseas, said Fetherling, who cites traffic from
places like China, Malaysia and Germany.
</P>
<P>
   When partnerships that place AHN's content on ABCnews.com,
Yahoo, ESPN.com and Real Networks are figured in, it is probable
that AHN reaches a wider audience on the Web than it does on
television. (A syndication deal with Katz Dimensions, a subsidiary
of Katz Media Group, puts AHN content on radio, too.)
</P>
<P>
   The Webcast surgeries, accompanied by the subdued play-by-play
of a narrator, have the voyeuristic, cinema verite feel of
behind-the-scenes emergency room shows.
</P>
<P>
   These broadcasts almost did not happen. The television staff was
concerned about showing the childbirth live, but the Web staff
jumped on the idea, Fetherling said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being interactive folks, we said, `Heck, yeah, let's try it.'
We had 1.4 million people watch the video stream live, and it blew
everybody away,'' he said. ``It showed us health on the Internet
and what it can be.''
</P>
<P>
   While television can demystify and humanize medical procedures
for information-hungry viewers, Fetherling said, the Internet
allows ``on demand'' access about specific procedures and ailments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Health care is episodic,'' he said. ``You go on a research
binge when you are diagnosed with cancer or diabetes.''
</P>
<P>
   The notion of the Internet as the digital age Dr. Spock is a
growing one. In addition to two coming cable health channels from
Discovery and Tele-Communications Inc., health resources on the
Internet have proliferated over the last several months. CNN.com
has just announced a partnership with an online health resource
called WebMD. In March, a private online service for doctors called
Medcast, which bills itself as the ``Bloomberg for the medical
profession,'' is being started by Greenberg News Network in
Atlanta. Alan Greenberg, a former publisher of Esquire magazine,
had built Medical News Network for Whittle Communications earlier
this decade before starting his own company.
</P>
<P>
   Another offering, the Seattle-based Onhealth.com, provides news,
columnists and data bases of health information, and features a
weekly audio talk show whose host is Brooke Gladstone of National
Public Radio.
</P>
<P>
   Two things have radically changed the way the public looks at
its health: managed care and the Internet, said Rebecca Farwell,
the editor in chief of Onhealth.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly, you don't have to go to the library and look at
books published two years ago for information,'' Ms. Farwell said.
``You don't have to go to a support group, or talk to your doctors.
You can get everything in one place on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Including, increasingly, medical supplies and pharmaceuticals,
which can be purchased on line at the click of a button.
Advertisers are eager to offer their wares to a natural audience
for them. At the same time, doctors say they are eager to demystify
their work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting how little the average person knows about
physiology and anatomy,'' said Cooley, the heart surgeon, who added
that he was honored to perform a coronary bypass on the Internet.
``It helps people to know what goes on during the procedure, for a
person to see a beating heart.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
