</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTERNET-STUDENTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NET-SAVVY COLLEGE STUDENTS ARE SHELVING LIBRARIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By ADAM PERTMAN   
 c.1999 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To prepare a lesson for his students, Harvard Law School
professor Jonathan Zittrain recently turned to an Internet site on
Tunisia that looked reliable. There, he read about the North
African nation's exemplary treatment of its citizens.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is, the information was posted by supporters of
Tunisia's autocratic ruler. They gave the site a deliberately
misleading name, www.amnesty-tunisia.org, even though Amnesty
International has lambasted the country's human-rights record.
</P>
<P>
   By any measure, the Internet rapidly has become the second
university library. Moreover, as a steadily escalating percentage
of students surf the Web rather than search the stacks, many
academics believe it could supplant the traditional library within
a decade or two as the primary destination for academic information
and research.
</P>
<P>
   But for at least the near term, even staunch supporters of the
Internet see major problems: Too much material in cyberspace is
incorrect, biased, or problematic in other ways. And while some
sites are easy to identify as the work of amateurs or advocates,
the veracity of many others that seem authentic or professional can
be difficult to assess.
</P>
<P>
   Web sites also appear and disappear at an extraordinary rate,
making it nearly impossible to know whether information cited in a
master's thesis today, for example, will be available to future
researchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's already a totally changed world . . . and it's still
changing,'' said James Stellar, dean of the college of arts and
sciences at Northeastern University. ``We're really still in the
infancy of this thing . . . but we're certainly headed in the
direction where the Internet, whatever its problems or limitations,
will be dominant.''
</P>
<P>
   Stellar, like most college officials and professors nationwide,
said the lack of editing or peer review of World Wide Web sites _
processes that books and magazine articles typically undergo before
publication _ doesn't prevent him from encouraging students to use
the Internet. The academics say many traditional books and
periodicals also contain errors or are biased, and the job of
teachers is to help students assess and gather good information
regardless of its source.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, actually, it's a wonderful way of teaching kids what
we've been trying to teach them for years: critical thinking,''
said Zittrain, who is executive director of the Berkman Center for
Internet and Society at Harvard Law School. ``Certainly, there are
issues to resolve, but I think we have to look at this new world
more as an opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   This historic shift within higher education is unusual, and
perhaps unique, in at least one essential way: It is being driven
primarily by students rather than by professional educators. That's
because a growing number of students are so adept at using the Web
_ frequently more than their teachers _ that they regard it as a
routine place to answer their questions.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with nearly two-dozen students at several campuses
around Boston underlined that reality. All of them said they use
the Internet for 15 percent to more than half of their research _
the younger the student, the higher the percentage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easier than going to the library, it's cheaper than
buying books . . . and there's no risk that it's going to be
checked out,'' said Rachael Goren, 19, a sophomore at Brandeis who
said she does about one-third of her research on the Web.``And it's
timing, too; if I want to find something out at 3 in the morning, I
can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   A study released last month by the Higher Education Research
Institute at the University of California in Los Angeles showed
that 83 percent of college freshmen use the Internet as a research
and educational tool. It was the first national poll of its kind,
and the results surprised even its authors.
</P>
<P>
   They nevertheless agreed, as did other educators, that the
number seems in keeping with the steep trajectory Internet use has
achieved in the past few years. By the time today's middle-school
students reach college, most of those interviewed predicted, they
will be prone to do the overwhelming majority of their work on
computers rather than in the stacks of libraries.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a stunning rate, I think, more and more students are
finding the Net to be a very convenient resource that they know how
to use, that they feel comfortable using, that they can use in
their dorm rooms or anywhere else,'' said Linda Sax, the director
of the UCLA institute and a proponent of Internet use. ``It's not
always at the college's encouragement, of course, and I think most
schools and libraries are scrambling to keep up.''
</P>
<P>
   That they are. Although no colleges or universities appear to
have devised campuswide standards or guidelines, professors and
departments are discussing the issue and formulating ideas on how
to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   As one of his first acts when he assumed his job last year, for
instance, Stellar established a task force at Northeastern to study
how professors and students should use the Internet and to evaluate
the hazards of this resource.
</P>
<P>
   Similar committees are being set up across the country. Even at
schools where they're not, debate about the Internet's benefits and
pitfalls has become commonplace at faculty meetings and,
especially, at libraries where staff members are routinely being
retrained to become Net specialists.
</P>
<P>
   It appears a majority of professors nationwide have decided to
allow at least limited Internet sourcing for research papers and
other projects, and some encourage very wide use.
</P>
<P>
   Many still prohibit the practice, however, because they fear
students will not use other important resources, such as books and
journals, and will be unable to adequately judge the value or
validity of too much of the Web content they find.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the old days, which was last year, we didn't do things
quite in the ways we do now,'' said Stanley Dodson, a zoology
professor at the University of Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Dodson said he encourages his students to use the Net to
acquaint themselves with a subject, find general information, and
get leads on pertinent journals and books. But he doesn't allow
citations to Web sites in their papers.
</P>
<P>
   Professors at other colleges have adopted similarly cautious
approaches, even as they seem a bit awed by the technological
advances they are watching and trying to keep up with.
</P>
<P>
   Several common threads connect the teachers who have banned
Internet sourcing: They still permit Web use in some circumstances,
they predict the Internet will become the dominant
educational-research tool despite their qualms, and they
acknowledge that one major reason for their reluctance to allow
more use of the Internet probably is their sense that students know
more about it than they do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to encourage students not to fall into a trap of
the Internet making things much easier for them and not allowing
them to learn all the research skills that they should,'' said
James Mandrell, a professor of comparative literature and film at
Brandeis. Smiling, he added, ``But I've got a murky suspicion that
my own limitations dictate some of my reservations.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig Runde, director of the International Center for Computer
Enhanced Learning at Wake Forest University in North Carolina,
predicts that most of the problems of the Internet will be remedied
over time. He said guidelines for evaluating sites will be
established, peer review and editing for on-line journals will be
instituted, lists of acceptable and unacceptable sites will be
compiled, and individual schools and professors will learn how to
assess various sites' worth just as they do with books today.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important, Runde said, many college classes
eventually will have Web sites or Internet components of their own.
Constructing and maintaining those presumably will build skills for
teachers and students that will help them evaluate cyberspace
information.
</P>
<P>
   The professors, students, librarians, and college officials who
discussed the Internet issue last week agree that their foremost
concerns relate to assessing Web sites and learning how to use them
well. But they list other potential problems. Those range from
serious copyright questions, such as who owns the completed
research or works in progress on the Internet, to deep worries
about the Internet making it too easy for students to plagiarize or
to buy completed research papers from the scores of companies that
provide the service.
</P>
<P>
   Their reservations pale, however, when compared with the glowing
future the academics foresee for computerized research.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, there will be scams and there will be victims,
and there will be crimes and punishments we haven't even conceived
of yet,'' said Richard Larson, director of the Center for Advanced
Educational Services at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
But he predicted that these ``growing pains'' of the Internet would
abate, and the US education system would become more mature as a
result.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-02-23-99 1356EST &QL;
</P>
