<HEADER>
A7362 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-INTEL-ANTITRUST-A     02-24 1468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTEL-ANTITRUST-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FTC NOW TURNS TO ITS ANTITRUST CASE AGAINST INTEL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The ``Wintel'' duopoly, as some have described the
domination of the computer industry by Microsoft's software and
Intel's hardware, is about to come under government assault on a
second front.
</P>
<P>
   With the Justice Department's antitrust suit against the
Microsoft Corp. wending its way to conclusion in a federal court
here, lawyers at the Federal Trade Commission are preparing to open
their trial against the Intel Corp. in three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Intel case may wind up having a lower profile than the
Microsoft trial, and any penalties _ if Intel loses _ may not be
nearly as severe as what government lawyers may seek for Microsoft.
But the stakes for both the industry and Intel, the world's largest
maker of personal computer chips, are considerable all the same.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the government and the chip maker disclosed their
list of possible witnesses, and later this week the two sides will
file briefs detailing their theories of the case. But a broad
outline already has been sketched out in court papers. Despite some
crucial differences, the Microsoft and Intel cases fundamentally
are similar to the extent they involve the competing policy
interests of antitrust law and intellectual property rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of similarities between the cases,'' said
Eleanor M. Fox, an authority on antitrust who teaches at the New
York University School of Law. ``Each company has control of 80 to
90 percent of its market, and both cases involve high-technology
intellectual property markets. Both cases also allege the dominance
of a monopoly firm by using its monopoly leverage to build a moat
around its power to prevent challenges that threaten control over
the market.''
</P>
<P>
   There also are important differences between the Microsoft and
Intel cases over the facts and the law, as well as in procedures of
the two trials. The government is seeking a far more limited remedy
in the Intel case than it is contemplating in the Microsoft case.
There, the most extreme measure under consideration is the breakup
of Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   In Intel's case, the government simply wants the court to order
the company not to withhold its technical information from
customers who are also developing rival technologies.
</P>
<P>
   But even if Intel's corporate future is not at stake, some
experts believe that if the company loses, the new ground rules
could have a long-term effect both on the profits of Intel and its
competitors and on computer prices generally. Chips are a much more
expensive component of personal computers than the operating system
software and Internet browsers at the center of the Microsoft
dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Microsoft and the Intel cases present stark clash _
between the protections that intellectual property law is meant to
give companies and the protection of the public that antitrust law
are supposed to provide.
</P>
<P>
   Intellectual property law gives the holder of a patent a kind of
monopolistic protection over an invention or process. But under
antitrust law, companies with a monopoly position in a market are
not supposed to abuse their power by chilling potential competition
or innovation.
</P>
<P>
   The government has accused Intel of a pattern of squeezing other
developers of chip technology who are also big customers of Intel
into surrendering technological advances to Intel as a quid pro quo
for receiving crucial information from Intel. Lawyers at the
Federal Trade Commission charge that Intel denied or threatened to
deny information about its chips to three companies that use those
chips in their own products _ Compaq Computer, Digital Equipment
and Intergraph _ as a way of coercing them to license their
innovations to Intel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intel's conduct threatened to injure, and did injure, the
ability of those targeted customers to remain competitive in
developing and bringing to market in a timely manner computer
systems based on Intel's microprocessors,'' the FTC said in its
complaint. Government lawyers assert that Intel's decision to
withhold the information stifled innovation and development of new
chip technologies.
</P>
<P>
   Agency lawyers announced on Friday that the witnesses they plan
to call include executives from companies that have been Intel
customers. One is Robert B. Palmer, who was chairman and chief
executive of Digital Equipment until it was acquired last year by
Compaq. Another is James W. Meadlock, chairman and chief executive
of Intergraph, a Huntsville, Ala., company that supplies computer
hardware, software and services for corporate and engineering
customers, based on Microsoft and Intel technology.
</P>
<P>
   Intel has not contested many of the facts of the case. Rather,
the company has said that antitrust rules do not outlaw its
decision to withhold technical information from anyone as a way of
defending itself from possible competition. Intel executives also
contend that the agency will be unable to show that the company's
decision to withhold information from its customers resulted in any
harm to competition or kept chip prices artificially high.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a case that is not a classic antitrust case but an
effort by the staff of the FTC to create new law,'' says Chuck
Mulloy, an Intel spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Signaling that it would take a different tack than Microsoft,
Intel announced on Friday that its witnesses might include its
chairman and co-founder, Andrew S. Grove, and its chief executive,
Craig R. Barrett, executives who not only transformed the industry
but also personify the company.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, by contrast, purposely kept its chairman and founder,
William H. Gates, and president, Steven A. Ballmer, from taking the
stand. Gates' evasive deposition, played on videotape in court by
Justice Department lawyers to great effect, has dented both the
company's image and its legal standing.
</P>
<P>
   Procedurally, the Intel case is also on a far different footing
than Microsoft's. The Intel proceeding will be heard by an
administrative law judge, James P. Timony, who has been on the
bench since 1976 and before that was a lawyer at the agency,
Administrative law judges, who work for the government's executive
branch, not the judiciary, are the professional referees of the
federal agencies. Both Intel and the FTC have won and lost their
share of pretrial skirmishes before Timony.
</P>
<P>
   If Intel loses in the administrative proceeding, and also at the
next level _ before the full commission _ the company would have
the right to select the federal circuit court in which to file its
appeal. ``Court shopping'' gives Intel to ability to select the
appeals circuit with the least stringent interpretation of
antitrust law.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is defending itself before a federal judge, Thomas
Penfield Jackson, whom it had sought to have removed from the case
because of his previous rulings against the company. If Microsoft
loses, it would have no choice but to proceed to the federal
appeals court in the District of Columbia _ not necessarily an
undesirable situation for Microsoft, since last year the court
handed Microsoft a major victory.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Beyond the contrasts of the two cases, and the similarities, are
some odd common threads _ including a six-degree-of-separation
aspect to some of the lawyerly relationships. A few years ago, for
example, Intel's main trial lawyer, Robert E. Cooper, beat David
Boies, the Justice Department's marquee lawyer in the Microsoft
trial, in a predatory price fixing case brought by Continental
Airlines and Northwest Airlines against American Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, while Intel's public relations war with the government
has been at a lower decibel level than Microsoft's, its legal
maneuvering has been just as bare-knuckled. Court filings made
public this month show that Intel's lawyers secretly and
unsuccessfully attempted to knock the government's top trial
lawyer, Richard G. Parker, out of the case.
</P>
<P>
   Parker had done legal work for the chip maker Advanced Micro
Devices Inc., an Intel competitor, before joining the government.
In that capacity, he was involved in responding to an FTC request
for information during the agency's investigation of Intel.
</P>
<P>
   In denying Intel's request to remove Parker, Timony found that
the lawyer's participation in the proceeding would violate no
ethics rules, a finding that was also made by both the agency's
ethics lawyer and the Office of Government Ethics.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-02-21-99 1739EST &QL;
</P>
