<SLUG> BC-CPT-AOLBOSS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Case Study _ A Look at Mr. America Online  
 By Jon Swartz   
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The man who would be online king calmly leans back into a hotel
lobby sofa and politely explains how America Online became an
American icon.
</P>
<P>
   Without raising his voice or wagging an I-told-you-so finger,
AOL chief executive Steve Case clinically and succinctly describes
how AOL stuck to its long-held plan and proved a legion of
techno-snobs wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our strategy has always been crystal clear,'' Case said.
``Consumers want a central location where they can find good
content. And they want someone to make it easy for them.''
</P>
<P>
   AOL has the sheen of an overnight success, but in fact, Case's
willpower and years of persistance are what propelled it to the top
of the Internet heap.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, its revenues topped $2.6 billion, making it the most
profitable online company. The Dulles, Va., firm's market value is
nearly $75 billion, dwarfing Ford Motor Co. and vaulting Case into
the Parthenon of high-tech superstars. His stock holdings are
valued at more than $1 billion, based on AOL's stock price of
$160.38. And technology experts have anointed Case as the most
serious challenger to Microsoft CEO Bill Gates' mantle as high
tech's 800-pound gorilla.
</P>
<P>
   ``AOL is a triumph of Steve Case's marketing skills,'' said Dave
Cassel, editor of AOL Watch, a Berkeley Web site. ``They have
flourished despite a series of technical problems.''
</P>
<P>
   What is all the more remarkable is that the shy, unassuming Case
has engineered a dramatic turnaround _ from a company in constant
crisis just two years ago to a dominant player that has some
whispering the ``M'' word.
</P>
<P>
   AOL's enormous clout allows it to charge retailers and
advertisers steep prices for space on its sites, sparking
speculation that antitrust investigators might consider it a
monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting the one thing the world needs the least: another
giant, powerful and synergistic information hydra,'' online
essayist Jon Katz wrote following AOL's announcement that it would
buy Netscape. ``We don't finally have some competition for
Microsoft. We just have another Microsoft.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a theory that rankles the normally stoic Case, who was in
San Francisco last week for whirlwind meetings and a speech at the
Commonwealth Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday, we were irrelevant, and now we're too powerful,''
Case said in what amounts to trash talking for him. ``I find that
argument silly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have anything remotely monopolistic,'' he continued.
``We have a little over half of the online audience, and there are
plenty of competitors _ ranging from 5,000 (Internet service
providers) and startups to big-momma companies like Microsoft, AT&AMP;T
and Disney.''
</P>
<P>
   With 16 million paying subscribers, AOL reaches as many homes as
cable TV giant Tele-Communications Inc., and it adds about 12,000
users a day. On weeknights during prime time, the number of people
plugged into AOL peaks at 1 million, outdrawing CNN.
</P>
<P>
   And most important, users spend an average of 55 minutes a day
logged on to AOL, compared with 14 minutes in 1996. All told, more
than half of the nation's cybersurfers use AOL in some capacity _
either by subscribing to the service or by visiting its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty heady stuff for Case, 40, who got his start developing
toppings at Pizza Hut before joining Control Video Corp., AOL's
predecessor, in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Today, many credit him with bringing the Net to the masses. Want
proof? The chirpy message with which it greets subscribers was the
title of the Tom Hanks-Meg Ryan hit movie ``You've Got Mail.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This company pioneered the model of content and access: You
spend $22 (a month) to get specific information,'' said Jim
Balderston, an analyst at Zona Research Inc. in Redwood City. ``A
lot of companies would kill to have anyone pay for their service.
This is a media powerhouse.''
</P>
<P>
   The 9,000-person companyhas snapped up rival CompuServe Corp.,
whacked Prodigy's online service, fended off Microsoft and AT&AMP;T and
is on the verge of completing a $4.2 billion acquisition of
Netscape Communications Corp.
</P>
<P>
   AOL's most recent deals showcase its caginess about where the
market is headed and what consumers want. It purchased cutting-edge
technologies that offer instant messages with sound over the Net
and soon will make the Internet available on TV sets. AOL also
reportedly is in discussions to buy a piece of eBay, the popular
San Jose online auction company.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few years ago, hardly anyone would have expected AOL to
be at the forefront of the Internet. It has weathered hostile
takeover bids from Microsoft and AT&AMP;T, several technical meltdowns
of its online service in 1996 and 1997, and persistent sniping from
the online elite who dismiss it as ``the McDonald's of
cyberspace.''
</P>
<P>
   While others engaged in strategy du jour, AOL remained steady
and plowed ahead with the same game plan. For more than a decade,
Case has focused on building an audience by offering an easy-to-use
Internet service for the rest of us. AOL is not so much the
McDonald's of cyberspace as the Apple Computer.
</P>
<P>
   Case is ``like a metronome,'' says an executive at a rival
company, who asked not to be identified. ``He stuck to his guns,
and now he's one of the most powerful people in the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock has become a bellwether indicator for the
Internet market, climbing more than sixfold last year, and should
continue its ascent on a wave of Wall Street lust for Net stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Confirming its new blue-chip status, AOL has joined the
prestigious Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index this year, displacing
Venator, formerly Woolworth.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the digerati, the Internet's elite crowd that
pooh-poohed AOL for catering to the masses, have dropped or toned
down their disdain after concluding that Silicon Valley companies
did not pay enough attention to what the average consumer wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people were wrong about AOL,'' Marc Andreessen, the
Netscape co-founder who recently became AOL chief technology
officer, said recently. ``They gave the public what it wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   AOL has mastered the technique of capturing _ and retaining _
the ``eyeballs'' of consumers by using a variety of chat rooms,
instant messages, e-mail and online shopping sites. Users of its
proprietary network and AOL.com site spend an average of 246
minutes a month on AOL, tops among online services, according to
MediaMetrix in New York.
</P>
<P>
   And AOL could get even bigger.
</P>
<P>
   According to Case, about 25 percent of American homes _ or 60
million people _ are connected to the Internet, and their numbers
are growing fast. Seven years ago this month, when AOL went public,
only 3 percent of the country was wired.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just in the second or third inning. It's still early,''
Case said. ``Three-fourths of the public doesn't have an Internet
connection, and we can't assume that they're going to sign up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to make things easier for those folks,'' he said.
``There is plenty of work to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-02-22-99 2158EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
