u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-INTERNET-JOBS-HNS     02-24 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTERNET-JOBS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON-LINE JOB SEARCHES GIVE NEWSPAPERS A RUN FOR MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By GEORGE RAINE   
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When Mike Gnoss was looking for a job in
December, he turned to the Internet instead of the newspaper want
ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``My attitude was that once it was in the paper, the job was
pretty old, and I didn't have time to look through the ads, to do
any of that leg work,'' Gnoss said. ``I just cut to the chase. I
told Career Central.com to send me what fits my criteria.''
</P>
<P>
   Gnoss, 30, had just graduated with a master's degree in business
administration from the University of Southern California and knew
that he wanted to work in the San Francisco area, in the food
industry, in a finance-related position. He entered these criteria
in his posting at Palo Alto-based Career Central's Web site
(www.careercentral.com), and within a few weeks he accepted a job
in the corporate finance department of Chevys Fresh Mex. He now
forecasts the restaurant chain's future.
</P>
<P>
   Within the past two years, the future of job and candidate
searching has changed with the extraordinary rise of Internet-based
services and employers' using their own Web pages to recruit
directly.
</P>
<P>
   High-tech workers and companies have been the first to adapt to
the new technology, eschewing print classifieds, threatening a
reliable newspaper revenue stream.
</P>
<P>
   The American newspaper industry, with annual classified
advertising revenues of $19 billion in 1998, has watched the change
with trepidation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will always be newspapers,'' said Renee LaBran, vice
president for classified advertising, new media and print at the
Los Angeles Times. ``Are we immune from being affected by the
Internet? Not a chance. We will see some of our business migrate.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say that help-wanted classified advertising sales have
dipped in the past four months at newspapers in technology-heavy
regions of the country for a variety of reasons. Ad sales are
cyclical in nature and are affected by economic forces, but one of
them is the rising tide of Internet-based services.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past two years, we've probably dropped our print ad
budget by 60 to 70 percent,'' said Diane Schlageter, director of
employment at Adobe Systems Inc. in San Jose, the nation's largest
maker of desktop publishing and graphics software. ``A half-page ad
in the San Jose Mercury News may be $15,000 to $18,000. You can do
a lot of stuff on-line for that amount of money.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet as a human resources tool provides a more focused
applicant pool at less cost. This ``has been the most fundamental
shift I have seen in this business in 20 years,'' Schlageter said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cambridge, Mass.-based consulting group Forrester Research
Inc. issued a recent report, ``Goodbye to Classifieds,'' showing
that business will spend more and more money on Internet job
advertising. Of the 6 million businesses in the United States,
Forrester estimated that only 15,000 are recruiting on-line today,
but pervasive Internet access will drive the figure to 124,000 by
2003.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to conducting paid searches for prospective
employees through the growing number of Internet job service
providers, companies are posting positions on their own Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   One of them is Industrial Light and Magic in San Rafael,
creators of marvelous visual effects, where Rick Ross, recruiting
manager for parent Lucas Digital, seeks gifted computer scientists
and artists from among the 100 resumes he receives daily. Some 75
percent of them arrive via the Internet (www.ilm-jobs.com).
</P>
<P>
   Ross said the Web has greatly expedited the recruiting process,
especially in assessing the technical skills of candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are doing the impossible here, and it's important to have
people who can communicate both with a keyboard and verbally
because it's a team environment,'' Ross said.
</P>
<P>
   Ross added, however, that technology isn't very helpful in
measuring communications skills and judgment, so there is still
some conventional human resource filtering to do.
</P>
<P>
   On-line help-wanted services say technology allows them to match
candidates' strengths and interests to job openings quickly and
accurately _ faster and generally less expensively than advertising
in a newspaper. The services don't charge people who post resumes
or surf for openings. They earn their revenues by charging
employers who use the site to find workers.
</P>
<P>
   Competition is fierce in this fast-growing sector. Profitability
has so far eluded most sites as they pump revenues into keeping up
with the latest technology.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders in terms of numbers of job seekers and employer
clients are Monster.com (www.monster.com), Career Mosaic
(www.careermosaic.com) and Career Path (www.careerpath.com).
</P>
<P>
   Hotjobs (www.hotjobs.com) and Monster.com spent millions of
dollars on Super Bowl advertising. For New York-based Hotjobs, that
was a reach: Its 1998 revenues were $4 million, yet it spent $2
million on advertising. It was necessary, said company president
Richard Johnson, because the Internet world is evolving rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, newspapers responded to the changing classified
industry by forming CareerPath.com (www.careerpath.com), which is
owned by the nation's eight largest newspaper companies _ The New
York Times Co., Times-Mirror, Tribune Co., Knight-Ridder Corp.,
Washington Post Co., Cox Newspapers, Gannett and the Hearst
Corporation.
</P>
<P>
   On average, there are 300,000 job listings on the Los
Angeles-based site, by far the largest of any such service,
according to Stephen Ste. Marie, CareerPath's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   In January CareerPath had some 8 million job searches, a 71
percent increase over searches completed a month earlier. It
offers, among other listings, jobs from 83 affiliate newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Its pitch to advertisers is that they can pay once to have their
message appear both in affiliate newspapers and on-line at
CareerPath.com. ``No one else can do that,'' Ste. Marie said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While heeding change, some newspaper executives are skeptical
about whether the Internet is truly revolutionizing recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every article about this reads, `Golly, gee whiz ... It's
incredible that somebody found a job on the Internet,' and they
forget that thousands of people are finding their jobs in
newspapers every day,'' said Charlie Diederich, director of
recruitment advertising at the Newspaper Association of America in
the Vienna, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Diederich considers Internet recruiting ``a wake-up call for the
newspaper industry,'' but he smells hype. ``I could be the guy who
is saying buggy whips will always be or men will always wear hats,
but radio did not replace papers and TV did not displace radio, nor
has cable displaced TV. All of these things have created new
opportunities for papers.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-02-22-99 1705EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
