<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE BAD NEWS ON THE IMPEACHMENT FRONT 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Yet another bad thing about that impeachment
trial: Strom Thurmond woke up.
</P>
<P>
   Now the 96-year-old senator from South Carolina wants to triple
the federal tax on wine.
</P>
<P>
   Hypocrisy strikes again. The conservative Republican who once
opposed the federal government when it came to integrating blacks
and whites wants to use the federal government to punish makers of
reds and whites. Bad priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Thurmond is mad at the wine industry, partly because his
daughter was killed by a drunken driver, but mainly because
vintners are putting labels on wine suggesting it has health
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Health benefits, hell. If it weren't for wine, there wouldn't be
civilization.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, what do you suppose Thurmond considers a well-aged
wine? Something from Thomas Jefferson's cellar, perhaps. As for
Jefferson's ideas, he wouldn't have a taste for it.
</P>
<P>
   This is America and everybody wants to pass a law banning or
taxing things they don't like.
</P>
<P>
   Here's my idea: For every new law or tax that's passed, an old
law or tax has to be taken off the books. And anybody who claims to
be doing something for ``the children'' should be forced to watch
an endless loop of ``Teletubbies'' tapes.
</P>
<P>
   A group called the Christian Action Network says it's launching
a national campaign to put homosexual content labels, ``HC,'' on
television shows.
</P>
<P>
   This could lead to problems. Would networks be required to put
an HC on ``Spartacus,'' ``Wizard of Oz'' or all those Charlton
Heston-in-a-Roman-skirt movies?
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Action Network also surveyed its members'
attitudes toward Disney. Sample questions and results:
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you believe Disney should have `Gay Pride Days' at Disney
World in Orlando, Florida?'' Results: 0-Yes, 11,172-No.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you believe Disney should assault religious faith?''
Results: 1-Yes, 11,172-No.
</P>
<P>
   Who was that one who voted yes? Strom, put down the
questionnaire and go back to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Where was this tidbit when we needed it? Sen. Barbara Boxer,
D-Calif., points out that two of the leading House prosecutors of
President Clinton, men who kept lecturing us about sexual
harassment, opposed and gutted sexual harassment legislation in
1990.
</P>
<P>
   James Sensenbrenner, R-Wis., capped damages for victims of
on-the-job sexual harassment at $30,000. A Democratic congressman
then recalled the case of a woman whose co-workers exposed their
buttocks to her.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, according to the Congressional Quarterly Almanac
of 1990, Henry Hyde, R-Ill., added the distasteful comment that
``someone can show me their buttocks all day if I can get $30,000
per view.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the man who bemoans the decline of American
civilization. Well, he got his metaphorical mooning by the majority
of the American people, but not the $30,000. How does it feel now?
</P>
<P>
   Boxer is promoting a bill she has co-sponsored with Rep. George
Miller, D-Calif. The proposal would allocate $1.4 billion every
year to a fund to create parks, conserve open space and preserve
historic sites. The money would come from offshore oil fees already
collected by the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   Call it part of the impeachment trial recovery process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Speakers kept getting up and saying, `This is the most
important vote you're ever going to make,''' Boxer said of the
impeachment vote. ```Really?' I thought. I don't want this vote to
be my most important vote.''
</P>
<P>
   She says she now wants to move on to bigger things in the fields
of education, gun control and, of course, the environment.
</P>
<P>
   I had to ask Boxer what it was like to be in the Senate during
Clinton's trial. It was bad enough watching it on TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like being a prisoner of war,'' she said. ``If (Senate
Minority Leader Tom) Daschle and (Majority Leader Trent) Lott let
us out for a 10-minute bathroom break we were grateful to them the
same way prisoners of war are grateful to their captors for small
favors.''
</P>
<P>
   Boxer said Republican and Democratic senators felt the same way,
and grew closer. ``It was equal opportunity torture.''
</P>
<P>
   I asked if she had any advice for Hillary Rodham Clinton, who is
considering a run for the Senate in New York. ``Go ahead and do
it,'' she said she would tell Hillary. Then she added: ``I must
admit I am being selfish. I want her there. I don't know if it's in
her best interest.''
</P>
<P>
   I don't know either. Her opponent would be New York Mayor Rudy
Giuliani, and he's meaner than any vast right-wing conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary has already made the mistake of advocating a Palestinian
state, which in New York can hurt a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
