<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE'S THE NEW SPEAKER OF THE SOX' HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ The torch is officially passed. In the Red
Sox relay of this half-century, it has been handed down from Ted
Williams to Carl Yastrzemski to Jim Rice to Roger Clemens to Mo
Vaughn . . . and now to Nomar Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   Nomar is nothing like those who came before him. He is an
X-Games, on-line, World Cup kind of guy. The only things Old Timey
about Nomar are his haircut and his game. Sox manager Jimy Williams
said it best when he observed, ``It's like he's been here before.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe there is some Ty Cobb in the old soul of the Sox
shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra was be part of the first full workout for all Sox
players at the club's minor league complex on the Gulf Coast
Wednesday (Feb. 24). Tuesday he did the obligatory new year
stand-up interview with a couple of dozen members of the media
corps. Like Williams and Rice before him, he seems pained by the
process of spreading the gospel of baseball to fans in the frozen
North. Nomar would be happiest if he could just give us his game
and go home, but the resident Red Sox superstar is obliged to talk
baseball occasionally. Almost always, Garciaparra sounds like he's
probably going to miss Mo's protection in the clubhouse more than
in the batting order.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind it,'' Garciaparra said when asked about his new
spokesman status. ``It's a matter of respect. I understand you guys
got a job to do. I understood the way it works over the years. As
long as everybody understands that I've got a job to do. There's
certain times I've got to be focused. I've got a job to do and
that's my first priority. As long as everybody knows the rules and
we all work together, we can be happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something you get used to or relish or get concerned
about. My concern is my job and I don't want to get taken away from
what I've got to do. I just don't like anything getting in the way.
My job's out there, it ain't in here. I don't think about it. I'm
not going to change. I'm out there to win a World Series. That's my
focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra and Vaughn are close. Nomar said they've spoken
frequently since Vaughn's departure. It's too bad Linda Tripp
wasn't around with her handy-dandy wiretap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody can take Mo's spot, what Mo's done for
the team and the community and everything,'' said Nomar. ``You
can't replace a guy like Mo. But nobody's looking to do that.
Everybody's still themselves. We've still got a great ball club.
Everybody's got their personalities and there's no need to
change.''
</P>
<P>
   He rejected the notion that he won't see as many strikes without
Mo in the lineup to protect him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not thinking about that at all,'' he said. ``I've got to
go out and play my game. I'm not gonna change anything. You just
make adjustments. We still have great people hitting in the lineup.
Last year it wasn't just Mo, it wasn't just me, it was everybody.
We didn't lose everybody. We lost Mo.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra speaks in a nervous, quick cadence. Issuing his
standard answers, he sometimes breaks into a smile for no apparent
reason. He might be a candidate for John Dennis's interview
academy, but Tuesday he was at his best with the microphone folk.
He even made a little joke when asked if he heard about Clemens
going to the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``That one I don't see how you could miss,'' he said. ``They
even said a news report in the middle of `Friends' while I was
watching. I thought it was part of the series, but it wasn't. What
are you gonna do? We can't worry about the Yankees. We have to
worry about ourselves. The hard thing is we don't have Mo. But
we've got the same attitude this year that we had last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra went to Ted Williams's hitters museum earlier in the
month and spent time talking with the Splendid One. It was there
that Williams said Nomar has a chance to become one of baseball's
all-time greats.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's flattering,'' he said. ``Ted Williams is unbelievable. I
love talking to Ted. I have so much respect for him and just to be
next to him is unbelievable. I love old-school baseball. I don't
follow people's numbers or stats. I just love the way the game was
back then. They played hard and enjoyed it. I think it's coming
back that way.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Sox were eliminated by the Indians at Fenway last
October, Garciaparra was the last Boston player to leave the field
and didn't disappear until he had applauded the Fenway legions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a tremendous year,'' he said. ``The end was
disappointing. We truly believed we were going all the way and at
the end we had that all in our hearts. People wrote us off, but
those fans in the stands were there every day, supporting us all
year, pulling us through. I just wanted to thank them. It was
really them that was showing the positive energy. They're there
every day supporting us and we appreciate that. I felt like it was
the fans and ourselves out there playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't read headlines or reports. I don't need anybody else
to tell me how we're playing. I know myself. Last year the only
people who believed in us were ourselves and our fans. We shocked
everybody who was negative against us. I don't pay attention to it.
Why am I going to waste my energy on that when I know what's going
on myself?''
</P>
<P>
   So he won't read about himself. And he won't pay any attention
to where the media pick the 1999 Red Sox to finish. He'll just keep
working to improve his already glorious game. And that should be
enough.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-99 1346EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
