<DOCNO> NYT19990224.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7398 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANALOG-UPTURN-ART-BOS     02-24 1260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANALOG-UPTURN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRIDGING THE WORLDS OF REAL AND DIGITAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It only takes a split-second. The car hits the lamppost or the
brick wall or the other vehicle, and a set of microscopic silicon
fingers detects the deadly deceleration that could send the
driver's face smashing into the steering wheel. The silicon fingers
twitch just enough to release an electrical pulse. And just like
that, the car's air bags inflate and save somebody's life.
</P>
<P>
   The silicon fingers are part of an accelerometer _ a device for
measuring changes in speed. Accelerometers used to be bulky,
expensive devices, but this one is inside a microchip the size of a
thumbnail. And chips like this one are made by the millions at a
nondescript factory in Cambridge, Mass., by an unglamorous Norwood,
Mass. firm called Analog Devices Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The accelerometer chip takes a real-world event _ the slamming
impact of a car crash _ and translates it into an electronic
signal. That is Analog Devices' specialty _ chips that mediate
between the messy, imprecise world of sound and motion and the
sharp, precise universe of digital information managed by computer
chips.
</P>
<P>
   ``Real-world signal processing,'' is how Analog's chairman Ray
Stata describes it. Stata cofounded the firm in 1965, back when it
focused on the comparatively simple business of amplifying analog
signals, like voices through a microphone.
</P>
<P>
   Analog signals move in waves. But computers work with data in
sharply-defined sets of numbers. So if you want to pump sound or
motion or some other analog information through a computer, you've
first got to digitize it. The latest digital cell phones turn the
caller's voice into a stream of data packets. The voice on the
other end arrives as a stream of digital data which must be turned
back into analog sound. And there's a good chance that chips from
Analog Devices are doing the converting.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good business to be in. According to the Semiconductor
Industry Association, worldwide sales of analog chips should pass
$24 billion this year. Rapid growth is expected through the turn of
the century, as the chips appear in phones and personal digital
assistants like the 3Com Palm Pilot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The analog industry is known to be the most stable in the
semiconductor business,'' says Stata, who's serving as chairman of
the SIA this year. ``There's just hundreds and hundreds of
companies that buy a little, but it all adds up.''
</P>
<P>
   It also helps that Analog Devices makes about 800 different chip
products, each tailored to a particular application. ``The lion's
share of our products are proprietary and there are no second
sources,'' said Jerald Fishman, Analog's president and chief
executive. ``We don't make commodity products that five or six
other companies produce.''
</P>
<P>
   This is why Analog Devices was able to keep its head above water
in 1998, a nasty year in the chip business because of excess
production capacity. SIA estimates that industry revenues fell 10
percent during the year, but Analog's revenue of $1.23 billion was
only slightly lower than in 1997. Net income of $119 million was
down from $178 million in 1997 because of price pressure in some
parts of Analog's business.
</P>
<P>
   Stata is predicting an upturn for the entire semiconductor
industry this year, but thinks Analog Devices can do even better,
partly because of its intense focus on one of the hottest chip
markets _ the devices that process incoming signals after they've
been translated into digital form.
</P>
<P>
   These chips are called digital signal processors. Each DSP is a
computer in its own right. But processors like Intel Corp.'s famous
Pentium series are all-purpose devices, designed to do many kinds
of computing reasonably well. DSPs do just a few things with
stunning speed.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine someone making a phone call from his car. Today's
digital cell phones can filter out the extraneous noises _ the
humming of the motor and shifting of the gears, for instance. This
is possible because of a DSP inside the phone that detects the
noises and deletes them instantly. Doing this requires processing
speeds of a hundred million calculations per second, or more. Not
long ago, that would have required a supercomputer. Today it takes
one DSP chip that costs a few dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The electronics industry has a seemingly limitless hunger for
these chips. The SIA says industrywide DSP revenues grew an
estimated 23 percent in 1998 to $3.9 billion. They expect DSP sales
to hit $8 billion by 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't want DSPs,'' said Tom Starnes, a chip industry
analyst for Dataquest in Austin, Texas. ``They want cellular
phones, they want hard drives, they want modems. And they want them
to go faster and faster all the time. And to do that, you need
digital signal processors.''
</P>
<P>
   Analog Devices is an also-ran in the DSP business, trailing not
only Texas Instruments Inc., but also Lucent Technologies Inc. and
Motorola Inc. But Analog is making a bid to enter the first rank of
DSP suppliers. On Feb. 3, the company announced a joint development
agreement with Intel, the world's biggest maker of computer chips.
The two firms will design a new generation of DSPs for small, cheap
computing devices, such as palm-sized computers.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement gives Analog access to Intel's brightest chip
engineers, who will work with an Analog team at a facility in
Austin. Perhaps most important, it means that the thousands of
engineers and programmers worldwide who design products around
Intel technologies will also begin designing for Analog products.
``From a marketing perspective, it gives them a whole lot of
additional leverage,'' said technology analyst Drew Peck of SG
Cowen in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   To further bolster its DSP know-how, Analog earlier this month
acquired White Mountain DSP Inc. of Nashua, and agreed to buy
Edinburgh Portable Compilers of Edinburgh. Both companies make
software tools are used in the design of DSPs.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Analog is well positioned for the expected boom in
high-speed Internet services. The company makes chips used to
provide ADSL, a high-speed data technology that works over standard
phone lines. The nation's major phone companies are committed to
deploying ADSL services to millions of homes and businesses this
year. Much of the underlying technology was developed by Aware Inc.
of Bedford, Mass., which has a strategic alliance with Analog.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's micromachining _ the complex process of building
tiny machines in silicon. Analog's air bag sensor is a
micromachine, with moving parts thinner than a hair. Fishman said
that micromachines make up only a trivial percentage of the
company's income. Still, he notes that his company has about
one-third of the world market for air bag activation sensors, and
that the business will turn profitable this year.
</P>
<P>
   And Stata predicts a wave of new applications that could create
a vast market for the micromachines. Microsoft Corp. already makes
a game controller which lets a player move through the game by
tilting the device in his hands. The Analog devices accelerometer
chip inside is so sensitive, it can detect the changing position of
the controller and alter the action on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're at the bleeding edge,'' said analyst Drew Peck. A
risky place to be, but often it's where the money is.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
