<HEADLINE>
BAY AREA EYES WATER ROUTES AROUND ITS GRIDLOCK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Gleaming icons of the Pacific Rim, they soar
above San Francisco Bay in Art Deco majesty. As artifacts of
beauty, the Golden Gate Bridge and the Bay Bridge to Oakland are
impressive tourist destinations. But as commuter routes, these
60-year-old engineering feats are inefficient, mostly because they
are parking lots several hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic, the petulant handmaiden of prosperity, is a favorite
topic of conversation in the counties surrounding the bay: Were you
stuck on the bridge the other night for hours? When does the rush
hour really begin now? Does it ever end?
</P>
<P>
   Few Californians rely solely on politicians for answers,
especially the business leaders who bankroll the Bay Area Council,
a private-public partnership that ``promotes economic prosperity
and quality of life in the region.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, the council hopes to revive the ferry system that
criss-crossed the bay In the 1930s. Before the bridges, ferries
carried 50 million passengers annually. After the bridges, highways
approaching them proliferated, as did traffic jams. By 1958, the
nadir of disinvestment in urban development in America, ferries had
vanished.
</P>
<P>
   Increased traffic and natural disasters, like mudslides near the
Golden Gate Bridge, resurrected ferry service. Some 3.5 million
people used water transit last year, to and from Vallejo, Larkspur,
Tiburon, Sausalito, Alameda, and Oakland. Most were satisfied with
a smoother, safer, more reliable ride.
</P>
<P>
   Then, let's do it right, suggests a Bay Area Council study,
outlining a $2 billion plan for fast and frequent ferries early in
the new century. A two-stage program would begin with a $680
million plan for 28 new terminals with 75 ferries traveling 440
miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who will pay for all this?'' is the question most people ask
after admiring the concept. This question is seldom asked about the
massive highway building and rebuilding constantly underway here.
</P>
<P>
   Like the queen in ``Alice in Wonderland,'' Californians are
known to believe several impossible things before breakfast. Every
day since 1956, they have believed that freeways are free. That was
the year President Eisenhower signed the bill creating the
Interstate Highway System, providing 90 percent funding for major
highways.
</P>
<P>
   Highways depend on federal and state gas taxes, so it is
somebody's money, a total of $4.5 million, according to the
Metropolitan Transit Commission. Few holler about highway costs
because the commission estimates that traffic will increase by 249
percent in 2020 if current trends don't change. Maybe by then, a
trifle late, an alternative to automobile travel may be attractive.
</P>
<P>
   California loves the automobile so much that it spends billions
just to stay still. The Cypress Freeway in Oakland, replaced after
a 1989 earthquake, was finally finished last year at a cost of $900
million. This project did not add capacity to the Bay Area's
transportation system. Nor will retrofitting the east span of the
Bay Bridge, which will cost $1.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   No, freeways are not free, and they are notoriously fragile in
earthquakes, a fact of life here. In the council's study listing 28
new sites, a terminal's functions are often catalogued ``commuter;
recreational; disaster recovery.'' Boats can still travel after an
earthquake while some freeways turn to jelly.
</P>
<P>
   Many potential ferry docks are already available in abandoned
military bases, from Moffett Field near San Jose to the Oakland
Army Base to the Presidio in San Francisco and to the north and
east at Hamilton Air Force Base and Mare Island. These sites are
also being eyed by housing developers for some of the 10 million
new Californians demographers expect in the coming decades.
</P>
<P>
   Common sense says that higher tolls and gas taxes should pay for
an efficient, pleasant alternative to the automobile, but to a
Californian, common sense can wilt at the first whiff of carbon
monoxide.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Martin F. Nolan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
