<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEER HUNTING IN THE 'HOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN MCNAMARA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even the dog is beginning to look askance when I wake him at
dawn to go deer hunting.
</P>
<P>
   Fritz treasures nothing so much as his morning walk, but his
brown eyes have been full of suspicion lately when I rouse him from
his favorite chair at first light. He does not know what to make of
a mistress suddenly so obsessed with stalking deer.
</P>
<P>
   It's not clear when they arrived in this neighborhood of
quarter-acre lots. They have probably been here all along, living
quietly in the wooded cemetery on the hill. In the last week,
they've wandered down among us, their sleek, graceful movements
belying their enormous size as they bound through backyards and
graze in the small groves of trees tucked between rows of
center-entrance colonials and split-levels.
</P>
<P>
   Not that I've seen them myself, mind you. I am sustained by the
reports of others. From my spouse, who caught sight of an enormous
buck on a solitary run across the Berens' front yard. From my kids,
who at dusk saw four does slip out of the narrow stand of trees
between the Doyle and Donahue homes.
</P>
<P>
   Big deal, you say. It is hardly news that the deer population is
on the rise in Massachusetts; deer are such a common sight in many
suburbs that some homeowners consider the magnificent creatures
nothing more than tick-carrying, traffic-stopping, shrub-devouring
nuisances.
</P>
<P>
   This is a personal thing, one urban woman agog that there are
big, wild animals roaming through her very own suburban 'hood! Grow
up in the city and a rat running along the railroad tracks or a
skunk snoozing under the back porch is what passes for wildlife.
There were no deer sightings on our dead-end street in North
Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   As kids, my best friend, Frances, and I would sit on her front
porch in the summer fantasizing about the lives we would make in
the country someday. We collected stuffed animals, instead of
dolls. We did not begrudge Snow White or Sleeping Beauty their
princes; we envied them the rabbits and owls and deer that cavorted
with them in those technicolor glens.
</P>
<P>
   At our adjoining country homes, we imagined, Frances would raise
horses and dogs. I would raise dogs and sheep. Not that either one
of us had ever been to the country or knew anything about horses or
sheep. It was a city kid's fantasy of life at the other extreme.
</P>
<P>
   Frances actually got there. I made it only as far as the
suburbs, a kind of in-between place where there are no tenants
living upstairs, but there are no paddocks out back, either. A dog,
a rabbit, and two guinea pigs live here, but there is no mistaking
them for anything but the pampered pets they are.
</P>
<P>
   It is fashionable to trash the suburbs, to mock the trimmed
lawns, the driveways littered with bikes and basketballs. But,
among the sports utility vehicles and the soccer fields, there are
brooks to walk along, lakes to stroll around, woods to hike
through.
</P>
<P>
   I've always known the animals were out there, of course. I
didn't expect them to display themselves for my entertainment. But,
lately, I have begun to suspect they will show themselves to anyone
BUT me. It is as though they smell the city on me. It is my
daughter who sees the muskrat swimming in the brook on her way home
from school. It is my husband who spies the foxes on the local
nine-hole golf course. It is my son who finds the wild rabbit and
her newborn bunnies in a hillside burrow in his pal's backyard.
</P>
<P>
   They know that when they announce their wildlife sightings, it
is only an act of will that keeps me from shouting: ``What about
ME? Why do I see nothing but gray squirrels and black crows?''
</P>
<P>
   Last summer there were reports of a coyote in the neighborhood.
The police came around to warn us to keep our cats inside, to leash
our dogs on walks. At lunch with a group of neighbors, Jackie
Norton recounted hearing the coyote one night. His howl had sounded
like a baby's cry. When she went to her bedroom window there he
was, baying at the moon, right between the lawn furniture and the
rhododendrons. She lives only a few doors away. I'd slept through
the whole show.
</P>
<P>
   Now the deer have come, and I figure this could be my last
chance. Who knows how long it will be before the developers in my
town chop down what woods remain and carve up what meadows still
exist to build ever bigger houses on ever smaller lots?
</P>
<P>
   So, this week Fritz and I are rising early. We are moving
steathily through the dawn, one obsessed woman and one bemused dog,
deer hunting in the 'hood.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Eileen McNamara's e-mail address is mcnamara(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
