<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HIDDEN COSTS OF HANDGUNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The booming economy of handguns is a boomerang. US gun makers
sold between $2 billion and $3 billion worth of arms last year. As
the gun makers show no conscience over the pain of their profits,
their consumers lock and load and unload onto America a staggering
bill that far surpasses the sales themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Gunfire leaves America with up to $4 billion a year in direct
medical costs, according to a 1995 study in the Journal of the
American Medical Association. While a name-brand handgun can cost
as little as $250 and a 9mm pistol magazine can cost $25, medical
experts estimate that the average cost of treating one gunshot
victim can cost anywhere from $14,000 to $33,000.
</P>
<P>
   That does not figure in long-term medical costs, police
services, lost wages, and lost quality of life. Published estimates
of all those costs can add up to between $300,000 and $400,000. The
Handgun Epidemic Lowering Plan (HELP), based out of Children's
Memorial Medical Center in Chicago, estimates that each firearm
fatality costs $938,500.
</P>
<P>
   The annual total cost to the nation of gun violence is vague,
but every estimate is stunning. The 1995 study in JAMA estimates
$20 billion. HELP's estimate is $33 billion. A 1996 study in the
Textbook of Penetrating Trauma estimated $112 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever the numbers, taxpayers directly or indirectly pay
80 &UR;  &LR; percent-85 percent of the bills because so many victims lack
health insurance. The bills are too much for the nation's mayors.
Chicago and New Orleans have filed lawsuits against the gun
industry. Boston and other cities plan to sue. They are suing
because they can no longer wait on the White House or Congress,
which regulate guns less than burgers, Barbie, and air bags.
</P>
<P>
   The City of Boston estimates that gun violence costs $10 million
a year. Hospitals and taxpayers in Philadelphia pick up $29 million
a year for uninsured victims of gunfire. Louisiana taxpayers lose
$6 million a year to treat uninsured gun victims. Gun control
advocates say the annual cost of firearm injuries in New York City
surpasses $94 million.
</P>
<P>
   To the mayors, gun violence is far more than an issue of crime.
Peter Welsh, a top aide to Boston Mayor Thomas M. Menino, said,
``We're riding a tidal wave of interest in this in terms of
consumer protection and public health. We want to hold handgun
manufacturers responsible the way car manufacturers and tobacco
companies are held responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   John Auerbach, executive director of Boston's Public Health
Commission, has added, ``The starting point for us is thinking of
this as a public health issue and not just a public safety issue.
Some would say it's a public health epidemic. So it makes sense to
think about the same interventions as you would with other public
health issues, like tobacco.''
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco is a fitting comparison. Deputy Treasury Secretary
Lawrence Summers last year said the national medical costs due to
smoking were $45 billion. The total costs of lost wages and
productivity, fires caused by smoking, and other costs led Summers
to estimate the total cost of smoking to the economy to be $130
billion. That is close to double the revenue of the two top
American cigarette makers, Philip Morris and RJR Nabisco.
</P>
<P>
   Even keeping merely to direct medical costs, the cost of gun
violence and smoking to society would be enough to pay for over
half of the $112 billion that the General Accounting Office
estimates it would cost to repair or replace the nation's public
school buildings. Add in lost productivity and students would of
course have not only buildings but the Internet and afterschool
activities to keep them off the streets. Summers said:
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important to recognize that all of these represent, in
the language of economics, real resource costs. That it is to say,
the $130 billion that smoking costs is much more burdensome to our
economy than the same amount levied in taxes, which impose a cost
on consumers, but provide offsetting revenues to our government. It
is proverbial that there is no such thing as a free lunch. But in a
sense, successfully preventing people from acquiring an addiction
they do not want to have _ by effectively combatting youth smoking
_ is a free lunch with real benefits for our economy as well our
nation.''
</P>
<P>
   There same is true of gun violence. Put $2 billion to $3 billion
of gun sales next to $20 billion, $33 billion, or more in the costs
of those sales to society and you have an argument stronger than
ever before that handguns have no place in the hands of civilians.
For that reason, it is encouraging to see mayors stand up where
Capitol Hill trembles. Let them all attack with the same kind of
gauntlet thrown down by Chicago Mayor Richard Daley. When Chicago
filed a $433 million lawsuit last fall against gun makers and
distributors, Daley said:
</P>
<P>
   ``If money is the only language they understand, then money is
the language we will use to make them understand that they have no
business in Chicago. We're going to hit them where it hurts _ in
their bank accounts _ and we won't stop hitting them until they
stop flooding our streets with guns.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-99 1351EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
