<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7406 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      02-24 1261
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOYS WILL BE BOYS; NEW YORK WILL BE NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A specter is haunting men's magazines _ the specter of Maxim.
</P>
<P>
   In the beginning, there was Esquire, which for two decades
pretty much had the guy-mag field to itself. Oh, there were
barbershop favorites like True and Argosy and the Police Gazette,
but it was Esquire that invented the upmarket-male formula: flashy
writing, fashion, and a whiff or two of musk. The arrival of
Playboy in the '50s reconfigured things a bit. What had seemed very
risque in the '40s (the Post Office actually wanted to ban Esquire
from the mail) seemed very tame in a post-Hef world. So with
Playboy creating its own male-demographic niche, the flesh book _
Esquire and, later, GQ _ had to find another way to generate
interest. Under Harold Hayes, during the '60s and early '70s
Esquire became as exciting a magazine as America has known. Loosing
Tom Wolfe and Gay Talese (among others) on an unsuspecting
readership, it pretty much invented the New Journalism. Then in the
'80s, under Art Cooper, GQ, which had previously been a fairly flat
Pepsi to Esquire's highly carbonated Coke, upped its editorial
ratio of substantial to sartorial and, by so doing, made itself one
of the hottest (and ad-heaviest) titles in the Conde Nast stable.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, the handwriting on the men's room wall appeared in the
early '90s, courtesy of another Conde Nast publication, Details.
Details started out as a downtown style magazine. Conde Nast bought
it and turned it into a men's magazine for guys in their teens who
wanted to fantasize about what it must be like to be guys in their
20s. Esquire and GQ had been, and still are, mostly for guys in
their 20s who want to fantasize what it must be like to be in their
guys 30s. Details was Fox to their NBC and CBS: higher energy,
lower rent, determinedly uncouth.
</P>
<P>
   Under James Truman, Details was an extremely hot book _ so much
so that, in 1994, Truman landed in the legendary Alexander
Liberman's chair as Conde Nast editorial director. That was then,
though, and this is now, and it's a sign of how much the times have
changed _ and how passe Details has become _ that the biggest news
it's made since Truman's departure came three weeks ago when it
hired away Maxim's Mark Golin to become its fourth editor in the
last five years.
</P>
<P>
   Maxim has been on US newstands less than two years but already
has a circulation of 950,000, twice that of Details. Its runaway
success has inspired at least one knockoff, Gear, and a less overt
influence has been discerned in a general unbuttoning (as one might
call it) among guy mags, the most frequently cited example being
Esquire's February cover story on ``Cleavage Culture,'' featuring
Pamela Anderson in high mammary mode.
</P>
<P>
   Maxim has the look of a supermarket tab on glossy paper _ lots
of reds, blacks, and yellows _ and the resemblance doesn't end
there. ``Sophistication's just another word for too much left to
lose'' could be the magazine's motto. Proudly prurient,
energetically sophomoric, it's Playboy's Party Jokes writ large,
the National Lampoon played straight: a canny reductio ad absurdum
of the guy-mag aesthetic. Maxim is for guys in their teens and 20s
who want to fantasize about what it must be like to be guys in
their teens. The March issue boasts (if that is the word) such
articles as ``Help! They Mangled My Penis'' and ``Pick Up Women
With a Sock Puppet!'' Now no one expects a men's magazine to be
Partisan Review (which, by the way, devotes its Winter issue to a
symposium on Czeslaw Milosz, with notable contributions coming from
Milosz's fellow Nobel laureate Seamus Heaney and Jack Miles, the
Pulitzer Prize-winning author of ``God: A Biography''). But the
mass-market success of a magazine that informs its readers ``If you
make her drool, you rule,'' does make one wonder, at least a little
bit, about the fate of Western civilization.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness, let it be noted that the March issue also includes
a wonderfully loopy interview with overnight radio
talkmeister/nutcake Art Bell. The Q's (``Aliens in entertainment?
Would that explain Michael Jackson?'') are almost as funny as the
A's (``the outrageous success of (`The X-Files') leads me to
believe there's some force behind the scenes there, helping us get
used to the idea (of aliens among us). Helping further their
agenda. These are the things I wonder about in my most private
moments''). As for the things Maxim readers wonder about in their
most private moments _ well, let's say guys just want to have fun,
and leave it at that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The latest Paris Review (Fall) ``Writers at Work'' interviewees
are Mark Strand and V. S. Naipaul. Strand suffers for having
Wallace Shawn as interlocutor. All the latter's tics as an actor
are on display as interviewer (``I have to ask you one more
personal question. Well, I don't have to, but I will, because I'm
curious''). In the Naipaul, all tics are supplied by the
interviewee. The author of ``A Bend in the River'' and ``A House
for Mister Biswas'' may or may not be the greatest living novelist
in English, but he is undoubtedly the Alexander Haig of literary
interviewees, leaving no doubt who's in charge here. ``Let me know
the range of what you are doing and how you are going to approach
it,'' Naipaul informs his interviewer at the outset. ``I want to
know with what intensity to talk.'' By the time he's done, Naipaul
is wondering, ``Do you think I've wasted a bit of myself talking to
you?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Far silkier as interview subject is the late Isaiah Berlin in
The Wilson Quarterly (Winter). Lewis M. Dabney has long been
working on a biography of Edmund Wilson, and in 1991 he sought out
the Oxford don to discuss his friend, America's greatest man of
letters. Berlin is reputed to have been without peer as a
conversationalist, and even someone uninterested in Edmund Wilson
can see why, watching him dazzle Dabney. Part of Berlin's talent
was a dexterity with the blade no less deadly for being sheathed in
velvet. Contrasting the critic Lionel Trilling with Wilson, Berlin
says of the former, ``he was a delicate, sensitive, extremely
honest, and very communicative writer, but he understood far
less.'' What Trilling had to offer, Berlin adds, was ``just
intelligent sentences.'' It's hard to say which is more lethal:
``just'' or ``sentences'' (``pages'' or even ``paragraphs,'' fine,
but ``sentences''!).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New Yorker (Feb. 22 &AMP; March 1) devotes a double anniversary
issue to its hometown. David Remnick takes a highly entertaining,
if not especially probing, look at Metropolitan Opera impresario
Joseph Volpe. Mark Singer ponders the long silence of his legendary
New Yorker colleague Joseph Mitchell. Richard Avedon offers a
portfolio of New York notables (Grace Paley, peeking out a
Palladian window on Page 134, is our personal favorite). Best of
all, Rick Hertzberg celebrates the ``Topless Tabloids of Gotham.''
It would be difficult to better how he describes the contents of
the likes of The New York Post, The Daily News _ or, for that
matter, The Boston Herald _ ``Inside is a version of what appears
in other daily newspapers, but with bigger headlines, shorter
paragraphs, tough-guy columnists, and heavy emphasis on sensation,
sports, and entertainment. The writing, at its best, is as direct
and riveting as a ransom note.'' And at its worst . . . well, Maxim
needs a new editor, doesn't it?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-99 1353EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
