u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-24 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELPRIN SHOULD JUST MOVE ON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mark Helprin is one of the greatest fiction writers in America.
His best work, in his short stories and in the novel ``Soldier of
the Great War'' is as good as the best writing of Timothy Findley
in his superb books ``The Wars'' and ``Famous Last Words.''
Literary conspiracy theorists speculate that both men are
underappreciated, Findley because he is Canadian and Helprin
because he is politically conservative. It is quite surprising that
Helprin has never bagged a Pulitzer nor a National Book Award, and
that Findley is never mentioned for a Nobel. Who knows? Even
conspiracy theorists have to be right sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years Helprin has distinguished himself less for his
brilliant fiction than for his political broadsides thundering off
the op-ed pages of The Wall Street Journal. Politics seems to be
the shiny stone that the youthful-looking, 52-year-old Helprin just
can't put down. He once told an interviewer he might run for the
Senate. During the 1996 presidential campaign, he briefly signed on
with Bob Dole as a speechwriter/Big Idea man, to little effect. Can
you recall a Bob Dole speech or Big Idea?
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Helprin has been exercising his considerable
rhetorical powers to dump all over the man who sent Bob Dole to
Viagra Sponsorship Heaven _ Bill Clinton. He has likened the
Clinton administration to the Cosa Nostra. He has called the
president the ``thinking man's Tawana Brawley.'' (Nasty but funny,
I have to admit.) In his pompous, house of burgess-era rhetoric, he
has ordered the president to resign: ``What will you do? I will
tell you, sir, what you will do. You will resign.'' Oddly, Clinton
seems not to have been listening.
</P>
<P>
   What I am suggesting here, respectfully, is that it is time for
Mr. Helprin to return to his day job.
</P>
<P>
   In his half-dozen anti-Clinton philippics, Helprin airs out the
grand martial themes that inform his best fiction: courage,
manliness, death, love, and honor. When he grants interviews _ and
when he curbs his penchant for self-invention _ Helprin waxes
Tolstoyan, and likes us to think that said themes suffuse his life.
After leaving Harvard, he volunteered for the Israeli air force. He
now complains about ``missing'' the Vietnam War: ``a regret that I
will carry to my grave.''
</P>
<P>
   I would forgive Helprin his incessant posturing, and much more,
but I would never forgive him for an article published last Tuesday
in The Wall Street Journal. In a lengthy, rambling essay called
``The Soldiers of Calais,'' Helprin compared the House impeachment
managers to the British Army's 30th Brigade fighting outside of
Dunkirk during World War II. Winston Churchill had to evacuate the
British Army across the English Channel, and he ordered the 30th
Brigade to hold off the pursuing Nazi Army at Calais, without
withdrawing or surrendering.
</P>
<P>
   The 30th Brigade withstood the Germans for three days, suffering
huge casualties. Churchill credited them with saving his army, and
possibly their country: ``Calais was the crux,'' he said. In his
essay, Helprin likens the House managers (Henry Hyde, Robert Barr &AMP;
Co.) to the dead soldiers at Calais: ``The House managers have died
a political death . . . by their sacrifices, their willingness to
risk, and their assumption of danger, (they) are the real senators
of this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from being wrong _ most of House managers are expected to
keep their seats in the 2000 election _ Helprin's analogy is
hideously twisted. Reasonable people disagree about the severity of
Bill Clinton's crimes and the resulting punishment, or lack of
punishment. But no reasonable person thinks the managers risked
their lives _ not even their political lives! _ for their country.
</P>
<P>
   Aristotle, the kind of author Helprin loves to invoke for his
baroque arguments, wrote at great length about the appropriateness
of metaphor. For an analogy to be successful, it must be
appropriate, as Helprin's is not. Instead of valorizing the
accomplishment of the heroic defenders of Calais, he has cheapened
it. Instead of honoring them, he has desecrated their memory. Now
they have suffered a second death, under the pen of a fatuous,
right-wing hack.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
