<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUOMO'S CALL TO COMMUNITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BY DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Winning high elective office is not the only way to influence
public policy. But there are only a handful of American
practitioners of the lofty political speech.
</P>
<P>
   Because there are so many ways to communicate now, communication
is cheaper, in more ways than one. For a generation that grew up on
Jerry Springer and Howard Stern, that thinks political oratory is
what dribbled over from the squalid impeachment imbroglio,
politician-speak means naught but spin, sophistry, and
cynicism-from-those-seeking-sinecures.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, there's Mario Cuomo. Thrice-elected and
once-defeated for governor of New York, the man who is probably the
nation's most gifted philosopher-politician delivered himself of
that most rare commodity Monday night at Harvard:
</P>
<P>
   A political oration rooted in Judeo-Christian theology, laced
with real-world examples and the hard lessons of 20th century
American history, and delivered with the pace and polish one
expects of a Grand Master. I've been in the room for a lot of Cuomo
masterpieces: his Notre Dame speech defending abortion in '84, his
Democratic convention declamations of '84 and '92.
</P>
<P>
   And now this one at the Kennedy School. It was a simple summons
to the gifted young to reach back to those in poverty. ``There is
still a Second City where the glitter doesn't show,'' he said,
where wages languish, health care is priced out of household
budgets, jobs and skills and basic education recede, and what is
left is a brooding, increasingly brutish underclass frozen out of
the brightly lit glassed-in towers of the wired, the connected, the
lucky.
</P>
<P>
   There is abroad in the land ``a lowering of aspiration . . . a
loss of confidence,'' that government can be organized to lift up
the downtrodden. The spirit that won wars, licked Jim Crow, raised
up women, and walked the moon has given way to artful appeals to
selfishness, couched in the language of tax cuts, suggesting
government can do nothing but take care of the rich, despite a
projected $4 trillion budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans represent the upper half of the American
spectrum of wealth, argued the most eloquent Democrat. Their take
on the country's central ethic derives from the Founding Fathers'
emphasis on ``freedom, liberty, opportunity.'' But today's
Democrats add a fourth concept: Community. Interdependence. The
strong reaching down to lift the weak.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Community' was not written into the Constitution,''
acknowledged Cuomo. ``We didn't believe it for 150 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Not until the depth of the Depression in 1932 did Franklin
Roosevelt enunciate the principle of interdependence that became
Social Security. Workers got unemployment and workmen's comp. As
American society evolved, blacks and women got to vote, to get a
leg up on rights and prerogatives previously denied, and what came
to be derided as Big Government leveled the playing fields on which
all Americans disported.
</P>
<P>
   The Reagan-inspired drumbeat against ``Big Government'' is a
hollow farce, he claimed. What do they mean, he demanded: Social
Security? No. Medicare? Medicaid? No and no. The defense budget?
Definitely no! So just what do Republicans mean when they attack
Big Government? ``Welfare _ one-and-a-half percent of the
government budget!'' That got a big laugh. Even former Republican
Senator Alan Simpson, the cowbody from Cody, Wyo., who brought his
barbed-wire wit to Harvard where he gets to introduce people like
Cuomo, was grinning from ear to ear.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo had put a lot into his Harvard speech. He cited Adam
Smith, Wall Street's ideological icon of choice, on the ultimate
value of funding public schools. He quoted Hebrew admonitions to
``repair the universe . . . make it better . . . sweeter, fairer,
surer.'' Cuomo's own Catholicism emerged in his peroration. ``The
truth is God made the world _ but didn't finish it.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not sappy religiosity to urge humankind ``to love one
another,'' concluded Cuomo. ``Because that's the only way it can
work.'' Things go better when there is an active sense of
community, of mutual responsibility, of less tribalism and more
tropism for cooperation, he pleaded. ``There's 47 million kids in
poublic schools,'' he said, ``and 5 million in private schools.''
He harpooned the conservatives' favorite remedy for failing public
education. ``You think you can do it with vouchers?'' Summing up,
Cuomo hit the heights: ``We're all in this together, for better or
for worse. So let's make it for better.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans don't have time for high-sounding speeches like
his, he conceded; they're too busy putting bread on the table. As a
young lawyer with five kids (and now nine grandchildren, all of
them girls), he was the same way. But thanks to his public school
education, his hardworking immigrant parents, his native skills,
and his hard work, he made it.
</P>
<P>
   For the able and fortunate like him and for the Harvard kids who
clogged his standing-room-only Arco Forum audience, he said making
it may be necessary, but it is not sufficient:
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to die now, and my old neighborhood is worse. And
I say, `I did great, I did OK.' '' In an era characterized by
public discourse on ``what the definition of `is' is,'' Cuomo aimed
far higher, at corralling the concept of ``I'' as opposed to
I-and-the-rest-of-humanity.
</P>
<P>
   `` `I' is not enough for me. If `I' am all I am of my life, it's
not enough,'' he reasoned. ``We're in this to make the whole place
better, after you take care of your own. That has meaning . . .
Make a contribution. Do everything you can.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd, I think it safe to say, loved it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
