<DOCNO> NYT19990224.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7419 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DARTMOUTH-CHANGE-BOS &LR;      02-24 1618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DARTMOUTH-CHANGE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DARTMOUTH LEADER TAKES ON CHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HANOVER, N.H. _ President James Wright spent the evening two
Mondays ago the way he has several in his 30 years as professor and
provost at Dartmouth College, at a casual dinner in a fraternity.
</P>
<P>
   The residents of Alpha Delta were so impressed that one e-mailed
the campus newspaper suggesting it do a story on what a great guy
the new president is. An improvement, he thought, on James
Freedman, the outsider president who spoke of cultivating a campus
for ``creative loners'' aspiring to write poetry or master the
cello. Here was a Dartmouth guy, who understood the keg-jumping
culture of this postcard-perfect campus, this ``fun Ivy'' for
students who play as hard as they work.
</P>
<P>
   But the paper had a bigger story to write. The next day, Wright
announced the new residential plan that will open fraternities to
women, ending, as the headline blared, ``the Greek system as we
know it.'' By Wednesday, students came not to praise the new
president, but to vilify him, in signs outside Greek houses, as
``Julius Brutus Arnold Wright.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet if the quintessential Dartmouth man had changed, he was only
reflecting how much Dartmouth, too, has changed.
</P>
<P>
   Once known as a boys club, it now boasts the highest percentage
of tenured women professors in the Ivy League. It was the first of
the Ivies, four years ago, to have the same number of women
students as men. While its admissions office once had a virtual
pipeline from redoubts of prepdom like Deerfield Academy, it now
draws its highest number of freshmen from New York's scrappy
Stuyvesant High. And The Dartmouth Review, which once drove campus
debate weekly and put the school on the national news for
conservatism and bigotry, now publishes only sporadically. It's
hard to find a copy on campus.
</P>
<P>
   While the fraternities once defined Dartmouth, officials now say
they had come to defy everything that Dartmouth has worked the
better part of the last decade to become. To the outside world,
they serve as a reminder that a Dartmouth alumnus coauthored the
movie ``Animal House,'' and make it difficult to attract minority
students. Inside the school, they remind many that the school has
not yet changed its social structure to embrace its newer, more
intellectual students.
</P>
<P>
   Wright may be a villain to some, but he has also become a hero
to many students and to the faculty, who have waited for this as
the final step in shaping a new Dartmouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``My own deep conviction is that this is a place that is far
richer than the stereotypes,'' Wright said in a low rumbling
monotone that seemed to play down the protests outside his house
and the hate mail he has received in the two weeks since he
announced his plan. ``The image is of a school up in the woods
where a bunch of guys partied hard, and there may have been some
truth to that. But this has not been `Animal House' since I have
been here. That part of our history tends to get lost . . . and
that frustrates the historian in me.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright insists this is not a public relations strategy.
Admissions Dean Karl Furstenberg, though, is less shy about the
need for a makeover.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our image has deterred students from applying,'' he said. ``I
really want the college to have a balanced image, to have people
appreciate it for all its range, to know that we've got
conservatives, we've got liberals, we have radical feminists.
Somehow our image is stuck on one dimension of our personality.
Images persist longer than you think they would. They're also out
of date.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For several notable firsts, Dartmouth deserves a better
reputation than it's had. Founded to educate American Indians, it
was the first college to admit an African-American student, in
1824. As early as the 1950s, its fraternities fought their national
chapters against policies that excluded Jews.
</P>
<P>
   But even loyalists admit that the party school stereotype fit.
Critics snickered that the old school song about ``Men of Dartmouth
. . . with the granite of New Hampshire in their muscles and their
brains,'' was true in a way the authors did not intend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of kids who saw this as a finishing school (20
years ago). They came here, they learned a little Horace, they
joined a fraternity, they joined a team, they made contacts among
their fraternity brothers, then went home and joined dad's
business,'' said Ed Berger, dean of the faculty and a 20-year
professor. ``We didn't send a lot of kids on to PhD programs.''
</P>
<P>
   To alumni who cherish that past, it died in 1972, when Dartmouth
admitted women.
</P>
<P>
   But the real changes began with Freedman, who arrived from the
University of Iowa in 1987 and began an aggressive campaign to
downgrade the ``Animal House'' image and upgrade its intellectual
distinction. He restored Japanese and Hebrew to the curriculum, and
established a presidential scholarship program that enlisted
top-flight students in research projects. He shaped a cluster of
residences around faculty advisers, in an attempt to foster a
climate of intellectualism even outside the classroom. Dartmouth
has always been a school for top students, but he demanded even
higher standards.
</P>
<P>
   Berger knew things were changing when a fraternity hosted a
lecture series. ``That was a major breakthrough,'' he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   The faculty welcomed the changes. It had voted to do away with
fraternities in 1978, saying they were anti-intellectual, and was
rebuffed by the trustees.
</P>
<P>
   But Freedman's changes were largely overshadowed by other
crises. He became the epitome of the political correctness
ridiculed in the Dartmouth Review. In one widely publicized
incident, Review staff destroyed a shantytown on the Dartmouth
Green that had been set up by black students protesting the
school's investment in apartheid South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Amid all this, applications dropped, especially among black
students, and black faculty left in large numbers, with fewer than
10 on campus in the early '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Alumni protested changes, too, in the school song (to ``Dear Old
Dartmouth'' from ``Men of Dartmouth'') and the mascot (from an
Indian head to a Big Green blob). In this atmosphere, most say,
Freedman never could have challenged the fraternities. Challenging
the party culture proved hard. The school banned keg deliveries in
1991, only to allow them in limited use a year later. Freedman
pushed fraternity rush from spring of freshman year to spring of
sophomore year, only to allow it again in fall of sophomore year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, though, the admissions office has worked
hard, and largely succeeded, over the past 10 years in what
Furstenberg calls ``a major recrafting of the message.'' Rather
than a nice small school in New Hampshire, it sold itself for its
research faculty. It sent recruiters to more schools, so that the
ratio of private school students has dropped by about 10 percent,
and got more students to visit the campus, where they might be
persuaded that it wasn't that movie.
</P>
<P>
   Still, change the Greek system? Wright, to most, seemed the last
person to do this, an unlikely intellectual, and an unlikely
liberal. A 58-year-old former football player and Marine, he worked
in the coal mines in his native Illinois after high school. Hearing
the tales of the mines, he fell in love with history, and entered
college at 21. He came to Dartmouth, and stayed. In manner and
visage, he is more the soothing country doctor than the college
president, more affable than inspiring in his speech, more
self-effacing than stuffy.
</P>
<P>
   He says he was frustrated by letters he received after a
``ghetto party'' hosted by a fraternity and a sorority last year,
to which some students came dressed as welfare mothers. He had
heard the same complaint from other students.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said it was not an inclusive culture, that they wished
that they had more opportunity to meet students of different
backgrounds,' he said. ``When I put the question to them, what is
it that does not encourage that, the answer is always the
fraternities, the sororities.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright says there is no social engineering in his plans, and no
magic in his timing. But a change of heart among alumni probably
influenced it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't hear tumult, revolt, and revolution the way I did with
coeducation'' said David Cook, a 1957 grad, a member of Theta Delta
Chi, and head of the alumni council. ``What I've been amazed at is
the number of e-mails saying this is wrapping up something that
should've been wrapped up 27 years ago with coeducation.''
</P>
<P>
   What has also surprised many is the support among students, many
of whom have written opinion pieces or letters to the editor
supporting the new plan in The Dartmouth, the student newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``The alcohol abuse is part of fraternity life, and the
fraternities are part of Dartmouth,'' said Leyla Kamalick, who
wrote one of the opinion pieces. Wright ``wants to eliminate
alcohol abuse entirely, and he's starting by eliminating it from
the school name, and I think that's a good idea.''
</P>
<P>
   So it might just be possible that Jim Wright's fan club is
growing.
</P>
<P>
   As Wright stood before a faculty meeting called last week, Tom
Luxon, an English professor, rose and told him, ``Thank you for
your courage. Thank you for your bravery.'' As the applause
started, became louder and sustained, Luxon continued: ``Your
bravery led me to trust you. Your leadership is what's making this
possible. It makes me feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright blushed, picked up his paper cup of water, and lifted it
to his mouth. Behind it, he smiled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
