u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     02-24 0820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ODD MAN OUT AT NUMERIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After all of the publicity he attracted for his mutual funds
over the years, John Bogle Jr.'s departure was announced in just
one terse paragraph.
</P>
<P>
   Bogle was out at Numeric Investors, the money management shop
known for its quantitative, or computer-driven, investment style.
Good work, thanks for the memories, a company statement said two
weeks ago. He was off to pursue other things. Then Numeric shut
down tighter than a drum, and Bogle was nowhere to be found.
</P>
<P>
   Now he has resurfaced. In an interview Tuesday, Bogle said he
became the odd man out at Numeric when founder and longtime
colleague Langdon Wheeler had a change of heart about plans to
retire within two or three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lang came to me with the suggestion that now was the time for
me to do something on my own,'' said Bogle, who was a managing
director at Numeric. ``I didn't disagree with him.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Wheeler's decision made Numeric, a firm that invests
about $5 billion for institutional accounts and mutual fund
shareholders, too top heavy with managers. And Bogle wasn't going
to run it anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``His staying with the firm made my staying with management
somewhat superfluous,'' said Bogle, 39. ``It created a surplus of
management at the top.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides Wheeler and Bogle, Numeric also counted chief investment
officer Mark Engerman as part of its senior management. Engerman
wasn't going anywhere and his skills were needed at the firm.
</P>
<P>
   We asked Bogle whether another person might look at the same
events and say they were precipitated by a different change of
heart, a decision to jump Engerman ahead in the Numeric succession
line.
</P>
<P>
   ``That had never come up,'' Bogle answered. ``It may happen, but
it's never come up in conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   Bogle, the son of John Bogle, founder of the Vanguard mutual
fund company, attracted a lot of publicity for Numeric's group of
funds, which manage a total of about $330 million. He was good copy
for slick investment magazines and newspaper columnists, including
us.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Bogle and Numeric's n/i family of funds stressed
shareholder-friendly issues that would resonate at Vanguard: a cap
on fees and a preference to quickly close funds that could become
less effective if they became too large.
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler, who will be 53 in May, was not available for comment
Tuesday. Bogle said Wheeler's original plan to leave the business
by age 55 started to change last summer, when they first started to
talk about ``management succession issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Bogle still speaks well of Wheeler and said there were no
hard feelings between the two of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly value my friendship and working experience with
him,'' said Bogle.
</P>
<P>
   But Bogle and Wheeler are both known for strong egos, and even
Numeric officials acknowledged ``differences'' between them at the
time of the split.
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler and Bogle first met at State Street Bank &AMP; Trust more
than a decade ago. Wheeler had been hired to develop a quantitative
model to replace one the company was buying from now-defunct Drexel
Burnham Lambert.
</P>
<P>
   Bogle walked in the door at State Street's asset management
department the day of the stock market crash in October 1987,
moving over from the corporate banking department.
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler launched Numeric a few years later, with the help of
Hilda Ochoa, a silent partner and former chief investment officer
of the pension division of the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Numeric built its own computer models that would select stocks
to buy and sell in investment portfolios. The models would jump in
and out of stock positions often, triggered by changes in analysts'
profit forecasts and other factors.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Numeric has a series of ``quants'' working its Cambridge,
Mass. offices. The typical background: heavy math and science
credentials mixed with a business degree.
</P>
<P>
   Numeric has its critics. Some people complain that the
portfolios move in and out of stocks too frequently, increasing
expenses. Others say Numeric closes its funds based on asset growth
too quickly, doing more harm than good. The company's original
institutional account was closed recently to work on problems after
a spate of weak performance.
</P>
<P>
   Numeric officials and Bogle insist none of those issues had
anything to do with this month's management change.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our philosophic approaches are not at odds,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bogle said he was spending time with his family at the moment
and didn't know what he would do next. He said he preferred running
a smaller operation but did not rule out becoming involved in a
larger organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty sure you're going to be hearing from me soon,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
