<HEADER>
A7431 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-24 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASH BALANCE IMBALANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; If you're a Generation Xer, it could be a pretty good deal: A
``cash balance'' account or pension plan dressed up to look like a
401(k), though it rarely requires employee contributions and calls
for no investment decisions.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a baby boomer or approaching retirement age, look out.
The cash balance account will do little to boost your pension, and
could slash its value by a whopping 20, 30, even 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, cash balance accounts have become one of the
hottest new benefits in the US workplace as more big companies,
eager to attract top young talent, have shifted traditional pension
plans to cash accounts that may be taken either as annuities or
lump sum payments when employees leave.
</P>
<P>
   Six percent of all US firms were using such accounts in 1994.
Today, more than 12 percent of the nation's top employers either
have switched to cash balance accounts from traditional retirement
plans, which delay payouts until 65, or are giving employees a
choice between the two, reports Hewitt Associates, a benefits
consulting firm in Lincolnshire, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big employers are definitely shifting,'' said Hewitt actuary
Michael Johnston. ``It has been the very large companies, the
AT&AMP;Ts, that have gone in this direction first, but others are
starting to follow.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the cash balance account allows companies to woo
highly mobile employees who are in demand by promising a cash
savings pension at the time of departure rather than regular
pension deductions employees can't take or touch until they are
ready to retire.
</P>
<P>
   ``The traditional pension plan takes a lot of money and
basically gives most of it to the career employee who eventually
retires, but it gives little to those who come and go early in
their careers,'' said Johnston. ``Technically, it is backloaded. It
throws the money to those in the back end of their careers. Cash
balance is egalitarian. It says, `You're here for five years, when
you go we will still reward you. You'll get more than you would
have if you left right after vesting.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Said James Delaplane, vice president of retirement policy at the
Association of Private Pension and Welfare Plans in Washington:
``The traditional pension has been the norm for many companies
primarily because they had large unionized work forces, but as
companies have evolved that's not necessarily the typical work
force anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Have workers really changed as much as this new trend suggests?
Delaplane couldn't say for sure, but the answer may be yes. After a
decade of layoffs and buyouts, a booming economy and low
unemployment are prompting US companies to hire again, and many are
not union.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the US Bureau of Labor Statistics reports the
proportion of union employees in the nation's work force dropped to
13.9 percent in 1998, from 14.1 percent. And while labor added some
new workers to its ranks, the increases in union membership failed
to keep pace with the extraordinary job growth the country enjoyed
in 1998, when 2.2 million new jobs were added to the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say employers who make the shift from a traditional
pension plan to a cash balance account are looking to offer optimal
benefits to an increasingly mobile work force for whom longevity
with one company is no longer sought after or even desired.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a Catch 22: The cash balance account may be a boon
to the under-40 set, but it won't boost the retirement plans of
older employees in their 40s, 50s, and 60s. Even among younger
workers, there may be conditions. Some companies, for example, will
permit an employee to take only a portion of his cash balance
retirement savings. Typically, that money is then rolled into an
IRA account when the worker leaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cash balance accounts are not our most desired alternatives to
traditional plans because they work to the disadvantage of older
workers,'' said Glenn Koocher, manager of programs and advocacy at
the American Association for Retired Persons' northeast regional
office in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Consider: Traditional pensions usually are based on a formula
similar to this _ number of years service times the highest average
salary in a worker's final years times a factor that may begin at
0.1 at age 40 and rise to, say, 2.5 or more by age 65.
</P>
<P>
   That means the longer you are with the company, the more you are
likely to accrue in pension benefits. In other words, the longer
you remain on the job, the higher the average salary upon which
your pension is calculated.
</P>
<P>
   ``At AARP,'' said Koocher, ``I get 1.6 percent of my high
average salary over five years times the number of years I've been
employed here.''
</P>
<P>
   Under a cash balance account, the company puts a fixed amount of
money into the account based on a percentage of annual salary, with
interest. If AARP switched from its traditional plan to a cash
balance retirement plan, Koocher's retirement annuity would be
based only on the money his employer has placed in the pot, rather
than other factors such as Koocher's age, 49, and his eight years
of service.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies have provisions that take length of service into
account. They may improve the employer's match to workers' 401(k)
plans, for example, or give older workers points for service.
``There are also instances where companies have set a certain age
or tenure level and everyone older will stay in the old plan, and
people in a particular age group or at a certain tenure level are
converted to the new plan,'' said Delaplane.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Koocher wouldn't want to switch. ``The (cash balance)
account works to the advantage of the 25-to-30 year-old who is
looking to pick up the money and go,'' he said. ``I don't think
it's discriminatory toward older workers, but it is definitely less
advantageous.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane E. Lewis's e-mail address is work(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
