<SLUG> BC-BAILEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TREASURER, OLD STORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Missing millions at the Massachusetts treasurer's office? Lax
management controls? Questions at the state lottery?
</P>
<P>
   As the state's new treasurer, Shannon O'Brien, put it: ``The
bottom line is this: We've inherited a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm shocked! Shocked!
</P>
<P>
   This story had to happen. In fact, two weeks before this
``widening scandal'' broke, I went to see O'Brien and her first
deputy, Michael Travaglini. My pitch to them: You're going to be
digging through predecessor Joe Malone's dirty underwear, and sure
as night follows day you'll find something, this being the state
treasurer's office.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the calls went to the political reporters, whose
stories land on Page One, but those calls were going to come
eventually. It was an alert BankBoston teller who got the ball
rolling early.
</P>
<P>
   Already we have the requisite bad guys, but if it had not been
some middle-level treasury supervisor nicknamed Trixie, it would
have been someone else. Because more than anything we have a lot of
new fixers standing around in need of something to fix.
</P>
<P>
   There's O'Brien and there's the state's new attorney general,
Tom Reilly, and if there's nothing to fix why do we need them?
Auditor Joe DeNucci, whose job description is fixer, has piled on.
And all of these Democrats have found just the thing to fix: the
treasurer's office, previously run by Malone, a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Malone, of all people, should be able to appreciate what's
happening. A man of sharp elbows and a heaping helping of piety, he
spent eight years building a career on the backs of his Beacon Hill
enemies, and enjoyed every minute of it.
</P>
<P>
   He spent virtually his entire tenure as treasurer running
against the man he replaced, Bob Crane, a Democrat. Even before he
took office in 1991, Malone was jawboning Crane to cancel a round
of last-minute raises to lottery employees. Malone rescinded
contracts to money managers Crane signed up for the pension fund in
his final days. And in the first year Malone wrote down $200
million in bad real estate investments that had been made for the
pension fund on Crane's watch.
</P>
<P>
   The center of the current investigations is John Trischitta, a
treasury worker who is accused of helping a so-called
``heir-finder'' pocket $6.5 million in return for a $50,000
kickback and a share of the profits. Malone and his former aides
say there is no way to build a fail-safe system against a crooked
employee. Just look, they say, at the problems BankBoston had in
its private bank. The bank still hasn't found that guy.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. But lax controls in state government? What a novel
concept.
</P>
<P>
   In a real sense, this is how the system should work. A place
like the treasurer's office is a backwater where big dollars are at
stake and influence can be exercised, but is rarely seen. It is a
place that should turn over often, not just from candidate to
candidate but from Democrat to Republican.
</P>
<P>
   At some point in the future _ in four years or eight years _
Shannon O'Brien, a woman, like Malone, of sharp elbows and strong
ambition, will make a run for governor or the US Senate, based on
the work she did cleaning up the mess at the treasurer's office.
And if we're lucky, we'll get a Republican in Room 227 who will
start digging through her underwear.
</P>
<P>
   And we will again be shocked. Shocked!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cocktail Weenies
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Robert Maloney, who ran the New England operations for Smith
Barney before he was convicted of illegally steering campaign
donations to his congressman-brother, is back in the brokerage
business.
</P>
<P>
   Maloney has taken a minority stake in Winslow, Evans &AMP; Crocker,
a tiny Boston retail brokerage house where he is a principal and
broker. The firm, whose majority owner is founder Peter Winslow,
has but 27 brokers; Maloney had 850 brokers working for him at
Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1998 Maloney was sentenced to 60 days of home
confinement and fined $256,000 for contributions he solicited from
Smith Barney employees for his brother, James H. Maloney, a
Connecticut Democrat. Maloney says the plans are to quietly grow
the business. ``After 25 years, I'm back at the beginning,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steve Bailey's e-mail address is bailey(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
