<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7455 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-MARTINEZ-B     02-24 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-MARTINEZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH RAZOR-SHARP DELIVERY, MARTINEZ GREETS HIS MATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ There was no mistaking the new arrival. And
it wasn't just the bright orange shirt Pedro Martinez was wearing,
as he worked the Red Sox clubhouse, shaking hands on both sides of
the aisle like a ward heeler at a pot-luck supper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rheeeeallll,'' he said, greeting his former teammate from
Montreal, Rheal Cormier, and giving him a hug. ``Que pasa?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mi amigo, Jin Ho Cho,'' he said, grasping the hand of the
bemused Korean pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, lovely boy,'' he said to newcomer Kip Gross, a teammate
from Martinez's early Dodger days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, fat boy,'' he yelled upon spying Jim Corsi in the
trainer's room. ``Yoda.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's face darkened momentarily when Corsi came over and
made a crack about showing up late, but brightened again when Corsi
extracted the needle without drawing blood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, what's up with the funny hats?'' Martinez said, picking
up the new red mesh caps the Sox are wearing this spring.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox clubhouse may be lacking the high drama of previous
springs, back in the days when Wade Boggs was falling out of his
pickup truck, Roger Clemens was jogging with his headphones, or Mo
Vaughn was turning up the heat on Dan Duquette and John Harrington.
</P>
<P>
   But as long as Martinez is around, there will be no shortage of
high spirits, the kind that can make his tardy arrival appear a
mere trifle, which essentially it is. Surely, Martinez's delayed
touchdown here, two days after the first official workout, wasn't
because he dreaded coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was home spending some good time with my family,'' said
Martinez, who had been given clearance by Sox management to come in
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked for permission to be home a few days later because it
was my dad's birthday,'' he said. ``We wanted to be there for his
birthday. We're never there. We always come over by the 15th or so,
so we took those two days to spend with him.''
</P>
<P>
   The only damage Martinez inflicted by showing up Tuesday, it
appeared, was to Joe Kerrigan's meticulous schedules, which chart
the daily activities of every pitcher in camp but will require some
alterations. Martinez underwent his physical, then did some running
and stretching with the other pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``So what do we have to do now?'' he said to Bret Saberhagen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably whatever you want to do,'' Saberhagen said.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, who had been working out back home in the Dominican
Republic, said he is able to go on the mound now, and perhaps will
as soon as this morning.
</P>
<P>
   He waded through the obligatory gauntlet of questions about Mo
Vaughn (``We've got to look to the future. Forget about Mo. Mo's
gone. It's true. It's a fact, we have to forget about Mo and focus
on the work we have to do here and get our things done.'')
</P>
<P>
   He also parried several questions about Jose Offerman, a fellow
Dominican and friend with whom he played in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offerman adds speed, defense, and a great bat,'' he said.
``Offerman can hit for average and RBIs. He's good in the clutch, I
can guarantee you that.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unfair, he said, to suggest that the Red Sox believe
Offerman can replace Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there should be any pressure for Offerman,'' he
said. ``He should just concentrate on his work. I don't think
anyone could have had more pressure than I did last year, and I
handled it right.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys should be professional. When he signed the contract,
Mo was still here. He didn't come to replace Mo, he came here to
play baseball for the Boston Red Sox. You guys have to understand
that and give him the respect he earned and treat him like a normal
player.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not Mo Vaughn. He can't replace Mo Vaughn, just like I
wasn't Roger when I came over.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez downplayed the impact of the Yankees' trade for
Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of teams have improved this year,'' he said. ``Hopefully
we'll be one of the big surprises like last year. You never know.
You have to go to the field and find that on the field, not off the
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because Roger's there doesn't mean anything. He's a great
pitcher, somebody very important to that team, but things can turn
around. You never know. We have to forget about other teams, and
focus on what we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez is in the house. Crank up the merengue, dust off
the Dominican flags, and smile until someone gives you a reason to
stop. Martinez hasn't found that reason yet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
