<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIER RUNS DOWN PATRIOTS' OPTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Bobby Grier is considering doing something
that Dan Duquette does routinely _ make a trade.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the norm in the NFL, ever since the Herschel Walker
heist involving the Minnesota Vikings and Dallas Cowboys, but
Grier, the Patriots' vice president of player personnel, says teams
have approached him about deals for a running back knowing that
Robert Edwards may have suffered a career-ending injury. Edwards
was released from Massachusetts General Hospital Tuesday and headed
home to Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are three ways we can address it,'' said Grier,
who had a lot of chatter with personnel men at the recent scouting
combine in Indianapolis. ``We could do it through the draft, or
look to free agency, or do something that seldom happens in this
league _ make a trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some proposals and we're listening. Some of the
people bandied about are lead backs and some aren't.''
</P>
<P>
   The New Orleans Saints reportedly offered Lamar Smith.
</P>
<P>
   If the Patriots decide to take the free agency route, they will
consider Darick Holmes, the former Bill and Packer who comes to
Foxborough for a visit Friday, and Travis Jervey, also a Packer,
who comes in Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   As for the draft, the Patriots aren't likely to package their
two first-rounders to get in position to take one of the top two or
three running backs coming out of college.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't make a deal like San Diego did with Arizona last
year,'' said Grier.
</P>
<P>
   Grier said he's a big fan of Boston College All-American Mike
Cloud and acknowledged that Jerry Azumah of the University of New
Hampshire had an impressive combine. He thinks Cloud will go in the
middle of the draft and Azumah a little later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Azumah is very athletic and can catch the football,'' said
Grier. ``He has a chance of playing as a situational back, and he
returns (kicks). I've always liked Mike Cloud. I told him that he
had his break-out at the end of his junior year when he torched
West Virginia for about 200 yards. I've watched him about seven
games. He's quicker than fast. He has great vision and catches the
ball well out of the backfield.''
</P>
<P>
   Grier isn't ruling out a player he already has, Sedrick Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a possibility,'' said Grier. ``Sedrick is a taleted
kid. He hasn't been able to take that talent from the practice
field to the playing field. This is going to be a very important
year for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Grier said Shaw is immature.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has to grow up and accept the fact that everything is not a
bed of roses,'' said Grier. ``That some of the things that have
happened to him here are his fault. That he can't lay the blame
elsewhere all of the time. This is his third year. If he can't help
us win, then he won't be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Grier said the running back crop in the draft will be similar to
last year, when there were three top guys (Curtis Enis, Fred
Taylor, and Edwards) and then a falloff. The Patriots, who pick
21st and 28th in the first round, might benefit from the strong
quarterback crop this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might get a better player than we expected because some
teams will feel that this is the year to draft a quarterback if you
need one,'' said Grier.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots may even dabble in the quarterback pool themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to draft a young quarterback and maybe sign a
veteran quarterback,'' said Grier, who didn't seem to be endorsing
a Scott Zolak return. ``I think if we did anything, we'd like to be
able to get a quarterback who can complement Drew (Bledsoe) and
throw on the run. We don't want to duplicate what we have. On draft
day a lot of weird things happen. We'll wait and see. There are
some quarterbacks we like, but there are other positions we like
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Grier said the departed Tom Tupa was actually the team's No. 2
quarterback last year and would have played when Bledsoe was hurt
if back problems hadn't arisen.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything would have happened during the year earlier, Tom
would have played,'' said Grier. ``As the year went on and reps
became more precious, that's where Zolak came into play. Tom was
punting and he did have some back injuries and there was a point
where we could't use him as a QB.''
</P>
<P>
   Grier all but anointed Heath Irwin the starting center,
replacing Dave Wohlabaugh, who signed a lucrative deal with the
Cleveland Browns.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always hate to lose a player of Dave's caliber,'' he said.
``I've always been very high on him. But I've also been high on
Heath as a football player and an athlete.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also like Jason Andersen. Heath wouldn't be one of the
bigger, stronger centers but I think he's more in the line of a
Dermontti Dawson, who is a smaller guy but very athletic and can do
a lot of things like get out on the backers, pull, etc. I'm not
saying he's Dermontti Dawson, but he has that kind of athletic
ability.''
</P>
<P>
   Grier also seemed inclined to grab an offensive lineman in the
first round. He said they were the most impressive athletes at the
combine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids are getting bigger and bigger and faster,'' he said.
``At one point, Aaron Gibson (of Wisconsin) got on the scale _ 6-6,
386. The kid (Derrick) Fletcher from Baylor got on and he was 6-6,
376. There was a kid who followed both of them who got on and
weighed 336 and he looked like a dwarf after following those two
kids. There are some huge offensive linemen who are good athletes
and are well-coached.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots may be close to signing free agent defensive tackle
Bob Kuberski of the Packers, who at 6-4, 300 pounds could back up
in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Grier also said the team is doing a detailed study of all the
injuries last season to see if there's an area they can pinpoint
for prevention. He doesn't blame the offseason conditioning
program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't use that as a primary factor in injuries we've had,''
said Grier. ``We've had guys who have been in this program from Day
1 who got hurt. Some of the hardest workers in the program got
hurt. Jacksonville had 16 guys on IR and they have a great
offseason program.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
