<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 14:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7463 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-VAUGHN-BOS &LR;      02-24 1053
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VAUGHN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAUGHN IN ANGEL DEBUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ Blame it on Mo's momma.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to know the real reason that Mo Vaughn is wearing an
Anaheim uniform these days, instead of Boston's, remember that
there is a reward in heaven for those who ignore their fathers and
do what their mothers insist is the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, making his official spring training debut with his new
teammates Tuesday, dropped this tidbit as he retraced the saga that
saw him end up with an $80 million contract that took him away from
Boston. When Vaughn became a free agent after the 1998 season, his
parents, Leroy and Shirley, disagreed on their son's choice of
clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Leroy wanted to see Mo retire in a Red Sox uniform. Shirley told
him not to be afraid to pursue his destiny, even if it meant
leaving the only ``home'' he'd ever known. Shirley won.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents were with me on every decision I ever made,'' said
Vaughn. ``How I did was just as important for them as it was for
me. My dad wanted me to retire in a Red Sox uniform because that
had been so much a part of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom can handle the intensity of things and the
expectations. My father wanted her to bite her tongue. She
couldn't. As a mother to a son, she just said it was time.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn said signing with the Angels was a business decision, but
one influenced by the fact that they treated him with more respect
in one offer than the Red Sox had shown him in a year and a half of
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn wanted to make a good impression on his first day as an
Angel, and most agreed that he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've finally got somebody who is not afraid to fail,'' said
pitcher Ken Hill, a Lynn, Mass., native. ``That's the bottom line.
In this game, you're going to be a hero or goat, but guys like him
want to take it on their shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Massachusetts native, shortstop Gary DiSarcina
(Billerica), broke his left arm in a freak batting practice
accident Monday. His goal is get well by Opening Day so he can play
in the same lineup with Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lived in Boston,'' said DiSarcina, ``and I have an
understanding of what he's all about and what he brings to the
table. It's not just performance sometimes. It's off the field, the
plane rides, dinner with the guys. The whole package. It's good to
have him on our side.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We know about his intensity,'' said Rod Carew, the Hall of
Famer who will be Vaughn's batting instructor. ``He's going to be a
leader and that is what we need. There is no looking back or
looking around and making excuses. They all know the challenge that
is ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We determined that Mo was the No. 1 free agent out there,''
said Angels general manager Bill Bavasi. ``You're not going to get
him cheap. First and foremost was his playing ability, his numbers.
But the makeup was a big issue for us.''
</P>
<P>
   It helped the Angels' cause that the Red Sox held off their best
offer until late in the negotiations. By then, Vaughn had made up
his mind that the Angels deserved first shot because they didn't
hesitate to roll the dice and put the dollars on the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't want to give anybody else a chance to get
there,'' said Bavasi.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn joins a potent lineup. The Angels outfield of Garret
Anderson, Tim Salmon, and Jim Edmonds, when healthy, is one of the
best in baseball. Darin Erstad, who played first base last year and
now will be the fourth outfielder, hit .296 in 133 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helps to bring in a guy who can hit 40 home runs,'' said
Salmon. ``It just makes our lineup that much stronger. You've got
to be excited with him hitting in front of or behind you. It will
make some things happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not looking for a savior. We've shown that in most
situations we have enough to win. He brings credibility to our
lineup. We match up better.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn is no stranger to several Angels. One of the candidates
for the shortstop job is Luis Rivera, a former teammate in Boston.
Coaches Rick Wise, Dick Pole, Carney Lansford, and John McNamara
all have Red Sox ties and are aware of Vaughn's history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he will make a difference with this club,'' said
Rivera. ``I'm still surprised he got out of there. Especially with
the community ties he made.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, incidentally, says he will maintain those ties and
continue to support the foundation he set up in Boston. There are
no plans to open a California branch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not here to make this club,'' he said. ``I'm here to help
this club. They already got talent and leaders. I've got to come
here and do my job _ to help this club to be as good as it can
be.''
</P>
<P>
   But he knows he also is here to offer advice and provide
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 31,'' he said. ``That's old, isn't it? I just recall when
I was a kid and I wished I had some guys who would come up to me.
It's all a mental game, anyway. You're already talented enough. You
have to get yourself ready mentally so that you can be consistent
every turn at bat.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of things happened in Boston the last couple of years that
contributed to Vaughn's departure. And he knows not everybody will
remember him kindly. Hopefully, it won't matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It put me on the map to have played there,'' said Vaughn. ``I
don't look at the situation in a negative light at all. It gave me
an opportunity to be here and do what I'm doing. No matter what you
say about me, when it came down to playing the game, I played the
way it was supposed to be played. I have no regrets.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, though, his tune changed a little.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything that happened fell on the shoulders of two guys,''
said Vaughn. ``The general manager and the owner. In life, you all
know that if you want something, you go get it, even if the money
isn't there. You take care of it. The Angels came with respect and
showed that they wanted me over here. I wasn't going to go on a
barnstorming campaign and see who made the best deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people talk out both sides of their mouth, it is really
hard. I look at the situation now and I wish them all good luck. I
just want to go out there and do what I'm capable of. It's not a
grudge. I'm a happy person. I just want to go out and do the things
I'm capable of doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
