<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7472 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-DUQUETTE-B     02-24 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-DUQUETTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUQUETTE TAKES POSITIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ Dan Duquette, still fighting off the remnants
of a weeklong bout with the flu but sounding as relaxed as the
black suit-and-sneakers ensemble he wore to the Red Sox training
complex Tuesday, gave a vigorous defense of the Jose Offerman
signing while making it clear that the club is prepared to deal for
more offensive punch this spring.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox general manager, making his first appearance in camp
after delaying his flight from Boston on doctor's orders,
acknowledged the strength of the Yankees while questioning
Toronto's willingness to put Roger Clemens in pinstripes. But he
also stressed that he expects a Red Sox team that won a wild-card
spot last season to be a contender again this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``With a stable pitching staff and good defense, that's the
foundation of our team,'' Duquette said. ``If it's artfully managed
like we know Jimy Williams and (pitching coach) Joe Kerrigan can
effectively do, that should be enough to put us in the pennant
race. Beyond that, if we need some more hitting, we'll get some
more hitting.''
</P>
<P>
   Addressing the Clemens trade to the Yankees and its impact on
the pennant race, Duquette said:
</P>
<P>
   ``See, what's been lost in this equation so far is that David
Wells was 18-4 last season, so whoever replaces Wells in the Yankee
rotation has to pitch at a high level, obviously, for them to
maintain the status quo. Obviously, the Yankees have a good team,
they had a great record last year, and they're returning with their
basic team intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our challenge hasn't really changed. The Yankees were strong
before the trade, and they're strong after the trade. That hasn't
changed our challenge. We've got to put together a team that can
get into a position to beat the Yankees in a short series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I thought we matched up with the Yankees pretty
effectively. Unfortunately, we didn't get to that short series to
play them. The pennant is still up for grabs, playoff spots are
still up for grabs, and we aim to do everything we can to challenge
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox won five of 12 meetings against the Yankees last
season, with all three of the top Sox starters _ Pedro Martinez,
Bret Saberhagen, and Tim Wakefield _ beating New York at least
once.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette said, ``It doesn't bother me,'' when asked about the
broad criticism he has received for giving a four-year, $26 million
contract to Offerman, expected Wednesday for the team's first
full-squad workout.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interesting thing about Offerman is our fans are going to
like watching him play,'' Duquette said. ``There are not too many
players who can do what he can do in the American League, and excel
in as many categories as he excelled.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette noted that Offerman's deal is about the same as the
four-year, $25 million deal the Sox gave third baseman John
Valentin last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, that's like the going rate for qualified established
major league infielders,'' Duquette said. ``Offerman is not only a
qualified established major league infielder, he's one of the best
producing players in the American League last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can talk all you want about what the Red Sox paid Jose
Offerman. There was interest in him from the Orioles. There was
interest in him from the Indians. What was the extent of the
interest from those clubs? I don't know exactly. I know Cleveland
paid significantly more for their second baseman than what we paid
for Offerman.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians signed free agent Robbie Alomar, a nine-time
All-Star celebrated as much for his fielding skills as his offense,
if not more. Offerman, whose defense has been a liability, has been
an All-Star once in his career, as a shortstop for the Dodgers in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will be a good sign for the Red Sox,'' Duquette
said. ``This kid is just coming into his own. He can hit when it
counts, he's a switch hitter, he's a premier on-base man and he's a
premier base-stealer. Over time, it will be a good and valuable
contract for the Red Sox.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette said he expects the Sox to compensate in part for the
power they lost when Mo Vaughn left by increased power in right
field, from rookie Trot Nixon, and a full season out of Mike
Stanley, who didn't join the club last season till the end of July.
He also pointed to a healthy Reggie Jefferson, who played just 62
games last season because of a stress fracture in his back, as a
key component.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wild card is what kind of offensive production are we
going to get from our DH,'' he said. ``It's well known that to win
in the American League, you need production from your DH.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's see how those questions are answered, in the event we
need more power for our lineup.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette said he hasn't had any discussions ``recently'' with
the White Sox about Frank Thomas, whose name has come up repeatedly
this winter in trade speculation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep reading that Frank Thomas is available in a trade, but
that hasn't really been confirmed to us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette seemed unconcerned about the abundance of second
basemen/DH types. First, he said, Jefferson and Jeff Frye, both of
whom finished last season on the disabled list, must show they're
healthy and capable of playing at optimum levels. Williams, he
said, has a knack for using his players, which could mean that
Offerman plays second at times, shares first base with Stanley on
other occasions, and platoons with Jefferson at DH.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some depth at second base that may create some
opportunities for us, if everyone is healthy, for a trade,''
Duquette said, ``where we can trade some of our depth at second to
address other needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will take care of itself as the season progresses.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette has said the Red Sox were interested in dealing for
Clemens. Without naming him, he took a swipe at Blue Jays GM Gord
Ash for his willingness to deal Clemens to the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a curious position Toronto established,'' he said.
``They established that early on in their trade discussions with
other ball clubs. Their position was they would trade him to the
Yankees because the Yankees were world champions and not really one
of their direct competitors, but they wouldn't engage their direct
competitors, us being one of them, in substantive trade
discussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, that's a curious position, because if you're going to
accomplish your ultimate goals you need to do it in your division
first. But that was their position all along. Very rarely do you
see the Red Sox make a trade with the Yankees, for obvious reasons.
They're our direct competitors. Very rarely do we make a trade with
the Orioles and Blue Jays.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-99 1408EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990224.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7474 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLASSICAL-MUSIC-SALES     02-24 1175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLASSICAL-MUSIC-SALES-2NDTAKE-$ADV28-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: release schedule.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having enjoyed recent successes with boxed sets devoted to
Sviatoslav Richter and William Kapell, the label is planning a
99-CD Rubinstein box (to be priced at about $1,500) for September,
and a big Heifetz box and a more expansive Richter set for next
year.
</P>
<P>
   The ratio of new releases to reissues is less extreme elsewhere.
Still, most labels know the value of their archives: Sony
Classical's beautifully packaged Masterworks Heritage series has
set a high standard for the presentation of historical recordings;
EMI has sold Maria Callas every which way and is reviving its Great
Recordings of the Century line; Deutsche Grammophon's Originals
series was a nostalgic hit as well.
</P>
<P>
   But the masters of ``secondary exploitation,'' as it is called
in the business, are on staff at Philips. Having cobbled together a
complete Mozart edition in 1991, using recordings from all the
Polygram labels, Philips is now issuing a 200-disk series, Great
Pianists of the 20th Century, which surveys the work of 73
pianists, with recordings licensed from all the major labels and
plenty of material not previously available on CD.
</P>
<P>
   The hunger for old recordings is so pronounced that orchestras
have started mining their radio archives to produce and market sets
of their own, with impressive results. On the heels of a pair of
high-profile mail-order sets from the Cleveland Orchestra, the New
York Philharmonic issued its ``Historic Broadcasts,'' a 10-disk
survey of varied repertory, in 1997, and a 12-CD Mahler cycle this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, ``Historic Broadcasts,'' priced at $185, sold 5,000
copies in its first year; at $225, the Mahler box sold 2,500 copies
in six months.
</P>
<P>
   Where does all of this leave living, developing artists?
Instrumentalists seem to be finding support, and period-instrument
bands are flourishing. As for conductors, the ones willing to
shelve their Beethovenian dreams in favor of unusual projects are
having an easier time.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have thought, a decade ago, that EMI executives would
speak with unbridled enthusiasm about a young English composer who
writes in an alternately accessible and thorny style? Yet the
company lists Thomas Ades' opera, ``Powder Her Face,'' among its
best sellers.
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Grammophon, which had an enviable new-music series in
the early 1970s but has since maintained a fairly staid image, has
just introduced 20/21, a series named for the changing century,
with disks devoted to Pierre Boulez, Toru Takemitsu, Mauricio
Kagel, Elliott Carter and Arvo Part.
</P>
<P>
   Singers have it made, sort of. The Alagnas, Matthias Goerne, Ian
Bostridge, Cecilia Bartoli, Jennifer Larmore, Ben Heppner, Thomas
Quasthoff, Renee Fleming, Bryn Terfel and Anne Sofie von Otter, new
to the record bins in the last decade, are now bankable stars,
churning out recital disks.
</P>
<P>
   Yet operas, like symphonies, are expensive and therefore less
plentiful. There, too, unusual works _ and works with links to
other media _ have an edge: Deutsche Grammophon released Andre
Previn's ``Streetcar Named Desire'' within months of its premiere,
thanks to the PBS broadcast, which yielded the live recording.
</P>
<P>
   The major labels have long been overdue to explore new
repertory, and if they lag behind independents in that regard,
their marketing and distribution power will help them take over the
areas the independents have pioneered. But the independents are
unequivocally devoted to classical music, something that cannot be
said of most multinational majors now.
</P>
<P>
   Conductors and soloists know they can get a green light for
projects involving popular young composers like Ades, Aaron Jay
Kernis, Richard Danielpour, Tan Dun or John Tavener. But they also
see a contrary trend, which is that if they really want to see
executives' eyes light up, they should propose recordings built
around film scores, nonfilm works by film composers, or hybrids
that draw on folk, pop, tango and world music, perhaps bringing
together stars from each world.
</P>
<P>
   Such projects ``treat the recording as an art form rather than
just a preservation medium,'' in record company parlance. Fair
enough: Glenn Gould approached his recordings that way, as does the
Kronos Quartet. ``We're extending the definition of classical
music'' is another commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   Who, at this late date, is against that? Yet the projects
themselves often have the aura of something dreamed up in a
boardroom, with sales projections discussed intently, and questions
of their appropriateness for a classical music label not at all.
</P>
<P>
   It may be unfashionable to say so, but definitions and
boundaries are useful in music. To argue that distinct styles
should inhabit their own realms is not to imply the superiority of
one over another, to preclude honest cross-fertilization or to
suggest that listeners should not experiment. But record labels
have implied charters, and if they regularly abrogate them, neither
the music nor its listeners are well served.
</P>
<P>
   Crossovers, like them or not, have become part of the charter.
But Sony Classical has started down a path that goes well beyond
crossover, and if other labels follow suit, classical labels as we
know them will be fundamentally altered.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bolton giving bad performances of opera arias is
crossover; but Marcus Roberts playing Joplin rags with wide-ranging
improvisatory freedom is jazz. Offering it on a classical label
misleads listeners who don't know Joplin and bypasses jazz fans who
would appreciate its subtleties.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, ``Appalachia Waltz'' is a folk music album, Yo-Yo
Ma's presence notwithstanding, just as Joe Jackson's ``Heaven and
Hell'' is progressive rock, and Eileen Ivers' ``Crossing the
Bridge'' is Celtic folk-rock. Nothing about these disks strikes the
ear as classical, yet because they are on a classical label, that
is how Soundscan registers their sales. The 2.3 percent of the
market accorded to classics, then, may be inflated by ringers.
</P>
<P>
   Sony may be responding to corporate pressure to make every
project profitable, pressures that executives at other labels say
they feel as well. If they all respond as Sony has, the effect may
be devastating in years to come. Classical labels, after all, have
always depended on the depth of their catalogs, and the current
passion for reissues suggests that they always will.
</P>
<P>
   The only way to insure the strength of the back catalog is to
approach new projects not just with a sense of their immediate
sales potential but also with an eye to their future usefulness,
either as perennials or as material that can be recompiled to suit
different needs.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to imagine that collectors a few decades from now
will hanker after ``Appalachia Waltz'' the way buyers today seek
out, say, Rubinstein's Chopin. The question is: will future
collectors look back at the turn of the 21st century as a time of
adventurous repertory expansion or a time when record labels
abandoned art music to chase the quick buck?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
