<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7476 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASIA-OPPORTUNITY-ART-     02-24 1773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASIA-OPPORTUNITY-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRMS FIND THAT ASIAN CRISIS HAS A FLIP SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   James Edgerly's e-mail was hastily composed in Bangkok and
zinged to Boston. But his business partner in the home office had
no trouble interpreting its message: Asia was teeming with
potential clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Following two large, important projects in South Korea. Great
opportunities in Thailand. Talk to you when I get back,'' wrote
Edgerly, head of international operations for The Recovery Group,
during a recent two-week trip to Asia to explore opportunities for
consulting to troubled enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   Asia would seem to be the last place on earth to scout for new
business. Economies across the region have cratered, and companies
are failing. Commerce in many places is barely moving.
</P>
<P>
   So why would American companies, including many in
Massachusetts, flock to the troubled region? Economic forces
ravaging Asia have created a vast land of business opportunity.
Although there is no stampede, some enterprising companies are
waking up to the unique opportunities for bargain-hunting in Asia's
worst economic slump since World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the work is in helping Asian companies work out of
financial trouble by reducing debt or restructuring operations. But
companies of all stripes _ financial firms, computer companies,
athletic shoe makers, importers _ are seeking new business or
beefing up operations all over the troubled region.
</P>
<P>
   A plunge in the value of most Asian currencies against the
steely US dollar means that office space, top-notch employees, even
entire companies can picked up at depressed prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you take the contrarian perspective . . . this is the
perfect time to go'' into Asia, said Anne Bailey Berman, president
of Chadwick Martin Bailey, a Boston market research firm with
international clients. Asia's slump offers a chance to ``buy low,
sell high,'' she noted. ``These are big markets. They're having
their financial woes, but it's not as if these markets are going
to'' disappear, she added.
</P>
<P>
   It's not surprising to find Recovery Group courting potential
clients in Asia _ its specialty is reorganizing companies and banks
in distress. ``Asia is where it's at right now,'' said Stephen
Gray, the managing director and recipient of Edgerly's e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Other businesses, acting now, also hope to get in early on a
recovery in some of the world's biggest markets.
</P>
<P>
   Most economies in the region slowed dramatically or contracted
in 1998, and many financial systems, including Japan's, are still
crumbling. Experts say full recovery could take years.
</P>
<P>
   Yet ``everybody who talks about Asia knows it's going to come
back,'' said Charles McChesney, executive director of The Alliance
for the Commonwealth, which tracks export trends for New England.
``Asians have shown they can grow their economies consistently.''
</P>
<P>
   First to rush in were Wall Street's financial giants beefing up
their presence in preparation for an eventual recovery. Auto makers
followed, including Ford Motor Co., which boosted its stake last
year in Japan's Mazda Motor Corp. With New Balance Athletic Shoes
Inc.'s shoes surging in popularity, the company is increasing
production in China.
</P>
<P>
   With Asia ``at its low ebb, this is the perfect time'' to build
Cambridge Technology Partners' business there, said James Sims,
chief executive of the computer consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, his company had virtually no overseas
operations. It opened a Tokyo office 1 1/2 years ago, just as a
currency crises cascaded through Asia. Cambridge Technology's
services _ sorting out computer hardware systems or designing
Internet systems for corporations _ are most critical for
struggling companies seeking to become more efficient or
competitive, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asian companies ``are spending huge amounts of money'' on
information technology, Sims said. ``When people go through tough
times they don't randomly cut everything. They say, `Where should I
be investing?' . . . If you're a global company you better make
those investments because you know your competitors in the US and
in Europe are making those decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   New York financial companies are snapping up Asian businesses, a
trend that is expected to continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The financial houses are doing business, because they're
involved in doing deals or they're buying up other financial firms
at a good price,'' said Lawrence Horwitz, managing director for
Boston-based Primark Decision Economics, a consulting firm that
opened an office in Tokyo this year.
</P>
<P>
   GE Capital Corp.'s agreement last month to acquire Japan Leasing
Corp. from the country's most troubled bank, Long Term Credit Bank,
is the latest in an Asian shopping spree by the Connecticut
company. Travelers Group, after announcing a merger with Citibank
to form Citigroup, acquired a stake last June in Nikko Securities
Co., one of Japan's biggest brokerage houses. Baltimore-based T.
Rowe Price Associates Inc. in January established a beachhead in
Japan to sell mutual funds there.
</P>
<P>
   Opportunity appears to exist for investment banks and workout
specialists who can help companies get back on their feet.
</P>
<P>
   At New York-based Salomon Smith Barney, Robert Morse, chief
executive of Asia-Pacific operations, said its Asia commitment was
increased at a time troubled companies there need his company's
services to sell unprofitable operations, raise cash, or reduce
debt through the sales of securities.
</P>
<P>
   Salomon, a unit of Citigroup, has bulked up by adding 400
employees to its Asia-Pacific operations through its acquisition of
CountyNatwest, Australia's biggest brokerage firm, and by hiring
another 100 employees in Singapore, Malaysia, Hong Kong and
elsewhere. Salomon's total Asia-Pacific work force is now 1,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Asian markets still are small relative to European and US
markets. There's a lot of opportunity,'' Morse said.
</P>
<P>
   The US accounting firm, PricewaterhouseCoopers, in a
high-profile piece of business, is presiding over liquidation of
the once high-flying Hong Kong investment bank, Peregrine
Investments.
</P>
<P>
   Marti Kopacz, a partner and head of the firm's workout practice
in New England, said some 20 partners are doing recovery work in
Asia _ up from seven in 1997. And there's need for a dozen more,
she said. ``The work is so voluminous you can't cover it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Asia may be a mother lode for workout firms _ but the business
is not easily won. Cultural issues present barriers to doing
business.
</P>
<P>
   Economic crises pose issues that are similar to those faced by
US savings and loans in the 1980s. But many Asian cultures are wary
of US-style restructurings in a part of the world where liquidation
is the traditional remedy for failure. South Korea, Thailand and
Malaysia seem to be the first to embrace Western expertise,
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Boston-based Recovery Group entered Asia gingerly, first dipping
its toe into Thailand while participating in a World Bank-sponsored
program to educate business people there about methods of
restructuring. Recovery Group hopes to win contracts with Thai
banks or companies needing help to work out nonperforming loans,
which could total nearly half of the country's total outstanding
loans.
</P>
<P>
   Recovery Group's Gray believes that Asia's potential may be
greater than that of Eastern Europe, where his firm helped
state-owned operations convert to private concerns. But, partner
Edgerly said, ``You can't march a bunch of foreigners in who don't
know anything about the country and expect everyone to sign up. It
doesn't work like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston bankruptcy attorney George Kelakos hopes family ties will
help if his Boston law firm sets up shop in Bangkok. His
Thai-American wife, Anchalee Kelakos, was born in Bangkok and knows
the language.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I'll be able to overcome those trust issues,'' he said.
When talking to Thai officials, he is careful to make clear he
would ``assist them as team players.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelakos is among a group of bankruptcy judges and attorneys who
have traveled to Bangkok to help the Thai government set up a
US-style bankruptcy system, which was created by legislation last
year. He and his wife escorted Thai officials who met World Bank
and US government officials in Washington. As a result of these
contacts, Kelakos is consulting to Thai law firms. .
</P>
<P>
   Plunging Asian currencies and stock markets have hammered US
investors. Nearly two years after the financial disaster began,
savvy Wall Street investors now view Asia as a rare opportunity to
bargain hunt.
</P>
<P>
   Acadian Asset Management, an affiliate of Boston-based United
Asset Management, recently teamed with a Singapore merchant bank,
Pegasus Capital Ltd. The goal: to invest equity ``in good companies
in Southeast Asia that have bad balance sheets,'' said Churchill G.
Franklin, Acadian's executive vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Edward Bozaan, president of Waterford Partners, which invests in
stock markets in emerging countries after they have declined,
raised $12 million from clients over the past year. He was able
hire an analyst in Singapore, who had worked at Jardine Fleming
Securities, to help manage the portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are so many bargains in Asia, Bozaan said _ his
New York firm could easily invest $100 million there _ investors
are hard-won. ``So many people lost so much money,'' investors are
``very, very cautious,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Asia bargain-hunting effect works in novel ways, too,
spawning Paul Counihan Jr.'s import-export business.
</P>
<P>
   Raised in Concord, Counihan has spent a decade moving from Guam
to Thailand to Indonesia as a manager of nightclubs and
restaurants. When riots broke out in the streets of Jakarta last
year, he moved from the Indonesian city to the island of Bali to
open a restaurant. That's where he spotted Balinese hand-crafted
teak furniture.
</P>
<P>
   Because Indonesia's rupiah had plunged against the dollar, the
furniture could be exported cheaply to the United States. Counihan
figured it would be ideal for outdoor use in New England, because
``it weathers into a beautiful silvery gray.''
</P>
<P>
   His siblings and parents are partners in his venture. The family
now waits for a ship carrying two 40-foot containers of furniture,
which they plan to sell at a store they are opening in Cambridge,
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a strong dollar, Counihan said he thinks he can
``really undercut the market here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-99 1409EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
