<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990224.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7478 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      02-24 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROOTING FOR SALSIFY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISON ARNETT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ You're a sophisticated diner. You negotiate French or
Italian menus with aplomb. Well-versed in hens-of-the-woods,
pomegranate molasses, and star anise, you're confident you can
shine before your dinner companions, instructing them in the
exotica of today's restaurant pantries. There's nothing you can't
expound on, you think, as you flip open the menu.
</P>
<P>
   Except, you realize in a moment of sheer panic, salsify.
</P>
<P>
   ``Petite lion's head bowl of steaming salsify soup served with
crisped oysters, hot horseradish, and osetra caviar,'' reads Biba's
menu.
</P>
<P>
   The first question comes quickly. ``This looks interesting.
What's salsify, dear? You know so much about gourmet cuisine,'' the
spouse says, smiling fondly.
</P>
<P>
   You blush and turn helplessly to the server for the answer.
</P>
<P>
   Menus at Boston's high-flying restaurants can do that to you
these days. Some ingredients are so unusual the diner needs a
dictionary. Salsify, cavolo nero, crone de Japonaise, patofa,
sunchokes, wild dried mulberries, parsley root _ what will they
think of next?
</P>
<P>
   As we all know, there's really nothing new under the sun.
Salsify, or the black-skinned scorzonera, which is more widely used
in restaurants than the white salsify, or oyster plant, is a root
vegetable hailing from 16th-century kitchen gardens in Europe.
Colonial America was wild about salsify, and Thomas Jefferson was
known to grow several varieties of it. As Elizabeth Schneider,
whose ``Uncommon Fruits and Vegetables'' (William Morrow) is the
bible in such matters, says, such vegetables ``grow out of fashion
rather than into it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nice, dowdy root vegetable,'' Schneider adds, voicing
regret that an ingredient long-used by European cooks should be so
little known here.
</P>
<P>
   But chefs are always looking for something new, something
different to capture the short attention spans of the dining
public. Jim Wilker of Specialty Foods Boston, which supplies 75
restaurants with unusual products, says he often gets calls from
chefs searching for out-of-the-ordinary ingredients. In his
warehouse, he shows off big, meaty king oyster mushrooms from the
West Coast; bleeding heart radishes that look a little like turnips
until he cuts one open to reveal a ravishing crimson and white
interior; bumpy sunchokes or Jerusalem artichokes; and inky-green
wrinkled leaves of the cabbage cavolo nero. The black salsify,
grown in Belgium, looks like a slender black carrot with a whiskery
top. Because it's uniform in size and thickness, it's preferred
over the unruly-looking white salsify, which was probably more
commonly grown in earlier America.
</P>
<P>
   Although some people think it tastes of oyster, to me it has an
artichoke-like flavor with a hint of something stronger, such as
turnip. Schneider also likens it to a soft-cooked artichoke heart
with a hint of coconut.
</P>
<P>
   Felino Samson, chef de cuisine at Galleria Italiana, grills
salsify and serves it with a frittata crespelle, a sort of crepe
made with eggs and radicchio, topped with shaved black winter
truffles. ``Salsify is a great vegetable,'' Samson says. ``I like
it because of its sweetness and earthiness, and it works well with
truffles.''
</P>
<P>
   Samson adds he likes to give unusual vegetables a star turn in
antipasti. ``A lot of foodies are really intrigued.''
</P>
<P>
   At L'Espalier, chef-owner Frank McClelland offers roasted wild
striped bass with a red rice crust accompanied by a salsify,
fingerling potato, and leek salad. The dish is accented with sea
urchin roe. McClelland believes the neutral flavor of salsify takes
on characteristics of strong elements in the dish, moving ``one
flavor into another gracefully.'' So the salsify enhances the sea
urchin roe and leek qualities while adding its soft texture to the
mix. The fish, topped with tiny greens and haricots verts, rests in
a lobster and truffle broth.
</P>
<P>
   Unusual ingredients ``spark interest,'' McClelland says. ``Let's
face it, the public is eager to learn and to try new things. It's
not the foundation of my cuisine,'' he says, but he admits that he
likes to offer diners tastes and textures they haven't often
encountered.
</P>
<P>
   Other unusual items get supporting roles on the plate. Jim
Becker of Rauxa in Somerville uses patofa, or taro root, in a puree
with his grilled pork chop with pomegranate sauce. McClelland uses
cavolo nero with a beet risotto. The Blue Room in Cambridge serves
it sauteed with cipollina onions, garlic, and olive oil alongside a
grilled skirt steak, polenta, and gorgonzola cheese. George Lopes,
sous-chef, says the ``big, meaty leaves like to be paired up with
meat.'' At Casablanca in Harvard Square, chef Ana Sortun treats
cavolo nero as a main ingredient along with semolina berries and
porcini mushrooms in ribollita, the thick vegetable soup that's
reboiled.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how unfamiliar restaurant ingredients seem to the
general public, it's amazing how quickly chefs' whims can make
their way into the eating vernacular. How many of us knew about
mesclun 10 or even five years ago? So, as author Schneider laments
our ignorance about a common European vegetable, Rene Shepard of
Rene's Garden Seeds of California sees a ``real connection''
between what diners eat in restaurants and then ask for in grocery
stores and, if they're gardeners, eventually want to grow for
themselves. ``If chefs are cooking with it, people eat it and then
want to know more.'' Eventually that spark may reach our kitchen
gardens.
</P>
<P>
   And we may be planting salsify again, just like Thomas
Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alison Arnett is the food columnist for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
