early this morning over a proposed treaty to regulate international
trade in genetically modified products. The European Union
countries and more than 110 other nations reached a consensus late
Tuesday on a Biosafety Protocol. But the United States, together
with Australia, Canada, Uruguay, Argentina and Chile, refused to
accept the proposal, insisting on a more narrowly focused treaty
that would have had a minimal impact on trade in the goods. By
Andrew Pollack.
