<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-VALUES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUSHING THE ENVELOPE TO THE BRINK 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DOUGLAS MACKINNON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans, Democrats, the news media, and most
Americans can only sit back and scratch their heads in wonder. Bill
Clinton becomes only the second president in U.S. history to be
impeached by the House and tried in the Senate, and his poll
numbers go higher.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last year, pundits and politicians have labored to
explain the discrepancy between President Clinton's high approval
ratings and what House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., has
called his ``reprehensible'' behavior.
</P>
<P>
   My answer as to why the American people keep giving the
president a much higher grade than he deserves is this: They have
been systematically and successfully conditioned by many in
Hollywood and the entertainment community to lower their moral
standards and reevaluate what is acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   If we were to take an honest look at television and movies over
the past two decades, we could clearly see that they have pushed
the ``what is acceptable'' envelope farther and farther each year.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, 90 percent of the American people may have
found a particular show or scene offensive, but five years later,
after seeing the same behavior _ violence, sex, nudity or lack of
respect for authority _ thousands of times, maybe only half that
number would find it offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next five years, the same envelope of ``what is
acceptable'' was pushed even farther and even more Americans
started to question their judgment and values. People may say to
themselves, ``Gee, that show really seems out of bounds to me, but
I guess I must be becoming a prude or something. Everybody seems to
be showing that stuff now.''
</P>
<P>
   Has this been a deliberate attempt by Hollywood and the
entertainment community to subvert morality and decency? Of course
not. But it should be noted that the majority of those in control
of the creative process in Hollywood would describe themselves as
very liberal, both in their politics and in their behavior. It's
natural that their personal beliefs and biases would infiltrate the
programs they write and produce.
</P>
<P>
   While one would hope that those in the entertainment community
would recognize the tremendous responsibility they have to the
nation, I'm afraid that is not going to happen anytime soon. Many
of the Hollywood power-brokers who donated the maximum $10,000 to
Clinton's legal defense fund have gone on record as saying that
even with (or because of) the impeachment, they support him and
think the Monica Lewinsky episode is just a plot created by
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr to derail their ideological
mission.
</P>
<P>
   The envelope has now burst.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Douglas MacKinnon is a former writer for Presidents Ronald
Reagan and George Bush, a former Pentagon official, and a
novelist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
