<DOCNO> NYT19990224.0160 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 14:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7533 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAXES-$ADV28-HNS &LR;      02-24 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAXES-$ADV28-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TAX CREDITS AND MORE COMPLEXITY AWAIT TAX PROCRASTINATORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Feb. 28)   (EDS: Filed in ``w'' and ``f'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For many Americans, those dreaded tax forms are
probably still sitting around waiting to be tackled. But thanks to
several tax changes that took effect in the 1998 tax year, you may
want to file sooner than April 15 because you might get a refund.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Internal Revenue Service, refunds through Feb.
19 were averaging $1,784, or 15 percent above last year's levels.
The jump is mostly because of new child and education tax credits.
</P>
<P>
   Tax preparers say the new credits are making tax returns of low-
and moderate-income taxpayers more complicated. Each credit has
different qualifying incomes. Determining what the IRS calls
modified adjusted gross income for each credit requires different
calculations.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's really where a lot of this complexity comes into
place,'' said Martin Nissenbaum, director of personal income tax
planning at the accounting firm of Ernst &AMP; Young. He said the
income tax forms of low- and moderate-income people are becoming as
complicated as those of high-income taxpayers who typically itemize
more deductions.
</P>
<P>
   He and other tax preparers recommend starting your taxes earlier
than usual and they recommend using a computer software package
like TurboTax or getting help from a professional preparer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't realize you need (help) until you start filling out
your forms,'' Nissenbaum said.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Yeager, manager of tax research at H &AMP; R Block, a
nationwide tax preparation firm, said clients are often confused
about many of the education tax credits.
</P>
<P>
   The new child and education tax credits can be taken whether or
not you itemize your deductions. They include:
</P>
<P>
   _Children: a $400 per child tax credit. The credit is reduced
for single people with incomes above $75,000 and married people
filing jointly with incomes above $110,000. The credit rises to
$500 per child beginning in the 1999 tax year.
</P>
<P>
   _HOPE Credit: allows students or parents of students to deduct
up to $1,500 per student for tuition and fees incurred in a
post-secondary or vocational education program. This tax credit
applies only for the first two years of post-secondary education.
</P>
<P>
   _Lifetime Learning Credit: provides a credit for students or
parents of students of up to $1,000 per year for undergraduate,
graduate and professional courses. The credit equals 20 percent of
tuition or fees with a cap of $1,000 per year per family. (To
receive the full credit, tuition and fees would have to total at
least $5,000.)
</P>
<P>
   The credit applies to tuition and fees incurred after June 30,
1998. The HOPE and the Lifetime Learning Credit cannot be used in
the same year for the same student. Both credits are phased out for
single people with incomes between $40,000-$50,000 and married
people filing jointly between $80,000-$100,000.
</P>
<P>
   _Interest on student loans: up to $1,000 of interest on some
student loans can be deducted. Loans have to be within the first
five years of repayment to qualify. For example, a person who began
repaying a student loan in 1992 or before would be ineligible for
the deduction. President Clinton has proposed eliminating the
five-year limit. The amount of interest that can be deducted will
rise to $2,500 in 2001. The deduction is phased out for single
taxpayers with incomes between $40,000-$55,000 and married people
filing jointly with incomes of $60,000-$75,000.
</P>
<P>
   _Individual Retirement Arrangements: More people may qualify to
take an IRA deduction this year up to a $2,000. A person's IRA
deduction is no longer limited by whether his or her spouse is
covered by an employer's retirement plan such as a 401(k). This
will allow a non-working spouse or a spouse who works part time to
place as much as $2,000 a year in an IRA and deduct it.
</P>
<P>
   _Roth IRAs: People can put aside up to $2,000 a year in
after-tax money for such an account. The money is not taxed upon
withdrawal in most circumstances. Individuals with incomes more
than $110,000 and married people filing jointly with incomes
greater than $160,000 are barred from opening Roth IRAs. Both types
of IRAs can be opened up until April 15 and qualify as being opened
in the 1998 tax year.
</P>
<P>
   Money can be withdrawn from both the traditional IRA and the
Roth IRA to pay for higher education and first-time homebuyers can
withdraw up to $10,000 to put toward a home purchase without being
subjected to the 10 percent early withdrawal penalty. The amount of
the withdrawal from the traditional IRA, however, is added to your
income in the year it's withdrawn and taxed accordingly. Roth
withdrawals are not taxed because such accounts are such up with
after-tax money, unlike a traditional IRA.
</P>
<P>
   If you owe money to the IRS, you can charge it on Mastercard,
Discover or American Express _ for a fee totaling between 1.5 and
2.5 percent of the amount owed. The IRS is prohibited from
absorbing that fee which is typically charged to merchants.
</P>
<P>
   Visa isn't participating because of a policy that prohibits
surcharging consumers.
</P>
<P>
   If you can't pay your tax bill, Nissenbaum recommends filing for
an extension with the IRS rather than charging it. The IRS charges
about 7 percent in interest for filing past April 15 while many
credit cards charge as much as 19 percent interest.
</P>
<P>
   If you write a check, make it out to the United States Treasury
rather than the IRS. The change was mandated as part of 1998
legislation aimed at overhauling the IRS. But if you happen to
write ``IRS or Internal Revenue Service'' on your check, it won't
be sent back to you. The IRS, which is a unit of the Treasury
Department, will still cash it almost immediately.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-99 1448EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
