A7557 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-COBURN-PROFILE-H     02-24 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-COBURN-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COBURN `FEELS GOOD' ABOUT WORK ON `AFFLICTION' AND `PAYBACK' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nobody in the movies grins bigger than James Coburn, and this
month those wall-to-wall teeth have reason to shine.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn is enjoying his best movie month in years.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Payback,'' the Mel Gibson shoot 'em down, Coburn plays the
kind of charming, lovable rascal that made him a big star in the
1960s. Only this time, he's doing it as a gangster.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Affliction,'' Paul Schrader's hard-hitting film version of
the novel by Russell Banks, Coburn gives an absolutely frightening
performance as an abusive, vile father to Nick Nolte's character.
</P>
<P>
   It would be enough just to have those two hugely different
characters on screen at the same time. The icing on the cake was
getting his first Academy Award nomination, as best supporting
actor in ``Affliction.''
</P>
<P>
   Coburn, fresh out of the shower after a workout in his Beverly
Hills home, admitted it was a surprise _ after more than 40 years
of film acting and dozens of films _ to finally get Academy
recognition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels really good,'' Coburn said. ``It's an honor and
everything, but it's definitely a surprise. When we started, it was
just, let's do a film and hope it works.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were saying all along, well, this is worthy of an Oscar
nomination. I said, yeah, yeah, yeah, that and a dollar and half
will get you a cup of coffee.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has seen Coburn's starring films _ ``Our Man Flint,''
``Waterhole No. 3,'' ``The President's Analyst,'' ``Duffy,'' ``Duck
You Sucker'' _ remembers the big, booming personality, the wide
grin and the infectious laugh that defined many of his roles.
Coburn kept his lean, tall body in tight control, so when the grin
came, smart and joyously wicked, it was startling.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn is 70 now. He's bulkier, and one hand is twisted a bit
from the rheumatoid arthritis that severely restricted his career
for many years. But he's healthy and active _ the arthritis no
longer a problem _ and the booming signature laugh is still very
much evident. Coburn laughs a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Told that he was very scary to watch in ``Affliction,'' he gave
one of those laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good,'' he said. ``That was my job.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Affliction'' is about a small-town underachiever, Wade
Whitehouse (Nolte), who slowly loses the nominal control he has
over his better nature. He becomes more and more like his aging
father, who was a tyrant in his own home when his children were
young.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (the father) is the full-blown affliction,'' Coburn said,
now much more serious.
</P>
<P>
   Nolte is a big man and a strong presence on screen. Director
Schrader needed an actor who could be believably intimidating to
Nolte.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted somebody of another generation of actors who was
powerful enough to play with Nick,'' Coburn said. But Coburn said
Schrader (director of ``American Gigolo'' and ``Touch,'' but
better-known for writing such screenplays as ``Taxi Driver'' and
``Raging Bull'') gave him little instruction, beyond not being his
usual likable screen personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me, `Well, you know, Jim, this guy is not a charming
man.''' Coburn laughs. ``I said yeah, I understand. He said, `Well,
you know, I'm just going to let you two guys go at each other.' And
(Nick and I) just looked at each other and said, `Ooookay.'''
</P>
<P>
   Coburn's role as Pop Whitehouse was only a few minutes here and
there in the movie, yet the character's presence dominates the
film's dark corners.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn got to get back to the charm in ``Payback.'' He has even
less screen time in that film, although his role ended up being
longer than originally intended.
</P>
<P>
   ``That (movie) was really a lark,'' said Coburn, who has been
friends with Gibson since ``Maverick.'' ``Mel called me up and
said, `How would you like to do a little thing in `Payback?'''
</P>
<P>
   Coburn shot a few days and was done. But the movie was plagued
with troubles between Gibson and rookie director Brian Helgeland
(scripter of ``L.A. Confidential'' and ``Conspiracy Theory'').
Helgeland was fired, and much of the movie was reshot so Gibson's
bad guy seemed, well, not so bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``About five months passed, and I got another call. `Listen, we
took some stuff out, and so we need to put something in to make it
work.'''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Payback,'' a remake of the Lee Marvin classic ``Point
Blank,'' Gibson is a crook trying to regain stolen money that was
taken from him by a member of the crime syndicate of which Coburn
is an officer. In one comic scene, when he's under Gibson's gun,
Coburn's character seems concerned only that the bad man will shoot
his expensive luggage. It's the movie's most entertaining moment.
</P>
<P>
   Although Coburn enjoyed doing ``Payback,'' it was ``Affliction''
that was the real treat.
</P>
<P>
   ``The independent films are the ones that are worthwhile
doing,'' Coburn said. ``Others are, like, build a set and blow it
up. Who cares? It gives you a little titillation for about 20
minutes, and that's it.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you have good literature that comes from a book, like
Russell Banks', you've got something to work with. You can say
something with it.''
</P>
<P>
   In his long career, Coburn has come full circle to character
acting. He started out in small roles, often in westerns. The roles
slowly but steadily got larger. He had one of his first stand-out
bits as the knife-throwing member of ``The Magnificent Seven,'' and
another as the Manufacturer in ``The Great Escape.'' He's one of
the lead baddies menacing Cary Grant and Audrey Hepburn in
``Charade,'' and has a key role in ``The Americanization of
Emily,'' with Julie Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   But it was in 1965 that Coburn broke into stardom playing one of
the best early satires of the James Bond phenomenon in ``Our Man
Flint,'' a low-budget spoof that became a big hit _ mainly due to
Coburn's infectious vitality. The movie is terribly dated now _
although ``Austin Powers'' fans should really dig it, baby _ but
Coburn is still fun to watch.
</P>
<P>
   But then the arthritis struck _ hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't do anything. I couldn't move,'' Coburn said. But he
continued to work, sometimes only doing narration or commercials.
</P>
<P>
   He had little luck with conventional doctors, of whom he has
little good to say. But everything changed for him when tried
homeopathic remedies, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm finished with the arthritis,'' he said. ``I cured that. I
mean, with a little help from my friends. It seems to be mainly on
its wane. I don't have any more pain.''
</P>
<P>
   He also does a regular work-out that includes some Asian
movements, hiking and stretching. He started it because of the
arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's become habitual,'' he said. ``It makes me feel good. The
activity is certainly good.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Oscar nomination brings him a lot more scripts, he'll
welcome them with open arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to work; that's my reality,'' Coburn said. ``The rest
of it's all jive. The reality is the work, because that's the thing
that lives forever. That's being recorded, and it will live as long
as there is somebody to look at it. The rest of it is just a
passing through, waiting for the in-between.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-99 1455EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
