<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 14:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7558 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HIV-DISCRIMINATION-HN     02-24 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIV-DISCRIMINATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEARFUL WORKERS HIDE HIV INFECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SYLVIA WOOD  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ David had been working too many hours. His weight
was down and his T-cell count was low.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he didn't want anyone to know he has the virus that causes
AIDS. To justify his sick time, he told his supervisors he had a
chronic illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, I just told them I was HIV positive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, David (not his real name) took a risk. Despite
the U.S. Supreme Court's decision last June to include HIV under
the Americans with Disabilities Act, the law that prohibits
discrimination against people with disabilities, many workplaces
still are hostile to people with HIV, advocates say.
</P>
<P>
   Yet statistics show that HIV is becoming more common in the
workplace as people live longer and healthier on new drug
combinations. According to recent estimates by the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention in Atlanta, an estimated 650,000 to
900,000 people in the United States are infected with the human
immunodeficiency virus, and some continue to work.
</P>
<P>
   Despite legal protection against discrimination, many workers
continue to go to great lengths to hide their illness from their
employers, including not turning in health claims for fear of
people finding out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had cancer, they'd tell their employers. If they have
HIV, they're terrified,'' said Robert Bank, director of legal
services and the advocacy department at Gay Men's Health Crisis in
New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very disturbing that in 1999, most people are still
fearful to tell their employer their HIV status for fear of
retaliation,'' Bank said.
</P>
<P>
   A year-old campaign by the AIDS Council of Northeastern New York
in Albany is hoping to make employers more sensitive to the needs
of HIV infected workers, and increase their awareness about their
legal obligations to workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of companies are afraid to tackle the issue of AIDS in
the workplace,'' said Dana Moss, a human resources partner at Fleet
Bank Corp. in Albany. Last October, he had his managers attend the
AIDS Council's day-long class as a pro-active step against any
problems.
</P>
<P>
   By law, companies must provide ``reasonable accommodations'' to
infected workers. That might include allowing a worker with HIV
enough time off at lunch to take medication, often a complicated
regimen that must be strictly followed, or eliminating forced
overtime that can cause undue exhaustion in someone with a chronic
illness.
</P>
<P>
   Doing otherwise, as the AIDS Council points out, could be the
grounds for an expensive lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an issue that employers need to know about,'' said Nancy
Fisher, director of education for the AIDS Council. ``Disclosure is
a huge issue for people with HIV and for good reason. There's still
discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   David, who works in a food manufacturing plant, had to assure
his supervisors, with the help of a physician, that HIV cannot be
spread through food. He also was asked to remain under the care of
a physician and to stop working when he became too sick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that was fair,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, David asked that his workday be no longer than 10
hours and that his confidentiality be protected. Living in a small
community, he is worried about how his co-workers would react.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm under suspicion and it's not the management of the plant
that I'm worried about,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Petesch, a Washington, D.C., attorney specializing in
employment law, recommends anti-harassment training for both
company managers and their staff.
</P>
<P>
   He cited a nationwide poll that showed a majority of employees
thought their co-workers would feel uncomfortable working near an
HIV-infected colleague. Some 24 percent believed their HIV-infected
colleague should be fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``That right there is a recipe for disaster,'' said Petesch, who
serves on the board for the CDC's Business Responds to AIDS
program, a national effort to raise awareness about the disease in
the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS is an affliction in which the human immunodeficiency virus
weakens the immune system, subjecting the body to serious
infection. AIDS is most often spread through sexual contact,
sharing contaminated needles and infected blood products.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The AIDS Council has visited a half-dozen workplaces in the
Albany area. The council's program covers different ways to protect
confidentiality and dispel myths about how the disease is spread.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still need to be getting the point out that you're not
doing stuff at work that puts you at risk,'' Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   David believes that's an important message since many people
with HIV and AIDS want to work and can work, despite their illness.
``I plan on staying working for as long as I can,'' he said. ``I've
worked since I was 14. I'm not used to handouts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
