</P>
<P>
   CRAFT-DESIGN (Undated) _ There are 13 million people in the
United States making crafts to sell, and over a billion dollars
being spent in the process. This could be construed as very bad
news. But it's not. Much of the most recent craft production is
more beautiful and more technically sophisticated than it has been
for 30 years _ since the heyday of American craft artists like
George Nakashima and Gertrude and Otto Natzler, the glittering era
of modern Italian art glass or the British studio pottery tradition
of and Lucie Rie. By William L. Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   NY-HAMPTONS-BARGAINS (New York) _ No one brags about them.
They're not featured in the color brochures. Queries are met with
an all-too-obvious effort to change the subject. ``They're really
not our niche,'' said Frank Newbold, the manager of the East
Hampton, N.Y., office of Sotheby's International Realty. ``I'd like
to help you, but it's not our thing.'' But bargain houses, it turns
out, form the backbone of much of the real estate business in the
Hamptons, even in these days of mega-houses and
multi-million-dollar sales. By Tracie Rozhon.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   MAILBOX (Ridgefield, Conn.) _ Monica Brunen, and her husband,
Cal, live in a giant, federal-style house they built themselves
after months spent photograping and measuring the period details in
Connecticut's finest 18th-century mansions. Their house could grace
the pages of Traditional Home magazine. But what's that green,
bulbous thing sprouting like a mushroom at the end of the driveway?
It's a one-piece, dent-proof, leak-proof plastic mailbox big enough
to hold a dozen magazines (no rolling!) and stand up to a Range
Rover's nudge. By Fred Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   NC-DAY-MUSEUM (Milton, N.C.) _ Nearly 10 years after a brush
fire reduced the historic Union Tavern to a roofless shell, a
determined committee is slowly raising money to repair it and
convert it into a museum devoted to Thomas Day, a black
cabinetmaker who worked here before the Civil War. Born free in
Virginia in 1801, Day walked a precarious line all his life.
Despite laws limiting the rights of free blacks, he established a
successful business in North Carolina, owned stock in a local bank,
trained white apprentices (and owned black slaves, himself), and
numbered among his customers North Carolina's most prominent
citizens, including the Governor, David S. Reid. By Liz Seymour.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered. By Dora
Galitzki.
