<SLUG> BC-MARINE-INVASION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEACE ACTIVITS DECRY MARINE EXERCISE IN OAKLAND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Resending to those needing)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SELNA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Peace activists criticized Oakland Mayor Jerry
Brown for his support of a mock military invasion that the Marine
Corps plans next month to test its urban warfare preparedness.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Coalition Against Urban Warfare, a group of more
than 15 anti-war organizations, said they were shocked that Brown,
who in recent years has disparaged U.S. military spending and the
``weaponry of death,'' would endorse a practice landing by the
Marines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really surprised that Brown supported this; I used to
listen to his radio show, and he regularly spoke out against the
military,'' said Sherry Larsen-Belville, of the Livermore
Conversion Project, a peace group. ``This is sending the wrong
message to our community. It is promoting violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Larsen-Belville marched with about 70 protesters Tuesday night
near the Oakland City Hall. Many carried anti-war picket signs and
chanted, ``Urban poverty they don't care, they give us urban
warfare.''
</P>
<P>
   The Marine operation, called ``urban warrior,'' is scheduled to
take place March 15-18 and will put 700 Marines in the Oakland area
at any given time. Military officials said the exercises would test
the Marines' ability to handle a 21st-century coastal urban
conflict, natural disaster or large-scale humanitarian effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oakland has a long history with the military, and we wanted to
maintain good relations with them,'' the mayor's spokeswoman,
Stacey Wells, said of the operation. ``Oakland will also get some
training and help with disaster relief.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells said that Brown saw no conflict between his past anti-war
sentiments and his current support for the military exercises. Nor
does the mayor's endorsement erode his stance on violence, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an exercise on a base,'' Wells said. ``It has to do
with training and readiness, not the military industrial complex.''
</P>
<P>
   From 1994 to 1997, Brown hosted a radio show called ``We The
People.'' Brown's guests included a number of progressive thinkers
and peace activists, and he would often chime in against increases
in military spending and technology.
</P>
<P>
   The Marine exercise was originally slated to take place at the
Presidio, the former military base in San Francisco, but in
December Presidio caretakers decided not to authorize the
operation.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy will participate in the exercises, which will allow
troops to practice a ``three-block war,'' including an armed
conflict, peacekeeping operations, humanitarian assistance and
disaster relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the year 2025, 70 percent of the world's population will
live in coastal urban environments, and 70 percent of the nation's
capitals and 70 percent of nuclear reactors are also located in
those kinds of areas,'' said Lt. Col. Gary Schenkel, the leader of
the operation.
</P>
<P>
   The main ``invasion'' will begin on March 15, when some 400
Marines will launch in amphibious landing craft and helicopters
from two carriers and other ships anchored near Angel Island in the
San Francisco Bay. The troops will perform a landing in Alameda and
then be escorted by the Oakland police to Oak Knoll Naval Hospital,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The 200-acre Naval facility, in the residential East Oakland
hills, was shut down in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   According to Schenkel, most of the combat exercises will take
place in and around the hospital, and will include Marines firing
blanks from M-16 rifles. Peacekeeping and disaster relief
operations will ensue at base housing, and will involve about 200
actors playing war-weary civilians. The troops will sleep in
existing base barracks.
</P>
</TEXT>
