<HEADER>
A7637 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-TEX     02-24 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CHAPMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPOON UP SOME FOOD FOR THE SOUL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When you find a dish that prompts a thousand recipes, it's clear
that the dish has been around awhile and that people enjoy it. It
wouldn't have lasted otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   You can guess that it's not too expensive to make, that it
probably doesn't take much time and that the cooks like to tweak
it. They like to put their personal stamp on it, put in a secret
ingredient, pay particular attention to it and make sure the family
enjoys it.
</P>
<P>
   It is probably soul food of one kind or another.
</P>
<P>
   Here, in the final days of Black History Month, it is
appropriate to look at soul food. To pick out something that fits
in that category; something rich, custardy, comfortable; something
that's a soulful regional staple.
</P>
<P>
   Soul food is a designation for an African-American style of home
cooking. Jonell Nash writes in her cookbook ``Low-Fat Soul''
(Ballantine, $14), ``Soul food was then born in the slave quarters
of Southern plantations as our ancestors pieced together amazing
meals mainly from scraps and leftovers. After choice portions were
selected for the `master's' table, the remaining neck bones, hock,
tails and tough cuts, along with cornmeal, molasses, lard and other
staples, were then rationed to the workers.''
</P>
<P>
   The finished meals were put together with produce from the
slaves' gardens and fish and game from the nearby lakes and woods.
</P>
<P>
   It was that way for a lot of people. Poverty knew no color, and
those who didn't have much made do with what they could find. They
grew it, caught it, spiced it up and cooked it with loving,
practical care.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Nash includes Southern, creole, Cajun and island
cooking as soul food. There is even a little Mexican thrown. The
differences in these styles are often indiscernible.
</P>
<P>
   Even when things became prosperous, when grocery stores appeared
on every corner and there was money to buy food off of shelves,
soulful cooking still demanded some of the old ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing about Southern cooking was that the food was
home-grown, fresh and not hybridized,'' Edna Lewis, an undisputed
pioneer in Southern cuisine, said in an interview for an online
newsletter. ``You picked the food from the garden each day, and
nothing was store-bought. You had your own meat, or you bought it
from a neighbor. We made our own butter and didn't give our cows
pills to make them give more milk. The food had a better taste when
it wasn't injected with something, like everything is today.''
</P>
<P>
   The days of growing vegetables and milking cows are gone for
most of us. We couldn't do it if we wanted to, and most of us don't
want to. But we can still use local ingredients. We can amend our
recipes to fit our surroundings, and we can make them with the kind
of care that brings more than just physical nourishment to our
family tables.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon bread is a good place to start. It is easy and adaptable.
It is a staple in many households, in many cultures. You can put
your own personality in it.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican spoon bread has Cheddar cheese and chopped green chiles;
the creamy mixture of Tennessee spoon bread is punctuated
throughout with country sausage.
</P>
<P>
   You can use ham or bacon; whole corn or cream corn or a mixture
of both; milk, sweet cream or sour, half-and-half. Make it as
sugary as you want. Just make it hot and steaming and inviting.
Make it soul food.
</P>
<P>
   As Nash says: ``Even more than specific dishes or ingredients,
soul food represents a certain spirit, an attitude, a flamboyance,
a kind of loving that one brings to the kitchen and stirs into the
pots.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is her basic recipe:
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHERN SPOON BREAD
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   Nonstick cooking spray
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup finely chopped yellow onion or scallions
</P>
<P>
   1 cup white or yellow cornmeal
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt (optional)
</P>
<P>
   3 cups 1-percent-fat milk
</P>
<P>
   1 egg yolk
</P>
<P>
   3 egg whites
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Coat 1 1/2-quart baking dish or
souffle dish with nonstick cooking spray; set aside. Heat butter in
nonstick skillet; saute onion until tender, about 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   In small bowl, combine cornmeal, sugar, baking powder, salt (if
desired) and 1 cup milk; stir until blended. In a 3-quart saucepan
over medium heat, scald remaining 2 cups milk (heat just until tiny
bubbles form around edges of pan). Stir in cornmeal mixture; cook,
stirring occasionally, until mixture resembles thick mush, 4 to 5
minutes. Remove from heat; let cool slightly.
</P>
<P>
   In medium-size bowl, beat egg yolk slightly; stir in a little of
cornmeal mixture. Stir yolk into warm cornmeal; mix well. Using
rubber spatula to scrape skillet, stir in onion mixture.
</P>
<P>
   In small, clean, deep bowl, beat egg whites until stiff. Fold
1/3 of whites into cornmeal mixture to lighten; fold in remaining
egg whites until evenly blended. Spoon batter into prepared dish.
Bake until puffed and golden brown, about 30 to 40 minutes. Spoon
onto plates to serve.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 188 calories, 4 grams fat, 18
grams carbohydrates, 9 grams protein, 44 milligrams cholesterol,
224 milligrams sodium, 43 percent of calories from fat.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes on food for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Write to him at: Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX
76101. E-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com. Web Site:
www.startext.net/interact/chapman.htm. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
