<HEADER>
A7671 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-KIDS-HABITS-NYT &LR;      02-24 0174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-KIDS-HABITS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIPS FROM TEEN-AGE MILLIONAIRES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is no simple recipe for becoming a teen-age millionaire,
but people who have been there have a few suggestions:
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't make earning money the goal. None of these kids even
thought about making money until they started earning some from
doing what they loved.
</P>
<P>
   _ Work for no pay. For a little while, at least. Then start
charging. Aron Leifer of Brooklyn, a millionaire at 18, built his
client base by answering programming questions at no charge. Later,
clients felt comfortable giving him their business.
</P>
<P>
   _ Stay focused. These young people finish what they start.
</P>
<P>
   _ Self-promote. When Dan Finley, a college freshman and Web site
entrepreneur, was in high school, he spoke regularly to groups
about his business.
</P>
<P>
   _ Enter contests. Winning helps jump-start careers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Avoid television. Oh, except for ``Dawson's Creek'', ``Buffy
the Vampire Slayer'' and ``The X-Files.'' (These are kids, after
all).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-99 1556EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990224.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7676 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-HOME-NETWORKS-ART     02-24 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-HOME-NETWORKS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTERS THAT TALK, EVEN WHEN FAMILIES DON'T 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Mass.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By MICHEL MARRIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rich and Ellen Levin and their preschool-age children, Nate and
Steffi, have a problem unique to the digital age: they have too
many computers.
</P>
<P>
   The Levins, who live near San Francisco, have three personal
computers at home _ two desktops and a laptop that Levin, who is a
technology information manager for a Bay-area company, lugs between
his home and his office.
</P>
<P>
   Friction started when more than one of the Levins wanted to use
the household's single Internet connection. There were also times
when the family came to loggerheads over the color printer: Mom and
Dad wanted to print out letters and reports at the same time the
children wanted to churn out puzzles and games.
</P>
<P>
   Levin thought he had a solution: setting up his own local area
network, or LAN. ``I suggested to my wife that I put in a network,
a real wired one,'' he recalled, explaining that he had wanted to
link all the household's computers with conventional network cards
and wire, the way millions of computers are commonly laced together
in offices and schools.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Levin vetoed that notion, insisting that her husband
not drill holes in the walls of their home. Then Levin heard about
a wireless way to connect the family's computers by way of an
old-fashioned technology: radio waves.
</P>
<P>
   A wireless home network allows computers to act in concert,
swapping files through a single, Windows-like interface, using the
same Internet connection simultaneously and sharing popular
peripherals, like printers, Zip and tape drives, and scanners.
Multiplayer computer games like Quake II can also be blasted across
home networks.
</P>
<P>
   Levin chose a system called Homefree from Diamond Multimedia
Systems, a major maker of modems, graphics cards and the Rio player
for MP3 music. Diamond introduced Homefree Wireless late last year.
The idea, the company said, is that computer networking should no
longer be prohibitively complicated, or limited mostly to
universities and corporations, which can hire professionals to
manage the systems.
</P>
<P>
   Diamond is not the only company to recognize the growing
interest in home networking. Apple has long shipped its computers
with networking cards inside that make wire-based networks possible
in homes.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Compaq and Dell have followed Apple's lead while
broadening the PC networking options by adding adapters that link
computers through home telephone wiring.
</P>
<P>
   For years, giants like IBM have been making networking systems
for computers in homes and small offices. But these systems have
been mostly conventional, using wires and networking cards. Intel
is preparing to release in the spring its own home-network system,
which will use phone lines, and systems that run along existing
electrical wiring are being sold and designed.
</P>
<P>
   Each approach offers a range of advantages and disadvantages.
The chief advantage of wireless networks is that users are not
tethered by cables to places near phone jacks, electrical outlets
or the other computers on their network.
</P>
<P>
   A wireless connection permits a user to, say, sit outdoors on a
terrace with a laptop and browse the Internet, yards away from the
computer in the house that is physically linked to the Net.
</P>
<P>
   Another advantage is easy installation. ``Part of the problem in
the past had been that setting up a network was not easy,'' said
Rocky Scales, director of product marketing for the communications
division of Diamond Multimedia, which licensed Homefree's
technology from another California company, Alation. ``They were
difficult to set up. They required drilling holes in the walls.
They required running wires underneath the carpet and throughout
the house.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Levin household, the wireless revolution has spelled an
end to hauling the laptop to the single color printer in the
upstairs office, and also having to transfer files from the
downstairs computer to diskettes to the upstairs computer for
printing. Everyone prints what they want when they want over the
network, Levin reported happily last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we don't have to worry about who is on the Net,'' he said.
Before the network, only one person at a time could go on line,
using the home's single phone line. Now all three computers can be
on line at once. ``I'm very happy with it,'' Levin added. ``It is
wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Affordable wireless networking for homes is relatively new.
Webgear, a technology company based in San Jose, Calif., introduced
one of the first systems, Aviator, a year ago. With Aviator,
pager-size modules are connected to the printer ports of the
computers' printer ports.
</P>
<P>
   The same year, Proxim, a wireless communications company in
Mountain View, Calif., released Symphony Suite, which uses its own
wireless modem for Internet connections. Last month, Innomedia,
which is based in San Jose, announced that its home networking
product, Infoaccess, would be on retail shelves by late March.
</P>
<P>
   Each Infoaccess unit looks much like an external modem with a
small antenna protruding from its side; it plugs into any of a
computer's COM ports and promises a range of 300 feet, twice the
indoor range of Homefree's system.
</P>
<P>
   So if networks are so useful, why did they take so long to come
into homes?
</P>
<P>
   Experts examining home computer trends point to an increase in
the number of multicomputer homes. Of the 47 million households
with computers in the United States, 12.4 million have more than
one, said Karuna Uppal, a home-networking analyst for the Yankee
Group, a technology research company in Boston. That number is
expected to jump to 17 million by the end of this year, and half of
all homes with computers are likely to have more than one by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Many factors are driving the increase in homes with multiple
PCs, including the growing availability of powerful computers that
are more affordable. In addition, more parents are giving their
children computers for educational purposes. Studies show that
parents seldom discard their older computers when they buy newer,
more advanced ones. As the Levins did, they usually give the older
one to the children.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Appleman, vice president of sales and marketing for
Webgear, said technological improvements in wireless communications
and consumers' comfort with cordless telephones had contributed to
the climate for radio-wave, also called radio-frequency, networks.
Another factor is that consumers want systems that are easy to
install and operate, even if they have to give up some features of
sophisticated office systems that are wired.
</P>
<P>
   The Homefree wireless system requires the use of cards
(available to fit either ISA slots or the newer PCI slots) that
must be inserted inside desktop computers _ an intimidating
prospect for some users. (Laptops require the simple insertion of a
special adapter card into the laptop's PCMCIA slot.)
</P>
<P>
   While the hardware installation was simple with a recent review
copy of Homefree, software glitches prevented it from working _
specifically, it could not locate the other computer on the system.
Diamond's toll-free help line was overloaded, resulting in
20-minute-plus waits for assistance. Once contact was made with
Diamond, the problem was quickly fixed with a downloaded driver
patch.
</P>
<P>
   Speed is another consideration for home networkers, and wireless
systems are slowpokes compared with wired ones. The Homefree and
the Aviator systems promise to move data to and from computers as
quickly as one megabit per second (a new version of the Aviator
that is expected to be shipped late next month is designed to
perform at more than twice its current speed).
</P>
<P>
   A common hard-wired network, using a 10/100 Ethernet card, can
push data along at 100 megabits per second.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Zai, product manager for the Infoaccess system,
acknowledged that while data on his system crept along at only 85
kilobits per second, much slower than the Homefree's megabite per
second, it was still almost twice as fast as today's commonplace
56-kilobit-per-second modems.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the radio-frequency systems require users to designate
one computer, usually the one with the fastest connection to the
Internet, to act as the network's hub. The hub computer must be on
for the others to share resources.
</P>
<P>
   With each new user sharing an Internet connection, the speed of
the connection drops. That drop can be slight or significant,
depending on the number of people sharing the line and the kind of
network being used.
</P>
<P>
   And using a home network to view movies from a computer-based
DVD would be troublesome because the transmission rates are not
fast enough yet to move such large video and sound files seamlessly
in real time.
</P>
<P>
   Another issue often raised by consumers interested in wireless
home networks is security. Can your neighbor use a wireless system
to tap into your network? Zai, the Infoaccess product manager, said
that would be practically impossible.
</P>
<P>
   One reason that the Joneses cannot peek into the Johnsons'
computers is that radio-wave networks like Homefree use
spread-spectrum frequency-hopping technology, which means that the
information is transmitted on various frequencies _ the
transmission jumps from frequency to frequency in a pattern that
only its dedicated receiver knows. (Homefree's hops over 80
channels up to a million times a second.)
</P>
<P>
   Other receivers, even those only a few yards away, cannot
recognize the pattern and capture the information, designers said.
</P>
<P>
   For Zai, home computer networks, while sophisticated in design,
must remain simple to set up and operate if they are going to be
the Next Big Thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``To use it,'' he said, ``you don't have to be a PC networking
wizard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
