<HEADLINE>
COMPARING THE NETWORK CHOICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (italics)In the past 14 months, there has been a surge of new
products that promise to enable consumers to set up home computer
networks easily, sharing printers, scanners, files and Internet
connections. Here is a list of some wireless home networking
systems and some of their features:(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HOMEFREE WIRELESS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturer: Diamond Multimedia Systems. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cost: $199.95 for the desktop kit that connects two desktop
computers; $229.95 for the kit that connects a desktop and a laptop
computer; $100 for each additional desktop card; $130 for each
additional laptop card. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Speed of transmission: Up to one megabit per second. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maximum number of computers on system: 16. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Range: 150 feet. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Advantages: Once installed, very simple and secure to use. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Disadvantages: Must open desktop computers to install cards, and
installation can be tricky. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SYMPHONY SUITE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturer: Proxim. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cost: $298 for a two-computer network; $149 for a card for each
additional computer; $299 for a cordless modem for Internet
sharing. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Speed of transmission: Up to 1.6 megabits per second. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maximum number of computers on system: 10. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Range: 150 feet. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Advantages: Highly reliable and well engineered. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Disadvantages: Expensive; does not share Internet connections
well without an additional 56K cordless modem; Internet sharing is
not possible for America Online users; you must open the desktop
computer to install a card. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AVIATOR  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturer: Webgear &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Speed of transmission: Up to one megabit per second. Aviator
Pro, due out in March, promises speeds of two megabits per second. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maximum number of computers on system: 32 computers
(manufacturer cautions that Web browsing will be slowed with many
connected) for Internet connections on a single phone line. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Range: 75 to 125 feet indoors, 200 feet outdoors. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Advantages: Simple installation; it is capable of connecting
peripherals that have U.S.B. ports. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Disadvantages: Modest range; network adapters use computers'
parallel ports but have no pass-through connections for other
devices that require the same port. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INFOACCESS  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturer: Innomedia. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cost: $200 for a kit that connects two computers. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Speed of transmission: Up to 85 kilobits per second. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maximum computers on the system: Two. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Range: 300 feet indoors and 800 feet outdoors. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Advantages: Good range; connects through any available COM
port. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Disadvantages: External device clutters desktop; relatively low
speed of transmission. Unable to connect more than two computers. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
