<HEADER>
A7685 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-HAMPTONS-BARGAINS-     02-24 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HAMPTONS-BARGAINS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HAMPTONS BARGAIN HUNT 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By TRACIE ROZHON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   No one brags about them. They're not featured in the color
brochures. Queries are met with an all-too-obvious effort to change
the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're really not our niche,'' said Frank Newbold, the
manager of the East Hampton, N.Y., office of Sotheby's
International Realty. ``I'd like to help you, but it's not our
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But bargain houses, it turns out, make up the backbone of much
of the real- estate business in the Hamptons, even in these days of
mega-houses and multi-million-dollar sales. One agent, Jerry
Preiser, of Prudential Long Island Realty, estimates that houses
under $200,000 make up 55 percent of his company's business. A
well-known local company, Cook Pony Farm Real Estate, currently has
318 houses under $250,000 listed on its computer.
</P>
<P>
   Even Newbold of Sotheby's was surprised when he checked his own
exclusive listings. ``Well, I'm amazed,'' he said. ``We have 23!''
</P>
<P>
   The unmentionables are scattered throughout the East End of Long
Island: in Bridgehampton, in Amagansett, on Shelter Island, in Sag
Harbor and Southampton and East Hampton and in the section of East
Hampton known as Northwest _ the ``hot new area,'' one agent said,
``because there's nowhere else to go.''
</P>
<P>
   But what does a buyer really get for $150,000? Or $200,000? Are
there better bargains in one town than in another?
</P>
<P>
   To find out, this reporter visited two dozen properties under
$250,000 _ and reviewed dozens more listings _ that were either for
sale or had just sold or gone into contract in that spit of land
known as the Hamptons.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and a word of warning: Don't expect brokers to fall all over
themselves to show you these properties. As Diane Saatchi of
Dayton-Halstead Real Estate said: ``Around here, everybody's such a
snob. Agents would rather go to cocktail parties and say they just
sold a $2 million house than 10 $200,000 houses.''
</P>
<P>
   Of all the East End locales, Bridgehampton is the toughest in
which to find a bargain: most of the smaller houses were built for
the potato workers decades ago and have long since been torn down.
But a couple of listings sound promising. One, at 97 Maple Lane, is
offering a three-bedroom house, plus what the listing describes as
a ``legal cottage with one bedroom'' for $250,000. The 1987 house
is said to be adjacent to land owned by a church. What could
possibly be wrong with that?
</P>
<P>
   It soon becomes excruciatingly clear: the house is actually in
the middle of an industrial park, hidden behind a long metal
warehouse building, right across the street from the Bridgehampton
railroad station. (``Close to transportation,'' Ms. Saatchi pointed
out.)
</P>
<P>
   The next house, at 41 Snake Hollow Road, the winding road to the
Hamptons Classic horse show, sounds irresistible: a 1910 cedar
cottage with two bedrooms and _ the magic words _ ``room for
pool.'' But that property, too, is a little, er, commercial. Not
only does it appear to be in a state of advanced deterioration _
its backyard shed is rusting corrugated tin _ but it overlooks the
back of a huge shopping center.
</P>
<P>
   Then, just when depression is setting in _ pay dirt.
</P>
<P>
   On the road between Bridgehampton and Sag Harbor, there's a
nondescript ranch house listed at $199,000. But here's the secret:
the back of the house slopes down to its own piece of Lily Pond. A
four-bedroom waterfront house for $199,000!
</P>
<P>
   It's true that the house is on a main road, but it's in a
residential neighborhood and far enough from the street that much
of the view of the road _ if not the sound _ could be blocked out
by rhododendrons or boxwood or a tall fence. And, anyway, you would
probably spend most of your time in the backyard.
</P>
<P>
   The house still has the fir floors, wide porcelain kitchen sink
and knotty-pine kitchen cabinets it was built with in 1954, said
Gioia diPaolo of Cook Pony Farm. On half an acre, there is room for
a pool, and there is 75 feet of pond frontage. ``It's just not the
second-home-buyer's dream; to be on a busy road,'' Ms. diPaolo
said.
</P>
<P>
   But things are looking up.
</P>
<P>
   In Sag Harbor, while there are nowhere near as many bargain
houses as there were a couple of years ago, there are still plenty.
Sag Harbor, always known for its mid-19th-century homes and its
Nantucket-like feel, has seen a real-estate boom in the last few
years, especially in the old ``fixer-uppers'' that might once have
fallen into the under-$200,000 class. Those fixer-uppers have now
been fixed up and are going for close to half a million dollars.
</P>
<P>
   But a two-story Victorian town house with a terrific location is
still on the market; right in town, at 13 Elizabeth St., and the
price is right: $189,000. But the street isn't as pretty as others
nearby, and a number of houses on the street need the same kind of
complete renovation this one does. Yet there is that front porch
and the rear deck, and the flower garden. And if Sag Harbor is
really booming, how long will it be before the other houses on the
street are restored?
</P>
<P>
   (If you're looking at wrecks, experts say to buy them in
neighborhoods with at least a smattering of more expensive houses _
that way, you'll get your renovation money back if you sell.)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Just beyond a Getty station, across from a town park, there is a
Victorian cottage that had once been adorable: the Wreck of the
Day. The house, set back from the road, cries out for everything;
even the floors look as if they need propping up. Still, the deep
backyard, with its pergola, has potential. But $225,000? On the
main road?
</P>
<P>
   The majority of the Hamptons houses under $250,000 are in East
Hampton, and a large percentage of those are in what is called the
Springs, the neighborhood north of the village and east of Three
Mile Harbor. ``There's a prejudice against the Springs,'' Elisabeth
Mills of Dayton-Halstead said, referring to the raffishness of the
area _ the sense that this is where the locals live year-round.
``But this is where you can get the most house for your money.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging by what is for sale this week, she is right. There is a
white postmodern house with an in-ground vinyl pool (``You're not
going to get Gunite for less than $350,000,'' Ms. Mills said) on a
side street; the price has just been reduced to $235,000. Because
of its pool, the agent estimated that the house would rent for at
least $18,000 for the season, which means that the rental income
might carry the mortgage, the goal for many Hamptons second-home
buyers.
</P>
<P>
   In the Northwest section of East Hampton (between Three Mile
Harbor and Northwest Harbor), two out of the dozens of listings
bear mentioning. One, a barnlike, little L-shaped two-bedroom, is
on a half-acre parcel of rolling woods, a short drive from its
neighborhood association's beach. Despite its $167,500 asking
price, the house has been on the market for years, local brokers
said.
</P>
<P>
   The problem? The kitchen is downstairs and _ worse _ it's
connected to the living room by a metal spiral staircase (spiral
staircases, whether in a Manhattan duplex or a Hamptons barn, are a
no-no). But it appears that the staircase might be replaced by a
regular wooden one by knocking through to the storage space beyond.
(Please, check with a structural engineer.)
</P>
<P>
   In general, experts caution would-be buyers to investigate the
town ordinances before they count on making changes. ``Maybe you
can put on another story and see the water,'' said Frank Newbold of
Sotheby's, ``but make sure you're not too close to the property
line.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, just a bike ride from Three Mile Harbor, is the only one
of the 23 listings the Sotheby's office would part with for this
article: a spick-and-span, $235,000, three-bedroom gray cottage
with a fireplace on a one-acre parcel of land (which, for this part
of the Hamptons, means there is an extra building lot that can be
split off or retained for privacy).
</P>
<P>
   In Amagansett, in Barnes Landing, not far from the water, an
architect-designed, one-bedroom saltbox on a quarter-acre just went
into contract for close to its $189,000 asking price. The
description doesn't do the house justice: the living room has beams
and stone floors, and even though the site is small, agents said
that town ordinances would allow the new buyers to enlarge the
house, within certain limits.
</P>
<P>
   Even though this house is gone, another one down the street is
still for sale, but it doesn't have the charm of the littler one.
For one thing, it needs a good paint job _ the lines of the
joint-compound tape can be seen through the paint.
</P>
<P>
   Over in Southampton, several houses under $250,000 are for sale
north of the Montauk Highway, a location considered less valuable
than the south-of-the-highway ``Gold Coast.'' An immaculate,
gray-shingle bungalow ($215,000) sits in a subdivision with the
aura of 1950s suburbia; the lack of trees is daunting.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a tiny, newly shingled bungalow on a perfect piece
of land on a quiet street ($185,000) and, finally, what seems like
the buy of the century: a ranch house on the top of a ridge, on a
full three-quarters of an acre _ a house that sold Tuesday for
$132,500.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, there's a bit of a problem: in the distance, wrecked cars
are piled on top of one another. Through the tree trunks, you can
see a junkyard.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Orton, of Cook Pony Farm, didn't flinch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' she said, with care, ``but when the leaves are out in
the summer, you can't see it at all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
