<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 16:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7701 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-GLOVER-GAME-NYT &LR;      02-24 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GLOVER-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CYBERNAVIGATION: JOYSTICK, MOUSE AND KEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By J.C. HERZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (italics)Long ago, in a magical land called the Crystal Kingdom,
lived a good wizard. Behind the walls of his Crystal Castle, the
wizard used magic gloves to produce strange potions and magical
spells. One day the wizard accidentally mixed the wrong potions and
__ KA-BOOM! A huge explosion sent the magic gloves flying, and
turned the wizard to stone! One of the magic gloves flew out a
turret window and landed safely on the ground. The other glove
wasn't so lucky. It landed in a cauldron of pure evil!''
</P>
<P>
   _ From the Glover Manual(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   This is a story about interface design. It's a story about game
consoles and personal computers, and how the innovations of the
former highlight shortcomings of the latter.
</P>
<P>
   Glover is a Nintendo cartridge. It is also published as a
CD-ROM. Both contain the same cinematic introduction. The good
glove flies out the window, lands on the ground and looks up in
horror as the castle's seven crystals (the life force of the
kingdom) pop off their turrets and begin to fall.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing they're about to shatter, the glove casts a spell,
turning them into something tougher: rubber beach balls. Thus
transformed, the crystals hit the ground and bounce rather than
break. Unfortunately, six of them bounce into different parts of
the kingdom and must be retrieved to restore the castle and bring
the wizard back to life.
</P>
<P>
   So the story is an archetypal quest _ a scavenger hunt about
redemption. The hero is a magic glove that looks like the Hamburger
Helper mascot. Sometimes he runs, walks or tiptoes, and his two
middle fingers become legs.
</P>
<P>
   And he sometimes turns into a hand that can roll, lob or dribble
a beach ball, and his arms and legs become fingers. (In either
case, his eyes blink at you expectantly from the back of the
glove.)
</P>
<P>
   Alone, Glover can jump, turn cartwheels and crawl on his belly
(palm?). But once he finds the beach ball hidden in every level, he
has an all-purpose object to manipulate (throw at a target, bounce
up stairs, use as a flotation device _ it slices, it dices).
</P>
<P>
   He can also transform the rubber beach ball into a bowling ball,
a magnetic ball bearing or its original crystal form, each of which
comes in handy, depending on the situation. Run into a glass window
and the beach ball does nothing. Heave a bowling ball toward it
(smash!), and it does nicely.
</P>
<P>
   It's an ingenious control system, particularly on the Nintendo
console, with its analog joystick that reads angle and direction,
allowing more subtle control. The joystick lets you fine-tune your
position, but it also lends degrees and gradations to your
movement. If you tilt the stick slightly forward, you're walking.
Tilt it all the way forward, and you're running.
</P>
<P>
   For subtlety, nothing beats an analog controller, be it a
joystick, steering wheel, tuning knob or volume dial. Shifting your
hands a millimeter to the left or the right, and you can squeeze a
two-ton hunk of glass and steel into a tight parking space.
</P>
<P>
   Nudging a dial imperceptibly in either direction, you can find
the perfect sound level. In digital space, analog control makes you
nimble and flexible and comfortable in your virtual skin.
</P>
<P>
   Contrast that with a keyboard, which is entirely digital. You
can move with arrow keys, but only at a uniform speed. You can
perform the same maneuvers with Alt and Shift as you can with
Nintendo control buttons, but the left middle and ring fingers on a
keyboard just don't respond like index fingers and thumbs wrapped
around a console controller. If Glover truly reflected the PC game
experience, he would be a mitten.
</P>
<P>
   But this frustration is typical of computer software, as opposed
to the software that runs on game consoles or in wired-to-the-gills
home theaters. The standard hardware interface for a home computer
is a 19th-century technology designed for alphanumeric data entry,
not for navigation.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of a mouse only half-solves the problem because all
you can really do with a mouse is draw on a flat surface and
shuffle paper in fancy ways, which starts to seem inadequate as our
information becomes less and less flat.
</P>
<P>
   In the world of digital media, cutting-edge designers don't talk
about pages. They're not interested in flat, static surfaces. They
talk about landscapes. They talk about information the way joystick
jockeys talk about a video game, in terms of volume and movement.
And that's great.
</P>
<P>
   But it's only great if you have an input device that lets you
fly, and the keyboard remains firmly grounded. There are 107 keys
on a standard computer keyboard. That makes it the centipede of
hardware interfaces. By the same token, a computer mouse, with its
two-dimensional flexibility, would be something like a snake.
</P>
<P>
   If digital media is a landscape, then computer input devices
allow people to crawl, slither and walk across it. They are
flatland devices for covering a vast ground. Remote controls allow
people to swim in it _ in a puddle of information on one audio CD
or the tidal pool of network television or the inland sea of 500
cable channels.
</P>
<P>
   And game devices are what allow people to fly, swooping down to
nab a quick tidbit of information or lingering in upward spirals
for hours over a thermal updraft of entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   When the fabled convergence comes about _ when televisions and
PCs and consoles all melt together and their contents blur at the
edges _ our choices about how to experience media may boil down to
our preferred means of locomotion: the keyboard, the remote control
or the joystick.
</P>
<P>
   Some people will walk. Some will prefer to swim. And the ones
who have been playing video games all their lives? They'll probably
plug joysticks into their information appliances in 2006 and fly
right off the desktop.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the video game, Glover returns to the castle, puts
the last crystal in place, brings the wizard back to life and hops
onto the magician's right hand. Summoning the evil glove, who
glowers and resists, Glover restores his demonic counterpart to
goodness and health. And they all live happily ever after.
</P>
<P>
   Until the wizard makes his next explosive mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Hasbro Interactive; cartridge for Nintendo 64, $59.95; CD-ROM
for Windows 95 and 98, $59.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
