<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7707 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICARE-FRAUD25-COX     02-24 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-FRAUD25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AARP OPENS DRIVE AGAINST MEDICARE FRAUD
 &HT;    With MEDICARE-FRAUD-DATA.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ AARP and the federal government Wednesday launched
a drive to recruit and train thousands of retired volunteers to
help detect Medicare overpayments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although reducing fraud, waste and abuse will not cure all
Medicare's financial problems, it is an essential first step in
keeping the system solvent in the long term,'' said Joe Perkins,
president of the AARP, formerly known as the American Association
of Retired Persons. About half of its 33 million members are 65 or
older, which qualifies them for Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Health care cheats should be on notice that we should use
every appropriate tool to combat Medicare fraud and abuse,'' said
Attorney General Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   In a new national poll of 2,000 adults released by the AARP, 83
percent said health care fraud is widespread, and 86 percent said
that if they knew more about health care fraud, they would be more
inclined to report it.
</P>
<P>
   Some physicians' organizations objected that encouraging
patients to look for mistakes or fraud in their medical bills could
damage the bond between doctors and patients.
</P>
<P>
   But the American Hospital Association and the Blue Cross and
Blue Shield Association endorsed the AARP's $500,000 initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's initial sessions in 31 cities started with a
satellite-linked briefing by Reno and officials of the AARP, the
FBI and the Department of Health and Human Services (HHS).
</P>
<P>
   ``We're actually asking you to be the eyes and ears of the
Medicare program,'' HHS Secretary Donna Shalala said.
</P>
<P>
   Using methods developed by U.S. Administration on Aging as it
trained 10,000 volunteers in pilot programs, the retirees were
taught how to double-check their Medicare bills and how to identify
common Medicare scams.
</P>
<P>
   They were told to ask their doctor, hospital, nursing home or
other provider about any item they don't understand. If still
unsatisfied, they were asked to report questionable items to the
Medicare contractor whose phone number is on the Medicare statement
and to report likely fraud on the the toll-free Medicare Fraud
Hotline at 1-800-HHS-TIPS (1-800-447-8477).
</P>
<P>
   Participants received baseball caps and magnifying glasses as
souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sending out patients to fight Medicare fraud with little more
than a baseball cap, magnifying glass and an 800 number trivializes
real fraud and creates an adversarial tone in every
physician-patient encounter,'' said Dr. Nancy Dickey, a Texas
physician who is president of the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   Shalala said the magnifying glasses and caps ``obviously bring
visibility to the program, but it's what's in people's heads, and
knowing how to read the bill, that would be very helpful.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I called (Dickey) yesterday and reassured her that we want
Medicare recipients to have enough training to review their bills,
but we also want those bills to be straightforward enough,''
Shalala said. ``Part of the campaign over the next couple of years
is going to be to simplify the billing.''
</P>
<P>
   Her department's efforts to simplify the more than 100,000 pages
of Medicare billing rules have been bogged down by the need to
divert money and manpower to solving Medicare's problems with the
Y2K bug. Otherwise, next year that programming glitch could plague
the network of computers used by the government and contractors to
handle nearly 1 billion Medicare bills annually.
</P>
<P>
   But some progress from changes encouraged and funded by Congress
and President Clinton are already apparent, according to June Gibbs
Brown, the inspector general who discovered that in 1996, 14
percent of the payments in the ``fee for service'' portion of
Medicare were unjustified.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since then, there has been a dramatic drop in these payments
which should not have been made,'' she said at the Miami session.
``That is down to 7.1 percent, but it also means we're still
misspending about $12.6 billion in that part of the program
alone.''
</P>
<P>
   She was unable to separate the portion due to waste or mistakes
from the part due to fraud or abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jane Orient, executive director of the Association of
American Physicians and Surgeons, said the AARP program would make
it harder for a doctor to trust his patient ``instead of worrying
that he's a government-anointed deputy, a paid informant, driven by
a profit motive to entrap him and looking to collect a bounty on
the back of a doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Reno said rewards to informants ``are a different
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Shalala said, ``Health care professionals themselves check their
bills and make sure they aren't paying for something they shouldn't
be paying for.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
