<SLUG> BC-CIR-EBAY-HSX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIRTUAL STOCKS LURE REAL MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MIKE ROMANO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leave it to Hollywood and the Internet to produce a virtual
stock market of fake stocks and fake money with such a fanatic
following that players are offering hundreds of real dollars to buy
a make-believe portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   First, the game. Hollywood Stock Exchange (www.hsx.com) was
founded in 1996 by two Wall Street veterans and movie buffs, Max
Keiser and Michael Burns. Today, nearly 200,000 HSX traders
speculate on box-office returns for current and forthcoming films
by trading Movie Stocks on the site.
</P>
<P>
   HSX keeps a real-time ticker of Movie Stock prices, which are
determined by the gross box-office revenue a film earns in its
first four weeks in United States theaters.
</P>
<P>
   For example, one HSX share of the forthcoming ``Star Wars''
prequel from George Lucas currently trades for roughly H$315,
meaning that players expect the film to gross $315 million in its
first month. ``Shakespeare in Love'' earned a little more than $46
million in its first four weeks, paying Movie Stock holders H$46.66
per share. A star player, Curtis Edmonds, got in when the film was
valued at only H$1.
</P>
<P>
   It was Edmonds who auctioned off his portfolio on Ebay
(www.ebay.com), the Internet auction site. The high bid for his
imaginary portfolio, worth $136 million in HSX dollars, was $1,050
in real dollars after a seven-day auction last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of an experiment to see if there was a real market
out there for Hollywood Dollars,'' said Edmonds, a lawyer for the
State of Texas and an amateur film reviewer. He said that after a
year of HSX trading, he was retiring from it because it had become
too easy.
</P>
<P>
   The portfolio was one of the largest in HSX history when it was
put up for sale, and it has earned a certain measure of fame for
Edmonds, known as Blueduck on the HSX site and also on a related
site, the Hollywood Stock Brokerage and Resource site
(www.hsbr.org), a fan site for HSX players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy when it was going for $100,'' Edmonds said. ``I
wouldn't have imagined anyone would want to pay over a thousand.''
Although Edmonds has yet to collect from the high bidder, he is
confident that his HSX habit will turn into real money because two
other E-bay bidders also eclipsed $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   As the bids on the portfolio skyrocketed last week, at least
nine other HSX high rollers put their portfolios on the Ebay
auction block. But even though some of those portfolios eclipse
Blueduck's in HSX value, none have garnered anywhere near $1,050,
which only adds to the absurdity of it all.
</P>
<P>
   A senior analyst for Jupiter Communications, Adam Schoenfeld,
links the portfolio's auction price to the inflated valuation of
Internet stocks: ``This is a pretend market mimicking the mania of
real markets. Caveat emptor.''
</P>
<P>
   John Riffe, a librarian in Billings, Mont., who is an HSX
trader, was an early bidder on the Blueduck portfolio. He said:
``It's for the prestige. It's like a Cadillac versus a Chevrolet _
they'll both get you to the same place, but the Blueduck just gets
you there in nicer style.''
</P>
<P>
   Riffe said he would have paid up to $200 for Edmonds' account
but that he had no interest in the other HSX portfolios on Ebay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
