<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-COLLEGE-APPLY-ART-730(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MULTIMEDIA COLLEGE APPLICATION? IT MAY HELP, BUT NOT OFTEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., N.J., N.Y., Ohio, Pa.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By LUCILLE RENWICK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rick Morrison arrived at his interview at Carnegie Mellon
University armed with more than just his charm and a rehearsed
spiel for admissions officers. A high school senior from central
New Jersey, he also took an interactive, graphics-laden multimedia
portfolio that highlights his academic record, activities and
creative writing and is saved on a compact disk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much more exciting and expressive than a few lines on a
traditional college application,'' said Morrison, 17, a student at
Hunterdon Central Regional High School in Flemington, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   His portfolio opens with a mini-submarine passing through a sea
of blue-green colored words and ending at a treasure chest which
contains the word ``dream.'' Clip-art graphics and new age
instrumental music follow as a backdrop to the portfolio's main
menu. Move the cursor to one of the subjects, click, and steel
doors open to the next level, with more detail and carefully
wrought graphics.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Yourst, a senior at Vestal High School in upstate New York,
didn't send a CD with his applications to MIT, Princeton, Cornell
and Carnegie Mellon. Instead, he sent the Internet directions
(called a uniform resource locator, or URL) to a website for a
software company, Laserstars Technology (www.laserstars.com) that
he started when he was 15. While he considered creating a link to a
personal site, Yourst, now 18, also sent details about other
projects, including his high school's website
(www.vestal.stier.org/vhs), which he helped to design, and a
software program he created that helps scientists at Cornell
University analyze molecules.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think including information about my site will certainly
differentiate me from other high school students, especially
because it shows the level of science and technology experience I
have,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Paper applications are still the main tool admissions officers
use to decide whether or not to accept a student. But additions
like these are part of the growing technological supplements that
frantic teenagers are either sending along with their college
applications, referring to in their essays or shipping out
afterwards.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pressure is on for students to distinguish themselves from
the zillions of other kids who have glowing SAT scores and great
marks,'' said Peter Kovaric, a professor at UCLA who specializes in
educational technology.
</P>
<P>
   For years, applicants to theater, film and music programs
regularly shipped off tapes of their performances. And applicants
seeking spots at universities like MIT or Caltech have regularly
sent disks with their originally written computer programs. Now,
such electronic supplements are moving beyond the realm of
specialized programs to the general college applicant pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've just tipped the iceberg in terms of what's
possible and what students can do with this technology,'' said
Michael Steidel, director of admissions at Carnegie Mellon.
``Students are just learning how to exploit it to their benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 13,000 applications Carnegie Mellon has received this
year, about 100 have referred to websites and about a dozen
applicants have sent CDs with multimedia portfolios. Steidel said
the number of CDs and floppy computer disks arriving with
applications has decreased slightly over the last two years as web
site citations on applications have increased.
</P>
<P>
   The real question is whether this extra effort to grab an
admissions officer's attention pays off. ``The supplemental
materials can help distinguish one student from another, but in 99
percent of the applications they don't particularly help the
applicant,'' said Bette Johnson, associate director of admissions
at MIT, in a comment typical of the admissions officers' attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   Added Kovaric: ``If they can't do library research or write a
clear paper, then all the animated gimmicks in the world aren't
going to change anything. But if they can write a compelling
personal statement and put together an interesting website, they
can set themselves apart from other students.''
</P>
<P>
   With official acceptance notices due out in April, it's too soon
to tell if Morrison's CD was a hit at Carnegie Mellon. ``I think
their reactions were very positive, even though they only saw a
small piece of it,'' Morrison said of admissions officers'
reactions to his disc.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, the CDs and websites are viewed only if
admissions workers have time. Normally they don't. Carnegie Mellon
skims most of the website referrals and CDs, Steidel said. Harvard
occasionally reviews the supplemental work, but normally does so
only once the students have passed the high academic hurdles, said
Marlyne McGrath Lewis, director of admissions for Harvard and
Radcliffe colleges. MIT's admissions officers sometimes look at the
website referrals they receive, Ms. Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do care what students are doing,'' said Erika Jonieta, an
MIT admissions officer who reviews most of the website referrals.
``But I see one in five that really make a difference in a
student's application.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of what the admissions officers say, students believe
their electronic portfolios will pay off. Hunterdon Central High
School students point to four previous classmates who used CD
multimedia portfolios with their applications last year, which are
archived at the school's website (www.hcrhs.hunterdon.k12.nj.us).
One received a full scholarship to Rider University and a job
working with technology, in part because of his portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   While Carl Storrs, 18, a senior at Walnut Hills High School in
Cincinnati, can't cite previous classmates with websites, he thinks
admissions officers will be impressed with his website
(http://meowing.ccm.uc.edu/carl), which explains his after-school
work in electronic computer music at a program at the Cincinnati
College's Conservatory of Music and an internship researching
pupillary dilation.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Cortina of Hunterdon Central High seized Harvard's
invitation to submit additional material for her application. She
applied for early admission and was deferred to the general
applicant pool. She finished her interactive multimedia portfolio
earlier this month and mailed copies to Harvard, Yale, Princeton,
Georgetown and Boston University with a letter from her teacher
explaining the portfolio and the CD portfolio project at Hunterdon
Central.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't just saying I can sing, I can write,'' said Ms.
Cortina, 17. ``It's saying `Look at the opportunities I've had with
technology. Look at the breadth of knowledge and capabilities. And
look, I can also sing and dance.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The portfolio opens with a quick animation of shapes and colors
gliding across the screen, followed by a short video of Ms. Cortina
introducing her portfolio. On the next page, mauve and blue hues
accent the main menu of choices: Academics; Activities; Writing, a
description of her high school. The academics section includes her
transcript, including awards and standardized test scores. The
writing page highlights three poems she wrote and interpreted
through multimedia presentations set to music and graphics. She is
proudest of the 30-second digitized video clip of her three theater
performances.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all say that if it's not something that catches their
eye, don't bother, `` she said of admissions counselors. ``But I
think this is eye-catching with some substance to who I am and what
I've done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
