<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV28-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN SPENDING ROBS VOTERS OF INFLUENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Feb. 28)   (For Use By New York Times News Service Clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Money. Money. Money. That is the name of the game
in American politics, where almost any campaign for public office
is likely to cost candidates and their parties more than a million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   If the prize is the Democratic or Republican presidential
nomination, a White House hopeful must be ready to solicit and then
spend at least $20 million before he or she ever has the
opportunity to square off against the nominee of the opposing
party.
</P>
<P>
   The love of money may be the root of all evil, as the Bible
teaches us, but the use of money, as a powerful California state
treasurer named Jesse Unruh once said, is the mother's milk of
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Long before anyone ever heard of Monica Lewinsky, Bill Clinton
was the target of investigators who believe he either broke or
badly bent the congressionally decreed rules that govern the ways
in which politicians can garner and spend campaign funds.
</P>
<P>
   He was accused of converting the Lincoln bedroom into a
celebrated sleep-over salon for individuals who filled Democratic
coffers. He was charged, as was his 1996 GOP opponent, Bob Dole,
with turning so-called soft money into hard money by fielding
television commercials that argued strongly for the election of a
candidate. Soft money was supposed to fund only institutional ads
that supported an issue or a party and not an individual.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's running mate, Al Gore, was charged by his opponents
with making fund-raising telephone calls from his White House
office in violation of a law passed in 1883 when Chester A. Arthur
was president.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also stirred up controversy when he denied being aware that
his appearance at a Buddhist temple in California was actually a
fund-raising excursion.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno declined to name an independent
counsel to probe the accusations against Clinton and Gore.
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr looked into some of them but so
far has not formally accused the president or vice president of
wrongdoing. Three committees of Congress have launched
well-publicized inquiries into their activities, but to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the use of money in political campaigns remains an
explosive and often nasty issue.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Congressional leaders had an opportunity last year to
bring some fairness and decency to the matter by passing a
bipartisan reform bill, but they refused to do so because the
legislation's strictures would cost the GOP money.
</P>
<P>
   So what has been the upshot? The barons of the AFL-CIO announced
two weeks ago that they will spend $46 million to help elect a
Democratic Congress in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., withdrew his
bid for election to a fourth term because he does not want to spend
the next two years raising campaign funds. Although Lautenberg, 75,
is independently wealthy, he figured he would have to collect at
least $12 million to run a successful campaign for reelection.
</P>
<P>
   It's sad that Lautenberg's career is ending because he no longer
wants to be involved in the tawdry exercise of seeking funds from
people who have a greedy vested interest in parceling out dollars
to politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it is the gun lobby, the tobacco companies, the
petroleum industry or the labor unions, contributors give money in
exchange for favors. That fact of political life was demonstrated
last year when legislation to levy a tax on tobacco as a means of
curtailing teenage smoking was defeated by GOP leaders on Capitol
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Money does not, of course, guarantee candidates' victory at the
polls. But lack of money can guarantee their defeat.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, we have seen such presidential hopefuls as
Texas Sen. Phil Gramm, publisher Steve Forbes and former Delaware
Gov. Pete duPont, all of whom were armed with millions of dollars,
go down to defeat.
</P>
<P>
   But the men who defeated them in the Republican primaries, Dole
and George Bush, also entered the battle laden with money.
</P>
<P>
   With the passage of time, campaigns have become more expensive
and candidates more beholden to special interests, whose objectives
often run counter to initiatives that benefit the people.
</P>
<P>
   Television has made it possible for voters to see the candidates
in informal settings dealing with major issues. But television also
has made it imperative that candidates raise and spend millions
more than they once did.
</P>
<P>
   American voters may not be upset by the manner in which big
bucks decide elections and policies, but they should be.
</P>
<P>
   As our system stands now, it simply encourages the irresponsible
use of money to influence the people's business.
</P>
<P>
   Winston Churchill once said: ``Politics are almost as exciting
as war, and quite as dangerous. In war you can only be killed once,
but in politics many times.'' Had he lived in America in the 1990s,
he might also have noted that politics is almost as expensive as
war.
</P>
<P>
   The cost is not just in dollars; it also is in an erosion of the
people's influence and authority.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-99 1629EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990224.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7729 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-FREE-PCs-ART-NYT &LR;      02-24 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-FREE-PCs-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVICE' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)  
 CONSUMERS FLOCK TO GET FREE PCs, BUT SOME FEAR `SURVEILLANCE (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ Noel C. Culberson has long since acceded to
a Faustian bargain offered by marketers.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers subsidize his television shows, newspaper
subscription and favorite sports teams, and in exchange, Culberson
concedes them a bit of his subconscious to soak up the commercial
messages directed at him.
</P>
<P>
   So when a company recently announced that it would offer free
personal computers to people willing to accept a constant display
of advertising in the right margin of the computer screen,
Culberson, 31, a financial analyst, jumped in line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can zone out ads from years of practice from watching
television and ignoring e-mails,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That seems of little comfort to privacy advocates and consumer
groups who are concerned about what they see as an intrusive level
of consumer monitoring required to sell the advertising needed to
cover operating costs.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, Culberson's main concern is that there are not
enough free computers to go around.
</P>
<P>
   Since Free-PC, the aptly named company behind the concept,
announced on Feb. 8 that it would give away 10,000 computers, more
than one million people have signed up for the offer. To qualify,
potential recipients have to answer several dozen questions that
will determine how desirable they are to potential advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   The questions ask for a telephone number, street address, e-mail
address, birth date, marital status, sex and household income.
There are also questions about hobbies and the magazines and
consumer electronics in the household.
</P>
<P>
   Free-PC, which is based in Pasadena, Calif., will choose the
10,000 winners of low-end Compaq computers, based on who best fits
the demographic profiles that advertisers are seeking.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, 6,000 schools have signed up for a similar program
offered by Zap Me, of San Ramon, Calif. Last October, the company
announced that it would give schools 15 computers with
satellite-based Internet connections. The catch: the computers
display advertising in the left-hand corner of the monitor. So far,
Zap Me has given computers to 55 schools in eight states.
</P>
<P>
   The concept of free computers represents an evolution from older
offerings of free, advertising-subsidized e-mail and Internet
access. The companies offering such services have generally
struggled, spending millions to build a subscriber base large
enough to attract enough advertisers to offset their costs.
</P>
<P>
   Those offering free computers say the enthusiastic response
proves that this business model's time has come and can be
profitable _ particularly with the rapid price drops of computer
hardware.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the companies promoting free PCs say they will give
advertisers an unprecedented ability to target ads toward likely
customers, based on their demographics and Web-surfing patterns. In
fact, that is pretty much Free-PCs only reason for existing.
</P>
<P>
   When students log onto one of the free Zap Me computers, the
system will know each one's grade level, sex and Zip code. The
computer will then dish out age and sex-appropriate advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   Yet so far, neither Free-PC nor Zap Me has announced any deals
with advertisers. While waiting for sponsors to sign on, Zap Mes
computers have been displaying advertisements from some of its
partners, including Microsoft and Compaq.
</P>
<P>
   The question of whether advertisers will sign on is just one of
the lingering questions about a concept that could forever change
the relationship between PC users and their computers.
</P>
<P>
   The main worry of privacy advocates is the monitoring of
information that will allow the advertising to be targeted. They
warn that recipients of free PCs must be aware that commercial
dossiers could track their buying and surfing habits.
</P>
<P>
   While both Zap Me and Free-PC promise not to disclose personal
information about any specific user, such information can still
become public through a lawsuit or if the company is ever sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you go to auction sites? What kind of research do you do?
Do you like sex? Do you explore prescription drugs?'' asked Evan
Hendricks, editor of Privacy Times, a newsletter based in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an incredible profile of you in the hands of strangers,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Catlett, president of Junkbusters, an organization that
opposes intrusive marketing, put it more bluntly: ``You're letting
a surveillance device into your home.''
</P>
<P>
   Responding to concerns that personal data could be subpoenaed,
Steve Chadima, a spokesman for Free-PC, said that seemed unlikely
and that the company would fight any such attempt. He stopped
short, though, of giving an ironclad assurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not prepared to go to jail for it,'' he said. ``But we
certainly would do everything in our power not to comply.''
</P>
<P>
   Chadima said privacy concerns had not stopped people from
signing up. ``It doesn't seem to be an issue, given how many people
have responded,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some consumers are wavering. Even Culberson said that
before he would actually accept a free computer _ if offered one _
he would have to know that it would not monitor his every mouse
click.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Ted Maddock, technology coordinator for Mount Diablo
High School in Concord, Calif., said he did not object to the Zap
Me advertisements, targeted or otherwise. Mount Diablo was among
the first to get the Zap Me computers.
</P>
<P>
   Some school districts have balked at the Zap Me offering,
arguing that their mission is to educate, not act as an advertising
conduit. Their objections recall similar ones over advertising on
Channel One, which has given free televisions to more than 12,000
schools nationwide in return for broadcasting programs and
commercials to students.
</P>
<P>
   But Maddock said Zap Me's advertising was no worse than banner
advertisements that students would have to see anyway when they
surfed the Net. Besides, he added, his school could not otherwise
afford the hardware.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone offered us $70,000 worth of computers,'' Maddock said.
``It's been working well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
