<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 16:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7734 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-LOST-LUGGAGE-NYT &LR;      02-24 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-LOST-LUGGAGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE ALL THE LOST BAGS GO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala.)  (mk) 
 By TERRY McMANUS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Next time an airline tells you your bags have been hopelessly
lost, you may want to head for Scottsboro, Ala. That city is home
to the Unclaimed Baggage Center, a halfway house for AWOL
possessions. Or, if you want to save time, you can just get on the
center's Web site (www.unclaimedbaggage.com) and sample some of the
goods for sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``For our customers and employees, it's a little like Christmas
every day,'' said Bryan Owens, 40, owner of the Unclaimed Baggage
Center. The company's Web site says it deals in ``lost treasures
from around the world.''
</P>
<P>
   More than half the stock is clothing, but you can also find
sporting goods, computers, camera equipment, jewelry and
miscellaneous trinkets. Some of the more unusual items that have
turned up in Scottsboro include a six-carat diamond ring, a case of
ancient Egyptian artifacts and a set of signed Salvador Dali
prints, Owens said.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines, Owens explained, sell bags and cargo by the pound
to Unclaimed Baggage with no knowledge of their contents; carry-on
effects are sold as is. (The airlines queried confirmed that their
companies sold lost baggage and cargo but would not identify the
buyers. For his part, Owens would not reveal his suppliers.)
</P>
<P>
   Brock Warner, a spokesman for Unclaimed Baggage, said the
company had no competitors because it had exclusive long-term
contracts with the airlines.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Owens said, only a tiny number of lost items ever
make their way to his block-long store in Alabama, which his father
founded in 1970. About 0.5 percent of bags are misrouted by the
airlines _ the problem worsens during the holidays _ but 98 percent
of the bags are claimed by customers within 48 hours, Owens said.
When you consider that 1 billion passengers check 2 billion bags
every year, Owens said, you begin to understand how stuff gets
lost.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines search for the owners for up to 90 days but do not
open the luggage. After that, they take legal possession of the
articles, including that laptop you brought on board or that novel
you left at the gate, and quickly sell them to Owens. He, in turn,
ships them to Scottsboro or donates them to charity. Since last
October, Owens has also been moving this merchandise on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The Unclaimed Baggage Center also occasionally auctions
exceptionally rare and expensive items, like the Egyptian
artifacts, through Christie's, Warner said. UBC has some of the
jewelry appraised before it is priced for sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're stocking about 2 million unique, never-seen-before items
in our store each year,'' Owens said. About 50 to 75 products are
sold online each week. Owens said in-store and Web buyers could
expect to pay 50 percent to 80 percent below retail prices.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, a car CD player (new and still in its box) was
available at Unclaimed Baggage for $150 while a Chicago audio
dealer was asking $279 for the same unit. But a pair of Adidas
Universal running shoes recently offered on line for $51 was just
$9 less than what a Chicago Foot Locker store was charging.
</P>
<P>
   So would a purchaser feel a little creepy about buying unclaimed
baggage? Who was the shoes' previous owner, anyway? Don't all
people who lose baggage wish they could have it back? And for that
matter, who owned the grass skirt and coconut top that sold for $5
under the ``unique clothing'' category not long ago? And who bought
the Polish military helmet for $125? Couldn't the airlines just
give these items to charity and take a tax write-off rather than
selling them?
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to realize that after 90 days, we've settled the
claim with the customer,'' said David Castelveter, a spokesman for
US Airways in Arlington, Va. He said he assumed that selling the
items ``is an attempt to recoup some of the costs of doing that,
though we're probably still losing money.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. airlines are liable for up to $1,250 per passenger for
luggage mishandled during domestic flights, but they are not liable
for lost carry-on possessions, Owens said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, business is brisk on the Unclaimed Baggage site,
which averages about 2,000 visits a day, Owens said. The traffic is
almost certainly encouraged by such helpful observations on the
Unclaimed Baggage site as the one about a someone buying a
``perfectly ordinary soap-on-a-rope'' only to find that it was
hollowed out and full of cash.
</P>
<P>
   And a woman recently found $2,000 in the lining of a suitcase
she bought, Warner said, adding, ``We can't check everything.'' Any
drugs found by Unclaimed Baggage are turned over to the Drug
Enforcement Agency, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's neat that they're selling these things and
they're not going to waste,'' said Leah Cruz of Tampa, Fla., who
has purchased several items from the site. ``It's still good
stuff.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
