<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-SEEDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE TO PURCHASE HEIRLOOM SEEDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ANNE RAVER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you are interested in unusual plants _ and helping out the
gene pool at the same time _ the following plant societies offer a
wide variety of seeds:
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAN HORTICULTURAL SOCIETY, based at River Farm in
Alexandria, Va., offers members a free seed-exchange program, which
draws from hundreds of annuals, perennials, woody plants,
vegetables and herbs. The $25 annual membership includes the
American Gardener magazine. Call (800) 777-7931; on the web:
www.ahs.org. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN STATE HEIRLOOM SEED SOCIETY, a nonprofit organization of
farmers and gardeners in Delaware, N.J., offers 1,000 varieties of
edible heirlooms in its 1999 catalog, like the genus Yellow, a
2-pound sweet, yellow tomato with red streaks. A $10 membership
includes reprints of old seed catalogs and the summer tomato
tasting. Member farmers receive seed free. For a catalog, write the
Society at P.O. Box 15, Valley Road, Delaware, NJ 07833.
</P>
<P>
   HEIRLOOM SEED PROJECT grows 90 varieties of vegetables, herbs,
flowers, fruits and field crops at its 100-acre farm at the Landis
Valley Museum in Lancaster, Pa., including Amish gnuttle bean,
black salsify, Hoffer lazy wife bean, Wren's egg pole bean,
birdhouse gourd, dipper gourd and Jenny Lind melon. Also available
are field crops like flax seed, red mangelwurtzel (it's a very
large beet), buckwheat and spelt. Apple varieties include Black
Gilliflower Sheepnose, Cox's Orange Pippin and Baldwin Woodpecker.
For information, write Heirloom Seed Project, Landis Valley Museum,
2451 Kissel Hill Rd., Lancaster, PA 17601; or call (717) 569-0401,
ext. 204.
</P>
<P>
   THE NEW ENGLAND WILDFLOWER SOCIETY lists more than 200
wildflower varieties in its 1999 Seed and Book Catalog. The
selection includes wild flowers that thrive in moist, shady
locations or in sunny and dry spots. There are easy-to-grow
varieties, like purple coneflower, cardinal flower and
Jack-in-the-pulpit, and those that require more patience, like
trillium and pitcher plant. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Requests for the catalog must be received by March 1; seed sales
end on March 15. Some seeds are in limited supply, and orders are
filled as they are received, so if you want seeds, don't delay. To
obtain a catalog, send $2.50 to Seeds, New England Wild Flower
Society, Garden in the Woods, 180 Hemenway Rd., Framingham, MA
01701.
</P>
<P>
   SEED SAVERS EXCHANGE, a nonprofit organization in Decorah, Iowa,
maintains more than 18,000 rare vegetable varieties at Heritage
Farm, as well as flowers, apples and grapes. You can buy heirloom
seeds through its catalog, or become a member, for $30, and have
access to 11,000 varieties of vegetables and fruits, as well as
three publications a year, including a yearbook with members' seeds
and addresses. The separate Flower and Herb Exchange offers members
3,000 varieties of flowers and herbs, with a similar yearbook ($10
to join). For information, call (319) 382-5990, or write Seed
Savers Exchange, 3076 North Winn Road, Decoarh, IA 52101. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE THOMAS JEFFERSON CENTER FOR HISTORIC PLANTS at Monticello,
in Charlottesville, Va., offers many plants Jefferson grew in his
garden, like double columbine, McMahon's Texas bird pepper,
perennial sweet pea, balsam apple and nutmeg plant. Also a
delightful variety of dianthus. For a catalog, call (804) 984-9821;
on the web: www.monticello.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
