r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX     02-24 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEARING THE NAME OF A WEST POINT GRAD
</HEADLINE>
 (for use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Good timing.
</P>
<P>
   In pardoning Henry O. Flipper during the last Black History
Month observance of the 20th century, President Clinton picked an
appropriate moment to undo one of the more glaring racial
injustices of the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   Flipper, the first African-American to graduate from West Point,
was dishonorably discharged from the United States Cavalry in 1892
under circumstances that emitted a pronounced smell of racist
taint.
</P>
<P>
   Flipper went on to a distinguished civilian career as a civil
and mining engineer in Mexico and the American Southwest. He also
became an outstanding linguist, a specialist in translating complex
Spanish land grant documents.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those accomplishments, Flipper tried for decades to
erase the stain from his military career. He had really wanted to
be a soldier more than anything else.
</P>
<P>
   Considering what he had to endure to gain his commission, his
soldierly ambition was understandable. In his book ``Colored Cadet
at West Point'' (published in 1878, a year after his graduation),
Flipper wrote of being subjected to continuous ostracism and
harassment. That he kept his silence and endured the ordeal
testified to his strength of character.
</P>
<P>
   Flipper was brought up on charges at Fort Davis, Texas, amid
accusations of embezzlement of commissary funds and conduct
unbecoming an officer. The court-martial found him not guilty of
embezzlement, for lack of motive, but guilty on several counts of
the latter charge.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, the court-martial said he didn't steal the money but
did try to cover up the fact that it was missing.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Flipper did try various means to hide the fact that the
money was gone until money owed by some officers came in to cover
the shortfall. He even covered part of it with a personal check,
for which he lacked sufficient funds. He was expecting a royalty
check from his book to arrive in time to offset that.
</P>
<P>
   Someone, however, did steal part of the money. Suspicion fell
for a while on a laundress with whom Flipper was friendly, who had
access to Flipper's quarters. He kept the commissary funds in a
trunk there.
</P>
<P>
   In later years, Flipper would maintain that his commanding
officer at Fort Davis, Col. William R. Shafter, set him up in
collusion with another officer who bore a long-standing grudge
against Flipper. The black lieutenant frequently went riding at
Fort Comanche with the woman that officer later married, and there
was bad feeling between the two men.
</P>
<P>
   It was the dishonorable discharge that gave off the strong smell
of racism. White officers convicted of much more serious offenses
were routinely given lesser sentences _ suspensions or setbacks on
the promotion list.
</P>
<P>
   Some scholars have speculated that the harsh sentence was
imposed in the expectation that it would be overturned higher up in
the chain of command. The judge advocate general of the Army, Gen.
David G. Swain, recommended as much to President Chester A. Arthur
and Secretary of War Robert Todd Lincoln, son of the late
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is believed that there is no case on record in which an
officer was treated with such personal harshness ... I would
recommend the sentence be continued but mitigated to a lesser
degree of punishment,'' Swaim wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln and Arthur ignored Swaim's recommendation and confirmed
the sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Flipper continued his efforts to get a law passed reinstating
his commission until 1924. He died in 1940. Descendants of his
brother, African Methodist Episcopal Bishop Josephus Flipper, and
other interested parties took up the cause again during the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, the Army changed the discharge to honorable. A statue
was unveiled in his honor at West Point in 1977, the centennial
year of his graduation. In 1978, his body was reinterred with full
military honors by a burial detail from Fort Benning, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's pardon this month completed the process of removing
the asterisk from Flipper's niche in black history.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
