<HEADLINE>
CLASSIC CAR BUFF LORIN TRYON DIES AT 71 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MALCOLM GLOVER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Lorin H. Tryon Jr., one of the world's most
respected classic car aficionados and president of the renowned
Blackhawk Automotive Museum, died Feb. 12 of a heart attack at the
San Ramon Valley Medical Center. He was 71.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his association with the museum, which he was
credited with bringing into national prominence among classic car
enthusiasts, Mr. Tryon was best known worldwide for his leadership
of the prestigious Pebble Beach Concours d'Elegance.
</P>
<P>
   His fascination with automobiles began at an early age and was
fostered by his grandfather, who was one of California's first auto
dealers. At the age of seven, when he was barely big enough to see
over the hood and operate the clutch and brake, he operated his own
car wash at his family's home and drove the cars back and forth to
his customers.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Tryon, who was born in San Francisco in 1927, pioneered many
shows and judged others, both nationally and internationally. For
27 years, he had been the driving force in the revitalization and
popularity of the renowned Pebble Beach display of classic cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``The loss of Lorin Tryon, my friend for 40 years and my partner
at Pebble Beach for 27 years, cannot be filled,'' said J. Heumann,
his co-chairman at Pebble Beach. ``I will miss not only his
friendship and his humor, but above all, his incredible knowledge
of the collector car movement, resulting from an entire life
devoted to it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Lorin has been the guiding light for the Concours,'' said
executive director Sandra Kasky. ``He was more than just a leader,
he was a mentor and a friend who set exacting standards that we
eagerly tried to meet and will continue to strive toward in his
memory.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time of his death, he was involved in organizing the
inaugural international Automotive Design Forum at Blackhawk
scheduled to be held Aug. 31 and Sept. 1 at the museum.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Tryon is survived by his wife, Dolores, a son, Bill, and a
daughter, Catherine.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Memorial contributions in Lorin Tryon's memory may be made to
the Blackhawk Automotive Museum or to the American Heart
Association, 11200 Golf Links Road, Oakland, Calif. 94605.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
