<HEADER>
A7747 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-FEEDBACK-NYT &LR;      02-24 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-FEEDBACK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNUGGLING UP TO TOUCHY-FEELY MICE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Mass., Wash.)   (af)  
 By ANNE EISENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   How big are the files on your C drive? Soon you will be able to
give them a push with your mouse to find out. The bigger they are,
the more they will push back.
</P>
<P>
   And instead of peering at the menu bar, you will be able to move
your mouse across the mouse pad until you bump into the image you
want _ you will be able to locate icons by touch as easily as your
fingers find a light switch.
</P>
<P>
   The standard, sometimes maddening system that people use to
interact with their computers _ the graphical user interface, or
GUI _ is about to be broadened. In the jargon of researchers, the
new ``modality'' is called haptics, and it will let users reach out
to move, stroke and push virtual objects on their screens and
``feel'' those objects under their hands.
</P>
<P>
   The word haptics comes from the Greek word ``haptein,'' for ``to
fasten.'' Some video games let players experience simple examples
of haptics; through force feedback, players can feel shudders and
jolts through joysticks and steering wheels that are linked to
virtual activities like driving vehicles with high-torque motors.
</P>
<P>
   Now haptics technology is poised to move from the joys of the
game arcade to the sober tasks of the desktop. Manufacturers hope
that the new devices will satisfy the need for the tactile in a
variety of ways, from the mouse that lets users ``finger'' the
fabric of a T-shirt advertised on the Web to handheld, pen-size
instruments that will let artists mold virtual clay or let
apprentice doctors practice palpating their virtual patients.
</P>
<P>
   At the Immersion Corp. in San Jose, Calif., which licenses
force-feedback technology, the company's president, Dr. Louis B.
Rosenberg, is applying Immersion's patented haptic technology to
trackballs, mice and other cursor-control devices. ``Our mission as
a company is to add feel to every desktop on the planet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Immersion has licensed its ``feelit'' technology to Logitech, a
manufacturer of computer pointing devices, which plans to introduce
a haptic device by late summer, Rosenberg said. It will cost about
$125.
</P>
<P>
   Will users be able to feel a texture as subtle as corduroy using
haptic devices? Margaret Minsky, a haptics consultant in Brookline,
Mass., who did her PhD dissertation on the simulation of textured
surfaces, said force-feedback devices could be surprisingly
effective. ``For corduroy, the devices modulate resistance at such
a fine scale that you are able to perceive tiny variations in the
surface,'' she said. ``But they aren't up to velvet yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Mice work in the two-dimensional world of flat surfaces, moving
left and right, and forward and back. Some high-end commercial
applications of haptics mimic three dimensions, allowing users to
hold slender rods in the air and move them to and fro to create
virtual paintings, music or surgical stitches.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert Playter, vice president for engineering at Boston
Dynamics in Cambridge, Mass., has worked on a number of haptic
simulators that he hopes will soon be on apprentice surgeon's
desks, permitting them to reach into virtual patients to practice
grasping and cutting spongy, slippery virtual organs before they
move on to the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctor holds an actual forceps in one hand and a needle
holder in the other,'' Playter said, describing one of the
company's simulation systems. Looking at the computer monitor while
moving the instruments in thin air, the doctor punctures the
virtual vessel, pulls the thread through, grabs the other vessel
and sews the two vessels together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the haptic feedback, you can feel the needle pop
through as you sew, and how tightly you are pulling on the
thread,'' Playter said.
</P>
<P>
   The forceps and needle holder of the Boston Dynamics system are
attached to a machine called the Phantom. Sold by Sensable
Technologies, based in Cambridge, the Phantom can measure not only
the location of the actual thread holder but also its angle _ handy
when it comes to sewing imaginary sutures.
</P>
<P>
   The desktop version of the Phantom, released in late 1998 and
priced at about $10,000, looks like a desk lamp on the outside. On
the inside, it is mechanically similar to a small, friendly robot:
optical devices mounted on three motors determine the position of
the tip of each instrument.
</P>
<P>
   For force feedback, torque from the motors is transmitted
through a cable to the tip of the device, changing the amount of
resistance the user feels while moving the instruments.
</P>
<P>
   The Phantom underlies some haptics applications that are
gradually emerging from research laboratories, many for
rehabilitative medicine or computer-assisted design for
engineering.
</P>
<P>
   At the Boeing Co. in Bellevue, Wash., for instance, Bill McNeely
hopes to use the Phantom to help improve airplane designs. Boeing,
like many manufacturers, does digital rather than actual full-size
mock-ups of its planes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to figure out maintenance for a virtual airplane,''
McNeely said. ``Without the sense of touch, you don't know when
your elbow is crashing into a virtual bulkhead.'' Force feedback
lets McNeely know if machinery will be accessible once it is
installed. ``Anyone who's twisted and turned to get an oil filter
out of the engine block knows the problems of removing objects from
a narrow, confined space,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The underpinnings of haptics technology are not new. Dr. Kenneth
Salisbury, a principal research scientist at the Artificial
Intelligence Lab at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology and
co-inventor of the Phantom, said the decades-old technology had
arisen partly as an offshoot of robotics interfaces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, one of the key problems was manipulating
hazardous materials at a distance,'' he said. In response,
researchers developed robot arms controlled by joysticks. ``They
developed force feedback so the operators could feel when they hit
an object,'' Salisbury said.
</P>
<P>
   In the past 10 years, research in haptics has accelerated,
moving closer to commercial applications, Dr. Minsky said.
``Graphics can tell us something is made of cloth, leather or wood,
but reaching out and touching is believing,'' she said. ``Haptics
satisfies one of our most basic human needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Jaron Lanier, the computer scientist who coined the term virtual
reality, agreed that haptics interfaces with virtual reality would
one day become common but said that would take awhile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Force feedback isn't just a way of organizing graphical
information, but a whole new modality, so it won't happen
tomorrow,'' he said. ``But inevitably we will make use of touch
because humans have haptic capability, and the best tools for us
are based on how our bodies work. Haptics is going to happen to us
all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
