<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CEMETERY-HISPANICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CEMETERY TO REMOVE FENCE THAT OFFENDED HISPANICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN MacCORMACK  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Members of a cemetery association in a rural South
Texas town voted to remove a recently-installed fence that divided
the white and Hispanic sections of the burial ground and threatened
to sour ethnic harmony.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the vote, the association's president, E.A.
Murff, who is credited with erecting the fence, resigned. His wife,
the group's secretary-treasurer, also quit.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Salge of the Waldheim Cemetery Association, which
maintains the white portion of the burial ground, said the vote to
remove the fence was 22-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``The community wants this settled peacefully and for everyone
to go back to their normal routine and peaceful obscurity. We want
to put this thing to bed,'' said Salge, a Bee County farmer whose
grandparents and parents are buried in the Waldheim Cemetery 3
miles outside of Tynan, which has a population of 175 and one
blinking yellow traffic light.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot chain-link fence was erected three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We laughed about it. I stood there and shook my head and said,
`Why do that?' It's ridiculous, and it looks exclusionary,'' said
Carol Polasek, 62, a resident of the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I saw it, I said, `This is trouble. We don't need
this,' ... There are local farmers who are willing to donate their
tractors to tear this fence down,'' she said by telephone Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   And trouble quickly arrived in this farming community where
white and Hispanic residents live in harmony.
</P>
<P>
   But the tranquility was disturbed recently because of news media
attention and when a Hispanic group threatened to file a civil
rights complaint with the U.S. Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few people did this, and it just put a bad reflection on
everybody, the whole town,'' said Margie Jostes, whose family
members are buried in the 4-acre Waldheim Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a community that gets along real good,'' Jostes said.
``This is modern times, and you just don't do a thing like that.''
</P>
<P>
   For most of this century, whites were buried in one section of
the Waldheim Cemetery and Hispanics in another, and until last
month when the fence was erected, no one thought anything of it.
</P>
<P>
   For Hispanics, who are accustomed to using a road through the
white section during wet weather for burial ceremonies, the fence
represented both a real inconvenience and a symbolic slight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not fighting to be buried on their side. That isn't the
issue. The issue was dividing the cemetery,'' said Diane Cavazos
Taylor, whose father maintained the Hispanic section for many
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to be able to use that road for funerals, and in my
opinion, the main reason that fence was put up was to keep us from
using that road,'' Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   She said if there must be a fence, it should enclose the entire
cemetery. And, she said, Hispanic residents are willing to do their
part.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're willing to put up the money to fence in the rest of it.
Our main goal is to tear down that middle fence, not to divide the
cemetery,'' Taylor said.
</P>
<P>
   Murff declined to comment on the issue before the Tuesday night
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   In earlier statements, Murff said the fence was erected to keep
out vandals and cattle, but since the fence gate is not locked, it
would pose little barrier to intruders.
</P>
<P>
   The American G.I. Forum, a Hispanic veterans' organization, was
quick to respond to the barrier. At a memorial service Sunday,
wreathes for Hispanic veterans were placed on their graves, but
those for white veterans were laid against the fence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
