``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF SUN., MARCH 7, 1999) &QL; 
 &UR; By EVERETT POTTER &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seasoned bargain hunters know that spring is the most affordable
time of the year to ski. When the daffodils are pushing through the
lawn and dedicated skiers are turning to boating and baseball, ski
areas find themselves with a surplus of snow and vacant condos.
Consequently, the discount ski season begins _ around the third
week of March _ in a last ditch attempt to garner maximum revenue
from empty hotel and condo rooms before the season's unofficial
last hurrah at Easter.
</P>
<P>
   But this ski season has been a particularly slow one, with good
snow arriving later than usual in much of the Rockies and the
Northeast. Smart skiers should be on the lookout for even deeper
discounts than normal. Prices will dip around the end of March and
then fall off after Easter, which is April 4 this year. That's when
reductions of 20 to 40 percent occur, with 50 percent off sales.
But remember _ prices fall at different times at different resorts.
Even within a resort, the discounting isn't always uniform.
</P>
<P>
   To take optimum advangtage of this year's spring skiing bonanza,
it pays to be flexible. Shop around, go where the empty rooms are
and keep an eye out for inexpensive airline tickets. To find the
cheapest seats, look to hub cities like Denver, which has a surfeit
of United flights, or Salt Lake City, which is well served by
Delta. Smaller ski town airports may pose problems _ there are
often fewer flights. And the smaller planes having access to these
mountain resorts may not reduce their prices substantially.
</P>
<P>
   Budget-minded skiers should consider a condo or hotel that isn't
``ski-in/ski-out.'' Accomdations located a short walk or a shuttle
bus ride away from the slopes may offer lower lodging costs. So can
staying outside the resort. Skiers heading to Purgatory can
economize by staying down the road in Durango. In Vail and Beaver
Creek, West Vail and Avon offer cheaper choices. Some skiers opt to
stay in discounted lodging in Salt Lake City and take the bus up to
Snowbird or Alta. Thanks to the strong U.S. dollar, Canada also
looms large as ski heaven for those on a budget. Whether its Lake
Louise, Whistler or Tremblant, rates drop precipitously.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, spring skiing is perfect for impulsive skiers. Call up
a ski tour operator, a central reservations office or check out a
Website to compare snow conditions and check out any condos
available for the upcoming weekend. The East has plenty of good
deals to be grabbed at the last-minute. So is the West, although
flying makes it a bit more complicated. When there's air involved,
the ideal minimum amount of time for last-minute Western ski trips,
from either the East or West Coast, is three days.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at some deals for Spring 1999. Prices are per
person, based on double occupancy.
</P>
<P>
   At Vermont's Stratton Mountain (RR1 Box 145, Stratton Mountain,
Vt. 05155; 800-STRATTON; www.stratton.com), a two-night package
with slope side lodging that includes two days of lift tickets
ranges from $98 to $198 per person. This deal begins March 26 and
is available any day of the week.
</P>
<P>
   At Maine's Sugarloaf/USA (RR 1, Box 5000, Carrabassett Valley,
ME 04947 800-THE LOAF; www.sugarloaf.com ), the week-day price is
$59.95 per person per night and includes accommodation in an
on-mountain condo, lift ticket and a 90-minute ``Perfect Turn
Clinic.'' Guests can also use the Sugarloaf/
</P>
<P>
   USA Sports and Fitness Center.
</P>
<P>
   At Colorado's Steamboat Springs, spring skiers can get mid-week
round-trip airfare to Hayden, transfers, five nights lodging at the
Harbor Hotel and Condominiums, a four-day lift ticket and taxes for
$789 from New York, $699 from Chicago, $819 from Miami and $729
(midweek only) from Los Angeles. Contact Moguls (Moguls Ski and
Snowboard Tours, Inc., 4876 Sterling Dr. Boulder, CO 80301;
800-666-4857; www.skimoguls.com).
</P>
<P>
   At Vail, the Lodge at Vail (174 East Gore Creek Dr., Vail, CO
81657, 800-830-SNOW) is one of the most luxurious ski properties in
the West. Look for a mid-week deal for $219 per room, per night _
good until April 1. The price is based on a Sunday or Monday
arrival and a three-night minimum stay is required.
</P>
<P>
   In Breckenridge, a spring skiing package beginning April 6,
includes round-trip airfare based on mid-week flights, an
intermediate-size car rental, five nights of lodging at the
Breckenridge Mountain Lodge, a four-day lift ticket and taxes. The
price is $739 from New York, $649 from Chicago, $759 from Miami and
$679 from Los Angeles. Contact Moguls Ski and Snowboard Tours, Inc.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ---- &QL; 
 &UR; Copyright 1999 Everett Potter &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL;
</P>
