<HEADLINE>
THE MATURE TRAVELER 
 CHINA SENIOR TOURS AND MORE
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature culled from The
New York Times Syndicate's ``Way To Go!'' travel package _ the rate
is not prohibitive _ contact DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at (732)
390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------FREE ART!---------------------
</P>
<P>
   ONE COLOR SLIDE is available by mail (or overnight delivery,
using your FedEx or Airborne delivery number) AT NO EXTRA CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. Please specify that you want the art
when you order the article.
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   (Our sales staff also has information on how to subscribe to
``WAY TO GO,'' a versatile package of six travel stories a week,
including Q&AMP;A travel tips and ``The Mature Traveler'' column.
Sources include The New York Times Sunday travel section and
leading travel writers. HERE'S AN OFFER YOU CAN'T REFUSE: TRY A
FREE TRIAL OF THE ``WAY TO GO!'' PACKAGE AND SEE FOR YOURSELF HOW
IT CAN ENHANCE YOUR PAGES!)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; Free to clients of Way to Go! &QL; 
 &UR; (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF SUN., MARCH 7, 1999) &QL; 
 &UR; Color slide included. &QL; 
 &UR; By GENE AND ADELE MALOTT &QL; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since 1999 has been declared the ``Year of the Elderly'' by the
United Nations, the University of Senior Citizens in China has
developed a special ten-day cultural tour of China with a focus on
senior-to-senior relations between U.S. and Chinese citizens.
Starting April 19, the trip offers unique opportunities to visit
the homes of Chinese seniors, explore styles of Chinese cuisine,
discover Chinese seniors' methods for dealing with longevity _
including Tai Chi _ and enjoy entertainment such as the Beijing
Opera. The university is similar to a community college but is
devoted exclusively to seniors, with classes ranging from brush
painting to photography.
</P>
<P>
   Stops on the 10-day tour will include the Forbidden City, Great
Wall, Summer Palace and Chinese villages and farms. The price _
excluding airfare _ is $1,288 and includes all meals, transfers,
tours and admissions. For information contact Kentours Wholesale
Ltd at (800) 387-2615, or visit the website at
www.china-hiking.com/seniortour.htm.
 &UR; FLORIDA DISCOUNTS LURE SENIORS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Orchids &AMP; Egrets Everglades Ecotours, based in Naples, gives
AARP members ten percent discounts April 30 through Dec. 15 on its
eight-day ``Trail of the Panther'' ecological study tour and
day-long wilderness tours.
</P>
<P>
   The Panther tour includes Sanibel and Captiva islands and
originates in Miami or Fort Myers. It offers a swim with dolphins
at Key Largo and kayak and boat tours through mangrove swamps,
animal rehabilitation centers and wildlife protection areas. Study
endangered species like the manatee and learn about the
environmental impact of public projects on local habitats. Regular
tour price starts at $1,695 (PP/double), for AARP and CARP members
is $1,525.
</P>
<P>
   Other Orchids &AMP; Egrets day-tours honoring the 10 percent AARP
discount include a trip through the western Everglades (regularly
$80); ``Swampwalk'' through the heart of the Everglades (reg. $66);
and Sanibel Island (reg. $80). For information contact your travel
agent or Orchids &AMP; Egrets Everglades Ecotours, 238 Silverado Dr.,
Naples, FL 34119; call (941) 352-8586.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers ages 55 and over save $17 to $39 a night_ about 15
percent off _ on private-pool homes managed by U.S. Holidays
International in the Orlando area. Contact U.S. Holidays
International, Inc., 4636 W. Orlando Bronson Hwy., Kissimmee, FL
34746; call (407) 397-2247.
</P>
<P>
   Peabody Orlando hotel continues its ``Seniors are Extra
Special'' $110-a room deal through 1999, giving travelers ages 55
and over more than half off rooms regularly ranging up to $320 a
night. Call (800) 732-2639.
</P>
<P>
   Holiday Inn/Main Gate East Hotel &AMP; Suites in Kissimmee gives
travelers ages 55 and over $79-$99 rooms for $49. Ask for the R49
or the Senior Fund Club package. (800) 366-5437.
 &UR; SWISSOTEL SPECIALS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Five Swisstels in the U.S. are offering mature travelers a
minimum 30 percent discount on properties located in Atlanta (one
block from Lenox Square), Boston (one block from Boston Common),
Chicago (with Sears Tower and the Art Institute nearby), N.Y.'s The
Drake (walking distance to Broadway) and Washington, D.C.'s The
Watergate (near the White House and Kennedy Center for the
Performing Arts).
</P>
<P>
   To qualify, you must be 60 years or older or a member of AARP
and make your reservation in advance. Children under 17 accompanied
by a senior can stay free in the guest's room. The regular rate at
Swisstel Atlanta, for example, is $200-$300 per room, per night,
while a mature traveler would pay just $125. Call your travel agent
or Swisstel at (888) 737-9477 or visit the website at
http://swissotel.com.
 &UR; SCANDINAVIAN CRUISES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fred Olsen Lines' Black Watch from Dover, England, to Norway and
the Baltic offer three ``SeniorSaver'' cruises for travelers ages
55 and over, and their companions of any age.
</P>
<P>
   Nine-day cruises to Norway and the fjords depart May 22 and June
17 from New York, cost seniors $2,635 in lowest outside cabin,
regularly $3,185. Lowest outside cabin for the 16-day Baltic
capitals tour departing July 17, regularly $4,520, costs mature
travelers $3,670. Prices include round-trip airfare.
</P>
<P>
   Book through your travel agent or EuroCruises, (800) 661-1119
for brochures, (800) 688-3876 for reservations; or check the
website, www.eurocruises.com.
 &UR; RAFTING THE SALMON &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Warren River Expeditions offers nine white-water rafting trips
for travelers ages 55 and over, and two expeditions for
grandparents with their grandkids. The six-day lodge-to-lodge
trips, on the Main Fork of Idaho's Salmon River, are limited to 16
rafters each.
</P>
<P>
   The lodges are rustic, and while you may have individual rooms,
sometimes you'll share with other guests. The guided trips feature
hiking, historic talks, fishing, swimming and kayaking. All trips
begin at Salmon, ID.
</P>
<P>
   Trips cost $1,525 a person, plus taxes. 10 percent discount for
ages 55 and over including ``Seniors Only'' trips. Contact Warren
River Expeditions, P.O. Box 1375, Salmon, ID 83467; call (800)
765-0421; or check the website at www.raftidaho.com.
 &UR; MIDNIGHT SUN VOYAGE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Senior discounts from $90 to $220 are available most of the year
for travelers ages 67 and over on the Bergen Line's Norwegian
Coastal Voyage, a 1,250-mile cruise along Norway's west coast.
</P>
<P>
   Fares through October 1999 for outside cabins range from $844 to
$1,702/double for the seven-day trip originating from Bergen. Call
(800) 323-7436 for information or visit the website:
www.bergenline.com
 &UR; GET UP AND GO! &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For mature travelers it's the best time of life to get up and
go! Remember to always ask for the senior-citizen discount, even if
it's not posted. That's one of the privileges of being among the
``chronologically gifted'' who are 50 or over.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ----- &QL;
</P>
