<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 17:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7779 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EMOTIONAL-INTELLIGENC     02-24 1336
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMOTIONAL-INTELLIGENCE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEELINGS VS. BRAINPOWER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (To publish this ``separate buy'' article, it must be purchased
_ the rate is not prohibitive _ from one of these New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives: 
 &HT;    (--U.S., Canada and the Pacific: CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at
1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or fax her at 816-822-1444. 
 &HT;    (--Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-996-0075;
fax, 310-996-0089. 
 &HT;    
 By JEFF GREENWALD  
 FROM: Wired  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 World rights excluding Japan  
 &HT;    What a trick of fate: The way to get ahead in the age of the
knowledge worker is not through raw brainpower, but by harnessing
your emotions.
 &HT;    Daniel Goleman, a Harvard-trained psychologist and former New
York Times science writer, turned this idea into a household phrase
with his 1995 blockbuster ``Emotional Intelligence.'' A primer on
the art _ and science _ of self-mastery and social persuasion, the
book remains an international best-seller, now translated into 30
or so languages. At the time of this interview it was topping the
charts in Turkey.
 &HT;    Goleman's follow-up volume _ ``Working with Emotional
Intelligence'' (Bantam, 1998) _ goes even further, providing a kind
of moral philosophy for corporate America. His thesis: In today's
technical fields, you need a highly developed set of soft
(emotional) skills to leverage your hard (knowledge-based)
expertise.
 &HT;    Now CEO of the consulting firm Emotional Intelligence Services
(www.eisglobal.com/), Goleman seems to be walking the talk; let him
know what you think at goleman javanet.com.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    JEFF GREENWALD: The mythical hero of Silicon Valley is the nerd
_ a brain trapped inside a geeky-looking body. Your research
suggests otherwise.
 &HT;    DANIEL GOLEMAN: The stereotype of the tech expert with no social
skills may be accurate. And I used to think these two factors were
independent. But friends at places like MIT argue that people drawn
into the technical fields spend many hours _ particularly in
adolescence _ alone, absorbed at the computer, or in a lab.
 &HT;    As they're increasing their technical understanding in math and
science, they're missing out on a parallel track of social
learning. They become emotionally de-skilled, and that pulls them
back later in their careers.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: The person who seems to belie this point of view is Bill
Gates, who by external appearances is almost autistic. He's hardly
what anyone would call a failure.
 &HT;    A: Gates is a fascinating case. He has a fabulous drive to
achieve, and that reverberates throughout his company. On the other
hand, he's notorious for the worst of emotional intelligence. He
yells, he's abrasive, and he doesn't seem to care how he's coming
off. If he were starting at the bottom _ if the playing field were
level for Gates _ he's not the guy you would pick to lead a team.
He'd work for you, not run you.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: So what's the role of technical skill?
 &HT;    A: It's an entry-level requirement. You have to have enough to
do the job _ but it's not what sets star performers apart. A
University of California/Berkeley study, started in the 1950s,
followed a group of Ph.D. students in science and the technical
fields for 40 years. It turned out emotional-intelligence abilities
were four times more important than IQ in determining professional
success and prestige by the end of their careers.
 &HT;    And in a study of managers who failed, it was always because of
a deficiency of emotional intelligence.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Does our penchant for smartcards, smart homes, and PDAs
encourage emotional intelligence in society, or impede it?
 &HT;    A: The early returns show a negative impact, particularly as it
affects kids _ the average level of emotional intelligence has been
declining among young people for the last 20 years. This generation
spends more time than any generation in history staring at video
monitors. It doesn't matter if they're doing educational CD-ROMs;
they're not out playing with other kids.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: What about the workplace?
 &HT;    A: The increasing reliance on communication via the Web and
e-mail _ if it replaces human touchpoints _ weakens the fabric of
connectedness that makes a company or organization work. That's why
emotional intelligence is so important in the high tech universe.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: How does emotional intelligence apply to people like Oracle's
Larry Ellison who are more inspired by the Japanese ``warrior
mentality''?
 &HT;    A: Samurai were Zen students _ they engaged more skillfully
because they cultivated inner peace. Emotional intelligence is
about being skillful, not squishy.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: What's today's most emotionally intelligent technology?
 &HT;    A: The MIT Media Lab's Roz Picard, who wrote a book about 2001's
HAL 9000, is investigating computers that can read emotions in the
user and adjust themselves accordingly. If you're frantic and
uptight, they can make things easier. If you're enthusiastic and
zeroed in, they'll up the level of challenge. They're user-friendly
in the real sense of the word _ which means they're emotionally
intelligent, for machines.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: It's one thing to program a computer; how about humans?
 &HT;    A: Competency in emotional intelligence is learnable. In
``Working with Emotional Intelligence,'' I set out guidelines for
training programs designed to make people better on the job, where
the payoff is. A lot of programs out there _ such as these one-day
motivational seminars, or doing ropes courses in the countryside _
have little, no, or even a negative effect. Companies are wasting a
lot of time and money on inappropriate solutions.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Could good training rescue a troubled company _ say, Apple?
 &HT;    A: Emotional intelligence is not the answer to every problem
faced by an organization. There are market realities. But how well
you face a market reality is determined by emotional intelligence.
Andy Grove, writing about Intel, makes a good point: The critical
thing is how managers respond emotionally to a crisis. So often
people panic, deny the crisis _ or kill the messenger. A company
has to be open to bad news, take it in fully, and respond quickly.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: What about other traditions that have a different way of
dealing with emotions?
 &HT;    A: In many Asian cultures you squelch expressions of emotion,
particularly of negative emotion _ which means that people are
getting eaten up inside without showing it. But I was amazed at
Asia's interest in emotional intelligence. In Taiwan, ``Emotional
Intelligence'' is the best-selling book of all time. In Korea,
they're starting to put emotional intelligence curricula in the
schools. ``We're very taken by the West,'' they told me, ``and very
influenced by your ideas and technologies. And here is Western
science affirming our most deeply held values.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Is emotional intelligence sort of bottom-line Buddhism?
 &HT;    A: It's very interesting. Buddhists read ``Emotional
Intelligence'' that way. Christians tell me it's about
Christianity. And Jews tell me it's a great book about Judaism. It
may in that way reflect what Huxley called ``the perennial
philosophy,'' which itself reflects the basic neurological
structures that govern human existence.
 &HT;    My work is grounded in science, particularly neurological
science. Apparently the eternal questions all the great religions
are grappling with are the legacy of evolution: What do you do with
destructive emotions? How can you live a good life, and have
healthy connections to other people? How can you help future
generations?
 &HT;     (c.1999 Conde Nast Publications Inc.) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Jeff Greenwald is the author of ``Future Perfect: How Star
Trek Captured Planet Earth.'') &LR;
</P>
