<SLUG> BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Q &AMP; A: CAPTURING THAT SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Please note that the word AT within parentheses has been
used in the end note instead of the symbol, which is
non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
(mk) 
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I want to put a picture of my band's Web page in our flier.
How can I take a picture of the screen so I can use it with
Microsoft Word?
</P>
<P>
   A. What you want is often called a screen grab or screen shot.
True to its name, it is a picture of exactly what was on your
screen at the time. There are slightly different ways to get a
screen grab, depending on which platform you are using, but here
are the basic steps:
</P>
<P>
   If you are using Windows 95 or 98 and have the image you want to
capture on the screen, press the Alt key along with the Print
Screen key (found in the top row of the keyboard). Pressing
Alt-Print Screen will capture the active window, and pressing just
Print Screen takes a picture of the entire desktop. Go to, in
order, your Start menu, Programs and Accessories, then to the Paint
program that comes with Windows. Open a new Paint window and press
Control-V to paste the picture into the window. You can crop it if
you want to and save it as a bitmap picture file, which can be
pasted into Microsoft Word or any word processor that allows you to
embed graphics in a document. These files can also be attached to
e-mail messages.
</P>
<P>
   If you are using a Macintosh, press Shift-Command-3 when you see
the screen image you want to capture. You will hear a click, and a
file in PICT format called Picture 1 will appear on the top level
of your hard drive. You can open the file and drag the mouse over
the area you want; press Command-C and then Command-V to paste the
selected portion into the Word document.
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
postal mail to Questions, Circuits, The New York Times, 229 W. 43rd
St., New York, N.Y. 10036-3959, or by e-mail to
QandA(AT)nytimes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
