<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRAFT-DESIGN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CONTRADICTION NO LONGER: STYLISH CRAFTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By WILLIAM L. HAMILTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There are 13 million people in the United States
making crafts to sell, and over a billion dollars being spent in
the process. This could be construed as very bad news.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the most recent craft production is more beautiful and
more technically sophisticated than it has been for 30 years _
since the heyday of American craft artists like George Nakashima
and Gertrude and Otto Natzler, the glittering era of modern Italian
art glass or the British studio pottery tradition of Lucie Rie.
</P>
<P>
   You can skip the hippies. Contemporary crafts _ that wide, vague
world of handmade ceramic, glass, wood, metal and fiber work _ are
no longer exclusively the countercultural mud cakes or the
whirly-twirly, funkadelic, post-modern confetti of the 1960s
through the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Crafts have become design conscious _ and the design market has
taken notice. From Barry Friedman Ltd., the East Side Manhattan art
and design gallery, to small downtown shops, crafts are being
included in a stylish vocabulary of modern furniture and
contemporary decorative objects. They enjoy a new peaceful
coexistence with home design. Think of them as ``contemporary
decorative arts.'' Or studio art, functional sculpture, painterly
vessels _ any of the phrases galleries and museums use to elude the
term ``crafts,'' which has an earthy, lingering stink.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been almost a taboo about objects made by
craftspeople,'' said William Georgis, an architect in New York
City. Georgis and his partner, Richard Marshall, a curator, collect
crafts, contemporary art and mid-century modern furniture. ``But
it's breaking down,'' he said. ``For me they're very appealing.
There's not the snobbery of an art object. They're functional
objects artfully made.''
</P>
<P>
   At Shi, a shop in the Noho section of Manhattan, handmade
ceramics like tea bowls and plates in a range between $12 to $60
are selling more strongly than production wares, to people who are
not collectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not suggesting a crafts look,'' said Laurie McLendon,
Shi's owner. ``But the more educated people become now about design
and style, the more confident they become. You were going to do
Russel Wright dinnerware, now you do something less recognizable,
with a handmade piece. There aren't thousands of them out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Olnick, who with her husband, Giorgio Spanu, collects
paintings, Art Deco furniture by Jean-Michel Frank and others, and
Italian glass by Carlo Scarpa, has also begun to buy contemporary
craft pieces, including glass by Yoichi Ohira, whose work ranges in
the thousands of dollars, and basketwork by Masako Maki, whose work
stays largely in the hundreds.
</P>
<P>
   ``If something attracts you, you should let yourself love it and
learn about it,'' she said. ``There's a workmanship that's
incredible, but a simplicity that makes you feel the designer
hasn't overworked it. That's what appeals to me about the Maki
basket, the Ohira glass and the Art Deco furniture _ they're basic,
uncomplicated, but you also see the hand of the artist.''
</P>
<P>
   Spanu explained that ``we never buy a piece without bringing it
into the house and living with it, to see the connections.'' He
added that collecting contemporary crafts could still be expensive,
frustrating pearl-diving. ``What keeps people out of the field is
the prices,'' he said. ``The bad work costs as much as the good.''
</P>
<P>
   But William Lipton, a New York Chinese antiques dealer who has
exhibited Ms. Maki's work, was optimistic about the expanding
choice among less expensive, more handsome objects. ``You have to
edit,'' he said. ``But $18,000 objects aside, these contemporary
forms can be quite reasonable, and are now easier to take a chance
with.'' Lipton said that he thought understatement, not notably
present in the contemporary crafts movement, had quietly entered
the field and was attracting new admirers.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the thaw is the interest in mid-century modern design,
first fashionable, now popular.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nineteen-fifties environments were very rich with craft,''
said Paola Antonelli, an associate curator in the Museum of Modern
Art's department of architecture and design. ``The quintessential
1950s environment, the Ray and Charles Eames house, is a
celebration of craft intermingled with design.''
</P>
<P>
   Liz O'Brien, the owner of 41, a New York modern design gallery,
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Craft was the detail of modernism that gave it depth _ the
textiles, the ceramics,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Lui, a mid-century modern collector in Tarzana, Calif.,
said he began typically, with 1950s Italian and Scandinavian glass.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
