A7795 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TVSURFER-COLUMN25-COX     02-24 0426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TVSURFER-COLUMN25-COX' </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WB syndrome: Teens rule TV _ and how
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's been said to the point of hoarseness that Hollywood is just
like high school, only with more money. But this is getting
ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   Television's infatuation with adolescents is spreading like a
nasty rumor about the prom queen. The WB, which does the best job
of any network of getting teen buzz, is also the only network
growing in audience rather than shrinking, and don't think that
hasn't gone unnoticed. Then add to the mix the escalating emphasis
on feature films aimed at teens, such as the upcoming ``Cruel
Intentions'' (March 5), a movie that hasn't even opened yet and is
already being touted as a possible TV series.
</P>
<P>
   It's pilot season, when the prototypes for new series are shot,
and there are so many new youth-must-be-served shows in the works
for fall that Fox has taken the unusual step of holding open-call
auditions for anyone ages 15-21 in New York and Los Angeles _ no
experience necessary.
</P>
<P>
   It's still too early to tell what the fall schedule will look
like _ a network typically commissions two or three times as many
pilots as it takes to series _ but here's just a partial sampling
of what's in the works.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Cruel Intentions.'' Fox. The black comedy (see above) hasn't
even opened yet. The sex would have to be toned down considerably,
and the stars (Sarah Michelle Gellar, etc.) would be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Brookfield.'' ABC. Drama set in a boarding school; one of
the producers is a 22-year-old college student. Not to be confused
with the WB's ``Young Americans,'' about an all-boys prep school
battling a blue-collar school in the same town.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Opposite Sex.'' Fox. Three guys enroll in an all-girls
school. A sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Wasteland.'' ABC. Another drama by Kevin Williamson, creator
of ``Dawson's Creek'' and orignator of the new onslaught of teen
horror movies. This one would track six friends just out of
college.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Roswell High.'' Fox. A drama that ties together high school
life and the Roswell UFO crash, of course.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Freaks and Geeks.'' NBC. High school drama set in the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Brutally Normal.'' The WB. Another high school drama.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Carson's Vertical Suburbia.'' ABC (tentative title). Comedy
about a teen and his family in a Manhattan high-rise.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-99 1708EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990224.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7796 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CRAFT-DESIGN-ART-2NDT     02-24 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRAFT-DESIGN-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: Scandinavian glass.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I kind of poo-pooed the idea of contemporary glass,'' he
explained. ``Then I started to see classic, simple designs
appearing, and I went into it. My interest is design, not rarity.''
Lui added, though, that much contemporary glass, which he has
purchased within the last 10 years, including pieces by Richard
Posner and William Morris, was now getting expensive quickly in the
auction market. Lui has found newer names, like Toshio Iezumi, in
the Corning Museum's annual publication New Glass Review.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Friedman, who began showing crafts two years ago with an
exhibition of glass by Michael Glancy, is considered an important
pivot in the strategy to interest noncraft collectors in the genre.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea if the market would accept this idea,'' he said.
``My clients came in to see 1950s glass or furniture, but they
bought Glancy's work, too.'' Friedman now represents work by
Bennett Bean, a potter; Mike Shuler, a woodworker; Toots Zynsky, a
glass maker, and 17 other contemporary ``decorative artists,'' as
he calls them.
</P>
<P>
   A large part of the thaw is the quality of the new craft work,
at both ends, in galleries and in shops.
</P>
<P>
   ``The critical element has been missing, and the contemporary
craft world traditionally has not been too rigorous,'' said Susan
Cummins, who owns a craft gallery in Mill Valley, Calif. ``But
expertise has grown. The level of skill now is quite phenomenal.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to galleries that specialize in craft media, like
Elliot Brown in Seattle or Charles Cowles, Garth Clark and Nancy
Margolies in New York, galleries like Max Protetch now also exhibit
ceramics or glass next to painting and sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   Craft establishments like the American Craft Museum in New York,
the Smithsonian Institution's Renwick Gallery in Washington and the
new Mint Museum of Craft and Design, which opened last month in
Charlotte, N.C., must now compete with the Metropolitan Museum of
Art in New York for audiences. The Met currently has on view a
selection of contemporary ceramics, ``Clay into Art,'' through May
30th.
</P>
<P>
   ``Museums that heretofore have turned their noses up at things
made by hand _ L.A. County, Boston Fine Arts _ are including them
now,'' said Mark Leach, director of the Mint Museum of Craft and
Design. ``It's a way to bolster attendance and income. The public
has an enduring relationship with this area, the tactile world.
There's no intellectual substitution for wrapping your finger
around the handle of a coffee mug that's been exquisitely
designed.''
</P>
<P>
   But is craft art?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sort of tired of that battle,'' said Jane Adlin, the
curator of the ceramics show at the New York Metropolitan Museum of
Art. ``The idea is to get people in to see art. The process is less
important. It's like saying, `Did the artist use brush or a palette
knife?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Adlin made a salient point about the effect of the
definition to a prospective buyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nice thing about collecting crafts is that they're
generally affordable when they're called crafts,'' she said. ``The
minute you call it art, the price goes way beyond.''
</P>
<P>
   Craftspeople themselves can be the most reasonable about the
issue of what they produce.
</P>
<P>
   ``I make decorative, functional work,'' said Peter Lane, a New
York ceramicist. ``It's not sculpture. When contemporary
craftspeople move away from design into art _ and higher prices _
it creates a new category that I don't find appealing.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Bonner, a metalworker in Providence, R.I., said, ``I
know craftspeople who want to be recognized in the fine art world,
but for me it's not a criterion I worry about. I enjoy them both.
I'm not frustrated about how I'm being perceived.'' Bonner added,
``A craftsman has a better crack at making a living if he doesn't
have the best crack at the high end of fine art market.''
</P>
<P>
   Having fought the battle about whether they were art for the
last 25 years, contemporary craft now stands poised to fight the
battle of whether they're stylish design, in some ways a harder
fight to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Crafts?'' asked Brian Murphy, the vice president of
Parish-Hadley Associates, incredulously. ``You mean, those things
you see at crafts fairs?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Murphy, an interior designer, answered with a nervous
laugh. ``I never use it in my work.''
</P>
<P>
   Lipton said that his customers for craft objects were largely
adventurous collectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Designers have been reluctant to use them,'' he said. ``The
word `craft' doesn't sound chic enough yet.''
</P>
<P>
   But Calvin Tsao, a New York architect, finds handmade objects an
indispensable part of the language of interior design.
</P>
<P>
   ``Design is not just an intellectual exercise,'' he said. ``I
love crafts as daily objects. Good crafts deal with details of
humanity.'' Tsao's own collection at home includes pieces he has
found traveling; he will stop the car to visit a potter's studio by
the side of a highway, and buy an inexpensive bowl from an unknown
artist.
</P>
<P>
   For more serious modern design collectors, the big question will
be whether contemporary crafts can hold their value as the market
tries to develop in their direction. Auction houses have entered
the fray, including crafts in their decorative arts category.
Sotheby's sale on March 12 in New York will include 50 lots by
craft artists like Albert Paley, a contemporary metalworker.
</P>
<P>
   Up until now, the real safety _ whether investment or esthetics
_ has been in vintage pieces. Kim Hostler of Antik, a modern design
gallery in TriBeCa, made a decision not to show contemporary work.
``The attraction of vintage pieces is that you know you might be
paying a high, but fair, price,'' she said. ``There's value
established in the piece, and you can resell it. If you buy new
work, you're buying on a purely emotional level.''
</P>
<P>
   For collectors like Ms. Olnick and Spanu, though, that is the
essence of the enthusiasm of living with what they collect.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't play it safe,'' said Spanu. ``I must be driven by
the beauty of the piece. Whatever mistakes I've made, I've never
felt I've made a mistake in terms of the art of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
