<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7797 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX     02-24 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S TIME TO ABANDON RACIAL BIASES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leon Reed is a political science major who hopes to hold
political office.
</P>
<P>
   On this night, the 30-year-old Texas Christian University senior
is looking the part, dressed in a coat and tie with a closely
cropped haircut framing his narrow, dark-brown face.
</P>
<P>
   When he introduces Don Jackson, chairman of the TCU political
science department, he sounds the part as well. But this is not a
political rally. It is a meeting Reed has organized to inform some
fellow students, whose skin color has put them at the center of an
intensive manhunt by Fort Worth and campus police, of their rights.
</P>
<P>
   It would be easy to understand if Reed were indignant about the
way African-American males are being treated in the wake of a rash
of rapes around the college campus. Not only are police stopping
them, but officers are asking them for DNA samples, their shoe size
and their feelings about white people. Of the dozen or so black
students attending the meeting this night, half said they had been
stopped.
</P>
<P>
   What Reed finds most distressing is the enduring image of
African-American males as criminals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just one of those aspects of America you learn to deal
with,'' he said. ``But it gets to you after a while. You don't feel
like fighting it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed said that he and the other African-American males at TCU
are victims of a society that clings to this image, and of law
enforcement officials operating under the presumption of guilt. Not
innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rape is a heinous crime,'' he said recently. ``We kind of joke
among ourselves that whoever is doing this better hope the police
catch him before we do, because we're the ones suffering.''
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Jim Lankford, supervisor of the Fort Worth Police
Department's sex crimes unit, said that police are gathering more
evidence with each offense, but that no arrest is imminent.
</P>
<P>
   Four young women, mostly students living around TCU, were raped
between January and April last year, and one attempted sexual
assault was reported last year. Another young woman was raped last
month, two days before the spring semester began.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said the attacker usually entered the young
women's homes through open windows, concealed his face and
features, and covered the victims' eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that sketchy physical description, Lankford said, ``The
victims are telling us he's a black male.''
</P>
<P>
   And that alone, Reed said, has made him and other black students
targets in the investigation. Police, he said, have been stopping
them on traffic violations, and in some instances, have been
waiting outside their classrooms and making unexpected visits to
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Lankford said investigators are simply following leads.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as I know, we're not unfairly targeting anyone,'' he
said. ``We're just following up on tips and leads that we receive
and trying to either confirm or negate them as suspects. It's
usually because we have more information than `a black male in the
TCU area.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to know whether police have been operating within the
law without more information about each stop, said Jackson, who is
also an attorney for the American Civil Liberties Union. But this
much is certain: Police cannot legally stop a person simply because
his race matches that of a suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``To stop every black man in the neighborhood that fits the
description,'' said Jackson, ``is not sufficient.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the first time Fort Worth police have run their
investigations this way, targeting African-American men based on
such broad descriptions of suspects. But it ought to be the last.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, police were accused of singling out black men
during a two-day sweep for suspects in a rash of attacks on people
in their driveways.
</P>
<P>
   Police officers are given a gun, a badge and the authority to
stop and arrest people. That is tremendous power. The public,
however, has a right to expect them to use it wisely. Or at the
very least, lawfully.
</P>
<P>
   Despite prevailing attitudes, not every black male is Willie
Horton, the Massachusetts convict who was the subject of a
political ad campaign by former President Bush. Nothing, though,
seems to soften this image. Not time. Not the fact that most
African-Americans are law-abiding citizens sickened by crime as
much as whites are.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, this image has become a filter through which many
whites and some blacks perceive black men. That is why it was so
easy for us to believe people such as Charles Stuart and Susan
Smith, who blamed black men for murders they themselves committed.
</P>
<P>
   What disturbs me most about this attitude is how it has been
internalized by some law enforcement officers, the people we count
on for protection.
</P>
<P>
   It is understandable that police might look at any person and
suspect the worst. They deal with crime and violence every day. But
far too often with blacks, especially black men, the presumption is
``criminal'' until proved otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, most African-American men reject the life of crime,
have never committed an offense. And they deserve more than to be
eyed with suspicion just because of their skin color.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
