<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDEN Q&AMP;A: CLIVIA CARE, APPLES FROM SEEDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By DORA GALITZKI   
 c. 1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clivia Care
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a potted clivia at home that looks very healthy. I
have had it for two years, and it has grown sizably in that time. I
am waiting for it to bloom, but it seems that I will not be favored
with a single flower this year. Can you tell me how I can help it
to flower?
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have grown Clivia miniata for many years. Recently the
flower appeared, as always, but it never grew up and out of the
plant base. Why?
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a healthy clivia that produces many flowers and
seedpods. How should I treat the seeds in order to grow new
clivias?
</P>
<P>
   A. With strappy, glossy, dark evergreen leaves and an impressive
stalk topped by a cluster of red-orange, sometimes yellow,
trumpetlike flowers, Clivia miniata is an old favorite with
houseplant lovers. But we sometimes forget that nature didn't
design it to live in a heated house and that it thrives best when
conditions are reasonably close to those in its native South
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   To bloom, a clivia needs to be on an annual cycle of warm and
cool temperatures. Starting in late October or November, the
temperature of the room should be kept at about 50 degrees
Fahrenheit, day and night, for eight to 10 weeks. During this time,
growth slows down, so reduce watering, although it is best not to
let the soil become completely dry. Flower stalks that never fully
elongate are a sign that the cooling period was not long enough or
cool enough. After the cooling period, keep clivias at 65 degrees
or warmer. They should bloom in March or April.
</P>
<P>
   Once the berries, or seedpods, have turned shiny red, remove
their seeds. Just barely cover the seeds with a well-draining
potting medium, kept moist but not wet. Then, grab a thick book and
wait. The seeds can take months to germinate. When they do, place
the seedlings in bright light (but out of direct sun), and go back
to the book. If you're careful and do a good job, it shouldn't take
more than three or four years before your new clivia is ready to
bloom.
</P>
<P>
   Apples From Seed
</P>
<P>
   Q. I wish to grow trees from the seeds of the apples I buy. I
have tried several times, with different varieties, but none have
germinated. Please tell me how to germinate and grow them. And at
what size and age can the young trees be planted outdoors?
</P>
<P>
   A. The seeds in an apple are part of life's lottery: a genetic
mix that is half the tree they grew on and half whatever apple tree
the bee happened to visit last. As in any lottery, there are more
losers than winners, and your future apples are not likely to meet
your expectations, but hey, you never know.
</P>
<P>
   Fair warning given, there are two steps before planting your
seeds. First, apple seeds, like many others, need a cold period,
called stratification, before they will germinate: 60 days in a
damp paper towel or sphagnum peat moss in the refrigerator (not
freezer) should do it. Second, apple seeds are coated with a
chemical that inhibits germination. Normally this would come off
when the seeds spend a little time in a digestive tract. So after
the cold period, wrap the seeds in cheesecloth, soak them for an
hour, and rinse, using hot water 100 to 110 degrees. Repeat the
soak-and-rinse several times.
</P>
<P>
   Place the prepared seeds in a damp paper towel in a plastic bag
in light, but not in direct sun. They should germinate in about a
week. Plant three or four of the germinated seeds a half-inch deep
in a 6-inch pot, and keep the seedlings in full sun indoors until
after all danger of frost is past. At the latest, plan your timing
so that the seedlings will be outside by midsummer and have time to
harden off before winter.
</P>
<P>
   Leave the pot in the ground until next spring, when the
seedlings can be transplanted to your future orchard site (better
mark them so that no one steps on them). Assuming you have a
compatible tree for cross-pollination, you'll have apples four to
10 years later _ and finally see if you've won the lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Address questions to Garden Q&AMP;A, The New York Times, 229 West
43rd St., New York, NY 10036, or by e-mail to
gardening(AT)nytimes.com. Those of general interest will be
published. Unpublished questions cannot be answered individually.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
