<HEADLINE>
EDITORS: 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Wednesday, Feb. 24, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file this additional story for
Thursday in the ``w'' and ``f'' categories:    (``HNS'' appears in
all slug lines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Y2K-LITIGATION (Washington) _ Sens. Dianne Feinstein and Orrin
G. Hatch on Wednesday introduced legislation to limit lawsuits
stemming from the Y2K computer problem, mainly by giving companies
90 days to fix any glitches. Economists have warned of serious
economic problems starting Jan. 1, 2000, if computers crash or
malfunction because they were not programmed to recognize dates
beyond 1999. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service/Washington
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-99 1716EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990224.0230 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 17:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7824 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-LITIGATION-HNS &LR;      02-24 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-LITIGATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILL WOULD CURB Y2K LAWSUITS BY GRANTING 90-DAY GRACE PERIOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Filed in ``w'' and ``f'' categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sens. Dianne Feinstein and Orrin G. Hatch on
Wednesday introduced legislation to limit lawsuits stemming from
the Y2K computer problem, mainly by giving companies 90 days to fix
any glitches.
</P>
<P>
   Economists have warned of serious economic problems starting
Jan. 1, 2000, if computers crash or malfunction because they were
not programmed to recognize dates beyond 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The threat of litigation stemming from those potential glitches
could take the form of customers suing vendors for failing to
deliver a product or service.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposed legislation, a potential defendant with a Y2K
problems would have 90 days to get it fixed. During that 90-day
``cooling off'' period, anyone intending to file a Y2K-related
lawsuit must first give the defendant written notice of the
problem. The defendant would then have 30 days to respond in
writing and an additional 60 days to fix the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein, a Democrat from California, said the bill is intended
to prevent ``frivolous and baseless litigation, but would not
restrict an individual's right to sue to mitigate real damages.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the legislation is ``especially important to
California, where over 20 percent of the nation's hi-tech jobs are
located.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to protect people's employment in this industry, it
is necessary to have some rules,'' Feinstein said, adding that she
became involved in crafting the legislation because she was
approached by representatives of California's hi-tech industries.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch, R-Utah and chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee,
said the bill is intended to encourage ``Y2K problem-solving rather
than a mad rush to the court house'' by imposing ``a brief
time-out,'' that would avoid litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch said some experts have predicted that the world-wide cost
of Y2K-related litigation could amount to $1 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch said the legislation is not intended to discourage
companies form solving Y2K problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any business that delays solving Y2K problems is putting its
entire company at risk,'' Hatch said. He said despite precautions
taken to solve Y2K glitches, ``there's still going to be myriad
problems that will arise and we want to make sure there is a legal
situation here that won't bankrupt the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The so-called Year 2000 Fairness and Responsibility Act would
require a 90-day ``cooling off period'' during which no Y2K lawsuit
could be filed. That is intended to give a company time to resolve
Y2K problems and avoid court battles.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation would limit punitive damages to $250,000 or
three times the economic damages, whichever is greater.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLL0WS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The bill would require anyone filing a Y2K lawsuit to specify
the damages sought and exactly how they were calculated.
</P>
<P>
   It would also limit a company's liability to the proportion of
the company's fault in causing the harm, to prevent plaintiffs from
going after the wealthiest defendants.
</P>
<P>
   Similar legislation was introduced Tuesday in the House by Reps.
Thomas M. Davis III, R-Va., David Dreier, R-Calif., James P. Moran,
D-Va., Christopher Cox, R-Calif., Calvin Dooley, D-Calif., and
Robert ``Bud'' E. Cramer Jr., D-Ala.
</P>
<P>
   The American Electronics Association, the nation's largest
hi-tech trade group representing more than 3,000 U.S.-based
technology companies, praised the legislation as ``a necessary
legal framework that employs balance and reason with a shared
responsibility to remedy any problems that may occur.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-99 1718EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990224.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
