<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 17:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7828 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TLC-THEYREBACK28-COX     02-24 2188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TLC-THEYREBACK28-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Group draws strength from overcoming obstacles
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, Feb. 28.
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ TLC fell from a pinnacle no other female group had
even reached.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the group produced the biggest-selling album ever by
women, selling 10 million copies of ``CrazySexyCool.'' Radio play
of the hit ``Waterfalls,'' a sophisticated plea for safe sex, was
huge. And the video, in which the three Grammy winners turned into
mercury water goddesses, earned four MTV Music Video Awards.
</P>
<P>
   They were everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Then they were nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   They filed for bankruptcy. One battled serious complications
from a lifelong illness. One went through a difficult pregnancy.
And one is still fighting a bad reputation earned after burning
down a $1.3 million Alpharetta manse.
</P>
<P>
   Now that TLC has finally released its third album, ``Fan Mail,''
the group faces yet another obstacle. In the tenuous world of pop
music, five years out of the spotlight can be murder on a career.
</P>
<P>
   But how Tionne ``T-Boz'' Watkins, Lisa ``Left Eye'' Lopes and
Rozonda ``Chilli'' Thomas, who transformed themselves from 1992's
condom-wearing caricatures to 1995's biggest crossover success, got
through their personal struggles has a lot to do with who they are
right now.
</P>
<P>
   And why, professionally, they'll probably survive.
</P>
<P>
   Trial by fire
</P>
<P>
   There were times when Watkins, 28, would come home after
battling her incurable sickle cell anemia in the hospital, only to
find the lights had been cut off.
</P>
<P>
   In simple terms, that's what declaring bankruptcy means: You
can't pay your bills. Your power gets cut off.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you're sick.
</P>
<P>
   Lopes spent the past half decade throwing water on her
fire-starter reputation.
</P>
<P>
   What was lost in the headlines, says Lopes, 27, was that
then-boyfriend Andre Rison knocked her around so many times that
she blacked out on the June 1994 evening she burned down their
house.
</P>
<P>
   But she was the only one called crazy.
</P>
<P>
   She was the only one who went to jail.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, also 27, was the last of the three to hit the gossip
columns, when she got pregnant in 1997 with her producer Dallas
Austin's baby. Never mind that she'd professed celibacy in Vibe
magazine. ``But that wasn't a big deal; that didn't even register
in comparison to all the other TLC talk,'' she says. ``That was a
living hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Watkins makes it sound like boot camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made me stronger, it made me rely on myself more, and it
prepared me and my group to do battle with the evils in this
world,'' the compact, fiery redhead says in a way that is,
surprisingly, not bitter.
</P>
<P>
   Her voice is gravelly, but she doesn't growl.
</P>
<P>
   Rough though her words may be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not going to sit on `Oprah' and start crying and say,
`Oh my God, they took my. . . . Naw. I don't want any sympathy. All
that's part of life.''
</P>
<P>
   And living is much easier these days for the Dunwoody resident.
</P>
<P>
   Only once last year was she felled by sickle cell anemia, the
hereditary disease in which red blood cells periodically change
shape, causing excruciating pain and soreness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like someone stabbing you with a knife, over and over
again, like Freddy Krueger,'' explains Watkins, now a national
spokeswoman for the Sickle Cell Disease Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins' bouts with sickle cell, made worse by the stress of
performing, cut short what could have been a profitable 1995
``CrazySexyCool'' tour. Soon after, the insurers of Rison's home
filed a $1.3 million lawsuit against Lopes. All that, plus having
to pay the group's operating and promotional expenses, forced TLC
to seek bankruptcy protection.
</P>
<P>
   Then everything stopped. Except the talk. The jokes. And the
rumors about the group.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins got sicker.
</P>
<P>
   ``That kind of stress can break a normal person down, so you
know what it did to me,'' says Watkins, whose swollen eyes this
recent evening at a rehearsal reveal she's suffering from allergies
only.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to wake up in the hospital, all those times I could
have died, and I would always see my mother's face,'' Watkins
recalls, her eyes narrowing with anger. ``That's when I finally
realized who really gave a damn about me. That's who had my back.
That's the person that loves me. That's the person I worry about if
she has something bad to say about me. No one else in the world can
say anything about me _ besides my mother _ and it'll mean anything
to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Powerful role model
</P>
<P>
   Watkins credits her strength to her mother.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother finds that funny.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time Tionne says that, I have to laugh to myself,'' says
Gayle Watkins, smiling as she puts up groceries in her Jonesboro
home. ``She's been strong-willed since the day she came into this
world. I don't know where she gets that `It's my mama' stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was watching the elder Watkins, now retired from UPS,
work three jobs simultaneously to care for Tionne and her younger
brother, Carnoy. Sometimes dinner in their Des Moines, Iowa, home
consisted of Kool-Aid and popcorn. But that was the way things were
from the time Tionne was about 6, when her mother and father split.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tionne's been through so, so much, but honestly, never more
than I thought she could deal with,'' says Marie Davis, who
introduced Watkins and Lopes to recording star friend Perri
``Pebbles'' Reid, TLC's first manager. ``She's just always had this
presence.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis could even see it when Watkins, then 17, was bent over the
shampoo bowl, assisting a stylist at Escape Salon off Stewart
Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to say `TT' _ that's one of her ghetto-fabulous names _
I'd say, `TT, you're a star!' '' Davis says. `` `You need to be
onstage.' `You're going to be famous.' ''
</P>
<P>
   No one had to tell ``Chilli'' Thomas that. When the Atlanta
native heard there was a female group looking for a third member,
``I was like, `I'm here! Oooh, I can sing! I'm ready to be the next
Janet Jackson!' ''
</P>
<P>
   What Thomas wasn't ready for was the verbal abuse she says she
endured from Reid when the R&AMP;B singer started developing TLC in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm, like, 95 percent almost me again,'' Thomas says as she
finishes off some fish from Piccadilly's, frequently splashed with
hot sauce from an industrial-size bottle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seriously. Pebbles gave me a complex. I'm not trying to dog
people, but you know, I'm just being very honest.''
</P>
<P>
   Being specific about the alleged abuse seems a bit harder. But
Thomas tries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Girl, I'm serious,'' she begins.
</P>
<P>
   Then stops.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just don't understand. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``That woman. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``I. . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Finally she gets a complete sentence out: ``I don't know if she
had a problem with me or not. The other two she didn't do like
that. I don't know if she felt like I was a threat or what. But she
always made me feel like I wasn't up to par.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long, long, long struggle back to confidence,''
continues Thomas, who like Watkins is clearly athletic, even in
baggy warm-up Nike gear. ``But I simply had to do it to raise my
son (Tron, who's named after the 1982 Disney movie, one of his
father's favorites). It's not about me now. I've had to get over it
and be strong for him. And I'm back.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's noticeable. TLC's 3 million-selling 1992 debut,
``Oooohhh . . . On the TLC Tip,'' featured rapper Lopes
prominently. ``CrazySexyCool'' was meant to ``grow the group up,''
Austin says, so it was centered on Watkins' throaty, more sensual
vocals. Now, on ``Fan Mail,'' Thomas' lighter, more pliant singing
takes the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``People may think I'm biased when it comes to rating Rozonda's
voice,'' begins Austin, 28, Thomas' on-and-off boyfriend of eight
years. ``But I'm being honest. I mean, I get in trouble all the
time for saying this: She's no Whitney Houston. And so what? You
can go into any black church and find those kinds of singers all
day long. But a special singer, like Rozonda, has a familiar tone.
A tone that makes people want to sing along with her, like Brandy
and Monica and Janet Jackson. With a Whitney or Celine Dion record,
you watch it from a distance and observe the vocal performance.
With Rozonda or Janet, you're right there with them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you hear `No Scrubs,' it doesn't even sound like a TLC
record, because we're not used to Chilli's vocals up front,'' adds
Kandi Burruss, who along with fellow Xscape member Tameka ``Tiny''
Cottle wrote the first single from ``Fan Mail.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She delivers it well.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I said, I'm almost back to being that super-hyped girl
that came into this business ready to be a star,'' says Thomas, who
like Lopes has a home in Stone Mountain. ``I'm working toward 100
percent.''
</P>
<P>
   An apology from TLC's first manager would help, she adds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't happen,'' Reid insists. ``You know, we're all grown
now. It's time we assume responsibility for our own lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Reid does concede, however, that they were once a major part of
each other's lives. In fact, all parties say the four were
inseparable at the start of this decade, planning what TLC would
look like and sing like in the basement of Reid's Country Club of
the South home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a slumber party every night,'' Reid says.
</P>
<P>
   Then it became business.
</P>
<P>
   TLC eventually signed with Reid's Pebbitone production company,
which then negotiated the deal with LaFace Records _ which is
co-owned by Reid's former husband, Antonio ``L.A.'' Reid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intermingling makes LaFace like Motown for more reasons
than the impact their music has,'' noted Nelson George, author of
``The Death of Rhythm &AMP; Blues.''
</P>
<P>
   When TLC filed for Chapter 11 creditor protection in July 1995,
claiming the group was $3.5 million in debt with less than $1
million in assets, many industry observers said aloud that part of
the blame was their deal with Pebbles Reid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now who's going to apologize to me for diminishing my name?''
an exasperated Reid asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's going to apologize for people lying on me?
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's going to say `Sorry' for having to deal with the rumors
that she slept with my husband?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm saved and filled with the Holy Ghost now, but we all have
to make our individual peace,'' adds Reid. After selling millions
of records (``Mercedes Boy'') in the late '80s, she gave up her
singing career and her Atlanta-based Savvy Records label in
November to lead a ministry called Women of God Changing Lives
Through Christ. ``I can't get into child's play.''
</P>
<P>
   Three lives get busier
</P>
<P>
   The serious business of rehearsing for TLC's ``No Scrubs'' video
was supposed to start at 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   It's 8:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas is in the lounge of this mazelike North Atlanta rehearsal
facility opening up another pack of peanut M&AMP;Ms. Watkins is
starting to stretch with two of their dancers. And Lopes, well, she
isn't around.
</P>
<P>
   Not that she would be talking anyway: The official line from
LaFace is that the firebrand isn't doing print interviews right
now.
</P>
<P>
   Strange, because in TLC's absence, Lopes was the most visible.
She hosted MTV's talent show, ``The Cut.'' She told Sister 2 Sister
magazine what led to her accidentally, she maintains, burning down
the Country Club of the South mansion she shared with Rison. And
now you can turn on urban radio and hear the first act from her
Left Eye Productions company, another female trio named Blaque
(``808'').
</P>
<P>
   The other two TLC members may not have been in the spotlight,
but they were busy.
</P>
<P>
   Though Watkins made her motion picture debut in the 1998 film
``Belly,'' she isn't thinking about acting anymore. Like pop singer
Jewel, she's written a book of poetry, as yet unpublished, called
``Thoughts, Vol. 1,'' which includes ``Move Out of the Way,'' a
poem about people who won't move out of the way for an ambulance.
She's also working on a Saturday morning cartoon and a clothing
line with Austin called ``Grungy Glamorous.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, meanwhile, is pursuing an acting career.
</P>
<P>
   ``That we could round up these three very different
personalities with all these things going on and get them back in
the studio was a feat, to say the least,'' LaFace co-president L.A.
Reid says. ``Things, I promise you, are finally fine.'' Looks that
way.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it's after 9 p.m. and rehearsal still hasn't started.
TLC's members have pulled up in $50,000-plus Lincoln Navigators and
Land Rovers, not the sign of a group scraping for dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fan Mail'' is out on Atlanta's LaFace Records, not the sign of
a group unhappy with its record deal.
</P>
<P>
   And Tower Records manager Keith Medlin says, ``Their absence
hasn't diminished this group's popularity one bit. I don't know how
this record is going to debut (on the music charts Thursday). But
with all the time away, with all they've been through, there's
still no one like TLC. All they've got to do, really, is top
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, it's nearing 11 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Left Eye has arrived. TLC is finally all together now.
</P>
<P>
   Step one.
</P>
<P>
   Sonia Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
