<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN EVER-PRESENT PLAGUE: DUST 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: A howto drawing is being sent to both photo and graphics
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
(DW) 
 By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Every housekeeper fights a never-ending battle
against dust. At times it seems that the dust begins to collect on
surfaces immediately after they are wiped clean. Actually this is
not an exaggeration, because the dust is circulating in the air
around us and it starts to settle when the air currents subside.
</P>
<P>
   What is dust and where does it come from?
</P>
<P>
   Dust is fine bits of matter that are capable of floating in the
air. It can range in size from invisible microscopic particles to
grains of sand.
</P>
<P>
   Dust particles are formed when a substance is broken down either
physically, through abrasion, or chemically, through combustion.
Every time someone enters your home they bring a little dust with
them from the outside. The best way to minimize this incoming dust
is by installing area rugs at all entrances. Encourage people to
wipe their feet before treading inside. Vacuum and shake out these
rugs weekly.
</P>
<P>
   This, however, is only a small part of the dust battle, because
most dust in a home is created inside. It comes from two major
sources: the fabrics around the house and our own bodies. Clothes,
drapes, carpets, upholstery, towels and other fabrics are
constantly being worn away every time we move or brush against
them. Eventually the fabric erodes into tiny lint and filament
particles that eventually settle as dust.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the human body continually produces considerable
quantities of dust as it sheds dried out layers of skin. As new
layers are created, old ones dry and disintegrate into dust
particles.
</P>
<P>
   Since neither of these dust sources can be eliminated, the best
the housekeeper can do is to pick up the dust as soon as it
settles. In spite of all the advances in technology, the best
dust-collecting tools are ones that have been around for decades:
the dust cloth, the dust mop and the vacuum. The techniques for
using these tools are basic and obvious.
</P>
<P>
   The only trick to using the dust cloth is in selecting one made
of natural cotton fibers. Cloths with synthetic fibers are less
absorbent and can produce a static charge that repels dust away
from the cloth. Dusting sprays are also useful because they give
the dust cloth or mop an electrostatic charge that attracts dust
particles. Sprays are effective, but can be expensive.
</P>
<P>
   The only way to pull dust from fabrics is by washing, shaking or
vacuuming them. Carpets should be vacuumed every week because they
are major dust collectors. Every time someone walks across a
carpet, the fibers throw some dust into the air. In addition, the
dirt and dust particles embedded in the carpet abrade the
surrounding fibers to produce even more dust.
</P>
<P>
   Upholstered chairs and sofas readily collect dust, and they spew
it into the air whenever someone sits down. You can vacuum more
dust from a chair cushion if you place it in a large plastic bag.
Close the mouth of the bag around the vacuum nozzle and allow the
machine to suck the air and dust out of the pillow.
</P>
<P>
   Most housekeepers ignore clothes closets during the weekly
cleanup, yet the closets are significant dust producers. Garments
shed fibers whenever they are removed or replaced from the rack.
This abrasion can be reduced considerably by keeping clothes in
individual plastic bags. Remember to vacuum the closet floor
periodically or the dust that settles there will be thrown into air
each time someone opens the closet door.
</P>
<P>
   With a vacuum cleaner, the amount of dust collected depends on
the suction power of the machine and the filter inside. In most
vacuum cleaners the collecting bag acts as a dirt filter. Paper
bags have a better filtration action than cloth bags; some can
capture particles as small as 10 microns. Special vacuum bags that
can capture particles as small as one micron are also available at
a higher cost, but they cannot be used in all vacuums because
require extra suction. They must be used in vacuums with powerful
motors.
</P>
<P>
   Dust is a byproduct of combustion. Whenever fossil fuels,
heating oil, natural gas or wood are burned, they are converted
into heat energy and combustion gases (wood also has an ash residue
that disintegrates into dust). The combustion gases carry minute
particles that settle as dust. Well-tuned burners consume more fuel
with less waste.
</P>
<P>
   Have the burner in your heating system tuned annually by a
heating specialist and make sure the venting system is well
maintained. In a forced-air system the filter traps airborne dust.
It should be replaced whenever it gets dirty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
