<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RADIO-CITY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOSING OUR SEATS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By JULIE V. IOVINE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``It made me very nervous, I can tell you that,''
said Carol Krinsky, an architectural historian. She was referring
to a picture on the front page of The New York Times on Saturday
showing the auditorium seating being carted out of Radio City Music
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Krinsky, the author of ``Rockefeller Center'' (Oxford
University Press, 1978), was not the only one to feel a twinge of
concern over the sight of dozens of plush red cushions being
wrestled into a trailer truck. Anyone who had been cradled by them
during performances by the Rockettes, Frank Sinatra or the Who, in
``Tommy,'' might have wondered: Where were they going?
</P>
<P>
   Radio City closed on Feb. 16 for a six-month renovation
estimated at $30 million to $40 million. This will be ``the first
true restoration of the music hall,'' said Hugh Hardy, of Hardy
Holzman Pfeiffer, architects for the project with the Rockwell
Group. Hardy, who is in India on vacation, says that the renovation
will include going back to original color schemes, fabrics,
wallpaper and carpet, as well as returning the famous armchairs by
Donald Deskey to their place in the lobby.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I hadn't already spoken with Hugh Hardy, who swears he's
going to restore it to exactly the way it was, I would have been
exceedingly nervous,'' Ms. Krinsky said. ``Now let's see if the
owners will let him do it.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, the interiors of Radio City Music Hall were designated
a landmark by the Landmarks Preservation Commission at a ceremony
witnessed by the lieutenant governor at the time, Mary Ann Krupsak,
a former Rockette. Its art deco splendor was created in 1932 by an
impressive array of artists and designers commissioned by Donald
Deskey. Besides Deskey himself, they included Stuart Davis, whose
painting for the men's room, ``Men Without Women,'' now hangs in
the Museum of Modern Art.
</P>
<P>
   What about the seats? While the metal casings, in some cases,
were still intact, the upholstery had deteriorated and been
replaced over the years, Ms. Krinsky said. The small lights on the
back of each seat and the distinctive black piping that made them
look so modern were long gone. The Landmarks Preservation
Commission gave permission for them to be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not wildly fabled chairs, just typical chairs of the
day,'' said Evan Blum, owner of Irreplaceable Artifacts in New
York. He had been contacted about finding a buyer for the 5,901
seats by Radio City Productions, a subsidiary of Cablevision, which
leases Radio City Music Hall from Tishman Speyer Properties.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, employees in the Hardy and Rockwell offices and their
consultants were offered the chairs for $75 a pair. Susan Arons,
spokeswoman at Radio City Entertainment, said that proceeds of this
sale went to ``Sharing for Children,'' but that the bulk of the
chairs had been deposited in storage and would ultimately be sold
to benefit the same charity.
</P>
<P>
   If they show up on the market, here's a shopper's tip. ``The
only ones worth anything are the ones on the end with the
decorative panels on the aisle,'' Blum said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-99 1728EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990224.0237 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7844 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DENVER-BRITAIN-ART-NY     02-24 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DENVER-BRITAIN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENVER IS LAPPING UP THE BRITISH ART OF A NATIVE SON 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ For some people here on the South Platte, talk of
``Western civ'' may conjure up the image of a Remington oil
painting of a buffalo hunt, not a Gainsborough tableau of a
steeplechase.
</P>
<P>
   But since October, 71,000 people have taken the elevators past
the Denver Art Museum's cherished American Indian floor, Spanish
Colonial floor, Asian floor and American West floor. Reaching the
seventh floor, they have disembarked, sometimes at the rate of 400
an hour, to visit the exhibition ``600 Years of British Painting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I often start out with 8 or 10 people, but when I end up I can
have 40 people following me,'' Ida Rifkin, a veteran gallery guide,
said of the popular response to this wide-ranging collection formed
by two Denver investors, Bill and Bernadette Berger.
</P>
<P>
   John Russell Taylor, art critic for The Times of London, said he
sampled this grass-roots response recently when he wandered lost
through Denver's airport. ``The first person I met in Denver was a
little gray-haired lady at the desk where they receive ski
parties,'' he recalled. ``She immediately cottoned on to the fact
that I was interested in art. `Oh, well,' she said. `If you are
spending any time in Denver, you should go to the British art
collection. It's really great. Everybody loves it.'''
</P>
<P>
   The interest in American ethnic diversity that blossomed in the
1960s made Anglophilia an embarrassment to many American
intellectuals. But if Denver's response to tableaux of fox hunts,
sea battles, Cotswold landscapes and Elizabethan aristocrats is a
measure, British art, culture and history in fact still exert a
powerful pull on the American mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are voting with their feet,'' said Malcolm Warner,
paintings curator at the Yale Center for British Art, which remains
the nation's largest collection of such works. ``Just look at all
the crowds that have gone in recent years to the Jane Austen
movies, and now to `Elizabeth' and to `Shakespeare in Love.'''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Berger collection's 215 paintings are but a small
fraction of the size of Yale's British collection, Warner hopes the
Denver phenomenon is a foretaste of things to come in New Haven.
After a year of renovations that cost $5 million, the Yale Center
reopened in January with shows by three 20th-century British
artists, Francis Bacon, Lucian Freud and Henry Moore. A bequest by
Paul Mellon, who died this month, has since brought $75 million to
the center, which he founded in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sense that Americans are starting to realize that an
interest in British culture is not necessarily insulting to fellow
Americans of other origins,'' Warner said, speaking with the
caution of a British transplant to the United States. ``Whereas for
many years there has been a slight stigma about Anglophilia,
perhaps that is wearing off now.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger doesn't tiptoe around the issue. ``Why British art?'' the
Bergers ask in a preface to their collection's lavish 290-page
catalog. ``Because it represents a heritage that belongs to all of
us today, no matter where our forebears come from. And because the
British people and their culture did more to advance our material
well-being than did any other country in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The collection stretches from a 1395 Crucifixion panel to a
stormy landscape painted in 1996 by Sir Howard Hodgkin. During
World War II, Berger, a fourth-generation Coloradan, interrupted
his studies of English literature at Yale to drive an ambulance for
Britain's Eighth Army. After the war he founded the Berger Group of
mutual funds here, all the while maintaining friends, business
partners and an apartment in London.
</P>
<P>
   After selling his mutual fund business five years ago, he and
his wife entered the British art market so forcefully that they are
said to have driven up prices. Although Berger declines to reveal
the cost of assembling the collection, art experts estimate that he
spent about $25 million in three years.
</P>
<P>
   Since opening on Oct. 10, the exhibition apparently has tapped a
latent vein of interest in Britain here. About 20 percent of
Coloradans claim British ancestry. Every winter Britons account for
a third of the foreign skiers who visit Colorado. Last fall, when
British Airways inaugurated a direct daily flight between here and
London, it sold out for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The show greets visitors with a room dedicated to England's love
affair with horses _ steeplechases, horse races and horse markets _
which is not an unknown passion here. In one equine portrait, the
rider is a blur, but the noble steed is lovingly detailed, down to
the hairs in his ears.
</P>
<P>
   Covering an entire floor, the show is broken up into small,
digestible rooms. Each is painted in a ``British color'' like teal,
plum or ultramarine and is equipped with comfortable armchairs and
sofas.
</P>
<P>
   Avoiding a chronological approach that might make a visitor feel
deficient in his knowledge of the sequence of kings and queens, the
exhibition is organized into theme rooms: everyday life, empire and
military, medieval, landscapes and a central salon hung floor to
ceiling with portraits in the style of a great manor house.
</P>
<P>
   Exhibits are devoted to stamps, coins, royal wax seals and a map
that shows California as an island and Colorado as an unexplored
wilderness. In the costume room, children can try on wigs, corsets,
an Edwardian top hat and Elizabethan lace ruffs.
</P>
<P>
   Each gallery has only one wall caption, with few dates and
names. ``We have taken the art history out of it,'' Timothy J.
Standring, the collection's curator, said over lunch at Palettes,
the museum's ground-floor restaurant, which is offering British
dishes during the six-month show. ``We have taken away the
stuffiness that has been equated with British art.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bergers often chose their paintings for their accessibility,
for their ability to tell a story. ``We are trying to get kids to
connect with art, to understand that there is a wonderful, big
world out there,'' Standring said. The exhibition runs through
March 28.
</P>
<P>
   To allow for more visitors, the Bergers waived a separate show
admission fee, heavily subsidized the cost of preparing the catalog
and donated $120,000 to prepare audio tours for children and for
adults. The museum, which hopes to become the permanent home of the
collection, charges nothing for the audio or guided tours. The
Bergers also have set up a Web site, www.thebergercollection.org.
</P>
<P>
   The Bergers venture that, in Denver, home to four major league
athletic teams, art can compete with sports.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Berger said that 3,000 people saw the show the Saturday
that the Broncos beat the Jets before going on to winning the Super
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said: ``We want to enliven the intellectual level of the
city, to bring a little more balance into our lives. Not all of us
are fascinated by football.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
