<SLUG> BC-DAY-REPRODUCTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SINCEREST FORM OF CABINETMAKING 
</HEADLINE>
  (Sidebar with NC-DAY-MUSEUM) (lh) 
 By MARIANNE ROHRLICH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I come from a family of cabinetmakers who worked in Alabama at
the time of Thomas Day,'' Derrick Joshua Beard said last week from
his cabinetry shop in South-Central Los Angeles. Beard, 40, has
introduced a line of handmade reproductions of pre-Civil War
furniture by free black craftsmen, including Day, based on pieces
in Beard's own collection of original furniture. The Day
reproductions, including a pier table, side chairs and a secretary,
are known as the Sankofa North Carolina Heritage Collection and are
made of solid mahogany.
</P>
<P>
   Beard has been collecting Day's furniture for 10 years. ``If it
weren't for Derrick Beard's enthusiasm about Thomas Day, very few
people would know about his work,'' Joan Gibbs, a New York interior
designer, said.
</P>
<P>
   The line is handmade in South-Central Los Angeles and
hand-finished on New York City's Lower East Side by Eduardo Fontan
and Baron Perez, who polish each piece with natural varnish. The
reproduction Day side chair is $1,200; the pier table, $3,500, and
the secretary, $18,000, available on Web site,
www.sankofaheritage.com. reproductions will be exhibited on
Saturday from 11 a.m. to 7 p.m. at the Antique Castle, 900 Park
Ave., Plainfield, N.J.; no charge for admission. Information: (908)
791-9700
</P>
</TEXT>
