<DOCNO> NYT19990224.0243 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7852 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-LEARNING-FRENCH-2     02-24 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-LEARNING-FRENCH-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TETE-A-TETES WITH NATIVE FRENCH SPEAKERS, SANS ATTITUDE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ERIC NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was about a year after moving to Paris that I first heard the
question pop up from friends and relatives back home: ``Are you
fluent yet?''
</P>
<P>
   No, I would answer in the patient, slightly smug tone that
expatriates use with their less fortunate cousins in the New World.
Fluency in French, I explained (yawn), would very likely be long in
coming.
</P>
<P>
   And in truth, it was longer in coming than I had imagined. As
the years passed, the question ``Are you fluent yet?'' became the
more ominous ``So you're fluent, of course.'' Only the answer
remained the same: No. Proficient _ sure. Fluent _ pas de tout.
</P>
<P>
   So forgive me if, back in the States after three-and-a-half
years in France, I still get a bit touchy on the subject of
fluency.
</P>
<P>
   That, however, is precisely what many French
language-instruction CD-ROMs on the market seem to be promising.
(``The fast and effective way to all-around fluency,'' says the
cover of the Berlitz French program from the Learning Company.) It
is hard, though, to imagine becoming truly adept at a foreign
language without being immersed in a setting where the language
predominates _ and having a live teacher to coax you through the
rough spots and force you to concentrate.
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say that there isn't much of value in many of
the French language products. The CD-ROM technology, far less
static than a book or tape, seems well suited to helping people
learn a language or, at least, speak it. You can hear people speak
words and phrases and repeat them as many times as you wish.
</P>
<P>
   That is especially important for French since, for all the
beauty of the language, it can be daunting to understand. Moreover,
CD-ROMs can present a wide variety of written and spoken quizzes to
reinforce learning, and they let you find out instantly if you have
made a mistake. Some of the programs allow you to connect to Web
sites for further study, and all the programs reviewed here also
feature native French speakers, not the usual fare in many North
American classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Another feature unique to language CD-ROMs is the ability to let
students speak and, on the more sophisticated programs, to
evaluate, to some extent, their attempts to do so. Several programs
come with microphones, of varying quality, that can be easily
plugged into the computer. The simpler language programs have you
repeat a word or phrase, then play it back, letting you compare it
with the words of the native speaker. The more elaborate ones,
using increasingly sophisticated voice-recognition technology,
actually assess your efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Still, users should be aware that some programs are rather, er,
forgiving in their assessments of accent and word choice _ much
more so than, say, a certain people for whom French is the native
language. Moreover, whatever the benefits of CD-ROMs for honing
your speaking skills and teaching some basic vocabulary, they seem
less useful for teaching the backbone of any language: grammar.
</P>
<P>
   And in French grammar, especially, mistakes there will be. We
are, after all, talking about a country where people take a
perverse pleasure in the pitfalls of their own language and avidly
follow on television and in newspapers accounts of regular events
in which a reigning French literary figure has contestants _
adults, mind you _ sit together in public and try to take down
correctly a complicated dictation.
</P>
<P>
   Learn To Speak French
</P>
<P>
   (The Learning Company; $79.95; $50 rebate available until Feb.
28; Windows 3.1 or later.)
</P>
<P>
   The corny accordion music that opens this program, accompanied
by timeworn images like the Eiffel Tower and a vineyard, does not
really prepare you for the high-tech scenes to follow. Learn to
Speak French, the most ambitious of the Learning Company's
French-language offerings, does not miss a trick. It draws on
extensive video, audio and other resources to present an
impressive, demanding course plan. And its language-recognition
software is excellent.
</P>
<P>
   The course is broken into 10 units, each with three chapters and
a short film about various parts of France. The first unit begins
with an elementary chapter teaching students ``please'' and
``hello''; in the video clips and animation that follow, students
are shown the words being spoken in context. A series of exercises,
grammar lessons and games allows students to practice what they
have learned. Interspersed throughout are useful tips about the
language and the culture. Each chapter culminates in the piece de
resistance: a ``conversation'' with a videotaped figure.
</P>
<P>
   From a technological standpoint, it is impressive stuff, even if
the program did crash several times when it got to this spot. From
a pedagogical standpoint, I don't know how useful this exercise is,
but it can't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   The program can also be a bit unsettling, like many real
encounters in Paris. I, for one, felt chills go up my spine when I
was forced to have a conversation with the dreaded gardienne _ sort
of a super with police powers _ as she wielded a broom outside ``my
building.'' When she was unable to understand my answers, she
looked at me as if I must be feeble-minded and delivered a
disgusted ``Pardon?'' My knees shook. If I had really been in Paris
at the time, I might have thought about packing my bags.
</P>
<P>
   My accent aside, the reason she was confused was that my answers
did not track the narrow responses she was programmed to accept. As
impressive as the technology is, it does not, of course, provide a
real conversation. So when she asked me if I was looking for a
taxi, determined at all costs to give me directions, she was at a
loss when I told her I wanted a train. She also did not seem to
know what to do when, after she introduced herself as the
gardienne, I replied (with a rash defiance French tenants
everywhere would applaud), ``So what?''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, another character reacted with aplomb when I told her
I had 16 children and that my sister was 120 years old and was a
prisoner. ``Interesting,'' she responded to each answer, ``very
interesting.'' When we were through ``conversing,'' she concluded,
``You have a very charming family.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   French Your Way 2.0
</P>
<P>
   (Random House/Syracuse Language Systems; $69.95; Windows 3.1 or
later.)
</P>
<P>
   This is a thorough, serious approach to teaching French. But
because multimedia is not used in an imaginative way, it is not a
very engaging one.
</P>
<P>
   That is a shame because a lot of thought and work clearly went
into the lessons, and its voice-recognition features are
impressive. For the motivated student, there is a lot to be learned
here. The French spoken is impeccable, and the students are held to
high standards to pass the various tests in the program.
</P>
<P>
   The basic problem is the way Syracuse Language Systems, a leader
in the field, has chosen to present the dialogues. A Syracuse
spokeswoman said the company had made a considered decision not to
use videos, believing that students learned better with a focus on
an audio presentation. In practice, this means that in lesson after
lesson, a student sees screens of panel cartoons with word balloons
that, when clicked, produce dialogue that is about as animated as
the drawings. (Syracuse also puts out Smart Start French, which
also relies on still cartoons but is considerably more lively.)
</P>
<P>
   The dialogues concern such staples of French life as a trip to a
restaurant, a visit to someone's home and making one's way around
town. Depending on their levels, students begin by listening to
simple conversations and watching as the appropriate cartoon panels
are highlighted. You can listen to the dialogue again and, in a
very useful feature, slow down the speakers (not that they are
breaking any speed records to begin with). That produces an
unnatural sound but allows the listener to get a handle on what is
being said.
</P>
<P>
   The French Your Way designers wisely allow a student to control
just how much help is wanted in understanding a dialogue. You can
have the words appear in French as they are said. You can also add
the English translation. Students are quite rightly urged to use
the minimum help possible.
</P>
<P>
   As you progress, you begin to guide the conversation, first by
using your mouse to choose from a series of possible answers and
then, when you are ready, by reading the answers aloud into the
microphone that is included. But be warned: French Your Way is a
tough teacher. Your accent counts. It caught some intentional
errors on my part _ and many more unintentional ones.
</P>
<P>
   The program is strong on grammar and pronunciation. It offers an
extensive dictionary that includes an audio rendition of how the
words should sound, which is a nice touch. It also comes with an
audio cassette tape to supplement the lessons.
</P>
<P>
   I question the decision by the designers to make the course
essentially without structure. Rather than following a sequence of
lessons, you can jump into it pretty much anywhere by choosing a
subject that interests you. The idea is that students will be more
stimulated if they can tailor the program to their needs, but I
think a beginner might find this more confusing than hospitable.
</P>
<P>
   Berlitz French
</P>
<P>
   (The Learning Company; $49.95; Windows 3.1 or later.)
</P>
<P>
   In contrast with the other programs, Berlitz French takes a more
traditional approach to teaching the language. Students follow a
clear lesson plan, and while lessons can be skipped, you will be
reminded that you may be overlooking material.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Berlitz imprimatur, this is far from the most
thorough or even the most inspired language program. It is probably
of more value to tourists than to those who want to learn the
language fully.
</P>
<P>
   Berlitz French is organized into 12 units, each consisting of
separate topics on subjects like how to ask directions or greet
people. At the beginning of each topic, you are shown a list of the
new vocabulary words and phrases that will be covered, along with
drawings showing their meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Within each topic is a series of exercises, including
fill-in-the-blank and true-false questions, and ``closer looks''
that provide additional information about the lesson. Every three
units, there is a review test.
</P>
<P>
   At any point, you can consult a dictionary or a grammar guide.
And the CD-ROM is accompanied by an audio-only disk that allows
more practice.
</P>
<P>
   Berlitz French also uses voice-recognition technology. But it
must be said that it was sometimes rather simple to fool the
program, sometimes by just repeating approximations of the key
words in a sentence. In one case, asked the location of the post
office, I was supposed to reply: ``The post office? Very close. To
the left.'' The machine settled for ``Post office close.'' ``Pool,
bus'' and ``theater hotel'' also made the grade. Not very useful to
anyone needing directions.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   French for the Real World
</P>
<P>
   (Knowledge Adventure; $20; Windows 3.1 or later, Power
Macintosh.)
</P>
<P>
   This program provides reassuring news: when low tech meets high
imagination, the latter is what counts. French for the Real World
has no speech-recognition software and makes no exaggerated claims
(``guaranteed to help you succeed in first-year French'' is as far
as it goes). What it has is a good sense of humor, a deft way of
enticing you into the program and an oily but likable guy named
Stephane.
</P>
<P>
   Stephane is your partner on an animated car race that takes you
across France. To make the trip, you have to undergo a series of
rigorous tests, from correctly trading pieces of fruit at a market
to negotiating with a sales clerk to buy something yellow. In each
case, the correct answers allow you to collect directions for the
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on in!'' Stephane invites you in French-accented English
(he later speaks French) as he jumps into his blue car. ``The
language is fine.''
</P>
<P>
   But first things first. Before you can go anywhere, you have to
fill out your driver's license _ along the way, you learn French
words for your date of birth and nationality. Then you have to
choose from a selection of cars. And finally, le visage _ your
face. You choose everything from your mouth to your eyes and hair,
with Stephane making humorous comments along the way. (One quibble:
many of these comments will be incomprehensible to beginners.)
</P>
<P>
   Then you are on the road with music coming from the car's radio.
Stephane narrates as you pass everything from cows to people and
trucks. All the while, a dictionary sits at the ready; you can
click on it to review the phrases being used in the lesson.
Periodically, a driver will pass you, lean out the window and
challenge you. ``Hey, snail!'' one says. ``Want to duel?'' What
follows next is a series of ``Concentration''-type memorization
drills designed to teach words by associating them with pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers can also take shortcuts, but only by proving that they
have learned to conjugate verbs. In one case, to build a bridge
over a crocodile-infested river, you must arrange the tiles of the
bridge so the right subject is aligned with the right form of the
verb.
</P>
<P>
   The language is lively and slangy _ like the way it is spoken in
real life _ and is punctuated throughout by quirky sound effects
straight out of the Saturday morning cartoon shows. While this
animated program is aimed at a younger audience, there is no reason
it should not appeal to anyone who would like to learn some
beginner French. And don't be fooled by its elbow-in-the-ribs
presentation: its underlying approach to teaching the language is
perfectly serious.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
