<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7861 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-JUILLIARD-PLAYWRIG     02-24 1820
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-JUILLIARD-PLAYWRIGHTS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUILLIARD'S COLLEGIAL PLAYWRITING PROGRAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By MEL GUSSOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There are no requirements, grades or academic credit
_ and no promises _ but the playwrights program in the Juilliard
School's drama division is a hot ticket, one of the training
grounds that hopeful young playwrights covet the most. The
atmosphere is charged with enthusiasm and encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the program is Marsha Norman, the Pulitzer
Prize-winning playwright. Along with Christopher Durang, Jon Robin
Baitz and occasionally such guests as John Guare, Terrence McNally,
Eric Bogosian, Wendy Wasserstein, Steve Martin and Spalding Gray,
she has been guiding this class for the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   Every Thursday evening from 4 to 7, seven young playwrights meet
for a master class at the Juilliard School. Their new plays or
parts of plays are read aloud, usually by the other students. The
reading is followed by a vigorous and frank discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Norman and her associates offer direct, practical advice
drawn from their own years as professional playwrights. They talk
about structure, characterization and motivation as well as
problems of production, including casting and the division of
responsibility between the writer and the director.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a high-intensity individual program,'' Ms. Norman said.
By involving working playwrights in the process, ``it is a
front-line kind of teaching operation, out of the trenches,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Based on what they have seen and heard, the students rewrite
their work, and every other Saturday one is read by Juilliard
actors in a playwrights' lab. An advantage of the program is that,
in contrast to many other schools, the writers can have their work
performed by highly skilled young actors. At the lab as in class,
there is a critical colloquy among the students and the teachers,
with only one stricture. No one is supposed to tell the playwright
how to rewrite the play. The feeling is collegial rather than
competitive.
</P>
<P>
   In a profession in which writers spend a great deal of time
waiting to hear from theaters and producers, the Juilliard program
offers an instant response. The class is like an artist's atelier,
with the teachers taking a hands-on approach to each play and each
playwright. Other institutions have sometimes had as many as 30
writers in a class. In the Juilliard program, there have never been
more than eight, and they are led by two teachers. Students are
given a certificate rather than a diploma; they are drawn to
Juilliard by the process.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, playwriting was taught _ when it was taught _ by
academics, with George Pierce Baker in the early part of this
century the emblem of Ivy League dramaturgy, the man who instructed
Eugene O'Neill and Philip Barry, among others. In some cases,
playwriting was taught by the book, one of the books being Lajos
Egri's ``How Not to Write a Play,'' in which the author arbitrarily
insisted that any play should be reducible to a one-sentence
summary.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, prominent playwrights have been teaching
playwriting: Edward Albee at the University of Houston, Romulus
Linney at the New School, Paula Vogel at Brown University and and
many more.
</P>
<P>
   The playwriting curriculum at Juilliard was restructured in 1993
when Michael Kahn became the director of the drama division. The
first year, the class was taught by Guare and McNally, followed by
Ms. Norman and Durang, with Baitz filling in this year when Durang
is on leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't teach playwriting by rules,'' Kahn said, ``Marsha
and Chris _ and now Robbie Baitz _ have a wonderful sense of how to
impart knowledge and criticism without getting in the way.''
</P>
<P>
   The names of the young Juilliard playwrights are unfamiliar to
the public, but each has a strong individual talent and several are
on the verge of a breakthrough. Although most of them are in their
late 20s, each has solid professional credentials and several have
already won awards. And they are productive. These are not one-play
phenomena but artists with a growing body of work.
</P>
<P>
   This week Jessica Goldberg was named the winner of the Susan
Smith Blackburn Award for ``Refuge,'' a play about siblings
grappling for life support in a world of drugs and
dysfunctionalism. The prestigious prize is given annually to a
female playwright in the English-speaking world. Ms. Goldberg and
Robert Kerr, a recent Juilliard graduate, are also two of the first
winners of the Helen Merrill Award for Playwriting, a new prize
established in the will of Ms. Merrill, a play agent.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Brooke Berman won the Francesca Primus Prize (for a
female playwright) for ``Wonderland,'' an anarchic comedy about
Hollywood and religion. She is also this year's winner of the
10-minute play contest at the forthcoming Actors Theater of
Louisville New Play Festival in Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Berman said of the Juilliard class: ``I've been forced to
justify what I'm doing, why I'm doing it and who I'm doing it for.
It's been an extraordinary experience to be in a community where
you're accepted and you're challenged.''
</P>
<P>
   In his absurdist comedy ``Middle-Aged Hipster,'' Daniel Goldfarb
spoofs everything from academics who lean too far over the cutting
edge to the heavy-duty basic training of women who enlist in the
Israeli army. Another Goldfarb play, ``Adam Baum and the Jew
Movie,'' is to be directed by Daniel Sullivan at the Drama Dept.
next fall.
</P>
<P>
   The class' other playwrights _ Alexandra Cunningham, Adam Rapp,
Michael Develle-Winn and Deborah Laufer _ also have current
productions or ones in the near future, as do Kyra Obolensky, David
Lindsay-Abaire and others from previous years.
</P>
<P>
   One of Develle-Winn's plays is about Tupac Shakur. Of the
Saturday laboratories, Ms. Norman said: ``In Michael's labs, the
room is hot because all the actors of color at Juilliard have been
waiting for `Othello' to come up. Suddenly Michael's here, and he's
writing about them. There's electricity in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   The program is practical rather than theoretical. ``What I think
is useful is for them to learn to think about plays, to watch them
carefully, as a colleague,'' Ms. Norman said. ``We're trying to
give careful, constructive feedback about what's clear and what's
not, what's moving, disturbing or dull. We almost never talk about
art. We talk about what works, about what's necessary. At the heart
of the failure of most plays is the inability to carry on a
thoughtful conversation about your work with yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of the program, playwrights are urged to audit classes
in other disciplines, like acting, directing and design. They are
given free tickets to Broadway and off-Broadway plays, and they
talk about that work in the classroom. Juilliard also helps them
find part-time jobs so they can support themselves while writing.
</P>
<P>
   In guiding the playwrights, the teachers call upon their own
experience. At one class, after hearing the first act of Rapp's
poetic play in progress, ``Dreams of the Salt Horse,'' Ms. Norman
said that first drafts of plays are often ``like character
auditions.'' Characters are introduced and ``you decide which ones
you want, which you really need,'' she said. ``There has to be time
for the audience's expectations to brew. It's like that great Toni
Morrison line: The audience needs to have a little dread before we
go forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally there is a group assignment. One year, each student
was asked to write a nine-minute play about a cat, with Ms. Norman
and Durang contributing their own sketches _ nine plays about nine
lives _ with Durang's play informally acknowledged as the most
hilarious.
</P>
<P>
   More than 300 writers apply to the Juilliard program every year.
After the applicants are narrowed to 20, Ms. Norman and her
colleagues choose four, with three or four returning from the
previous year. Ms. Goldberg is back for a third session. Those who
are rejected often reapply again and again.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the current students have already gone through other
playwriting programs: Ms. Cunningham at Columbia, Ms. Goldberg and
Goldfarb at New York University. Develle-Winn was discovered at
Howard University, where he was performing his own one-man show.
Ms. Norman found Ms. Laufer, then a comedy writer, at the
University of Montana in Missoula. Her play, ``Fortune,'' was just
optioned for a commercial production.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to talent and commitment, Ms. Norman looks for a
comic sense: ``Chris and I both believe that there's a kind of
intelligence that manifests itself through humor.'' It is also
clear that the course is in playwriting, not screenwriting. She
realizes, however, that most students, trying to diversify their
craft, are privately writing screenplays.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent class, three Juilliard actors read Goldfarb's
``Dulce de Leche,'' a dark comedy about a young married couple
haunted by Holocaust memories during a honeymoon in Buenos Aires.
Hitler is a character in the play.
</P>
<P>
   That day Guare joined Ms. Norman as team leader. Following the
reading, he said: ``What's so brilliant about the play is in using
the terrors of a wedding night to deal with survivor guilt. The
play is about the fear of the future and our need for the past.''
He added that he felt the humor could be even more manic. Shifting
to the question of structure, he suggested that there might be some
way to indicate earlier that the play was going to have such
enormous stylistic shifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the question you have to ask yourself is, What do we
do with memory?'' Guare added. ``You're the only one who can answer
that. In a sense, all American theater is about memory: `Long Day's
Journey,' how to keep the memory alive; Tennessee in `The Glass
Menagerie,' trying to get rid of it, but it keeps coming back. Your
answer will define you as a writer.''
</P>
<P>
   For an exercise, he recommended that Goldfarb write a draft of
the play from the point of view of the female character. ``You
might end up with only five lines from that draft, but it might
answer questions.'' He said it would also help the actors: ``Actors
are like truffle hounds'' looking for clues on the trail of their
characters.
</P>
<P>
   After the playwrights gave their comments, Guare warned: ``Keep
the freshness. Watch out for workshops! This is where plays can get
killed. You have to know when to say goodbye to a play'' and move
on the next one.
</P>
<P>
   The training at Juilliard is meant to be rigorous but
supportive. As Ms. Norman says: ``This is a place where it's safe
to be a writer. We have no agenda so if the work doesn't come in we
sit around and talk. The slate is clean, the door is open, and
anybody who writes something gets it read that week.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
