<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARDEN-EXHIBIT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BRUSH WITH GREATNESS: MARDEN MAKES POETRY IN PAINT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JANET TYSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Brice Marden is an old-fashioned blue-chip artist. His
beautiful abstract pictures, early and recent, grace museum and
high-end private collections worldwide. His activities, inside and
outside his studios in Greece, rural Pennsylvania and his home base
of New York, are the stuff not only of art-critical writing but
also of ``Vanity Fair, Vogue'' and ``W.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, recent paintings, drawings and prints by Marden, 60, are
being presented in a Dallas Museum of Art show that has drawn its
share of international interest. Walking through it is a bit like
bumping into a dynamic acquaintance of long standing: There are
intriguing changes, but the character is consistent _ as
intelligent and engaging as ever.
</P>
<P>
   Organized by DMA Curator of Contemporary Art Charles Wylie,
``Brice Marden, Work of the 1990s'' continues through April 25 and
then goes on tour to Washington, D.C.; Miami; and Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition includes about 50 works, most on loan from
collections. In varying degrees of complexity, each picture
features sensitively painted lines that meander, loop, jog and
otherwise slowly map their respective surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   In earlier works, the strokes of paint and the clusters of lines
they create echo Chinese calligraphy, which Marden claims as an
important influence. Moving into the later images, some of Marden's
lines retain a certain calligraphic irregularity, while others
thicken and become less halting and more fluid.
</P>
<P>
   In either case Marden works slowly, standing back and painting
with a long brush at certain times, moving in more closely at
others, looking to see what developments the painting suggests.
While in close, he also scrapes at the wet paint until bumps from
the picture's canvas surface emerge through the pigment _ a
procedure that further integrates paint and surface.
</P>
<P>
   When Marden was in Dallas for the show's recent opening, he
described his painting process, echoing his words with deft
movements of wrist and arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put one thing down, then go back in with another color and a
form that relates to the other forms _ like an echo, maybe,'' he
said. ``And then I make a lot of readjustments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sort of free association ... a sort of dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   Marden's work nurtures and challenges people who savor the
experience of looking at arbstract art. This is not always a bad
thing _ although Marden often makes paintings that are, despite his
best efforts, simply pretty.
</P>
<P>
   But the work, on balance, is both thoughtful and alluring. If
Marden seduces the senses through his use of color _ with celadon,
rich yellow and other hues that suggest Chinese porcelain glazes _
his best works also contain the aesthetic equivalent of dietary
fiber.
</P>
<P>
   But then, Marden has always been known as a superb colorist _
even during the '70s, when he was coating canvas panels with opaque
layers of color that resulted in, say, a putty-coated rectangle
hung atop one covered with gray.
</P>
<P>
   True, along one edge would be evidence of preceding layers of
paint, which suggested that what was seen wasn't all there was.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Marden for years was classified as a minimalist _
and more or less went along with that pigeonholing, presumably
because it helped him sell artworks.
</P>
<P>
   In the '80s, however, Marden changed what he was doing. He took
a leave of absence from painting for about a year and tried to
figure out ways to marry painting (widely regarded as the most
desirable art form) with drawing and line (which he loved).
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always drawn, and I kept thinking my drawings and
paintings would eventually grow together,'' Marden said. ``But it
didn't happen, and I decided I had to get the drawing in there
somehow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess what I have now are linear paintings, although I never
consciously thought, `I'll do linear paintings.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Chinese poetry and Jackson Pollock showed Marden the way.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of layering colors one on top of the other as he did in
his '70s paintings, he began applying color in a more melodious
way. But, despite the obvious change, Marden's work today strongly
relates to his '70s canvases _ and in a way that shows how far from
minimalistic those early, opaque rectangles were. By opening up his
layers of colors now, Marden reminds us how layered and complex
were his colors 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Continuity. Change. Simplicity. Complexity.
</P>
<P>
   This is engaging work. Go visit it at the Dallas Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
 &QL; 
``Brice Marden, Work of the 1990s''
</P>
<P>
   Through April 25 11 a.m.-4 p.m. Tuesday-Friday, 11 a.m.-5 p.m.
Saturday and Sunday, also 4-9 p.m. Thursday Dallas Museum of Art,
1717 N. Harwood St.
</P>
<P>
   Admission: $5 for adults, $3 for students and senior citizens,
and $1 for children under 12; admission is free after 5 p.m. on
Thursdays.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (214) 922-1200
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
