<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV26-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAD ENERGY ATTRACTS RATS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Friday Feb. 26)  
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As if New Yorkers do not have problems enough already, what with
trigger-happy cops and the very real possibility that Hillary
Clinton will be their next senator, a self-described ``angel
therapist'' has suggested that the city's sewer rat problem may be
caused by New Yorkers' surly attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   In her book ``Angels Guide,'' author Belinda Womack says sewer
rats are psychic sponges that absorb negative energy from humans.
</P>
<P>
   New York has an abundance of rats, she says, because residents
have negative attitudes and foul moods that magnetically attract
rats.
</P>
<P>
   If New Yorkers could ``... create a reality of joy, oneness and
good,'' she says, then the negative feelings would disappear along
with the rats.
</P>
<P>
   While one might wonder if it is not the surly rats whose
negative energy is responsible for attracting swarms of
disease-ridden New Yorkers to New York, I think that Ms. Womack may
well be on to something here, and not simply a new species of
hallucinogenic mushroom.
</P>
<P>
   I am often in a cranky mood (out of beer, can't find the TV
remote, no clean underwear, you name it), which could explain why
my yard is overrun with fire ants. Fire ants are much meaner than
rats. In fact, I wouldn't be surprised if rats moved to New York to
get as far away from them as possible. There are some chemicals
that would take care of my fire ant problem, but they're expensive,
smelly and, from what I've been told, cannot be applied from the
confines of one's air-conditioned living room while watching senior
golf on TV.
</P>
<P>
   A better solution, I see now, is to simply think happy, generous
thoughts about fire ants and then watch them march off toward the
yard of my neighbor, whom I've always found to be annoyingly jovial
and badly in need of something to send him spiraling down the black
hole of despair.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it will take more than the threat of rats or fire
ants to make some people rewire their energy generators from
negative to positive. Take Congress, for instance. (There is so
much negative energy in Washington that some congressmen have even
started looking like rats. Take Henry Hyde for instance.) Could, as
Womack described it, the ``reality of joy, oneness and good'' have
prevented the mess we just went through if the House of
Representatives had looked upon President Clinton not as
``impeachable'' but as ``handsome, neatly coifed and
approachable?''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. Perhaps not.
</P>
<P>
   As with New Yorkers and sewer rats, it's hard to tell whether
negative vibrations bring on unpleasant consequences or the other
way around. I have entered restaurants exuding such positive
vibrations that I half expected to be charged for leaving visible
pits in the walls. Yet that sunny aura is not always sufficient to
ward off unpleasant consequences, including, but not limited to,
the waiter who quit immediately after taking our order. (This
actually happened. We never learned what set him off; perhaps the
thought of serving up yet another grouper amandine was more than he
could bear.)
</P>
<P>
   Service in a restaurant can be fast or slow for a variety of
reasons, but having one's waiter quit before the salad course
arrives is not a possibility that pops first into most people's
minds, ours included.
</P>
<P>
   This incident happened years ago and it is possible that we may
have been sitting there to this day, staring forlornly at our empty
bread plates, wondering if the calamari appetizer we ordered had
arrived yet from Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately another waiter became curious as to why two people
would sit in a restaurant booth for four hours without ordering any
food or even a glass of water and explained the situation, as best
as a situation of that sort can be explained.
</P>
<P>
   My vibrations, needless to say, were considerably less positive
upon leaving the restaurant, but not so bad that I was besieged by
rats.
</P>
<P>
   Which is probably a good thing because, hungry as I was, I might
have eaten one.
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
