<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-IV-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISTORY MEETS REALITY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Back then, it seemed that on every street corner in
Dorchester and Roxbury, young African-American men like John
``B.J'' Mills were trying to sing their way out of poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was our way of trying to get off the streets,'' said Mills.
``It was our way of getting the American dream.''
</P>
<P>
   It was 1968. Unemployment was up in Boston, the country was in
turmoil, Martin Luther King had been assassinated, riots had
erupted, and the government had released a report warning that
America was dividing into two societies: one black and one white _
separate and unequal.
</P>
<P>
   For Mills, a Vietnam-era veteran, the divisions that ripped
through America went against what he was beginning to learn about
himself: that he came from a long line of American soldiers and
musical pioneers. That he was a direct descendant of Barzillai Lew,
a free-born black man who had fought at Bunker Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years later, Mills, now 54, still struggles with the
importance of knowing his family's history and the reality of being
black in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel connected. I'm vested in this country, more than
most,'' said Mills, a clerk at the Boston Medical Center. ``But
when you are black, people don't look at your background or what
your family has done. To them, you are only black. You are
invisible.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of how long blacks have lived in America and how much
they have contributed, they will always face the dilemma of being
true Americans, said Richard Newman of Harvard University's W.E.B.
Du Bois Institute of Afro-American Studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The central question of black identity in America is `Who am
I?' '' said Newman. ``You might be American, but you can't get a
cab to Roxbury. You are never allowed to forget that you are
black.''
</P>
<P>
   This is what happened to one Lew descendant, Eric Brooks, 28, a
cousin of Mills. In 1997, when he was accepted to the University of
California at Berkeley School of Law, he found himself in the
center of the national debate on affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   The University of California Board of Regents had repealed all
race and gender-based preferences programs, and Brooks was left as
the only first-year black law student enrolled at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very difficult,'' he said. ``But I didn't want to walk
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Brooks was marching with Jesse Jackson and speaking
for affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   During that time, he began to recall the drives to Martha's
Vineyard with his grandmother, Ethel Buzzelle, and his great aunt,
Mae Theresa Bonitto. The two women would tell him stories about
Barzillai Lew and Barzillai's father, Primus, who was also a
musician and soldier in the French and Indian War.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would roll my eyes. I didn't want to hear another Barzillai
and Primus Lew story,'' said Brooks, a native of Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, to say my family goes back to the Revolutionary War is a
very proud statement to make,'' he said. ``But at the same time
there is the question of where would they be if my family were
white?''
</P>
<P>
   The current generation of Lew family members is as diverse as
Mills and Brooks. They range from mechanics to engineers. Gerard
Ashe, 46, is a state trooper. Kym Lew Nelson, 41, a Harvard
University graduate, is an executive at Cincinnati-based Procter &AMP;
Gamble. Many live in eastern Massachusetts, but others are
scattered across the country, from Indiana to California.
</P>
<P>
   Although they share the same heritage, some don't know each
other. For instance, Mills and Brooks have never met. In this
sense, they are typical of many American families. And as in many
families, one or two older members keep the memories alive.
</P>
<P>
   The musical thread that has run through the family for 200 years
still remains, but it has frayed somewhat. And while some family
members like Mills and Brooks have remain interested in Lew family
stories, others are like Brooks's uncle, Neil Brooks, who says
``that and a dollar will get you a cup of coffee.''
</P>
<P>
   For Mills _ as for Brooks _ it was an aunt, Laura Ashe, who
began passing down family history. He was serving a tour of duty in
Korea during the Vietnam era when he began receiving letters from
his aunt. She wrote of the family's military and musical
background, how ancestors had harbored runaway slaves, died in the
Civil War, served in World War II, and had become music pioneers,
breaking color barriers time again in the 19th and 20th centuries.
</P>
<P>
   These stories were especially important to Mills, who still
doesn't know his own father: ``That has been the most painful thing
of my life, to never know the other half, the man who fathered
me.''
</P>
<P>
   While overseas, the stories he read in letters from home helped
him know who he was. Even so, life was not easy for him, especially
after his discharge from the military in 1966. Like many black
Americans, Mills returned to a society that still overflowed with
prejudice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I became an angry young man,'' said Mills. ``Boston was a
hostile place for people of color.''
</P>
<P>
   He remembers wearing his military uniform while waiting for a
table at a swank restaurant in downtown Boston. He was skipped over
several times, as if he wasn't there. And like every black person
who has ever felt invisible _ Mills was outraged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here I was in my uniform, my country's uniform, and I was
being ignored,'' he said. ``By the time the young lady asked me
what I wanted, I had lost my appetite.''
</P>
<P>
   Mills worked in a factory at the time, but he believed it would
be music that lifted him out of poverty.
</P>
<P>
   It was the era of ``Doo-wop,'' a form of a cappella singing
popularized by groups like the Temptations and Frankie Lymon and
Teenagers. Young men would gather on the street corners singing.
The best four singers would become a quartet, said Mills.
</P>
<P>
   By then, Mills, a baritone dared to try out twice for a spot in
the Temptations. He was good, but not that good.
</P>
<P>
   The turning point in his musical career came in 1968, recalled
his wife, Linnell Mills.
</P>
<P>
   His group, ``The Elegant Four,'' was singing at Estelle's
Riveria, the popular black entertainment spot in Roxbury. They were
wearing black bell bottoms and Mills wore a hot pink top with a
large collar.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they began singing, there was a hush. You could hear
every word,'' Linnell Mills recalls.
</P>
<P>
   They all believed the successful gig would be their start to
fame, but the group disbanded after one of the member's personal
life got in the way.
</P>
<P>
   Mill's idea of the American Dream changed from fame to a family.
He would marry Linnell in 1970. While he found steady work for 20
years with the Boston Public Schools, he still loves music,
breaking into song in the middle of conversations.
</P>
<P>
   Without a high school degree, he would rise to the assistant
director of medical records department for Boston City Hospital.
After Boston City merged with Boston University Medical Center, his
job was scaled down to clerk.
</P>
<P>
   Mills received his high school diploma in 1995. Over the years,
his anger cooled, his feelings warmed toward the country that his
family had done much to shape.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years ago, he placed a large American flag outside his
house.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the way I feel about this country,'' he said. ``I didn't
have this (the flag) up when I came out the military, believe me.
It was an evolutionary process.''
</P>
<P>
   In his eyes, he has reached the American dream: A good job, a
loving family, including Leah, his 14-year-old daughter, and his
son, Kharay, 19, a student at Boston College of Communication.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of what anybody else thinks about me, and aside
from my Lew background _ I paid my dues,'' Mills said. ``I am an
American.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his heritage, Mills is proud, but he keeps it in
perspective: ``I tell my children being a Lew is not going to open
any doors.''
</P>
<P>
   And in spite of their long history, stretching back to before
the Revolutionary War, the Lews are not mentioned in the same
breath with the other noted families of old Boston _ the Adamses,
Lowells, Forbeses. They have gone largely unheralded in the history
books.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been lost, invisible in the making and remaking of
Boston's history,'' said Gerald Gill, a professor of history at
Tufts University..
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Mills has taken the torch from his aunt and is
passing the family's history down to the young. As he looked over
family photos last week, he grabbed a visiting cousin. They sat
down and he pointed to an old photo of four young children. Their
names are scribbled at the top of the picture. It's his grandmother
and her siblings.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see,'' he starts. ``This is you. This is your history.''
</P>
</TEXT>
