   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   JASPER _ JASPER, Texas _ William ``Bill'' King's father, ill
with emphysema and heartsick about a son convicted of capital
murder, could be the only witness to take the stand in King's
defense. Defense lawyers were to begin Wednesday afternoon
presenting their case to jurors about why King should not be
sentenced to death. Closing arguments are scheduled for Thursday
morning, after which the jury will decide whether King should be
sentenced to life in prison or to death by lethal injection.
(Gamino, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-UNDECIDED _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush, fresh from
another round of talks with out-of-staters who want him to run,
remains publicly undecided about a presidential race. But sources
close to Bush say he has made up his mind and will announce the
formation of an exploratory committee to get the ball rolling
within weeks. (Herman, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   TYPHOID-OUTBREAK _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Frozen mamey products
from countries such as Guatemala have been pulled from the
marketplace because of a typhoid outbreak in Florida. But fresh
mamey from these nations was never allowed in the United States
because of sanitary conditions in the countries of origin, and with
health officials conceding salmonella typhi can survive prolonged
periods of freezing, one wonders why frozen mamey was ever allowed
into the country. The FDA is putting thought into the question now.
Investigators are focusing on processing points in Guatemala, the
source of more than one frozen brand name. Meanwhile, tests on
confiscated samples conducted by Department of Agriculture have
been inconclusive, failing to isolate any `salmonella typhi.
(developing) (Donald, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   AIRFORCE-CUTS _ The Air Force's effort to squeeze more space
technology from smaller research budgets will cost laboratory jobs
at Wright-Patterson Air Force and elsewhere, lawmakers and
congressional sources say. The Air Force Research Laboratory is
preparing to announce job cuts nationwide, possibly by the end of
the month, as it struggles to downsize to a smaller budget by Oct.
1. Lawmakers are irate because the cuts reflect abrupt changes as
the Air Force has killed or severely cut back some programs to
funnel an extra $100 million into space-based radar and laser
programs. ``The abruptness of it all will result in an enormous
waste of science and human capital,'' said Michael Gessel, an aide
to U.S. Rep. Tony Hall, D-Dayton. (Gaffney, Dayton Daily News).
</P>
<P>
   MISSGAMB _ A Biloxi casino wants to fill in 54 acres of the
Mississippi Sound to expand its operation. Another proposed casino
project in Gulfport would take away the last access to recreational
waters in that city. Gambling has been good to the Mississippi
coast, but how much is too much? (Konigsmark, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   EVERGLADES-BIRDS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The word on wading
birds for 1999: Better. But not great. For wood storks, herons,
egrets and ibises looking to feather their nests this spring, the
Everglades is once again rolling out a soggy welcome mat. Fewer
birds than average are flocking to South Florida's marshes, where
rain has pushed water levels nearly to the brim for yet another
yer. (King, Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON/POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   COUNSEL _ WASHINGTON _ The Senate Governmental Affairs Committee
holds a hearing Wednesday to review the law authorizing independent
counsels. Many in both parties say the post should be abolished or
drastically revised after the impeachment and Iran-contra
investigations. (Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton holds a joint news
conference with Jerry Rawlings, the president of Ghana. (Deans, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-PRICES _ WASHINGTON _ Members of Congress and pharmacy
experts will discuss the extent to which Americans buy prescription
drugs in Mexico and Canada and how American pharmacies struggle to
compete. Rep. Jim Turner, D-Lufkin, is among the event organizers.
Panelists will include Dr. Marv Shepard, from the University of
Texas and John Marvin of the National Council of Senior Citizens.
Moscoso, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE _ WASHINGTON _ The National Bipartisan Commission on
the Future of Medicare holds a meeting, just days before their
deadline to propose a reform plan. (Lipman, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-FRAUD _ WASHINGTON _ Health and Human Services
Secretary Donna Shalala joins Attorney General Janet Reno at
satellite-linked rallies hosted by AARP to recruit the elderly to
fight Medicare fraud, waste and abuse. Doctors (AMA) are upset, but
hospitals (AHA) approve. With poll results, info-box. (Mollison,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   ISAKSON _ On his first day as congressman-elect. Trying to get
with him and key staffers to see what House leaders say about his
appointments, house-hunting, swearing-in, etc. (Visser, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   w/BAXTER-COLUMN _ Washington can use Johnny Isakson's brand of
bipartisanship. The question is, will it? Or will it chew him up
and spit him out? (Baxter, Atlanta JOurnal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   GACLINTON _ The donor list for Clinton's defense fund is
released Wednesday. We highlight the Georgians who gave. (Foskett,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS _ WASHINGTON _ The Census Bureau will conduct a
traditional head count for congressional reapportionment, but a
Clinton administration official says the bureau plans to use
statistical sampling for all other purposes in the 2000 census. At
the census news conference today, Southeastern Legal Foundation
Director Matt Glavin says he will again sue over the sampling plan.
(Sherman, Cox News Service)
</P>
