<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-III-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THROUGH CENTURIES, A FAMILY UNITED BY THE LOVE OF MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ William Edward Lew, who was born in 1865, the year
slavery was abolished in this country, moved audiences of all races
with a tenor voice so strong it seemed to shake a room.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, in 1943, when he was 78, too old to be a star any more,
his life took on an unusual turn _ he joined the merchant marine
during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said they needed `men,' '' a Boston Globe article quoted
him as saying at the time.
</P>
<P>
   From the turn of the century to the second world war, members of
the Lew family, one of the oldest in Massachusetts, distinguished
themselves as African-American artists during an era when the
country was struggling to find its own identity.
</P>
<P>
   Descended from Barzillai Lew, who was born a free man in Groton,
Mass., and who fought at the battle of Bunker Hill, the Lews are
rare among modern black American families. Their history was not
obliterated by slavery. They can trace their story to before the
founding of this country.
</P>
<P>
   A fifer and drummer during the Revolution _ and later the leader
of a popular family band in the Boston area _ Lew passed his
musical skills down to his descendants.
</P>
<P>
   By early in this century, William Lew's nephew had become an
arranger for the white minstrel star Al Jolson. Another nephew,
Harry ``Bucky'' Lew, a trained violinist, broke racial barriers in
1902 when he joined the Pawtucketville Athletic Club of The New
England Basketball League and became the first black man ever to
play professional basketball. And yet another relative was the
first woman of color to play with Arthur Fiedler's Boston Pops.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the family upbringing,'' said Frank Dorman, a Cambridge
author who documented the family in his book, ``Twenty Families of
Color in Massachusetts.'' ``The education, the atmosphere. They all
had instruments. Whenever they got together they played. Music
became a family tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   The daughters, nieces, and cousins of these musical pioneers are
still alive. They are now great grandmothers and grand aunts _ true
last links to the family legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can remember my uncle Willie had a marvelous tenor voice,''
said 83-year-old Mae Theresa Bonitto of William Lew. ``I can see
him as an elderly man at my aunt's home playing the piano and
singing.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura Ashe, 79, recalls that her mother, Marion, a pianist,
would treat her children before bedtime to a mini-concert. ``She
would play Handel's `Largo' _ my favorite,'' said Ashe. Francis
Johnson, 69, the youngest of Bucky's daughters, still has her
father's violin: ``It's precious to me, it's all I have of my
father,'' she said. ``As the story goes _ my mother fell in love
with my father while he was playing in a band.''
</P>
<P>
   It was essential as children that they take piano and violin
lessons. As adults, they joined choirs and frequented operas and
jazz sets. Of all these women, only Bonitto would become a
professional performer, a dancer in the 1930s for Jimmie Lunceford,
one of the big band greats.
</P>
<P>
   Music is still central: Bonitto's home often hums with the
sounds of John Coltrane. Ashe, who resumed piano lessons at age 60,
practices on her small electric piano.
</P>
<P>
   In different ways, they are keeping their family's history
alive. Bucky's middle child, Phyllis Lew, 78, of Roxbury has tried
since the 1970s to get her father's name into the Basketball Hall
of Fame in Springfield.
</P>
<P>
   ```My father certainly deserves to be recognized,'' said Lew.
</P>
<P>
   By family rights, Bucky's oldest daughter, Eleanor Johnson, 88,
the oldest of these women, should have inherited her ancestor's
Revolutionary War powderhorn. Instead, she prefers that it stay at
the DuSable Museum of African-American History in Chicago for
people to see _ and where her uncle, one of the museum's founders,
placed it.
</P>
<P>
   And Bonitto has collected hundreds of photos and documents to
prove that the extraordinary stories they tell of the family are no
myth.
</P>
<P>
   The Lew family's musical path had been paved long ago by its
patriarch. After the Revolutionary War, Barzillai Lew, his wife and
13 children formed a musical band known from Boston to Maine. In
those days, black musicians performed classical songs for
high-society events. But after the Civil War, blacks began to
develop their own style of music. It was symbolic in a way, helping
the country detach itself from the strains of European culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the beginning of American popular music,'' said Gerald
Gill, associate professor of history at Tufts University.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, blacks saw ways to develop their talents
``despite the fact that for every new avenue open to them twice as
many barriers were thrown to prevent their advances'' said Eileen
Southern, a music historian and former Harvard professor, in her
book ``The Music of Black Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Until early in this century, blacks were barred from performing
in operas, but many like William Lew were accepted in some of the
finest music schools in New England.
</P>
<P>
   As a child, probably in the 1870s, Lew and his sister Edith
White performed duets at local churches. Initially, he was
musically educated by his father but would later study piano and
voice at the New England Conservatory of Music.
</P>
<P>
   When he was only 18, in 1884 Lew formed the Lew Ensemble, a male
quartet that toured the country. He played organ for Morning Star
Baptist Church in Boston and was known as the first black person to
conduct an all-white orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   His nephew, Carl White, achieved even greater success. As
evidence of how few opportunities were available to black
musicians, White, who also trained at the New England Conservatory,
would become the first known black man to sing in a Boston cafe in
the early 1900s, according to historians and family members.
</P>
<P>
   But his talent would take him much further than cramped, smoky
restaurants. In 1923, he formed a trio that would include the black
entertainer Paul Robeson, according to a letter he wrote to
Bonitto. Later, White would become a special arranger of spirituals
for Jolson, the white entertainer who gained fame with his black
face routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Singing with Al Jolson would be a racial breakthrough,'' said
Gill. ``But at what cost? How do you think they felt with Jolson
singing `Mammy' and in black face?''
</P>
<P>
   Still, this was one of few avenues a black entertainer could
take at the time. It allowed White to form his own successful bands
and to travel the country.
</P>
<P>
   But most black musicians, regardless of their talent, needed a
second job to make a living. William Lew and his sister Edith were
tailors.
</P>
<P>
   Most often, said Gill, black musicians taught piano lessons to
Boston's black elite.
</P>
<P>
   ``A woman was supposed to know how to play the piano. It was
part of the dating ritual. She was suppose to entertain her suitor
by playing the piano,'' said Gill.
</P>
<P>
   As a young woman, Bonitto would take piano lessons from a close
relative, Doris Dandridge, who had a studio on Massachusetts and
Columbus avenues in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Ashe recalls finding Dandridge, who had by now studied in France
and was a popular pianist in Boston, sometimes playing alone in the
studio.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1940s, Dandridge appeared as a guest pianist for The
Boston Pops. To see a relative and a black woman perform at
Symphony Hall was the height of the family's pride.
</P>
<P>
   World War II was just beginning and William Lew who had achieved
unthinkable goals as a black musician, was now a retired music
professor. He wanted to do more for the country, said Bonitto. In
1943, at age 78, he joined the merchant marine and for one year
served as a cook. He died five years later.
</P>
<P>
   Proof of how proud the family was of his service, his wife in
1949 made no mention of his illustrious music career on his death
records, points out Dorman, the Cambridge author. Instead, he was
simply described as a seaman.
</P>
</TEXT>
