<HEADER>
A7881 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRAHAM-STUDIO-ART-NYT     02-24 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAHAM-STUDIO-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADIEU TO THE BOARDS FROM WHICH GRAHAM'S DANCERS LEAPT 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Fla.) (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By RALPH BLUMENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With misty-eyed dancers invoking the departed Martha
Graham and Doris Duke, the curtain came down last week on a
long-running real estate drama involving a small tract below an
off-ramp on the Manhattan side of the Queensboro Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Wreckers began tearing apart the Martha Graham School for
Contemporary Dance at 316 East 63d Street, the home of the renowned
dance company for almost 50 years and for a studio that draws about
500 students a year from all over the world. It was a finale that
the artistic director, Ron Protas, said would have been
inconceivable in the lifetime of Miss Graham, the dance modernist
who died in 1991 at 96, or in the lifetime of Miss Duke, the
tobacco heiress who was her fervent champion and died two years
later at 80.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doris' passions were jazz, gospel, and preserving old
houses,'' said Protas, as workers pried up the floorboards of the
vine-draped, three-story town house where Nureyev, Fonteyn, and
Makarova danced, where Madonna, Woody Allen and Liza Minelli
studied and where Jacqueline Onassis watched.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doris also took classes here,'' Protas said. ``She said,
`Martha, darling, don't worry, this will always be.'''
</P>
<P>
   But for reasons entangled in the intrigues over the $1.2 billion
Duke estate and the financial struggles of many arts groups today,
the heavily mortgaged headquarters was sold under pressure last
summer, sending the company to temporary sites downtown while
leaving it nearly $1.5 million richer. It expects to be housed in
larger new quarters in the apartment building that is to rise on
the East 63d Street site next year.
</P>
<P>
   Nostalgia ruled on Friday as dozens of dancers and students
stepped one last time through the wrought iron gate to wander the
building, snip sprigs of ivy and pluck souvenirs from boxes of
waterlogged photographs (there had been a flood in the basement).
</P>
<P>
   Martin Lofsnes, a teacher and principal dancer who performed the
role of He Who Summons in ``Dark Meadow'' this season, drafted a
fellow dancer to help him carry off a chipped stone bench from the
garden. ``Better it should go to family,'' said Protas, who waved
his approval.
</P>
<P>
   Many gravitated to a far corner of the garden where the gnarled
trunk of a towering sumac tree bulged through an unyielding chain
link fence that cut deep into the wood. The fate of the tree is
uncertain, although Protas remembered that Miss Duke once spent
$225,000 to save a single tree in Newport, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   ``My teachers in school would tell me about this tree, how it
grew through, basically, steel,'' said Jennifer Binford of Utah, a
first-year student. ``The first time I came here I just lay my body
on it, wanting to absorb the energy and the history.''
</P>
<P>
   For three and a half decades starting in the '20s, Miss Graham
operated out of a studio in Greenwich Village, developing a new
vocabulary of movement that thrust dance into the 20th century. In
1952, Lila Acheson Wallace, co-founder of Reader's Digest,
presented her with the building on East 63d Street, which had been
owned by the Baroness Bethsabee de Rothschild. It was there in the
'70s that Miss Duke, the only child of James Buchanan Duke,
president of the American Tobacco Company, and thought to be the
world's richest woman, met Miss Graham and became a dance student,
patron and member of the Graham board.
</P>
<P>
   ``She gave in an erratic way,'' recalled Protas, who also became
close to Miss Duke. ``We'd ask for $5,000, and she'd give
$30,000.'' Around 1992, he recalled, the company needed money and
discussed with Miss Duke a $1 million loan that she would ``stand
behind.''
</P>
<P>
   The company already had borrowed $200,000 in a mortgage on the
school. Protas said that Miss Duke agreed to ask Chemical Bank to
grant the Graham company a second mortgage of $1 million with the
idea, he said, of asking the bank later to forgive the loan.
</P>
<P>
   But in the months before Miss Duke's death in October 1993,
Protas said, his frequent calls to her suddenly went unreturned.
She had rewritten her will several times, in the end naming her
butler, Bernard Lafferty, as co-executor, along with the U. S.
Trust Company, an investment management house.
</P>
<P>
   U. S. Trust later lent Lafferty $825,000 under circumstances
that led a New York judge in May 1994 to remove the two as
co-executors. The state's highest court, however, restored them as
executors on appeal in January 1996. Lafferty, who had acknowledged
problems with alcohol and was taking medications, was found dead in
his bed in November 1996 at age 51.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before Miss Duke died, Protas and Barbara M. Groves,
then the company's executive director, had continued calling her,
fruitlessly, for word about the loan. Finally, they heard from a
lawyer for Lafferty and Miss Duke, William Doyle of Chicago, that
Chemical had been replaced and U. S. Trust would not grant the
loan.
</P>
<P>
   After spirited appeals, the two Graham officials said, U. S.
Trust agreed, but on difficult terms: the money was to be repaid in
five years, with no mention of a guarantee by Miss Duke.
</P>
<P>
   As feared, the company fell behind in its monthly payments of
more than $6,000.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for U. S. Trust, Allison Kellogg, said the company
never commented on client relationships. Doyle said he would have
no comment.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1996, Todd Dellinger, who was hired by the Graham
board as development director, then managing director, found that
the Graham company had stopped making payments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I was maladroit,'' acknowledged Mr. Protas. ``But we
were in a moment of rebirth.''
</P>
<P>
   Delores Barr Weaver, who sits on the Graham board and with her
husband, Wayne, owns the Jacksonville Jaguars football team,
offered U. S. Trust $350,000 to excuse the loan but the offer was
refused, said Bill Prescott, the Weavers' chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   When the sale of the property seemed the only option, he said,
the Weavers asked U. S. Trust to settle for the $1 million, without
the interest. That too was rejected.
</P>
<P>
   By early 1997, the Duke estate's assets had been transferred to
the Doris Duke Charitible Foundation. Protas said he offered to
name the building for Miss Duke for the foundation's help in saving
it, but got no response.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Edelman Spero, the foundation's president, said last week
that the policy was to award grants to arts agencies for
redistribution, rather than to give money directly to individual
arts companies.
</P>
<P>
   J. Carter Brown, a trustee of the Duke foundation, subsequently
said that the foundation would soon be announcing a $1 million
grant to the Library of Congress to acquire archives and videotapes
of performances by the Graham company.
</P>
<P>
   The Graham board sold its property to an East Side developer,
Benedetto Caiola, for $3 million. U. S. Trust collected the full
amount due, nearly $1.5 million. After paying debts, the Graham
company ended up with about $500,000 cash plus $400,000 to be put
into an endowment. The Weavers severed their own business
relationship with U. S. Trust.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
