<HEADER>
A7882 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAMILY-I-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-AR     02-24 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-I-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 CAMBRIDGE, Mass.: ... independent nation.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The revolution was about achieving freedom, but not about
ending slavery,'' says James Horton, author of ``Black
Bostonians,'' which chronicles black life in Boston from slavery to
the modern era.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was about attaining freedom from the British. For blacks,
it might have meant that too for them, but mostly it offered the
hope of ending slavery as an institution, or personally.''
</P>
<P>
   Lew joined Captain John Ford's company of the 27th regiment as a
fifer in the summer of the 1775. About that same time, the mounting
concern that black men bearing arms could eventually turn on white
patriots led General George Washington to bar all blacks from
enlisting in the war.
</P>
<P>
   Washington reversed that order after the British promised
freedom for those black men who fought for them. Eventually, 5,000
black soldiers would risk their lives in the American cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black enlistment was generally longer,'' said Horton. ``They
were at a disadvantage, often serving in the place of their master,
their master's kids. This didn't mean they didn't serve for the
same patriotic reasons. They were fighting the same injustice.''
</P>
<P>
   In June 1775, Lew and other black men fought in the Battle of
Bunker Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Although the United States allowed slavery until the mid-19th
century, Massachusetts _ one of the first colonies to legalize
slavery _ abolished it in 1783.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Lew built a home on a sizable tract of land in
what is now Lowell, near Varnum Road and Totman Street. As
Barzillai aged, his large family and the townfolk called him by the
nickname ``Old Zeal.'' For a century, the street where he lived was
called ``Old Zeal Road.''
</P>
<P>
   Lew and his sons tended the farm and worked on construction of
the Middlesex Canal, between 1793 and 1805, said Martha Mayo, a
historian at the University of Massachusetts at Lowell. Much of the
waterway is filled in now, but it was once the main corridor to
transport goods from Boston to Lowell.
</P>
<P>
   With the sparse written record of Lew's life, it is difficult to
separate fact from legend. One story from the DuSable Museum of
African-American History in Chicago places Barzillai and Primus
among the group of black men at the Boston Massacre, where ex-slave
Crispus Attucks was killed in 1770. Family members and a few
history books claim the family performed at the inauguration of
George Washington. ``The Colored Patriots,'' written by black
Bostonian abolitionist William Nell, has Lew leading a ``guerrilla
band'' made up of his sons. That would have been nearly impossible,
however, since his oldest child was only 9 when Lew was discharged
from the service.
</P>
<P>
   What is known through books and newspaper articles is that in
the post-Revolution years Lew, his wife, and children made up a
traveling dancing band that performed from Boston to Portland.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all possessed a natural talent for music, and most of
them could play any kind of wind or stringed instrument _ the girls
as much as boys,'' according to a Dec. 31, 1889, article in the
Lowell Morning Mail.
</P>
<P>
   The Lews would perform at elegant parties and college
commencements in New England. Although blacks were relegated to the
balconies of white churches at the time, the Lews would sing in
choirs and play the piano during the services. Always standing
proud, the Lews on Sundays were known as some of the most stylish
citizens in town. Lew's children spent so much time performing in
Boston that they lived there in the winter.
</P>
<P>
   As adults, most of the Lew children became laborers, farmers and
musicians. Some, however, took on prominent social roles.
</P>
<P>
   Lew's daughter, Lucy Dalton, lived with her husband, Thomas
Dalton, a black abolitionist, in Charlestown. One son is described
in the 1889 Lowell Mail reminiscence as tall, dignified in
appearance with ``fine features.'' He was well-educated ``and a man
of some property and consequences.'' He rode in a coach and owned
the largest library in the Lowell area.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it wasn't for the degradation to which the race had been
reduced, he would have been chosen for the first offices of his
town if not the state,'' according to the article.
</P>
<P>
   Through records, it's clear that owning land was important to
Barzillai Lew. He sold land to his children, and when he died in
1822 he left the farm to sons, Zadock and Zimri. The latter died in
a train wreck. When Zadock, a popular musician, died, his wife,
needing money to live on, sold a large part of the farm and a
collection of his instruments, many of which were bought by his
siblings.
</P>
<P>
   Even to this day, the Lews have tried to keep their ancestors'
belongings in the family. For a while, Barzillai Lew's powder horn,
now in Chicago's DuSable Museum, was passed down to the oldest
grandchild in each generation.
</P>
<P>
   Bonitto, who in her youth danced for Jimmie Lunceford, a popular
black band leader in New York, keeps photos and vital records of
each family member in neat, organized folders. The stories of
Barzillai Lew, the proud musician and landowner, are passed down to
the young just like they were once passed to her and her older
sister Ethel Ursela.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always been told about our family. Always,'' said
Bonitto.
</P>
<P>
   That Lew tradition of passing down information and land would be
instrumental in the next chapter of American history. The Lew
farmhouse, a simple six-bedroom home built by one of Lew's
grandchildren, would become a secret station on the road to freedom
in the years leading to the Civil War.
</P>
</TEXT>
