</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUG-PRICES25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HIGH DRUG PRICES SPUR BUYING IN MEXICO, FORUM TOLD
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Americans pay higher prices for prescription drugs
than consumers in any other country, a panel of experts said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something is broken in this market,'' said Steven
Schondelmeyer(cq), associate dean of the College of Pharmacy at the
University of Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Schondelmeyer and other pharmacy experts told a congressional
forum that pharmaceutical companies make the highest profits of any
business in the U.S. _ about 16 cents of each dollar paid by the
consumer.
</P>
<P>
   The average Fortune 500 company makes about five cents per
dollar profit, and the gap between them and pharmaceutical
companies ``has been getting wider over the last decade,''
Schondelmeyer said.
</P>
<P>
   The expense of prescription drugs and the stress and hardship it
causes senior citizens has been a focus for Rep. Jim Turner,
D-Texas, one of three members of Congress who organized the
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Turner has been trying to make prescription drugs available to
Medicare beneficiaries at substantially reduced prices. As part of
a congressional task force on the issue, Turner commissioned a
study that found that some senior citizens in his district are
paying twice as much as drug companies charge large customers such
as health maintenance organizations.
</P>
<P>
   At the meeting, Turner spoke of a growing problem in Texas,
where cash-strapped senior citizens resort to buying prescription
drugs in Mexico, and not only in the border towns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ran into a fellow the other day in my East Texas district
who says that he's got a buddy that flies him down into the
interior of Mexico, and they get a better price down there,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Buying drugs in Mexico is a dangerous practice, since drugs sold
in Mexico are not approved by the federal Food and Drug
Administration and are not sold by trained pharmacists who can
answer questions or give advice, said Marvin Shepherd, director of
the Center for Pharmacoeconomic Studies at the University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like buying a Hershey bar,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he said, the prescription drug business in Mexico
is thriving. One out of four people who cross the border comes back
with prescription drugs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Nuevo Laredo, pharmacies and tequila drive the economy,''
Shepherd said.
</P>
<P>
   Although most people who buy prescription drugs in Mexico are
under 35 and buy drugs such as Valium and Rohypnol to sell in large
cities around the United States for recreational purposes, there is
still a population of seniors who cross the border because they
simply can't afford to pay U.S. prices for medicine, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal of the Mexican market can also be seen on Internet
pages. One page offers an e-mail list of Mexican pharmacies
offering medicines for 80 percent less than at U.S. pharmacies _
and without a prescription.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
