<HEADER>
A7884 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT &LR;      02-24 1150
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK TALK: BETTING ON BUZZ AND SYNERGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the wagering wonder world of book publishing, celebrity has
its purpose. And so it is almost appropriate that without
publishing a single book, Tina Brown's new book-publishing company
is receiving and encouraging submissions from literary agents, has
already consummated two deals and hopes to announce two bigger
nonfiction ones next week.
</P>
<P>
   How does a new publisher demonstrate effectiveness in the
editing, marketing, promoting and distribution of books? Can Ms.
Brown's skills and pizazz as a magazine editor translate to books?
</P>
<P>
   Many agents think the answer is yes. Others in the industry are
more doubtful. For the believers, it is partly wishful thinking,
because an agent's happiness quotient zooms whenever there is a new
buyer for a writer's work. This is particularly true now because of
the perception that the book-publishing universe is in contraction,
not expansion. This is why it is not surprising that much of the
talk in publishing is about Talk Miramax Books, a shank of the new
Brown, Miramax and Hearst company called Miramax Talk Media.
</P>
<P>
   The company will also publish Talk magazine, edited by Ms.
Brown, with movies and television programs to come. The books will
be distributed by Hyperion, which is a sister company and which
will initially handle such matters as foreign rights.
</P>
<P>
   When publishers are ``being gobbled up at a terrifying rate, we
welcome any newcomers,'' said agent Lynn Nesbit. ``Why would we
think they couldn't succeed?'' she said of Talk Miramax Books. ``It
helps to have somebody hip, and they have a serious editor in
chief.'' Ms. Nesbit said she had not submitted any projects to the
new publisher, but that younger agents in her agency had.
</P>
<P>
   There had always been a nonwincing snap about Ms. Brown's method
of putting out Vanity Fair and The New Yorker, a belief that she
not only had a mastery of marketing and hype, but also the ability
to somehow eyeball that trend just around the curve. There is no
reason to believe she will lose her ability to divine trends, but a
trend has to last a long time to make a successful book. Moreover,
it is a lot harder to generate the excitement for a book that
roosts on bookstore shelves than it is for a sizzling magazine
article that's here today and gone tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that is the gamble of Gail Ross, a Washington-based
literary agent who sold Talk Miramax Books for a low six-figure
advance in one of the company's first two acquisitions: a sort of
the art of how to run a business based on the psychological lessons
culled from Shakespeare, to be written by former diplomat Kenneth
Adelman and former Lockheed Martin Corp. chairman Norman Augustine.
</P>
<P>
   Two other major publishers were after the manuscript, but Talk
Miramax Books won out, not only because of Ms. Brown's glitz but at
least as persuasively because of the speed with which its editor in
chief and president, Jonathan Burnham, moved to make the purchase.
( Burnham came to the new venture from Viking Penguin, where he was
a senior editor.)
</P>
<P>
   ``My intention was to bring the authors to New York to meet
publishers,'' Ms. Ross said, ``but Jonathan was in Washington, was
told about the book, came to my office and took it back to New
York. The next day he bought it.'' Such decisiveness isn't always
the norm.
</P>
<P>
   Simon &AMP; Schuster also has a Shakespeare on business leadership
in the works. ``There's a race, so why not do something to get a
lot of attention?'' Ms. Ross said. ``Why do we care about
Shakespeare? It's a book that could use a little dazzle, and this
is the extra dazzle we gained. With Tina involved, we'll get a lot
of attention, and their first list of books will get a lot of
attention.''
</P>
<P>
   The other book acquired by Burnham, for about $90,000, is a
novel by Frances Park to be titled ``When My Sister Was Cleopatra
Moon,'' which will be excerpted in Talk, where Burnham also is the
literary editor. There it is, that media hip-hop word, synergy.
</P>
<P>
   Molly Friedrich, Ms. Park's agent, said, ``There's no reason,
with all their backing, they can't thrive as book publishers.'' She
added: ``Jonathan gets on a plane to close a deal. There's great
dispatch and energy there. When you get an editor who blubbers for
a book, you can't do better than that.'' (Ms. Friedrich sold the
novel's German rights Wednesday for $50,000.)
</P>
<P>
   The company's philosophy is all about synergy, a pinballing of a
writer's work from book to magazine excerpt, or magazine article to
book, or either one to movie or television, or even movie to novel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a shared taste,'' Ms. Brown says of herself and
Burnham, ``and the guy with the shared taste is just down the hall.
Something in the works now came about because of a photographer
doing covers. We suddenly realized a big truth _ Jonathan talked to
him and we talked and we thought book.''
</P>
<P>
   Burnham said: ``We can put together very convincing arguments to
come with us. There's a lot to be said for being on a small list
like ours, with our energy and the marketing abilities we bring to
it. We think laterally, and when we buy a book we buy a lot of
potential elements _ buy a magazine, television, movies, on a
case-by-case basis.''
</P>
<P>
   What Talk Miramax Books actually buys is not only the book, but
the first option to turn a project upside down into something
additional and quite different from its original packaging.
</P>
<P>
   Which is precisely what worries some authors and their agents.
One agent in a prominent talent agency who talked only on the
condition of anonymity said: ``If I submit a book to them it will
be read by movie people and magazine people, and I can't control
that. And not many of us are willing to let rights slip away in
such a fairly dramatic fashion. This is particularly dangerous
because of the many hats everyone wears over there.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the agent said that the book market ``is terrible right
now; a lot of publishers are publishing books poorly. There's
something sexy about being on the ground floor with a new
publishing house with an aggressive stance.''
</P>
<P>
   The new company's first catalog will be out this fall with its
2000 Spring list of 15 books, including titles inherited from
Miramax Books, which published mainly film scripts and other
movie-related books. Miramax Books was merged with the new company
and its former head, Susan Dalsimer, is now publisher.
</P>
<P>
   Burnham's answer to author-agent trepidation is speed. Decisions
on what Miramax Talk Media will want to turn into what will be made
very quickly, within days of submission, and the agents will get
their option rights back in a flash.
</P>
<P>
   Velocity. Publishers competing for a book with Ms. Brown and
Burnham will find themselves running. Perhaps sometimes in circles,
but nonetheless running.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
