<HEADLINE>
ATTN EDITORS:  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: Photos are being sent to NYT clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)  
 For Immediate Release
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Meet the Lews, one of Massachusetts' oldest black families.
Their story, recounted in a four-part series, is a saga of
generations and a civil rights document. Freed from slavery before
the Revolution, the Lews have participated in the decisive passages
of American history, from aiding runaway slaves through the
Underground Railroad to serving in World War II. A story of
struggle, success and love &LR;   &UR; by Globe staff reporter Tatsha
Robertson and staff photographer Pat Greenhouse. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FAMILY-I (Cambridge, Mass.) _ Few American families can trace
their historical stake in this country so directly. Slavery and
prejudice saw to that, separating them from their families and _
with only a few exceptions _ keeping black Americans and their
achievements out of history books. PHOTO. (2 takes)
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   FAMILY-LETTER (Boston) _ In a letter discovered in a small
Massachusetts town, a cry for justice rises again. 540 words.
</P>
<P>
   FAMILY-II (Lowell, Mass.) _ Dozens of escaped slaves made their
way to the home of Adrastus Lew. It was a safehouse on the
Underground Railroad and is still standing today. PHOTO. 1400
words.
</P>
<P>
   FAMILY-III (Boston) _ For decades, the Lew family followed a
tradition of excellence in music. Members distinguished themselves
as African-American artists during an era when the country was
struggling to find its own identity. PHOTO. 1420 words. PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   FAMILY-IV (Boston) _ Although John ``B.J'' Mills knows he's
``vested in this country, more than most.'' But as a black man he
feels ``people don't look at your background or what your family
has done. To them, you are only black. You are invisible.'' PHOTO.
1550 words.
</P>
<P>
   For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  All stories will bear the BOS
designator and move under the General National (a) category code.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
</P>
