<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-II-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECHOES OF THE UNDERGROUND RAILROAD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOWELL, Mass. _ As a child, Laura Ashe would listen intently to
the stories told of her great-grandparents, who hid runaway slaves
in a hallway closet of her childhood home.
</P>
<P>
   She would spend what seemed like hours staring, wondering how
could those poor souls survive all packed up in the closet?
</P>
<P>
   Now, seven decades later, Ashe, 79, of Boston walked through the
Lowell home with Marie Desheneaux, the woman who bought it from her
family 50 years ago. Hand in hand, they rediscovered its legacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Upstairs, that's where the slaves hid in the long closet,''
Ashe recalled. ``And that's the chimney corner,'' she said, moving
to the dining area. ``It was where the slaves would come down, sit
and tell their stories.''
</P>
<P>
   The home was built about 1850 in the middle of a secluded forest
area by Ashe's great-grandfather, Adrastus Lew. He was the grandson
of Barzillai Lew, a black musician who in 1775 fought in the Battle
of Bunker Hill. Lew's skills as a musician would be passed down
through eight generations.
</P>
<P>
   The story of the Lew family of Massachusetts _ carefully
preserved by family members over the years _ intersects time and
again with key episodes in the black struggle for freedom in
America.
</P>
<P>
   While Adrastus Lew, a farmer, and his wife, Elizabeth Freeman,
would live a seemingly simple life, they became an important part
of the Underground Railroad, a secret system developed in the years
before the Civil War to harbor slaves making their way to freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Historians only recently have determined that it was black
northerners like the Lews who made up the majority of the
abolitionist movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a chapter that has never been told,'' said Richard
Newman, research officer at the W.E.B. Du Bois Institute of
Afro-American Studies at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   The role of whites was important because they had the homes and
power, he said. ``So, I don't want to minimalize the white
abolitionist role, but the black role has been minimalized.''
</P>
<P>
   They were not always abolitionists in the formal sense, said
James Horton, who examines the interactions of free blacks and
ex-slaves from the South in his book ``Free People of Color.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They were just people helping people. Some people helped one
person in their whole life, and others helped thousands,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The slaves who crept to the Lew home were probably fugitives
hiding out in Boston or runaways from the South heading to Canada.
Most of them couldn't read or write. They were farmers who were
guided by the stars and the streams in their travels north.
</P>
<P>
   The infamous fugitive slave law in 1850 placed severe penalities
on anyone harboring slaves. During that year, an estimated 200
fugitive slaves left Boston for Canada, according to Horton,
professor of American studies and history at George Washington
University.
</P>
<P>
   When runaways arrived at Ashe's great-grandparent's home, the
family quickly hid them in the closet. ``My (great-) grandparents
would put a pallet down there and the slave would sleep there
during the day and come down to the kitchen at night,'' Ashe
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   There, they ate and told their stories. Later, they would climb
into a horse-drawn wagon, and Adrastus Lew, said by family members
to be nearly seven feet tall, would pack it tight with hay.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would take them to the Pelham, N.H., line. They were met
by someone else to take them to Canada. If no one else was there to
take them, then my (great-) grandfather or Elizabeth Lew would,''
said Ashe.
</P>
<P>
   During these dangerous journeys, free blacks and runaway slaves
had created a secret system of communicating. The popular black
jockey statue, for example, served as a message for those slaves,
said Newman.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the statue was in front of the house and lit, it meant it
was an abolitionist safe house. But if it wasn't lit, it meant
don't come in. Something is wrong,'' said Newman.
</P>
<P>
   Now historians are discovering that even quilts and spiritual
songs contained obscure messages for the journeys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going to Canaan really meant `go to Canada,' '' said Newman.
``They developed a vocabulary of secret coded messages. It's in
everything _ the songs, the quilts. Here is an enslaved people but
they are not just sitting down, they are communicating in front of
white people who didn't get it.''
</P>
<P>
   While Adrastus and Elizabeth chose to discreetly participate in
the abolitionist movement, some years earlier Barzillai Lew's
daughter, Lucy Dalton, and her husband, Thomas Dalton, were in the
thick of a radical antislavery movement in Boston. Dalton, a
caterer and bootblack, was also the president of an all-black
antislavery society that preceded the efforts of the white
abolitionist William Lloyd Garrison.
</P>
<P>
   The family continued through the years to be engaged in the
fight for freedom. In 1865, for instance, Adrastus Lew's brother,
Zimri, died at age 38 in South Carolina while serving in the Civil
War.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, a white minister named Theodore Edson was
riding in a carriage with a man believed to be 47-year-old Adrastus
Lew, according to Martha Mayo, a historian at the University of
Massachusetts in Lowell. As they turned toward the Merrimac River
to a cemetery to bury Lew's brother, Adrastus told the minister of
his grandfather, Barzillai Lew, who bought the freedom of his wife
for $400 before the Revolutionary War, according to a copy of an
excerpt from Edson's diary.
</P>
<P>
   While Adrastus Lew never mentioned his or his wife's role in
helping blacks gain their freedom, his conversation with Edson was
one of the first records of a Lew family member passing down his
history.
</P>
<P>
   In 1912, Adrastas' wife, then 89 and the oldest woman in Lowell,
told a reporter of their participation in the Underground Railroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband and I helped many of the escaping slaves to get
safely to Canada, giving them rest for the night, food and clothing
and money to help them on their way. Those were terrible times,''
said she in the article in the Lowell Sunday Telegram.
</P>
<P>
   Their home was the second to be built in the area, she is quoted
as saying: ``We had to cut a path through the woods to get to the
other side of the house.''
</P>
<P>
   There were no street cars at the time, and the children would
play and catch rabbits in the pasture.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership forged between Elizabeth and Adrastus during the
Underground Railroad days would end when she filed for divorce,
alleging her husband committed adultrey. She kept the home.
Sometimes she'd sit on the porch smoking a pipe. Later, she passed
the home down to her son. When he died, his wife _ Ashe's
grandmother _ would find herself in the center of a fight for the
land around the house. Her husband's siblings, raised by Adrastus
and Elizabeth in the home, believed they had the right to the land.
</P>
<P>
   But according to family members, Ashe's aunt, Theresa Lew, a
popular Lowell teacher who had gone to law school, successfully
fought the case on her mother's behalf. The land across the street
from the home would be distributed to the siblings.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, the home would be sold to Desheneux and her
now-deceased husband, a childhood friend of Ashe.
</P>
<P>
   As Ashe and Desheneux walked through the home earlier this
month, Ashe noticed the changes _ the chimney corner is now
occupied by a stereo system and the closets, in which the slaves
once hid, have been renovated.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother had a large, old-fashioned piano right here,'' Ashe
said, standing in the living room.
</P>
<P>
   Generations of Lew children raised in the home would become
accomplished musicians and singers.
</P>
<P>
   As Ashe walked down the front steps of the house with the help
of her son, Gerard, she patted the stone stairs. ``I use to sit
here and read,'' she said.``There were many of good days in this
house,'' she told her son. ``Many of good days.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
