<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-LETTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN DISCOVERED LETTER, SLAVES' CRY RISES AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANCIE LATOUR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was the kind of discovery historians spend a lifetime
searching for and almost never find. But for Elizabeth Reilly, a
local historian in central Massachusetts, the rarest glimpse into
New England's black Revolutionary War history came by quiet
accident, nestled in the crates of a town's forgotten archives.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly, president of the Hardwick Historical Society, had begun
a tedious job going through handwritten tax records from the 1700s.
Last month, as she went about sifting through the reams of flaking
documents, she stumbled upon the signatures of four Boston slaves,
and their early, radical plea for freedom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect great things from men who have made such a noble
stand against the designs of their fellow men to enslave them,''
read the request to Massachusetts legislators, dated April 20, 1773
and signed by the slaves on the brink of the American Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   After taking the brown-ink broadside to experts, Reilly soon
learned how rare her finding was: The letter is among the earliest
political writings by slaves. Printed by the hundreds and
distributed like fliers across Massachusetts two centuries ago,
only three other original copies remain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just stunned that it was sitting there, tucked in among
all these old tax records,'' Reilly said of the discovery. ``It
felt so immediate to know that this little piece of paper came to
this rural town, that I could sit here in the 20th century and read
it, knowing their petition would never be granted, knowing it would
be 90 more years before slavery was abolished. It was almost like
reading the letter of someone who was going to die in battle and
didn't know it.''
</P>
<P>
   The plea was as reverent as it was radical. Strategic in their
request, the slaves asked for only one day a week of freedom. And
subversive beyond their time, they used the reading skills given
them by their masters to rebel, and held a shaming mirror to a
people that cried for liberty even as they held blacks in bondage.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the people of this province seem to be actuated by the
principles of equity and justice,'' the letter read, ``we cannot
but expect your house will again take our deplorable case into
serious consideration, and give us that ample relief which, as men,
we have a natural right to.''
</P>
<P>
   But like every other slave petition of the era, the letter was
tabled indefinitely. It was 10 years later that Massachusetts
abolished slavery. The nation as a whole would have to wait close
to a century.
</P>
<P>
   ``We almost never think of blacks speaking up themselves about
the evils of slavery,'' said Reilly of the letter, soon to be
placed on permanent loan at the American Antiquarian Society in
Worcester. ``To know there were vocal black leaders talking about
freedom and writing it more than 100 years before the Emancipation
Proclamation, it pushes our whole vision of the movement for
freedom back in a profound way. It was such a long, long
struggle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-99 1750EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
