<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JONBENET-BOOK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PERFECT MURDER' A PERFECT STUDY OF JONBENET CASE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF GUINN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Perfect Murder, Perfect Town''
</P>
<P>
   by Lawrence Schiller
</P>
<P>
   Crime reporting
</P>
<P>
   HarperCollins, $26
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Schiller made his mark as an investigative crime
reporter two decades ago, when he was Norman Mailer's chief
researcher for ``The Executioner's Song,'' the Pulitzer
Prize-winning study of Utah killer Gary Gilmore.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Schiller topped bestseller lists with his own book,
``American Tragedy: The Uncensored Story of the Simpson Defense,''
penned after he helped O.J. write ``I Want to Tell You.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Schiller, in his customary fascinating-but-exhaustive way,
addresses the 1996 Christmas-night slaying of JonBenet Ramsey in
Boulder, Colo. As with Schiller's previous subjects, we know much
about the case: A picture-perfect little girl who won juvenile
beauty pageants was found dead in the basement of her home. Her
parents, John and Patsy Ramsey, appeared to many to be the most
logical suspects, but shoddy investigative work by the Boulder
police supposedly allowed them to escape a properly exacting
investigation. The case remains open. A grand jury is expected to
return some sort of initial finding this month, but whoever killed
little JonBenet Ramsey remains at large.
</P>
<P>
   This killing seems particularly repugnant because of the victim:
JonBenet's photos display her either as a lovely, smiling, normal
child or an overly made-up, strutting parody of adult beauty
queens. Either way, she evokes sympathy, and the circumstances of
her death and the discovery of her body _ her father found her in a
cellar room after Boulder police had searched the house _ lend
themselves to speculation.
</P>
<P>
   Schiller's is the first ``serious'' study of the case. (A few
quickie paperbacks did little but rehash newspaper accounts.) With
``Perfect Murder, Perfect Town,'' Schiller demonstrates why he is
the perfect writer to chronicle murder stories that have captured
public attention. Schiller never embellishes facts, never spends
page after page laboriously explaining his conclusions. Instead, he
simply interviews everyone involved, records what they say, and
lets the reader work it out.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best thing about ``Perfect Murder, Perfect Town'' is
Schiller's commanding demonstration of how the nature of Boulder,
Colo., hampered the investigation. Boulder, we learn from
residents, is a place where rich people congregate to enjoy
luxurious lifestyles without interference from outsiders or law
officers. The district attorney's office had instituted pre-trial
bargaining for prominent citizens about to go into the dock for
drunken driving, speeding, and other nonmurderous transgressions.
When officers first went to the Ramsey house on the morning of Dec.
26, 1996, the head of the Boulder homicide unit cautioned them to
treat the Ramseys with respect instead of as suspects. John Ramsey
owned and operated a billion-dollar business in downtown Boulder.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the Ramseys were allowed to roam the house freely before
forensic evidence was collected and later bargained with police
over ground rules for how and when they would be questioned. This
despite these details: A ransom note was written on a pad of paper
already in the house; although a basement window had been broken,
there were no real signs of forced entry; the
``kidnappers/killers'' signed their note with an acronym also used
for a base where John Ramsey had once been stationed; the amount
($118,000) of the ransom matched exactly Ramsey's annual bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Using interviews with friends and business acquaintances,
Schiller skillfully depicts JonBenet as a bright, sometimes bratty
child who was used by her mother, a former Miss America contestant,
to live out Mom's dreams. One dance teacher hired to instruct
JonBenet in stage performance declares herself perplexed at the
child's sexy gyrations in some pageants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never taught her that,'' the teacher protests, and the clear
implication is that Patsy Ramsey decided sensuality had to be part
of her first-grader's allure.
</P>
<P>
   By book's end, readers will not like John or Patsy Ramsey, nor
Boulder's rich-can-do-no-wrong ambience. And it seems obvious that
Schiller believes that one or both parents are implicated in
JonBenet's death.
</P>
<P>
   But the most striking part of ``Perfect Murder, Perfect Town,''
the passage that will haunt readers, is Schiller's cut-and-dried
description of JonBenet's autopsy. It is impossible to read about a
skull fracture, an abraded vaginal area, blood on a blanket,
suspected semen on a thigh and a self-inscribed red ink heart on
JonBenet's left palm without realizing, in a stomach-lurching way,
that a little girl was brutally, horribly killed, and whoever did
it is still at large.
</P>
<P>
   Like Mailer's ``The Executioner's Song'' and Truman Capote's
``In Cold Blood,'' Schiller's ``Perfect Murder, Perfect Town'' will
eventually be considered a ghastly classic about brutal murder.
Schiller is, for now, the best at what he does; but considering his
subject matter, he must have nightmares all the time.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
