<DOCNO> NYT19990224.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7893 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAMILY-I-ART-2TAKES-B     02-24 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-I-ART-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BLACK FAMILY BOASTS EARLY AMERICAN ROOTS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo   is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Mae Theresa Bonitto, 83, who in the 1930s
graced the stages of New York and Boston as part of a dance troupe,
now shifts her frail body on a piano stool to try her hand at a
song she used to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, isn't it awful,'' she says after a half-dozen attempts.
``I can't think of these things anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Her memory of the song comes and goes. But Bonitto, who lives
with her husband in Cambridge, can pinpoint the beginning, more
than 200 years ago, of her family's fame for musical talent: an
African-American fifer and drummer in the Revolutionary War named
Barzillai Lew.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started . . . '' she says as she points to a framed
painting on her living room wall of a young black man holding a
flute, ``It started with him.''
</P>
<P>
   The painting _ a copy of a portrait called ``The Flutist'' that
hangs in the Walter Thurston Gentlemen's Room of the State
Department building in Washington _ is believed to be of Bonitto's
great-great-great grandfather, who fought at the Battle of Bunker
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Lew's father passed the musical skill to him, and Barzillai
(pronounced BAR-zeal-ya) passed it down to his 13 children. Thus
began a musical heritage that would thread through the Lew family
for eight generations _ through classical music, jazz, gospel and
soul, through all the ages of American history and the struggle of
black Americans for freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Lew was immortalized in song by Duke Ellington in a 1943 piano
composition entitled ``Barzillai Lou.''
</P>
<P>
   Few black American families can trace their stake in this
country back in time so directly. Slavery and prejudice saw to
that, separating them from their families and _ with only a few
exceptions _ keeping black Americans and their achievements out of
history books.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up here in the North, census takers and town clerks tended to
make mistakes and to leave (blacks) out entirely, like they were
invisible,'' said the Rev. Frank Dorman, who documented the lives
of the Lews and other families in his 1998 book: ``Twenty Families
of Color in Massachusetts.'' ``The Lew family represents the fact
that European-Americans had on blinders, and that is why they
couldn't see them. But they were here, in the center of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Barzillai was a war hero and family members like Bonitto
kept treasured vital records and passed down oral history, the
Lews' story was never lost, said Dorman.
</P>
<P>
   Barzillai Lew was born Nov. 5, 1743, in Groton. Two years later,
his father, Primus Lew, went off to fight in conflicts with French
and Indian forces, helping to set a precedent for black men joining
the War for Independence.
</P>
<P>
   Primus, a musician, was born about 1715 (it is not clear where)
during a time when trading black people in Massachusetts was as
common as stock market trading is today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston was deep in the slave trade, because there was money in
it, fortunes to be made,'' said Richard Newman, research officer at
The W. E. B. Du Bois Institute for Afro-American Research at
Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   Lacking the vast agricultural tracts of the South, New England
never had much need for a large slave population, but most blacks
who lived in New England were slaves _ and remained slaves until
the late 18th century.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, they could own land, go to court, marry within
their race, but slaves were restricted in where they could travel
and where they could sit in church, and they were not allowed to
bear arms. They were mostly domestic servants, field hands for
small farms, or sailors.
</P>
<P>
   In Groton, Primus was able to earn a living as a cooper, making
the barrels that would hold the rum often traded for slaves. He
bought land on the west side of Nashua River in Pepperell. He
married twice and was initially described in records as the servant
of a Captain Jonathan Boyden. While living descendants emphasize
that Primus was no slave, that can't be confirmed. The word
``servant,'' says Dorman, a Cambridge genealogist, often meant
slave in the mid 1700s. ``It was a nice way of saying it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten years after Primus Lew's first marriage, according to
Dorman, records in Pepperell call Lew a free man. His firstborn,
Barzillai Lew, would be given the stamp of freedom at birth,
offering him more _ though still limited _ opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Barzillai was 17, he had fought in the French and
Indian War. In 1768, when he was 25, he had saved $400, enough to
buy the freedom of the woman he would marry, Dinah Bowman, a
biracial slave. That same year, the young couple had their first
child _ a boy named Zadock. Like his father, he was named for an
Old Testament figure.
</P>
<P>
   Around this time, sentiment toward slavery was beginning to
change in New England, the first hint of a schism in America that
would eventually become the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   ``What comes out of that is that more and more black people
start getting set free,'' said state Representative Byron Rushing,
a historian. ``People voluntarily set them free or cut deals and
allowed the slaves to buy themselves out of slavery.''
</P>
<P>
   For free black men like Lew, the Revolutionary War offered the
possibility that slavery would be abolished in a new, independent
nation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
