<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, Feb. 25, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Windswept snow will batter extreme southeast New England
Thursday as a formidable low pressure system moves slowly off the
Northeast coast. Depending upon the precise track of the low,
anywhere from several inches to over a foot of snow could
accumulate on parts of Cape Cod. Winds near 40 miles an hour will
cause considerable drifting of the snow. The snow will spread north
into southern New Hampshire and eastern Maine during Thursday night
and Friday.
</P>
<P>
   There will be a sharp line marking the leading edge of the
precipitation with little snow expected from just west of New York
City to the Connecticut River. Indeed, sinking air currents
associated with high pressure over eastern Canada will suppress
clouds, causing intervals of sun from northern Pennsylvania to
western Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Patches of mainly light snow will accompany a jet stream
disturbance crossing the central Appalachians Thursday morning. The
snow will spread east, reaching the Middle Atlantic coast by
evening. The system will produce a modicum of snow, though a few
inches may blanket the West Virginia mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Abundant sun will combine with air warming on decent from the
Rockies to bring unusually mild conditions to the Front Range and
western Plains. It will also be rather warm from the desert
Southwest to Texas as sunshine mixes with intervals of clouds.
</P>
<P>
   Intermittent showers will continue to plague western portions of
Washington and Oregon with snow falling in the Cascades above 5,000
feet. Snow is also likely along the west slopes of the Sierras and
in the Bitterroots.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Wet Washington
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday and Monday, a record amount of rain fell on
Washington's northwest coast when a potent disturbance from the
North Pacific moved inland. The town of Quillayute has measured
23.31 inches of rain so far in February, eclipsing the previous
record of 20.60 set in 1982. In fact, this winter season, which
began on Dec. 1, has brought 59.92 inches to Quillayute, less than
one inch below the record wet season set in 1966-67. Another
barrage of Pacific fronts this weekend should guarantee that this
cold season will be the wettest ever on Washington's Olympic
peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   Extended Forecast for Thursday, Feb. 25
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Sunday: The jet stream will lift up into Canada
allowing much milder air to flow into the Northeast. In the
Southeast, it will be mild with clouds and showers arriving late in
the weekend. A cold front will bring rain and snow showers into the
Great Lakes region. The Plains states will be generally dry and it
will be warming in the Dakotas. Pleasant, warm conditions will
continue in Southwest, while the Northwest remains unsettled.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Tuesday: A departing storm will leave behind clouds and
windy conditions in New England. It will be mainly dry and cooler
in the Southeast. A disturbance will bring a wintry mixture to the
Great Lakes and a few showers to the Ohio Valley. Warmer air will
blow in to the southern Plains, while the northern Plains will be
cool and breezy. The West will be cooler with snow in the
mountains. Dry air will cover California.
</P>
</TEXT>
