<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNSEL25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INDEPENDENT COUNSEL LAW ATTACKED AT SENATE HEARING
 &HT;    420&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The law that launched the independent counsel
investigation of President Clinton should be abandoned after two
frequently stormy decades, senators were told Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But what, if anything, should replace it is far less certain,
witnesses told the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Howard H. Baker Jr., the former Senate Republican leader who
helped write the anti-corruption law in the post-Watergate era,
told the panel he now opposes it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The act ought to expire'' as scheduled next June, Baker said,
urging Congress to go slow in writing a new statute. ``We ought to
cool off, let some time go by'' after the Clinton impeachment
battle, he said.
</P>
<P>
   As for what form any new law would take, he acknowledged, ``In
good conscience I cannot say that I know what the answer is.''
</P>
<P>
   Another veteran official who was present at the creation of the
statute also told the panel that the government doesn't need an
independent counsel law.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin B. Bell, who was the first attorney general to work
under the act, said the country should ``go back to the system that
we have always had and under which the Watergate prosecution was
conducted, the Teapot Dome oil scandal was handled, and the Carter
peanut warehouse was investigated.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell recalled that before the statute was passed, President
Jimmy Carter had been accused of laundering bank funds through his
peanut warehouse. Bell appointed an outside investigator who spent
six weeks going over the case with help from Justice Department
professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he accounted for every peanut and every nickel'' and
exonerated the president, Bell, now an Atlanta attorney, told the
senators. ``We can go back to that system.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said at a news conference Wednesday that he had ``some
ideas'' about rewriting the law, but he withheld announcing them.
``I think it would be better for me at this time to say less so
that others can say more,'' he said. He said administration lawyers
would give their views to Congress next week.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno has also agreed to testify on the
issue next month on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Among the changes floated during the initial meeting, Sen. Carl
Levin, D-Mich., proposed replacing the current system with an
expanded Office of Professional Responsibility within the Justice
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Others suggested limiting the jurisdiction of the investigators
to just three officials, the president, vice president and attorney
general, instead of the current total of about 70 officeholders.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Senators in both parties took turns taking pot shots at the
current system, which has triggered 21 independent counsels since
1978, angering first Republicans in the Iran-contra probe and now
Democrats, who have blasted Kenneth Starr's investigation of
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were wrong,'' said Sen. Robert G. Torricelli, D-N.J., of
his party's previous backing of the law. He added that his
opposition was so entrenched that he would filibuster any effort to
renew the law.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Fred Thompson, chairman of the Governmental Affairs
Committee, which has jurisdiction over the law, said he had always
opposed independent counsels for having unlimited time and money to
go after a single target.
</P>
<P>
   He expects changes ``now that Capitol Hill is littered with
gored oxen from both sides,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   Some senators raised concerns about dropping the independent
counsel law altogether, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can the executive branch be trusted to investigate itself for
potential criminal wrongdoing?'' said Sen. Joseph Lieberman,
D-Conn. ``The answer, hopefully, is 'Yes,' but what do we do when
the answer is 'No'?''
</P>
<P>
   ``The independent counsel law is not about sex scandals and spin
doctors and mud throwing,'' he said. ``It's about good
government.''
</P>
<P>
   But he acknowledged that many people have already written the
epitaph for the law. In fact, that was an idea endorsed by Bell,
who said, ``I was hoping that today would be the beginning of the
funeral.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
