<SLUG> BC-US-MEXICO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE SEEKS CERTIFICATION OF MEXICAN ANTI-DRUG EFFORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A top State Department official told Congress
Wednesday that Mexico should be recertified as a drug-fighting U.S.
ally, but two other government officials accused the Mexican
government of drug-related corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Rand Beers, the State Department's assistant secretary for
narcotics and law enforcement affairs, praised the Mexican
government for embarking on an ``unprecedented anti-drug campaign
that, to my knowledge, has never been duplicated with any other
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Beers acknowledged that Mexico should do more to stem the flow
of illegal narcotics but insisted that the country was making
strides.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a black record _ it's a mixed record,'' Beers said,
adding that Mexico spends a higher percentage of its budget to
fight drugs than does the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But Thomas Constantine, the head of the federal Drug Enforcement
Administration, said corruption in Mexican law enforcement was the
worst he'd seen in his 39-year law enforcement career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Continuing reports of corruption and the rapidly growing power
and influence of the major organized criminal groups in Mexico
cause us great concern about the long-term prospects for success,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Constantine said, ``There is little effective law enforcement
activity leading to the arrest of major traffickers in Mexico.'' He
declined to discuss his view of re-certification but said the
Mexican drug cartels ``have little to fear except the slim
possibility that they will be extradited to the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Nelson, the director of international relations and
trade issues for the General Accounting Office, the congressional
research arm, said corruption is a major impediment in the drug
war.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corruption remains widespread within Mexican government
institutions, including the criminal justice system,'' said Nelson.
He said the cartels spend over $6 billion annually to bribe Mexican
government officials ``at all levels.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said Mexico's overall drug-fighting record was lax. Drugs
continue to flow over the border at the same rate as 1997, he said,
while ``there have been no significant increases in drug
eradication and seizures.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexico has yet to extradite a major drug trafficker to the
United States or to aggressively prosecute money-laundering
operations, Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most drug trafficking leaders continue to operate with
impunity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The officials testified Wednesday before the Senate caucus on
international narcotics control.
</P>
<P>
   In the next several days, President Clinton is expected to
certify that Mexico has been fully cooperative with U.S.
counter-narcotics activities. The administration is required to
rate about 30 countries each year on their drug-fighting efforts.
Those that are decertified face possible economic sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Asked under what circumstances the Clinton administration would
decertify Mexico, Beers said there would need to be drug-related
corruption at the senior levels of the Mexican government.
</P>
<P>
   That was the standard applied in 1996 when the administration
decertified Colombia over allegations that Colombian President
Ernesto Samper accepted $6 million dollars in campaign funds from
the Cali cartel.
</P>
<P>
   Congress could vote to cancel Mexico's recertification as it
unsuccessfully attempted in 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers have hinted they might try again because of their
unhappiness with Mexico's efforts to halt the drug flow.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jeff Sessions, R-Ala., announced Wednesday that he wants
Mexico decertified.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., said she was disappointed that
Mexico has not extradited alleged drug kingpins to the United
States for trial. But she declined to say whether she would support
the recertification of Mexico. Feinstein opposed certification last
year.
</P>
<P>
   According to Constantine, Mexican narcotics cartels operating in
the United States have grown ``virtually geometrically'' over the
last five years.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican drug cartels have penetrated the United States to the
extent that, for the first time, they ``virtually dominate the
nationwide drug trade,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Constantine called the cartels ``the greatest challenge to law
enforcement agencies in the United States that are enforcing
narcotics laws today.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexican cartels are responsible for shipping approximately
two-thirds of the cocaine available on U.S. streets.
</P>
<P>
   They are responsible for smuggling in precursor chemicals for
methamphetamine production and starting up laboratories in
California to produce and distribute the drug, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is common now to find hundreds of traffickers from Mexico
... most of them illegal aliens, established in communities like
Boise, Des Moines, Omaha, Charlotte and Kansas City, distributing
multi-pound quantities of methamphetamine,'' Constantine said.
</P>
<P>
   Marijuana from Mexico dominates the U.S. import market, while
Mexico accounts for a steadily increasing amount _ now 14 percent _
of heroin available on U.S. streets, Constantine said. But the DEA
estimates that more than 29 percent of heroin used in the United
States is smuggled in by Mexican cartels.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
