<HEADER>
A7915 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-8MM-TEX     02-24 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-8MM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LURID MOVIE, BUT MAYBE NOT LURID ENOUGH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``8MM,'' in which Nicolas Cage stars as a clean-living,
conservative private eye who is pulled into the world of snuff
films, looks as if it might emit the same kind of grimy charge as
``Hardcore.'' ``(Hardcore'' starred George C. Scott as a hard-nosed
Calvinist who has to thunder into the world of porno to get his
daughter back.) But ``Hardcore'' had a new-to-movies messiness,
although it was finally too pat to be very interesting. ``8MM,''
however, plants a flag where too many have been before.
</P>
<P>
   Cage is Tom Welles, a man uses the distance of professionalism
to view the scummy world of lies and affairs that he monitors for
other people. He is hired because of his sterling reputation for
discretion. Cage internalizes the cramped, slightly cold nature of
such a guy a little too efficiently. Unfortunately, he's not as
interesting playing a remote, unimaginative man as he is at
portraying a wild, impulsive one _ and the picture is built around
him. Which means ``8MM'' has a dried-out, flavorless center. When a
wealthy widow asks him to dig into the truth behind a snuff film _
a movie in which someone is killed on camera _ he gets to come to
life a bit. Although he warns the woman that snuff films are
``urban legends,'' watching what looks like the geek from ``Pulp
Fiction'' murder a worn-out and frightened young girl horrifies
Welles. It's the most arresting point of the picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``8MM'' refers to the size of the film _ 8 millimeter, a very
old format _ on which the film was shot, and figuratively to the
amount of imagination that went into the making of the film.
Directed by Joel Schumacher, whom many haven't forgiven for any
number of other films _ ``A Time to Kill, Batman Forever, Batman &AMP;
Robin, Falling Down'' _ ``8MM'' has a strange gleam of
professionalism despite its sordidness. The characters' fear seems
only decorative, as if it were just an element to spice up the
proceedings rather than an intrinsic part of the material.
</P>
<P>
   Welles leaves behind his wife (Catherine Keener) and young
daughter to stalk the seedy underworld of LA and find the men
responsible for the snuff film. He meets a weaselly but
good-hearted adult-film store employee (Joaquin Phoenix), who
introduces him to its perverse denizens. Phoenix gets to play the
live-wire second-banana role that Cage would have played 10 years
ago. And Cage, who made his bones with bravura, has a lead that's
even more thankless than his part in perhaps the stupidest movie
ever made, ``Con Air,'' in which he at least got to show some comic
flair.
</P>
<P>
   He is strapped to a movie that, given its potential low-rent
allure, takes itself way too seriously. He's stranded with a number
of fine actors, including James Gandolfini, currently giving the
most finely tuned performance in series TV on HBO's ``The
Sopranos.'' (Poor, talented Keener is relegated to the role of
perching a baby on her hip and, inevitably, warning her husband
that if things keep him away too long, she won't there when he gets
back.)
</P>
<P>
   As written and conceived by Andrew Kevin Walker, who created
``Seven'' (and did an uncredited major rewrite on ``The Game''),
``8MM'' is another feature about a man having to test himself in
circumstances that will probably scar him forever. When he works
with ``Seven'' director David Fincher, who has an intuitive gift
for getting under your skin, the seams don't show in the way they
do here. The only reason people may be talking about this movie
after today is because by blurring the line between sex and
violence _ which American movies do pretty often; this just calls
attention to it _ ``8MM'' is sure to stir up some controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``8MM'' is rated R for violence and adult language, including
frank talk about perversion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``8MM'': 2 stars on a scale of 1-5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Joel Schumacher
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Nicolas Cage, Joaquin Phoenix
</P>
<P>
   Length: 123 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
