<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-PHONE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW WAY TO GET AN EARFUL OF ART
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ You're at the Kimbell Art Museum to see
``Matisse and Picasso: A Gentle Rivalry.'' And dozens of people are
TALKING ON THE PHONE?
</P>
<P>
   Jeez, you fume, can't people leave their busy little lives
behind for just an hour or so to enjoy a little culture?
</P>
<P>
   Calm down. They are.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, Kimbell patrons can use the ArtPhone, a
digital random-access audio guide that allows far greater freedom
than the old earphones-and-tape system. It rents for $4, $3 for
museum members.
</P>
<P>
   Black, thin, about a foot long and manufactured in Israel, the
ArtPhone does away with having to tour an exhibit in strict order
in a big mass of people _ and worrying about getting your hair
mussed or losing an earring.
</P>
<P>
   The phones come via Acoustiguide, the New York company that
distributes them to more than 100 sites worldwide, including the
Museum of Modern Art in New York, zoos, aquariums, botanical
gardens, and historic homes and sites such as the Roman baths in
Bath, England. The phones debuted at the Louvre in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Simply hit ``C'' for clear, the number of the stop on the tour
(there are 22 for ``A Gentle Rivalry''), and ``play.'' And you're
instantly listening to narration by Kimbell director Timothy Potts,
with guest curator Yve-Alain Bois doing the voice of Pablo Picasso
and former curator Joachim Pissarro doing the voice of Henri
Matisse.
</P>
<P>
   You can pause. You can repeat. You can skip numbers. Because the
ArtPhone has random access, you can go where you want, when you
want.
</P>
<P>
   ``People love it because they have control,'' says Judy
Wilbanks, who manages the ArtPhones for ``A Gentle Rivalry.'' She
adds that the Kimbell has 740 phones for the exhibit; each is
stored, programmed and recharged in a large rack. Charges last
eight hours. ``They can find out about the exhibit they're standing
right in front of. They feel more free with it,'' Wilbanks said.
</P>
<P>
   And if you just HAVE to have earphones, they're still available
_ by request.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
