<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7924 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TURNER-SOUTH-COX     02-24 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURNER-SOUTH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Turner South to repackage stock films, TV shows
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jesse ``The Gov'' Ventura will wrestle again, this time in
reruns of his famous bouts to be aired on a new regional cable TV
channel, Turner South.
</P>
<P>
   The revival of Ventura's wrestling career illustrates the
strategy behind Turner Broadcasting's 18th cable TV channel,
formally announced Wednesday and scheduled to debut sometime this
fall. It will air in Georgia, the Carolinas, Tennessee, Mississippi
and Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   As of yet, Turner Broadcasting has signed neither cable or
satellite distributors. The sales effort for Turner South began
with the formal announcement of it at a morning press conference
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The channel is a classic Turner play. It will repackage and
market movies and TV shows from Turner's vast film libraries. ``We
have a history of launching new channels off our content,'' says
Bill Burke, the president of TBS, who will serve in the same
position for Turner South.
</P>
<P>
   Burke says a regional channel makes sense for Turner
Broadcasting because the company's brand is second only to
Coca-Cola in the South. It's a reputation built over the 25 years
since founder Ted Turner first began beaming Braves games across
the region in one of the first cable TV channels.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Turner South represents a new play for the
company. Turner South is the first regional cable TV channel and,
if it works, the company may try others in different parts of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we have considered other regional networks,'' says Burke,
although he declined to disclose any details.
</P>
<P>
   Turner South also represents a change in the cable TV industry.
No longer are big new national channels the rage. They're too
expensive to launch, and channel space at cable systems is limited.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is difficult, if not impossible to start new networks,''
says Burke.
</P>
<P>
   So Turner Broadcasting is trying a niche channel that, at best,
would have no more than 6 million subscribers. That's the total
potential market for Turner South, according to its parent's market
research.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't expect full distribution but, even so, Turner South
will make money,'' says Burke.
</P>
<P>
   How can that be? Because the expenses of Turner South would be
relatively low, with the company drawing on its current
administrative, sales and marketing staff to run it.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, most of the Turner South's content would come from
the film libraries of Turner Broadcasting and parent Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   For Turner South, shows will be packaged and marketed with a
Southern spin. The best of World Championship Wrestling, including
Ventura's old bouts, is an example. Another idea in development is
``Kudzu Theater.'' It will feature B movies with the marketing
slogan ``Movies that grow on you.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner Broadcasting executives will also heavily season Turner
South's programming with original shows. A big part of original
production will include live sporting events.
</P>
<P>
   The company owns three local sports teams, the Braves, the Hawks
and nascent hockey team the Thrashers. Most of the rights to games
played by these teams are already owned by other channels,
including Turner Broadcasting's own TNT and TBS cable channels.
</P>
<P>
   But Burke says he anticipates the broadcast rights for 30 Braves
games will be available each year. Turner South would try to
acquire the rights to a yet-undetermined number of these games, for
example.
</P>
<P>
   Turner South, though, is not modeled after Fox Sports South and
other regional sports channels, says Burke. He explains, ``This
channel is really a first of its kind, the first regional
entertainment channel.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
