<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7928 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON25-COX     02-24 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON SAYS SCANDALS WON'T HAMPER DEALINGS WITH CONGRESS
 &HT;    460&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton dismissed concerns Wednesday that
a year of scandal has severed the trust between the White House and
congressional Republicans, even as he dodged new allegations
reaching 20 years into his past.
</P>
<P>
   With his Senate acquittal less than two weeks old, ''some of the
nerves are still raw'' on both sides of the impeachment issue,
Clinton said, and it should surprise no one to see an erosion of
confidence between him and his political foes.
</P>
<P>
   But ''their feelings are not important here _ just like my
feelings are not important,'' he said. ''We have an oath to
fulfill, a responsibility to fulfill. We were hired to do the
public's business, and they expect us to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the president still can't put troubling questions about
his personal life behind him. In the session's first question,
Clinton was asked to comment on allegations by Juanita Broaddrick,
an Arkansas nursing home operator, that he forced her to have sex
with him in her Little Rock hotel room in 1978, when he was the
state's attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   ''My counsel made a statement'' in response to those
allegations, Clinton replied. ''I have nothing to add to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's personal attorney, David Kendall, released a statement
Friday that said, ``Any allegation that the president assaulted
Mrs. Broaddrick more than 20 years ago is absolutely false. Beyond
that, we're not going to comment.''
</P>
<P>
   Broaddrick has never filed formal charges against Clinton. In
fact, she signed an affidavit a year ago contending that no assault
ever took place.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, though, she has said in interviews with The New York
Times, the Wall Street Journal, The Washington Post and NBC
television that Clinton did assault her, and that her sworn
statement to the contrary was a lie to protect herself and her
family from the trauma of revisiting the incident.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from that question, Clinton focused on foreign affairs in
his 50-minute appearance with President Jerry Rawlings of Ghana. He
offered lengthy explanations of U.S. policy in Africa, Iraq and
Kosovo in his most expansive news conference since the Monica
Lewinsky sex-and-deception scandal erupted 13 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly enjoying questions that allowed him to step from the
shadows of his impeachment scandal and hold forth on policy
matters, Clinton smiled often during the press conference, joked
with Rawlings, held his hand and even offered an apology, of sorts,
for the dearth of questions from the U.S. press about Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really my fault, because I don't let them ask me enough
questions on other occasions,'' said Clinton, who has held only one
solo White House press conference since December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ''So I'm forcing them to use this opportunity to pepper me,''
Clinton joked to Rawlings. ``I apologize.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Clinton accused Iraq of seeking a ''symbolic victory'' through
its almost daily attempts to shoot down U.S. warplanes patrolling
Iraqi skies.
</P>
<P>
   American pilots, however, will continue to fire on Iraqi
military positions whenever they are targeted by Iraqi radar and
anti-aircraft guns, Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. jets have attacked Iraqi missile sites more than 80 times
since the United States led air raids and cruise missile launches
against the Mideast oil giant last December.
</P>
<P>
   By some estimates, the almost daily attacks have done more
damage to Iraq than the hundreds of missiles and bombs that struck
the country during the December offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he would prefer for the dangerous situation to end.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I regret this,'' said Clinton. ``I wish he would
stop doing that,'' he said, in an apparent reference to President
Saddam Hussein's orders for his military to target U.S. warplanes
that overfly his country every day to enforce a United
Nations-mandated no-fly zone across northern and southern Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are trying, obviously, for the symbolic victory of
shooting one of these planes down and perhaps trying to intimidate
us from enforcing the no-fly zone, which we're still bound to do
under the United Nations resolution,'' said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish he (Saddam) would make an agreement with the United
Nations to let the inspections go back,'' Clinton said, referring
to the U.N. teams that were inspecting Iraq's alleged efforts to
produce and stockpile chemical, nuclear and biological weapons
until Saddam expelled them in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have shown that we are not interested in hurting the Iraqi
people,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Following an Oval Office meeting Tuesday between Clinton and
House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., and Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott, R-Miss., both Republicans repeatedly declined to say
whether they trust Clinton in the wake of the year-long Lewinsky
sex-and-deception scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they parried reporters' questions on the subject and
spoke only of wanting to work with the White House across an array
of policy matters.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Clinton refused to say on Wednesday whether he
trusts Hastert or Lott, both of whom voted against him in the
impeachment process.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we focus on the American people and doing our duty, and not
on whether we're mad or happy, disappointed or elated about the
events of the last year, then all this in the course of time will
work itself out, and the American system will be validated,'' said
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   As a political leader, ''it is simply wrong for you to think
about what your feelings are,'' said Clinton. ``Your responsibility
is to fulfill your oath and do what the public needs, and if we
focus on that, we'll be just fine.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
