<HEADER>
A7934 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-CIGARETTES-TEX     02-24 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-CIGARETTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
``200 CIGARETTES'' IS SHALLOW PUFFERY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``200 Cigarettes'' is like a Rhino Records compilation with
pictures that move, a various-artists soundtrack that someone
draped a story on. It takes place on New Year's Eve 1981, with
several young characters drifting through New York en route to an
East Village party, but it could take place in 1998 for all the
'80s nostalgia it offers. Unlike ``American Graffiti,'' this
picture's most obvious influence, it feels more like an excuse for
young stars to play dress-up than a wistful look back at a simpler
era.
</P>
<P>
   After Christina Ricci had such a breakthrough year in 1998, it's
depressing to see this movie waste her, as it does Janeane Garofalo
and Martha Plimpton. With three such strong, watchable actresses in
the cast, it's surprising that Courtney Love gives the movie's best
performance. Her Lucy is a cliche, the tramp who just wants to be
loved, and it's probably fair to say that Lucy is close to Love's
heart. But she grabs hold of the old tough-vulnerable bit, using
her oversize mouth and astonishingly warm eyes to create the
movie's only fully rounded character.
</P>
<P>
   Why Lucy wants longtime friend Tom (Casey Affleck, Ben's
brother) is a mystery; he's a world-class moper, and he sports such
bad sideburns that you wish you could shave the screen. But then,
nobody here is a prize catch (hang on, because this gets
complicated). Angela Featherstone and Nicole Parker play friends
who believe that they'll be jinxed for all of 1982 if they don't
have New Year's sex; maybe this is be the Northern, pre-AIDS
version of eating black-eyed peas for luck. They both try to land a
clumsy bartender who's really a smarmy wannabe lawyer (Ben Affleck,
who gives a decent performance laced with self-mockery). Lucy has
her eye on him, too, but she also has her eye on Tom, who runs to
his most recent ex (Garofalo) at the most inconvenient time.
</P>
<P>
   But wait _ there's more! There's Ricci's adventurous Val and her
nervous pal, Stephie (Gaby Hoffman), really Noo Yawking it up as
Long Islanders who get lost looking for the party; they hook up
with a shy, Adam Ant-inspired punk (Clueless' Paul Rudd) and his
silent buddy (Guillermo Diaz). And over here, we have Jay Mohr as
Jack, who can't help making women fall in love with him almost
immediately, including Cindy, the klutzy woman he just deflowered
(Kate Hudson). Jack doesn't know why he has this effect on women;
but then, neither does the movie, which can't figure out how to
explain this device. The Jack-Cindy plot thread, filled with bad
slapstick, is the movie's most annoying element.
</P>
<P>
   But wait _ there's still more! There's Monica (Plimpton), the
party's host, verging on a breakdown because it's 9:30 and nobody
has shown up. Who should be the first person through the door but
ex-boyfriend Eric (Brian McCardie), a guy so bad in bed that women
dump him after first contact. The movie never explains this,
either; when Eric suggests that he can learn to be a better lover,
women simply tell him, no, he can't.
</P>
<P>
   Linking all this together is Dave Chapelle as a good-natured,
pot-smoking cabdriver who gives the characters unsolicited advice
(he has to be good-natured, because he's apparently the only cabby
in New York who picks up fares). He's a device like Wolfman Jack
was in ``American Graffiti,'' but he's used badly; it's a mistake
to get him to interact with the other characters. His real purpose
seems to be to get some Kool &AMP; the Gang and Manhattans songs onto
the soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   Elvis Costello, who has a credit as ``music consultant,'' shows
up in a gratuitous cameo that feels like a sitcom's sweeps-month
casting stunt.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first feature for director Risa Bramon Garcia and
screenwriter Shana Larsen, who may have bitten off more than they
chew with a movie so ambitious. Because it doesn't have the ease of
``Graffiti,'' and because its nostalgia is all surface, it comes
off as a shallow exercise for a bunch of stars who weren't out of
preschool when the movie takes place. This nostalgia thing is
getting frightening; one shudders to think of a 2010 movie that
looks back fondly on the '90s. Back in 1981, we probably thought
that by 1999, we'd be looking forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``200 Cigarettes'' is rated R for strong language, sexual
situations, drug use and some crude humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``200 Cigarettes'' 2 stars on a scale of 1-5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Risa Bramon Garcia
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Courtney Love, Christina Ricci, Ben Affleck
</P>
<P>
   Length: 97 min.
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
