<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7938 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEGALA25-COX     02-24 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEGALA25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BEGALA STILL LOVES TEXAS, BUT WILL STAY IN D.C.
 &HT;    (Attn: Texas)
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Nothing personal, Texas. But now that presidential
adviser Paul Begala is leaving the White House, the former
Austinite plans to keep on living in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that I don't love Texas. Cut me and I bleed orange,''
Begala said in an interview Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife's whole family is in Austin and I have family all
across Texas,'' Begala said. ``My undergraduate and law degrees are
from UT, and my wife got two graduate degrees there.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, ``I just couldn't stomach the thought of moving
again.''
</P>
<P>
   He and wife Diane moved their family to Washington after his
work with partner James Carville for Clinton's 1992 campaign led to
plentiful business as a political consultant, and to a position as
an unofficial adviser to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   They moved back in 1995 to Austin, where he represented
corporate clients at Public Strategies Inc. and taught a course on
``Politics and the Press'' at the University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Begala's old Washington friends became as distant
emotionally as they had become geographically because they thought
he was one of the major sources of the descriptions in Bob
Woodward's book, ``The Agenda,'' of liberal disenchantment with
Clinton's first-term record.
</P>
<P>
   But all that changed when the Begalas moved back to Washington
in mid-1997, after Clinton asked him to join the White House staff
as part of an effort to jump-start the president's stalled second
term.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now our kids are in school here, and I got some good jobs
lined up, so we won't have to move again,'' Begala said. ``I'll be
teaching, writing and lecturing.''
</P>
<P>
   Begala, who said he is ``37 and aging rapidly,'' said he plans
to hit the public lecture circuit, write a political column for
George magazine and start this fall at Georgetown University as a
research professor teaching graduate and undergraduate courses in
public policy and ``the inner workings of American government.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he won't be returning to Public Strategies, he consulted
Tuesday with its founder, Jack Martin, about how to announce his
departure. Begala revealed his plans Wednesday morning on Don
Imus's radio show.
</P>
<P>
   Imus asked Begala, one of Clinton's fiercest defenders on the
talking-head TV shows throughout the Monica Lewinsky debacle,
whether he would return to Clinton's side if another shoe drops.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know about any shoes dropping; I feel like I spent the
last year in Imelda Marcos' closet,'' Begala joked.
</P>
<P>
   In an effusive written statement released shortly afterwards,
Clinton said, ``I am grateful that he has used his razor-sharp mind
and wit in the service of core values and the common good. Paul has
given long hours to the service of his country, and he has more
than earned the right to seek new horizons through teaching and
writing, and to spend more time with his three young children.''
</P>
<P>
   Begala said he was profoundly grateful for the chance to work
with Clinton, even though Begala was among those whom the president
misled about his private activities with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texans understand loyalty. Only in Washington is loyalty a
dirty word,'' Begala said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so proud of the policies this president has enacted for
the country,'' Begala said. ``And look what he did for me. He took
me from being a perfectly good Triple-A ballplayer and, when I was
barely 30, he put me in the big leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
