<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'98 TRADE DEFICIT SHOWS U.S. IS STILL STRONG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) The media treatment of the record 1998 trade deficit
has been a vivid reminder of how the issue promises to become
increasingly ripe for political exploitation in the next election
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The general tone conveyed the view that the $169 billion
shortfall was a bad thing when it was nothing of the sort.
</P>
<P>
   Do Japan's media characterize that country's huge trade
surpluses as beneficial developments? It would be difficult to do
so and be taken seriously with Japan mired in its worst downturn
since it became a global economic power.
</P>
<P>
   By the same token, does it make sense to put the worst possible
face on a record U.S. trade deficit during the eighth year of
expansion? This growth occurred, incidentally, as most of the rest
of the world was struggling.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, exports of U.S. goods declined, which was troubling. It
should hardly be surprising, however, that America's exporters
would suffer when we're an island of prosperity in a sea of
economic malaise.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the question of whether the red ink was all that
humongous in relative terms. The previous record was $153 billion
in 1987. Since then the Consumer Price Index has soared well over
40 percent, which means the record really wasn't when adjusted for
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Another way of looking at the deficit is in the context of gross
domestic product, which is the value of the economy's output. To
its credit, The Wall Street Journal distinguished itself by
providing this perspective. The trade deficit in 1987 was 3.3
percent of GDP, but only 2.2 percent of last year's GDP. Moreover,
it shouldn't be forgotten that total international trade was a much
smaller component of the overall economy in '87 than it is now.
</P>
<P>
   In economic terms, trade balance numbers can't be characterized
as best or worst. They're only accounting constructs. If deficits
were bad and surpluses good, Japan would have long ago surpassed
America as the biggest and strongest economy in the world.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if anyone cares to make the bad-good argument, it could
be argued that the '98 trade deficit was a good thing. The most
obvious reason is that the deficit is a reflection of prosperity
that allows American consumers to purchase prodigious amounts of
both domestic and foreign goods.
</P>
<P>
   The less obvious reason is that without the affluence of
acquisitive Americans, most of the rest of the world would have no
hope of reviving their economic fortunes. Forget the International
Monetary Fund with its suffocating and often counterproductive
prescriptions for economic revival in troubled countries. The best
medicine for most of the world's economies is an open world market
that allows Americans to be the buyers of last resort. Without this
freedom to trade, the world would be a much less stable place
politically.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the obviousness of this situation, trade issues are
always easily distorted by politicians seeking to use economic
jingoism to woo voters. As a result, cries for protectionism will
be raised during the next election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   If they're heeded, it will mark the beginning of the end of the
nearly two decades of rising prosperity Americans have enjoyed
thanks to increasingly liberal trade policies worldwide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
