<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUINEAPIG-FILMS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG FILMMAKER IS MAKING HER MARK WITH GUINEA PIG FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT W. BUTLER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAWRENCE, Kan. _ Mickey and Minnie, Donald and Daisy, Huey,
Dewey and Louie _ with these creations of ink, paint and celluloid
Walt Disney captured the world's imagination and built an
entertainment empire.
</P>
<P>
   On a more modest scale, Alyssa Buecker of Lawrence is doing much
the same thing with Hazel, Curly Fry, Milkshake, Slinky, Brown 'Un
and Winky and Dinky _ guinea pigs who are the stars of the
14-year-old's homemade video shorts.
</P>
<P>
   Although she hasn't yet launched a Disney-style show-biz
dynasty, Alyssa is making her mark. Her guinea pig films have won
prizes in the annual Kan Film Festival _ a competitive event for
film and video makers in Kansas and Missouri _ and her first three
shorts are playing on HBO Family, the kid-themed cable channel that
began operating earlier this month. (The channel is not yet carried
by local cable systems).
</P>
<P>
   The stories have such subjects as stolen lettuce leaves and an
alien guinea pig (in a lunchbox rocket), and _ in all candor but
quite understandably _ they aren't very technically sophisticated.
</P>
<P>
   But Alyssa is fearless about finding her own solutions to
cinematic problems in her shorts, which range from 2 to 5 minutes.
And that _ as Dolores Morris, vice president of HBO Family, notes _
may be the most important thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's astounding how much these kids learn on their own,'' said
Morris, who selected Alyssa's films for the channel's ``30 By 30:
Kid Flicks'' series. ``They aren't afraid of technology. They grab
cameras and computers and just figure it out. Some of the work is
so sophisticated it's almost scary. Other films _ like Alyssa's _
look like they were made by kids, but they're also spontaneous and
fresh and unself-conscious.''
</P>
<P>
   And now that Alyssa has been offered an HBO contract to create a
fourth guinea pig movie, she's mulling over topics.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first I thought I'd make `Guinea Pig for President,' which
would be about an election,'' Alyssa said recently in an interview
in her south Lawrence home. ``But now I'm thinking about a medieval
movie. I could build cardboard castles, and I've got a friend who
could make costumes.''
</P>
<P>
   If it happens, Alyssa will have no problem staging crowd scenes.
She and her parents _ Brad Buecker and Nancy Pistorius _ share
their home with 19 of the South American rodents (as well as two
Yorkie dogs, a cat and a couple of African frogs). All those guinea
pigs require lots of wood-chip bedding, which leaves the Buecker
home smelling like a cedar chest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tend not to do things in moderation,'' said Pistorius.
``Both my husband and I have a soft spot for animals, but we've
finally drawn the line on accepting more guinea pigs. The pet
stores saw us as an easy touch, someone who would adopt all their
unsold pigs. At one point we even ended up with a gerbil with no
back legs that was destined for snake food.''
</P>
<P>
   But what are you going to do when your only child is a guinea
pig fanatic and the president of the local guinea pig club? Alyssa
seems to love everything about the cuddlesome creatures. Perhaps
most appealing are their distinctive personalities.
</P>
<P>
   Hazel, for instance, is ``stupid but sweet.'' Onion Ring is
``short-tempered and rambunctious.'' Sonya is ``completely
laid-back. Not a fighter.''
</P>
<P>
   Given Alyssa's attraction to guinea pigs, it only makes sense
that they became the subject of her first movie, ``Hazel the Guinea
Pig's Package,'' which was shot three years ago as part of a
community filmmaking class at Oldfather Studio in Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
   Her second effort was ``The Christmas Caper,'' shot in Alyssa's
bedroom with the family's video camera on a set dressed with Barbie
furniture. The story: When tasty lettuce intended as a Christmas
present is secretly gobbled down by a couple of young guinea pigs,
their mother calls in a detective _ Hazel again _ to solve the
mystery.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, Alyssa turned out ``Guinea Pigs From Mars,'' in
which Earth pigs encounter a spacecraft inhabited by a rodent from
outer space. They provide the fuel the visitor needs to go home.
</P>
<P>
   Alyssa said that guinea pigs don't take direction well. As a
result, her films rely on luck and circumstance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I can get them to go where I want by waving carrots
just out of sight,'' she said. ``But mostly I just let them run
around the set and film them, and then see what I can do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Alyssa handles just about every aspect of production: building
sets, operating the video camera, dubbing most of the pigs' voices
and editing the footage.
</P>
<P>
   So far Alyssa isn't getting rich from her films _ she received
$100 from HBO for her three shorts _ and she's not even sure that
she wants to make a career of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to do something with computers and pets _ maybe
become a vet,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
