<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABUSE-FAMILY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN CONVICTED IN PHYSICAL ABUSE OF TWO CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY RIZZO  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLATHE, Kan. _ They came to Kansas City last summer to enjoy the
area's attractions. But for the 8-year-old Wichita-area boy and his
6-year-old sister, the visit became a nightmarish month of torture
at the hands of the relative who was supposed to take care of them.
</P>
<P>
   Their 12-year-old sister was forced to watch as the younger
children were beaten and kicked. They were bound with duct tape and
burned with hot water and bleach, and clumps of hair were pulled
from their heads.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Merriam woman whom the children stayed with last
July and August pleaded no contest in Johnson County District Court
to two felony counts of child abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Silvia Wheeler, 35, leaned on a cane and cried as
Assistant District Attorney Sheri McCracken detailed the children's
injuries in the case against her.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing evidence that would have been presented at trial,
District Judge Peter Ruddick found Wheeler guilty of the charges.
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler is a cousin of the children's father. Relatives told
police that Wheeler may have injured the children in an attempt to
obtain prescription pain medication.
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler has a history of drug-related offenses, according to
Johnson County court records. She is on probation for prescription
fraud, and she illegally possessed methadone when she was arrested
in the abuse case. The methadone charge was dismissed as part of
Tuesday's plea.
</P>
<P>
   Merriam police Detective Mike Daniels said investigators were
never able to determine the motive for the abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as the injuries and trauma, this is one of the top two
child-abuse cases I've ever seen,'' said Daniels, who has been in
law enforcement for 12 years. A previous case involved similar
injuries to a younger child.
</P>
<P>
   Daniels was dispatched to Wichita to interview the children
after the abuse was reported there in August. They were scared and
withdrawn, he said. The little girl sat clutching a teddy bear and
wouldn't talk at all. He said it was obvious that they were
suffering painful injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Photographs that McCracken offered in court Tuesday showed both
children with swaths of bright pink flesh on their faces, buttocks,
backs and arms where the outer skin had been burned or rubbed away.
</P>
<P>
   The children came to stay with Wheeler in early July. The abuse
was not discovered until Aug. 9, when their mother took them back
home to the Wichita area.
</P>
<P>
   A week before, their father had tried to get them, but Wheeler
turned out the lights and hid the children, McCracken said. Other
relatives assured the father that the children were fine, and he
went home without them.
</P>
<P>
   The 12-year-old sister later told police that Wheeler had
threatened to blame her for the injuries if she tried to tell
anyone.
</P>
<P>
   The older girl said she saw her siblings slammed into floors and
doors. Scalding water and bleach were poured on them and scrubbed
on their bodies. A chemical burn damaged the little girl's left
eye. Her brother was suffering extreme weight loss and dehydration,
according to McCracken.
</P>
<P>
   She said both children suffered second-degree thermal and
chemical burns. At times, the children were bound with duct tape,
had socks stuffed in their mouths and their mouths were taped shut.
</P>
<P>
   The boy told police that Wheeler was ``always mad.'' Once, he
told police, he tried to run away, but she caught him and
threatened to kill him.
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler remained free on bond pending her sentencing, which was
scheduled for April 9. How long Wheeler may have to serve will be
determined by Kansas sentencing guidelines, which depend in part on
previous convictions.
</P>
</TEXT>
