<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CHINA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA THREATENS TO VETO U.N. FORCE IN MACEDONIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO, KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-ASSESS) 
(nk) 
 By PAUL LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Adding a new dose of uncertainty to the
Balkans, China said Wednesday that it would veto leaving a United
Nations peacekeeping force in Macedonia, which borders the region
where Serbs and ethnic Albanians have been locked in bitter
fighting.
</P>
<P>
   The peacekeeping force, which has served as a firebreak against
spreading instability in the Balkans since 1995, is due for renewal
with a vote on Thursday in the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   The council's 14 members other than China have indicated their
support for the mission, but as one of the five permanent members,
China has veto power.
</P>
<P>
   In explaining Beijing's decision, its representative here, Qin
Huasan, said his government had previously made clear its
reservations about the Macedonia force but had taken a ``flexible
and cooperative approach.'' Now, he said, ``the situation is
changed.''
</P>
<P>
   What has changed, Western diplomats here agreed, is that
Macedonia has become embroiled in China's dispute with Taiwan. Last
month the Macedonians granted diplomatic recognition to Taiwan in
return for a substantial aid package, estimated here at between $1
billion and $1.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days Chinese diplomats told other Security Council
members that they ``cannot be responsible for the consequences'' of
Macedonia's decision to recognize Taiwan, which Beijing regards as
a renegade province, and they repeated their argument that the
Macedonia force was no longer justified.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Qin said, the 1,100-member force _ consisting mainly
of some 360 American soldiers, 640 Scandinavians, and 51
Indonesians _ had completed its mandate and ``should be
concluded.'' Consequently, China would exercise its veto for only
the fifth time and kill a resolution that would have extended the
mission for another six months.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats said that a Chinese veto means that the peacekeepers
will be forced to return to barracks and can no longer continue
their assigned task of monitoring Macedonia's borders with Albania
and the troubled southern Serbian province of Kosovo in order to
prevent the unrest in those areas from spreading.
</P>
<P>
   It also means that the force will be unable to play its other
role as a confidence-builder between the various ethnic factions
within Macedonia, which broke away from Yugoslavia in 1992.
Macedonia has a population that is about 30 percent ethnic
Albanian, with important Bulgarian, Turkish and Gypsy minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats say they will now try to persuade China to let
the troops remain at the bases in Macedonia for another month or so
while they work out some other solution. Various possibilities are
under discussion, including turning the mission over to NATO, the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe or some group
of interested countries operating outside the U.N. framework.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping a military force in Macedonia might come to seem less
necessary if the Serbs and the Kosovo Albanians agree to the West's
peace plan for Kosovo and allow NATO to deploy a large force there.
</P>
<P>
   Last week when he recommended that the Security Council keep the
peacekeepers in Macedonia for another six months, U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan said their presence has helped
insulate the country against ``spillover'' from the conflict in
Kosovo as well as from the general instability pervading the
region.
</P>
<P>
   ``The confidence inspired by its presence has been useful in
defusing tensions that could have arisen as a result of the
continued crisis in Kosovo,'' Annan wrote in his report.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing has consistently sought to punish countries that afford
Taiwan recognition as an independent state. Conversely, Taiwan,
with a prosperous industrialized economy, is known to have offered
substantial rewards in the past to countries willing to defy
Beijing's wishes.
</P>
<P>
   This is the third time China has used, or threatened to use, its
Security Council veto to block U.N. peacekeeping operations in
countries whose friendly relations with Taiwan angered Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 China blocked plans to send military observers to
Guatemala after that country tried to raise Taiwan's international
status in the General Assembly. But it lifted its veto 10 days
later after receiving private assurances from the Guatemalans. The
previous year China threatened to do the same over Haiti but gave
way again after receiving private assurances.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
