<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORD-SPEECH-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP MUST GO TO THE MIDDLE TO WIN, GERALD FORD TELLS AUDIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN BURNES  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDEPENDENCE, Mo. _ Republicans should concentrate on reclaiming
the middle of the political road, former President Gerald Ford said
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are not going to win if you retain only the policies of
the hard right,'' he said during a private reception at the Truman
Library in Independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democrats lost when they were on the hard left. Don't be
stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford addressed more than 200 people in the Truman Library
auditorium. His appearance highlighted the public opening Wednesday
of a traveling exhibit, ``/{Time/} and the Presidency,'' which
showcases /{Time/} magazine photographs of every president since
Franklin Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   In prepared remarks, and later in responses to questions put to
him by longtime /{Time/} magazine staff writer Hugh Sidey and
Walter Isaacson, the magazine's managing editor, Ford discussed the
possibility of a woman president as well as his belief that the
country's politicians should be prepared to move beyond the
President Clinton-Monica Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know something about healing a divided country,'' Ford said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why, last October, well aware that it wouldn't be
popular with many in my own political party, I proposed to end the
Lewinsky matter with a formal, public and bipartisan rebuke of the
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, ``I hope that anyone who wants to be president in 2001 will
focus on America's future rather than Bill Clinton's past. The past
we can leave to history. And there's no way to spin history.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford insisted the country would soon see a woman president, and
even had a scenario as to how it would come to pass. A woman first
will get elected as a vice president, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then the president will die, get shot or something, the woman
will become president and that will be the last time we have a male
president,'' he said, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, Sidey explained how sexual indiscretion is
not synonymous with the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Sidey, who has covered each president since Dwight Eisenhower
for /{Time/}, said that one result of the Clinton-Lewinsky scandal
was the rise of the dubious wisdom that ``everybody did it'' when
serving in the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's nonsense,'' Sidey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I covered nine presidents. Two of them did, and one of them
possibly did. But six of them did not.''
</P>
<P>
   If Presidents Clinton and Kennedy did commit such indiscretions
while in office, and if Lyndon Johnson did also, as some historians
have speculated, Sidey said, that leaves many more presidents who
did not. That's one reason the institution of the presidency will
survive today's scandal, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there is no doubt in my mind that Bill Clinton's
presidency has been diminished,'' he said
</P>
<P>
   Isaacson said the Lewinsky scandal demonstrated the strength of
the office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I happen to be one of those optimists,'' he said. ``I believe
that the events of the last year showed the strength of the
presidency and the common sense of our democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   The /{Time/} exhibit consists of several small galleries devoted
to presidents from Franklin Roosevelt through Clinton, all
featuring photographs from the pages of /{Time/}. The exhibit,
which will travel to other presidential libraries over the next two
years, starts at the Truman Library, where it will stay through May
15.
</P>
<P>
   Sidey conceded that the White House correspondents he joined
during the Eisenhower administration operated under different rules
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then, the press was not as hostile or destructive. Most
of the media people back then wanted the president to succeed.
There was a feeling that we all were in this together, and there
wasn't this wretched hostility that has grown up over the years.''
</P>
<P>
   John Kennedy, Sidey said, was an indiscreet president whose
infidelities were not brought to light because he enjoyed what now
appears to be a ``window'' before the rise of more aggressive
broadcast television correspondents.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was before there was Geraldo, before the scrutiny that
was so intense,'' Sidey said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
