<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-DR.ROSS-SPI </SLUG>
  
 DEAR DR. ROSS: wHY LEAVE `ER' TO COME HERE?  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors love to localize the big story, give it a spin that
resonates with the hometown crowd. In a report from the Super Bowl,
for instance, you'll always find an item on the athlete who once
played for the Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   So, in a pre-emptive strike against any editors who may have
been watching George Clooney's valedictory on ``ER'' last week, we
offer this journalistic localization.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Dr. Ross,
</P>
<P>
   Word is you've ordered your last Chem-7 in the Windy City and
are heading west. Northwest, to be precise. Portland or Seattle, to
be more precise.
</P>
<P>
   What's up with that?
</P>
<P>
   You think a hospital out here is going to hire a rule-flouting,
lip-pouting, authority-doubting guy just because he went to medical
school in Seattle and happens to love kids? I can't speak for
Portland, Dougie, but we don't brook any violation of protocol out
here in the Big Wheezy. Aside from Starbucks' plan for peace,
harmony and good parking kharma through self-espresso, we take
things seriously. Shoot, anyone who breaks a humerus has to go to
California for treatment. No funny business in Seattle. No sirree,
Bob, Doug.
</P>
<P>
   So don't get any ideas, Mr. pesky pediatrician. There'll be no
cutting in the latte line without permission, no honking the horn
without permission, and no upping the morphine drip without
permission.
</P>
<P>
   As to your job prospects, well, let's go to the videotape. You
engaged in a little unauthorized euthanasia, lied to your
supervisors, jeopardized their careers, walked out on the woman who
loves you, prompted her demotion and almost got her clinic shut
down, endangered the life of a colleague in a car wreck, and seem
to have lost the will to shave. Based on a preliminary scan of the
job market, the only things you're qualified for right now are
tortured country singer and special guest on Springer.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle liked country before country was cool, Doug, but
Nashville might be the smarter choice here. As for Jerry Springer,
he tapes in Chicago. You wouldn't even have to leave town. (Carol
Hathaway would be so happy.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, if you must go, here's a tip. When you get out this way,
find KACL on the radio dial and tune in this shrink of the airwaves
named Frasier Crane. He's so haughty he makes Microsoft humble, but
he gives good counsel when not engaged in dilettantish foppery. You
may not like him, but he recently spent a few months in your shoes.
Unemployed, that is. Besides, he grew up here and has been back in
the area for almost six years. Might be a good contact.
</P>
<P>
   One more thing. Before you leave Chicago for good, there's this
German place on Adams, just off State. It's called the Berghoff.
Been there forever. If you don't mind, could you pick up a hot
corned beef sandwich with potato salad? Hold the gastric lavage.
</P>
<P>
   Many thanks.
</P>
<P>
   Best regards,
</P>
<P>
   John
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
