<HEADER>
A7961 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRFORCE-CUTS25-COX     02-24 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRFORCE-CUTS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Air Force to cut research jobs
 &HT;    By Timothy R. Gaffney
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The Air Force is preparing to cut research jobs
at Wright-Patterson Air Force and elsewhere as it struggles to
downsize to a smaller budget.
</P>
<P>
   Cuts in the Air Force Research Laboratory's highly technical
work force of about 6,000 people are expected as early as next
week. Congressional staff sources say the Air Force wants to
complete the lengthy reduction-in-force process by Oct. 1, when the
next fiscal year begins.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force has not disclosed the size of the cuts, but
lawmakers are bracing for ``significant'' cuts in their districts,
one congressional aide said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Tony Hall (D-Dayton) said the expected cuts will have
``a dramatic, long-term effect on our ability to design new weapons
systems'' and will ``affect the lives of hundreds of the scientists
who conduct the research.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall is among several lawmakers critical of the sudden move. The
Clinton administration just delivered the budget for fiscal year
2000 at the beginning of February.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Air Force is trying to push this change before Congress
has a chance to question it or examine other options,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional sources were uncertain how big the personnel cuts
will be, but the scale of the funding cuts has stirred concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't know the magnitude of the personnel cuts until the
Air Force completes its (accounting) exercise. However, given the
magnitude of the budget cuts, the personnel cuts are significant,''
Hall aide Michael Gessel said.
</P>
<P>
   Any cuts in AFRL are likely to have a big impact on Wright-Pat.
</P>
<P>
   AFRL's headquarters is there and half of its 10 research
facilities, dubbed directorates, are located at Wright-Pat in the
Wright Research Site. The Wright site is responsible for nearly
half of AFRL's approximately $1.27 billion in science and
technology funds in this year's budget. About 2,400 civilian and
military AFRL personnel work at Wright-Pat.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers contend the cuts result from an abrupt decision in the
Air Force to funnel an extra $100 million into space-based radar
and laser programs at the expense of other research.
</P>
<P>
   Hall and other lawmakers whose districts include AFRL research
sites said the Air Force is shortcutting the congressional budget
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hasn't become law yet (but) they're already assuming it's
going to happen,'' U.S. Rep. Ciro Rodriguez (D-Texas) said Tuesday.
His district includes Brooks Air Force Base, where AFRL confirmed
it plans to eliminate research on pilot physiology and training.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force's proposed budget would reduce applied research,
basic research and advanced technology development _ the three
accounts that form its science and technology budget _ by more than
$84 million.
</P>
<P>
   Research programs at Wright-Pat, such as advanced propulsion and
materials, would take significant cuts. One area _ hypersonics,
research on extremely high-speed aircraft and missiles _ would be
eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, AFRL is boosting space-related research, mainly on
space-based radars and lasers.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the space-based laser _ a derivative of the Reagan
administration's so-called ``Star Wars'' ballistic missile defense
program _ would get $63.8 million next year, nearly double this
year's funding level.
</P>
<P>
   Laboratory cuts cause special concern because the Air Force was
founded on the notion that its war-fighting ability would be based
on science. Today's most advanced technologies, such as stealth,
``smart'' bombs and night-attack capability, reflect years or
decades of scientific research and technology development.
</P>
<P>
   But the Air Force's science capability resides in the brainpower
of its researchers. More than half of AFRL's work force _ about
3,500 _ are scientists or engineers. More than 800 have Ph.Ds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Air Force has suddenly decided to dismantle a major part
of its capability,'' Gessel said. ``When these people go out the
door, it will be very difficult to get (the capability) back.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez likened the research cuts to getting rid of farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't start a farm after you realize you need food. It
takes time to develop,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   AFRL spokeswoman Maj. Ginger Jabour said she couldn't release
any information about job reductions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Air Force is going to be making the announcement'' at the
Pentagon, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But AFRL Commander Maj. Gen. Richard Paul acknowledged the
``painful internal exercise'' of identifying jobs to be cut In an
open letter to AFRL personnel.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force's push to become an ``Expeditionary Aerospace
Force'' means research must focus on space-based programs, he wrote
in the February ``Commander's Corner'' on the AFRL Internet Web
site.
</P>
<P>
   ``The above strategy will affect almost every AFRL site in terms
of reducing or eliminating programs and their associated manpower.
We are in the process of identifying specific numbers for each,
which we hope to have by the end of February,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
