<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-COLUMN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Isakson a civil influence for Washington
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If ever a town seemed to need somebody, Washington
needs Johnny Isakson.
</P>
<P>
   It's not simply Isakson's affable, low-decibel style that makes
one hopeful he can have a positive influence in the poisonous
atmosphere of present-day Washington. Many a rational,
bridge-building civic leader has gone off to Congress and been
turned into a partisan cynic.
</P>
<P>
   What's especially encouraging about the newly elected 6th
District congressman is that his civility has already been tested
under difficult circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Before most of his Republican colleagues in Washington knew what
it was like to play hardball with James Carville and Paul Begala,
Isakson had the experience in his 1990 governor's race against Zell
Miller. He had a bitter battle within his own party in the 1996
U.S. Senate primary with Guy Millner, and has differed with the
religious right over the most contentious subject, abortion.
</P>
<P>
   But the Isakson family fortune is based on residential real
estate, a field in which the ability to smooth over disagreements
in order to make a deal is reckoned a virtue. It's been the
defining stamp of his political career.
</P>
<P>
   As a suburban legislator during the Georgia GOP's formative
years, Isakson learned how to operate within the House of Tom
Murphy and the party of Newt Gingrich, a contradictory challenge
that would test the skills of the most nimble negotiator. When
Miller reached across party lines to tap him for the job of state
school board chairman, his reputation, as one who could put old
grudges behind him and provide leadership for a bipartisan agenda,
was sealed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't plan on being any different in Washington than I am in
Georgia,'' Isakson said Wednesday. As the most junior member of the
House, until Louisiana's 1st District elects a successor to Bob
Livingston this summer, Isakson's ability to work any change on the
prevailing culture of Washington will be modest, but he arrives at
a time when the capital is searching for signals of the national
mood.
</P>
<P>
   Isakson said he thought his solid win in Tuesday's special
election ``sent a message about negative politics.'' It didn't hurt
that he had an overwhelming advantage in money and name
recognition, but after two bruising losses in which negative
attacks against him played a part, Isakson was entitled to draw his
own lesson from the victory.
</P>
<P>
   For whatever it means as a bellwether, there could hardly be a
sharper change in style than the transition from Gingrich to
Isakson. In the long run they are in the same party, however.
</P>
<P>
   His differences with social conservatives have been ``by degree,
but not by direction,'' Isakson said. Within Republican ranks that
direction isn't always clear right now.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert is backing away from the 10 percent
income tax cut Isakson campaigned on, but the new congressman said
he was confident the Republican Congress will continue to search
for ``responsible tax cuts'' and that the income tax would be ``the
major debate of the presidential election in 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime there is the necessary work of making Washington
a more civil place, a job Johnny Isakson was made for.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
