<SLUG> BC-VETERANS-BUDGET25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LAWMAKERS CRITICIZE CLINTON BUDGET FOR VETERANS
 &HT;    By SUE SCHULTZ
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lawmakers on Wednesday criticized the
administration's Department of Veterans Affairs budget for next
year, claiming it would degrade medical care for veterans.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's plan would freeze the VA medical care budget
at $17.3 billion, same amount appropriated this year. The budget
also called for new initiatives, including treatment of hepatitis
C, treatment of 54,000 additional veterans, and the opening of 89
new outpatient clinics.
</P>
<P>
   ``While the president's budget supports a number of important
initiatives, it offers no new dollars to support them,'' said Rep.
Lane Evans of Illinois, the ranking Democratic member of the House
Committee on Veterans Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Clifford Stearns, R-Fla., who chairs the panel's health
subcommittee, called the VA budget proposal ``troubling. This
budget includes $1 billion in cuts.''
</P>
<P>
   The subcommittee's ranking Democrat, Rep. Mike Doyle of
Pennsylvania, said members on both sides of the aisle were
concerned about the proposed budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``This committee will work to increase the budget for the
Department of Veterans Affairs,'' Doyle said.
</P>
<P>
   State veterans' officials who testified at the hearing were
sharply critical of the budget proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This administration ... does not understand anything about the
military or about our veterans and could care less,'' said Nick
Bacon, director of the Arkansas Department of Veteran Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Trujillo, a former Veterans Health Administration network
director for Arizona, New Mexico, and the western part of Texas,
said ``administering this budget will be like trying to build a
house of cards in an Oklahoma tornado.''
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference earlier Wednesday, several veterans groups
asked the department to release plans for any possible cuts in
veterans' medical care and services or the closure of any
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   In a joint statement, the organizations expressed concern at the
plan to eliminate nearly 8,000 fulltime employees from VA health
care nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our nation's veterans should be warned now what medical
services stand to be curtailed or eliminated in the event this
restrictive budget is allowed to prevail,'' said Homer Townsend,
Jr., national president of the Paralyzed Veterans of America.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
