<HEADLINE>
SMILE AT THE LAPTOP AND SAY `CHEESE' 
A TAG KNOWS YOUR NAME, AND IT KNOWS WHERE YOU ARE  
NEW PLAYSTATION IS EXPECTED TO HAVE THE POWER OF A PC  
PRIVATE E-MAIL GREETINGS ARE MADE PUBLIC BY MISTAKE  
HITACHI OFFERS BIGGER NOTEPAD FOR THE SCREEN-TAPPING CROWD  
GATEWAY TO GIVE A YEAR OF NET ACCESS WITH COMPUTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)   (rk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Users of a new Sony laptop computer can alternately
``point and click'' and ``point and shoot.''
</P>
<P>
   At last week's Technology Entertainment Design Conference, Sony
introduced the Picturebook, a $2,300 laptop computer with an
embedded digital camera. The camera, which sits at the top of the
monitor and can be swiveled 360 degrees, is designed to capture and
store still images and up to 60 seconds of video images. The
computer runs at 266 megahertz, with 64 megabytes of memory and a
4.3-gigabyte hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to differentiate its new laptop from a zillion clone
computers with similar processing speed and memory, Sony promises
that the Picturebook is an ``all-in-one solution for professionals
on the go,'' including such disparate users as real-estate agents,
interior designers and journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the company insists that the Picturebook will be a boon to
parents who want to store images of the family and use e-mail to
send them to far-flung relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it may be a while before desktop-based digital cameras
are seen as something more than a gimmick, particularly given that
limited bandwidth makes it time-consuming to send and receive
pictures. And users may still find it socially awkward to arrange
the children into a portrait, raise the mobile computer, and say,
``OK, everyone, smile for the laptop.''
</P>
<P>
   _ MATT RICHTEL
</P>
<P>
   A Tag Knows Your Name, And It Knows Where You Are
</P>
<P>
   Should employees be paranoid about their own name tags? A new
technology called Arial View uses badges that emit infrared signals
every two seconds to monitor electronically the exact location of
employees. Receiver-transmitters can be placed in each room of a
business to pick up the signals and report an employee's
whereabouts to a computer system.
</P>
<P>
   But the maker of the Arial View, the Arial Systems Corp. of
Vernon Hills, Ill. (www.arialsystems.com), insists that employees
should not mind. It says the system gives salespeople and managers
more freedom to move around the office, while still being
accessible for urgent phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   What if the employee does not want to be found? It is not
possible to turn off a badge's infrared emitter, an Arial spokesman
said, acknowledging that some skeptical clients worry that the
monitoring technology may be less of a big help and more like Big
Brother.
</P>
<P>
   _ MATT RICHTEL
</P>
<P>
   New Playstation Is Expected To Have the Power of a PC  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Parents who worry that their children while away too many hours
playing video games now have permission to become apoplectic.
</P>
<P>
   The new version of the Sony Playstation will be powered by a
processor many times more powerful than the current generation,
some video game industry analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   For nerds keeping score at home, the chip is expected to run at
250 megahertz, up from 33 megahertz in the current Playstation. The
processor is slated to be 128-bit, up from 33-bit (the bit
measurement indicates the amount of information that can be
processed at once).
</P>
<P>
   Translation: the game station is expected to include a big
upgrade in graphics, 3-D imagery and video capability that could
induce an entire generation to never leave the joystick.
</P>
<P>
   Sony acknowledged that it was working on such a chip in
partnership with Toshiba. But Sony did not confirm that it would
use the chip in the next generation Playstation, nor would it
disclose when the game system would be in stores. Industry analysts
expect it to be available late this year.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the advance in the microprocessor means that the
brain of the Playstation _ and for that matter, the brains of
competing game systems _ is matching and in some respects exceeding
the power of PC processors.
</P>
<P>
   Sega, a Sony competitor, sells a game station in Japan called
Dreamcast that can double as a CD player and Internet terminal.
Dreamcast, with a 128-bit processor and a 200-megahertz chip, will
be available in the United States in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Video game chips ``used to be the ugly stepchildren, while PCs
got the real he-man chips,'' said Tim Turley, senior editor of The
Microprocessor Report, which follows the chip industry. ``One of
the trends we're seeing is that chips in consumer items will give
PCs a real run for their money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The gory details are uninteresting to most consumers,'' he
added, but he said the bottom line was that ``the next-generation
Playstation will be even cooler than the current one.''
</P>
<P>
   _ MATT RICHTEL
</P>
<P>
   Private E-Mail Greetings Are Made Public by Mistake  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hallmark, which encourages lovers to open their hearts,
inadvertently opened a database of supposedly private personal
tidings, leaving some of them in a public place.
</P>
<P>
   The Hallmark site permits well-wishers to send private e-mail
missives to one another. The trouble is, the company left a file
containing some private messages attached to the site's publicly
accessible search engine.
</P>
<P>
   Hallmark attributed the mistake to a ``programming error'' that
occurred when the company upgraded its servers in December. Julie
O'Dell, a company spokeswoman, said the messages were publicly
accessible for eight weeks, until Hallmark corrected the problem
earlier this month. She also noted that the affected messages were
from 18 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   But if Hallmark is having trouble with Web secrecy, it is not
having any problem keeping secret the number of messages affected
by the programming error.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. O'Dell would say only that fewer than 1 percent of messages
sent from the site had been affected. She declined to give an
absolute figure or provide a number from which the percentage was
drawn.
</P>
<P>
   _ MATT RICHTEL
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Hitachi Offers Bigger Notepad For the Screen-Tapping Crowd  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hitachi has given the stone writing tablet a major upgrade. This
week, the company introduced the HPW-600ET Handheld PC, which is
something of a mix of a personal digital assistant and a stone
tablet. The computer is 6 inches long and nearly 9 inches wide, but
the surface area is taken up almost entirely by a touch-sensitive
screen.
</P>
<P>
   Users interact with the device either with a stylus or the
old-fashioned way, with a finger (or the really old-fashioned way,
with a stick). The computer comes loaded with Windows CE fare,
including Pocket Word, Powerpoint and Excel.
</P>
<P>
   Selling for $1,199, the gadget also includes a 56K modem and 16
megabytes of memory. It weighs less than two pounds and has a
battery life of nine hours, the company said. The company is
pitching the tablet not just for consumers but also for industrial
uses, like the documentation of patients' status by health-care
workers.
</P>
<P>
   _ MATT RICHTEL
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gateway To Give a Year Of Net Access With Computers  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the clearest evidence yet that the Internet is the main
catalyst for PC sales today, computer maker Gateway said Wednesday
that it would now include a year's worth of Internet access in the
price of nearly all new computers it sells.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, customers had to pay about $15 a month to connect to
the Internet through Gateway's own Internet service, Gateway.net.
</P>
<P>
   The company also said it had paid about $21 million for a 19.9
percent stake in the online retail operation of NECX, a company
based in Peabody, Mass., that sells computers, software and
peripherals over the Internet. NECX will operate a new online store
for Gateway called Spotshop.com, where customers can shop for more
than 30,000 computer products, not just Gateway products.
</P>
<P>
   Gateway customers will be able to have all of their computing
needs met entirely through Gateway's Internet services, said Ted
Waitt, the company's co-founder and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Waitt said he expected that other PC makers, including Gateway's
chief rivals, Dell and Compaq, would also eventually begin bundling
Internet access as a standard feature on new PCs.
</P>
<P>
   Gateway was the first direct vendor of PCs to become a
nationwide Internet service provider, but early customers
complained of unreliable service and difficulty connecting to the
system.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Gateway subcontracted its Internet operations
to UUNet, a division of MCI Worldcom, which will provide service
under the new bundling plan.
 &UR;  &LR; _ PETER H. LEWIS &QR; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
