<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDEPENDENT-COUNSEL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS SPLIT OVER WHETHER INDEPENDENT COUNSEL LAW IS NEEDED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite growing pressure in Congress to kill the
independent counsel law, several senators warned Wednesday that
letting the statute die this summer would mean trusting the
president to police himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we truly going to let the executive branch investigate
itself?'' asked Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., at the opening of a
hearing by the Senate Government Affairs Committee into whether the
law should be extended beyond its June 30 expiration date.
</P>
<P>
   Domenici and other Republican senators pointed to the refusal of
Attorney General Janet Reno to recommend an independent counsel to
investigate possible campaign finance violations by President
Clinton and Vice President Al Gore. The refusal, they said, proves
that the Department of Justice cannot be trusted to investigate the
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attorney general has turned a deaf ear to this issue
despite overwhelming evidence of wrongdoing, and recommendations
from FBI Director (Louis) Freeh and her own top official to appoint
an independent counsel,'' Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Penn., said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Reno's hand-picked campaign-finance prosecutor,
Charles La Bella, who left the job in July, urged that an
independent counsel look into charges of campaign law violations by
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The ranking Democrat on the committee, Sen. Joseph Lieberman of
Connecticut, also warned his colleagues against letting the law
expire. ``I don't think we should walk away from a noble goal: to
protect the integrity of this country's legal system,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Lieberman and other supporters of the law said it must
be changed. ``We've either got to fix it or drop it and look for
another mechanism,'' said Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., a principal
author of the 1978 statute that was supposed to take politics out
of investigating high-ranking officials.
</P>
<P>
   Levin and other senators suggested cutting the scope of such
probes and the time prosecutors can spend on them. The recommended
changes include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Limiting the tenure of independent counsels to 18 months;
</P>
<P>
   _ Giving the attorney general more power to investigate
allegations before requesting an independent counsel;
</P>
<P>
   _ Requiring that the scope of the investigation be narrowly set;
</P>
<P>
   _ Barring prosecutors from practicing law privately while they
serve as independent counsels.
</P>
<P>
   _ Limiting the subject matter of a probe to issues that arose
during an official's tenure in office, not before;
</P>
<P>
   _ Requiring that lawyers considered for independent counsel
positions have significant prosecutorial experience.
</P>
<P>
   But many committee members, including Chairman Fred Thompson of
Tennessee, appeared skeptical that any changes could offset the
problems they say the law has caused.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is nobody's independent, and if they are, they're
probably dangerous,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he worried that the intense media spotlight placed
on independent counsels ``pressured'' them to produce results,
regardless of the merits of the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Independent counsels know that they will be judged by the
number of scalps they put on the wall,'' he said. ``That wouldn't
happen with a normal prosecutor in a normal case.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Durbin, D-Ill., said the law had created an
``out-of-control'' office that has no ``limits on its power.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I made the mistake four years ago of voting to renew this
law,'' he said. ``I won't make the same mistake this time.''
</P>
<P>
   Former White House Chief of Staff Howard Baker agreed with the
senators who want the law to expire. He said almost any effort to
revise it so soon after President Clinton's impeachment acquittal
``is likely to be a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker, who is also a former Senate Reublican leader, added, ``We
ought to write on a clean slate. We ought to cool off, let some
time go by'' before deciding how to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel law was passed in 1978 in the wake of
the 1972-1974 Watergate scandal during which President Richard
Nixon ordered the attorney general to dismiss special Watergate
prosecutor Archibald Cox after Cox refused to drop a subpoena for
Nixon's incriminating White House tapes.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional Republicans complained about Independent Counsel
Lawrence Walsh's six-year, $48 million probe into the Ronald Reagan
administration's Iran-Contra arms-for-hostages deals of the 1980s,
saying the investigation was politically inspired.
</P>
<P>
   The law lapsed in 1992. When it was taken up again in 1993, 28
Senate Republicans threatened to filibuster against renewing it.
But a newly-elected President Clinton lobbied for it and won.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, when a three-judge federal court panel appointed
Kenneth Starr to investigate Clinton, Democrats have repeated many
criticisms of the law that Republicans had voiced earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that each side has seen its oxen gored by this law, there
isn't a whole lot of stomach left for keeping it around,'' Thompson
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The law requires the attorney general to seek appointment of an
independent counsel when there is substantial and credible evidence
of a crime by any one of 49 top federal officials, including the
president. A panel of three federal judges then picks an attorney
for the job.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutor has an unlimited budget to hire aides and
investigate _ a frequent point of criticism. Starr has spent nearly
$50 million on his investigation of allegations against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   With approval from the attorney general and the appointing
judges, the independent counsel can broaden investigations far
beyond the original mandate, another target of the law's critics.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's mandate, for example, began with inquiries into
Clinton's Whitewater land deals in Arkansas and widened repeatedly,
finally to the Monica Lewinsky scandal that led to his impeachment
and trial. The Senate acquitted him Feb. 12 of perjury and
obstruction of justice.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Testifying before the committee Wednesday, a panel of legal
experts, including several former independent counsels, disagreed
on whether the law should be allowed to expire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I long ago concluded that this statute is unworkable,'' said
Griffin Bell, attorney general under President Jimmy Carter. He
said that because of their unlimited resources and tenure,
independent counsels ``unfairly'' investigate every aspect of an
official's life.
</P>
<P>
   However, Arthur H. Christy, who in 1978 was the first
independent counsel appointed, said that while the law had
``flaws,'' it was necessary to check the power of the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``This law is not perfect and needs to be changed,'' he said.
``But there must be some mechanism in place to ensure the executive
is not allowed to commit crimes and sweep them under the rug.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
