<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-ARREST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAR OWNER CHARGED IN NORTHERN IRELAND BOMBING 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JAMES F. CLARITY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBLIN, Ireland _ A 48-year-old bar owner was charged Wednesday
with complicity in the bombing that killed 29 people and wounded
more than 200 last Aug. 15 in the Northern Ireland town of Omagh.
The attack was the deadliest in the violence that has killed more
than 3,200 in the northern British province since 1969.
</P>
<P>
   The bar owner, Colm Murphy, from Dundalk, Ireland, near the
border with the North, is the first person charged in the attack.
He is said to have conspired to cause an explosion likely to
endanger life between Aug. 13 and Aug. 16 and was also charged with
membership in an illegal paramilitary organization.
</P>
<P>
   As he was charged here in the three-judge Special Criminal
Court, which has no juries, Murphy spoke only to acknowledge his
identity. The court was established to eliminate intimidation of
jurors in cases of organized crime and political terrorism. Murphy
was held pending another court appearance on March 18.
</P>
<P>
   He was one of about 60 people questioned since the attack. Last
weekend, the police in the Irish Republic and Northern Ireland
arrested 11 people for questioning, of whom six were still being
held Wednesday. Murphy is believed by the police to have been close
to a splinter group calling itself the Real IRA, which opposes the
parent Irish Republican Army's 19-month-old cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   The IRA, while refusing to disarm, is supporting the
participation of its political wing, Sinn Fein, in the effort of
the new Northern Ireland Assembly to put in effect the provisions
for new governmental structures under the peace agreement approved
by Roman Catholic and Protestant leaders 10 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Real IRA's political affiliate, the 32-County Sovereignty
Committee, opposes the peace agreement as a sellout to the British
government and the Protestant majority in the North. Sinn Fein says
the agreement is a good start toward closer ties between the North
and the Catholic Irish Republic, although it does not guarantee the
end of British sovereignty in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Among those being held in the North in connection with the
bombing is Francis Mackey, chairman of the Sovereignty Committee,
and an Omagh city councilman who quit Sinn Fein after it approved
the peace plan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
