<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-CONTROL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YORK TAKES CONTROL OF 49ERS, LIMITS DEBARTOLO'S ACCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHUCK FINNIE  
 and SCOTT WINOKUR  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Denise DeBartolo York consolidated her control
over the San Francisco 49ers Wednesday, putting her husband in
charge of the team and moving to end her brother's access to club
cash to pay his personal expenses.
</P>
<P>
   York issued the orders in writing to all 49ers personnel after
she consulted with National Football League Commissioner Paul
Tagliabue and following clashes within the organization over
demands by Edward DeBartolo Jr., the team co-owner, to pay his
bills, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The development is the strongest sign yet that DeBartolo's
banishment from managerial involvement in the NFL is not likely to
end soon, and could be permanent.
</P>
<P>
   York described in a memo to all 49ers personnel the details of
new lines of command and financial controls: ``I hope that you can
appreciate my efforts to provide you clear direction and to assure
compliance with NFL directives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Please be assured that Eddie was provided a copy of this ...
before it was issued. While I would not be surprised if he is not
in agreement with some of these decisions, I know that he
understands my concerns and appreciates that this memorandum was
issued at my direction to provide everyone with a clear set of
guidelines.''
</P>
<P>
   York, who is chairwoman and chief executive officer of the 49ers
parent company, the Edward J. DeBartolo Corp. of Youngstown, Ohio,
gave her husband, John York, and an aide, Keith Lenhart, oversight
responsibility for the team. John York is a DeBartolo Corp. senior
vice president and member of the board of directors. Lenhart is the
corporate controller. Both men will become vice presidents of the
49ers.
</P>
<P>
   Denise York also named former 49ers head coach Bill Walsh as
team vice president and general manager, giving him day-to-day
command of the team. In recent weeks, Walsh served the organization
as an informal adviser.
</P>
<P>
   John McVay will remain team vice president and head of football
operations.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo, apparently taken by surprise, had no immediate
comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all the club's business,'' said NFL spokesman Greg
Aiello. ``I really don't want to try to interpret a club memo.''
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo stepped down as head of the team's operations in
December 1997 when his role in a federal gambling and bribery case
in Louisiana became public. He pleaded guilty in October to a
federal felony, failure to report an alleged extortion attempt in
connection with the government's prosecution of former Louisiana
Gov. Edwin Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo's separation from the team was formalized by Tagliabue
and remains in effect.
</P>
<P>
   Denise York said she must pre-approve any request by DeBartolo
for cash reimbursements for his expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Eddie was involved in the direct management of this team,
he enjoyed many of the benefits, which are earned when undertaking
such responsibility. He no longer functions in that capacity,''
Denise York wrote.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo's free-spending habits have been well-known to club
officials, players and sportswriters for years. After Super Bowls
in 1989 and 1994, he flew players and their wives and girlfriends
to Hawaii and Colorado Springs, Colo. He has lavished expensive
gifts on his players.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-99 1919EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
