<DOCNO> NYT19990224.0320 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7992 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONGKONG-CHINA-NYT &LR;      02-24 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-CHINA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG GOVERNMENT WANTS COURT TO CLARIFY RULING THAT UPSET
MAINLAND CHINA  
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Seeking to quell a bitter dispute with mainland
China, Hong Kong's government Wednesday asked its high court to
clarify a recent landmark ruling that provoked strong objections
from Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have looked at the concerns expressed by a lot of
parties,'' said a government spokesman, Stephen Lam. ``Because
there has been such great concern in the community, we have decided
to seek clarification.''
</P>
<P>
   Late last month, the Hong Kong Court of Final Appeal ruled that
children born on the mainland who have at least one parent living
in Hong Kong have the right to residency here. Officials in Beijing
criticized the decision as a violation of the Chinese Constitution
and warned that they wanted it ``rectified.''
</P>
<P>
   Far from calming the waters, Wednesday's move rattled legal
experts, who said the Hong Kong government appeared to be pressing
the court to retreat from the ruling before the Chinese government
forced its hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is close to a government subversion of the court,'' said
Yash Ghai, an expert in constitutional law at the University of
Hong Kong. ``I would almost prefer if China took the action itself
and bore the responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers here have said that if China overturned the decision, it
would ignite a constitutional crisis. Under the agreement between
Britain and China _ known as ``one country, two systems'' _ Hong
Kong is supposed to be a semi-autonomous region within China, with
its own legal system.
</P>
<P>
   China has not formally demanded that Hong Kong overturn the
ruling. But many people here believe that if the local government
does not mollify Beijing, the Chinese government will probably
repudiate parts of the decision during the annual meeting of the
Chinese National People's Congress next month.
</P>
<P>
   Such a move could stain Hong Kong's reputation as an
international financial center, which depends in part on having
courts that operate without meddling from Beijing. The dispute has
already set off a crisis of confidence among Western diplomats and
business executives, some of whom fear that the rule of law could
become a relic of Hong Kong's colonial past.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ruling is central to Hong Kong's autonomy,'' Ghai said.
``If we lose out on this, Hong Kong will have no more autonomy.''
</P>
<P>
   By asking the court to explain its decision, the Hong Kong
government is raising nettlesome legal issues. Lawyers here said
they were not aware of a precedent for the government to ask its
highest court to reconsider a decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``How is the public supposed to view this?'' asked Margaret Ng,
a lawyer and member of the Legislative Council here. ``I can't help
feeling that the government hasn't thought this through.''
</P>
<P>
   Lam said the government was not acting on orders from Beijing,
though he acknowledged it had taken China's objections into
account. He also said Hong Kong was not trying to overturn the
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very special case,'' Lam said. ``It's not like from
now on, whenever the court makes a ruling we don't like, we're
going to file a motion.''
</P>
<P>
   In its effort to resolve the dispute, Hong Kong is focusing on
the nature of Beijing's objection, which is not to the substance of
the ruling _ that some mainland Chinese children have the right to
live here. What troubles Beijing is that the court said it has the
right to strike down Chinese laws if they violate Hong Kong's
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Some legal experts here said China was misreading the ruling as
an attempt to place Hong Kong's courts above the National People's
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel R. Fung, Hong Kong's former solicitor general who is now
a visiting fellow at Yale Law School, said the court asserted the
right to invalidate Chinese laws ``only insofar as they affect Hong
Kong, not the mainland.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Hong Kong hopes that if its highest court affirms it is
not challenging China's sovereignty, Beijing will let the matter
drop.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-99 1919EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
