u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ACCOUNTING-R&AMP;D-NYT &LR;      02-24 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ACCOUNTING-R&AMP;D-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ACCOUNTING RULES WRITE-OFFS PROPOSED  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.)   By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The board that writes the nation's accounting rules decided
Wednesday that companies should no longer be able to write off
immediately the value of research acquired from other companies.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by the Financial Accounting Standards Board is
preliminary but significant because it could soon stop a practice
that is being used by an increasing number of companies buying
other businesses and that recently has raised concerns among
federal securities regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies have been able to acquire another company and
then make most of the purchase price vanish on their accounting
books by using a footnote in the accounting rules that relates to
research expenses. The rule allows companies to write off the cost
of continuing research they acquire by immediately deducting the
amount from the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   The board decided Wednesday to abolish that rule and instead
require companies to put the value of the acquired research on
their books as an asset, which would then be slowly written off
over the years, reducing future earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Securities regulators and some accounting analysts have
criticized the current rules, saying they allow companies to mask
the real cost of their acquisitions and leave the buyers looking
more profitable than they are.
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission recently has forced some
companies to reduce significantly the amount that they planned to
write off as projects involving continuing research, which is often
called ``in-process research and development.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, America Online said last year that it planned to
write off most of the $316 million it had paid for Mirabilis Ltd.
and Netchannel Inc. But the company then reduced the research
write-off to $70.5 million, or about 22 percent of the purchase
price of the two companies, after the SEC objected.
</P>
<P>
   If the rule proposed Wednesday by the board had been in place,
America Online would not have been allowed to write off even the
$70.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   The accounting rules relating to research are most often used by
high-technology, pharmaceutical and biotechnology companies. But
even companies like U.S. Filter Corp., the nation's largest
provider of water-treatment systems, have used the rules to write
off acquisition costs recently.
</P>
<P>
   Some Wall Street analysts said Wednesday that if the proposed
rule received final approval, some companies would think twice
about certain acquisitions because their future earnings would be
reduced.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be deals that won't get done,'' said Robert
Willens, a managing director at Lehman Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's decision is part of a larger set of rules relating
to mergers and acquisitions that the board expects to publish this
summer. Companies would then have three months to comment on the
proposed rules before the board's final approval.
</P>
<P>
   But securities regulators have asked the accounting board, which
is based in Norwalk, Conn., to move quickly on the rules relating
to research costs. Timothy S. Lucas, the board's research director,
said Wednesday that the board might decide to separate the research
rules from the rest of the merger accounting rules so that they
could be put in place more quickly. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
