<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEDICARE PANEL HEADS FOR EXTENSION
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A commission on Medicare reforms remained sharply
divided Wednesday over the structure of proposed reforms and
appeared unlikely to meet Monday's deadline for issuing a plan.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Breaux, D-La., the 17-member commission's chairman,
said he would discuss the situation with panel members over the
weekend to determine whether to attempt to finish by the end of
March. The commission's deadline is March 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're close to reaching and agreement, we're going to make
that effort,'' Breaux said Wednesday. He spoke after a three-hour
meeting to review savings estimates for his proposal to let managed
care programs compete for government-subsidized Medicare premiums.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Thomas, R-Calif., the panel's co-chairman, said he was
encouraged by Wednesday's meeting. Thomas said he counted 10 votes
for Breaux's plan, which needs 11 votes to win approval under the
rules that created the panel.
</P>
<P>
   The sharpest opposition to the plan came from several
congressional Democrats and former Medicare head Bruce Vladeck.
They objected to remarks by several commissioners who said they
expected savings from the plan to cover the cost of providing drug
coverage to elderly people with incomes of 135 percent the poverty
level, or about $11,000 for one person.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the premium support fairy is going to come down
out of the sky and give us a drug benefit,'' Vladeck said.
</P>
<P>
   Although various government agencies have estimated Breaux's
plan could save hundreds of billions of dollars over the next
decade by relying on competition to lower premiums, Rep. John
Dingell, D-Mich., said ``I have not gotten a shred of information
that this competition is going to result in any savings.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, said he didn't know if the plan would
result in any savings for Medicare, but said he believed it would
make health care delivery more efficient, which would pay for drug
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
