<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7998 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AVALANCHE-CONTROL-580     02-24 1138
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AVALANCHE-CONTROL-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN COLORADO, AVALANCHE POLICY STRESSES PREVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo.)  (With AUSTRIAN-AVALANCHE) 
(mk) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The kinds of deadly snow rivers that are crashing through Alpine
ski chalets this winter could be crashing through Rocky Mountain
ski condominiums in the future, according to avalanche experts
interviewed Wednesday in Colorado and Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   In the Alps, some of the highest snowfalls in half a century
have set off vast snowslides that have killed dozens of people,
catching many of them in houses built on sites where avalanches are
most likely. Similar scenes could be repeated in the Rockies, where
the populations of some mountain counties are expected to double
over the next 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have the narrow, heavily inhabited valleys of the
Alps,'' said Knox Williams, director of the Colorado Avalanche
Information Center, a state agency. ``But if there is enough of
this condo-mania, enough of this expansion of home sites, we will
start to see this problem in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Because villages dot many Alpine valleys, avalanche control in
Europe involves mainly passive measures. In Switzerland, for
example, about 250 miles of steel and stone fences have been built
on high mountain flanks in order to hold snow in place, and near
the bases of mountains, washboards of earthen mounds have been
built to dissipate the energy of avalanches and to divert them from
houses.
</P>
<P>
   But this winter, with as much as 20 feet of snow falling in
Switzerland in the last six weeks, the barriers have not been
strong enough to hold or divert the snow. Winds have raged up to
150 miles an hour, whipping up dangerous snow packs above villages.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an extraordinary series of weather fronts and strong
northwestern winds,'' Martin Schneebli, a researcher at the Swiss
Federal Institute for the Study of Snow and Avalanches, said from
Davos, which has been marooned by snow for several days.
</P>
<P>
   While Switzerland is one of Europe's leaders in avalanche
deaths, with an average of 20 a year, Colorado leads the United
States, averaging six a year.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Colorado's 20,000 avalanches a year occur on remote
federal land, typically posing no threat to people in towns. In
this setting, avalanche controllers use ``active'' methods, either
bombs or careful ski runs, to trigger smaller avalanches before the
snow masses become too large.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Europe they don't use explosives to trigger avalanches
because they don't know how big the avalanches will be when they
release them,'' said Dale Atkins, an avalanche forecaster in
Colorado. ``In Europe they have more towns, villages, highways and
rail lines'' along avalanche paths ``than we do in the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   Drawing on information from avalanche forecasters and snow
monitors, the Colorado Department of Transportation routinely
closes roads just before dawn and then sets off explosive charges,
either dropped by helicopter or fired from Army howitzers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our whole thing is prevention,'' said Chuck Loerwald, a
regional supervisor for the state DOT, as he prepared to trigger
mini-avalanches Wednesday on Berthoud Pass, a major ski-area access
route. ``We let the little ones come so we don't have the big
ones.''
</P>
<P>
   At Colorado's 20 largest ski areas, many built on historic
avalanche paths, about 300 ski patrollers check for avalanche
threats each morning. They trigger avalanches either by firing
mortar charges or by making ski-cuts _ traversing slopes on skis,
jumping up and down. Nationwide, about one ski patroller is killed
every winter while performing avalanche-control work.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the Rockies, this system has been successful so far. In
Colorado there has not been a skier killed by an avalanche in a ski
area since 1975. On the roads, the last travelers killed by
avalanches died in 1963. But several snowplow drivers have been
killed in recent decades.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these advances, the American avalanche picture is
changing rapidly, owing to an explosion in back-country recreation
in the winter and a surge in home construction in the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Largely because of a rapid increase in back-country skiers,
snowboarders and snowmobilers, the average number of Americans
killed by avalanches has more than tripled, rising from seven a
year in the 1970s to 24 a year in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Although about 100 vacationers were caught in avalanches in
Colorado last year, the state has kept fatalities down through an
aggressive program of educating people on how to survive sliding
snow. Nine out of 10 avalanche victims in the United States set off
their own avalanches, fracturing fragile snow layers through noise
or movement.
</P>
<P>
   With February being the deadliest avalanche month in North
America, Denver television stations recently started broadcasting a
new public service announcement that shows a ``frozen'' snowboarder
hanging on a meat hook next to a pig's head. As the camera pans
around the meat locker, an avalanche beacon can be heard pinging.
</P>
<P>
   Last winter, the Colorado Avalanche Center held safety classes
for 3,500 vacationers, fielded 77,000 calls to its seven
avalanche-status hotlines, registered visits to its Web site, sent
out 30,000 avalanche-alert e-mail messages, and broadcast daily
messages on 11 mountain radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want people's avalanche skills to catch up with their
athletic skills,'' said Knox, who trains people in the use of probe
poles, avalanche shovels and high-tech beacons.
</P>
<P>
   On the technological front, stores recently started selling
digital avalanche beacons that can cut search time in half, to
about 15 minutes. These transceivers can indicate with arrows and
distance measurements the location of a buried victim who is
carrying a beacon. Although only one-third of buried victims
survive, 90 percent are still alive 15 minutes after being buried.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time is the enemy of the buried victim,'' said Atkins, who
teaches avalanche safety.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe, some vacationers have started carrying a German-made
``avalanche airbag.'' With the pull of a ripcord, this backpack
device inflates into a large orange nylon balloon, carrying the
wearer to the top of the snow. It has been credited with saving 18
lives in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   While training and technology may slow fatality rates, some
experts fear that the Rockies are following the residential
development of the Alps, allowing homes to be built at the bases of
old avalanche chutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Avalanche run-out zones are terrific building sites,'' Atkins
said. ``They are down near the valley floor; they have great views
because of the lack of trees. Over the next 20 years, we will see a
significant increase in people building in avalanche areas.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
