<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-EXEC-QUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T'S BUSINESS SERVICES CHIEF QUITS AFTER FIVE MONTHS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Reviving questions about AT&AMP;T Corp.'s ability to
retain entrepreneurial managers, Robert Annunziata, who took over
AT&AMP;T's $22 billion business services unit less than six months ago,
quit Wednesday to become chief executive of Global Crossing Ltd.,
one of AT&AMP;T's fast-moving international competitors.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T bought Annunziata's previous company, Teleport
Communications Group Inc., for more than $11 billion last July
after Annunziata helped build Teleport into one of the nation's
largest local phone companies for business customers.
</P>
<P>
   In September, AT&AMP;T, the nation's biggest communications carrier,
made Annunziata the head of its business services operation.
</P>
<P>
   As AT&AMP;T has tried to shed its ponderous Ma Bell image, it has
occasionally held up Annunziata as the sort of versatile,
quick-thinking executive the company is trying to attract. Losing
him could reinforce the lingering perception among some
communications experts that AT&AMP;T is simply too big and stodgy to
hold on to some top executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a dynamic opportunity, and that's really the
reason,'' Annunziata, 50, said Wednesday during a conference call.
In an interview, he added, ``I'm an entrepreneur and I know how to
run my own company, and this is just a great opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to talks over the last few weeks with Gary Winnick and
Lodwrick M. Cook, Global Crossing's co-chairmen, and with John M.
Scanlon, whom he will replace as chief executive, Annunziata said:
``We hit it off as people who can move quickly. And we moved
quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Scanlon will become Global Crossing's vice chairman. Global
Crossing is based in Bermuda, but Annunziata said he would be at
the company's operational headquarters in Los Angeles on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Taking advantage of the exploding market for international
communications, Global Crossing has raised more than $4 billion to
build and operate undersea fiber optic networks. After initially
offering shares to the public in August at $19, the company's
shares closed Wednesday at $57.875, up $4.25, in Nasdaq trading.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T said that Michael Keith, 50, who has been with the company
for 21 years, would replace Annunziata. Keith will be the third
person to run AT&AMP;T's business unit in less than 18 months. AT&AMP;T's
shares closed at $84.5625, down $1.375, on the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the business services post, another top AT&AMP;T job
that has come to resemble a hot seat is the one at the top of the
company's international unit.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, two people, Pier Carlo Falotti and R.C. Mark Baker,
have left that job and the company after less than a year. Now,
seven months after announcing that it would fold most of its
international operations into a joint venture with British
Telecommunications PLC, AT&AMP;T has still not announced a leader for
the new unit.
</P>
<P>
   Such an announcement could come soon, however. Executives close
to the process said that among the people who had been or are being
considered for the job is David W. Dorman, the former chairman of
Pacific Bell. Dorman is now chairman of Pointcast Inc., an Internet
media company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
