<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-LAST </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUMAN SPIRIT PREVAILS OVER THE WORST EVIL IN `LAST DAYS'
</HEADLINE>
 DAYS-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Holocaust has provided material for many thoughtful films,
from the relentless documentary ``Shoah'' to the stately
``Schindler's List'' to the almost naively romantic ``Life is
Beautiful.' But, as a subject in the Oscar-nominated documentary
``The Last Days'' says, unfortunately, the Holocaust was even worse
than what you see in the movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Last Days'' is a brief attempt at showing how much worse.
Some may argue that it's too brief; by concentrating on the final
year of World War II and the experiences of five Hungarian Jews who
survived the Holocaust, director James Moll risks oversimplifying,
turning his movie into a sort of Holocaust Cliff's Notes. Yet the
brevity makes the movie more accessible, as does the structure of
present-day interviews interspersed with remarkable _ and graphic _
archival footage.
</P>
<P>
   The survivors, who have endured horrors most of us cannot even
imagine, are presented as tributes to the human spirit; they can
make your own self-indulgent angst look pretty silly. Among them
are Tom Lantos, who went on to become a California congressman _
and, not surprisingly, a human-rights advocate; Alice Lok Cahana,
an artist whose experiences are reflected in her work; and Renee
Firestone, who provided the movie's key sound bite, about her
refusal to let the Nazis take away her soul.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is wrenching because Moll doesn't try to make it
wrenching. He films with as objective an eye as possible, letting
the survivors tell their stories and even tracking down an
Auschwitz doctor who was acquitted at the Nuremberg trials because
he performed useless experiments that actually worked to help keep
Jews alive; as long as the people in his charge were scientific
subjects, they were spared execution. The doctor paints himself as
a person of conscience, but his evasiveness upon meeting Firestone
reveals another side of his character.
</P>
<P>
   Several survivors revisit death camps at Auschwitz, Dachau and
Bergen-Belsen, or their former Hungarian homes, often with their
children in tow. The memories move them to tears while Moll uses a
casual voyeurism to film the pastoral beauty of the Hungarian
countryside, the faded majesty of Budapest and the startling size
of the ghostly concentration camps. The immensity of the evil is
made clear when one of the survivors remarks on how the camps
didn't just exist; they had to be conceived and meticulously
planned. The camps were brutally efficient, from the crematoriums
and gas chambers right down to the latrines.
</P>
<P>
   But what emerges, more than a portrait of evil, is a celebration
of the survivors' vibrance. They have made their peace with what
happened, even while they are still unable to comprehend it. Many
survivors say that before they were routed to the camps, they never
expected the Holocaust to reach all the way to Hungary. Movies like
``The Last Days'' warn us that no one is immune from horrors but
also let us know that no one can take away our souls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Last Days'' is rated PG-13. It contains graphic footage of
Holocaust victims, including some nudity, but is more than
appropriate for thoughtful teens.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Last Days'' 4 stars on a scale of 1-5
</P>
<P>
   Director: James Moll
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Tom Lantos, Alice Lok Cahana
</P>
<P>
   Length: 88 min.
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
