<DOCNO> NYT19990224.0326 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8002 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-OTHERSISTER-TEX     02-24 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-OTHERSISTER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NICE TRUE-TO-LIFE LOVE STORY CAN'T SAVE WEAK `SISTER'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For about half of ``The Other Sister,'' I was trying to figure
out why I was guiltily enjoying it, despite these not-small
reservations: It's manipulative and condescending, it's a glorified
TV movie, it relies too much on cheap laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Answer: The love story, involving mentally challenged couple
Carla (Juliette Lewis) and Daniel (Giovanni Ribisi), is the least
tricked-up romance we've seen in ages. No messages in bottles, no
blasts from the past, no Pygmalion-style bets. Best of all, none of
that trio of devices we've seen way too often over the past couple
of years: fate, mistaken identities or fake boyfriends.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, this is a story about two people who meet each other
(fairly naturally), are attracted, discover enough common ground to
spend time together and enough differences to keep things
interesting and work with it from there. Along the way, they
experience joy, sadness, rage and much confusion, a lot like people
do in real life.
</P>
<P>
   Many folks would shudder at the prospect of spending more than
two hours with Juliette Lewis; she's one of those actresses, like
Jennifer Jason Leigh, who throws herself into her roles so hard
that her performances can become mannered. What she's doing here is
a stunt performance; it works not because of the exaggerated slur
in her voice or the contortions in her face, but because of the
things she does with her body. As Carla becomes more confident,
Lewis' posture changes and braces harder against the many obstacles
in her way. Ribisi, taking advantage of his ``Saving Private Ryan''
fame, isn't quite her match, but he does lend Daniel a lot of charm
with his shy stutter and nervous laugh.
</P>
<P>
   If the movie had stuck with the love story, it could have been a
small gem, but director Garry Marshall and his battery of
co-screenwriters want it to be some sort of grand statement. The
result is an uncomfortable mix of ``Rain Man, Hannah and Her
Sisters'' and ``Ordinary People.'' Diane Keaton, trying hard to
suppress her natural charm, is a lighter version of Mary Tyler
Moore's ``People'' character as Carla's overprotective mother. This
mom is the type of perfectionist social butterfly who can't
understand how she had one daughter with an IQ of 50, another who's
a lesbian and yet another who commits perhaps the biggest sin:
She's teaching second grade when she could be a college professor _
not to mention that she's getting ready to marry an ordinary guy.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall, whose career has been a real mixed bag (''Pretty
Woman'' and ``Exit to Eden,'' anyone?), can be a crass guy, and too
often he wants to have it both ways in ``The Other Sister.'' He
wants us to respect Carla and Daniel's independence, but he
includes scenes that make us laugh at their expense (Daniel's love
of ``The Graduate'' _ hey, another influence! _ leads to some
particularly awkward scenes). Marshall wants to condemn Keaton's
character for shunning her other daughter's lesbian lover,
Michelle, yet he and the writers barely make Michelle a character.
It's as if they were ashamed of her themselves. Marshall has been
making feature films for nearly 20 years, so you'd think by now he
would have grown past his TV roots, but he still stages comic
scenes as if he were waiting for a laugh track.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the love story keeps us watching, and the movie lifts itself
up whenever it has a scene featuring only Carla and Daniel. They
give the movie a sleeper appeal, because they're two people so new
and surprised by the game of love that they don't play it as a
game. When they want something, they say so; when they don't, they
say so. It's enough to make you wish we were all that smart.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Other Sister'' is rated PG-13 for strong language, frankly
sexual dialogue and situations, and alcohol abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Other Sister'' 2 1/2 stars on a scvale of 1-5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Garry Marshall
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Juliette Lewis, Giovanni Ribisi, Diane Keaton
</P>
<P>
   Length: 130 min.
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
