r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JONES-RELIGION-COLUMN     02-24 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JONES-RELIGION-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORDINARY MAN'S EXPERIENCES WITH GOD HAVE EXTRAORDINARY EFFECTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It no longer surprises people: God is immensely popular in U.S.
bookstores.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Miles' ``God: a Biography'' (Vintage Books) won the
Pulitzer Prize for biography for 1995. Two years later,
``Conversations With God _ An Uncommon Dialogue'' (Putnam), by
Neale Donald Walsch, became a bestseller. It is still a bestseller,
along with its two sequels.
</P>
<P>
   But even before those bestselling books out, the Rev. Henry
Blackaby was drawing attention with his ``Experiencing God,''
published by Broadman &AMP; Holman in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Why so much interest in the Almighty?
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes from God,'' Blackaby said. ``There is a huge
heart-cry on the part of the American people not to just know about
God, but to experience God.''
</P>
<P>
   Once an obscure Southern Baptist pastor from Canada _ believe it
or not, Southern Baptists exist that far north in our hemisphere _
Blackaby is almost a guru among evangelicals seeking a deeper
relationship with God.
</P>
<P>
   His fame started to spread in 1990 after he left an affluent
church in Downey, Calif., near Los Angeles, to pastor a church near
Saskatoon, Saskatchewan, which was down to 10 members.
</P>
<P>
   He began conducting workshops on ``Experiencing God,'' and the
Canadian church flourished. Blackaby put his ideas into a book four
years ago, and it has sold 2.5 million copies.
</P>
<P>
   Now he gets 4,000 to 5,000 requests to speak each year. People
from many denominations say his book changed their lives. Karla
Faye Tucker, a born-again Christian who was executed in Texas last
year for her role in a pick-ax murder, taught ``Experiencing God''
to her fellow prisoners on Death Row.
</P>
<P>
   Walsch's popular ``Conversations With God'' is very
nontraditional compared with Blackaby's book. Walsch says that God
spoke to him in the middle of the night and that he began writing
down notes on a yellow legal pad.
</P>
<P>
   Walsch concludes that there is no good and evil, no right or
wrong and that even Hitler went to heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Blackaby's books take a traditional Christian view. When God
invites people to have a relationship with him, they should be
awe-stricken and willing to radically adjust their lives to God's
teachings, revealed through the Bible and Jesus Christ, he writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Experiencing God'' teaches: God is love. His will is always
best. God is all-knowing; his directions are always right. God is
all-powerful; God can enable you to accomplish his will.
Experiencing God is a love relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Blackaby is the first to admit that his ideas aren't new, but he
says that finding God is not easy _ not even in church.
</P>
<P>
   Churches across America focus on entertainment and winning
converts, rather than helping people to experience an all-powerful,
holy and loving God, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Blackaby, an executive with the Southern Baptist North American
Mission Board in Atlanta, said his greatest challenge in trusting
God came when his youngest daughter, Carrie, was found to have
cancer when she was 16. He and his family still maintained their
faith in God's goodness.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daughter came to me and told me that she had had a good
life, and that she had been able to serve God, and that she was
ready to go,'' Blackaby said. ``I just wept.''
</P>
<P>
   Carrie's life was spared. Now in her late 20s, she holds a
master's of divinity from Southwestern Baptist Theological
Seminary. She and her husband, Wendell Webb, who is a student at
the Fort Worth seminary, have applied to become missionaries in
Eastern Europe or wherever God leads.
</P>
<P>
   Blackaby's five children graduated from the Fort Worth seminary.
The oldest, Gerald Richard Blackaby, is president of the Canadian
Southern Baptist Seminary near Calgary.
</P>
<P>
   TV camera crews followed Henry Blackaby to Canada and to Fort
Worth because the Southern Baptist broadcast division, based in
Fort Worth, is filming a three-hour special on his life that is
scheduled to air on various TV outlets this year.
</P>
<P>
   But Blackaby says his celebrity is unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   ``It surprises me because I see myself as a very ordinary
person,'' he said. ``I never sought to be recognized. I never
sought to speak. I've tried very hard to be faithful to the Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's not so ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDSD/
</P>
</TEXT>
