<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GHANA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON REAFFIRMS U.S. WILLINGNESS TO HELP AFRICA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton sought Wednesday to reassure
Africans that Americans will ``do the right thing'' for the
continent as the United States redefines its role in a world no
longer dominated by superpower confrontations.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, hosting Ghanaian President Jerry Rawlings, called on
Congress to pass the Africa trade bill that died last year and
announced his Cabinet would meet next month with ministers from 40
African nations to discuss economic development.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton accorded full ceremonial pomp to Rawlings, who received
an official state welcome on the South Lawn of the White House, a
lengthy meeting with the president and a state dinner in the
evening.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the occasion paled in comparison to the welcome Ghanaians
gave Clinton last March as more than 500,000 people filled Accra's
Independence Square on a 102-degree day to give the president one
of the largest crowds of his tenure.
</P>
<P>
   The stop in Accra kicked off Clinton's historic 12-day journey
to six nations and focused Americans' attention  &UR;  &LR; on positive
aspects of the continent where democratic nations seeking
international investments are becoming the norm.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not simply a continent with problems, it's a continent
with promise,'' Clinton said during a news conference with
Rawlings. Clinton said he and Rawlings spent half their time
discussing how to refocus the United States' attention onto Africa
and the investment opportunities that are producing 30 percent
returns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, after the president was, you know, pounding on me
to do better by Africa, I did say, `Reverend Rawlings, you're
preaching to the saved,''' the president joked.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton added a philosophical note, saying that the past
decade _ since the Cold War ended _ has been the first period in
U.S. history in which the United States engages with other nations
in a peacetime environment without its existence threatened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know when you see a child die of AIDS or you see a child
step on a mine in Angola, or you see an economic opportunity going
unfulfilled, or you think that we could help you to end a war more
quickly, I know it's frustrating,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But our friends in Africa have to understand what we have been
doing for the last 10 years is unique in more than 200 years of
history for us. I think we'll get it right and do the right thing;
but it requires a certain departure that I think most people who
don't know the history of our country have difficulty accepting,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Clinton said, the United States will provide $800
million in economic assistance to Africa and debt forgiveness will
amount to $500 million over two years. He also renewed his call for
Congress to enact his Africa trade bill, which would provide
special tariff concessions.
</P>
<P>
   Rawlings called Africa a ``continent in transition'' and noted
the annual return on U.S. investments in the continent vastly
surpassed investment returns in Europe, Asia and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is rather unfortunate that the stereotype image of Africa
as a continent full of conflict, lack of democracy, et cetera, et
cetera, continues to dominate the international media, and yet
there are many positive developments taking place on our
continent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that 21 African nations have growing gross domestic
product rates, democracy is taking root, and many nations are
trying to create a favorable climate for foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Africa could very well be the continent of the future,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   During the news conference, during which Rawlings seemed bemused
by the domestic questions thrown at Clinton, the presidents
discussed the need for peacekeeping forces in the Congo and Ghana's
proposal to extend dual citizenship to African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the United States would support ``whatever
necessary force'' was placed into war-torn Congo to stop the civil
war there. He said the United States would be willing to help with
logistical support, if needed.
</P>
<P>
   Rawlings said the dual citizenship would mean U.S. blacks would
not need a visa to enter Ghana and would have the same rights as
Ghanaians without surrendering their American citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   ``My continent is the mother of, what do you call it, not all
continents, but humanity and civilization as we've come to know it
today. Is there any reason why you should not have the right to
enjoy the citizenship of where you come from?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton attempted to interrupt him, Rawlings jokingly shot
back, ``No no, you're not going to explain this for me.'' But
Clinton did press ahead, noting that many Americans returned to the
Eastern European nations after the fall of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Ghana does this, it certainly won't hurt in trying to get
more Americans interested in Ghana, going to Ghana and contributing
to Ghana's future. I thought it was quite a clever idea, myself,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
