<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-290&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDICARE PANEL WILL TRY TO DEVISE NEW BENEFIT FOR PRESCRIPTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal advisory commission studying the future
of Medicare agreed Wednesday to work past its March 1 deadline so
members could try to devise a major new benefit covering
prescription drug costs.
</P>
<P>
   The drug benefit emerged as the linchpin of any agreement
between Republicans and Democrats on the panel.
</P>
<P>
   A top Medicare official told the panel Wednesday that its
proposals for far-reaching changes in Medicare would increase
premiums for most beneficiaries, even as they slowed the growth of
the program and saved money for the government.
</P>
<P>
   Under existing law, the monthly premium for beneficiaries in the
traditional fee-for-service Medicare program is already scheduled
to double, to $105 in 2009 from $45.50 today.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Foster, chief actuary of the Medicare program, told the
commission that its proposals would further increase premiums for
these beneficiaries, perhaps by 10 percent. But, he said, costs
would be lower for many people who join health maintenance
organizations and other private health plans.
</P>
<P>
   At least 10 of the 17 commission members support a proposal by
the chairman, Sen. John Breaux, D-La., to remodel Medicare in the
image of the Federal Employees Health Benefits Program, which
covers 9 million people. The government would offer a fixed amount
of money to each Medicare beneficiary, who would then enroll in a
private health plan or in the traditional Medicare program.
</P>
<P>
   Under the 1997 law that created the commission, it is supposed
to submit its final report to President Clinton and Congress by
Monday, March 1, but it needs at least 11 votes to endorse any
recommendation.
</P>
<P>
   As the commission finished work Wednesday night, Breaux said,
``We are close to agreement.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Breaux is desperately trying to win support for his proposal
from two of President Clinton's appointees to the commission, Prof.
Stuart Altman of Brandeis University and Laura D'Andrea Tyson,
former chief economic adviser to Clinton. As a condition of their
support, they insist on Medicare coverage of prescription drugs,
not only for people in HMOs, but also for people in the original
fee-for-service program.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Tyson said she was ``sympathetic'' to Breaux's proposal to
redesign Medicare. But she added, ``If we are going to discuss drug
benefits, we certainly need more time.''
</P>
<P>
   Foster, the Medicare actuary, said the commission's proposals
would reduce projected Medicare spending by 10 percent over the
next decade and by 11 percent from 2000 to 2030. Under Breaux's
proposal, beneficiaries would have to pay more if they chose more
expensive health plans, so, he says, they would have a strong
incentive to switch to lower-cost plans, and plans would compete
for business by offering lower prices, or premiums.
</P>
<P>
   But Foster said most of the savings would come from other
changes proposed by Breaux. These include an increase in the
eligibility age, to 67 from 65; higher premiums for affluent
beneficiaries, and a new 10 percent co-payment for the frail
elderly people who receive home health care visits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
