<HEADLINE>
A REAL NEIGHBORHOOD WELCOME FOR CLINTON
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   The folks in the Pacific Heights 'hood found their turf adorned
yesterday wed &LR;  with posted warnings: ``Neighborhood Alert!'' the
signs began. ``Sexual Predator Headed Our Way.'' The notices made
mention of the visitor's alleged ``method of operation'' (words
like ``groping'' and ``exposing'' were used) and noted _ citing the
Wall Street Journal and the Washington Post _ that ``subject is
accused rapist.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Predator will be guest of honor,'' said the signs, ``at a
$25,000 per person fund-raiser at the  &UR; Gordon &LR;  and  &UR; Ann Getty &LR; 
residence.'' The president's name was at the bottom of these
unsigned flyers, along with the disclaimer, in small print, ``But
he's so GOOD on women's issues.''
</P>
<P>
   It was foggy Wednesday, and not every neighbor was bopping
around outdoors. An assistant to the Gettys said they had no
comment because they were unaware of the signs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NO MORE BUTTS FOR BOND &LR;
</P>
<P>
   For the first time ever, James Bond, who smoked 60 hand-rolled
cigarettes a day when he was a literary character, will be
smoke-free. Bond, as played by  &UR; Pierce Brosnan &LR;  in the forthcoming
``The World Is Not Enough,'' will drive a BMW with a ``Please do
not smoke'' sign on the dashboard.
</P>
<P>
   The very first image of Bond in a movie showed him taking a
lighter to his cigarette when he said his name: ``Bond. James
Bond.'' Although Brosnan is a smoker, the actor is said to have
thought that smoking set a bad example for kids likely to see the
movie. In his last Bond movie, his hand was seen smoking, but not
his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it will be mentioned that James has given up
smoking,'' an insider told the Mirror. ``The ideas &LR;  is to let it be
known by having a sign on the dash ... and he might go and sit in
the no-smoking section of a restaurant.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Al &LR;  and  &UR; Tipper Gore &LR;  will become grandparents in late June,
when their eldest daughter,  &UR; Karenna Gore Schiff &LR; , 25, and her
husband,  &UR; Drew Schiff &LR; , 33, have their first child. The second lady
said in a statement that the Gores are ``thrilled.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Righting wrongs: Several readers have informed Personals that
hot cross buns traditionally are available all through Lent.
</P>
<P>
   And no, ``No Tipping'' did not refer to the  &LR; turning cows on
their sides, a dastardly deed that no proper Australian would do.
``No Tipping'' means, in a language vaguely related to ours, ``No
Dumping Rubbish.'' A ``tip'' in Australia is a garbage dump.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Y2K-K-K-KATY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Having learned that as many as 25 million visitors are
expected to celebrate the millennium in Rome, foreseeing the huge
number of people who will line up to pay something like $10 each to
see the Sistine Chapel ceiling, San Francisco artist and
entrepreneur  &UR; Winston Smith &LR;  wants to set up a half-price
concession allowing art lovers to see the roof, which he notes is
``higher even than Michelangelo's God.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Republicans and Democrats in Congress are fighting over the
2000 census. Democrats want to boost their rolls by using sampling
methods to raise inner-city counts; Republicans say the sampling
methods are unconstitutional and illegal.
</P>
<P>
   This week, gloating Democrats released a copy of a letter from
Rep.  &UR; Dan Miller &LR; , R-Fla., to  &UR; Carolyn B. Maloney &LR; , D-N.Y.: ``While
I want to work together,'' he wrote, ``I cannot risk a successful
2000 census.'' Careful readers will realize that that can be read
two ways.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Bud Johns &LR;  is intrigued by an Indiana University Press notice
of a ``Pre-End of the Millennium Book Sale,'' which includes a
disclaimer that might be handy for interminable arguments that have
already arisen: ``Questions on whether the year 2000 actually
begins a new millennium will be referred to our Staff
Chronologist.''
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The best thing about the future,'' said  &UR; Abraham Lincoln &LR; ,
in a quote forwarded by  &UR; Sir Real &LR; , ``is that it comes only one day
at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted a woman who could get me out of a Third World prison.
What I wanted was someone resourceful. But nobody knows what you
mean when you say, `I'm looking for a resourceful woman.' If I tell
somebody I am looking for a woman who can get me out of a Third
World prison, they start thinking Ross Perot.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Amazon.com founder Jeff Bezos telling Wired magazine how he
went about searching for a wife. Mary-Ellen Mort, the librarian who
harvested this item, says the most resourceful women are
librarians.
</P>
</TEXT>
