<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8072 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COUNSEL-LAW-HNS &LR;      02-24 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COUNSEL-LAW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE PANEL TOLD INDEPENDENT COUNSEL LAW UNFAIR 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The law that spawned investigations of sexual
misbehavior by President Clinton and of the Iran-Contra scandal
during the Reagan and Bush administrations should be scrapped, two
former government officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Former Attorney General Griffin Bell and former Senate
Republican leader Howard Baker told a Senate committee that the
independent counsel law is flawed, unfair and inefficient, and
urged Congress not to renew the statute before it expires June 30.
</P>
<P>
   Baker, who was instrumental in creation of the law after the
Watergate scandal, told senators that after appointment of 21
independent counsels, at a cost of $150 million over the past 20
years, ``the time has come to reverse directions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The act ought to expire. We ought to work from a clean slate.
We ought to cool off,'' the Tennessee Republican said, urging
lawmakers to revisit the issue when partisan tempers have calmed
after Kenneth Starr's investigation of the White House sex scandal
and Clinton's impeachment fight.
</P>
<P>
   Baker later told reporters that ``political tempers are still so
warm that you're likely to make a mistake if you try to do it right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell, the attorney general during the Carter administration,
called the law ``poor governmental policy'' and told the Senate
Government Affairs Committee there is no need for the independent
counsel law, even if radical changes are made in the existing
statute. Urging the law's demise, Bell told senators, ``I was
hoping today would be the beginning of the funeral.''
</P>
<P>
   Created in 1978 in the wake of the Watergate scandal that led to
President Nixon's resignation, the independent counsel law allows
the attorney general to seek appointment of prosecutors who are
free from political constraints to examine alleged criminal
wrongdoing by top administration officials.
</P>
<P>
   Republican and Democratic critics say that, instead of assuring
fair and independent inquiries, the law has set loose prosecutors
with unlimited power, no spending restraints and a mandate to
search until they find something wrong.
</P>
<P>
   If the law expires, the current independent counsels _ Starr and
four others who are investigating cabinet members and former
administration officials _ would not be affected, although some
Democrats want to cut off their appropriations and force their
inquiries to end within six months.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who earlier this month was acquitted in the nation's
second presidential impeachment trial, has been targeted by Starr
in a five-year, $40 million inquiry that began with the president's
former Arkansas business partners and expanded to include his
affair with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Clinton declined to be drawn into a discussion of
the independent counsel law. ``I have been, to put it mildly,
closely involved with the operation of the statute,'' Clinton said
at a press conference with Ghanaian President Jerry Rawlings. ``I
think the important thing is that everyone feel free to express
their opinion,'' Clinton said, referring to lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The statute is badly flawed from the standpoint of fairness
and efficiency,'' Bell told the Senate committee, which has
scheduled three more hearings into the law.
</P>
<P>
   Former independent counsel Lawrence Walsh, the chief prosecutor
of Reagan and Bush administration officials in the Iran-Contra
scandal, said Wednesday that Congress is ``not going to get rid of
independent counsels by getting rid of the act.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh, whose seven-year, $47 million investigation of
Iran-Contra drew heated Republican criticism, urges keeping the
independent counsel law but with some changes. He told CNN that
``with or without the statute, there's going to be somebody with
the power to conduct investigations of administration officials.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh, who is expected to testify before the Senate committee in
the coming weeks, said the investigations would be handled within
the Department of Justice, much as they have since the first
special prosecutor was appointed during the administration of
President Ulysses S. Grant in the 1870s.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving investigations to the Justice Department, or to a
professional prosecutor appointed by the attorney general, was
endorsed by Bell and former independent counsel Joseph DiGenova,
who spent three years investigating the Bush administration's
misuse of then-presidential candidate Bill Clinton's passport file.
</P>
<P>
   Committee chairman Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., expressed skepticism
about the panel's ``ability to tinker'' with the law sufficiently
to overcome strident, bipartisan opposition in the Senate,
including the leaders of both parties _ Sens. Trent Lott, R-Miss.,
and Tom Daschle, D-S.D.
</P>
<P>
   Among members of Thompson's committee, three Democrats said
Wednesday they want to scrap the law. Two of them _ Sens. Robert
Torricelli, D-N.J., and Dick Durbin, D-Ill. _ voted to revise and
re-enact the law in 1994. The third, Sen. Max Cleland, D-Ga., said
the nation is tired of independent counsel investigations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel much like the drunk on the Titanic _ I ordered ice, but
this is ridiculous,'' Cleland said. ``I feel like it's time to let
the independent counsel statute die the most ignominious death it
so richly deserves.''
</P>
<P>
   A bipartisan group of committee members, led by Sen. Joseph
Lieberman, D-Conn., favors overhauling the law instead of letting
it die. Others senators siding with Lieberman are Susan Collins,
R-Maine, Pete Domenici, R-N.M., Carl Levin, D-Mich., and Arlen
Specter, R-Pa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we just going to trust the executive branch to investigate
itself?'' asked Domenici, referring to the concern that a
prosecutor appointed by the attorney general _ who is appointed by
the president _ cannot truly be considered an independent
investigator when examining the president or members of his
administration.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
