<SLUG> BC-GLF-WORLDMATCH-NOTES25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Prestigious, but hardly next major
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARLSBAD, Calif. _ Before the first ball was struck Wednesday
morning at the La Costa Resort, the Andersen Consulting Match Play
possessed instant credibility. Rare for a new event, but why not?
The top 64 players in the world meeting head to head in
single-elimination with a $1 million reward available Sunday?
What's not to like? Even if it isn't a major, and in some players'
minds, never will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see that happening,'' Tiger Woods said. ``Golf is all
about traditionalists, and traditionalists don't ever want to see
another major added.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Masters, the British Open, the PGA and the U.S. Open have
got tremendous history behind them,'' Mark O'Meara said. ``These
World Championships are just another way to promote the game of
golf and to promote a lot of the best players getting together and
playing.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain. If the Match Play is not the one to
someday approach the significance of, say, The Players
Championship, it's probably not going to happen with any of the
World Golf Championships.
</P>
<P>
   TOO MANY NO-SHOWS
</P>
<P>
   Karrie Webb, defending champion at this week's Australian Ladies
Masters, is disappointed that most LPGA stars chose to skip the
event. ``If the LPGA is prepared to sanction an event, then it
would be nice to see some of the top players give more support, but
I understand it's a long way to come,'' Webb said.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament features five of the six former winners,
including England's Laura Davies. But among the missing are 1995
champion and world No. 1 Annika Sorenstam of Sweden and South
Korean star Se Ri Pak. Meg Mallon, Beth Daniel, Betsy King, Helen
Alfredsson and Liselotte Neumann did not make the trip.
</P>
<P>
   The only women ranked in the top 10 on the 1999 money list who
are playing are Webb, Kelly Robbins, Alison Nicholas and Kris
Tschetter.
</P>
<P>
   NOD FOR NORMAN
</P>
<P>
   Offering a gesture that four years ago would have seemed
impossible, PGA Tour commissioner Tim Finchem on Tuesday thanked
Greg Norman, whose own World Tour plans were steamrolled, ``for his
determination and suggestions in 1994.'' ... Mike ``Fluff'' Cowan
is not on Woods' bag for the second time in three weeks; no reason
has been stated, but Fluff has had back problems in the past. Bryon
Bell, Woods' college friend who was on the bag for his victory at
San Diego two weeks ago, will caddie again. Bell earned the
customary 10 percent, $48,600. Not bad for a guy going through
medical school. If Woods wins this week, the paycheck would be
$100,000. ``We've never lost a tournament together,'' Woods said.
``We're 4-0.'' David Duval's fondness for the BellSouth Classic was
demonstrated when he remained in the field but bypassed both Doral
and Bay Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
