<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERSHEY-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: NEW AD CAMPAIGN FOR HERSHEY'S COMING ON STRONG  
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Just as the willpower to stick to all those
calorie-cutting New Year's resolutions begins to wane, consumers
are facing a wave of new products from Hershey Foods &UR;  &LR; Corp. that
are being aggressively marketed with new commercials, print
advertisements and store promotions.
</P>
<P>
   So those who already find it hard to eat just one Reese's Peanut
Butter Cup will now have to deal with Reese's Bites, a miniature
version of the peanut candy that the company says is for ``mindless
munching.'' Translation: before you know it, you've eaten the whole
bag.
</P>
<P>
   And it gets worse. The company has also come out with ``bites''
of its Hershey's Milk Chocolate with Almonds, Cookies &AMP; Cream and
Almond Joy candy bars. And Hershey is making it hard to miss the
treats because it is aggressively promoting them on network
television in various time slots and in national magazines and
newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign, which was introduced this month, is created by DDB
Needham Worldwide in New York, part of Omnicom Group.
</P>
<P>
   Hershey, the nation's largest maker of chocolate candy, has also
been expanding its nonchocolate brands. It introduced Jolly Beans
under the Jolly Rancher brand in 1997 and last month branched out
into lollipops by putting Jolly Ranchers on a stick.
</P>
<P>
   Hard as it may be to believe, though, Hershey is not simply
trying to break dieters' resolve with all of these new munchies.
Rather, the maker of Hershey Kisses, Twizzlers and Milk Duds, is
trying to sweeten its profits and fatten its stock price.
</P>
<P>
   Hershey has disappointed investors lately with two quarters of
earnings shortfalls and a stock value that has declined by about 5
percent in the last year. One reason is that like its competitors
Hershey has been struggling with flat sales of chocolate products.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of chocolate candy last year were flat at $3.2 billion
while sales of nonchocolate candy increased 32 percent, to $265
million, according to Information Resources Inc., a research firm
in Chicago. The seasonal and assorted candy category increased 9
percent, to $2.51 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But in what it calls a key strategy, Hershey has been
diversifying its product mix in recent years. In addition to
maximizing best-selling brands through product extensions such as
the Hershey Bites, the company is also looking for opportunities in
areas in which it has not had a presence, such as lollipops.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent that some people think chocolate is a dirty word
but they still want some kind of sugar fix, it's a proper strategy
to get those people as well,'' said Edward Froilich, an analyst who
follows the company for the Pershing division of Donaldson, Lufkin
&AMP; Jenrette.
</P>
<P>
   That was the thinking behind the company's $330 million purchase
in 1996 of the North American confectionery business of Leaf Inc.,
a unit of Huhtamaki Oy &UR;  &LR; of Finland. The acquisition gave Hershey
the Jolly Rancher, Good &AMP; Plenty and the Pay Day candy bar brands,
which added, in some cases, low-fat products that have been driving
much of the growth in the candy business.
</P>
<P>
   ``New products bring a lot of excitement to the candy category,
and we have obvious areas where we are underdeveloped,'' said
Kathie Rhyne, director of new products at Hershey. ``This allows us
to pursue those and we will develop products that help us gain
sales from other categories as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning this month, Hershey is promoting the Jolly Rancher
lollipops through product sampling in schools and through
promotions with ads created by Ogilvy &AMP; Mather New York, part of
the Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Worldwide unit of WPP Group &UR;  &LR; PLC. And to
promote Pay Day candy bars, Hershey is using a mischievous elephant
in new commercials.
</P>
<P>
   In the spots created by DDB Needham, the elephant goes to great
lengths to secretly swipe the peanut and caramel candy, including
stuffing himself in a toll booth and demanding the bars as fare
from passing motorists. The commercials, as well as print ads, use
the tag line ``Can't get enough peanuts?''
</P>
<P>
   To create an awareness of Hershey Bites as candy that is based
on already popular treats, DDB Needham uses the product logos and
packing to introduce new treats while reminding customers that the
products come ``in four of your favorite flavors.'' The commercials
use computer-animated candy bags that come to life in whimsical
spots under the tag line ``For a big taste, have a little bite.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hershey Bites is a perfect example of creating a new brand
built on the equities of four popular brands already out in the
marketplace,'' said Peter Tate, president of DDB Needham New York.
</P>
<P>
   And with already strong brands to work with, said Charlie
Piccirillo, a group creative director at the agency, ``your job is
made much easier.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All we needed to do was keep it really simple and
entertaining,'' he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
