</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BIGMAC25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McGwire returns to strange new world of big expectations
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUPITER, Fla. _ Life, in some ways, has remained constant. He
joined all the other dads watching their sons playing youth-league
basketball this winter. He traveled, went on vacation. He
reconsidered his life. And when January expired, Mark McGwire felt
compelled, as he always has, to make an early showing at training
camp.
</P>
<P>
   Where, it turned out, precious little of his life was constant.
He dispelled a report that he had hired private bodyguards. New
parents came to him to say they'd named their children for him. And
not Mark _ kids named McGwire. A new teammate, Carlos Barega,
chirped that an 80-home run season is a possibility. McGwire had
kissed a pope over the winter. He's kissed Helen Hunt on network
TV. Everywhere he went, America seemed to need to confide in him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had so many people join me for dinner,'' McGwire
said. ``It was amazing. These people just walk up and sit down and
tell me their stories. Sometimes I'm too nice a guy. And I'd sit
there and listen to them.''
</P>
<P>
   More than four months ago, a first baseman from St. Louis
changed baseball and the world as he knew it by hitting 70 home
runs. On Wednesday, McGwire took opportunity of the Cardinals first
full-squad workout to survey whom he had become. Someone asked if
it would feel normal to be at a ballpark again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will become normal,'' he said, ``but my life has
changed forever. And for the better.''
</P>
<P>
   In a 70-minute exchange with some 100 media members, McGwire
resumed his spot at the game's center stage. He still worries about
baseball's future. He's still taking the muscle-building supplement
androstenedione. He still thinks he has five good seasons in him,
after which he will be 40. But most of what Wednesday proved is
that McGwire remains baseball's biggest story, even six weeks
before anyone actually plays a game.
</P>
<P>
   Looking out at a room filling with reporters, Cardinals general
manager Walt Jocketty said, ``This is more people than we used to
draw for spring-training games.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, McGwire stated that he is seeking no record this
season, which is what he has always said in the sspring. His goal,
as it has been for years, is to reach 50 homers. And while he will
continue to discuss what happened in 1998, Jocketty made no secret
that ``what we want to try to do is turn the page,'' to allow
McGwire to enter 1999. When the first question came about the
possibility of reaching 70 again, McGwire gave that piercing
red-eye look the nation saw after every game last September.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I did last year, ball players have been trying for 38
years,'' he said. ``I never thought about it. Anything is possible,
breaking any record. In order to hit 70 home runs, I would have to
think you'd have to be at the 40-plateau by the All-Star break. I
can only imagine the amount of pressue. I know what it entails to
reach 60, 61, 62. Try going 10 more. Seventy is a really big
number. I was in awe of myself. I think I'm still in awe of
thinking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of his surroundings have changed. Only he and center
fielder Ray Lankford are holdovers from the Opening Day lineup of
last April. Rookie J.D. Drew will hit ahead of McGwire this season,
yet the public expectations mount daily. The Cardinals are 430,000
tickets ahead _ at 2.2 million _ of last year's advance sale at
this time. All for a team that was a mere four games over .500 last
year and finished six games out of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line,'' manager Tony La Russa said, ``is we were
our best in the second half and in Sepember. We had the best
September (18-7) in Busch Stadium history. It's real clear to me
that having people follow our club and Mark is good for the rest of
the team. It's tough to have a flat day when you have that kind of
attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the afternoon was over, McGwire would discount his
chances to reach 700 home runs _ he stands at 437 _ and said the
only comtemporary player with a strong opportunity is Ken Griffey
Jr., with 350 at age 28. He defended his use of andro, claimed that
his 1998 season would need no asterisk if baseball banned it and
stipulated, ``I don't endorse the product.'' He also called the $3
million auction price for the 70th home run ball ``ridiculous,''
and could hardly believe that the legal squabble for ball No. 66
wound up televised on ``The Peoples' Court.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he had a sickening thought. After nearly two decades in
baseball, something was finally stolen from his locker last summer,
a protective cup he had used back through his minor-league career.
These have become strange times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gawd,'' he said, ``I hope that doesn't show up on the show.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
