<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8079 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-BAYLOR25-C     02-24 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-BAYLOR25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q&AMP;A with Atlanta Braves hitting instructor Don Baylor
 &HT;    By Carrol Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After six years as the manager of the Colorado
Rockies, Don Baylor has returned to the coaching ranks as the
Atlanta Braves hitting instructor. In the first of a series of
weekly question-and-answer sessions with key Braves personnel,
staff writer Carroll Rogers spoke with Baylor on his thoughts on
Braves hitters, his new job, and his outlook on the 1999 edition of
the Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How is spring training going so far for you?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's been a real good camp. It's a little different how
successful teams go about doing their job. I've been taking a lot
of notes. It's baseball _ no B.S. Everybody comes in, they get
their work, they get their throwing, get their groundballs. It's a
gradual work-your-way-into playing the games.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When you look at the Braves' hitters as a group, what do they
have to offer?
</P>
<P>
   A: Their work habits are outstanding. I have not found one guy
here yet that I say, ``Let's go to the cage,'' and they say, ``I
don't want to do this today.'' Not a one, and that's a rarity.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are some of your goals in your new job?
</P>
<P>
   A: Every day we go out there, we have a plan. Not just
freelancing the opposing pitcher. We're going to have enough
information on guys, what they throw in certain situations _ with
nobody on base, with the bases loaded _ and not throw away at-bats.
If you throw away 30 to 40 to 50 at-bats, that's the difference in
hitting .280 and .310, .290 and .300. I want every at-bat. To throw
away four at-bats, and say, `OK, I'll get him tomorrow.' No, I want
you to put in four quality at-bats. If we get some hits, fine. If
we don't, we'll come back tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What other area would you like to see improve?
</P>
<P>
   A: Last three years, the Braves have been over 1,000 strikeouts.
To me that's alarming. These guys are much better hitters than
that. But sometimes when you freelance, that's what's going to
happen. We're going to think about the off-field when we get two
strikes. That means we'll stay on the ball and not let our head
fly. I want us to be able to put the ball in play.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do you go about helping Ryan Klesko improve his hitting?
</P>
<P>
   A: I know Bobby (Cox) would love to have Klesko play against
left-handers. I told Ryan today: ``My goal is for you to play every
day. That means we have to take the left-hander and put the ball in
play. We can't strike out because if you do, you're going to be
over here sitting with me.'' So if we go 1 for 4 against a lefty,
we've had a pretty good day. But then if you got 2, you had a great
day. Then we'll get those right-handers later.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How much of a difference can a hitting coach make?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's like with (Andres) Galarraga. He got to a point (that),
if he didn't change something, he was going to be out of the game.
That was in 1992. He did. He won a batting title. The day they
presented him with the Silver Slugger he wanted me to go out with
him to accept it. I said `Hey, Cat, you did the work. It's all
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is it about you that makes you so successful at reviving
careers, like you've done with Galarraga and Vinny Castilla?
</P>
<P>
   A: You know what hitting is? It's about what every sport has _
try to be positive through working hard. These guys have tremendous
ability, because they're in the major leagues. It's that other
little mental part, the guy that sits up on your shoulder up here,
that little negative thing: ``I don't know. I'm not too good
today.'' A hitting coach or a pitching coach or a manager is trying
to get these guys focused and positive.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What will it take to get the Braves where they need to be?
</P>
<P>
   A: A lot of times when you have good pitching, as a position
player you say, ``We're going to win 2-1.'' Only if it's a No. 1
guy out there. But if it's a No. 3 or No. 4 or a No. 5 pitcher out
there, that's not acceptable. We want to pound those guys. Get the
hitters to think good about themselves and not rely on pitching all
the time.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can the Braves improve their offense in the postseason?
</P>
<P>
   A: In the playoffs, I watched these guys get beat. I watched
(Sterling) Hitchcock pitch against this team. It was one of those
twilight games, 5 o'clock, shadows. He threw one strike, one ball
in the dirt, one strike, one ball in the dirt. He got them out like
it was nothing. This was a team that won 106 games.
</P>
<P>
   I used to tell guys all the time in playoff situations, even in
the World Series, the game is still played the exact same way.
There are more people watching, a satellite here, a satellite
there, but the bases are still 90 feet (apart). They don't move the
mound in. Think, ``Slow the game down,'' so it's not racing through
your mind. You've got to say it's the same game you've played for
162 games. Don't put that pressure on your back. ``I'm the guy
who's got to do it'' _ then it gets away from you. Next thing you
know, you're sitting at home watching like I've been watching for
the last six years.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
