<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wohlers impresses teammates
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. _ The Mark Wohlers batting-practice
throwing session had two new features on Wednesday _ some big
Braves hitters in the batter's box and a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   With each passing day of spring training, the stakes rise for
the Braves closer trying to make a comeback from a disastrous 1998.
Wohlers took the next step Wednesday by throwing for the first time
since position players reported. Instead of facing pitchers and
catchers and minor-league hitters, Wohlers was staring down such
hitters as Chipper Jones and Bret Boone.
</P>
<P>
   Those two, as well as a group of about 100 fans who applauded
Wohlers on his way off the mound, liked what they saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had better control of everything,'' said Jones, who
reported that about half of the dozen Wohlers pitches he saw were
strikes. ``First time I've seen him this year. (He) had a couple
back-door sliders. The splitter had good action. The fastball was
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Boone agreed. ``(A) few balls in the dirt, but nasty,'' Boone
said. ``Really good curveball. Some fastballs that were close. He
had his velocity there, I'll tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers said afterward he's throwing the fastball at 90 percent.
``I'm getting close to the point now where you can really let it
loose,'' Wohlers said, and grinned. ``I'm about at the reckless
step.''
</P>
<P>
   And yes, the applause was well-received. ``It's been awhile
since it's been fun,'' Wohlers said. ``It's nice to go out and have
some positives happen.''
</P>
<P>
   BRAVES SIGNINGS
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Ligtenberg, who saved 30 games last year, agreed to terms
Wednesday on a one-year deal worth $250,000. He earned $175,000 in
'98 in his first full season in the majors. He came to the Braves
in 1997, after they found him in the Prairie League playing for the
Southern Minny Stars in Austin, Minn. ``I could be doing a lot
worse,'' Lightenberg said, smiling. ``I never got into this for the
money. That's not what it's about for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Four other Braves agreed to terms Wednesday: Bruce Chen to his
first major-league deal, worth $200,000 if he makes the 25-man
roster; rookie left-hander Odalis Perez; minor-league pitcher
Damian Moss; and minor-league outfielder George Lombard. That
leaves only Andruw Jones, Kevin Millwood and Randall Simon
unsigned.
</P>
<P>
   JORDAN BACK
</P>
<P>
   Right fielder Brian Jordan rejoined the Braves on Wednesday,
after spending Tuesday in Baltimore to visit his mother in the
hospital. Betty Jordan had found blood in her stool and doctors
haven't yet found the cause, Jordan said. Outfielder Gerald
Williams is still out of camp because of some personal business.
</P>
<P>
   DRIVING EXPERIENCE
</P>
<P>
   For the second year in a row, manager Bobby Cox took his turn
behind the wheel of a stock car by driving in Disney's Richard
Petty Driving Experience.
</P>
<P>
   Cox won the team lead-foot award on Tuesday, reaching the
highest speed of any Brave who participated at 125.6 mph. That was
a 5-mph improvement over last year.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Cox were pitchers John Rocker and Chen, shortstop Mark
DeRosa, outfielder George Lombard, third-base coach Ned Yost and
trainer Jeff Porter.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
