<SLUG> BC-CHINA-CRASH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
61 KILLED IN JET CRASH IN CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ All 61 people on board were killed Wednesday when a
Russian-made jet crashed on its descent to Wenzhou, a southern
coastal city, according to the New China News Agency.
</P>
<P>
   The 61 people were all Chinese citizens, the agency said.
Airport officials said there were also casualties on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The plane, a Tupolev-154 operated by China Southwest Airlines,
crashed in fields 25 miles south of Wenzhou at 4:29 p.m., said an
official in the manager's office at Wenzhou Airport who gave her
name as Ms. Lan. The plane was from Chengdu in Sichuan Province.
Ms. Lan said the weather was calm and visibility was good.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the crash was not immediately apparent. Although
initial reports described a midair explosion, airport officials
said they believed the plane had first crashed and then exploded.
The area around Wenzhou is extremely mountainous. Ms. Lan said the
aircraft had been descending over a flat plain.
</P>
<P>
   The crash will almost certainly raise questions about the safety
of Russian planes, which have been involved in a relatively high
proportion of Chinese air disasters even though they make up just a
tiny fraction of the commercial air fleet.
</P>
<P>
   China's commercial airlines have had a good safety record in
recent years, industry experts said. Most Chinese commercial planes
are made by Boeing and Airbus. Those Western planes are used
exclusively for international and major domestic routes.
</P>
<P>
   ``China is absolutely passionate about air safety, and that's
why you see aging aircraft _ and those are mostly Russian planes _
being hustled out of the fleet as fast as they can,'' said Thomas
Gallagher, managing director in charge of aerospace for CIBC
Oppenheimer, the investment bank in New York, who has worked
extensively in China.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gallagher called the Tupolev ``not a bad plane,'' though
he noted that it was ``probably more maintenance-intensive'' than
Western planes. Only 7 percent of commercial planes in China were
Tupolevs in 1995, a number that has almost certainly dropped
further, Gallagher said.
</P>
<P>
   The deputy director of the propaganda department for China
Southwest Airlines, who gave only his surname, Xu, refused to give
the age of the plane in the crash Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from China's civil aviation administration are
investigating, the news agency said. Earlier in the day, before the
crash, the newspaper China Daily reported that China planned to
spend $1.2 billion to modernize its air-traffic controls over the
next 10 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
