<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSING-YOSEMITE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REUNION GOES AWRY; WOMAN AND 2 TEENS ARE MISSING
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif. Ariz., Colo., Minn., Nev., Ore., Texas, Wash.)   (jw) 
 By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MODESTO, Calif. _ One thing Jens Sund can say about his wife,
Carole, is that she knows how to plan. When she created a detailed
itinerary for a trip to Yosemite National Park with the couple's
daughter, Juli, 15, and a family friend from Argentina, Silvina
Pelosso, 16, Sund said, he had no reason to believe Mrs. Sund's
plan would go awry.
</P>
<P>
   Over a week ago Tuesday, that plan called for Mrs. Sund and the
two teen-agers to return from Yosemite and rendezvous with Sund and
the couple's three younger children at the San Francisco airport.
Sund would fly in from the couple's home in Eureka, while Mrs. Sund
and the two girls were to drop off a rental car here in Modesto,
then fly to San Francisco. Everyone would then fly to Phoenix for a
trip to the Grand Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Sund and the girls did not show up in San Francisco,
and eight days later, they were still missing.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday morning, part of Mrs. Sund's wallet, holding her
credit cards but no cash, was found at a roadside here, more than
60 miles from El Portal, near the western edge of Yosemite, where
Mrs. Sund and the two girls had last stayed. The wallet appeared to
weaken one of the FBI's prevailing theories, that the women had a
car accident in a remote area of the park, and to strengthen
another, that they met with foul play.
</P>
<P>
   But FBI officials said they could not rule out the possibility
of an accident. Along with teams from the California Highway Patrol
and the National Park Service, the FBI intensified its search in
Yosemite, focusing on the Highway 120 pass. The mother and two
girls had been spotted near Highway 120, asking for directions to a
meadow in Tuolumne Grove in Yosemite, on Tuesday morning, Feb. 16.
Their rental car, a red 1999 Pontiac Grand Prix, was seen in the
Tuolumne Grove parking lot on Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   A Holiday Inn a half mile from where Mrs. Sund's wallet was
found has become a headquarters for friends, family members and
volunteers who have been papering gas stations with fliers.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Sund, 42, comes from a prominent Santa Rosa family, the
Carringtons, who have been in real estate development for more than
a century. She is a principal in Carrington Co., based in Eureka,
which owns shopping centers in California, Colorado, Minnesota,
Nevada, Oregon, Texas and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   FBI officials said they had no reason to believe that Mrs. Sund
and the girls had been kidnapped because there was no ransom note
or any other evidence of an abduction.
</P>
<P>
   Sund, 43, a Carrington vice president, has offered a $250,000
reward for the safe return of the three.
</P>
<P>
   Sund said he last spoke to his wife on Monday, Feb. 15, when she
telephoned from the motel where the three were staying in El
Portal. Mrs. Sund and the girls were supposed to have met friends
at the University of the Pacific in Stockton on Tuesday afternoon
for a campus tour, then make the short drive to Modesto to fly to
San Francisco. When Sund's plane to San Francisco was late and his
wife was not there to meet him, he caught the last flight to
Phoenix. He said he took the flight because he figured that his
wife had already flown to Phoenix or had made other arrangements
when his plane did not show up.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is very organized and resourceful,'' Sund said. ``My wife
has joked with me that if something should ever happen to her, I'd
be in big trouble, because she arranges everything. ''
</P>
<P>
   Sund said he was so sure that she made plans to meet him in
Phoenix, that he did not report her missing until after noon on
Wednesday, Feb. 17, after playing a round of golf.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
