<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON MUM ON LATEST ASSAULT ALLEGATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as Clinton-Questions)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, still struggling to break free
from the aura of scandal, refused to comment Wednesday on an
Arkansas woman's allegations that he sexually assaulted her when he
was state attorney general in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Questioned for the first time since Juanita Broddrick went
public with her story, Clinton said he had ``nothing to add'' to a
statement last week from his personal attorney, David E. Kendall.
The lawyer had called Broddrick's allegations ``absolutely false.''
</P>
<P>
   With his presidency still reeling from a yearlong sex scandal
and his impeachment, Clinton was forced to field questions at a
joint news conference with Ghanian President Jerry Rawlings about
some of the fallout, including the inability of some Republicans to
trust him and whether he thought the independent counsel law should
be renewed.
</P>
<P>
   But he also spent much of the time dealing with such
foreign-policy questions as US relations with Africa, including
Ghana's offer of dual citizenship for African-Americans, possible
US military action in Kosovo, and the continuing conflict with
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   In one of several surprising moments during the news conference,
which was far livelier and less formal than others Clinton has held
with foreign leaders, an African journalist said that based on the
questions from US reporters, Africa obviously does not play a major
role in the mindset of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told the journalist not to take it personally. ``It's
really my fault, because I don't let them ask me enough questions
on other occasions, so I'm forcing them to use this opportunity to
pepper me,'' Clinton said. ``I apologize.''
</P>
<P>
   Rawlings said he had been briefed on the possiblity that most of
the questions would relate to ``American domestic situations and
not the fact that I'm here from Africa,'' a point that made Clinton
stiffen, suggesting he would have preferred Rawlings had kept that
to himself.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton acknowledged that ``nerves are still raw'' in the
aftermath of the impeachment process, which he said may account for
GOP congressional leaders' reluctance to say they trust him enough
to do business with him.
</P>
<P>
   After filing out of a White House meeting with Clinton Tuesday,
both Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, who had said just after the
impeachment trial that Clinton could not be trusted, and House
Speaker Dennis Hastert refused to directly answer when asked
whether they trusted him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any answer they give makes it more difficult for them,
potentially at least, within their caucus or within the country,
depending on what answer they give,'' Clinton said Wednesday.
``Their feelings are not important here, just like my feelings are
not important.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that last year he was able to work with the GOP
majority to pass a balanced budget and legislation to begin hiring
100,000 new teachers. ``It would be hard to imagine a year that was
more strained than last year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we focus on the American people and doing our duty, and not
on whether we're mad or happy, disappointed or elated about the
events of the last year, then all this in the course of time will
work itself out, and the American system will be validated,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   On renewing the independent counsel law, which expires this
summer, Clinton refused to say where he stood before White House
attorneys testify next week before Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have some ideas about it. But I think it would be better for
me at this time to say less so that others can say more,'' he said.
The president added that he didn't want his opinions about the law
to ``in effect, cast a shadow or illuminate what others might wish
to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the emphasis on impeachment and scandal, foreign policy
dominated Clinton's second meeting with reporters since he was
acquitted in the Senate impeachment trial 12 days ago.
</P>
<P>
   The president defended his decision to agree to extend the
deadline in the Kosovo peace talks, saying it was the ``right thing
to do'' if that was the wish of the parties involved. He also
justified his decision to consider sending up to 4,000 US troops as
part of a NATO peace-keeping force.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does the United States have an immediate, selfish interest in
what happens on some lonely road in Kosovo to some poor farm family
driving a wagon with horses that are underfed because they haven't
been able to get food? No,'' he said. ``But the United States does
have a direct interest in whether there is instability in the
Balkans.''
</P>
<P>
   On Iraq, Clinton said he hoped the United Nations weapons
inspectors could ultimately resume their work, despite frequent
sqirmishes between the Iraqis and US and British forces in the
no-fly zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying obviously for the symbolic victory of shooting
one of these planes down and perhaps trying to intimidate us from
enforcing the no-fly zone, which we're still bound to do,'' Clinton
said. Saying the attacks were ``little encounters,'' he said he
wished Iraq would stop provoking them.
</P>
<P>
   He also seemed to endorse the idea of a bill the Ghanian
parliament is expected to pass that would grant black Americans
dual citizenship in Ghana, eliminating the need to apply for visas
and giving them freedom of movement.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton joked ``I don't qualify.'' But, he said he ``thought it
was quite a clever idea.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
