<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-DONNAN25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia football coach offered $500,000 `longevity incentive'
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Spring practice is weeks away at Georgia, but the
football program is generating news away from the field.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jim Donnan has been approved for an $100,000-a-year salary
increase _ but he only gets the money if he stays at Georgia for
five more seasons. If he is still the Bulldogs' coach in December
2003, he'll receive a lump-sum payment of $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ticket prices will be raised to $27 for all games. Last
season, tickets were $22 or $25, depending on the opponent, and the
increase is expected to generate more than $2 million a year in
additional revenue.
</P>
<P>
   _ Georgia will expand the SkySuites at Sanford Stadium, which
could generate another $1.14 million annually. Twenty-two skyboxes
will be added to the existing 30 boxes and will be available for
occupancy in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The moves were approved by the university's athletic board
meeting Tuesday. Donnan, who received a $295,000 raise in January,
1998, has five years remaining on a contract that currently pays
him $650,000 annually.
</P>
<P>
   The university will invest $100,000 a year for five years on
Donnan's behalf through the UGA Foundation and the coach can
collect the money, with interest, if he is still coaching Georgia
in 2003. Should Donnan leave, he would have to pay $300,000, the
amount of the buyout clause in his contract, and the invested money
would be returned to the athletic association.
</P>
<P>
   With the annuity figures included in his salary, Donnan ranks
among the top one-third of coaches in the SEC in compensation.
Florida's Steve Spurrier is the league's highest-paid coach at $2
million per year while Tennessee's Phillip Fulmer earns $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was to let Coach Donnan know that we like what he is
doing and we want him to be our coach for a long time,'' Georgia
athletics director Vince Dooley said Wednesday. ``It's a longevity
incentive.''
</P>
<P>
   Dooley added that he plans to recommend an ``increase in
base-salary compensation'' for Donnan at the board's annual spring
meeting in St. Simons. Donnan, who has led Georgia to 19 victories
the past two seasons, turned down an $850,000 annual salary and a
$1 million annuity package from North Carolina in 1997 to remain at
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I appreciate the university supporting our program and me and
I intend on being here for a long time,'' Donnan said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
