<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tiger takes win in first round of championship
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARLSBAD, Calif. _ His frustration became typified at LaCosta's
par-3 14th Wednesday. Heading into his downswing, a cell phone went
off at the tee box. Nick Faldo flinched and yanked his tee shot
into a eucalyptus tree, the ball falling about 80 yards from its
starting place.
</P>
<P>
   Finally at the green, standing over a 2-footer for bogey that
somehow halved the hole and temporarily delay his first-round loss
to Tiger Woods, Faldo became irritated by an ABC-TV cameraman who
approached from behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry, am I in your way?'' Faldo asked sarcastically.
</P>
<P>
   Faldo (No. 64), of course, is no longer in the way of Woods (No.
1) in the Andersen Consulting Match Play Championship. On a day of
great first-round upsets in the $5 million tournament _ Ernie Els,
Davis Love III, Mark O'Meara, Colin Montgomerie and Lee Westwood _
the sure thing held up. Playing decently but not spectacularly,
Woods won 4 and 3 over the guy who won the Masters 12 months before
he did in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Had Faldo not scrambled for a few key up-and-downs early, the
match might have been over in proximity for Woods to grab a
clubhouse cheeseburger. He was 3-up at the turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, comfortable,'' said Tiger's mom, Kultida, at the 14th
hole, ``but you never know in match play.''
</P>
<P>
   Mom already wanted to know what David Duval was doing, hoping
for an eventual final against her son (he won 2 and 1 over
Australia's Stephen Leaney). Later, Tiger would offer respectful
comments for Faldo, who hits too many loose shots and unstable
putts these days to really scare anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit a lot of good shots at crucial times in the match,''
Woods said. ``I was just able to hang in there and beat a great
champion.''
</P>
<P>
   After firing his approach to a foot at the 10th hole _ inside of
Faldo _ Woods moved in for the kill with birdies at the 12th and
13th. It ended at the 15th after Faldo bunkered his approach, came
out short, then rammed a desperation chip by the hole. With Woods
facing an easy two-putt for par, Faldo conceded.
</P>
<P>
   Woods faces Bob Tway, who beat Tom Watson 6 and 4, in today's
second round. Woods said he felt ``relieved ... It's always good to
get one match under your belt and get fired up about the next
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Wearing his game face firmly at the start, Woods immediately
jumped on Faldo with a 310-yard drive rocketed into the turquoise
sky on a perfect Southern California day. When Faldo pushed his
drive into the right fairway bunker, the mood had been established.
</P>
<P>
   From the gallery a cruel fellow said loudly, ``Ask for strokes,
Nick.''
</P>
<P>
   AT A GLANCE
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's highlights
</P>
<P>
   _ Tiger Woods def. Nick Faldo, 4 and 3.
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Pate def. Davis Love III, 1-up.
</P>
<P>
   _ Paul Azinger def. Ernie Els, 1-up.
</P>
<P>
   _ Michael Bradley def. Mark O'Meara, 4 and 2.
</P>
<P>
   Today's top matches
</P>
<P>
   _ Phil Mickelson (12) vs. Lee Janzen (21).
</P>
<P>
   _ Fred Couples (13) vs. Scott Hoch (20).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
