<SLUG> BC-OLY-PAYNE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Group pays $975,000 for Atlanta Olympic chief's memorabilia
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta Olympic chief Billy Payne was paid $975,000
for his personal collection of Olympic memorabilia by the nonprofit
sports foundation that succeeded the Atlanta Committee for the
Olympic Games and which he co-chairs.
</P>
<P>
   Payne's collection includes a commemorative torch he carried in
Greece, the first Centennial Olympic Park brick and correspondence
with heads of state.
</P>
<P>
   Payne received the payment two years ago from the Georgia
Amateur Athletics Foundation, an organization he founded in 1987 to
bid for the Olympic Games and which remains in existence to carry
on the Olympic legacy.
</P>
<P>
   The money from GAAF, in part, paid off Payne's personal debt
accumulated during the years he volunteered for the Atlanta bid
effort. GAAF held that $606,000 loan on its books, and Payne paid
it off with the cash he got for his collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to give me the money to satisfy my personal loan,
but I wouldn't accept the money without giving something back,''
Payne said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   GAAF President Ralph Jernigan Jr. said Wednesday that the
foundation, whose board of directors is the original volunteer bid
team assembled by Payne, offered several times to pay off Payne's
personal loan with revenue left over from the roughly $12 million
in private funds raised during the 1987-90 bid effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy had run up a substantial debt during that period of
time,'' said Jernigan, a sports marketing consultant who has headed
GAAF since its inception. ``After the announcement in Tokyo (when
Atlanta won the right to host the 1996 Games), we tried to
reimburse Billy for his expenses, roughly $750,000. I had a check
cut, but he wouldn't take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Payne paid back part of the loan in 1993. GAAF then assumed the
debt from the original lender, who has been identified only as a
friend of Payne's.
</P>
<P>
   After three years working with no salary, Payne was paid
handsomely as chief executive of ACOG. His salary when the
organization was incorporated in 1991 was $519,000. In 1996,
Payne's last full year at ACOG's helm, he was paid $767,000,
according to federal tax returns. That amount was one of the
highest salaries in the country for a chief executive of a
nonprofit organization.
</P>
<P>
   The details of Payne's financial dealings with GAAF emerged as
Atlanta's Olympic effort is being scrutinized amid an Olympic
influence-peddling scandal of global proportions.
</P>
<P>
   The financial records of GAAF and ACOG indicate the interlocking
relationship between the two organizations, both founded and led by
Payne and several close friends. Payne co-chairs GAAF with former
Mayor Andrew Young. A former top executive at ACOG, Linda
Stephenson, is part-time executive director of the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ACOG will officially dissolve this summer, but GAAF will remain
to plan for an Atlanta Olympic museum, fund youth sports and help
coordinate an Atlanta Community Olympic Development Program.
</P>
<P>
   In spring of 1996, ACOG's board of directors turned over
responsibility for mountains of historic memorabilia and documents
to GAAF. Payne's personal collection was not included, according to
Jernigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was stuff he mainly kept in his house,'' Jernigan said.
``Billy was very careful after we won the bid to be sure his
personal gifts were kept separate from gifts for the
organization.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, the foundation was to make the materials
not kept by Payne available to the public and would explore a
long-term plan for the collection's permanent home. To that end,
GAAF entered into a five-year agreement with the History Center in
1997 to archive the materials and to host exhibitions and Olympic
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Payne's private collection was valued by an independent
appraiser and is carried on GAAF's books as an asset worth $1.503
million, according to Jernigan. The $528,000 in value above what
was paid to Payne is identified on GAAF's books as a contribution
to the foundation, which would allow Payne a tax write-off.
</P>
<P>
   No other ACOG executives were paid for their papers, photos and
mementoes, but they concur that Payne's compensation was fair.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an absolutely right thing to do,'' said A.D. Frazier
Jr., ACOG's chief operating officer. ``Billy sat on that debt for
years. He was sitting there with it at the end of the Games. This
isn't bonuses. It is about repaying loans. This was a proper way of
getting it done, at a fair value and something Billy would accept.
He was giving something of considerable value for what he was
getting in return.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
