<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-WELFARE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT DETAILS FATE OF FAMILIES FORCED OFF WELFARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DORIS SUE WONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In its first look at how families are faring who have
been forced off the welfare rolls in the last three months, the
state said Wednesday that most are working, at jobs that pay an
average of $200 a month more than what they got from welfare.
</P>
<P>
   Those who are not working, the report says, are generally either
receiving child support, have shifted to federal disability
assistance programs or have moved in with other people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time limits,'' said Transitional Assistance Commissioner
Claire McIntire, ``have obviously had a positive influence in
encouraging welfare recipients to enter the workforce and begin the
road toward self-sufficiency for themselves and their children.''
</P>
<P>
   Advocates for the poor said the study shows that the jobs these
women are finding are insufficient to lift their families out of
poverty.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Transitional Assistance studied 444 of the
1,500 families who have been cut from the rolls over the last three
months under new welfare rules that limit benefits to two years.
</P>
<P>
   The study did not address another 3,600 families who have
reached the time limit but have applied for extensions. Their cases
are still being decided.
</P>
<P>
   The report found that 75 percent of the 444 former recipients
are working. Most of those working had already held low-paying jobs
while on welfare; 28 percent did not get jobs until their welfare
benefits ran out.
</P>
<P>
   The working parents are earning on average $772 a month, more
than the $565 monthly welfare grant that a family of three
receives. Childcare is free to families in their first year off
welfare.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Harris, an attorney specializing in welfare issues at
the Massachusetts Law Reform Institute, believes the study's
findings are nothing to be proud of.
</P>
<P>
   The parents' average earnings will amount to less than $9300 a
year, which, Harris noted, will be far below the federal poverty
level of $13,650 for a family of three.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the 1996 law overhauling the welfare system
originally sought to create an incentive for parents to work by
allowing them to receive partial welfare grants to supplement low
wages. For example, a single parent with two children earning $772
a month would still be eligible for a supplemental welfare grant of
$239.
</P>
<P>
   DTA, however, decided the supplemental grants should not be
available to anyone who reached the two-year limit on benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``As usual,'' Harris said, ``the administration is trumpeting
success without bothering to look at the real facts. The fact is
desperately poor families are losing the partial grants that allows
them to survive on low wages. They were poor before and they are
poor now.''
</P>
<P>
   The DTA gathered its information on 444 randomly selected
families through telephone surveys, home visits and review of the
department's case files.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 25 percent of the group who are not working, seven
percent are receiving child support, five percent are receiving
cash assistance through other government programs such as Social
Security Disability Insurance and Supplemental Security Income and
six percent have moved in with someone else. Another seven percent
may have left the state, or no longer have children to support.
</P>
<P>
   The study is the latest in a series of statistical snapshots
that DTA has taken of families who have left the rolls since the
1996 welfare reform law went into effect. Earlier tracking studies
of families who left welfare on their own found that about half
found jobs that paid more than welfare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welfare reform is a work in progress,'' said DTA spokesman
Dick Powers. ``We continuously ahve to fine tune it and we can only
do that with accurate data.''
</P>
<P>
   The next study will focus on families who applied for extensions
of their benefits, but were denied.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
