<SLUG> BC-MFS-MANAGERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO MFS MANAGERS LEAVE TO LAUNCH HEDGE FUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Chris Felipe and John Brennan, high-profile managers at
one of the hottest mutual fund companies, have resigned from MFS
Investment Management to launch their own private investment fund.
</P>
<P>
   Felipe, 40, managed the $6.3 billion Massachusetts Investors
Growth fund, which earned 40 percent last year and 48 percent in
1997. He also runs the $1 billion MFS Strategic Growth fund, ranked
as the second-best performing growth fund over the last three years
by Lipper Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Brennan, 39, managed the highly rated $2.2 billion MFS Capital
Opportunities fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is a very big deal,'' said Burton Greenwald, a
Philadelphia-based consultant who advises mutual fund companies.
``MFS has picked up extraordinary momentum. That's a reflection of
marketing and outstanding performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Felipe's funds invested in large growth stocks with a heavy
emphasis on leading technology issues like Microsoft Corp. and
Intel Corp. Brennan's fund tended to invest in a mix of stocks that
crossed investment categories.
</P>
<P>
   ``MFS was fantastic,'' Felipe said in an interview Wednesday.
``From my vantage point, I had accomplished what I wanted to
accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   He and Brennan will form a ``hedge'' fund, a private investment
vehicle that caters to the wealthy and is not restricted by the
same rules that govern mutual funds. Hedge fund managers have more
freedom to invest in different investments and also to short
stocks, betting they will decline in price. Best of all: They are
rewarded with big payoffs in good years. Hedge fund managers
typically keep about 20 percent of fund profits, on top of a basic
annual fee.
</P>
<P>
   Felipe and Brennan said they were interested in managing a hedge
fund's investments and believed overvalued stocks would become an
opportunity instead of a headache.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of overvaluation in different pockets of the
market,'' Brennan said Wednesday. ``I don't think the next 10 to 15
years will be as smooth a ride as we've had in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   MFS has selected Stephen Pesek to manage Massachusetts Investors
Growth. Pesek has managed institutional portfolios at MFS and has
been running a similar large-stock growth fund. Pesek and Irfan
Ali, a software analyst, will team up to run MFS Strategic Growth.
</P>
<P>
   Maura Shaughnessy, manager of the MFS Utilities fund, was chosen
as Brennan's successor at MFS Capital Opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, they were very good investors,'' MFS's chief executive,
Jeffrey Shames, said of Felipe and Brennan. ``We think we're
replacing them with very good investors who obviously aren't as
well known.''
</P>
<P>
   Felipe and Brennan each joined MFS straight out of business
school in the 1980s and rose from stock analysts to fund managers.
High-profile departures are rare at MFS, a subsidiary of Sun Life
Assurance Co. that has relatively low management turnover.
</P>
<P>
   Shames said the firm discussed ways to keep the pair, including
an arrangement so they could grow a hedge fund business at MFS, but
decided not to pursue them. ``We just felt it wasn't in the best
interest of the team approach at MFS,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hot performance helped MFS attract net sales of $11.1 billion
last year, according to Financial Research Corp., a Boston firm.
That inflow was just behind the performance at local competitors
Putnam Investments and Fidelity Investments, which are much bigger
companies. Sales in 1998 increased the firm's assets by 25 percent,
triple Putnam's rate and about five times Fidelity's.
</P>
<P>
   Felipe's Massachusetts Investors Growth accounted for $2.3
billion of MFS's sales last year. His other fund and Brennan's
Capital Opportunities added about $900 million.
</P>
<P>
   Shames said early MFS sales figures for 1999 are substantially
ahead of last year. He doubted management changes alone would have
any impact on the individual funds' popularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're under scrutiny for the next three to nine months,''
Shames said. ``If there are dramatic slippages, you'll see sales
slow down. But as long as we deliver good performance, we don't
even think we'll notice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
