<HEADLINE>
SHAYS-MEEHAN BILL TO BE REINTRODUCED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It helped make Representative Martin T. Meehan a
darling of the public. It forced politicians to address the
trickiest of topics, and made ``campaign finance reform'' a
household phrase.
</P>
<P>
   But some three years after being unveiled in its original form,
Shays-Meehan, the legislation that would revolutionize the way
campaign contributions are made, remains in limbo. It still needs
to pass both houses of Congress. It still has a core of powerful
detractors.
</P>
<P>
   And on the eve of a press conference _ being held Thursday by
co-authors Meehan, a Massachusetts Democrat, and Representative
Chris Shays, Republican of Connecticut _ to announce that the bill
will be introduced again, Speaker Dennis Hastert Wednesday
indicated that Republican leaders are still ready to stall it, as
they tried to do last year.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert, who controls which legislation is voted on, said he had
``talked to Shays, and we intend to see it on the agenda either
later this year or early next year.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added noncomittally: ``We have not set a date.''
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Dick Armey said Republicans are ``so
focused on implementing the agenda, getting the budget moved
early'' that they have yet to address campaign finance legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't give any prediction about when that will occur,''
Armey said Wednesday. ``We've talked about it. That's all.''
</P>
<P>
   The urgency to pass the legislation has increased since last
year, its supporters said. Meehan insists that, in order for the
law to have an impact on the 2000 presidential race, it must be
implemented before next January, and hopefully within the next six
months _ well before Hastert intends to put it on the calendar.
</P>
<P>
   The bill's greatest impact would be felt on so-called ``soft
money,'' banning the contributions to political parties that are
subsequently turned over to candidates. It would also place curbs
on the way special interest groups raise money for political
campaigns, and would create a roadmap for future reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's long overdue, and we should pass it early on in the
session...We don't need a campaign finance reform bill passed too
late for 2000,'' Meehan said. ``Both parties continue to raise
unprecedented amounts of soft money. The special interest groups
are already planning campaign advertisements that masquerade as
issue ads...Unfortunately, the Republican leadership is unwilling
to make this a priority.''
</P>
<P>
   Meredith McGeehee, legislative director for Common Cause, a
public-interest organization that backs the bill, said there are
``three issues on the table _ timing, timing, timing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody acknowledges up on the Hill that there is a
majority, certainly in the House, and that, brought up under a fair
procedure, it will pass,'' McGeehee said. ``The question is, of
course, what will the Speaker do? Will he repeat his predecessor's
efforts to bury the bill and delay? Or will he let it come up
earlier? That's the $64,000 question.''
</P>
<P>
   Meehan is prepared to circumvent Hastert, as he and Shays
circumvented former Speaker Newt Gingrich last time around, using a
parliamentary measure to force the House to a vote. The bill passed
in the House, 252-179, last August, with 61 Republican votes. It
was then blocked in the Senate, where Majority Leader Trent Lott
strongly opposed it. Although 52 senators were in favor of the law,
there were not the 60 Senate votes needed to bring it to the floor
for a final vote.
</P>
<P>
   This year, there are signs the bill may move through the House
more swiftly than before, Meehan said. Some 110 members are
co-sponsoring the bill _ including 27 Republicans, among them
Representative Charles Bass of New Hampshire, who said he was
looking ``forward to participating in the fight for reform.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Although it doesn't include every provision I support, it is a
step in the right direction and has the best chance of being signed
into law,'' Bass said earlier this year. At least three pieces of
legislation involving campaign finance issues are expected to be
introduced in the House this year.
</P>
<P>
   According to a spokesman for another House Republican, however,
``for anyone to say it's going to sail through is incorrect.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'll see a process similar to last year,'' said Mike
Scanlon, spokesman for Majority Whip Tom Delay. ``It's going to be
an interesting navigation course that Mr. Shays and Mr. Meehan have
to go through.''
</P>
<P>
   Shays and Meehan are gearing up, collecting support from both
sides of the aisle and preparing a discharge petition _ the piece
of paper they will need to file if they decide to bypass Hastert.
Wednesday, Meehan also met with Senator Russell Feingold, Democrat
of Wisconsin, who joined Senator John McCain, a Republican from
Arizona, in authoring the Senate bill.
</P>
<P>
   But Hastert was preparing, too _ not for campaign finance but
for a host of other debates on agenda items, especially tax cuts
and Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Shays, who has spoken with Hastert several times, said he has a
commitment the bill will eventually reach the floor. ``He's told me
that we will be voting on it this year, but the end of this year
would be too late,'' Shays said.
</P>
<P>
   Meehan agreed. But according to John Feehery, a spokesman for
Hastert, the congressmen will simply have to wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might not happen when Mr. Meehan wants it to happen,''
Feehery said, ``but there will be a vote on it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
