<HEADLINE>
PIVOTAL MEETING UNCOVERED UNCLAIMED CHECK FUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHEN KURKJIAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ While former Massachusetts Treasurer Joseph D. Malone
defended Monday his management of the state's Treasury and Lottery,
it took the persistence of the head of a Boston heir finder's
company to provide guidelines on how the multimillion-dollar Unpaid
Check Fund was to operate.
</P>
<P>
   Complaints by Kim S. Sawyer, president and general counsel of
Locator Services Group, about the fund's operation led to a pivotal
meeting with top Malone officials where, according to one, the fund
``came on our radar screen for the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   Until then, it had operated in the shadow the state's Abandoned
Property Fund, which was trumpeted annually in newspaper ads and
internet sites as Malone's way of returning millions of dollars
every year to those who had forgotten about bank accounts or stock
certificates that had long lay fallow in financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Sawyer was one of about dozen individuals and firms who had
operated as heir finders, locating money that individuals or firms
had been owed by an agency of state government and was part of the
state's Unpaid Check Fund. But there were no rules or regulations
to determine when Malone's office -- or John Trischitta, the Unpaid
Check Fund's sole manager -- should approve an application for
payment by an heir finder.
</P>
<P>
   Over the months, Sawyer said that her firm had not been paid for
85 claims on which she believed she had provided proper
documentation, such as power of attorney, to prove she represented
the company in getting the money it was due.
</P>
<P>
   Trischitta did not attend the meeting but his boss, Deputy
Treasurer Robert E.Foley did and defended the Fund's operation. He
said any delay in approving Sawyer's applications _ and cutting the
checks to the firms _ were based on the need to be scrupulous in
proving it represented the company. ``It got into a `he said, she
said' but it was obvious there were larger issues involved that
needed to be addressed about authenticating claims, and I think we
did that,'' said one Malone official who attended the meeting but
asked not to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, Foley issued a memo announcing that Marie M.
Lawlor, Malone's general counsel, had issued new procedures for
approval of claims submitted by heir finders. Not only would heir
finders have to present powers of attorney but they also needed to
provide a business card or letter and the company's taxpayer
identification to show they represented a corporate client. But no
more would heir finders have to wait months before knowing if their
claims had been approved or not - now such notification had to be
given in 30 days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
