<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISAKSON25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Isakson prepares for office, heads to Washington to be sworn in
 &HT;    By Steve Visser
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Johnny Isakson goes to Washington today, convinced
that bickering and finger-pointing will make representing his 6th
Congressional District harder, not easier.
</P>
<P>
   Happy but tired, Isakson spent the Wednesday after his election
saying his thank-you's, visiting the state Capitol, and tending to
the details of setting up an office and staff hundreds of miles
away.
</P>
<P>
   He was to board a 6:45 a.m. Delta flight to Washington for a
midmorning swearing-in ceremony, but will return later this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview at his campaign headquarters in Sandy Springs,
the Republican congressman-elect said voters can expect him to work
with Democrats and both wings of the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to be speaker of the House, but I'll have more
time to concentrate on my district,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Isakson said the lesson in his 65 percent margin of victory is
that his constituents want a negotiator to free up federal funds to
protect the environment, unlock traffic and keep C-130Js rolling
out of Lockheed Martin Aeronautical Systems in Marietta.
</P>
<P>
   Isakson said he won't be the revolutionary in the mode of Newt
Gingrich, who stepped down as House speaker and vacated his seat
last month. ``Newt and I share the same principles and different
personalities,'' he said, and then quoted his working credo: ``To
seek consensus in the pursuit of conservative principles is no
vice.''
</P>
<P>
   Isakson and his staff were anxious to see him sworn in quickly.
The election results haven't been certified, but Congress can allow
him to be seated via a vote of unanimous consent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the kind of consensus builder who will not only be
beneficial to our state delegation, but the Congress as a whole,''
said U.S. Rep. Nathan Deal (R-Ga.), who served in the Legislature
with Isakson.
</P>
<P>
   Isakson's reputation for conciliation showed Wednesday, when he
was asked if he was irked at congressional Republicans, who on
election day were abandoning a 10 percent tax cut _ one of
Isakson's campaign promises.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not upset with anybody,'' he said. ``I'll let you know
when I'm upset,'' he snapped when pressed.
</P>
<P>
   He said the goal is lower taxes in general _ how that is
accomplished is immaterial, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the tax issue, Isakson will focus on local issues
_ and the one at the forefront is getting metro Atlanta into
compliance with the federal Clean Air Act so it will be eligible
for federal transportation funds.
</P>
<P>
   He has asked to be on both the Education and the Workforce and
Transportation and Infrastructure committees, and seats have been
kept open for him.
</P>
<P>
   Isakson will do the homework on the bills and that will make him
effective, said U.S. Rep. Jack Kingston (R-Ga.) ``Johnny Isakson
reads the bills. When you know what you're talking about, a lot
more people will listen.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
