<SLUG> BC-NUCLEAR-TERROR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NRC TO CUT MOCK RAIDS ON ATOM PLANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Nuclear Regulatory Commission plans to weaken the program
that tests nuclear plant readiness for terrorist attacks even
though almost half of the tested plants did not repel the assaults,
according to a former Navy Seal who oversees the mock invasions.
</P>
<P>
   The NRC counterterrorism team found security problems at 27 of
the 57 nuclear plants at which they have staged mock assaults since
1991, including 14 where real invaders could have caused a nuclear
core meltdown. In New England, testers scaled fences undetected,
and they smuggled in a fake handgun at Vermont Yankee last year.
</P>
<P>
   Now, amid nuclear industry complaints about the program, NRC
officials want to give reactor operators more control over the
drills. Under the new antiterrorism effort, plants would test
antiterrorism procedures more often, but with far fewer NRC
officials to watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither the nuclear industry nor the NRC senior staff appears
to be taking seriously the threat from terrorist attacks and
sabotage on commercial nuclear plants,'' Representative Edward J.
Markey, Democrat of Massachusetts said in a letter this week to the
NRC chairman, Shirley Ann Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has reversed a plan to phase out the antiterrorism
program to save money, after Markey objected in November. This
time, NRC officials say, the changes in the antiterrorism plan, are
aimed at safety rather than savings. By sending fewer inspectors to
each site, they say they can cover more ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have it my way, the licensees will test so often that we
won't even be able to get to a lot of the tests,'' said Dick
Rosano, the NRC's section chief for reactor safeguards.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy has arisen as the Clinton administration has
requested an overall 12 percent increase in counterterrorism
spending next year, after attacks on US embassies in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Although terrorists have struck just once at a US nuclear plant
_ sabotaging transmission wires at an Arizona reactor in the 1980s
_ plants have been threatened. Captain David Orrik, a retired Navy
Seal who runs the Operational Safeguards Response Evaluation
program, said the FBI had received a credible threat against a
plant this year.
</P>
<P>
   Orrik, mentioning Vermont Yankee, also said the nuclear industry
cannot be counted on to police itself, pointing to Vermont Yankee's
problems as proof. In a test of intruders' ability to sneak in
undetected, Orrik's team found six fences where monitors could not
see ladders.
</P>
<P>
   Vermont Yankee officials said the test had helped them to
improve security. ``It was a challenge to our systems and we'll
continue to challenge our systems to make sure we maintain a high
level of preparedness,'' said Rob Williams, spokesman for the plant
in Vernon, Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   Orrik's office runs two types of drills, one involving an open
attack bent on creating ``an American Chernobyl,'' the other by
intruders who try to sneak inside the plant undetected. The NRC
cited Vermont Yankee for two violations last year under testing for
surreptitious entry.
</P>
<P>
   Under the open attacks, plant operators are told 6 to 12 months
ahead of time the day of the drill, but not the exact targets of
the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the notice, Orrik said, ``at a minimum of 14 plants,''
of 57 tested, ``targets were hit such that there would be no saving
the plant . . . Security lost the battle.''
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, Pilgrim security repelled a mock assault last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Rosano said the nuclear industry is better prepared for
terrorists than Orrik's figures suggest, but he agreed that the
mock attacks were valuable. Plant owners invested up to $1.5
million in new doors, perimeter defenses and the like as a result
of mock attacks.
</P>
<P>
   However, Rosano argued the attack drills are too rare, averaging
once every eight years per plant. He said smaller NRC teams of four
or fewer could visit more sites.
</P>
<P>
   Rosano added that industry complaints _ repelling Orrik's mock
invasions require security investments above legal requirements _
were not a factor in his changes. He argued that the industry will
have to work harder under his plan.
</P>
<P>
   Orrik formally objected to Rosano's recommendations this month,
saying much of his staff agreed. ``They are weak and non-committal,
and will reduce . . . the nuclear power industry's counterterrorist
capability,'' Orrick wrote.
</P>
</TEXT>
