</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOTUS-IMMIGRANTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES RULE RESIDENT IMMIGRANTS DEEMED UNDESIRABLE CAN BE
DEPORTED 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Wednesday gave the attorney
general broad authority to begin deportation proceedings against
resident immigrants deemed undesirable, ruling that federal law
prevents those persons from turning to U.S. courts for help at the
outset of the process.
</P>
<P>
   By a 5-3 vote, the justices also held that immigrants illegally
in the United States have no constitutional right to argue in court
that the attorney general has singled them out for deportation,
using selective enforcement of the rules.
</P>
<P>
   The high court, agreeing with the Clinton administration's
position, ruled that the 1996 Illegal Immigration Reform and
Immigrant Responsibility Act prohibits immigrants from turning to
the courts to stop deportation proceedings from commencing.
</P>
<P>
   Justices David H. Souter and John Paul Stevens broke from their
colleagues in saying that the 1996 law does not apply to
deportation proceedings that were under way before April 1, 1997,
the effective date of the act.
</P>
<P>
   That time selection was no comfort to the American-Arab
Anti-Discrimination Committee, which for 12 years has challenged
the federal government's effort to deport eight Arab U.S. residents
who belong to the Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine.
The committee turned to federal courts in California, arguing that
the attorney general unconstitutionally selected the eight people
because of their affiliation with a group the Justice Department
has classified as a terrorist organization.
</P>
<P>
   The American-Arab group had won in the U.S. District Court for
Central California and the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, which
stopped deportation proceedings so judges could rule on the merits
of the committee's claim.
</P>
<P>
   But the Supreme Court, overturning those decisions, said the
1996 immigration law gives the government latitude to commence
deportation proceedings against a variety of immigrants, including
those who overstay their visas to reside in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The high court's decision drew a strong rebuke from the
American-Arab committee, which called the ruling ``a major blow to
civil liberties.'' The justices have given the government ``a green
light to use selective enforcement routinely against aliens it
doesn't like,'' added the group's spokesman, Hussein Ibish.
</P>
<P>
   The Immigration and Naturalization Service, the Justice
Department agency that enforces the law, welcomed the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Antonin Scalia, writing for the high court, said the
government's breadth of authority in deportation cases permits the
attorney general not only to begin proceedings but to halt them for
humanitarian reasons without fear that some group will oppose that
decision in court. In addition, the government may single out
specific immigrants for deportation once they have exceeded their
legal authority to remain in the United States, Scalia said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a general matter ... an alien unlawfully in this country
has no constitutional right to assert selective enforcement as a
defense against his deportation,'' Scalia wrote. ``When an alien's
continuing presence in this country is in violation of the
immigration laws, the government does not offend the Constitution
by deporting him for the additional reason that it believes him to
be a member of an organization that supports terrorist activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Joining Scalia's opinion on selective prosecution were Chief
Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justices Sandra Day O'Connor,
Anthony M. Kennedy and Clarence Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Souter, the sole court member who would have upheld the lower
courts' decisions, said the high court should not have addressed
the issue of selective enforcement because that issue was not
directly before the justices. The Supreme Court agreed to hear the
case solely on the issue of whether federal courts had jurisdiction
to hear challenges to the government's commencement of deportation
proceedings, Souter wrote in a dissenting opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens agreed that the American-Arab group was entitled to its
day in court but said the district court should not have stopped
the government from proceeding with deportation. ``I have no doubt
that the attorney general may give priority to the removal of
deportable aliens who are members of such a terrorist
organization,'' he wrote in an opinion concurring with the court's
judgment.
</P>
<P>
   Justices Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Stephen G. Breyer agreed with
Scalia that immigrants have no recourse to ask courts to stop
deportation proceedings at the beginning. But the justices added
that immigrants have the right to press claims of selective
enforcement before a final deportation order is issued.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
