u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILITARY-PAY-421&AMP;ADD-     02-24 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILITARY-PAY-421&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE APPROVES MILITARY PAY INCREASE THAT IS BIGGER THAN CLINTON
SOUGHT 
</HEADLINE>
 (fe) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate overwhelmingly approved a sweeping
military pay and pension increase on Wednesday that is bigger than
a plan President Clinton proposed two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, a top Republican priority, was approved 91-8, with
most Democrats joining the politically popular measure that the
Joint Chiefs of Staff say is essential to help recruit and retain
the highest-caliber armed forces. Three Republicans and five
Democrats opposed the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Pay raises and sweetened pensions are traditional Republican
issues that Clinton seemed to co-opt with his proposal in December
to increase military salaries by 4.4 percent for all 1.4 million
members of the armed forces on active duty, starting in January
2000. The administration also sought to give larger bonuses to
selected mid-career personnel and to improve the pensions of
veterans who joined after 1986. Although the administration has
said it was not happy with the bill in its current form, officials
said it was unlikely that the president would veto such popular
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Republicans, eager to show that Clinton's impeachment
trial had not derailed their legislative agenda, split off the pay
and pension provisions from the annual Pentagon budget bill to make
it the first major legislation the Senate considered this year.
</P>
<P>
   Senators then made the measure _ called the Soldiers', Sailors',
Airmen's, and Marines' Bill of Rights _ more generous than the
president's version. The Senate bill authorizes a 4.8 percent pay
raise next year; allots bonuses of up to 10.3 percent, compared
with the administration's 9.9 percent, and provides for slightly
better pensions.
</P>
<P>
   It also adds more educational aid under the Montgomery GI Bill,
creates 401(k)-style savings accounts for service members and
provides $180 a month to as many as 10,000 low-ranking troops who
are eligible for food stamps.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is something of a bidding war going on between the
administration and the Congress,'' said Steven Kosiak, an analyst
with the Center for Strategic and Budgetary Assessments, a policy
research institute.
</P>
<P>
   The Congressional Budget Office estimated that the Senate plan
would cost $55 billion over 10 years, $18 billion more than the
administration's plan. Either proposal marks the largest pay raises
since 1982, when a newly elected President Ronald Reagan approved
increases of 14.3 percent for officers and 10 percent to 17 percent
for enlisted personnel.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Senate action puts the White House in a bind. A policy
statement from the White House's Office of Management and Budget
said the administration ``does not support'' the bill in its
``current form.'' But the president cannot risk blocking a pay
raise for troops at a time that the Air Force is begging for
pilots, the Navy is short on sailors and recruiters are scraping to
meet their monthly quotas.
</P>
<P>
   The House, while undecided whether it will break out the pay
provisions as the Senate has, is likely to follow the Senate's lead
closely. At a hearing on Wednesday of the House Armed Services
Committee, lawmakers pressed the military service chiefs on their
personnel problems. ``Recruiting in the Army today is a very tough
challenge,'' said Gen. Dennis J. Reimer, the Army chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William S. Cohen favors extra pay increases
but only if Congress increases the Pentagon's overall budget to pay
for them. Otherwise, Cohen, a former Republican Senator from Maine,
has said the Republicans' one-upsmanship could force the Defense
Department to cut training, spare parts or other areas that
Congress insists are vital.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be counterproductive and completely contrary to our
mutual desire not to undercut our modernization effort and other
readiness priorities,'' Cohen said in a letter last week to Sen.
John Warner, R-Va., who heads the Armed Services Committee.
</P>
<P>
   An influential conservative, Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla., the
majority whip, expressed a similar concern on Wednesday about the
bill's cost. Nickles said the proposal to increase the pensions of
20-year veterans to 50 percent of their basic pay, from 40 percent,
was ``a mistake'' that would cost $14 billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Trent Lott, R-Miss., the majority leader, who put the
bill on a fast track and helped rush it to the floor with no
committee hearings, dismissed any hand-wringing over budget
constraints. ``There is one thing that takes higher priority than
budgets, and that's the defense of our country,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   Warner added, ``We simply cannot allow the best military force
in the world to wither and atrophy.''
</P>
<P>
   But some independent military analysts say Congress may be
overreacting to a problem that has yet to be fully analyzed. Some
specialists say, for example, that the frequency of overseas
missions has more sway over whether troops decide to remain in the
military than a sweetened pension.
</P>
<P>
   Major studies on pay and pension by the Congressional Budget
Office, General Accounting Office and the Pentagon are nearing
completion, and some lawmakers advised waiting until the study
results are known and the budget picture becomes clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill,'' said Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., the ranking
minority member of the Armed Services Committee, ``represents a
promise to the troops that may or may not be possible to redeem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
