<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSEUM-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSEUM SEEKS TO RETURN PLUNDERED PAINTING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WALTER V. ROBINSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It measures just 5 by 10 inches. But the 16th-century
Flemish landscape by Herri met de Bles has been housed in two of
this century's most dissimilar art collections since it was whisked
out of the Netherlands after the Nazi occupation in May 1940.
</P>
<P>
   For the duration of World War II, it was in the notorious
private collection of Nazi Reichsmarshal Hermann Goering, a
collection of art looted or ``bought'' at gunpoint in occupied
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1946, an American dealer sold the de Bles to the Boston
Museum of Fine Arts, whose documents suggest the museum was
indifferent to its ownership history.
</P>
<P>
   Like other paintings that passed through soiled hands during and
after the war, the landscape raises embarrassing questions about
the postwar policies of museums such as the MFA, which first
learned 51 years ago that the painting might have been illicitly
traded during the war.
</P>
<P>
   Dawn Griffin, the MFA's spokeswoman, said the museum is eager to
return the landscape as soon as the evidence establishes its
rightful ownership. The MFA, she said, is continuing to search its
records to ensure that the rest of its artworks have no wartime
taint.
</P>
<P>
   No museum, Griffin noted, is immune from the possibility that it
might have inadvertently acquired art after the war that had been
looted by the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch first alerted the MFA in 1948 that the painting had
been taken from Holland by the Nazis, according to MFA
correspondence obtained by the Globe. That year, Dutch authorities
asked for its return, but the MFA's director at the time, G. H.
Edgell, insisted that the Dutch provide ``definite'' evidence it
had been stolen.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch, trying to rebuild their country in the chaos of
post-war Europe, dropped the claim. And so, for 50 years, the MFA
shelved the matter.
</P>
<P>
   But last March, soon after the Globe raised questions about
other MFA post-war acquisitions and amid growing international
attention to Nazi-looted art, the museum discovered documents from
1948 and contacted the Dutch government with an offer to return the
painting if the Dutch would provide the long-overdue evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Dutch officials said they are about to do so, and
they praised the MFA for coming forward to settle a case that
present-day Dutch officials say they were unaware of.
</P>
<P>
   To some art specialists, the tale of the tiny painting
underscores persistent moral issues that confront the art world,
including the eagerness of postwar collectors and curators to
acquire paintings like the de Bles even though the works crossed
the Atlantic with suspicious pedigrees.
</P>
<P>
   In 1948, for instance, the MFA's director unapologetically
acknowledged to the Dutch that the museum had virtually no
information about the prior ownership of the de Bles.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is even more awkward for the Netherlands. More than 90
percent of Dutch Jews perished in the Holocaust, by far the highest
rate in Western Europe. Recent public outrage has led to the
creation of a commission to examine why 90 percent of the artworks
recovered from the Nazis after the war, including major works by
Rembrandt, remain unclaimed in Dutch museums.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dutch government behaved despicably after the war and was
so intent on keeping the looted art that they dispossessed their
own citizens,'' Christine A. Koenigs, whose grandfather owned the
de Bles until 1940, said in an interview this week.
</P>
<P>
   Koenigs, who lives in Amsterdam, holds the Dutch, and not the
MFA, accountable. But others take a different view.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dutch incompetence does not excuse five decades of inaction by
the MFA,'' said Willi Korte, a specialist in locating Nazi-looted
art who is not involved in the de Bles case.
</P>
<P>
   If the MFA needed evidence to support the claim, it arrived
unsolicited last July when Koenigs filed her own claim. She
included documents that leave little doubt that the artwork, like
tens of thousands of others, was a casualty of the war. The
documents, she said, were in official Dutch files in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   Among the documents Koenigs has is a copy of a list of 19 of
Franz Koenigs's paintings that Goering acquired in 1940, including
receipts signed by Goering's administrative assistant at Carinhall,
his palace outside Berlin. The de Bles painting, ``Burning City,''
is on the list. Evidence that the painting was in Goering's illicit
collection has long been publicly available in the US National
Archives.
</P>
<P>
   For the MFA, the case of the de Bles landscape is the latest in
a series of disclosures that raise questions about the museum's
collecting ethics. Those questions encompass both its postwar
acquisition of paintings and its recent acquisitions of antiquities
that the museum had reason to believe had been illegally taken from
grave sites in countries such as Italy and Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
   A number of other European paintings the MFA has acquired since
the 1940s have ownership histories that, according to art
specialists, raise suspicions they might have been looted during
the war. The MFA has refused to say whether it has subsequently
investigated the history of those artworks.
</P>
<P>
   Last June, a panel of the Association of Art Museum Directors
that included the current MFA director, Malcolm Rogers, pledged
that AAMD members would look for evidence any of their art had been
looted by the Nazis, would deal ``promptly'' with any claims, and
would publicly disclose if any of their artworks had been illegally
confiscated during World War II and not restituted.
</P>
<P>
   Until asked Wednesday, the MFA had said nothing about the de
Bles. When the Globe inquired late last year whether the museum had
found any evidence of looted Nazi art in its collection, the MFA
sidestepped the question. ``We have no specific discoveries to
report to the Globe,'' the museum replied.
</P>
<P>
   Yet last March, according to Bob G.C. Lodder, the deputy
director of the Cultural Heritage Department of the Dutch Ministry
of Culture, Rogers wrote to the Dutch government about the de Bles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The MFA contacted us to say they had been looking at their
records on this painting and had found some very strange things,''
Lodder said Wednesday. ``When we checked our own records, it became
clear the painting was ours.'' The Boston museum, he said, should
be praised for coming forward.
</P>
<P>
   In 1948, when the Boymans Museum in Rotterdam asked that the de
Bles be returned, MFA director Edgell wrote that the MFA's trustees
``would return the painting to the Boymans Museum when definite
proof is given us that it was stolen.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Edgell admitted that the MFA knew almost nothing about the
landscape's origin. ``The dealer can tell us little beyond the fact
that the picture was bought in a small auction room in New York,
the owner of which says that the picture came to him from Chicago.
We are trying to get more information about its history but
probably shall not succeed,'' Edgell wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Though the MFA was uncertain about the work's history, Edgell
told the Dutch that he thought it likely the painting ``may have
left the Koenigs collection before it was seized by the Nazis.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Edgell concluded, ``We are not hedging and certainly
have no intention of being receivers of stolen goods, but equally
you will realize that our trustees cannot return a painting without
definite legal proof that it was stolen.''
</P>
<P>
   Korte, who has represented several victims of Nazi art looting
who have made claims against American museums, said there is a
double standard implicit in Edgell's 1948 explanation, one that
echoes through other cases in which museums have resisted claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same trustees and curators, who ask no questions, who
raise no suspicions when they acquire a painting, and who have no
records of where the painting came from, all of a sudden develop
very high standards of proof when a claimant comes along,'' Korte
said.
</P>
<P>
   How the de Bles landscape ended up in Chicago is unclear, but
Korte said it is likely that one of the American GIs who liberated
Carinhall took the miniature painting home in his duffel bag as a
trophy.
</P>
<P>
   Given the complex manner in which Franz Koenigs's massive
collection was lost, Korte said, the only issue is whether the
painting belongs to the Koenigs family or the Dutch government.
Lodder made it clear Wednesday that the government believes it owns
the collection.
</P>
<P>
   Franz Koenigs was a wealthy German businessman who emigrated to
the Netherlands in 1931, bringing one of Europe's most
extraordinary art collections. It included numerous paintings,
among them the de Bles landscape and many works by Rubens. More
importantly, Koenigs had one of the world's best collections of Old
Master drawings, 2,144 in all.
</P>
<P>
   But Koenigs, who was not Jewish, fell on hard times, and used
the collection as collateral for a loan from a Jewish-owned bank.
With the Nazi invasion imminent, the bank was advised to liquidate
its holdings, selling most of Koenigs's collection and consigning
35 paintings to an art dealer to be sold. After the Nazi invasion,
the dealership was taken over by a Nazi art procurer, who sold 19
of the paintings, including the de Bles, to Goering.
</P>
<P>
   Under a 1943 Allied declaration, adopted as law by the Dutch,
all wartime sales to Germans in Occupied Europe were deemed null
and void. Dutch policy, which has come under fire from claimants
like Koenigs, declares the state the owner of works that were sold,
even in questionable circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   In Koenigs's case, hundreds of his drawings were seized by
occupying Soviet forces and kept as war reparations. Those that
were returned, including many of the paintings from Carinhall, have
been kept by the Dutch government, despite Christine Koenigs's
insistence that her grandfather would have retained his collection
but for the invasion and the bank liquidation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
