<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  JOHNSTOWN AREA RESIDENTS GIVE TO CLINTON LEGAL DEFENSE FUND
</P>
<P>
   By Lisa Fine
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Feb. 24 -- Retired Johnstown resident Louis Will was
so angered by the impeachment process, he wanted to help pay to
defend President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   He sent a check for $35 to the Clinton Legal Expense Trust,
which was set up to accept donations to help the president pay his
legal bills which are at $9 million -- and growing. ``I just
thought about the opposition he was up against,'' Will said. ``I
thought it was important that I help. I didn't like the tactics
used against Clinton. It was my vote they were trying to
overturn.'' Will was among more than 50,000 donors from around the
nation gave more than $4.5 million to President Clinton's Legal
Expense Trust in its first year, according to a report released
Wednesday by the trust. In the second half of 1998, there were
1,132 donors from Pennsylvania, about a dozen of whom are from the
Johnstown area. Contributions from the Keystone state came to more
than $75,000.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the numbers were made public in June, the trust
had received more than $1.5 million in contributions from about
10,000 people. In the second half of 1998, the trust received $2.2
million from about 29,500 contributors.
</P>
<P>
   Since the start of this year, the Trust has received 11,000
additional contributions totaling more than $800,000.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Essaye, director of the trust, said they referred to the
impeachment process in direct mailings to potential donors. But
they said donations came in at a steady pace without peaks,
regardless of turns in the Monica Lewinsky scandal and impeachment
trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``The effort to impeach President Clinton is only the latest in
a series of legal actions that have left the First Family with a
staggering personal debt,'' the letter said. ``If you are disturbed
by the way politics is conducted today, then what better response
than to offer the First Family your own gesture of support.''
</P>
<P>
   Only six people asked for refunds of their $173 in donations,
after Clinton admitted having an ``improper relationship,'' with
the former White House intern, Essaye said.
</P>
<P>
   The Trust has already paid $3 million to the lawyers
representing Clinton and the First Lady, in the past six years,
leaving about $6 million in bills that still need to be paid.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never set paying off everything as the objective,'' Essaye
said. ``But it is reachable.'' The trust attracted donations from
the likes of entertainer Tony Bennett, who gave $10,000, and writer
Stephen King, who gave $5,000. But half of the donations were $25
or less. About 95 percent of the donations were under $100,
trustees said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were impressed by how personal this is for people,'' Essaye
said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnstown area residents who donated include: Warren Feaster of
Bedford gave $1; Donald Young of Bedford gave $20; Lisa Fetzer of
Bensalem gave $5; Milton Richlin of Bensalem gave $15; Mildred
Zelenko of Bensalem gave $50; Mabel Hornbake of Edensburg gave $50;
Ralph Grove of Indiana gave $40; Pepita Himinez of Indiana gave
$25; Irene Luxenberg of Indiana gave $15; Esther Ondo of Indiana
gave $20; William Glosser of Johnstown, gave $25; Johanna
Mendenhall of Johnstown gave $10.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
