<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 20:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8152 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-DOG-CONTROL-ART-NY     02-24 1242
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DOG-CONTROL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEXT UP IN CITY'S QUALITY-OF-LIFE CRACKDOWN: OWNERS OF DOGS WITHOUT
LEASHES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By BLAINE HARDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Three dogs without leashes took off in joyous pursuit
of a 47-year-old architect last week while all four were out for a
morning's run in Manhattan's Riverside Park.
</P>
<P>
   One dog bit the architect's ankle. Another urinated on a
shoulder bag he had dropped. The architect complained furiously to
city, state and federal officials about a ``tyranny of the
minority.'' But he did not want his name published, saying that he
feared a backlash from militant dog owners in his Upper West Side
apartment building.
</P>
<P>
   Dog wars: a chronic conflict made worse by New Yorkers who are
owning bigger, stronger, more robust dogs. As never before, tens of
thousands of big dogs who loathe the leash are lunging out of
apartments to do what dogs must do in city parks that are better
maintained, safer and more crowded than they have been in decades.
</P>
<P>
   There's the rub.
</P>
<P>
   So to preserve Central Park and especially Riverside Park, which
the city regards as ground zero in the dog wars, Parks Commissioner
Henry J. Stern announced stiffer fines, increased enforcement and a
public-relations campaign Wednesday that attempts to equate dog
owners who violate leash laws with smokers.
</P>
<P>
   By getting tough on free-range dogs _ an echo of Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani's quality-of-life crackdown on everything from squeegee
men to jaywalking to chewing-gum spitters _ the city hopes to
persuade dog owners that it is unhealthful, inconsiderate and even
shameful to let dogs run free.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might call them dog terrorists,'' Stern said. ``They let
them off leash at all times, frighten other people, especially
children, and trample the public lawns.'' He added, though, that
these ``arrogant and abusive'' New Yorkers are a relatively small
percentage of dog owners.
</P>
<P>
   To protect the gussied-up parks and the people who use them,
Stern said he is proposing a doubling in fines for repeat violators
of leash and pooper-scooper laws. The $100 fine will double, he
said, for second-time offenders and double again and again for
subsequent violations to a limit of $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Stern also said the Parks Department would invite more police
into the parks, build a data base of habitual dog-law violators and
outfit civilians with radios and cell phones so they can report dog
owners who violate canine-control laws.
</P>
<P>
   Riverside Park dog owners have reacted angrily to efforts to
restrict dogs. When fences were put up to block dog access to a
popular play field for off-leash dogs, owners put up signs that
called the enclosure ``Treblinka.''
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the largest dog-owner group in Riverside Park
responded Wednesday to the proposed crackdown with a plea for space
for dogs to run free of leashes and a veiled threat of civil
disobedience if such space is not forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is not sufficient space for people to play with one's
dog off leash, then people either will feel persecuted or forced
into what the commissioner considers antisocial behavior,'' said
Dr. Jeffrey Zahn, an anesthesiologist who is president of the dog
group, FLORAL.
</P>
<P>
   Stern would tend to agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see in Riverside Park there is a fringe of very intense
dog owners,'' he said. ``These owners when ticketed give names such
as Eva Braun. They cast themselves as victims of authority. They
hope a gullible press will see their victimhood. In fact, it is
mothers and children who use the parks who are the victims.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern stressed in the interview that he is not anti-dog and that
he owns and loves a golden retriever named Boomer, who the
commissioner's aides insist is never allowed off his leash. ``I
really believe that owning and relating to an animal is a
life-enriching experience,'' Stern said.
</P>
<P>
   As a matter of law, dogs have no right to run free anywhere in
New York. They lost that right 123 years ago when Frederick Law
Olmsted, who designed Central and Riverside parks, personally wrote
a set of rules that tethered them to a leash not more than 6 feet
long.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the 1970s and early 1980s, when many parks were
ill-maintained and relatively empty because of crime, the Parks
Department did not much care if dogs ranged off leash. In those
years, park managers saw dogs and their owners as a civilizing
influence. Better the depredation of dogs, they reasoned, than the
marauding of muggers and drug dealers.
</P>
<P>
   It was in those dark days that dogs and owners wrested an
informal but crucial concession from the parks department. Dogs
have since been allowed off-leash in parks between 9 p.m. and 9
a.m. At the time, it hardly mattered. There wasn't much carefully
tended greenery for dogs to destroy.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last decade, at a cost of many millions of dollars,
desolate, no-go landscapes in city parks have been restored. Crime
has fallen as steeply in parks as in the rest of the city. And the
dog presence that once helped stabilize the parks has become, in
the view of Adrian Benepe, commissioner of parks in Manhattan,
``our biggest problem.'' The Parks Department estimated Wednesday
that it spends $250,000 a year in Central and Riverside parks to
repair damage done by dogs.
</P>
<P>
   The informal off-leash concession, though, has evolved into what
many dog owners see as a God-given right. Some Parks administrators
say that by giving dog owners the off-leash night, they have
inadvertently encouraged them to seize the off-leash day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The relaxing of the rules doesn't win us any cooperation,''
said Charles E. McKinney, administrator of Riverside Park. ``In
fact, it has encouraged more people to have dogs off leash during
the day.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern, for the moment at least, is unwilling to challenge the
informal agreement that lets dogs run free at night and in the
early morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are talking about things that happen during the day,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Park managers are convinced that the problem of dogs being off
leash, both in the permitted night and the illicit day, is
compounded by the size of the offending dogs. ``One now sees in
Central Park and Riverside Park a larger dog than one typically saw
in a New York City setting,'' Benepe said. ``A big dog running
circles on a dormant park lawn can do a lot of damage. They kick up
divots like a golf club.''
</P>
<P>
   Many dog owners regard such statements as ill-informed, unfair
and profoundly offensive. While they acknowledge that dogs can
damage park land, owners contend that ball players, frolicking
children and homeless people are also to blame. They say that the
best way for park officials to limit dog damage is to work in good
faith with responsible owners _ and refrain from saying hurtful
things about dogs.
</P>
<P>
   When pressed, many dog owners say that their dogs _ particularly
their big dogs _ have an inalienable right to run off-leash. When
parks do not honor that right, they say, there is bound to be
blatant disregard for leash laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should we be deprived of all nature?'' said Madeleine Dale, a
founder of FLORAL, who runs in Riverside Park with her 85-pound
Scottish deerhound _ off leash, of course. ``Should we be deprived
of all courtesy? I would hate to see Manhattan become that kind of
heartless place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-99 2045EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990224.0406 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8155 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-RETREAT-740&AMP;     02-24 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-RETREAT-740&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS TO SEEK PEACE AT A RETREAT ON `CONGENIALITY' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Calif., Mich., N.C., Ohio, Ill., Ga., Md., N.Y.)  (jw) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The oft-feuding, bitterly divided,
impeachment-scarred Democrats and Republicans in the House have
decided to give peace a chance.
</P>
<P>
   Under the guidance of the man who helped broker the Northern
Ireland peace talks, members of both parties plan to travel
off-campus next month to a retreat in Hershey, Pa., where they can
be themselves, vent their ire and learn to try to get along.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need this opportunity,'' Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif.,
said Wednesday, speaking at a podium decorated with silver-wrapped
Hershey's Kisses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people are tired of seeing their politics
degenerate into rancor and personal attacks,'' said Rep. David
Bonior, D-Mich., making a pitch to his fellow Democrats to attend
the three-day retreat that begins March 19. ``I believe this
Congress faces no more important challenge than making democracy
work again in a manner that is civil and respectful.''
</P>
<P>
   A chartered Amtrak train is to take lawmakers from Washington to
the retreat, and while leaders of both parties are encouraging
members to go, not everyone is on board. Some members are
suspicious, believing that the retreat will make little real
difference and wary of being portrayed as part of a happy face that
the leaders want to stamp on the new Congress. (Rep. Eva Clayton,
D-N.C., said that the chocolate Kisses were ``a little too
simplistic'' a symbol for the retreat. ``It's not `kiss and make
up,' '' she cautioned.)
</P>
<P>
   The event, financed with $700,000 from the nonprofit Pew
Charitable Trust, is a reprise of a similar ``civility'' retreat
held in Hershey in 1997. With a nod to an apparent desire by both
sides for longer-lasting results, the organizers have invited John
Hume, leader of the Social and Democratic Labor Party, who won the
Nobel Peace Prize for 1998 for his efforts in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he can bring peace in Ireland, perhaps he can bring peace
here in the halls of Congress,'' said a hopeful Rep. Ray LaHood,
R-Ill., who drew attention by presiding in the speaker's chair last
year during the House impeachment of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the Hershey roster is Sam Waterston, the actor noted for
his stage portrayals of Abraham Lincoln. Waterston has employed a
team of historians and dramatists to gather Lincoln excerpts that
will be, in the words of Rep. Tom Sawyer, D-Ohio, ``suitable to our
current circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   The organizers have also altered the moniker by which they want
the retreat to be known. Instead of ``civility,'' they are calling
it the ``congeniality'' retreat. One aide explained the distinction
this way: `` Civility is just, `Oh, hello,' but congeniality is,
`Let's grab lunch, let's grab a drink, we're all in this together.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Still, bruised feelings seem to be the order of the day in the
House, the result of both the tempestuous tenure of former Speaker
Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., and the searing impeachment ordeal. Democrats
are also feeling aggrieved over what they perceive as unfair
treatment at the hands of the majority Republicans. For example,
most committees have a higher ratio of Republicans to Democrats
that is out of proportion to their overall numbers in the House
(222 Republicans compared with 211 Democrats). In addition,
Democrats complain that their committee staffs are vastly
underfinanced.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of Democrats are talking privately about boycotting
the event. ``A lot of our people are angry, but a lot of them are
going,'' said a Democratic leadership aide. ``There's no reason to
think that after what we just went through, with them trying to
throw out the leader of our party, that we're all suddenly going to
be buddies. That's absurd.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats, like Rep. Steny Hoyer of Maryland, are attending
the retreat but intend to air their grievances. Bonior said that
this could be useful. ``We're encouraging people to come and vent
their frustrations and their ideas,'' he said. He said the party
was meeting ``some resistance'' but expected that more than half
the Democrats would show up.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said that more than half of their members would
attend too, but there were signs that all was not well on that side
of the aisle either. Rep. Amo Houghton, R-N.Y., lamented that some
Republicans would not appear and they were the ones who ``need it
the most.'' Asked how many members of the House Judiciary Committee
would attend, LaHood said quickly: ``Next question!''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Wednesday's news conference, with its bipartisan display and the
announcement of speakers _ who will also include Doris Kearns
Goodwin, the historian _ was intended to persuade more members to
sign up.
</P>
<P>
   To this end, LaHood suggested that even if Democratic griping
was not officially sanctioned, it would happen anyway. ``When you
get 200 freely elected politicians in a room, you're not going to
tell them what they can and cannot say,'' he said. ``People deviate
from agendas all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The news conference was also intended as a signal to Pew that
the retreat is worthy of support.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Rimel, president of the Pew trust, based in
Philadelphia, said in an interview: ``A week ago there was a little
bit of higher anxiety, but I understand they've turned the
corner.'' She said she understood that more than 140 members had
signed up so far, about 60 percent of them Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always said that the hope was that it be a majority and
the requirement is that it be bipartisan,'' she said. ``Given all
that's transpired over the last six months, the planning committee
needs to see if it can excite people about the agenda and get
people committed to the time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
