<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-DELLUMS2-NAT </SLUG>

 &HT;        DELLUMS' NEW BOOK A TRIBUTE TO PACIFISM   By Mark
Stricherz  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Feb. 24 -- When he was in Congress, former Oakland
Representative Ron Dellums was rarely accused of being unambitious,
as was demonstrated during the early 1970's when he held a war
crimes tribunal to protest the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   Now that he is out of Congress, Dellums may be relaxing a bit
more, but he isn't exactly loafing around either. Aside from trying
to head off Africa's AIDS epidemic, Dellums is writing an
autobiography, which is scheduled to be released this fall by
Beacon Press. A former aide, Lee Halterman, is his co-author.
</P>
<P>
   Tentatively entitled ``A Warrior for Peace'' or ``Journey for
Peace,'' Dellums' book will focus on the Oakland-native's main
devotion during his political life: pacifism. It's the cause that
first won him a seat in 1967 on the Berkeley City Council, when he
ran as anti-war candidate. That same activism ricocheted back at
him in Congress, when, as chairman of the Armed Services Committee,
he opposed using force against North Korea in 1994 during a
stand-off over nuclear power.
</P>
<P>
   As a New Republic article once noted, Dellums said in 1971 his
philosophy was based on the idea that ``violence is totally
nonproductive even in revolutionary terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Talking about peace 28 years later, Dellums sounds positively
wistful that the values he embraced during the 1950s and '60s are
now out of fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to keep the romantic ideals of the '60s alive,''
Dellums said of his current employer, the all-black Healthcare
International Management Co. ``We feel we're responsible for our
brothers and sisters -- the kind of spirit you don't see in the
late '90s.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many in his generation, Dellums credits Martin Luther King,
Jr. for leading his embrace of non-violence. But Dellums also cites
his uncle, C.L. Dellums, who was a lesser known but leading civil
rights figure during the 1920s and '30s.
</P>
<P>
   C.L. Dellums, whose name now graces a train station in Oakland's
Jack London Square, made his name by teaming up with A. Philip
Randolph to organize the Brotherhood Sleeping Car Porters. The
group, which organized the first civil rights march on Washington
in 1941, helped establish a series of victories in labor law for
blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up on stories that stressed the danger of organizing.
During the '20s black people had to have a lot of audacity to fight
for civil rights. If you worked in states like Utah and California,
like my uncle did, and they threw you off the train, well, you got
thrown off the train. How you going to get home as a black
person?''
</P>
<P>
   While C.L. Dellums died in 1989, he was able to see his nephew
rise to prominence in the Bay Area's leftist politics during the
1960s, an ascension that began after a three-year stint in the
Marine Corps in the 1950s. He graduated from San Francisco State
College in 1960, worked as a psychiatric social worker, and won the
Berkeley-Oakland congressional seat in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   During his 27-year tenure in Congress, Dellums was renowned for
not only opposing many of the largest military spending items, such
as the B-2 bomber and the MX missile. He also was known for
objecting to some military spending in his own district -- most
notably, in 1993, the recommendation to pull the plug on the
Alameda Naval Air Station, which employed 11,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Dellums' commitment to pacifism was such that the closest he
came toward advocating military involvement was during the Haiti
crisis of the mid-1990s, though he did not recommend the immediate
dispatch of U.S. troops.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, while Dellums models himself after his uncle, he maintains
he has his own causes. Like Africa and the AIDS epidemic. ``To say
we should sit around while 20 million people die in the next 10
years, I say, to hell with it,'' he declares, sounding not unlike
his uncle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
