<SLUG> BC-JASPER-T-SHIRTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTIM'S FAMILY FILES SUIT AGAINST T-SHIRT SELLERS IN JASPER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See JASPER-TRIAL and JASPER-SENTENCE) 
 
By PATTY REINERT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ As jurors at the Jasper County Courthouse
listened Wednesday to testimony on punishment for a white
supremacist convicted in the dragging death of a black man, the
victim's family was filing suit against T-shirt sellers outside.
</P>
<P>
   Eligah ``Ricky'' Jason, a Beaumont, Texas, singer with the duo
Colorblind, said sheriff's deputies served him with the lawsuit and
a temporary injunction Wednesday morning and closed down his
sidewalk stand across the street from the courthouse, where he had
been selling T-shirts, hats and compact discs.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the nonprofit James Byrd Jr. Foundation for
Racial Healing filed a breach of contract lawsuit in state district
court, alleging that Jason and his singing partner, Robin Zaruba,
had failed to obtain prior approval to sell the merchandise outside
the courthouse and had not turned over the foundation's portion of
the proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an agreement, a permit, a license,'' Jason said. ``We
intend to donate 10 percent of the T-shirt sales and 10 percent of
the BMI royalties from the album to the Byrd family. We were
supposed to be together on this. It was a joint deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Darrell Verrett, Byrd's nephew and executive director of the
foundation, acknowledged that he had signed an agreement with
Colorblind, allowing them to use Byrd's name, photograph and
likeness for commercial purposes. But he said he never gave the
singers permission to sell the T-shirts outside the courthouse
during the trial.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit says Verrett terminated the agreement Feb. 16, the
first day of testimony in the capital murder trial of John William
``Bill'' King. The lawsuit says Jason continued to sell the
T-shirts without permission.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not really the money,'' Verrett said during a break in
the court proceedings. ``It was tacky and undignified, selling them
out there during the trial. They didn't have prior approval for
that. It's a simple breach of contract. We asked them to stop and
they wouldn't, so we had to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason, who stood outside the courthouse with a copy of his
agreement, his permits, his lawsuit and a framed ``certificate of
appreciation'' signed by Byrd's parents last September, said he
approached the Byrd family shortly after last summer's killing and
told them he wanted to dedicate his album of religious music to the
49-year-old disabled man who had suffered such a brutal death.
</P>
<P>
   Since the trial began, he and two friends have been selling
T-shirts with a portrait of Byrd on the front and an ad for
Colorblind's CD, ``Love, Peace and Harmony,'' on the back, along
with the CD itself, which carries an extensive dedication to Byrd,
and hats touting ``Trial of the Century, Jasper, Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason estimated they had sold $5,000 to $6,000 worth of the
merchandise to reporters and trial spectators, and intended to give
the Byrd foundation its share.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really upset,'' he said. ``I've been friends with these
people. They've stayed at my house. I've eaten at their house. We
never wanted to hurt the Byrd family. We wanted to help them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
