<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8161 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIVETTI-TELECOM-310&AMP;     02-24 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIVETTI-TELECOM-310&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLIVETTI MANEUVERS TO GAIN REGULATORY APPROVAL FOR TELECOM BID 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Opening a new round in the fight for control of Italy's
biggest phone company, Olivetti SpA approved some technical steps
Wednesday that are required by stock market regulators for it to
proceed with a $60 billion hostile bid for Telecom Italia.
</P>
<P>
   Olivetti's moves, which included raising billions of dollars in
new capital and the sale of an Olivetti communications business to
Mannesmann AG, a German partner, came after hours of meetings in
Milan of Olivetti officials with lawyers and investment bankers.
</P>
<P>
   The moves were intended to overcome objections of Italian stock
market regulators, who on Monday invalidated an earlier Olivetti
bid for Telecom Italia, which is five times Olivetti's size.
</P>
<P>
   Olivetti, a typewriter maker turned computer company and then
communications provider, has struggled in recent years Yet its
audacious effort to purchase Telecom Italia represents one of the
biggest hostile takeover attempts by any company.
</P>
<P>
   Resubmitting a valid bid for Telecom Italia quickly is a crucial
piece of Olivetti's strategy. Under Italian takeover law, a company
cannot take defensive steps once a valid offer has been made.
</P>
<P>
   But late Wednesday night, it was still unclear whether
Olivetti's steps were sufficient to validate its bid. In addition,
there was surprising news that the bid price of 10 euros a share,
or $11, for all of Telecom Italia's voting stock would not be
raised.
</P>
<P>
   Investors, buoyed by hopes that Olivetti would sweeten the
offer, had pushed up Telecom Italia's share price Wednesday by 5
percent, to 10.06 euros, or $11.06, adding $2.6 billion to the
market value of the phone provider's common stock. In New York, the
American depository receipts of Telecom Italia closed up 2.5
percent, at $109.6875. Olivetti shares, which had fallen for two
days, gained half a percent, to 2.92 euros.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Even without a sweetened price, officials close to Olivetti,
Italy's No. 2 phone company, remained confident that the bid would
succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Among the measures approved Wednesday was an enormous bond issue
of $15 billion by Tecnost SpA, the Olivetti unit that will be used
to make the bid. Olivetti officials cited a strong rating expected
to be given the bondsby Standard &AMP; Poor's as a sign of confidence
in the bid. Standard &AMP; Poor's earlier said it would not comment on
the rating.
</P>
<P>
   Olivetti chief executive Roberto Colaninno, who is engineering
the bid, called the boards of Olivetti and Tecnost to meet one
after the other on Wednesday afternoon. They approved two capital
increases _ $2.8 billion for Olivetti, and a second, totaling $11.3
billion, for Tecnost, a small maker of gaming machinery controlled
by Olivetti.
</P>
<P>
   The board of Telecom Italia planned to discuss measures to
defend itself Thursday. Those measures were expected to include a
merger of Telecom with its mobile phone unit, Telecom Italia
Mobile. That would increase Telecom's net worth and raise the price
Olivetti would have to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Under Italian law, a company that is the target of a hostile bid
is barred from taking measures to immunize itself. It was unclear
that Olivetti could present its bid and obtain regulatory approval
before Telecom Italia's board meets Thursday. But officials close
to the regulator's office, Consob, were unable to say Wednesday how
a renewed Olivetti bid would affect Telecom Italia's decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday, Telecom chief executive Franco Bernabe met in
Rome with labor union leaders of Telecom Italia to seek support.
The union leaders, who said that Bernabe disclosed no details of
his plans, generally support him nonetheless, driven by fear that
an Olivetti takeover would burden the combined company with debt,
forcing management to sharply cut jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with knowledge of Telecom Italia's plans said Bernabe
would ofer proposals to the company's board that could include
weeding out unprofitable domestic operations, selling minority
stakes in phone companies abroad and selling some phone-equipment
manufacturing assets.
</P>
<P>
   One proposal said to be under consideration was to pay
shareholders a large dividend as a means of reducing Telecom
Italia's cash.
</P>
<P>
   A senior executive at an Italian multinational company who has
been in touch with Bernabe described him as ``a fierce fighter when
he is up against the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning, Bernabe was chastised by Consob after an
article in The Wall Street Journal's European edition quoted him as
saying that Telecom would approve the merger with Telecom Italia
Mobile, an announcement that would violate Italian law unless
previously made to Consob. Bernabe was forced to backtrack, issuing
a statement that while Telecom Italia had discussed such a plan, a
formal proposal was never made. But officials close to Telecom said
nothing would be excluded from Thursday's discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Telecom Italia controls 60 percent of Telecom Italia Mobile.
</P>
<P>
   The parent company was also shaken by rumors that its chief
financial officer, Fulvio Conti, had resigned over differences with
Bernabe. Officials of Telecom Italia would not comment.
</P>
<P>
   government officials also said that Consob had started an
investigation into possible insider trading in both companies'
shares in the run-up to Olivetti's original bid over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies had reassurances that the government, which took
Telecom Italia public in 1997 and still holds a 3.4 percent stake,
would stay out of the fight.
</P>
<P>
   Frightened by the prospect of lost jobs or a foreign takeover, a
wide range of political leaders had called for the government to
exert its rights to insure that Telecom Italia was not
``dismembered'' or bought by a foreign company. But Carlo Azeglio
Ciampi, whose Treasury Ministry controls the government stake,
rebuffed the calls, saying, ``Telecom is a private company, and its
choices are made by its board.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision not to alter the terms of the bid signaled that
Colaninno expected to be in he battlen for the long haul.
</P>
<P>
   In a $1.4 billion bid in December for an American company,
Cellular Communications International, which held a 10 percent
stake in Omnitel Pronto Italia, Olivetti's mobile phone unit,
Colaninno, made the bid in two stages. It did this at the advice of
investment bankers, raising the stakes each time. This successful
strategy, it appeared, might be what prompted Olivetti to stick
with the original price here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
