<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8163 &Cx1f; gen-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STATES-DELLUMS-NAT     02-24 1313
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-DELLUMS-NAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        DELLUMS' NEW DILEMMA: AVERTING AFRICAN DISASTER
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Mark Stricherz  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Feb. 24 -- At a Congressional Black Caucus seminar
on AIDS recently, a bespectacled, earnest-looking African-American
man poised a question to former Oakland Congressman Ron Dellums.
</P>
<P>
   He asked about Dellums' new cause in life, his AIDS Marshall
Plan for Africa -- a campaign to raise $200 million, from both the
federal government and pharmaceutical companies, to treat AIDS
victims in the southern part of the continent.
</P>
<P>
   ``What about the African Diaspora?'' the man, who identified
himself as Dr. Ware, asked. ``What about helping Africans in
countries where they're living now -- places like Haiti, the United
States, London?''
</P>
<P>
   Dellums, whose interest in Africa dates back at least to 1971,
when he called for sanctions against South Africa, did not give the
answer his conservative critics may have presumed. Though often
branded a hard-core leftist, Dellums assailed the question's
underlying ideology with a bluntness that would have made Newt
Gingrich blush.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about romanticism,'' Dellums, 63, said. ``This is
not about the motherland. This is real. This is about 70 percent of
all newly infected people with HIV living in southern Africa. This
is about 20 million people dying in the next ten years.''
</P>
<P>
   As Dellums sees it, Africa's problem is just as much moral and
political as it is medicinal. Of the 30 million people worldwide
affected by HIV, an estimated 21.5 million of them live in
countries such as South Africa, Zimbabwe, Botswana -- a pandemic on
a scale of the bubonic plague in 17th-century Europe. But, unlike
the situation in the United States, billions of dollars aren't
available in Africa for treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to breach that gap is Dellums' mission. His new job,
actually, is as president of the Atlanta-based Healthcare
International Management, which he took last February after
retiring from a 27-year career in Congress. But the AIDS Marshall
plan, he says, is what sometimes gets him up at 3 a.m., wondering
what more he can do.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, while Dellums concedes that the plan faces an uphill
battle, it may be steeper than even he foresees. Already, several
critics to the proposal have emerged. Clinton administration
officials contend it ought to be spent on prevention, rather than
treatment, while others say that parts of the proposal are
politically unworkable.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the possible reasons Washington could object to the plan,
personal enmity toward Dellums does not appear to be one of them.
Dellums may have compiled a record in Congress as a die-hard
pacifist -- he not only opposed the Gulf War, but economic
sanctions against Iraq -- but it has not diminished the level of
bipartisan admiration for him.
</P>
<P>
   House National Security Chairman Floyd Spence, R-S.C., who
served with then-Chairman Dellums on the committee, said he has
``never served with anyone who did as much as Ron to protect and
promote bipartisanship.'' Rep. Barbara Lee, D-Oakland, goes
further, saying that other members liken Dellums to a ``prophet.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, congressional support for the proposal seems to be
strongest in the Congressional Black Caucus. Caucus Chairman Rep.
James Clyburn, D-S.C., said the plan has ``natural support'' within
the 38-member group, adding that he knows of no members who oppose
it.
</P>
<P>
   Dellums' lobbying of Republicans has been less extensive, he
concedes. But Rep. Mark Foley, R-Fla, who worked with Dellums on
eliminating the B-2 bomber, says he likes parts of the proposal,
and says other possible Republican backers include Rep. Nancy
Johnson, R-Conn., and Mike Castle, R-Del.
</P>
<P>
   Since unexpectedly retiring from Congress last February, Dellums
has sought support for his plan from world leaders and prominent
international officials such as South African President Nelson
Mandela and World Bank President James D. Wolfensohn .
</P>
<P>
   Dellums also said he plans to meet with the heads of
pharmaceutical companies to raise help $100 million, which he
thinks they will do given their reputation for one-sided concern
for the region. And now that the one-year ban on former
representatives lobbying Congress has passed, Dellums will have
unique access to members, such as visiting with them on the House
floor with the hopes of gaining wider support.
</P>
<P>
   Also, to maintain support for the plan, Dellums intends to
recruit help from outside Congress.
</P>
<P>
   His grand idea is for Mandela to lead a board of trustees to
administer the fund. This board, composed of ``distinguished
persons'' from science, religion and politics, would oversee
efforts to secure appropriate drugs, assure healthcare workers are
trained and steer the drugs to where they are needed most. Dellums
anticipates spending at lest $5,000 per person, per year on drug
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   If the plan succeeds, U.S. spending on AIDS programs in South
Africa would increase dramatically. For example, the U.S. Agency
for International Development (USAID), one main government agency
that oversees African AIDS activities, will spend $91 million this
year.
</P>
<P>
   But the bulk of that money goes toward prevention, not
treatment, which is what Dellums wants. ``We focus almost entirely
on sexual transmission, rather than blood treatment,'' said Paul
Delay, chief of the HIV/AIDS division for USAID, adding that buying
condoms is one such program.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when U.S. funding for global AIDS activities has
declined in real dollar terms since 1993, it is perhaps not
surprising that some Clinton administration officials say Dellums'
Marshall plan should go toward prevention programs.
</P>
<P>
   According to Delay, the problem is that sub-Saharan Africa lacks
the necessary infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   ``To try to apply this plan in a setting with none of the lab
settings, none of the roads just doesn't make sense,'' he said.
``The average expenditure on health per person in Africa is less
than $10, and you're talking about spending $3,000 to $5,000 per
person, per year? That's just not feasible.''
</P>
<P>
   Within Congress, opposition to the thrust of Dellums' plan
appears to be equally firm. Staffers from the House Africa
subcommittee said Congress is very unlikely to appropriate $100
million for AIDS programs in Africa, on top of what it is currently
spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, Congress is a bunch of isolationists. They're
worried about their own constituents,'' said one aide, who spoke on
the condition of annonymity. ``The only way you're going to get
this money is if the administration pushes for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, even opponents to Dellums' plan concede weaknesses with
their own arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Delay acknowledges, for example, that 20 million people will die
within the next ten years if no money is spent on treating AIDS in
southern Africa -- a situation he calls ``an extreme tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, support for the plan could blossom if the projected
budget surplus grows, said Clyburn. He notes that, while the
surplus is supposed to $79 billion for this fiscal year, it may
burgeon to $117 billion for next year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Dellums is also banking on contributions from
pharmaceutical companies, which he hopes may pressure Congress to
fund the program.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, despite the opposition, Dellums is no stranger to such
resistance either. On Tuesday, when Congress designated a federal
building on 1300 Clay Street in Oakland the ``Ronald V. Dellums
Federal Building,'' his supporters made note of his support for
causes once-thought to be doomed.
</P>
<P>
   Said Delegate Eleanor Holmes Norton, D-District of Columbia,
``Ron fought for sanctions against South Africa when it was all but
a lost cause, until finally they developed a national and an
international consensus that in fact led to the elimination, the
beginning of the end, of South African apartheid.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
