<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. ATTACKS TARGETS 30 MILES FROM DOWNTOWN BAGHDAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States carried its low-level war against
Iraq to the outskirts of the Iraqi capital, as American fighter
jets attacked two surface-to-air missile sites only 30 miles from
downtown Baghdad, the Pentagon said &UR;  &LR; Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time since the four nights of air and missile
strikes in December that U.S. jets attacked targets so close to
Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   In Baghdad, air-raid sirens sounded shortly after dark and soon
antiaircraft artillery began bursting in the sky, though Pentagon
officials said the U.S. jets never came close enough to the city to
be within range of Iraqi gunners.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon said the strikes occurred just below the 33rd
parallel, within the southern no-flight zone that the United States
and its allies created in 1992 to protect Shi'ite Muslims from
repression by President Saddam Hussein's forces.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq denounced the latest strikes as ``a grave escalation'' and
reported that the attack had killed civilians, although it did not
immediately say how many.
</P>
<P>
   ``This grave escalation indicates the ill intentions against
Iraq,'' said Uday al Tai, head of the official Iraqi news agency,
according to Agence France-Presse. ``And we reaffirm once again
that Iraq does not and never will recognize the so called no-fly
zones imposed on it in an unjust and aggressive manner.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, appearing at a news conference with President
Jerry Rawlings of Ghana, accused Saddam's forces of trying to shoot
down a U.S. or British plane. He said the United States would not
be deterred, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are trying, obviously, for the symbolic victory of
shooting one of these planes down and perhaps trying to intimidate
us from enforcing the no-fly zone, which we're still bound to do
under the United Nations resolution,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, no U.N. resolution created the restricted zones, though
the United States cited resolutions passed after the end of the
Persian Gulf War ended in 1991 to justify creating and later
expanding the zones.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the U.S. and British strikes were taking a toll on
Iraq's air-defense weapons, but he also expressed regret that the
strikes were continuing, saying he wished Saddam would allow the
United Nations to resume its inspections of Iraq's nuclear,
chemical and biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I regret this,'' he said. ``I wish he would stop
doing that. I wish he would make an agreement with the United
Nations to let the inspections go back. We have shown that we are
not interested in hurting the Iraqi people.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday was the fourth consecutive day of strikes. Since
December's bombardment, U.S. and British jets have been steadily
chipping away at Iraq's air defenses whenever confronted by Iraqi
forces. Operating under more aggressive rules approved by Clinton
last month, the pilots have been attacking predetermined targets,
not just those that challenge them directly.
</P>
<P>
   In Wednesday's fighting, Air Force F-15Es and Navy F/A-18s
attacked surface-to-air missile launchers near Al Iskandariyah, on
the edge of the southern no-flight zone after an Iraqi jet entered
the area and Iraqi antiaircraft artillery opened fire. Farther
south, an F-16 fired a radar-seeking missile at a missile site near
Tallil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
