<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sampling to be used for nonelectoral purposes
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Reigniting the partisan controversy over the 2000
census, the Clinton administration plans to count the nation's
population in traditional fashion to allocate congressional seats,
then use scientific methods to arrive at a ``more accurate'' number
for other purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Census Bureau director Kenneth Prewitt said Wednesday that the
traditional population count, which begins April 1, 2000, will be
no better than the troubled 1990 census, which he said missed more
than 4 million people, disproportionately African-American,
Hispanic and poor.
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, the head count will be done to comply with a
Supreme Court ruling last month barring the use of sampling _ a
scientific estimate of the population _ in apportioning the 435
seats in the House of Representatives among the 50 states.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the work will not be then finished,'' Prewitt said at a
news conference. ``Census 2000 will continue its work ... in order
to produce more complete and accurate numbers,'' which could be
used to distribute federal funds or redraw congressional and other
electoral district boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Glavin, president of the Atlanta-based Southeastern
Legal Foundation, promised to file a lawsuit to prevent the
two-tiered approach favored by the Census Bureau. The public
interest law firm initiated the suit that the Supreme Court decided
last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want one set of numbers,'' Glavin said. ``The Census Bureau
is acting rather like the Mafia, one set of books for legitimate
purposes and a second set of crooked books for more sinister
motives.''
</P>
<P>
   Glavin said the court ruling forbids using sampling for
redistricting, but advocates of sampling disagree.
</P>
<P>
   The administration had planned to use sampling for all purposes
until the court decided otherwise. The head count could add up to
$2 billion to the cost of the census, according to some estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt declined to estimate the cost of the 2000 census, noting
only that President Clinton requested less than $5 billion for it
in his latest budget proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction to the census plan was split along party lines.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Dennis Hastert (R-Ill.), a leading critic of
sampling plans, said, ``While congressional Republicans are
committed to developing legal, community-based initiatives to count
everyone in America, I'm disappointed that the Clinton-Gore
administration apparently will not allow the professionals at the
Census Bureau to actually count everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Rep. Carolyn Maloney of New York praised the Census
Bureau for devising ``a way to best comply with the Supreme Court
decision while still getting the most accurate count possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampling probably would add population to solidly Democratic
urban areas at the expense of the more Republican suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt said Wednesday that no method would produce a
``perfectly accurate'' census. But he said, time is running out for
bickering over how to conduct the once-a-decade count.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
