<HEADER>
A8167 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GACLINTON25-COX     02-24 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GACLINTON25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Average Americans push Clinton defense fund to total of $4.5
million
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton used some of Washington's best
lawyers to fight independent counsel Kenneth Starr, and he has
people like William Crumbley, a retired mortgage lender from
McDonough, Ga., to thank for paying his seven-figure legal bills.
</P>
<P>
   Crumbley was one of nearly 50,000 Americans who kicked in
donations ranging from $10 to $10,000 to Clinton's legal defense
fund last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I support President Clinton and have always supported him,''
said Crumbley, who gave Clinton $25. ``Ken Starr and the
Republicans have absolutely been on a witch hunt. It's the radical
right, the extreme right, that wants to drive him out of office,
and I just don't think it's fair.''
</P>
<P>
   In all, Clinton's legal defense fund raised $4.5 million in its
first year, the fund reported Wednesday, mostly in response to more
than 600,000 pieces of direct mail sent out at the height of
Clinton's impeachment battle. From July to December, the fund
raised $2.2 million, about $390,000 in chunks of $10,000, the
highest allowable contribution.
</P>
<P>
   J.B. Fuqua, the retired chairman of Fuqua Enterprises, was among
the 39 donors who gave $10,000. Fuqua said he approached Clinton at
a fund-raiser for Georgia Democratic senatorial hopeful Michael
Coles last summer and told the president he wanted to help him out.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the unfunded liability that he had, I felt that those who
had supported him and had profited from his term should come
forward and put up some money,'' said Fuqua, who lives in Atlanta.
``I have been disappointed in his personal life. We all knew when
he was elected the first time that he had cheated on his wife, but
we elected him anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will need a lot more help if he is to leave the White
House without a crushing legal debt. To date, his lawyers have
submitted bills totalling $9 million. Fund trustees expect there
will be another $1 million in bills stemming from the two months
and a half months in December, January and February when Clinton's
lawyers argued his case before the House, which impeached him Dec.
19, and the Senate, which acquitted him Feb. 12.
</P>
<P>
   The figure does not include the amount the federal government
has spent defending Clinton through the office of the White House
Counsel, which is paid for by taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   About $3.8 million, or 40 percent of the bills submitted so far,
has been paid out of the trust, fund trustees said. The amount
includes $800,000 paid out of Clinton's first legal defense fund,
which was established in 1993 and disbanded in 1997 after trustees
were forced to return more than $600,000 in questionable donations.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's news fund, established by former Arkansas Sen. David
Pryor, has faced no ethical or legal challenges. Fund trustees said
the fund-raising pace set last year signaled that the fund might
raise $10 million by the time Clinton leaves office _ provided that
he faces no new legal obligations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is reachable,'' said Anthony Essaye, the fund's executive
director.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of well-known names from Hollywood and the
entertainment industry were among the big donors.
</P>
<P>
   Lew Wasserman, the former chairman of Universal Studios, and a
family member each contributed $10,000, along with singer Tony
Bennett and Don Henley, a member of the Eagles band. Actor Robert
DeNiro and author Stephen King each gave $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   But the vast majority of contributions came from people like
Crumbley and others who contributed $100 or less. About 95 percent
of the contributions came in donations of less than $100, and in
response to direct mail solicitations.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
