<SLUG> BC-BBO-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A MEMO ON UMPIRES STRIKES A FUNNY BONE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By   HARVEY ARATON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ ``Memo?'' Rickey Henderson said, waving a
bat inside the Mets' clubhouse Wednesday. ``What memo?''
</P>
<P>
   It was the official Bud Selig-stamped memo that the
commissioner's office sent recently to its 30 teams, promising
stricter enforcement of the strike zone this season, including the
strike above the belt, the kind Henderson has long been accustomed
to letting pass on his way to first base with a walk.
</P>
<P>
   He, like the umpires, hadn't been informed of any memo, and
snickered when I told him of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you say you're going to make all the umpires call the
game the same way?'' Henderson said. ``Every pitcher is different.
Every player is different. Every umpire is different.''
</P>
<P>
   So is every official in every sport. What is traveling? What is
offensive holding? What is a high strike zone?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's whatever the umpire that day says it is,'' Henderson
said. ``It's whatever he sees, or thinks he sees. As long as he's
consistent with it, it's up to you as the player to adjust.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, umpires are not very consistent on balls and strikes,
which is a problem for everyone except those making a living on
instant replay. Umpires have bad days, same as players.
</P>
<P>
   Some aren't as good as most. That is a matter of competency, not
rule enforcement. If one continually distorts the spirit of the
strike zone, by all means, make him stop.
</P>
<P>
   But the critics who howled about pitch-calling during the last
post-season _ to whom the commissioner's office seems to be
overreacting _ make the sweeping charge that the umpires won't call
the high strike and will call the wide strike.
</P>
<P>
   Why umpires would have arbitrarily decided in a secret meeting
at a terrorist camp deep inside Afghanistan to shrink one part of
the strike zone and grow another is one of the unsolved mysteries
of the late 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strike zone is the strike zone,'' Richie Phillips, the
umpire's union director, said.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it is, Henderson, after two decades in the majors, is
not complaining about it. From his pronounced crouch, he has walked
more than anyone in history except Ted Williams and Babe Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say I'm in my deep crouch, like this,'' Henderson said,
bending over, halfway to the carpet. ``Then my high strike is about
right here.''
</P>
<P>
   He placed his hand on his chest, just under the breast. Then he
held the bat up again, but in somewhat less of a crouch.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I straighten up, even a little, my strike zone changes,''
he said. ``Then the high strike is right over the belt.''
</P>
<P>
   With the bat back at his side, serving as a cane, Henderson
added: ``The interpretation of the strike zone, man, that's been
part of baseball for years and years. That's what baseball's all
about.''
</P>
<P>
   People just seem determined these days to legislate against or
eliminate the human element of judgment. The howling over the
umpiring last season carried right into pro football. Somehow,
deserving teams made the playoffs and the unquestioned best teams
managed to overcame the evil officials to win the World Series and
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   I can make no case for pro basketball's traveling travesty, but
that's not the officials as much it is part of the league's
marketing strategy (imagine what the scores would be if the players
didn't walk). The high strike, especially in the National League,
was obviously redefined years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lower strike is something that's just part of baseball
evolution,'' Steve Phillips, the Mets' general manager, said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the rule book, a pitch two inches above the waist
should be called a strike. We're talking about inches, and dipping,
swerving balls thrown into the high 90s, and baseball has the nerve
to imply that the umpires have collectively been failing to enforce
the rules?
</P>
<P>
   This, from a sport that rightly revels in its variety of stadium
configurations, features games on grass and carpet and makes little
effort to resolve the designated hitter issue.
</P>
<P>
   In a knee-jerk and none-too-union brotherly statement, the Major
League Baseball Players Association said it supported the memo. But
Phillips said he wasn't about to assign a team to study its
implications, while Bobby Valentine did everything but roll on the
floor laughing in his manager's office when asked if he would read
the memo to his team.
</P>
<P>
   Figure on baseball being as blind to this act of administrative
grandstanding as an umpire can be on any given call.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
