<HEADER>
A8193 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-H     02-24 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BLINEBURYCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ It wasn't as if Jeff Bagwell would sit bolt
upright in the middle of the night haunted by the memories,
trembling in fear at dreams of another Kevin Brown sinker, bathed
in cold sweat at the mere thought of one more helpless playoff
at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think about it, sure,'' he said. ``You think about it
while the rest of the playoffs and the World Series are going on. I
couldn't help but think during the World Series that we were the
only team in baseball that could really have given the Yankees a
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were the best team in the National League last year. But we
didn't get the job done again in the playoffs, and you have to
accept that and move on. If you dwell on the loss, it's going to
keep you down. What you have to do is make a commitment to get
better, make a change, even if it's just a small one.''
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell's change here in the early part of spring training has
been to work on a slightly different batting stroke that he hopes
will produce big results. As usual in baseball, it's the little
things.
</P>
<P>
   He still stands up there in the batter's box with his feet
spread so wide apart that you'd think he was a bull rider at the
rodeo. He still squats low in a crouch and holds the bat straight
up in the air like an exclamation point. The difference is in the
location of his hands, which are now held higher _ around shoulder
level, rather than down around his belt _ in hope of eliminating
some of the hitch from his swing and producing more line drives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I thought about as far back as the beginning of
last season when I was struggling from the start,'' Bagwell said.
``I talked about it all year long with (hitting coach) Tom McCraw.
We came to the conclusion that it was something I needed to work on
but not during the middle of the year, because that wouldn't have
been fair to the team. They needed me to be hitting, not
experimenting. I just knew there had to be a better way for me.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the talk of his troubles last season, Bagwell still
finished with a .304 batting average, 34 home runs and 111 RBIs.
For a lot of players, that would have been a career season. But for
him, a fiercely competitive perfectionist, it was a reason to go
back to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like I've said about Cammy (Ken Caminiti), the worst
thing that ever happened to him in terms of everybody's
expectations was his winning the MVP in '96,'' Bagwell said. ``Once
you do that, put up those kinds of numbers, it's what people think
you should do all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell, of course, was the National League Most Valuable Player
in 1994, and while there may be some pressure to live up to that
level coming from the outside, it is not close to the weight of the
burden he puts on himself.
</P>
<P>
   When he goes into a slump at the plate, you can read the
frustration in his face, feel the anguish in his voice. Which is
why you know that having hit just .115 (3-for-26) in the playoffs
the past two years against Atlanta and San Diego has him ready to
do anything at all to prevent it from happening a third straight
time. Including a willingness to tamper _ even in a small way _
with the swing that has made him one of the most feared and
productive hitters in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not looking at it like it's such a big thing,'' Bagwell
said. ``Carl Yastrzemski used to change his swing every year. I
know, because I'd change every year with him when I was a kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Until finally, somewhere, Bagwell's stance evolved into the
crouching, wide-open, hands-low trademark that made you wonder how
he ever got his bat on the ball, let alone hit it out of the park.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where it came from,'' he said. ``I just kind of
settled into the whole thing. You know, moving my front foot back
instead of stepping into the ball and all that other crazy stuff. I
do everything just about the opposite of what they teach you. But
no manager or coach ever tried to get me to change, because I
always hit.''
</P>
<P>
   What bothered Bagwell last season was the nature of his slumps.
When he'd had problems in the past, they usually revolved around
being unable to see the ball properly. Last season, however, he was
always seeing the ball but not always making solid contact. Too
many times, he said, the up-and-down path of his hands produced a
frustrating grounder to third instead of a line-drive single.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd see Craig (Biggio) and Moises (Alou) with a flatter swing,
starting up high, and they'd hit the line drives. It just seems to
make sense for me to try it. Maybe I can hit .300 again and drive
in 100 runs the old way. But maybe if I do this, I'll be able to
get that one more hit this time in the playoffs. You try to do the
little things.''
</P>
<P>
   Which often have a way of making a big difference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
