<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-GRAMMY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEMALE ARTISTS LEAD PARADE TO PODIUM AT GRAMMY AWARDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Budgeted as TV-Grammy)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ I am woman, hear me roar _ the famous pop refrain
from Helen Reddy _ was the overwhelming theme at Wednesday night's
Grammy awards at the Shrine Auditorium. Madonna started the parade
by winning best pop album for ``Ray of Light,'' with Lauryn Hill
and Shania Twain also taking the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   The traditional Grammy bickering was at a minimum during the
afternoon, when the majority of the Grammys were awarded in
pre-telecast ceremonies. Deserving artists won to an impressive
degree _ and most of them were women.
</P>
<P>
   Hill got off to a fast start with three Grammys, dominating the
R &AMP; B field by winning best R &AMP; B album (``The Miseducation of
Lauryn Hill''), best female R &AMP; B vocal performance, and best R &AMP; B
song (a songwriter award) for ``Doo Wop (That Thing),'' a track
from her album.
</P>
<P>
   Country phenomenon Twain was right behind her with two awards
for best country vocal and best country song for ``You're Still the
One,'' which also was a huge Top 40 pop hit, signaling country's
renewed crossover potential.
</P>
<P>
   The staying power of the ``Titanic'' soundtrack was felt again,
as Canadian chanteuse Celine Dion won best pop female vocal
performance for the megahit ``My Heart Will Go On.'' It also won
for best song, the award going to composers James Horner and Will
Jennings.
</P>
<P>
   Madonna, who described herself last week as ``the Susan Lucci of
the Grammys'' because she's often been shunned, won the new best
dance recording award for ``Ray of Light.'' The song also was
represented in the best short form music video award for director
Jonas Akerlund.
</P>
<P>
   Boston-based artists fared well, with Aerosmith winning for best
rock performance by a duo or group with vocal for the risque
``Pink,'' though the group lost in a shocking upset in the
counterpart pop category, where their No. 1 song ``I Don't Want to
Miss a Thing'' (from the ``Armaggedon'' soundtrack) was beaten by
an obscure Brian Setzer Orchestra track, ``Jump Jive an' Wail.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Burton, the jazz vibist who doubles as vice president of
Berklee College of Music, shared best jazz instrumental solo with
Chick Corea for ``Rumbata.'' Said Burton afterward: ``This is my
fourth Grammy and my third with Chick. This is especially
important, because I've had a Grammy in each of the last four
decades, so this was my last chance in the '90s!'' And longtime
Cambridge resident Pat Metheny won two Grammys, also in the jazz
field.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Pops conductor Keith Lockhart, who MC'd part of the
afternoon program, missed out on his first Grammy bid, in the new
classical crossover category. His ``The Celtic Album'' lost to
``Soul of the Tango: The Music of Astor Piazzola,'' by Lockhart's
friend cellist Yo-Yo Ma. It was Ma's 13th career Grammy.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart expressed satisfaction at the creation of the crossover
award (``It makes sense because we've always been a genre without a
country''), and he was thrilled to give the best instrumental
composition award to Bela Fleck and the Flecktones, who have played
with the Pops.
</P>
<P>
   Country artist Vince Gill set a record by winning a Grammy for
his 10th year in a row. It was for best country instrumental
performance for ``A Soldier's Joy,'' an award shared with Randy
Scruggs. Gill has also amassed awards for vocal performance,
instrumental performance, collaborations, and songwriting. ``I'm
glad to be recognized for the diversity, which is what I've tried
to do with my career,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Chieftains won their sixth Grammy, this time in the
traditional folk category, for ``Long Journey Home.'' Leader Paddy
Moloney, who has a son at MIT, said he was headed to Boston for the
next few days and may turn up in a local Irish tavern or two.
</P>
<P>
   The best contemporary folk award went to Texas whirlwind Lucinda
Williams, for ``Car Wheels on a Gravel Road'', which has factored
into as many Top 10 lists this year as Hill's groundbreaking
hip-hop/soul CD.
</P>
<P>
   In the rock field, Alanis Morissette's ``Uninvited'' won best
rock song, while best hard-rock performance went to Page &AMP; Plant's
``Most High.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
