<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush forms exploratory committee
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush has decided to form an
exploratory committee that will allow him to begin raising money
for a possible presidential candidacy, according to several people
close to the governor.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is expected to announce the formation of the committee
within two weeks. If he decides to run for president, he has said
that he wouldn't formally announce his candidacy until after the
legislative session ends on May 31.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly, Bush continues to be noncommittal about his
intentions. ``I will have an announcement here later on that will
begin to clarify whether or not the answer is yes, no or maybe,''
Bush said Wednesday, after another round of private talks at the
Governor's Mansion about his potential presidential race. Despite
the reports about an exploratory committee, he insisted that
``maybe'' is still a possible answer.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said last week that he was ``warming to the task'' of
seeking the presidency. During a four-day Washington weekend, Bush
held several private political sessions in conjunction with the
National Governors Association meetings.
</P>
<P>
   For months, the governor has said his decision would be based on
family considerations as well as whether he thought he could make a
difference for America. And, also for months, he has been calling
in a variety of political, policy and fund-raising experts to offer
input.
</P>
<P>
   Already in place is a team of policy experts that Bush said
could wind up as part of a campaign team. ``I would characterize
them as conservative thinkers,'' said Bush. He said the top
advisers helping him gear up for a potential presidential race are
Harvard professor and former Federal Reserve Board governor Larry
Lindsey for economic issues, Indianapolis Mayor Stephen Goldsmith
for domestic issues and former Stanford University Provost
Condoleeza Rice for international issues. Rice is a Bush family
friend and helped former President Bush compile his recently
published book, ``A World Transformed.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bush said Paul Wolfowitz, dean of Johns Hopkins
University's Paul H. Nitze School of Advanced International Studies
in Washington, D.C., is also advising him on international affairs.
Wolfowitz served in the Reagan and the Bush White House and has
been an outspoken critic of President Clinton's foreign policies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remain deeply skeptical that President Clinton has learned
about foreign policy,'' he said when Clinton named Madeleine
Albright as secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   Another foreign policy expert, Dick Cheney, who served as
secretary of defense for President Bush, met with the younger Bush
here Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did we discuss?'' said Bush. ``Guess. Dick Cheney is a
friend of mine. It's not the first time he has been down here. It
won't be the last time he is down here. He is a person whose
judgment I rely upon a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   In Independence, Mo., on Tuesday for a display on President
Franklin Roosevelt at the Harry S. Truman Library and Museum,
former President Gerald Ford said Bush is the GOP's best shot at
recapturing the White House because he is not straying too far to
the right.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're not going to win if you retain the policies of the hard
right,'' said Ford. ``The Democrats lost with hard-left policies. I
think we can win if we're wise enough to go down the middle.
</P>
<P>
   ``George W. Bush is talking a lot more moderately than his
father,'' he added. ``(Republicans) aren't going to win on one
issue. They've got to have a broader view.'' The younger Bush has
met with a number of Republican fund-raisers in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had people from all over the country in today, just like we
do most every day,'' he said after the lunch meeting at the
Governor's Mansion. ``This was not a specific meeting with a
specific group. This was people who were interested in my
candidacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those at the lunch were Colorado Republicans Gov. Bill
Owen and U.S. Rep. Scott McInnis, both of whom said they urged Bush
to run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark my words,'' said McInnis, ``if he makes the decision (to
run), he'll be the next president and this state will have a lot to
be proud of.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, Bush received letters from Republican state
lawmakers in Massachusetts who want him to run.
</P>
<P>
   ``We urge you to step forward and then run forward as a
Republican candidate for president who has clearly mastered the art
of governing and winning,'' the state senators said in their
letter.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts Gov. Paul Cellucci has been a leading booster of a
Bush candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said no decision had been made whether to seek federal
funds if he runs. Candidates who take matching money must abide by
spending limits, limit personal money used on their campaigns and
submit to federal audits.
</P>
<P>
   FEC spokeswoman Kelly Huff said Wednesday that the decision
whether to accept federal money does not have to be made before
forming an exploratory committee.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
