<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8201 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRIVE-PIX25-COX     02-24 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRIVE-PIX25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    S. Carolinians oppose sale of drivers' pictures
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENWOOD, S.C. _ Is Big Brother lurking in the lingerie
department at Wal-Mart, or in frozen foods over at the Winn-Dixie?
Not yet, and state Rep. Jim Klauber wants to keep it that way.
</P>
<P>
   So do thousands of other South Carolinians, judging by the
state's controversial _ and confusing _ sale of driver's license
photos, a dispute to be aired today during a legislative hearing in
Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public in South Carolina is irate,'' said Klauber, a
32-year-old Republican from Greenwood who is chairman of the House
special laws subcomittee.
</P>
<P>
   In what's expected to be a long and contentious public forum,
the panel plans to question officials of Image Data, a fraud
prevention company ensnarled in South Carolina's intensifying
debate over privacy in this era of free-flowing information.
</P>
<P>
   Klauber is among legislators who are suspicious of Image Data
because it failed to disclose it had received nearly $1.5 million
in start-up funds from the Secret Service, the federal agency
responsible for combating wire fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ``When has the government ever used information just for what
they said they would use it for?'' Klauber said. ``Conceivably,
they could track you buying shoes at J.C. Penney and a shirt at
Wal-Mart. ... People are fearful.''
</P>
<P>
   Image Data officials said such a scenario is preposterous, and
it blamed public officials for stirring confusion among South
Carolinians.
</P>
<P>
   In the controversy's wake, state legislators are considering
bills that would ban the sale of driver's license information. This
week, the company sued South Carolina Attorney General Charles
Condon, who has sought to void the state Department of Public
Safety's sale of driver's license photos to Image Data.
</P>
<P>
   The company said Condon is waging a ``personal vendetta''
against Image Data and its president, Bob Houevener. In a recent
appearance on a national TV news program, Condon referred to
Houvener as ``Big Brother Bob.'' The attorney general is seeking
federal documents related to the Secret Service grant in hopes of
making a perjury case against Houvener.
</P>
<P>
   ``These actions have been taken to the point of damaging the
reputation of our president and our company,'' Image Data vice
president Lorna Christie said.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in Nashua, N.H., three years ago, the small, privately
owned company recently paid $5,000 for 3.5 million South Carolina
driver's license photos. It also bought drivers' images from
Florida and Colorado in its effort to build a national data base to
help retailers and other businesses prevent check and credit card
fraud.
</P>
<P>
   The governors of Florida and Colorado are trying to stop the
sale of driver's license information.
</P>
<P>
   Image Data hasn't sought a deal with the Georgia Department of
Public Safety, agency spokesman Gordy Wright said. The state's
privacy act prevents the agency from releasing driver's license
photos or driving records to third parties, such as Image Data,
without the individual's written permission, Wright said. The
company is testing its fraud-prevention system in several stores in
South Carolina. When a customer writes a check, the clerk processes
it through Image Data's ``True ID'' terminal.
</P>
<P>
   The device matches information on the check with the company's
data base, and it sends back a photographic image of the customer
authorized to write the check. If the photograph doesn't match the
customer's appearance, the cashier can stop the transaction, or
seek to verify the customer's identity in another way. Christie
said the system is safe from computer hackers, and the company will
not sell its information to marketing companies or provide it to
government agencies. The South Carolina Merchants Association has
endorsed Image Data's system to curb the damage of check fraud,
estimated at $200 million a year in the state.
</P>
<P>
   But here in Greenwood, a city of 21,000 people where traditional
values are intertwined with textiles, some people resent the idea
that their driver's license photos might someday appear on a screen
in the check-out line at local stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had rather take my wallet out of my pocket and show my
picture rather than have it come up on a computer,'' said Blake
Barfield, a Greenwood retiree. ``Nobody needs to have my
photograph.''
</P>
<P>
   Countered 48-year-old Gene Pinson, director of the Greenwood
County Office of Veterans Affairs, ``It is a lot of hullabaloo over
nothing. In this high-tech age, they can find out anything about
you they want.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Houvener explained his company's business in
meetings with South Carolina officials and in a Feb. 3 appearance
before the House subcommittee that was reviewing the deal. Condon
sued last month to void the sale of driver's licence information,
but a circuit judge denied the request. Condon then appealed to the
South Carolina Supreme Court, hoping the case will be sent back to
a lower court with orders to force Houvener to answer questions
about the Secret Service funding.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, congressional leaders, including Sen. Ernest Hollings
(D-S.C.), who helped arrange the federal grant, said they
envisioned Image Data's technology being used to combat terrorism
and immigration abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Such heavy-duty crime fighting goes far beyond Image Data's
claim that its system would only be used to prevent check and
credit card fraud. Houvener said he did not try to slip the Secret
Service grant past South Carolina officials. None asked him about
it, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
