<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8203 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JASPER-SENTENCE-HNS &LR;      02-24 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-SENTENCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACIST KILLER DESERVES DEATH PENALTY, SAY BLACK JASPER RESIDENTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See JASPER-TRIAL and JASPER-T-SHIRTS) 
(Eds.: Cloria Young is cq) 
 
By ALLAN TURNER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ As jurors heard testimony Wednesday that could
send white supremacist John William ``Bill'' King to the Texas
death chamber, some local black residents advocated ``eye for an
eye'' vengeance for the man convicted in the racially motivated
murder of James Byrd Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Such pro-death penalty views are atypical of African-Americans,
who traditionally have felt that the ultimate punishment falls
unfairly on blacks.
</P>
<P>
   While many expressed ambivalence about capital punishment, some
felt that justice cried out for it.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors are expected to begin deliberating King's punishment
Thursday. Because he was convicted of capital murder in the slaying
of Byrd, the 24-year-old ex-con can be sentenced to life in prison
or death.
</P>
<P>
   If sentenced to die, King would be the only white inmate in
Texas facing execution for the murder of a black man.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, black residents of Jasper said King's sentencing
is taking place in a racially charged atmosphere. One man, Billy
Floyd Larkin, warned that violence might erupt if the killer's life
is spared.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are going to burn Jasper down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But that prediction was quickly discounted by others who argued
that violence could have resulted only if King had been acquitted
of murder. Once in prison, they suggested, King likely will be
targeted by hostile black inmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either way he's probably going to die,'' one woman observed.
</P>
<P>
   To Butch Adams, a quick, painless death isn't cruel enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The needle is too easy,'' Adams insisted. ``Give him 99 years
and a dog day. Let him think about what he did.''
</P>
<P>
   And some were opposed to capital punishment, even in this most
brutal of cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two wrongs don't make a right,'' said one woman who didn't
want her name used. ``You shouldn't take what you can't give, and
you can't give life.''
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Spikes said she had just ``turned it over to the hands
of God and prayed for him to do what's right.''
</P>
<P>
   Most questioned, though, favored execution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it should be eye for eye,'' said Cloria Young, who
immediately was shushed by friends shocked at the violence of her
opinion. ``He killed the man.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Adams, another Jasper resident, asserted, ``Normally, I
don't believe in execution, but he needs to be executed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is too easy. He sort of needs to be tortured some
first. He needs to be confronted with the crime scene every day he
is alive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He done made history,'' added Johnny Bronson, alluding to
King's written contention that, regardless of the trial's outcome,
he had struck a historic blow for white supremacy. ``Now kill him.
Hang him to a tree.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Way I feel about it,'' scoffed Glenn Bronson, ``is why don't
they just let him move in with us? Let him live here. We'll feed
him and everything. If he's guilty, why do we have to feed him,
doctor him, fix his teeth? It'll cost the state $2 million or $3
million.''
</P>
<P>
   Some residents said it was the brutality of the crime that
prompted them to support capital punishment for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   A national survey released last May found that black support of
capital punishment may be growing. From 1974 to 1996, the poll by
the University of Chicago's National Opinion Center indicated that
the number of blacks favoring the death penalty rose from 40
percent to 57 percent. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   That has not been the case in Texas, however. A Scripps-Howard
Texas Poll earlier this year showed that only 46 percent of blacks
endorse the death penalty, compared with 81 percent of whites.
</P>
<P>
   The perception of the justice system in Texas may feed the
misgivings blacks have about capital punishment. Texas' death row
has 59 African-Americans convicted of murdering whites.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Texas prison observers know of no white man
ever executed for the murder of a black.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Houston State University criminal justice professor James
Marquart, who co-authored a recent book examining capital
punishment, suggested cross-race murders are rare. The larger
number of blacks convicted of killing whites, he said, results in
part, from the type of crimes blacks commit _ armed robberies, for
instance.
</P>
<P>
   Typical of Jasper blacks questioned about King's pending
sentencing were Ronnie and Deann Armstrong. It was their fourth
wedding anniversary party that Byrd had attended the night he was
offered a ride home and wound up being chained to a pickup and
dragged to his death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, I am opposed to the death penalty,'' Deann
Armstrong said. ``The reason is that many innocent people, innocent
black people, have been convicted of murders ... But when a crime
is this brutal _ and there is no doubt of King's guilt _ I say the
punishment should match the crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say that even if the suspect were black.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronnie Armstrong, who said he had driven two intoxicated guests
home from the party but had not seen Byrd leave on foot, said he
was in favor of execution because of the crime's brutality and
King's lack of remorse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't do a dog the way they did him,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Armstrongs _ as did other Jasper blacks _ suggested the
crime occurred in an atmosphere of racial injustice. And, Deann
Armstrong said, violence in the community might have been a
possibility had King not been convicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``But justice has been served,'' she said. ``If he gets life, he
may hope for death. Either way, he's probably going to die.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
