<SLUG> BC-KAMPALA-MAYOR2-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KAMAPLA MAYOR   TO SERVE 15 MONTHS IN US FRAUD CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATRICIA NEALON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In halting English, the man dubbed ``the George
Washington of Kampala `` invoked the names he'd pulled from the
history books: Gandhi, Nelson Mandela, John F. Kennedy and Martin
Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   But Nasser Ntge Sebaggala lingered longest on one name in
particular, the one whose crimes and causes he thought most closely
tracked his own: James Michael Curley.
</P>
<P>
   If the legendary Boston mayor could be pardoned after serving
time in federal prison for mail fraud -- and return triumphantly to
the mayor's seat -- perhaps US District Judge Reginald C. Lindsay
could do the same for Sebaggala, the first democratically-elected
mayor of Uganda's capital city, Kampala, who was convicted in
December of eight charges, including bank fraud and lying to US
Customs agents.
</P>
<P>
   Or, if an outright pardon wasn't possible, maybe a just a short
prison sentence, like the six months Sebaggala's lawyer, Paul V.
Kelly, had suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``His case is similar to mine,'' Sebaggala, speaking alternately
in English and his native Lugandan, said of Boston's popular
political rogue. ``I seek forgiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindsay, cautioning that Curley wasn't a ``real good example''
of a role model, nonetheless did cut in half the 30-month sentence
recommended by the prosecution, ordering Sebaggala, 51, to prison
for 15 months.
</P>
<P>
   But he did so, not because Sebaggala's continued absence from
the mayor's office could destabilize a fledgling democracy -- as
Kelly had argued - but because Sebaggala was the sole support of
his elderly blind mother and two young sons, circumstances he
termed ``extraordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   The burden to safequard Ugandan democracy, ``should not fall on
me,'' said Lindsay, pointing out that it was Sebaggala's foray into
criminality and subsequent conviction that threatened the stability
of his hometown. Besides the 15-month sentence, Sebaggala must
repay $44,000 to the bank he defrauded and pay a $10,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Sebaggala's political advisor Matthias Nsubuga called
the sentence ``a political disaster.'' Under a deal worked out at
home, Sebaggala could hold on to his office as long as he was
sentenced to no more than 9 months in prison. He has been in
custody -- either under house arrest or in prison -- since he was
arrested at John F. Kennedy Airport in New York last June, one
month after he took office. In his absence, the deputy mayor has
been in charge.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the 15-month sentence, Sebaggala might be out in time,
but it will be ``close to the line,'' Kelly said. He will get
credit for the time he's been in prison since December awaiting
sentencing, as well as time off for good behavior, perhaps reducing
his actual sentence to about 10 months.
</P>
<P>
   Nsubuga was among a contigent of more than a dozen supporters,
both from Uganda and the Boston area, who attended Wednesday's
two-hour sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   The trial, which ended with Sebaggala's conviction Dec. 4, drew
the attention of Ugandans here and abroad. Last fall, 40,000 of
Sebaggala's political supporters signed a petition urging that he
be freed pending trial.
</P>
<P>
   Ugandan politics even seeped into what was a straightforward
fraud case. There were references to Sebaggala's beatings and
harassment at the hands of former Ugandan strongman Idi Amin, and
to the fact that his children had been granted political asylum in
the United States because of their father's political activities.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, jurors were unswayed by suggestions of an
international political conspiracy. Rather, they were convinced by
a paper trial, including deposit slips, letters and doctored checks
with erasure marks.
</P>
<P>
   Sebaggala's trouble began on June 13, 1998 at Kennedy Airport,
where he was charged with lying to customs officials in Boston when
he entered the country on an earlier trip the previous January. He
was also charged with misstating the amount of traveler's checks --
$108,000 in all -- bundled in packages in his suitcase.
</P>
<P>
   Two days later, a federal grand jury in Boston charged
Sebaggala, who owned a foreign currency exchange in Uganda, with
depositing four stolen and altered checks into an account at
BankBoston.
</P>
<P>
   One check, originally made out to another party for $400, was
changed to $44,000 and made payable to Sebaggalla, according to
evidence presented at trial. Another check, originally for 99
cents, was changed to $39,000 and made payable to Sebaggala.
</P>
</TEXT>
