<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SONY-DIGITAL-MUSIC-280&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONY TO PROPOSE PROTECTION PLAN FOR DIGITAL MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Responding to the growing threat of digital music piracy via the
Internet, Sony Corp. plans to propose a new copy protection scheme
Thursday designed to enable the recording industry to sell music
safely, both online and on digital formats like CDs and audio DVDs.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is the first such scheme to be submitted to an
industry standards group, the Secure Digital Music Initiative,
which was established in January by the Recording Industry
Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   The new scheme consists of two separate copy protection systems,
Magicgate and OpenMG, both of which require special hardware
systems for scrambling music files before they are sold and
unscrambling them for listeners.
</P>
<P>
   Magicgate will embed a special chip in each recorder and
playback device. OpenMG, which is intended for personal computers
and related devices, will require that consumers purchase a
hardware device known as a dongle, which will attach to a personal
computer's serial port. The dongle will ensure that an encrypted
music file be copied by an approved digital recording device before
it can be played.
</P>
<P>
   Sony said it had also developed a third copy-protection system
known as Super Magicgate, which is intended to be a long-term
solution to the business problems presented by copy-protection
schemes. Such an approach might permit a consumer to listen to an
unlimited amount of music for a single subscription fee.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswomen for the recording institute said Wednesday that
the standards group planned to meet Friday in Hollywood and that 90
companies had expressed an interest in joining the initiative. She
said the group expected other proposals besides the Sony plan.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The recording industry has been reeling in recent months as
consumers have begun routinely using a technology known as MP3 to
share digital, compressed music files that can be played on a
personal computer or recorded as CD's.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the institute unsuccessfully sued Diamond Multimedia
after it introduced a tiny portable player known as the Rio that
permits a computer user to get an MP3 file from the Internet and
then listen to it anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   And many consumer electronics industry analysts believe that the
emergence of the Internet and inexpensive digital copying systems
presents a profound threat to the existing system of music
distribution on compact discs.
</P>
<P>
   Already, a number of musicians have begun to break ranks with
the studios and are distributing their music directly via the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a tsunami headed toward the recording industry,''
said Rick Doherty, the president of Envisioneering, a consulting
firm for the industry in Seaford, N.Y. He said the danger facing
the industry is that it was attempting to make it more complicated
for consumers to listen to music at the very time that the Internet
was dramatically lowering the barriers to digital music.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a marvelous reflection of everything that is good
about the Internet, and the world is voting with its keyboards,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the industry may succeed in erecting technical
copyright barriers around music recorded in studios, Doherty said
that it would face a growing challenge from musicians who retain
control over their live performances.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the standards group, five record companies
announced Feb. 8 that they were joining IBM to conduct a market
trial of a system that permits distribution of full-length,
CD-quality recordings to consumers in an encrypted format. The
music companies included BMG, EMI, Sony Music, Universal Music and
Warner Music.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-99 2116EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990224.0436 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8207 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRUGSTORE.COM-520&AMP;ADD     02-24 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUGSTORE.COM-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW WEB SITE TO BE AN ONLINE PHARMACY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Does Internet surfing give you a headache? Now a new site,
backed by Amazon.com, wants to sell you aspirin along with
prescription drugs and other over-the-counter health and beauty
products.
</P>
<P>
   After establishing itself as the most successful bookstore on
the World Wide Web, Amazon has been moving quickly to become a
full-service electronic mall. It offers music and videos itself,
and its new ``shop the Web'' service offers links to dozens of
other online merchants.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon, which owns 46 percent of Drugstore.com, will promote the
new site with links throughout its service and through e-mail to
its customers. But the two stores will be otherwise separate. Thus,
a flu sufferer will not be able, in one transaction, to order
decongestant and a novel.
</P>
<P>
   Drugstore.com, which is to start business Thursday, is hardly
counting on Amazon for its customers and has bought promotional
space on popular Internet services, including America Online, Yahoo
and Excite.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon's involvement was orchestrated by John Doerr, the
influential venture capitalist at Kleiner Perkins Caufield &AMP; Byers,
who had been an early backer of both companies. Last summer, Doerr
persuaded Jeff Bezos, Amazon's chief executive, to invest in
Drugstore and to serve on its board.
</P>
<P>
   The companies declined to say the amount of Amazon's investment.
But they did say that Drugstore.com has raised $60 million, and
that Amazon owns 46 percent of the shares outstanding, though
employee stock options will dilute that holding to 40 percent.
Bezos declined to say if Amazon has investments in other
electronic-commerce companies.
</P>
<P>
   So far, few sites have sold drugs and beauty products online,
though many smaller sites sell vitamins and nutritional
supplements. But the stakes are huge. Drugs and cosmetics are a
$150 billion-a-year market in the United States, more than seven
times the market for books.
</P>
<P>
   Nicole Vanderbilt, an electronic-commerce analyst at Jupiter
Communications, estimated that $66 million of health and beauty
products would be sold online this year. By 2002, she estimated
that online sales in the category would be $1.2 billion _ 3 percent
of the overall market. By contrast in that year, she estimated that
11 percent of books would be sold on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Building an online pharmacy is difficult because of the
complexity of making it fast and easy to use for buying a large
number of small items. So far sites offering groceries over the
Internet have had disappointing results, though they face the
additional challenge of handling perishable goods. And Wal-Mart,
which originally had emphasized staples on its large Internet site,
has changed to focus on bigger-ticket items like electronics.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, the Internet cannot help people who need
prescriptions immediately for an acute condition. There is a
thriving mail-order pharmacy business, now accounting for 13
percent of the market, for drugs that people take on a regular
basis. But the Internet sites may not be able to tap into all of
that market because many managed care plans have exclusive
relationships with mail-order pharmacies.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Despite these challenges, a number of other companies are vying
to serve as the pharmacist to cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Soma.com began in January and is emphasizing the prescription
drug market. Planet Rx, backed by two other top Silicon Valley
venture funds _ Benchmark Capital and Sequoia Capital _ is to open
in a few days.
</P>
<P>
   William Razzouk, chief executive of Planet Rx, said it would
emphasize information and communities of users built around a
series of specific Web sites like Cancer.com.
</P>
<P>
   The major drugstore chains have been slow to enter the market.
Drug Emporium, a regional chain based in Powell, Ohio, does sell
some products on its Web site. And Rite Aid and General Nutrition
have announced plans to open a site in the fall to sell drugs and
vitamins. Rite Aid is already selling $1 million a month in
prescription refills that its customers order online and pick up in
their local stores.
</P>
<P>
   Marie Griffin, editor in chief of Drug Store News, said Internet
sales were unlikely to be a threat to the big chains.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a lot of categories, people go to the Web because it is
more convenient,'' Ms. Griffin added. ``But there is no more
convenient retail outlet than a drugstore.'' Drugstores also
disproportionally serve older people, who are the most reluctant to
shop online, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Drugstore.com hopes to compensate for this by exploiting the
benefits of the Internet. The site will carry 15,000 items, three
times the stock of the average chain drugstore. And it will store a
record of its customers' purchasers, making regular shopping
faster.
</P>
<P>
   It will also have articles written by its staff, giving advice
on which products to buy. Unlike Planet RX, it will not feature
comments by users.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want teen-agers writing about which condoms they
liked,'' said Peter Neupert, the company's chief executive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
