<DOCNO> NYT19990224.0439 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8210 &Cx1f; ttc-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC- &LR; 20DATES-REVIEW &UR; --LAD     02-24 0480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
LONELY GUY FINDS LOVE, LUCKILY 
</HEADLINE>
 BC- 20DATES-REVIEW --LADN  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients  Friday, Feb. 26 or
thereafter ) 
OUR RATING:  3 STARS  
By GLENN WHIPP 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Myles Berkowitz wanted to make movies, but no one
in Hollywood would return his phone calls. He had the same problem
with women _ messages would go unanswered, potential girlfriends
suddenly would be transferred to jobs in places like Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
   Unfazed, Berkowitz decided to combine the failures of his
personal and professional lives and turn them into a career move.
The result, ``20 Dates,'' is an amusing, unflinching look at one
man's quest for fulfillment that plays at times like a documentary
and, at other moments, an old-fashioned romantic comedy.
</P>
<P>
   At its heart is Berkowitz, a headstrong, annoying, opinionated
guy in his mid-30s trying to sort through the mysteries of life and
love. His agent says he needs to learn to compromise; his friends
say he pushes too hard. No one wants to set him up on a date
because past experiences have proved embarrassing, and ``20 Dates''
contains plenty of documentary evidence to support their position.
</P>
<P>
   Berkowitz aims to go out on 20 dates, film them and come away
with a movie _ and maybe, just maybe, true love. Initially, he
tries to shoot his encounters secretly to give the footage a raw,
natural feel. A lawsuit from a disillusioned date puts an end to
that. Another date ends badly when she orders a three-pound lobster
at Gladstone's 4 Fish, a meal that taxes Myles' already
overburdened credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   Berkowitz also comes under fire from his financial backer, a
foul-mouthed producer, Elie Samaha, who wants the movie to have
more skin and less gab. Berkowitz surreptitiously tape records
Samaha in his office, and his tirades (so crude as to be almost
surreal) provide some of the film's funniest moments.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through his quest, something unexpected happens.
Berkowitz meets a beautiful, seemingly intelligent woman named
Elisabeth and falls in love. What's more surprising is that she
actually seems to like him and enjoy his company. What she doesn't
appreciate is the fact that Myles still has to go out on several
dates to complete the project. This provides the film's major
conflict: love or career? Berkowitz provides a deft resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``20 Dates'' could have been too cute by half, but Berkowitz's
abrasiveness (not to mention his willingness to look foolish) keeps
things lively. Still, the movie often feels rather slight, like an
extended David Letterman stunt. And if Berkowitz had not actually
met his dream date, ``20 Dates'' would have been an exercise in
tedium. Interestingly enough, Berkowitz found his movie at the
precise moment he found love. It's that serendipity that makes this
a moviegoing courtship worth pursuing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-99 2119EST &QL; 
