</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TICKET-REVIEW--LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JUST THE TICKET' MORE CLOYING THAN CUTE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients  on Friday, Feb. 26 or
thereafter ) 
OUR RATING: 2 STARS  
By GLENN WHIPP 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the sluggish new romance ``Just the Ticket,''
level-headed Linda (Andie MacDowell) tries to explain why she can't
stay away from her no-account boyfriend, a noble ticket scalper
named Gary (Andy Garcia).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's those puppy-dog eyes!'' Linda sweetly murmurs. ``Those
puppy-dog eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just the Ticket'' is a puppy-dog-eyes kind of movie. As such,
it's hard to resist at times. It might even be kind of sweet if it
didn't try so hard. But what writer-director Richard Wenk really
needed here was a swat on the nose with a rolled-up newspaper.
Because too often, he crosses the line between cute and cloying,
resulting in a movie that's more heartburn than heartwarming.
</P>
<P>
   Gary is a likable, salt-of-the-earth ticket scalper _ in other
words the kind of guy who exists only in the movies. When the pope
comes to Yankee Stadium to deliver a state-of-the-world address,
Gary sees the chance of a lifetime. He hopes to lay his hands on as
many tickets as he can find and then turn around and sell them for
as much money as the faithful will fork out. Then, maybe Linda will
regard him as something more than a lovable schmoe.
</P>
<P>
   Linda, though, already has seemed to have moved on. She has a
dependable (read: boring) boyfriend and is hoping to turn her
culinary training into a trip to the Cordon Bleu in Paris. But
then, Gary shows up, and she looks into those puppy dog eyes and
(cue romantic soundtrack) her resolve begins to melt.
</P>
<P>
   There are a lot of things wrong with ``Just the Ticket,''
starting with the character of Gary himself. When you think of
ticket scalpers, several thoughts come to mind, but none of them
are sympathetic or even remotely likable. Most of them, in fact,
can't be printed in a family newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Add to this the fact that Gary dreams of sticking it to devoted
people who simply want to see a revered religious leader, and you
have a guy, when you look beyond those dewy eyes, who is pretty
much scum of the earth.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe you can get beyond that because it's Andy Garcia
acting here and he's so darn nice. Unfortunately, writer-director
Richard Wenk doesn't trust his actors enough to let them do the
heavy work. Thus, you have countless shots of a cute little dog
preciously reacting to the action. (Even then, the dog by itself
isn't adorable enough. Wenk has to add one of those veterinary cone
collars for maximum cuteness.) Kisses are filmed in slow-motion.
Garcia wears a funny hat.
</P>
<P>
   Add to this some clumsy transitions, a plot that takes much too
long to resolve and a poorly sketched female lead and you have a
movie that's hard to like even when it's practically forcing you to
do so.  &UR; !ital! &LR; (Those eyes!) &UR; !off! &LR;  The final straw comes in the
home stretch when Gary employs a gambit straight out of ``Sister
Act'' to elude police and fulfill his dream of gouging New York's
Catholics. Bad sign: You root for the cops. &UR; !end! &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-99 2119EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990224.0441 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8213 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-WORLDMATCH-NOTE1S     02-24 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-WORLDMATCH-NOTE1STLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Upsets reveal not much difference in Nos. 1-64
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carlsbad, Calif. _ Welcome to Black Wednesday at the Andersen
Consulting Match Play Championship. All the title sponsor needed
after such a brutal first round was to combine it with a stock
market crash.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the danger of match-play tournaments. Top seeds fall and
TV ratings suffer. And while Tiger Woods avoided The Unthinkable by
beating Nick Faldo in his first-round match, the debris was
everywhere else at the La Costa Resort.
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 3 Mark O'Meara lost to No. 62 Michael Bradley, 4 and 2.
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 4 Davis Love III of Sea Island lost to No. 61 Steve Pate,
1 up.
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 6 Colin Montgomerie lost to No. 59 Craig Stadler, 5 and 3.
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 7 Ernie Els lost to No. 58 Paul Azinger, 1 up.
</P>
<P>
   _ No. 11 Jim Furyk lost to No. 50 Patrick Sjoland, 5 and 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had an enviable position,'' said Azinger, who handled Els, a
three-time England World Match Play champion. ``I think even though
I was playing this great player, I really had everything to gain
and nothing to lose. I really wasn't nervous today or anything
else.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a day when 18 lower seeds beat higher ones. Players
ranked 41-50 were 7-3. But, then again, we're talking about
rankings that constantly draw criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players all know the rankings are pretty silly,'' Azinger
said. ``This isn't tennis, where if a sixth seed gets beaten by the
60th seed, it's a big shock.''
</P>
<P>
   David Duval, the No. 2 seed but generally regarded as the
world's best player for the last year and a half, beat Australia's
Stephen Leaney 2 and 1 and said, ``There's so little difference
between No. 64 and No. 1. It may be one or two putts through the
course of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara, who won England's Cisco World Match Play over Woods,
said of Bradley, ``He made no mistakes today, and that's the key in
match play. Any one of these guys can beat the other guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie, who won the Andersen event in its previous form two
years ago, was peeved at Stadler for a few short putts not
conceded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andy North (of ESPN) told me that (Monty) gave me a good
little glare on 13,'' Stadler said. ``But, you know, when it's to
stay in the match and he's got four feet, I'm not going to give it
to him. He can glare all he wants.''
</P>
<P>
   CINK ADVANCES
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's Stewart Cink could be headed for a third-round meeting
against Woods. Cink, seeded 48th, ousted No. 19 Payne Stewart 3 and
2 by birdieing four of six holes on the back nine. To force a match
with Woods, whom he handled capably in college, Cink needs to
handle Australia's Craig Parry while Woods moves past Bob Tway.
``Payne didn't play like his normal self,'' Cink said. ``He wasn't
comfortable. I just played my game. I didn't give myself a chance
to mess up.'' ... The 16 second-round matches begin today at 12:15
p.m. ... Duval meets Bill Glasson, who defeated Stuart Appleby 2
and 1.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
