<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8217 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JASPER-TRIAL-HNS &LR;      02-24 1250
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATHER PLEADS FOR SON'S LIFE DURING PUNISHMENT PHASE OF TRIAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See JASPER-SENTENCE and JASPER-T-SHIRTS) 
(Eds.: Walter Quijano is cq) 
 
By RICHARD STEWART 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ Sitting in a wheelchair and breathing oxygen,
Ronald King begged a jury to spare his son's life Wednesday. ``I
love him,'' he gasped. ``You don't love everything they do.''
</P>
<P>
   The jury, which a day earlier convicted avowed white supremacist
John William ``Bill'' King, 24, of the brutal dragging death of
James Byrd Jr., a black man, will begin deliberating Thursday on
whether King will be sentenced to life in prison or death by
injection.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday two experts differed on whether King poses a
continuing threat to society should he be given a life sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've invested a lot of love in that boy,'' the elder King,
who suffers from emphysema, said on the stand, ``and I'd hate to
think we're going to lose him.'' When a defense attorney asked if
he wanted the jury to sentence his son to life in prison, King
gasped, ``Anything is better than losing him.''
</P>
<P>
   His son, who was adopted when he was 3 months old, began to get
into trouble after his mother died when he was 16, the elder King
said. He never showed racist tendencies before going to prison in
1995, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other testimony showed that King was assaulted on his first day
in the Beto I prison unit at Tennessee Colony. He later became part
of a tiny Ku Klux Klan group called the Confederate Knights of
America.
</P>
<P>
   His son asked to be excused from the courtroom and watched the
testimony on a television monitor from a side room. He had sat
emotionless during the trial, seeming even to fall asleep as a
psychologist testified in his favor earlier Wednesday. But King
appeared to have been crying when he returned to the courtroom
after his father's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   After the elder King's testimony Wednesday, three members of
Byrd's family approached him outside the courtroom. Byrd's
28-year-old daughter, Renee Mullins, hugged Ronald King and said,
``God bless you.'' He answered, ``Thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's sisters, Clara Taylor and Betty Boatner, also introduced
themselves to Ronald King and his daughter, Carol King Spadaccini.
Boatner told him: ``He's in God's hands. Put it in God's hands. God
loves everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said Ronald King talked to her family by telephone
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   King's father was the second of two witnesses called by his
attorneys during the punishment phase of the trial. The other,
former Texas prison system psychologist Dr. Walter Quijano, said
there would be little likelihood that King would perform violent
acts if kept in prison until he is at least 64 _ when he would
first be eligible for parole.
</P>
<P>
   Quijano said King had a history of burglary, not violence. ``A
burglar need not become a murderer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But one became one in this case?'' asked John Stevens, one of
the prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' the psychologist said.
</P>
<P>
   Quijano predicted that if sentenced to life in prison, King
would be kept in a small, single cell for 22 hours a day, being let
out only to spend time in a small recreation room by himself.
</P>
<P>
   Royce Smithey, a state investigator who specializes in crimes in
Texas prisons, said that if he gets a life sentence King could
possibly earn good conduct credit to be put into the general prison
population.
</P>
<P>
   Quijano also said King has shown no sorrow about the death of
Byrd, who was dragged behind a pickup for 3 miles along back
country roads June 7. Along the way his head, right shoulder and
arm were ripped from his body.
</P>
<P>
   A person who shows no remorse for a crime remains more dangerous
than those who do show sorrow, Quijano said.
</P>
<P>
   Beaumont psychiatrist Dr. Edward Gripon testified that King's
writings and his racist and satanic tattoos show that he will
present a continuing threat of violence. ``It's plain common sense
that that's not going to go away,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the letters King wrote from jail and prison show that he
has no regret for what happened to Byrd and that he is a racist.
``If they are heavily invested in that kind of ideology, it's not
going to just go away,'' he said of people like King.
</P>
<P>
   He said some crimes are so extreme and so dramatic, ``they
remove all doubt what the person is capable of.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside of the courtroom Gripon said King reminded him of a
Bosnian soldier accused of terrible war crimes whom he once
interviewed. ``I asked him how he could do the terrible things he
did to other human beings,'' Gripon said. ``He said they weren't
human beings.''
</P>
<P>
   Gripon said he thinks King's racist beliefs are based on
feelings of inadequacy. At the time he first went to prison he was
only 5-foot-7 and weighed only about 165 pounds, Gripon said. The
tattoos that cover much of his body are an attempt to make himself
appear more fierce, Gripon said.
</P>
<P>
   In other testimony Wednesday, Jasper County Deputy Sheriff Joe
Sterling said King threatened him with violence in January when he
refused to leave his cell for a court appearance. ``He said he had
nothing to lose,'' Sterling said.
</P>
<P>
   Jailer Kenneth Primrose said that same day King smashed a
television and radio in his cell. King was removed from his cell
while jailers cleaned up the mess, Primrose said. While cleaning
the cell they also searched it and found a noose made of electrical
cords and an eight-inch, home-made knife, called a ``shank'' made
of parts torn from the radio and television.
</P>
<P>
   King was apparently upset because he had learned that his former
girlfriend and the mother of his 6-month-old son was living with
another man and was pregnant by her new lover, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys will make final arguments Thursday before the jury is
asked three questions _ if King intended for Byrd to die, if King
will pose a future threat of violence and if there are any
mitigating circumstances that should keep him from being given the
death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   If each of the jurors answers ``yes'' to the first two questions
and ``no'' to the third, King will be sentenced to death by lethal
injection. If any juror answers the other way to any of the three
questions, he will be sentenced to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real simple: Did he intend for Mr. Byrd to die. Is he a
future threat? Are there any mitigating circumstances?'' said
Jasper County District Attorney Guy James Gray. ``If they answer
one way, he'll get life. If they answer the other way, he'll get
death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not real big on the death penalty,'' Gray said, ``but I
don't want this guy out when he's 65 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   Court-appointed defense attorney C. Haden ``Sonny'' Cribbs said
the trial has been a difficult one for him. ``What I say might make
the difference in whether he lives or dies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be an awful long night till tomorrow,'' Cribbs
said. ``It gets harder each time (he handles a death penalty case.)
I don't believe in the death penalty. I just plain do not believe
in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is all horrible,'' he said. ``No matter what the world
sees, this man is loved, he loves and he is a human being.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other men, Shawn Allen Berry, 24, and Lawrence Russell
Brewer Jr., 31, also are awaiting trials on capital murder charges
in Byrd's death.
</P>
<P>
   Gray said he has no idea when those trials will take place. ``I
like to take one trial at a time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
