<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 21:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8222 &Cx1f; tth-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOEING-CAPITAL-SPI &LR;      02-24 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOEING-CAPITAL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING VOWS TO GET RID OF MONEY-LOSERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Top Boeing executives Wednesday promised a review of
every company program, with an ``immediate full court press'' on
the three or four losing money.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman Phil Condit and the company's new chief financial
officer Debby Hopkins wouldn't say what programs those are or
specify their plans, although they said the moves could range from
canceling ailing commercial jetliner programs to closing
machine-parts plants.
</P>
<P>
   But they said $1.3 billion of the company's capital, about 10
percent of the total, is invested in money-losing,
``value-destroying'' ventures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have zero tolerance for value destruction at The Boeing
Co.,'' Hopkins declared. Except for the Boeing Learning Center
(which handles worker training and education), she said, all
programs will either make money or be sold. She noted that the
company sold its civilian helicopter division last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not just airplane programs. It is every single program
we've got,'' Condit said. ``There are no sacred cows.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Boeing would consider dropping the 717 or other
civilian jets, Condit said: ``Of course. There's nothing that
escapes scrutiny here.'' He said Boeing also will consider
consolidating machining and composite-parts building into just a
few locations, which could result in plant closures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to do high-speed machining in 15 different
places,'' he said. ``We're going to focus that activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the commercial-jet unit is likely to get the most
attention, where Boeing could cancel the slow-selling 717 model or
scale back expensive plans to develop longer-range versions of
other jets. People close to the company have said it plans to sell
an information-services unit based in Vienna, Va., that has about
$300 million in annual sales.
</P>
<P>
   The military-aircraft division isn't likely to see major
changes. Boeing executives said they're pleased with progress in
the highly profitable unit, which generated 85 percent of Boeing's
profit while accounting for just 23 percent of last year's sales.
</P>
<P>
   The policy was explained Tuesday to stock analysts gathered in
Orlando, Fla., and Wednesday in a phone conference with the news
media.
</P>
<P>
   Safeco money manager Bill Whitlow said the most notable aspect
of the announcement was that Boeing had not known until now what
its money-losing programs were.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now they've got the new chief financial officer, and they find
they've got these problems,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In recognition of the company's ongoing problems, Condit and
Harry Stonecipher, Boeing's president, asked the board of directors
Tuesday not to grant them bonuses for 1998. They also asked for no
bonuses for ``several Boeing Commercial Airplanes Group
executives.'' They didn't identify them, but the group may include
former executives, such as one-time divisional boss Ron Woodard.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Condit was paid $884,675 and received a bonus of
$446,000, plus stock options. Stonecipher received $895,345 in
salary and a $489,300 bonus. He also received $14.7 million in
other compensation, nearly all from before the merger with
McDonnell Douglas, where he was chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   In an e-mail to Boeing employees, Condit and Stonecipher said
their action ``is fitting and proper if we are truly to move
forward with a performance-based culture.''
</P>
<P>
   It may also be part of the pre-negotiation positioning with the
Aerospace Machinists. In the last negotiation cycle, big bonuses to
top bosses were an irritant to union workers being asked for
concessions on their medical plan. The same union is negotiating a
contract this year.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Johnson, union president, didn't comment on the bonuses,
but released a statement on the threat of program sell-offs.
``Simply raising the possibility of eliminating programs does
nothing to boost the already low morale on the shop floor,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Condit declined to comment on the recent rumor that General
Electric is about to buy Boeing. A GE acquisition would raise major
antitrust concerns, because GE is one of three producers of jet
engines used on Boeing's commercial aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing stock, which declined $1.75 a share to close at $35.38 a
share in trading Wednesday, has fallen 32 percent in the past two
years, the worst performer in the Dow Jones Industrial Average.
Rising costs and steep discounts on civilian planes have eroded
Boeing's earnings. Led by Hopkins, named to her post late last
year, Boeing is trying to show it's serious about boosting returns.
</P>
<P>
   Concerning his recent statement about Boeing being a potential
takeover target because of its low stock price, Condit said,
``There is real value to be created in this company. Our choice is,
do we do it? Or do we let somebody else do it? I like the idea of
us doing it a heck of a lot more.''
</P>
<P>
   Condit and Hopkins also discussed Boeing's opportunities. Among
Boeing's three divisions, commercial aircraft, missiles and
defense, and space and communications, the company sees the biggest
opportunities in the latter group, Condit said. In commercial
aircraft, its opportunity is in maintenance and overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's 10,683 Boeing jets flying around the world,'' Condit
said. ``What are we doing to capture our fair share of that
services market? The answer is, not enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Boeing does not plan any big new commercial airplane programs.
``I don't think the market requirement is there, and you can't
create something out of nothing,'' Condit said.
</P>
<P>
   This report includes information from Bloomberg News and The
Associated Press.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
