<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- Feb. 24, 1999 -- CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN, 2-24 --
New palm pilots, including the Palm Pilot III seen here, are
thinner, brighter and more expensive then their predecessors. Next
on the horizon is the 3Com Palm V, code named Sumo, and the Palm
Pilot IIIx, the latest versions of the world's most popular pocket
PCs. The Palm V, which is half the thickness of the original Palm
Pilot and twice as stylish, is likely to solidify Palm's place in
the pocket. (Naum Kazhdan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 24, 1999 -- KOSOVO-U.S., 2-24 -- -
Flanked by Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., right, chairman of the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee, and Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., the
ranking minority member, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
reaches out to greet committee member Sens. Sam Brownback, R-Kans.,
left, as Sen. Gordon Smith, R-Ore., looks on, Wednesday on Capitol
Hill. Albright told Congress that there was no chance that a
fragile peace plan for Kosovo could succeed without an
international force that included U.S. troops. (Stephen Crowley/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) HUNTERDON, N.J. -- Feb. 24, 1999 -- CIR-COLLEGE-APPLY,
2-24 -- High School seniors Rick Morrison, right, and Anne Cortina,
pose next to a computer display of their web page which they will
use to supplement their applications to universities. Paper
applications are still the main tool admissions officers use to
decide whether or not to accept a student. But multimedia
presentations are part of the growing technological supplements
that frantic teenagers are either sending along with their college
applications or referring to in their biographical essays. (Norman
Y. Lono/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) FOSTER CITY, Calif. -- Feb. 24, 1999 --
CIR-HOME-NETWORKS, 2-24 -- Rich Levin, a technology information
manager, looks on as his wife Ellen assists their children Nate, 5,
and Steffi, 3, with a printout at their home near San Francisco
last week. The Levins, who have three computers, installed a local
area network which uses radio waves rather then wires to connect
their computers and peripherals. Now everyone prints and sends
files when they want from where they please without having to have
drilled a single hole or laid any wires. (Peter DaSilva/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Feb. 24, 1999 -- CIR-KID-ENTREPENEURS, 2-24
-- Jerry Fuzayluv opens the door for his boss, Aron Leifer, center,
in Brooklyn. Leifer, 18, who founded Multi Media Audiotext, is the
latest in a quickly growing group of young people, most of them
young men, getting rich from their computer businesses. Leifer
writes software for things like database management and computer
phone systems. (Steve Hart/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) CONCORD, Calif. -- Feb. 24, 1999 -- CIR-FREE-PCS, 2-24 --
Ted Maddock, techonolgy coordinator for Mount Diablo High School,
works with a student, James Brackenridge, on a PC given by ZapMe!.
Some 6,000 schools have signed up for a program offered by Zap Me!
which announced in October that it would give schools 15 computers
with satellite-based Internet connections. The catch: the computers
display advertising in the left-hand corner of the monitor. The
concept of free computers represents an evolution from older
offerings of free, advertising-subsidized E-mail and Internet
access. (Dan Krauss/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
