<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 2/24/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) NEW YORK -- Feb. 24, 1999 -- NY-DOG-CONTROL-2, 2-24 --
Dogs play in Riverside Park on Wednesday. The administration of New
York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has begun the latest in its
quality-of-life campaigns, to curtail unleashed dogs in the city's
parks, using such measures as increased fines and citizen patrols.
(Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) NEW YORK -- Feb. 24, 1999 --CONTACT-LENSES-2, 2-24 --
Dr. Penny Asbell looks into the eyes of her patient, Angel Castro,
at Mount Sinai Hospital. Dr. Asbell inserted arcs, known as Intacs,
into Castro's eyes to correct nearsightedness. The arcs, an
experimental treatment made by Keravision, a small California
company, can be inserted during a 10-minute procedure in an
opthamologistUs office. Once placed, they flatten the cornea to
correct mild nearsightedness, or myopia, a condition that affects
some 22 million Americans. (Fred Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) ARLINGTON, Virg. -- Feb. 24, 1999 --
EXCL-UNKNOWN-SOLDIERS, 2-24 -- An honor guard marches past the Tomb
of the Unknowns at Arlington National Cemetery on Wednesday. A
guard takes a precise 21 steps to march across the tomb, indicated
by worn area on the rubber mat which is replaced once a year on
Memorial Day. With science outpacing military tradition, the
Pentagon has concluded that it will not place new remains from the
Vietnam War in the Tomb of the Unknowns. (Paul Hosefros/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) NEW YORK -- Feb. 24, 1999 -- RADIOCITY, 2-24 -- Chairs
leaving Radio City Music Hall. Radio City closed on Feb. 16 for a
six-month renovation estimated at close to $40 million. This will
be ``the first true restoration of the music hall,'' says Hugh
Hardy, of Hardy Holzman Pfeiffer, architects for the project with
the Rockwell Group. Employees in the Hardy and Rockwell offices and
their consultants were offered the chairs for $75 a pair. (Andrea
Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) NEW YORK -- Feb. 24, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., FEB. 28 --
WEISSLER-THEATER, 2-24 -- Fran and Barry Weissler on the stage of
the Shubert Theater with dancers from ``Chicago.'' The couple that
started out driving their acting company to parochial schools in
the Northeast has, over the last several years, presented Broadway
revivals of ``Gypsy'' with Tyne Daly and ``My Fair Lady'' with
Richard Chamberlain and Melissa Errico. (Sara Krulwich/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) NEW YORK -- Feb. 24, 1999 -- BRIGHT-THEATER-REVIEW, 2-24
-- John Link Graney, left, and Patrick Wilson in ``Bright Lights
Big City,'' the new musical based on the Jay McInerney novel. The
produciton, which opened last night, easily qualifies as the most
frustrating experience of this bottom-drawer season for the
American musical. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) NEW YORK -- Feb. 24, 1999 -- NY-JUILLIARD-PLAYWRIGHTS-1,
2-24 -- From left, Marsha Norman, the playwright and leader of the
Juilliard playwrights program, with John Guare, the playwright, and
Brooke Berman, a student. ``It's a high-intensity individual
program,'' Ms. Norman says, adding that by involving working
playwrights in the process, ``it is a front-line kind of teaching
operation, out of the trenches.'' (James Estrin/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- Feb. 24, 1999 -- NY-JUILLIARD-PLAYWRIGHTS-2,
2-24 -- Kate Grant, left, Katie Kriesler and Peter Jacobson reading
a Juilliard student's play. There are no requirements, grades or
academic credit, but the playwrights program in the Juilliard
School's drama division is a hot ticket, one of the training
grounds that hopeful young playwrights covet the most. (Nicole
Bengiveno/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- Feb. 24, 1999 -- NY-GRAHAM-STUDIO, 2-24 --
Members of the Martha Graham Dance Company in their school's
dismantled studio. For reasons entangled in the intrigues over the
$1.2 billion Duke estate and the financial struggles of many arts
groups today, the heavily mortgaged headquarters was sold under
pressure last summer, sending the company to temporary sites
downtown while leaving it nearly $1.5 million richer. (Fred R.
Conrad/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) DENVER -- Feb. 24, 1999 -- DENVER-BRITAIN, 2-24 --
Bernadette Berger, who built a collection with her husband, John.
If Denver's response to tableaux of fox hunts, sea battles,
Cotswold landscapes and Elizabethan aristocrats is a measure,
British art, culture and history still exert a powerful pull on the
American mind. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- Feb. 24, 1999 -- CRAFT-DESIGN, 2-24 -- An
ebony bowl by Mike Shuler, at Barry Friedman, includes 5,000 chips
of holly, tulipwood and pink ivorywood. There are 13 million people
in the United States making crafts, and over a billion dollars
being spent buying them. Much of the recent craft production is
more beautiful and more technically sophisticated than it has been
since the heyday of American craft artists 30 years ago. (Catrina
Genovese/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) BOSTON -- Feb. 24, 1999 -- FAMILY-IV-BOS, 2-24 -- John
W. Mills, a Vietnam-era veteran, proudly showcases two of his
passions - singing and patriotism. ``I'm vested in this country,
more than most,'' says Mills, 54, whose flag has flown over the
front steps of his home for eight years. (Pat Greenhouse/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) BOSTON -- Feb. 24, 1999 -- FAMILY-III-BOS, 2-24 -- The
daughters of Harry ``Bucky'' Lew show off his violin, which is more
than 100-years-old. From left, Eleanor Lew Armstrong, 88; Frances
Emma Johnson, 69; and Phyllis Lew, 78. ``It's precious to me,''
says Ms. Johnson of the violin. ``It's all I have of my father.''
(Pat Greenhouse/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) LOWELL, Mass. -- Feb. 24, 1999 -- FAMILY-II-BOS, 2-24 --
Laura Ashe studying a 19th century photo of the Lowell house where
she grew up hearing tales about her great-grandparents and their
involvement in the Underground Railroad. ``Upstairs, that's where
the slaves hid in the long closet,'' Ashe recalls. ``And that's the
chimney corner,'' she says, moving to the dining area, ``where the
slaves would come down, sit and tell their stories.'' (Pat
Greenhouse/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Feb. 24, 1999 -- FAMILY-I-BOS, 2-24
-- Mae Theresa Bonitto searching through old family photos at her
Cambridge home. Ms. Bonitto credits her great-great-great
grandfather, Barzillai Lew, a Revolutionary War fifer, with
establishing the family's penchant for music. ``It started with
him,'' she says as she points to the framed painting on her living
room wall of a young black man holding a flute. (Pat
Greenhouse/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- Feb. 24, 1999 -- NY-DOG-CONTROL, 2-24 --
Unteathered dogs play in a Brooklyn park on Saturday. The
administration of New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has begun the
latest in its quality-of-life campaigns, to curtail unleashed dogs
in the city's parks, using such measures as increased fines and
citizen patrols. (Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) BALTIMORE -- Feb. 24, 1999 -- BALTIMORE-POLITICS, 2-24
-- It took no time for the would-be successors to line up, once
Baltimore's three-term Mayor Kurt Schmoke, left, announced in
December that he would not seek re-election this year. Lawrence
Bell, second from left, the president of the City Council, appears
to be the early front-runner. However Howard Rawlings, an
influential Democratic state legislator, and former Gov. William
Donald Schaeffer, right, are hoping for a stronger field of
candidates. (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) FOSTER CITY, Calif. -- Feb. 24, 1999 --
CIR-HOME-NETWORKS-2, 2-24 -- Rich Levin, a technology information
manager, browses the web using a Home Free Wireless Network card.
The Levins, who have three computers in their home, installed a
local area network which uses radio waves rather then wires to
connect their computers and peripherals together. Now everyone in
the house can surf the internet, print and send files when they
want from where they please. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Feb. 24, 1999 --CONTACT-LENSES, 2-24 -- A
close-up of a patient's eye after having clear polymer arcs
implanted to correct near-sightedness at Mount Sinai Hospital. The
arcs, known as Intacs, are an experimental treatment made by
Keravision, a small California company. The arcs, which can be
inserted during a 10-minute procedure in an opthamologistUs office,
flatten the cornea to correct mild nearsightedness, or myopia, a
condition that affects some 22 million Americans. (Mount Sinai
Hospital/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) RIDGEFIELD, Conn. -- Feb. 24, 1999 -- MAILBOX, 2-24 --
The maxi-mailbox has a useful back door. What's that green, bulbous
thing sprouting like a mushroom at the end of Monica and Cal Brunen
driveway? It's a one-piece, dent-proof, leak-proof plastic mailbox
big enough to hold a dozen magazines (no rolling!) and stand up to
a Range Rover's nudge. (Suzanne DeChillo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) SAG HARBOR, N.Y. -- Feb. 24, 1999 --
NY-HAMPTONS-BARGAINS, 2-24 -- An immaculate cottage and a piece of
Sag Harbor for $225,000. No one brags about them. They're not
featured in the color brochures. But bargain houses, it turns out,
form the backbone of much of the real estate business in the
Hamptons, even in these days of mega-houses and
multi-million-dollar sales. (Maxine Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) UNDATED -- Feb. 24, 1999 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W, 2-24
-- Cleaning dust is a never-ending battle. At times it seems that
the dust begins to collect on surfaces immediately after they are
wiped clean. In spite of all the advances in technology, the best
dust-collecting tools are ones that have been around for decades:
the dust cloth, the dust mop and the vacuum. (New York Times Photo)
*LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 24, 1999 -- CONGRESS-COUNSEL, 2-24 --
Griffin Bell, the former Attorney General, looks at Howard Baker,
the former Senate majority leader, during their testimony before
the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee on Wednesday. Bell and
Baker were presenting their views on whether the Independent
Counsel Act should be changed when it comes up for renewal in June.
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Feb. 24, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., FEB. 28 --
CANBY-THEATER-REVIEW, 2-24 -- Swoosie Kurtz, as both the ``good''
sister, left, and the ``bad'' sister in ``The Mineola Twins'' at
the Laura Pels Theater at the Roundabout. There is such an
abundance of theatrical life on view in the production that it
comes as a shock when, at the curtain call, only five people show
up. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Feb. 24, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., FEB. 28 --
LIZZIE-BORDEN-OPERA, 2-24 -- Jack Beeson in his apartment; he began
writing librettos as an adolescent. Beeson, 78, concedes that in
the context of American contemporary music, his opera ``Lizzie
Borden,'' which had its premiere at the New York City Opera in
1965, is probably considered musically conservative. (Nicole
Bengiveno/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Feb. 24, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., FEB. 28 --
ANNIE-OAKLEY-THEATER, 2-24 -- Tom Wopat as Frank Butler and
Bernadette Peters as Annie Oakley in ``Annie Get Your Gun,''
opening next week at the Marquis Theater. ``Broadway is changing
and the roles aren't there because of that,'' she says. ``With
'Annie,' I saw a wonderful character there. She says what's on her
mind and doesn't hold anything back, which is kind of refreshing.''
(Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) CAMBRIDGE, Mass. -- Feb. 24, 1999 -- ANALOG-UPTURN, 2-24
-- Ray Stata, chairman of Analog Devices Inc., shows some of his
company's analog chips on the floor of the factory. The chips take
the messy, imprecise world of sound and motion and translates them
into the sharp, precise universe of digital information needed by
computers. According to the Semiconductor Industry Association,
worldwide sales of analog chips should pass $24 billion this year.
(Frank O'Brien/Boston Globe Photos)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) BOSTON -- Feb. 24, 1999 -- ASIA-OPPORTUNITY, 2-24 --
Steve Gray, managing director of Recovery Group, which specializes
in reorganizing companies and banks in distress, in his office last
week. Economic forces ravaging Asia have created a vast land of
business opportunity. Although there is no stampede, some
enterprising companies are waking up to the unique opportunities
for bargain-hunting in Asia's worst economic slump since World War
II. (John Blanding/Boston Globe Photos)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- Feb. 24, 1999 -- CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN, 2-24 --
New palm pilots, including the Palm Pilot III seen here, are
thinner, brighter and more expensive then their predecessors. Next
on the horizon is the 3Com Palm V, code named Sumo, and the Palm
Pilot IIIx, the latest versions of the world's most popular pocket
PCs. The Palm V, which is half the thickness of the original Palm
Pilot and twice as stylish, is likely to solidify Palm's place in
the pocket. (Naum Kazhdan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WASHINGTON -- Feb. 24, 1999 -- KOSOVO-U.S., 2-24 -- -
Flanked by Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., right, chairman of the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee, and Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., the
ranking minority member, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
reaches out to greet committee member Sens. Sam Brownback, R-Kans.,
left, as Sen. Gordon Smith, R-Ore., looks on, Wednesday on Capitol
Hill. Albright told Congress that there was no chance that a
fragile peace plan for Kosovo could succeed without an
international force that included U.S. troops. (Stephen Crowley/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) HUNTERDON, N.J. -- Feb. 24, 1999 -- CIR-COLLEGE-APPLY,
2-24 -- High School seniors Rick Morrison, right, and Anne Cortina,
pose next to a computer display of their web page which they will
use to supplement their applications to universities. Paper
applications are still the main tool admissions officers use to
decide whether or not to accept a student. But multimedia
presentations are part of the growing technological supplements
that frantic teenagers are either sending along with their college
applications or referring to in their biographical essays. (Norman
Y. Lono/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) FOSTER CITY, Calif. -- Feb. 24, 1999 --
CIR-HOME-NETWORKS, 2-24 -- Rich Levin, a technology information
manager, looks on as his wife Ellen assists their children Nate, 5,
and Steffi, 3, with a printout at their home near San Francisco
last week. The Levins, who have three computers, installed a local
area network which uses radio waves rather then wires to connect
their computers and peripherals. Now everyone prints and sends
files when they want from where they please without having to have
drilled a single hole or laid any wires. (Peter DaSilva/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Feb. 24, 1999 -- CIR-KID-ENTREPENEURS, 2-24
-- Jerry Fuzayluv opens the door for his boss, Aron Leifer, center,
in Brooklyn. Leifer, 18, who founded Multi Media Audiotext, is the
latest in a quickly growing group of young people, most of them
young men, getting rich from their computer businesses. Leifer
writes software for things like database management and computer
phone systems. (Steve Hart/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) CONCORD, Calif. -- Feb. 24, 1999 -- CIR-FREE-PCS, 2-24 --
Ted Maddock, techonolgy coordinator for Mount Diablo High School,
works with a student, James Brackenridge, on a PC given by ZapMe!.
Some 6,000 schools have signed up for a program offered by Zap Me!
which announced in October that it would give schools 15 computers
with satellite-based Internet connections. The catch: the computers
display advertising in the left-hand corner of the monitor. The
concept of free computers represents an evolution from older
offerings of free, advertising-subsidized E-mail and Internet
access. (Dan Krauss/New York Times Photo)
</P>
