</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENO-STARR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO AND STARR AGREE TO NEGOTIATE FRAMEWORK FOR INQUIRY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.) (nk) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON and DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a private meeting at the Justice Department,
Attorney General Janet Reno and Kenneth Starr agreed amicably to
negotiate a framework for an investigation of his tactics in the
Lewinsky case, government officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The unusual meeting, which took place on Sunday after Reno's
return from South Africa, was an effort to repair the breach
between the two officials. Their once-cordial relationship had
soured as a bitter dispute broke out over the Justice Department's
decision to open an internal ethics inquiry into whether Starr's
prosecutors abused their authority.
</P>
<P>
   The officials' efforts to move forward, however, have suddenly
been thrown into question, now that an authoritative third party
has decided to intervene. The three-judge panel that appointed
Starr as independent counsel issued an order, announced on Tuesday,
directing Reno and Starr to file legal briefs staking out their
positions on whether the department has jurisdiction to investigate
an independent counsel's practices.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's order was in response to a petition filed on Feb. 11
by the Landmark Legal Foundation, a conservative law group in
Virginia, which asked the three federal appellate judges to stop
Reno's new inquiry. Landmark contends that the attorney general
does not have the authority to investigate an independent counsel
about his official duties. The department and the independent
counsel have until early next month to reply.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, several government lawyers said they were mystified
by the panel's ruling, maintaining that the independent counsel law
did not appear to give private groups like Landmark any legal
standing to intercede in a Justice Department investigation. Nor,
they said, did the law grant the judicial panel the authority to
discipline independent counsels.
</P>
<P>
   The department has told Starr that the investigation will focus
on whether Starr's prosecutors improperly coerced witnesses like
Monica Lewinsky or withheld information from department lawyers
about possible conflicts of interest at the outset of the Lewinsky
inquiry in January 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel law gives the attorney general sole
responsibility for dismissing an independent counsel. Department
officials have told Starr that inherent in that removal power is
the authority to conduct a fact-finding investigation that they
believe is necessary to determine whether Starr should be
dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, stepping squarely into the dispute creates the
impression that the judges are trying to protect Starr, government
officials said. The judicial panel is headed by Judge David B.
Sentelle of the District of Columbia Court of Appeals, who pushed
for Starr's appointment as the independent counsel. Starr, who was
appointed in August 1994 by Sentelle and two other appellate
judges, replaced Robert B. Fiske Jr., who had been appointed by
Reno.
</P>
<P>
   Mark R. Levin, Landmark's president, said in an interview
Wednesday that the attorney general was trying to exercise
authority that the statute reserves as a function of Congress. ``I
think the Justice Department is going to have to explain what
exactly it seeks to investigate and why, and what its legal
authority is,'' Levin said.
</P>
<P>
   At their meeting, the attorney general bristled at reports that
Starr's prosecutors had complained that the department was
operating at the behest of White House officials, the government
officials said. In turn, Starr complained to her that the
department was behind news articles about the internal inquiry, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But Reno and Starr were conciliatory, the officials said. Reno
indicated to Starr that she did not want the department's inquiry
to be perceived as a prelude to another Saturday night massacre,
like President Richard Nixon's dismissal of special prosecutor
Archibald Cox on Oct. 20, 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Starr appeared willing to accept the investigation as long as it
its fairness could be assured, and Reno appeared willing to accept
a negotiated plan as long as she retained authority over the
inquiry, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Coming as the Independent Counsel Act is about to expire and
when lawmakers appear unlikely to re-authorize it, the attorney
general's dispute with the independent counsel seems like the final
battle waged after the combatants have decided to give up the war.
But the stakes are high for both sides.
</P>
<P>
   For Reno, the inquiry culminates a year in which she has grown
frustrated by Starr's practices, some of which she believed were
overreaching, government officials said.
</P>
<P>
   For Starr, the inquiry poses a much more direct threat. If Reno
found that he had engaged in prosecutorial misconduct, she could
remove him from his office or issue a reprimand that would taint
Starr's inquiry. Her findings could serve as an official
endorsement of the view of President Clinton's lawyers that Starr
had abused his prosecutorial powers in a relentless pursuit of the
president.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Starr's office, some prosecutors remain highly suspicious
of Reno's motives. One of Starr's associates recently called the
Justice Department inquiry ``politically motivated,'' and wondered
whether an aggressive investigation, coming less than two weeks
after the Senate's acquittal of the president, had been quietly
encouraged by a vengeful White House.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
