r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRAGGING-DEATH-TEX     02-24 0935
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRAGGING-DEATH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATHER PLEADS FOR LIFE OF RACIST KILLER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ In an emotion-choked voice, the father of the
white supremacist convicted of capital murder in the dragging death
of an African-American man begged jurors Wednesday to sentence his
son to life imprisonment, not lethal injection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've invested a lot of love in that boy,'' Ronald King,
seated in a wheelchair, said of John William ``Bill'' King, 24,
whom he and his late wife adopted when the boy was 3 months old.
``I hate to think we're going to lose him.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked by defense attorney C. Haden ``Sonny'' Cribbs if he
thought the jury should give his son life imprisonment, the retired
timber worker fought back sobs. ``Anything is better than ... '' he
said before he was too overcome to finish his reply.
</P>
<P>
   The younger King was found guilty of capital murder Tuesday in
the torture slaying of James Byrd Jr., 49. Two other ex-convicts,
Lawrence Russell Brewer, 31, and Shawn Berry, 24, will be tried in
the same crime later.
</P>
<P>
   After final arguments Thursday morning, the jury of 11 whites
and one black, who is the foreman, will be sequestered to decide
King's fate.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald King, 67, said his son had black friends while he was
growing up in Jasper, including one whom the father considered a
role model for his son. But the younger King changed after going to
prison in 1995 for violating probation on a burglary conviction, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   William King's attorneys contended that his transformation into
a racist _ after six black inmates beat him on his arrival at the
Beto I Unit _ is a mitigating factor that the jury should consider.
</P>
<P>
   In considering punishment, the jury must determine whether King
intended to kill Byrd and whether he would be a continuing threat
to society, either in prison or after his possible release 40 years
into a life sentence.
</P>
<P>
   A forensic psychiatrist, Dr. Edward Gripon of Beaumont,
testified for the prosecution Wednesday that King would remain a
``continued threat for future acts of violence.'' He said that
crimes such as the kidnap-slaying of Byrd are ``so extreme and so
dramatic, they remove all doubt what the person is capable of.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Walter Quijano, a former chief psychologist of Texas prisons
who practices in Conroe, testified for the defense. He maintained
that, with proper prison classification and safeguards, King would
not be a risk.
</P>
<P>
   But under cross-examination, Quijano conceded that black and
Jewish inmates could risk bodily harm in a chance encounter with
King.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the courthouse, Quijano said that King, based on his
racist writings, ``would accomplish his goal if he is executed:
becoming a martyr'' in the white supremacist movement.
</P>
<P>
   After the day's session, District Attorney Guy James Gray said
Quijano ``may have been a better witness for us than our witness.''
</P>
<P>
   King, who sat impassively Tuesday when the jury found him
guilty, asked to leave the courtroom Wednesday before his father
testified.
</P>
<P>
   His attorney later said that King cried while watching his
father on closed circuit television from an adjoining room.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not as strong as you think he is,'' Cribbs said. Later,
the Beaumont attorney said, ``He loves. He is a human being. He's a
proud man _ Billy. Sometimes it becomes unmanly (for him) to show
emotions.''
</P>
<P>
   After testifying, Ronald King was wheeled to an elevator, where
he was breathing heavily through a plastic tube connected to an
oxygen tank because of his emphysema.
</P>
<P>
   There he encountered three of Byrd's relatives for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``God bless you,'' said Byrd's eldest daughter, Renee Mullins,
28. She leaned down and gently hugged the man who frequently wept
in court while his son sat expressionless, even snoozing at one
point during Wednesday's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you,'' Ronald King replied. ``This happens.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in God's hands,'' said one of Byrd's sisters, Betty
Boatner as tears ran down the cheeks of all present. ``He loves
everybody,'' said Boatner, a Sunday school teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, a Jasper County jailer testified that a homemade knife,
called a ``shank'' in prison jargon, and a small noose were found
under King's mattress after the defendant smashed his TV set and
boombox in his cell. The weapons were fashioned from TV and radio
parts, jailer Kenneth Primrose said. The testimony was apparently
aimed at depicting King's violent nature.
</P>
<P>
   Under cross-examination, Primrose said King was then placed
under suicide watch.
</P>
<P>
   But the jailer said he was unaware that King's outburst was
prompted by Kylie Greeney, his girlfriend and the mother of his
child, who had just informed him that she was pregnant and living
with another man.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Sterling, an investigator with the Jasper County Sheriff's
Department, testified that King issued a threat after refusing to
be taken to the courthouse on Jan. 6. He paraphrased the defendant
as saying, ``It's nothing personal, but assaulting a peace
officer'' didn't mean anything because he had nothing to live for.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, witnesses detailed King's criminal record, which had
previously been kept from the jury. He stole a shotgun and tools
from a small metal storage shed at 16, then helped break into a
video rental store a few months later. He was charged with
assaulting a sister but was not prosecuted. After violating
probation after a stint in boot camp, King spent two years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
