A8238 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-LYONS-TRIAL-715&AMP;A     02-24 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-LYONS-TRIAL-715&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY WILL DECIDE IF PREACHER CHOSE PROFIT OVER HIS PULPIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., Nev.) (nk) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LARGO, Fla. _ A day of reckoning is drawing near for the
embattled preacher who heads the largest black religious
organization in the nation, a man who used his pulpit for profit
and once even pocketed money that had been donated to rebuild
churches destroyed by arson, prosecutors said Wednesday in closing
arguments in the monthlong trial of the Rev. Henry J. Lyons.
</P>
<P>
   A jury was expected to begin deliberations here on Thursday in
the racketeering trial of Lyons and his former aide, Bernice
Edwards, a convicted embezzler who, prosecutors say, helped the St.
Petersburg preacher swindle more than $4 million from corporations
eager to do business with the National Baptist Convention USA.
</P>
<P>
   In closing arguments Wednesday and on Tuesday, prosecutors
described the relationship between the defendants as a ``Bonnie and
Clyde'' partnership in which they used the pulpit and the good name
of a 100-year-old religious organization to finance a lifestyle of
posh real estate, luxury cars and shopping sprees for clothes and
jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Lyons and Ms. Edwards peddled a nonexistent
membership list to large companies that wanted to market cemetery
plots, life insurance policies and even credit cards, and then
devised elaborate schemes to hide the profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their creed was greed,'' Assistant State Attorney Jim
Hellickson said in the prosecution's closing arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Lyons is accused of stealing some $250,000 from the
Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith, money that had been donated
to rebuild some black churches in the South that had been destroyed
by arson.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Lyons and Ms. Edwards, who before moving to Florida
was convicted in Wisconsin of embezzling from a school for at-risk
children, were living richly. They had a $700,000 waterfront house;
a time-share condominium in Lake Tahoe, Nev.; two Mercedeses; a
Rolls-Royce; a diamond that one witness described as being as big
as a dime; and other expensive items, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of using a gun to rob their victims, they used a pen
and they used their word,'' said Hellickson. Lyons is also charged
with grand theft.
</P>
<P>
   But in their own closing arguments Wednesday, lawyers for the
defendants argued that the state was trying them in a criminal
court for issues that could be resolved in civil court _ failed
business dealings are not criminal, they said _ and that the morals
of neither Ms. Edwards nor Lyons were on trial.
</P>
<P>
   As Lyons left the courtroom at one point, a small group of
parishioners and friends gathered around him, hugging him,
squeezing his arm and telling him, as one man said, that he was
sure to walk free. Both Lyons and Ms. Edwards face as much as 30
years in prison if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the prosecution has piled more and more evidence around
the minister and his aide, both the National Baptist Convention USA
and a loyal congregation have refused to desert him. Lyons remains
pastor at Bethel Metropolitan Baptist Church, a large, influential
church, and is still president of the National Baptist Convention
USA.
</P>
<P>
   ``They accepted his apology, and they said let's move on,'' said
Denis deVlaming, a lawyer representing the minister. Lyons has
admitted that he has sinned but has denied criminal wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers said Wednesday that the money the defendants
spent on themselves was money they earned _ he as president and she
as head of public relations for the convention _ and that it
belonged to them.
</P>
<P>
   In a long closing argument, deVlaming said that the money the
state claimed was stolen by the defendants was never stolen at all,
and merely floated from account to account. It was never really
missing, he said, stressing to the all-white jury that it was just
how the convention did business.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a case about race, but about cultural
differences,'' said another of Lyons' lawyers, Grady Irvin.
</P>
<P>
   As for the money intended for the burned churches, it was never
taken, defense lawyers said. But prosecutors told jurors that the
minister had to scramble to return it when the Anti-Defamation
League demanded an accounting. Prosecutors said Lyons had already
spent the money on himself, his wife and alleged mistresses.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In a trial that has stretched over 27 days, prosecutors have
painted a picture of a man who seemed to serve money more than God.
</P>
<P>
   They said that even the convention membership of 8.5 million is
inflated, and that the defendants used that number to entice
corporations, who thought they were paying the minister and his
aide to have their cemetery plots and supplies and life insurance
policies promoted by a respected minister to large numbers of
members.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers have countered that the convention claimed such
a large membership before Lyons became president.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors, who are to rebut the defense arguments on Thursday
before the case goes to the jury, said the profitable scheme began
to come apart in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   That was when Lyons' wife, Deborah, found a deed in his
briefcase that showed he owned a lavish waterfront home with Ms.
Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Lyons, who would later be charged with arson, set several
fires at their house. That prompted prosecutors to follow a paper
trail of the minister's money, leading to records of his lavish
lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Lyons, who received five years' probation, would later say
that she never believed her husband was having an affair, and that
personal problems, not jealousy, prompted her to set the fires. She
has stood beside her husband in his legal troubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have displayed human weaknesses and frailties,'' Lyons said
when the investigation into his fiances began. ``I am not the
devil,'' he later said.
</P>
<P>
   Although he is still in the pulpit and in the presidency, some
black residents of St. Petersburg said that Lyons' power was
diminished and that even old friends had started to distance
themselves from him. He still faces a federal trial later this year
on charges of bank fraud, wire fraud, extortion and money
laundering.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
