<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8240 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRAMMY-NYT &LR;      02-24 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAMMY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAURYN HILL AND MADONNA EACH WIN 3 GRAMMYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Early story. It will be updated by 12 a.m. ET)  
(sw) 
 By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Though Grammy voters are well-known for their
erratic, unpredictable and often outlandish choices, it was no
surprise at this year's awards ceremony at the Shrine Auditorium
here when Lauryn Hill gathered three awards.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hill, the member of the rap group the Fugees who released
her first solo album to popular and critical acclaim last year,
even beat herself. In the best R&AMP;B song and the best female R&AMP;B
vocal performance categories, her own song warning women about what
men really want, ``Doo Wop (That Thing),'' won Grammys at the
expense of Aretha Franklin's ``A Rose Is A Rose,'' which was
written by Ms. Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was excited about Lauryn Hill the day I heard that record,''
said Michael Greene, the president of the National Academy of
Recording Arts and Sciences, which presents the Grammys, in an
interview before the show. ``I sweated bullets because I wondered
if the Academy membership would get it. But they got it. They got
it big time.'' Ms. Hill received 10 Grammy nominations, more than
any other artist this year.
</P>
<P>
   Though some have called this year's Grammy celebration the year
of the woman (a phrase used just about every year in music) because
of the large number of female performers nominated in top
categories, the awards show could also be called Madonna's revenge.
Despite 15 years of recording, she had only previously received one
award, for best longform video in 1991. Now, in her latest guise as
a raven-haired spiritualist, Madonna, who opened the show with an
Asian-themed performance of ``Nothing Really Matters,'' has three
more Grammys to her name: best pop album, best short-form video and
best dance recording.
</P>
<P>
   The rapper Jay-Z learned on Wednesday night that snubbing the
Grammys doesn't lose a musician any points. The gangsta rapper
announced that he was boycotting the Grammys for overlooking
rappers and asked that his name be withdrawn from the running. He
was specifically upset with Grammy voters for not nominating his
fellow rapper DMX for best new artist and at the music industry in
general for paying more attention to violence in rap than his
upcoming tour. Nonetheless, his ``Vol. 2...Hard Knock Live,'' won
the award for best rap album. Jay-Z was not there to accept the
award.
</P>
<P>
   In a year of major changes for the music business, particularly
the sale of Polygram to The Seagram Co. and the industry's
resistance to the rise of music sales via the internet, Sheryl Crow
was the first award-winner to acknowledge the upheaval. During her
speech for best rock album (for ``The Globe Sessions'') she
delivered a eulogy for her record label, A&AMP;M, which was shut down
by Seagram, and the executives who lost their jobs there.
</P>
<P>
   Past winners of top awards remained favorites this year,
particularly Celine Dion, who won the album of the year award in
1996. Her ``My Heart Will Go On,'' from the seemingly unsinkable
``Titanic'' soundtrack, won one of the top awards, ``Song of the
Year,'' which was presented to the songwriters James Horner and
Will Jennings. ``You all need to write me something, man,'' the
rapper and actor Will Smith told them when presenting the award.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Heart Will Go On'' also won an award for best pop vocal
performance. Eric Clapton, the big winner in 1993, won best male
pop vocal performance for ``My Father's Eyes'' and Alanis
Morissette, who swept up in 1996, won best rock song for
``Uninvited.'' However, one Grammy favorite, Tony Bennett, lost
this year to Elmo of Sesame Street for best children's musical
album.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, previously neglected artists received long
overdue Grammys. In her acceptance speech for best traditional pop
vocal performance for her live at Carnegie Hall album, Patti Page
said that when her grandchildren asked what name to call her, ``I
said Grammy because I'll never get one. Now they have to call me
granny.''
</P>
<P>
   Prior to this ceremony, Ms. Page, whose career predates the
Grammys by ten years, had never been nominated before. And Shirley
Horn, after receiving six nominations previously, won her first
Grammy for best jazz vocal performance for ``I Remember Miles.''
</P>
<P>
   Grammy critics who've complained after watching Elvis Costello
get snubbed year after year were temporarily quelled. Costello
finally won a Grammy by collaborating with a four-time winner, Burt
Bacharach, on an album, a song from which (''I Still Have That
Other Girl'') won best pop vocal collaboration. Backstage, Costello
said that he hadn't given much creedence to the Grammy Awards in
the past, but maybe now he will. And Lou Reed, another Grammy
oversight, won his first one for Best Longform Music Video for
``American Masters: Rock and Roll Heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Over half a decade since its heyday, swing is officially pop
music again. The Brian Setzer Orchestra, led by the former member
of the rockabilly revivalists the Stray Cats, won best pop
instrumental performance for ``Sleepwalk'' and best pop vocal
performance by a duo or group for ``Jump Jive an' Wail.''
</P>
<P>
   In the classical field, the conductor Pierre Boulez won, adding
to his 20 awards, for best opera recording (''Bluebeard's
Castle''), and best orchestral performance (''Mahler: Symphony No.
9''). And in a new category added this year, best classical
crossover album, an old Grammy hand, 12-time winner Yo Yo Ma, won
with the conductor Jorge Calandrelli for their album of Astor
Piazzolla compositions, ``Soul of the Tango.''
</P>
<P>
   Recordings released between Oct. 1, 1997, and Sept. 30, 1998,
were eligible for an award. The winners were selected by the 10,000
voting members _from musicians to producers to industry executives
to liner note writers _ of the Recording Academy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
