</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT: LATEST MICROSOFT VIDEOTAPE IS TRUE BUT MISLEADING 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A government lawyer questioned another videotape
demonstration at the Microsoft &UR;  &LR; trial Wednesday, but this time the
challenge dealt not with the reliability or honesty of Microsoft's
tape but with its message.
</P>
<P>
   David Boies, the government's lead trial lawyer, has
successfully attacked several videotape demonstrations Microsoft
has played in court over the last few weeks, arguing that they were
deceptively edited or did not show what the narrators' claimed they
did.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, as a new witness took the stand, Microsoft played a
new tape showing that the company is allowing computer
manufacturers to customize the Windows desktop, the computer screen
that users see when turning on the computer. With these
customizations, the first screen shows the manufacturers'
promotions and advertisements ahead of Microsoft's.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government and 19 states say Microsoft's contracts
prohibiting computer makers from shipping machines with the Windows
desktop altered in any way as evidence of antitrust activities.
This requirement, which Microsoft abandoned before the trial even
started, is important to the case because the opening screen serves
as a gateway to the Internet and to the tremendous profit potential
in steering consumers to specific Internet service providers and
Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's demonstration Wednesday showed that the company was
already granting manufacturers the flexibility to change the
desktop. Computers being sold by Compaq, Hewlett-Packard, Sony and
Acer, among others, were shown with their desktops modified so that
they showed Internet sign-up offers and other options, either
alongside Microsoft's offers or ahead of them.
</P>
<P>
   Several of these computers also offered Netscape Navigator
prominently. The Netscape Communications &UR;  &LR; Corp. is Microsoft's
chief rival in the browser market, and the government charges that
Microsoft has used the monopoly it enjoys with the Windows
operating system to prevent computer manufacturers from offering
Netscape's browser.
</P>
<P>
   Boies did not challenge the authenticity of the videotape, but
he did challenge Microsoft's motivation for allowing the companies
to alter the desktop.
</P>
<P>
   ``It basically shows how fast the industry is changing as this
case goes on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Joachim Kempin, a Microsoft vice president responsible for
contracts with computer makers, responded: ``I don't think it has
anything to do with this case. I don't think the industry is
changing because of this case.''
</P>
<P>
   Boies did show, however, that all the Windows customization in
Microsoft's videotape demonstration is still in clear violation of
the Windows licensing agreements the companies must sign. But
Microsoft gave permission to a dozen companies that asked to make
the changes, and Kempin insisted the same permission would be given
to any others that came forward.
</P>
<P>
   Boies suggested that he did not think it was a coincidence that
these exceptions had been granted last spring, weeks before the
government filed suit against Microsoft. And as a senior government
official noted, ``What they give, they can take away if this suit
goes away.''
</P>
<P>
   Kempin returns to the stand Thursday morning for continued
cross-examination by Boies.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Wednesday morning the trial had focused on another issue in the
suit as a government lawyer, Phil Malone, cross-examined Eric
Engstrom, a Microsoft executive, about whether Microsoft had tried
to force Apple Computer &UR;  &LR; out of the market for multimedia software
that runs on Windows and had sabotaged Apple's software as part of
that effort.
</P>
<P>
   Multimedia software is used to play audio and video clips from
the Internet. An Apple executive, Avadis Tevanian, testified last
year that Microsoft had designed Windows so that Quicktime, Apple's
audio-video software, would not run properly.
</P>
<P>
   Engstrom said the problem was caused by Apple.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was amazing to me that Dr. Tevanian could come in here and
make the claim that we sabotaged Quicktime,'' he said. ``At
Microsoft, our company would never do anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   As to the other charge, that Microsoft had tried to push Apple
out of the market for multimedia software for Windows, Engstrom
acknowledged that it was true. He had little choice, faced with
several e-mail messages from within Microsoft showing that as the
company's intent.
</P>
<P>
   But Engstrom said that multimedia software was a low-level
product, a commodity in essence, and it did not make sense for the
two companies to spend time and money competing over it.
``Audio-video software is so perfectly well understood,'' he said,
``that I don't think this is the place for product
differentiation.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the courtroom, Boies said, ``This is just another
example of Microsoft going to a company and saying, `If you'll stop
doing this, we'll help you in some other area.'''
</P>
<P>
   A key charge in the government suit is that Microsoft tried to
persuade Netscape not to sell a version of its Web browser for
Windows 95. In exchange, Microsoft would offer Netscape numerous
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape refused, and the government says Microsoft then began a
campaign of predatory and illegal behavior that led to the
lawsuit. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-99 2143EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990224.0457 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8249 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     02-24 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: MATCH PLAY IS GOLF'S DAYTONA 500  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Calif., Spain, South Africa, U.K.)   By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARLSBAD, Calif. _ It's different. That's how everybody
described the Andersen Consulting Match Play Championship even
before Wednesday's first round. Now it's so different, it's already
more like the Daytona 500 than a golf tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Wrecked and smoking cars are everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Mark O'Meara, last year's player of the year for winning the
Masters and the British Open, crashed into the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Els, last Sunday's winner of the Nissan Open in Los
Angeles, blew an engine.
</P>
<P>
   Davis Love III collided on the far turn with two European Rider
Cup players, Colin Montgomerie and Lee Westwood.
</P>
<P>
   Only five of the top 10 ranked golfers remain.
</P>
<P>
   The world's No. 3 (O'Meara), No. 4 (Love), No. 5 (Westwood), No.
6 (Montgomerie) and No. 7 (Els) are out of the race. In a poker
game, the 3, 4, 5, 6 and 7 of clubs would be considered a winning
hand.
</P>
<P>
   But in this first World Golf Championship match play tournament,
it's a winner only for their respective conquerors: Michael
Bradley, Steve Pate, Eduardo Romero, Craig Stadler and Paul
Azinger.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the marquee was wrecked. Tiger Woods and David Duval,
golf's No. 1 and No. 2, cruised into Thursday's second round of
this tournament at the La Costa Resort and Spa in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Only the winners were hitting balls. All the first-round losers
were on their way to the San Diego airport.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 64 starters in golf's Daytona 500, only 32 cars were
still running. By Thursday night, only 16 will be. After Friday's
two rounds, only four; by Saturday night, only two; by Sunday
night, only the winner.
</P>
<P>
   But that's the nature and the appeal of match play, as oppposed
to the usual weekly medal play, alias each golfer's aggregate
score.
</P>
<P>
   It's not new. When the PGA Championship was a match play event
before 1958, there were days like this. In 1931, Walter Hagen, Leo
Diegel, Johnny Farrell, Ed Dudley and Al Espinosa all were knocked
out in the first round. Sam Snead lost four second-round matches.
Ben Hogan lost a first-round match.
</P>
<P>
   Because of those upsets, a relatively obscure pro occasionally
won the PGA in those match play years, but the big names won, too.
</P>
<P>
   Hagen won five titles, Snead three, Gene Sarazen three, Ben
Hogan two, Byron Nelson two.
</P>
<P>
   So there's still hope for Sunday's dream final: Woods against
Duval over 36 holes. But in match play, there's no guarantee it
will happen.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the odds are that it won't happen. That's why match
play is different.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love match play,'' said Greg Norman, who eliminated John
Cook, 3 and 2, and now will oppose Argentina's Romero. ``I think
it's the best competitive golf you can play, especially at this
level.''
</P>
<P>
   And what a level: the top 64 players according to the World Golf
Ranking playing for $5 million in prize money, with $1 million to
the winner (and a consolation $25,000 to each of Wednesday's
first-round losers).
</P>
<P>
   Two more World Golf Championship tournaments will be played this
year: the NEC Invitational with as many as 48 Ryder Cup and
Presidents Cup golfers at Firestone in Akron, Ohio. Aug. 26-29 and
the American Express Championship with some 70 golfers at
Valderrama in Spain, Nov. 4-7.
</P>
<P>
   But with those two events at medal play, they won't be that
different.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
