<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INITIATIVE TARGETS FLAGSTAFF, ARIZ., FORESTS FOR MILLIONS OF CUTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE YOZWIAK  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF _ During Arizona's driest months, the late spring and
early summer before the monsoon rains, Paul Delaney lives in fear
of fire.
</P>
<P>
   Delaney's five-acre residence is covered with conifers, trees
that could explode into flames if touched by a spark.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live on the edge of town where there's a lot of transients
who come though. They camp in the woods and make fires. There
hasn't been a summer where a fire hasn't started within a couple of
miles of here,'' the 47-year-old geologist said.
</P>
<P>
   Delaney supports an initiative that could result in the logging
of millions of trees during the next decade across a 100,000-acre
doughnut of the Coconino National Forest. In some areas, as many as
90 percent of the trees that ring Flagstaff would be cut down.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative is backed by the Grand Canyon Forests
Partnership, a coalition of 18 organizations, government agencies,
business and environmental groups that have joined the U.S. Forest
Service in a use-'em-or-lose-'em policy of cutting the trees before
they burn. The Forest Service holds final approval for the
initiative. &QL; 
PROTECTING THE PEAKS
</P>
<P>
   Many here fear conditions are ripe for more and bigger fires _
firestorms that could sweep from the forest into the city, or up
onto the gorgeous San Francisco Peaks, the highest mountains in
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``The peaks are the signature of Flagstaff,'' said Brad Ack,
program director of the Grand Canyon Trust, an environmental group
that is helping spearhead the partnership.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if that was all just one big blackened place,'' Ack said,
``this town's economy would really suffer.''
</P>
<P>
   The rhetoric of partnership members is reminiscent of the timber
industry, with a significant difference. While the timber barons
fought to cut down the largest, most valuable trees, the
partnership aims to cut down the smallest trees, leaving the bigger
ones to provide recreational opportunities and wildlife habitat.
</P>
<P>
   It's the smaller trees that make up the vast majority of
fire-prone trees in the forest. But some environmentalists are
concerned that many mid-size and some large trees would come down
in the process. And they are concerned that cutting so many trees
could devastate the forests for people and wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   Cutting mostly small trees also presents the partnership with a
problem: how to pay for forest restoration.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to get (the trees) out of the woods,'' Ack
said, ``we've got to find a way to use (the lumber). Otherwise, you
just can't come up with enough money to pay people to pull it
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Markets for the smaller trees are limited, but they include
firewood, posts, poles, furniture, building materials and pulp for
paper mills.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Maurer, president of the Flagstaff Chamber of Commerce, is
hopeful the project will produce several new small businesses that
could rely on a steady supply of small trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps there's a chance _ not to go back to the old logging
days Flagstaff is known for _ but perhaps to bring back an industry
of sorts,'' Maurer said.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Bennett, regional manager of Stone Forest Industry, said
the days of large-scale commercial logging are gone in Arizona.
Logging now is limited by environmental policies aimed at saving
the forests' remaining old-growth trees and endangered wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   Stone's inclusion in the partnership is a red flag to many
environmentalists. But Bennett said Stone has no intention of
turning the partnership into a way for his company to resurrect
large-scale commercial logging, at least not in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``What experience is gained here may be applicable to other
parts of the country where Stone operates,'' Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   ECONOMY OR ECOLOGY?
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Southwest Forest Alliance, a coalition of more
than 50 environmental groups in Arizona and New Mexico, worry that
methods adopted by the partnership are being driven more by the
timber markets than by ecology.
</P>
<P>
   Alliance members agree that there are too many small trees and
that a fire-prevention perimeter around Flagstaff is needed. But
they say the partnership's plans go beyond the city's borders and
deep into threatened wildlife habitat.
</P>
<P>
   To prove a more moderate approach, the alliance is working with
the U.S. Forest Service on experimental plots near Williams, about
25 miles west of Flagstaff.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than trying to guess how to re-create the forest before
it was altered by logging, livestock grazing and fire suppression,
the alliance is using the existing trees to guide them in crafting
a natural-looking forest that also is less likely to burn.
</P>
<P>
   Half the trees were cut down on the alliance's plot near
Williams. In contrast, between 83 percent and 91 percent of the
trees were logged on the partnership's six experimental plots near
Flagstaff.
</P>
<P>
   Wally Covington, a professor of forest ecology at Northern
Arizona University, is the guiding force behind forest restoration
plans for the perimeter of Flagstaff and at experimental plots at
Grand Canyon National Park. He said the alliance isn't removing
enough trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leaving that many trees (50 percent) leaves the forest in a
condition where it will still support crown fires,'' the
devastating fires that can wipe out sections of the forest for
decades, Covington said.
</P>
<P>
   But Kieran Suckling, executive director of the Southwest Center
for Biological Diversity, said Covington's plans can't guarantee
against fires.
</P>
<P>
   Covington admits that fire killed big trees on some of his
initial experimental stands on Mount Trumbull, northwest of the
Grand Canyon. But he blames that on excessive dryness in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Suckling believes the public won't buy it.
</P>
<P>
   ``To mess around with a few acres on Mount Trumbull is one
thing,'' he said. ``But now, they're talking about doing 100,000
acres around Flagstaff. It would have just an enormous impact on
the ecosystem. The citizens of Flagstaff are going to go berserk
when they find out that (up to 90 percent) of all the trees around
them are going to be logged.'' &QL; 
Steve Yozwiak can be reached at 444-8810 or at
steve.yozwiak(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-99 2146EST &QL; 
