<SLUG> BC-UKRAINE-ASYLUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER UKRAINIAN PRIME MINISTER ASKS FOR POLITICAL ASYLUM IN U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Ukraine's former prime minister, Pavlo Lazarenko, who
was detained by federal officials last Friday as he tried to enter
the United States, has requested political asylum, his American
lawyer said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, James Mayock, said Lazarenko, who faces corruption
charges in Ukraine, fears persecution by the government of
President Leonid Kuchma should he return to his homeland.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration officials interviewed Lazarenko on Wednesday, the
first step in a potentially lengthy process to establish whether
his fear is credible or merely an excuse to remain here. The
officials had taken him into custody shortly after he arrived at
New York's Kennedy International Airport traveling on a tourist
visa.
</P>
<P>
   Lazarenko was Kuchma's deputy prime minister and then prime
minister until mid-1997, when the president removed him amid news
reports accusing him of using his political positions to amass
hundreds of millions of dollars. He has denied the reports.
</P>
<P>
   Lazarenko said that he was prepared to expose political
corruption in Kuchma's government. Kuchma has called such
accusations the acts of a desperate man.
</P>
<P>
   The two are not only bitter political opponents now, but
Lazarenko is also on the ballot as an opposing candidate in the
presidential election this October. Lazarenko has repeatedly
accused Kuchma's government of misusing its power to trump up
corruption charges to destroy his political career.
</P>
<P>
   However, in December, the Swiss arrested Lazarenko after he
sought to enter that country, and charged him with laundering
millions of dollars through numbered bank accounts. He was freed on
bond; the case has yet to come to trial.
</P>
<P>
   Lazarenko has said that he left Ukraine for Greece Feb. 17 for
medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Ukrainian prosecutors issued a warrant for his
arrest for embezzlement and misuse of state property.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
