<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-COUNSEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAKER ADVISES CAUTION ON INDEPENDENT COUNSEL LAW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn., N.J., Ill., N.M., Conn.)  (Eds: See also RENO-STARR) 
(mk) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the Senate apparently poised either to scrap
or strip back the independent counsel law, Howard Baker, the former
Senate majority leader, counseled senators at a hearing Wednesday
to take a post-impeachment cooling-off period and delay the
decision until next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recommend to the Senate and this committee that we cool it,
think about it for a while, let the temper of these times soften,''
Baker told the Senate Committee on Governmental Affairs, which had
its first day of hearings on the law on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Baker, who has been sharply critical of the law and once called
it a ``fourth branch of government,'' suggested that Congress
permit the law to expire on June 30 and take up the issue next
session. The former senator, who voted in the 1970s to create the
law, pointed out that it had lapsed for two years, from 1992 to
1994, with no dire consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a mistake'' to rush headlong into a decision, with
the passions over impeachment still fresh, said Baker, who was
President Reagan's chief of staff while then independent counsel
Lawrence Walsh was investigating the Iran-Contra affair.
</P>
<P>
   A few of the other panelists, including a former independent
counsel, did not hesitate to advise the senators to abandon the
law, calling it fundamentally ``flawed.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffin Bell, President Carter's first attorney general,
suggested to the senators that the country return to the system
that existed before the Watergate-era law, when the attorney
general had sole power to appoint outside prosecutors to handle
cases involving high-level wrongdoing. That system was changed in
1978, in the wake of Watergate and President Nixon's decision to
order the firing of Archibald Cox, at the time the special
prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Bell and Baker are co-chairmen of the National Commission on the
Separation of Powers, an organization that issued a report in
December concluding that the current independent counsel law should
not be reauthorized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I long ago concluded that this statute is unworkable for a
number of reasons and represents very poor governmental policy,''
Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a view shared by all the experts. The first special
prosecutor ever appointed, Arthur Christie, recommended renewing
the law, but with restrictions. ``Personal mistakes and
limitations,'' he said, should be off limits. Christie was
appointed in the Carter administration.
</P>
<P>
   The Governmental Affairs committee, chaired by Sen. Fred
Thompson, R-Tenn., began the first of several hearings Wednesday on
whether Congress should revise, scrap or replace the contentious
independent counsel law. If Congress does not act, the law, which
was created in 1978 and has been reauthorized and tinkered with
three times in the past 20 years, will simply expire June 30.
</P>
<P>
   The committee could hear from Attorney General Janet Reno and,
perhaps, Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr in March.
</P>
<P>
   The statute was harpooned by both Republicans and Democrats on
Wednesday. Under the law, the attorney general must seek the
appointment of an independent counsel when there is substantial and
credible evidence that a crime has been committed by the president
or other government officials. A panel of three judges selects the
counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Members of both parties agree that something needs to be done to
rein in prosecutors who spend millions of dollars and take years to
complete their investigations with little accountability.
</P>
<P>
   Just as disturbing, Thompson and Baker said, the law has altered
the dynamic of impeachment by ordering a prosecutor to refer to
Congress evidence of ``possible impeachable offenses.''
</P>
<P>
   The law has drawn bipartisan animus in the wake of the
impeachment proceedings and public disapproval of Starr's
wide-ranging, 4 1/2-year, $50 million investigation of President
Clinton. Senators from both parties are threatening to filibuster
any attempt at reauthorizing the law.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, two Democrats on the committee, Robert Torricelli
of New Jersey and Richard Durbin of Illinois, said they had been
mistaken to vote for the law in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli also criticized Walsh's conduct during the
Iran-Contra investigation, saying it was ``wrong and inexcusable''
that the inquiry lasted seven years and cost $40 million. The
investigations of other counsels, including Donald Smaltz, who
looked into former Agriculture Secretary Mike Espy's conduct, also
were criticized.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were wrong,'' Torricelli said, adding that he would not
vote to reauthorize the law.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., asked, ``What are we going to
do?''
</P>
<P>
   On that question, there is not much consensus, and Thompson
warned that simple ``tinkering'' would not pass muster.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans said they were open to hearing about revisions,
perhaps placing restrictions on prosecutors. But most Democrats
said they would like to get rid of the statute. Some, like Sen.
Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., said an alternative must be created to
insure public confidence in cases involving conflicts of interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``A different sort of danger may surface when no statutory
system exists to provide for the independent investigation of our
top officials,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
