<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-COUNSEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: FIX THE INDEPENDENT COUNSEL ACT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Feb. 25:
</P>
<P>
   One reality of the post-impeachment era in Washington is that
the Independent Counsel Act will not be renewed in its present
form. The only options are for forces of reform in Congress to
revise the act or see it vanish forever on its June expiration
date. Right now, a handicapper would have to bet that the law will
disappear, so great is public and congressional disenchantment over
the investigation conducted by Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Senators who believe in status-quo politics, led by Mitch
McConnell on the Republican side and Robert Torricelli on the
Democratic side, are stoking that resentment to make sure the act
dies.
</P>
<P>
   That would not serve the public interest. The act should be
reformed to prevent sprawling, protracted inquiries like that
conducted by Starr and by Lawrence Walsh during the Reagan
administration. But it should not be junked, for an easily
documented reason.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with Watergate and extending through the dismal tenure
of Janet Reno at a politicized Justice Department, the public
record shows that attorneys general cannot conduct independent
inquiries into allegations against sitting presidents or their
close associates.
</P>
<P>
   Senators who want to bury the act have a lot going for them.
Christopher Dodd, the Connecticut Democrat, has adopted the old
canard of the Reagan Republicans that the independent counsel law
has criminalized politics. Also, as the Democratic Sen. Joseph
Lieberman of Connecticut says, if the renewal debate becomes a
referendum on Starr, the game is over.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, along with Sens. Carl Levin, a Democrat, and Susan
Collins, a Republican, are shopping for alterations that will fix
some of the law's defects. These changes include having the
attorney general and a panel of federal judges share authority for
picking a counsel without partisan baggage. Other possibilities
include reducing the number of covered offices, putting time limits
on inquiries and excluding matters that occurred before an
individual's term of office.
</P>
<P>
   There are problems with each of these remedies. A time limit,
for example, would encourage stonewalling by people under
investigation. Campaign tactics and fund-raising should not be
covered in any exclusion of pre-election events.
</P>
<P>
   But some kind of ``surgery,'' to use Lieberman's word, is
necessary to save this flawed but important law. Senators who want
to kill it belong to a bipartisan coalition against public
accountability. The experience of the past 30 years has shown that
such accountability is needed to keep Washington honest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
