<HEADLINE>
GRAND CANYON PARK CONSIDERS LOGGING EXPERIMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE YOZWIAK  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND CANYON _ Flying over the forests near the Grand Canyon,
especially now when there is snow, it's easy to see the line
between Grand Canyon National Park and the Kaibab National Forest.
</P>
<P>
   The forest on National Forest lands _ after a century of logging
the largest old-growth trees _ is thin, the snow on the ground
clearly visible.
</P>
<P>
   The forest on National Park lands _ after decades without
logging and without natural wildfires _ is thick, the snow covered
by interlocking branches of the forest canopy.
</P>
<P>
   Both are unnatural, the result of two radically different
land-management philosophies.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists now say both styles have left millions of small,
fire-prone trees throughout the forests, providing the fuel that
could erupt in catastrophic infernos across this northern tip of
the world's largest Ponderosa pine ecosystem.
</P>
<P>
   Near Flagstaff and Williams, the Forest Service is experimenting
with logging these small trees to reduce the threat of fire.
</P>
<P>
   Grand Canyon officials, who on Friday will celebrate the 80th
anniversary of the park, want to try their own experiments this
year by logging small trees north and south of the Canyon. If
applied throughout the park, hundreds of thousands of trees could
be cut down.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; It's a proposal as politically hot as the firestorms that swept
through Yellowstone National Park in the summer of 1988, burning
800,000 acres of forest. It's exactly those kind of hot-burning
crown fires _ where the flames rapidly jump from one treetop to the
next _ that Grand Canyon officials desperately &UR; want to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of much rain or snow so far this year has park
officials and some scientists worried that huge fires could ignite
anytime.
</P>
<P>
   But environmentalists are worried that cutting so many trees at
the Grand Canyon could set a precedent for the nation's other
national parks. &QL; 
An experiment, not logging
</P>
<P>
   Don't mention ``logging'' to park officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a science experiment. It is not an effort by the
National Park Service to start logging practices in national
parks,'' said Superintendent Rob Arnberger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a research experiment designed to test mechanical
thinning.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mechanical thinning'' means a $900,000 experiment using chain
saws to cut 16,000 trees _ mostly small ones _ across 80 acres:
half on the south rim near Grandview Point, and half on the north
rim along Swamp Ridge.
</P>
<P>
   If, as could happen, the experiment is applied across the park's
120,000 acres of forest lands _ 10 percent of the 1.2 million-acre
Canyon park _ the plan eventually could result in hundreds of
thousands of trees being cut down. The cost of such an operation is
unknown, and environmentalists are worried that Congress may order
park officials to recoup the costs by selling the logs to
commercial timber operations.
</P>
<P>
   Finding a market for these trees may prove difficult, since the
overwhelming majority of them would be less than 5 inches in
diameter. Removing them, park officials say, would allow the
survival of the remaining large trees _ the ones critical for
maintaining wildlife habitat.
</P>
<P>
   No trees older than 120 years or greater than 16 inches in
diameter will be touched, unless they are in a meadow or grassland,
said park scientist Bob Winfree.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to do everything we can to save the oldest trees,''
many of which are 300 to 400 years old, Winfree said.
</P>
<P>
   The logistics of logging
</P>
<P>
   Still, cutting so many trees is a prospect that seems radical to
environmentalists like Martos Hoffman, executive director of the
Southwest Forest Alliance, a group of more than 50 environmental
and wildlife groups from across Arizona and New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   During public hearings this month, Hoffman urged park officials
to delay their experiment for at least three years, until more
scientists could review the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``People perceive the national parks as an environment where,
for once, they can walk around and not have their perception of the
natural landscape encumbered by a field of . . . stumps.''
</P>
<P>
   The park was created in 1919, Hoffman said, for the very purpose
of preventing logging, mining, livestock grazing and other
activities that would detract from the Canyon's natural splendor.
Even cutting small trees, on a large scale, would leave hundreds of
thousands of stumps in the forests.
</P>
<P>
   And most of the park is proposed as wilderness, he said, a
designation that precludes the roads and mechanized transportation
required in most large-scale logging operations.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt said that while the nation's
parks are supposed to be natural, a century of putting out every
wildfire has left the forests in a dangerous condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without meaning to, (we) created artificial, unhealthy and
dangerous forest,'' said Babbitt, a former Arizona governor who
grew up in nearby Flagstaff.
</P>
<P>
   ``This experiment (in cutting trees) is an attempt to learn how
to return the forests to their natural, healthy state and eliminate
the danger of catastrophic forest fires. And that's all it is,''
Babbitt said.
</P>
<P>
   But Sharon Galbreath of the Sierra Club is concerned that the
planned experiment will not only set a precedent for the rest of
the Grand Canyon, but for forests in other national parks.
</P>
<P>
   There also is the question of how to pay for forest restoration.
Many environmentalists are concerned that pressures to market the
timber will overshadow efforts to improve the ecosystem, and that
pressure from industry and Congress will dictate excessive logging.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will have to have a commercial-scale logging operation,''
to take out as many trees throughout the park as are called for in
the initial experiments, Galbreath said.
</P>
<P>
   Park officials do not anticipate developing more roads, but they
might try to use horses to remove logs from roadless areas.
</P>
<P>
   The natural state of the forest
</P>
<P>
   Using thousands of tree-ring samples, anecdotal accounts of
military expeditions and the letters and diaries of early pioneers,
scientists at Northern Arizona University have reconstructed a
vision of what Southwest forests were like prior to Anglo-European
settlement more than 120 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Wally Covington, a professor of forest ecology, believes the
natural Ponderosa pine forests were open and parklike. Large trees
stood far enough apart that wagons easily moved between them.
Grasses reached the bellies of horses. Lightning would occasionally
ignite the grasses. Cool, quick-burning fires kept small trees in
check, moving past the fire-resistant bark of older trees.
</P>
<P>
   White civilization brought livestock that ate those grasses,
grasses that kept tree seeds from taking hold. Logging of the
largest trees opened spaces for still more small trees. In
Smokey-Bear fashion, putting out all fires let the small trees grow
out of control.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, which Covington said was the driest summer in the
Southwest forests since 1730, some of the region's largest recorded
fires burned out of control for days across the Canyon's north rim,
and along the western slopes of the San Francisco Peak north of
Flagstaff.
</P>
<P>
   ``The predictions that many of us have been making about a
crown-fire holocaust are coming sooner than we thought they
would,'' said Covington, a guru of forest restoration who has
attracted scientists from around the world to his experimental
plots near Flagstaff.
</P>
<P>
   Park and forest officials for decades have intentionally set
small fires in the forests, intending to mimic the natural fires
that once removed the undergrowth and excess small trees.
</P>
<P>
   But they can't keep up, and the park's forests are so thick,
setting ``prescribed burns'' is dangerous. They easily can burn out
of control, fed first by dead pine needles and thickets of tiny
trees, then racing through ladders of smaller trees and into the
crowns of the giants.
</P>
<P>
   Controlled fires just don't do the job of re moving many
juvenile ponderosa pines, which quickly grow a thick bark resistant
to cool-burning ground fires. They remain, however, susceptible to
hot-burning crown fires.
</P>
<P>
   Covington believes time is running out to restore the forests to
a more natural state.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are now at the 50,000-acre fires. I think the 150,000-acre,
200,000-acre fires are within the next five years,'' said
Covington, who through Sen. Jon Kyl, R-Ariz., and Babbitt helped
secure more than $1.7 million for forest experiments.
</P>
<P>
   For wildlife, less isn't more
</P>
<P>
   Some environmentalists warn that if what happens at the national
park is anything like Covington's previous experiments near
Flagstaff and at Mount Trumbull, northwest of the``'' Grand Canyon,
it would be a disaster, especially for wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   New experimental efforts, which could affect 100,000 acres
surrounding Flagstaff, are especially worrisome to Kieran Suckling,
executive director of the Southwest Center for Biological
Diversity.
</P>
<P>
   He is concerned that Covington's ``Wally World'' forest-thinning
procedures are a cure worse than the disease, and he fears they
could be adopted in national forests throughout the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think of this as the catastrophic restoration model,''
Suckling said. ``If they go forward with this, it will result in
millions of acres being nuked.''
</P>
<P>
   Other scientists are beginning to raise questions, too.
</P>
<P>
   A new wildlife study by the Arizona Game and Fish Department
warned in September: ``Forest management practices that focus on
intensive, widespread thinning will adversely impact tassel-eared
squirrels,'' a key prey species for raptors like the rare northern
goshawk.
</P>
<P>
   Biology professor Peter Stacey, who teaches restoration ecology
at the University of New Mexico, also is concerned about removing
too many trees.
</P>
<P>
   After a tour this month of northern Arizona restoration
projects, Stacey described some of them as ``radical.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They could have profound effects on wildlife,'' Stacey said.
</P>
<P>
   Arnberger, the Grand Canyon superintendent, said critics have
``righteous'' concerns about the thinning proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``People love their parks. And the Grand Canyon is an icon. When
you open the parks to some kind of manipulative type of use, then
lots of people become concerned,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's another segment of the population that might say,
`It's about time.' '' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
