<SLUG> BC-BKC-HOOPCOL-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POSTSEASON FATES WILL BE DECIDED IN UPCOMING DAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Teams and games to watch as Selection Sunday approaches. Ten
days and counting. . .
</P>
<P>
   __ The postseason fate of several mediocre teams in major
conferences hinges on the outcome of mid-level conference
tournaments that begin this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   If Miami-Ohio (Mid-American), Detroit (Midwestern Collegiate),
Evansville (Missouri Valley), Murray State (Ohio Valley), Gonzaga
(West Coast) and College of Charleston (Southern) don't earn
automatic berths, they might scoop up precious at-large bids
usually reserved for, say, the sixth-place team in the Big 12.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be surprised if the Mid-American gets three bids, with
Toledo and Kent joining Miami-Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   __ Teams from power conferences that are in tenuous positions
include Minnesota (6-8 in Big Ten play), Nebraska, Oklahoma State
and Missouri from the Big 12, UNC-Charlotte and Alabama-Birmingham
from Conference USA, Mississippi (7-7 in SEC play), and everyone in
the Western Athletic Conference except Utah.
</P>
<P>
   New Mexico played a lousy schedule and has no road wins of
substance. Fresno State has 10 losses. UNLV has just 15 wins. Of
all the WAC contenders, Texas Christian (18-8, 6-6) might have the
best chance for an at-large bid. The NCAA selection committee
probably will dismiss the Horned Frogs' two losses without star
center Lee Nailon.
</P>
<P>
   __ From the Pac-10, Stanford, Arizona, UCLA and Washington are
in. Cal is out. Arizona State is out. Oregon (14-10, 6-9) has
decent power ratings but needs to win its final games (Oregon
State, Cal, Stanford) to squeeze in.
</P>
<P>
   __ Coaching changes: The best job available is San Diego State,
which has a new arena and a new conference (the Mountain West) to
offer. The Aztecs would love Utah's Rick Majerus _ he's arguably
the best coach in the game _ but Majerus has no reason to leave his
kingdom in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Harrick, weary of Rhode Island and longing for the West
Coast, wants the San Diego State job and might get it. The Aztecs
want an established head coach to turn the program around.
</P>
<P>
   If not Majerus or Harrick, perhaps Gonzaga's Dan Monson. San
Diego State athletic director Rick Bey hired Monson's father, Don,
at Oregon years ago. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Long Beach State probably needs to finish strongly for Wayne
Morgan to save his job. He was a questionable choice in 1996 _ a
Syracuse assistant with no roots in Southern California _ and he
has done nothing to reverse that perception.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the Morgan experience, the 49ers might pursue a
proven head coach. If they don't, UCLA assistant Michael Holton
seems a logical candidate. A Pasadena native and former UCLA
player, Holton knows the area, has relationships with high school
coaches and would bring players to the Pyramid. What Holton lacks _
head-coaching experience _ can be overcome with time and a veteran
assistant. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Four names to watch for the Nevada-Reno job: Northern Arizona
coach Ben Howland, one of best young coaches in the game; Monson,
ditto; Utah assistant Donny Daniels; Stanford assistant Trent
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   __ Schea stuff: Former UCLA recruit and current Long Beach City
College player Schea Cotton attended the UCLA-Syracuse game. Cotton
recently won his appeal to the NCAA and is eligible at a four-year
school next season.
</P>
<P>
   He said he has a working list of six schools, with a tie to
each: Rhode Island (Harrick); Alabama (ex-UCLA assistant Mark
Gottfried); USC (it's local); Oregon State (he's buddies with guard
Dino Tanner); Connecticut (he attended prep school there), and
South Florida (ex-Long Beach State coach Seth Greenberg).
</P>
<P>
   One place you absolutely, positively will not see Cotton next
year: UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: Duke sophomore and Orange County native Chris
Burgess is unhappy with his playing time and might transfer. UCLA,
Utah and Brigham Young are possible destinations. Burgess' plans
might change if sophomore center Elton Brand turns pro, as
expected. . . .
</P>
<P>
   The most important result of the NBA collective bargaining
agreement _ as it relates to the college game _ is the rigid
slotting of salaries for free agents and rookies, which might
reduce the need for agents. For instance, Arizona guard Jason Terry
is expected to hire an hourly attorney, not a full-time agent, to
examine his contract. . . .
</P>
<P>
   St. Mary's manchild Russ Millard played last weekend _ against
his coach's advice _ for the first time in almost 18 months. In 14
minutes against Santa Clara, Millard was 0 for 6 from the field but
changed the game defensively with his 7-3, 350-pound frame. Watch
for Millard, a fourth-year junior plagued by foot problems, to
enter the NBA. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Washington State senior Steve Slotemaker disclosed last week
that he has suffered from clinical depression since high school.
During a trip through the Columbia River Gorge several years ago,
Slotemaker said he considered driving into the water. . . .
</P>
<P>
   It was obvious to anyone who watched Paul Pierce play at Kansas
that nine NBA teams blundered when they passed on him in last
year's draft. Now it's apparent to THEM. . . .
</P>
<P>
   In next year's Wooden Classic, Stanford will play Auburn and
Duke will meet USC. By the way, the event is scheduled for Nov. 27,
the same day USC plays Louisiana Tech in football and UCLA faces
Iona in basketball. Nice timing. . . .
</P>
<P>
   And finally: College basketball says goodbye to one of its great
arenas this weekend when North Carolina State plays its final game
in storied Reynolds Coliseum _ former home of Jim Valvano, Chris
Washburn, Lorenzo Charles, Monty Towe and the greatest non-center
in NCAA history, David Thompson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
