r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ENCOUNTER-IMAX-REVIEW     02-24 0469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENCOUNTER-IMAX-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN `ENCOUNTER' OF THE 3-D KIND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients on Friday, Feb. 26 or
thereafter) 
OUR RATING:  3 STAR S  
By DAVID BLOOM 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Nearly half a century after its cheese-drenched
heyday, 3-D film may be ready to make a comeback of sorts,
especially in the large-format theaters created by companies such
as IMAX and Burbank's Iwerks Corp.
</P>
<P>
   If that's to happen, of course, it'll take more fun, eye-popping
titles such as ``Encounter in the Third Dimension,'' which is
opening today at the IMAX theater at the California ScienCenter
museum in Exposition Park. It also plays at Edwards IMAX theaters,
Irvine Spectrum and Ontario Mills Mall.
</P>
<P>
   The 39-minute piece features Stuart Pankin as a bumbling
professor who enlists Elvira, a saucy flying-saucer assistant,
clips of top 3-D theme-park attractions and vivid,
computer-generated virtual sets to explain the science and history
of stereoscopic photography and film.
</P>
<P>
   The film does a nice job briskly tracing forward from Sir
Charles Wheatstone's 1838 discovery of stereoscopic still
photography, through the early 1950s 3-D movie craze up to recent
3-D theme-park attractions.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, the film also gently explains the simple science
behind tricking the eyes into believing a two-dimensional picture
has depth and volume, just as in real life.
</P>
<P>
   Just as importantly, however, the film is a treat to look at,
which of course is the whole point of 3-D.
</P>
<P>
   The large-format screen is partly responsible for that, as is
the use of mostly computer-generated sets. Both factors allow the
film to sidestep the limits of 3-D live-action films, paradoxically
making the virtual sets look more ``real'' than ones made out of
atoms instead of digital bits.
</P>
<P>
   The film also benefits from clips excerpted from some of the
most stirring 3-D film attractions around, including the
``Terminator 2 3-D'' ride now being installed in Universal Studios
Hollywood, ``Journey to the Center of the Earth'' and ``Return to
Dino Island.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Journey'' clip is particularly long and wonderful,
providing a great visual ride without going anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, you'll still have to wear glasses to enjoy this ride, in
this case clown-sized if lightweight polarized lenses. But you
quickly forget them (as long as you don't tilt your head and
misalign the polarization) in the onslaught of
close-enough-to-touch eye candy.
</P>
<P>
   And ``Encounter'' still suffers from its own occasional
outbreaks of cheesy jokes and one overly long cheesecake shot.
</P>
<P>
   But there's little enough of that, and the film moves along
briskly, providing an entertaining science lesson as it goes.
Overall, this is a multi-dimensional ``Encounter'' of the best
kind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
