<HEADER>
A8281 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TYPHOID-OUTBREAK25-CO     02-24 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TYPHOID-OUTBREAK25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mamey products pose potential health risk for nation, officials
say
 &HT;    By Peter Donald
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ While imported frozen mamey products
were pulled from Florida's stores and restaurants because of a
typhoid fever outbreak, they are readily available in cities with
large Hispanic populations such as New York and Los Angeles, posing
a potential national health risk, officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Frozen mamey, a tropical fruit grown in South Florida and the
Caribbean, is used to make ice cream, sherbert and the popular
shakes known as ``batidos'' in the Hispanic community.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the imported product is not safe in Florida, why would it
be safe anywhere else?'' said Terry McElroy, a spokesman for the
Florida Department of Agriculture, which halted sales of frozen
mamey products in the state last week. The federal government
``will have to make a decision on this.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Food and Drug Administration is warning consumers not
to eat frozen mamey because of its preliminary epidemiological
links to typhoid fever, but it has not blocked imports of frozen
mamey products.
</P>
<P>
   So far, officials said, there are no signs that the outbreak of
the bacterial disease has spread beyond Florida.
</P>
<P>
   An FDA spokeswoman said the agency's policy would not change
because of a single outbreak, but that surveillance of frozen mamey
products had increased.
</P>
<P>
   She said communicating the dangers of frozen mamey was
complicated by language barriers, as well as a large undocumented
population fearful of authorities: `It's hard to get the word out
in the underground.''
</P>
<P>
   FDA investigators are focusing their inquiry on frozen mamey and
where it comes from, specifically Guatemala, Honduras and the
Dominican Republic, Miami-Dade health officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Simultaneously, the federal Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention are warning health departments across the nation about
the Florida outbreak and its possible connection to frozen mamey.
</P>
<P>
   Typhoid fever, a bacterial disease characterized by sustained
fever, headache, fatigue, constipation, appetite loss and a rash,
can be treated with antibiotics. In more than 99 percent of cases
treated, the patients survive.
</P>
<P>
   Another suspected case was identified in the Miami area Monday.
That brings the total number of Florida cases to 15, including
three in Palm Beach County. The outbreak is considered unusual
because none of the patients had traveled to foreign countries
where typhoid fever is more common.
</P>
<P>
   Health investigators have reached the preliminary conclusion
that frozen mamey products were contaminated with the bacteria that
causes typhoid fever; they found that the sick people were far more
likely than healthy people to have eaten frozen mamey.
</P>
<P>
   Typhoid fever germs are excreted in the stool of an infected
person and can be spread if they contaminate food or water.
</P>
<P>
   FDA investigators are focusing on a processing plant in
Guatemala where more than one frozen mamey brand is manufactured,
an agriculture official said Wednesday. The FDA has issued a
consumer warning about El Sembrador, a frozen mamey product from
Guatemala that the agency said was found in the freezers of all the
patients as well as in restaurants where some of the sick people
drank it in shakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That appears to be the common link,'' said McElroy. ``And it
appears that more than one product is handled by the same processor
in Guatemala. We're not sure, but we have our suspicions of one
plant.''
</P>
<P>
   FDA officials said they're investigating where frozen mamey is
processed and distributed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're working on it nonstop,'' said Dr. Mary Jo Trepka,
Miami-Dade's director of epidemiology and disease control. ``I'm
sure they're going to be doing more things. It's their call.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, tests on samples of confiscated frozen mamey products
have been inconclusive, but all the results aren't in, officials
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The tests done so far have not found any salmonella typhi, the
bacteria that causes typhoid fever, said Dr. Jean Malecki, Palm
Beach County's health director.
</P>
<P>
   Due to sanitation and health concerns, the federal government
has banned imports of fresh mamey from the very Caribbean countries
that ship the frozen product into the United States _ even though
officials have said Salmonella typhi can survive freezing
temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that unprocessed fruits from Guatemala have harbored
toxins and bacteria,'' one state official said. ``They can't be
imported into this country. Why would we let the frozen product
in?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
