<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8291 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JASPER25-COX     02-24 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ailing father defends son convicted of dragging death
 &HT;    By Denise Gamino
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ A parent's anguish filled a Jasper County
courtroom Wednesday as the weeping father of a convicted racist
killer pleaded for his son's life.
</P>
<P>
   But John William ``Bill'' King refused to be in the courtroom as
his ailing father, sitting in a wheelchair and breathing through an
oxygen tube, spoke to jurors who must decide if King should go to
death row for dragging a black man to death last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald King's emotional testimony came after his son appeared to
nap while a psychologist for his defense acknowledged that he never
showed a hint of remorse for the harrowing murder of James Byrd Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The jury will begin deliberating today whether to give the white
supremacist a life sentence or death. The jury found him guilty
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   King, 24, sat in a holding room adjacent to the courtroom while
his father told the jury, ``Anything is better than losing him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've invested a lot of love in that boy. I'd hate to think
we're going to lose him,'' said Ronald King, a retired lumber
worker. ``I guess, as a daddy, I'll never be able to resign myself
to that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I love that boy. You don't have to love what (children) do,''
said the father _ the only character witness for a son whose
bigotry and anger are so intense a psychiatrist testified that he
should die to keep society from future harm.
</P>
<P>
   Several jurors looked at their laps when the elder King became
distraught and put both hands to his face to hide his sobs. One
juror never looked at the murderer's father, choosing instead to
train his gaze on a courtroom wall.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd's family watched from the front two rows of the courtroom,
and one of the murder victim's sisters wiped her eye.
</P>
<P>
   Renee Mullins, the eldest of Byrd's three children, approached
Ronald King outside the courtroom after his testimony and gave him
a hug.
</P>
<P>
   ``God bless you,'' Mullins said.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Boatner, one of Byrd's six sisters, also hugged him, and
said: ``He's in God's hands. Put it in God's hands. God loves
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   King was convicted Tuesday of kidnapping and dragging Byrd down
a country road outside Jasper until he was beheaded. Evidence
showed that King wanted to kill a black person to gain credibility
for a new white supremacy gang he was organizing.
</P>
<P>
   Two of King's white friends _ Shawn Allen Berry, 24, and
Lawrence Russell Brewer, 31 _ also await trial for allegedly
participating in the gruesome death that stunned people around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the jury heard testimony about Bill King's inability
to control his anger, including an incident in January when he
smashed a television in his Jasper County jail cell in front of a
jailer who had inquired about noise he had been making.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, 'If you think that's a noise, that's nothing,''
jailer Kenneth Primrose said. ``He picked up the TV and threw it at
the stool.''
</P>
<P>
   Primrose showed the jurors an 8-inch homemade knife and a noose
fashioned from a radio cord that were found hidden in Bill King's
cell after he broke the television.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors also put on the witness stand Dr. Edward Gripon, a
forensic psychiatrist from Beaumont. He testified that Bill King
poses a threat to society because of his intense racist beliefs and
the torturous nature of Byrd's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel he would pose a continued threat for future acts of
violence,'' Gripon said.
</P>
<P>
   Crimes like Byrd's murder are ``so extreme and so dramatic, they
remove all doubt what the person is capable of,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Quijano, a former chief psychologist for the Texas prison
system who testified for the defense, said Bill King likely would
continue to commit crimes in the free world but not in prison. He
said a life sentence _ which would imprison Bill King for at least
40 years _ would protect society.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be about 64 if released, and the probability of people
at age 64 committing acts of violence is very low,'' Quijano said.
</P>
<P>
   But, under cross-examination by assistant U.S. Attorney John
Stevens, Quijano acknowledged that Bill King has a law-breaking
history, intensely bitter feelings toward society and no remorse
for killing Byrd.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one certain way we can have a say in control, in ensuring
innocent people are never harmed again by (such) a defendant _ who
has proven clearly that he is a danger _ is for him to be
executed,'' Stevens said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is true,'' Quijano said.
</P>
<P>
   As Quijano testified about Bill King's lack of remorse, the
convicted killer slumped in his chair and appeared to be dozing.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the courtroom, defense lawyer C. Haden ``Sonny'' Cribbs
Jr. said that Bill King had not wanted his father to testify and
chose to leave the courtroom because he feared he would be overcome
with emotion if he watched.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a proud man, Bill is,'' Cribbs said. ``Sometimes it
becomes unmanly to show emotions, and I think maybe that's possibly
was happening.''
</P>
<P>
   An audiovisual feed allowed Bill King to see and hear what
occurred in the courtroom while he sat in the holding room.
</P>
<P>
   Jasper County District Attorney Guy James Gray said Bill King's
decision to leave the courtroom may have hurt him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to be the opposite of what you ought to do,'' Gray
said.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Wednesday, peddlers of James Byrd Jr. memorial T-shirts
and hats were ordered by state District Judge Joe Bob Golden to
stop selling the items outside the courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   The Byrd family requested the order after alleging that the
vendors had breached a contract to give some of the proceeds to the
James Byrd Jr. Foundation for Racial Healing. The family created
the foundation with donations that poured in after Byrd's June 7
murder.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
