<HEADER>
A8295 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IBM-PENTIUM-NYT &LR;      02-24 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IBM-PENTIUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IBM SAYS NEW FEATURE INCREASES PENTIUM'S SECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Responding to a growing controversy over a security feature in
Intel Corp.'s new Pentium III microprocessor, IBM said Wednesday
that it would ship Pentium III computers with the feature hidden by
the computer's hardware.
</P>
<P>
   Intel has responded to protests about the feature, a built-in
serial number, by offering a specific software program, known as a
utility program, to prevent the number's being read by other
software. IBM's remedy goes further and hides the number at the
hardware level, which is harder to penetrate.
</P>
<P>
   IBM made the announcement yesterday in a letter to the Center
for Democracy and Technology, a Washington-based privacy group that
has asked the nation's major computer makers to provide computer
users more security than is offered by Intel's software remedy.
</P>
<P>
   Intel announced the processor serial number in January as a tool
for authenticating documents, electronic messages and copyrighted
material. Privacy groups, however, asserted that the number could
be used to track people surfing the Internet. Privacy advocates
have traditionally opposed universal numbers, including Social
Security and driver's license numbers, arguing that they can
simplify tracking an individual across many computer sources by
companies or agencies that create digital dossiers on people.
</P>
<P>
   In response to critics, Intel agreed to give computer makers the
software to switch the feature off in computers sold to
individuals.
</P>
<P>
   But privacy activists have raised questions about the security
of the software used to control the number. In recent days, editors
at the German magazine C't said they had developed a program that
could read the number without a computer user's knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   IBM said it would give consumers more security by moving the
control of the feature into the computer's basic input-output
system, a group of instructions permanently stored in a set of
silicon chips.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although there are constructive ways to use the processor ID
feature to validate user identification, there are also legitimate
privacy concerns raised by the potential misuses of this feature,''
Christopher Caine, IBM's vice president for government affairs,
wrote in a letter responding to Center for Democracy and
Technology.
</P>
<P>
   Intel has stood by its decision to offer the serial number as a
security and copyright protection feature. A company spokesman said
it had been recommending that computer makers place a switch in the
basic input-output system of each machine and that it be set to off
when the computer was shipped from the factory.
</P>
<P>
   With the switch shipped in the off position, consumers have to
go intentionally to the computer's basic input-output system setup
screen when the computer is booted and switch the feature on if
they choose to permit the number to be seen by a software
application.
</P>
<P>
   ``From our perspective it provides another layer of choice and
control from the consumer's perspective,'' said Tom Waldrop, an
Intel spokesman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-99 2210EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
