<SLUG> BC-CADBURY-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CADBURY'S EARNINGS UP, BUT COMPANY STILL FACES QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Cadbury Schweppes PLC reported a 6 percent gain in
1998 earnings Wednesday despite slower sales, and it tried to
portray the results as a success. But the British confections and
beverage company found itself facing questions from analysts and
shareholders about its plans.
</P>
<P>
   The questions came following the release of the company's 1998
financial results in London, which showed earnings rose to 609
million pounds, or $980.3 million, from 575 million pounds the year
before. Overall sales fell 2.7 percent, to 4.1 billion pounds, or
$6.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the profit came from the confectionery business, which
rose 6 percent, even with the turmoil in Russia, one of Cadbury's
major markets.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street seemed unimpressed. Shares in the company, traded as
American depository receipts, fell $4.625, or 7.3 percent, to close
at $63.50.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reaction may have been the lack of strategic detail
offered by company executives, who startled the beverage industry
in December by agreeing to sell nearly all of Cadbury's non-U.S.
beverage businesses to the Coca-Cola Co.
</P>
<P>
   The $1.85 billion deal has led to speculation that the company
may be planning an eventual exit from all its soft-drink
operations. The company reiterated Wednesday that it plans to focus
on the U.S. soft-drink business and on its international
confectionery brands.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, Cadbury owns Dr Pepper, 7-Up, Crush,
Canada Dry and several other brands, which have contributed strong
profits in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Cadbury has also been under pressure to describe how it plans to
invest the proceeds from the Coca-Cola deal. Another $798 million
is expected to be raised from the sale of bottlers the company owns
outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The company has listed acquisitions in the confectionery
business, which will become the largest part of its operations once
the sale is completed later this year, as a priority. Additional
bottler consolidation in the United States has also been mentioned,
as has a stock repurchase.
</P>
<P>
   Cadbury executives said next to nothing about their strategy
going forward, except that they would have one. ``As we complete
the value-based restructuring of our businesses, strategic growth
will clearly become the new focus for us,'' said John Sunderland,
the company's chief executive. ``A share buyback remains one of
those options.''
</P>
<P>
   The company is widely believed to be examining several possible
acquisitions, but gave no details.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
