</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KERRY-RUN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KERRY EXPECTED TO DECIDE AGAINST ENTERING 2000 RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Key advisers to Senator John F. Kerry say they expect
the senator to tell supporters in Boston this weekend that he will
not enter the 2000 race for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is of the view that he's going to say he's going to run
for president,'' said one longtime adviser who asked to remain
anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   After months of hand-wringing and intense conversations with
potential financial backers, Kerry has not relayed a final decision
to anyone in his large inner circle. And the senator could not be
reached for comment Wednesday. But key advisers in Boston and
Washington have grown increasingly doubtful that Kerry will move
ahead with a campaign for the Democratic presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, Kerry backers have said he waited too long to
investigate the possibility of a presidential run and that he does
not have enough time to mount a credible challenge against Vice
President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   While many politicians spent much of the last year or two
meeting with activists in New Hampshire and Iowa, Kerry did not.
When Senators Bob Kerrey of Nebraska and Paul Wellstone of
Minnesota, both Democrats, said they would not run at the end of
last year and the beginning of this year, Kerry was only just
beginning to investigate the possibility of a presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of the last two months, Kerry never visited
Iowa, the preeminent caucus state. And his two visits to New
Hampshire, the first-in-the-nation primary state, were cursory at
best.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democratic activists who would have allied themselves with
Kerrey of Nebraska, or with Richard A. Gephardt, the House minority
leader, who never received so much as a phone call from Kerry.
Gore, on the other hand, scooped up major players, while former New
Jersey Senator Bill Bradley has attracted attention from Democrats
who are less prominent in their party.
</P>
<P>
   But Kerry and his aides have argued vehemently that lining up
activists was the least pressing need. At the top of the list,
Kerry was trying to come up with a rationale for his candidacy
against Gore, and he was trying to line up financial backing.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Kerry traveled across the country to fund-raising
events, working to pay off his remaining 1996 Senate debt. At the
same time, he spoke to Democratic money-raisers about whether they
would help him pull together the approximately $20 million
necessary to run for president. In Boston, however, many of his
most ardent financial supporters, such as Alan Solomont, Elaine
Schuster and Steve Grossman, had told him that they were already
committed to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   William Verge, the Rockingham County Democratic chairman, has
been talking up Kerry's candidacy in New Hampshire. Wednesday he
said he is not sure what Kerry will do, though he said he knows
that ``the word on the street is h's not going to run.''
</P>
<P>
   Following an afternoon conversation with Kerry, Verge said, ``He
doesn't want to get in unless he thinks he can win.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Vallelly, a longtime friend, recently put the odds against a
Kerry bid at 75-25.
</P>
<P>
   Another adviser later concurred with Vallelly's odds, but said
the 25 percent chance of running was very real.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent appearance on CNN's ``Inside Politics,'' Kerry
appeared to be talking himself out of a presidential bid as he
talked up Gore's financial and political advantages.
</P>
<P>
   He also reacted defensively to the notion that he was taking too
long to make a decision. In fact, Kerry had said all along that he
would wait until President Clinton's impeachment trial had ended,
and then he would take a couple of weeks to make his decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not agonizing about this, incidentally, and I don't have
any great _ there's no Hamlet routine going on,'' Kerry said.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Rosenblith, a former Kerry staffer who has talked
extensively with Kerry this week, described the presidential
decision as a highly personal one. He said it is premature to count
Kerry in or out of the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's trying mightily hard to come to grips with this,''
Rosenblith said.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry is expected to attend a meeting of the Democratic Policy
Committee in Washington Friday. He is supposed to fly from Boston
to Colorado on Saturday to give a speech, returning to Boston on
Sunday. Kerry is expected to announce his decision in Boston, and
it could come as early as Friday evening, or perhaps on Sunday or
Monday, sources said.
</P>
</TEXT>
