<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-XYLAN-RUMORS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPECULATION SENDS XYLAN SHARES SOARING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALABASAS, Calif. -- Shares of computer-networking specialist
Xylan Corp. jumped 16 percent Wednesday amid takeover speculation
that has seen shares of the company climb 39 percent over the past
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's obviously something going on here,'' said Andy
Schopick, an analyst with Nutmeg Securities. ``There could be a
buyout materializing.''
</P>
<P>
   Xylan rose $3.5625 to $25.5625 a share Wednesday with 6.2
million shares changing hands, more than six times its three-month
daily average. It was the highest close since last July and marks a
clear rebound from a September slump that saw shares fall under $10
on worries of slow sales to Alcatel SA and International Business
Machines, Xylan's largest customers.
</P>
<P>
   Shares have climbed nearly 40 percent over the past week with
several analysts saying Xylan should be trading above $30. The
company is worth $1.08 billion based on Wednesday's price.
</P>
<P>
   The latest surge may have been fueled by Xylan Chief Executive
Steve Kim, who said Tuesday at a conference that he was
``frustrated'' by the stock price and asserted Xylan is ``very
focused on increasing shareholder value.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts believe Paris-based Alcatel, which recently bought
Oregon-based Packet Engines for $315 million to enlarge its network
offerings, is a possible buyer.
</P>
<P>
   Calabasas-based Xylan posted a 63 percent gain in 1998 profits
to $39.4 million, or 83 cents a share, on a 65 percent rise in
sales to $347.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Schopick, who has a price target of $30 a share, said investors
had been focused mostly on major data-networking players until the
recent increases. ``This stock had kind of been left behind,'' he
said. ``It's a quality company, one of the few with established
presence that remains independent. The financial performance over
the past couple of years has been exceptional.''
</P>
<P>
   The question of remaining independent is the key long-term issue
for Xylan, Schopick said, adding, ``They're playing in a world of
giants with intense competition from people like Cisco and
Lucent.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisco's market capitalization, based on Wednesday's close, is
approximately $157.9 billion; Lucent's is $136.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
