<HEADER>
A8304 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-PATAKI-ALBANY-NYT &LR;      02-24 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PATAKI-ALBANY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI SHUNS ALBANY'S MENTALITY AND ITS GEOGRAPHY 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Gov. George Pataki returned to Albany on Tuesday
afternoon after two weeks away, a hiatus born not of a fact-finding
trip or bout of political wanderlust or even a vacation. The
governor had been governing, but, as usual, not from the seat of
government.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his recent predecessors, Pataki has not made Albany the
center of his life. His regular absences from here provide insight
into not only his work style but also his seeming ambivalence
toward a place that often feels like an insular bureaucratic
kingdom _ the embodiment, in other words, of the kind of expansive
government that Republicans like Pataki continually assail.
</P>
<P>
   The governor does not live full time in the lavish Executive
Mansion, choosing to remain with his family in his own 24-room
Victorian home in Garrison, 50 miles north of New York City and 100
miles south of Albany.
</P>
<P>
   When the Legislature is in session _ typically two or three days
a week in the winter and spring _ Pataki will usually journey to
the capital by car or helicopter and stay overnight at the
Executive Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   On other days, more often than not, he is driven or takes a
helicopter from Garrison to his New York City office near Grand
Central Terminal, which is where he has worked for most of the last
two weeks. (He also delivered a speech in Missouri and attended a
National Governors' Association meeting in Washington.)
</P>
<P>
   It is a routine that has left some Albany denizens feeling
slighted, and exposed the governor to sniping that he is disengaged
and aloof from the daily labors of state government. The president,
this line of thinking goes, would never regularly shun the White
House for a faraway home and auxiliary office.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's tendency to be out of Albany has attracted attention in
part because of his management approach, which is to focus so
intently on certain matters _ such as cutting taxes, improving the
state's fiscal condition and protecting the environment _ that he
sometimes leaves the impression that he finds other policy areas
uninteresting.
</P>
<P>
   His habits differ starkly from those of his immediate
predecessor, Mario Cuomo, who was famously obsessive about
hunkering down in Albany, often taking late-night, long-distance
flights in order to avoid spending another day away. For much of
his tenure, Cuomo, who once went on a 48-hour trip to Argentina,
had no other residence but the Executive Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   Such contrasts raise an obvious question: Does it matter where a
governor works in the state, particularly in an age of the
Internet, fax machines and other gadgetry that have turned so many
people into telecommuters? If Pataki is not in Albany, does that
mean that the $70 billion state government is rudderless?
</P>
<P>
   Pataki says emphatically no, and some of Cuomo's former aides
agree, saying that they were often frustrated by how wedded Cuomo
was to the Capitol. And even though Cuomo was around a lot, he
often had fractious relations with the Legislature. Some lawmakers
still remember when he referred to them in a speech as monkeys.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki goes out of his way to say nice things about Albany as a
place to live, but when he discusses the city, there is a hint of
the conservative, big-government-is-the-enemy oratory that he has
been honing as he tries to broaden his national reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely essential to get out of the Capitol and out of
Albany to be able to govern effectively,'' he said in an interview.
``Ultimately, it's constricting to talk with the same people and
read the same papers and meet with the same interests as you do on
a regular basis in the capital. There is no question that just as
you have a Beltway mentality in Washington, you have a capital
mentality in Albany. It's extremely important to realize that it's
a big state with diverse interests and real people who live outside
the capital.''
</P>
<P>
   Such talk irritates some local officials, who say residents are
put off by the governor's absence _ though it should be noted that
the city is a Democratic bastion. ``A great number of people in the
Albany area are offended by the fact that he doesn't use the
governor's mansion as his home,'' said state Sen. Neil Breslin, an
Albany Democrat. ``Having said that, he has been very helpful to
the Albany area in terms of promoting legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki does not apologize for not moving into the Executive
Mansion, saying that he promised his wife and four children when he
ran for governor in 1994 that he would do his best to avoid
disrupting their lives. And while his many trips between Albany,
Garrison and New York City cost the state money, his decision to
stay in Garrison costs him money. If he had wanted, he could have
sold his home, as Cuomo did, and lived for free in the Executive
Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the mansion, and we have wonderful people there,''
Pataki said. ``But for an 11-year-old kid, it's far better to have
your own room, where you have to pick up your own socks.''
</P>
<P>
   The paradox, of course, is that Pataki is less popular in New
York City than Cuomo was, though Pataki spends more time there than
did his predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Cuomo declined to criticize Pataki for spurning
the mansion. Cuomo pointed out that he was often concerned about
the impact of Mansion living on his son Christopher. He recalled
how he once castigated Christopher for requesting that his dinner
be delivered to his room.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Cuomo, echoing criticism sometimes heard around the Capitol,
suggested that Pataki's unwillingness to spend more time in Albany
might hurt his ability to lead. Cuomo said that by immersing
himself in the social and day-to-day life of the city, he got a
better sense of state government.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot that happens on the streets of Albany,'' said
Cuomo, who was defeated by Pataki in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki essentially responds that there is also a lot that
happens elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting out of the political setting is a positive thing,'' he
said. ``It's one of the reasons that I have been so effective.''
</P>
<P>
   After alighting here on Tuesday afternoon, Pataki attended a
crime conference Wednesday morning. By mid-afternoon, he had
already traveled by helicopter to New York City, where he plans to
work the rest of the week. He had spent less than 24 hours in the
state capital.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
