u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-700&AMP;ADD-N     02-24 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCGWIRE KNOWS HE HAS A TOUGH ACT TO FOLLOW 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUPITER, Fla. _ First he sent batting &UR;  &LR; practice baseballs
soaring majestically over the left &UR;  &LR; field fence on Field 1 of the
St. Louis Cardinals' spring training complex. Nothing new there.
His batting &UR;  &LR; practice shows alone are worth the price of admission.
</P>
<P>
   Then he patiently signed a plethora of autographs for eager,
polite fans. Nothing different about that either. He is one of the
more accommodating players for signing his name on balls, pictures,
magazine covers, hats and assorted other surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   But then, once inside the complex, Mark McGwire revealed an
aspect of his phenomenal performance of 1998 that he had not
previously articulated: holding onto the home run record, McGwire
said Wednesday, was achieved in the face of greater pressure than
breaking the record initially.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have to say they're very, very close, but I think the
pressure of holding onto the record was greater than getting 62,''
McGwire said referring to Sammy Sosa's also reaching the mark after
the Cardinals' first full-squad workout of spring training.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire, speaking in a wide-ranging hourlong news conference
before reporters and television cameras, was five months removed
from his September to remember. It was five months in which he
traveled to Australia once and Mexico twice for vacations, met the
Pope and kissed his ring in St. Louis, took a celebrity turn on the
television show ``Mad About You,'' winding up in bed with Helen
Hunt, and heard hundreds of unsolicited stories from fawning fans
about where they were and what they were doing when he hit No. 62.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire broke the 37-year-old record of Roger Maris the night of
Sept. 8. Five days later, Sammy Sosa, having his own awesome
season, tied him. On Sept. 23, Sosa caught McGwire again at 65 and
actually passed him for 45 minutes with No. 66 on Sept. 25. But
that would be Sosa's last home run, and McGwire would hit two each
in the final two games of the season. Pressure-filled mission
accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sammy Sosa had a pretty damn good year,'' McGwire said. ``He
was right there with me. When I broke the record that night, I knew
there was a lot of time left in the season and I knew what he was
doing. Trying to hold on to keep it and own the record, there was a
lot of pressure for that because he was right there.''
</P>
<P>
   In discussing the record and a variety of other related
subjects, McGwire was as amiable as he was during the final stages
of last season, which, in retrospect, he handled remarkably well
considering the attention focused on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing could be any worse than what I went through the last
two months of last season,'' he said. ``I don't think there's ever
been another athlete to be singled out in one sport like I was
singled out the last two months of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   His use of a controversial supplement, androstenedione, brought
unwanted attention, but Wednesday he continued to defend his use of
it.
</P>
<P>
   Saying he was still taking the testosterone-producing substance,
McGwire said: ``It's legal. Major League Baseball is not the IOC.
It has absolutely nothing to do with me hitting a baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Why use it then? ``It has something to do with me getting
through the workouts during the season when you're worn down,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball has commissioned a study by two Harvard medical
researchers to determine what androstenedione does when a player
takes it. The results of the study will help baseball officials
determine whether to ban it as the International Olympic Committee
does.
</P>
<P>
   If it is banned, will McGwire's use of it taint the record?
``No,'' he said. ``It has nothing to do with hitting a baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   The ball that McGwire hit for No. 70, on the other hand, has
become tainted, he said, because it was bought at auction for $3
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty ridiculous,'' McGwire said of the auction price.
``There's one place and one place only where that ball belongs, and
that's the Hall of Fame. I said if there's going to be any money
exchanged, I will have nothing to do with the ball. I will never
touch it. I don't care to ever see it, because it's not in the
right place.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Will there be a No. 71 ball in the future to be sold or placed
in the Hall of Fame? McGwire was skeptical about his or anyone
else's chances of breaking the record, but he said: ``Anything is
possible. But in order to break 70 home runs, I would have to think
you'd have to be at the 40 plateau in home runs by the All-Star
break.'' McGwire had 37 at the break last season.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to speculate about how many home runs he might hit
this coming season, but he has hit more than 50 each of the last
three years, a major league record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've set a standard of hitting 50,'' he said. ``Even
with what I did last year, a standard of hitting 50 is still a very
good number. I'm sure no matter what I do this year, if I don't
reach 70 again, someone will say I had an off year.''
</P>
<P>
   And if he hits ``only'' 50?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll feel pretty good,'' he said. ``If I hit 50, it means I've
reached the 50 plateau and that's pretty important.'' He has 457
career home runs.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire injected one ominous note into his comments. Talking
about the major comeback baseball made last year, three years after
the end of its disastrous strike, he said it would be awful if
players and owners had another labor dispute when the current
agreement expires, either after the 2000 or 2001 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm scared to death to see what happens after 2001,'' he said.
``I sure hope what happened in '94 doesn't happen. The salaries are
getting up there. You can see it now. The small markets are going
to a place where they can't compete right away. I hope we can get
something done before that.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``If we had a work stoppage in 2001, I'd be so
disgusted I'd walk away from the game.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
