<HEADLINE>
TURNER ANNOUNCES PLANS FOR SOUTHERN CABLE NETWORK  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., Ga., Miss. Tenn. S.C., N.C.)   By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Turner Broadcasting System Inc., which grew from the seed of a
local Atlanta television station, Wednesday announced a return to
those roots with plans for a 24-hour regional cable network called
Turner South.
</P>
<P>
   Starting next fall, Turner South will be available in Alabama,
Georgia, Mississippi, Tennessee, South Carolina and parts of North
Carolina, said Bill Burke, president of TBS Superstation, who also
will head the new network. TBS is a division of Time Warner &UR;  &LR; Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Turner South will feature movies and television series from
Turner Broadcasting's library, regional news from CNN, games from
Turner's three Atlanta sports franchises (the baseball Braves,
basketball Hawks and hockey Thrashers), supplemented by some
original programs made especially for Southerners.
</P>
<P>
   Among the original shows are a series based on the magazine
Southern Living (owned by Time Inc., a sister company), a weekly
country-music show from the Bluebird Cafe in Nashville and another
featuring the Atlanta comedy improvisation troupe Whole World
Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Among the repeat programs, Burke said shows that would have
strong appeal in the South include ``The Andy Griffith Show'' and a
series called ``WCW Classics,'' with popular pro wrestling matches
from the past _ including bouts featuring ``Jesse (The Governor)
Ventura,'' as he put it.
</P>
<P>
   Burke said many Southerners identify with Turner Broadcasting,
which began as a local station, WTBS, that Ted Turner turned into a
satellite-distributed ``superstation'' in 1976. Later the company
developed cable networks like CNN, TBS and TNT. Burke said Turner
South would inevitably compete with those channels in that region,
but he hoped it would draw viewers away from USA and other general
entertainment networks.
</P>
<P>
   The company has begun talks with advertisers, and with cable
operators to gain distribution, Burke said, estimating that the
region has more than six million cable subscribers. Florida is not
part of the new network, he said, because Turner does not own the
rights in Florida to all its programming, especially in sports.
</P>
<P>
   The new network will enable the parent company to make further
use of its programming assets, at a minimal start-up cost. ``We
have a lot of appealing programming that's not being utilized,''
Burke said, on Turner's other networks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
