<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-CRIME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYC COLUMN: THE BIG CITY AFTER VICTORY IN THE WAR ON CRIME
</HEADLINE>
   (lh) 
 By JOHN TIERNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; NEW YORK _ &UR;  &LR; The police are not yet confiscating the shoes of
jaywalkers, but Mayor Rudolph Giuliani is taking up just about
every other righteous suggestion that has come along. Now that
patrol officers have started seizing the cars of people arrested
for drunken driving, and tactical units are expanding the offensive
against drug dealers, the war on crime is escalating once again.
</P>
<P>
   But why now? Might this not be a better time to savor past
victories? Aggressive tactics eventually yield diminishing returns.
At the moment, besides offending people on the street and appalling
civil libertarians, the tactics may not even be doing much good
against crime. They might even be increasing people's propensity to
break the law.
</P>
<P>
   The statistics that guide Giuliani and the department do not
include a vital bit of data: how aggressive tactics affect people's
attitudes. The researchers who have measured this find that it can
be the most important consequence of police work.
</P>
<P>
   ``People's attitude toward the police is shaped less by the
crime rate than by how they're treated by officers,'' said Tom
Tyler, a professor of psychology at New York University who has
tracked attitudes toward the police in Chicago, Los Angeles and
Oakland, Calif. ``In our surveys, being treated properly _ with
respect and dignity and fairness _ is two to three times more
important to people than what happens to the crime rate in their
neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyler's findings help explain why so many black and Hispanic New
Yorkers are angry at the police even though their neighborhoods
have enjoyed some of the most dramatic drops in crime. They're more
concerned about the disproportionate number of black and Hispanic
men being stopped by the police, which seems especially galling now
that relatively few criminals are on the street. And when something
goes wrong, as in the recent fatal shooting in the Bronx, they're
ready to assume the worst about police motives.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, many New Yorkers may end up resenting the crackdown
on drunken driving, no matter what good it does. If people think
it's unfair for the police to summarily seize a car without a trial
_ and perhaps try to keep it even if the driver isn't convicted _
that inequity could matter much more to them than a decline in the
accident rate.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't just a public relations problem. Tyler's work shows
that people angered by an encounter with a high-handed police
officer are more likely to later commit a crime. ``One encounter
raises the likelihood by about 5 percent,'' he said. ``That's not
an overwhelming effect, but if you and your neighbors keep having
these encounters, it adds up.''
</P>
<P>
   Other researchers, who tracked men in Milwaukee accused of
domestic violence, found that a police officer's demeanor in
dealing with the men was more important than whether or not an
arrest was made. The men who felt they'd been treated respectfully
went on to commit 40 percent fewer offenses than the other men,
according to one researcher, Lawrence Sherman, the chairman of the
department of criminology at the University of Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Officers need to realize that their best weapon for reducing
crime is the mouth, not the pistol,'' said Sherman. ``In training
police, the big challenge is get officers who are oriented toward
action to take the salesman approach.'' It's especially challenging
to get an action-oriented mayor to take this approach. Giuliani's
former Police Commissioner, William Bratton, faults the mayor for
not being more flexible in adjusting to changing circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that crime has fallen so much,'' Bratton said, ``we're in
a position to make the transition from a crisis mode to a peacetime
mode. We can begin giving cops more training and putting more of
them in precincts instead of in tactical units. As things get
quiet, we can have more officers walking beats and focusing on
improving community relations, so that people are having more
positive encounters with officers.''
</P>
<P>
   Bratton, of course, is hardly a disinterested observer. There is
no love lost between him and Giuliani, and he has been mentioned as
a potential candidate for mayor himself. But his criticism can't be
dismissed as easily as that of the mayor's other political rivals.
The pacifist notions of Bratton are not coming from someone with a
reputation for being soft on crime. He's the one who started this
war.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
