u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-IMMIGRANT-POLICE-N     02-24 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-IMMIGRANT-POLICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE CRITICS RENEW CALL FOR CHANGE IN ATTITUDES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A group of task force members appointed in 1997 to
examine police-community relations only to have most of their
recommendations rejected by Mayor Rudolph Giuliani reconvened
Wednesday to reiterate their call for new police policies in the
aftermath of the shooting of Amadou Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   The group of 10 task force members called on the mayor to review
the task force's final reports and update the public on how its
recommendations have been followed. The recommendations included a
greater push for affirmative action, a requirement that all new
police officers live in the city, and better sensitivity training.
</P>
<P>
   Several members of the group criticized the mayor's response to
the Feb. 4 shooting of Diallo, an unarmed West African street
peddler, by four white police officers in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   ``Public distrust of the police appears to be increasing,'' the
group said in a memo to Giuliani released at the Central Baptist
Church on Manhattan's Upper West Side. ``We believe there may be
serious consequences for all New Yorkers if public trust and
confidence in our police is not restored,'' they added.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor appointed a 28-member task force in 1997 after four
police officers were charged with torturing a Haitian immigrant,
Abner Louima. When the task force released its recommendations last
year, Giuliani said some of the proposals were ``unrealistic and
make very little sense,'' and sarcastically derided the task
force's work.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Washington, where he had traveled to
testify Wednesday before the House Subcommittee on Criminal
Justice, Giuliani said he did not specifically know what the task
force members were now suggesting, but maintained that Police
Commission Howard Safir has made a big different in the
department's community relations over the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday, Safir said the department had already adopted
``62 percent'' of the task force's recommendations. He did not
provide a list, but mentioned plans to establish an advisory board
for the Police Academy as an example, and said that the proposal
for a residency requirement was a ``pie in the sky'' idea because
it would require action in the state Legislature and is vigorously
opposed by the police officers' union. On Tuesday, Safir announced
a recruiting program to attract more city residents to the force.
</P>
<P>
   The task force members at the church included several frequent
critics of the mayor, including Norman Siegel of the New York Civil
Liberties Union and Michael Meyers of the New York Civil Rights
Coalition, but also supporters of the mayor, like Irwin Rochman and
Richard Davis, both lawyers. They expressed various levels of
frustration with the administration, but were unanimous in
expressing concern that the reaction to the Diallo shooting, and
the task force report, had been insufficient.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost unimportant as to whether or not the police turn
out to be justified in a particular shooting,'' said Davis, who is
the chairman of the mayor's Commission on Combat Police Corruption.
``Distrust is growing. That has to be dealt with.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
