<DOCNO> NYT19990224.0493 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8316 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENSUS-2000-HNS &LR;      02-24 0712
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW PLAN INCLUDES STATISTICAL SAMPLING AFTER 2000 CENSUS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: Optional ending included) 
 
By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration, guaranteeing a
continued legal wrangle over the 2000 census, announced Wednesday
that the actual count of population would be followed quickly by a
second tally using statistical sampling.
</P>
<P>
   Census Bureau director Kenneth Prewitt said the first count, due
Jan. 1, 2001, would be the traditional national enumeration called
for in the Constitution and insisted on by the Supreme Court in a
January decision. Slapping down a Clinton administration plan, the
high court, split 5-4, ruled that only an actual count of residents
nationwide can be used in reapportioning the 435 seats in the U.S.
House among the states.
</P>
<P>
   Then on April 1, 2001, Prewitt said, the Census Bureau will
provide a more detailed, sampling-adjusted count that will be
available to legislatures and other governing bodies for actually
drawing of political districts within a state. The administration
is, in effect, betting that Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, the swing
vote in the January ruling, will uphold use of sampling-enhanced
census counts for anything but the apportionment of House seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some may describe this as a `two-number census,' but it in
fact is a census that is progressively more complete, more
accurate,'' Prewitt said.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement was a red flag to Republicans and conservative
groups who had criticized the Clinton administration's initial plan
to use sampling in the reapportionment count and mounted the legal
challenges against the process.
</P>
<P>
   Sampling involves taking a sample of the population and
extrapolating those figures to cover a larger area.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew J. Galvin, president of the Atlanta-based Southeastern
Legal Foundation, stood at the back of Prewitt's news conference,
promising a court test of the new plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will again take swift legal action against this
administration to prevent the unconstitutional use of statistics in
the upcoming census,'' said Galvin, whose group mounted the first
legal challenge to census sampling.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dan Miller, chairman of the House census subcommittee,
denounced the new plan and suggested that the Census Bureau put it
forward only under pressure from the political realms of the
Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``To provide a legal, Supreme Court-mandated number to the
Congress and then concoct another number for the states is a recipe
for disaster,'' said Miller, R-Fla. ``This irresponsible approach
will only serve to confuse and confound the American people while
hiding under a thinly veiled shield of so-called accuracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller said any state that uses Census' ``second, manipulated
number'' as the basis for drawing political boundaries ``will have
their redistricting plans ties up in courts for years.''
</P>
<P>
   The call for census sampling was one result of complaints from
minorities _ primarily blacks and Hispanics, two reliable
Democratic constituencies _ that their ethnic groups were
undercounted in recent decennial enumerations, especially in 1990.
Census tallies figure not only in political apportionment but also
in federal funding formulas and also have commercial importance.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans oppose census sampling because they believe it is an
unreliable tool.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt sought to remove his agency from the long-running
political dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the task of the Census Bureau to produce the best
numbers possible, not to decide how they will be used,'' said
Prewitt, an advocate of census sampling.
</P>
<P>
   The initial, unadjusted count is ``not likely to be an
improvement'' on 1990, Prewitt said. In the last census, he said,
almost all Anglos were counted but only 95 percent of blacks and
Hispanics and an even lower percentage of American Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt refused to estimate how much the sampling-adjusted count
would add to the current $4 billion tab for conducting the census.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-controlled Congress could attempt to deny any
funds to the Census Bureau for a sampling-enhanced count.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
