<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANTA-CLARITA-GROWTH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOM EXPECTED TO KEEP GOING IN L.A. SUBURB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY JASON TAKENOUCHI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARITA, Calif. -- Prepare for even more.
</P>
<P>
   That was the message Wednesday night from one of the state's top
economists to Santa Clarita, the former bedroom community that has
quickly become the tiger of economic development for Los Angeles
County.
</P>
<P>
   Already one of the fastest-growing cities in Southern
California, Santa Clarita will continue its breakneck pace even as
the economic growth of the county, state and nation slows in 1999,
predicted Jack Kyser, chief economist with the nonprofit Economic
Development Corp. of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to re-create the type of growth we're seeing
there in the rest of the county,'' said Kyser, keynote speaker at
Santa Clarita's Fourth Annual Economic Forum, held at the Hyatt
Valencia.
</P>
<P>
   The suburban city, approximately 26 miles north of downtown Los
Angeles, saw a 4.36 percent increase in jobs in 1998, far more than
the roughly 2.38 percent increase countywide, Kyser said.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Santa Clarita-area employment will grow at about the
same pace while job creation countywide slows to an estimated 1.55
percent growth rate, Kyser said. That means Santa Clarita's
employee base will grow three times faster than the rest of the
county.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically Santa Clarita has all the right elements,'' Kyser
said. ``Of all the areas in Los Angeles County right now, it has
the best combination of all the factors that point to continued
growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Those elements include housing construction, a ready supply of
quality industrial space, good schools and a pleasant environment,
Kyser said.
</P>
<P>
   The city also may be benefiting from a San Fernando Valley land
shortage that is pushing expanding businesses north, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Explosive growth is nothing new to Santa Clarita's 150,000
residents. Tractors and tract homes have been common sights this
decade as developers carved new communities between the valley's
foothills.
</P>
<P>
   But boosters say the continuing strength of the area job market
and its thriving industrial parks are testament to a new, sustained
boom that is changing the face of both Santa Clarita and its
residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Job growth is always good news,'' said Santa Clarita Mayor Jo
Anne Darcy. ``It balances the community. If people can make a
living here and live here, they have more time for their
families.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials are not resting on their successes, though.
</P>
<P>
   The city surveys residents every year on quality-of-life issues,
and last year it held its first retail survey to identify new
businesses sought for the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at the city as a marketing product that we're trying to
compete with other cities,'' said Michael Haviland, city economic
development manager. ``In some ways, you could compare us to a tube
of toothpaste that we're in the business of selling.''
</P>
<P>
   But the boom in Santa Clarita has brought problems, and critics,
as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not all rosy,'' said Santa Clarita Councilwoman Jill
Klajic.
</P>
<P>
   While she said she supports continued growth, especially
industrial growth, Klajic said the city needs to address
overcrowding in schools, hospitals and on the city's winding roads.
</P>
<P>
   If current growth patterns hold up, Klajic said, ``eventually
the quality of life in Santa Clarita will not be any different or
any better than that in central Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   Problems or not, economist Kyser said the region will continue
to be a poster child for economic development for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Santa Clarita has been riding that crest since about 1993.
Because of the control on the use of land, and because Santa
Clarita is choosing wisely, it will probably continue to ride that
crest.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
