<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8328 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-TREASURY-BOS &LR;      02-24 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TREASURY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$60 MILLION IN UNCASHED CHECKS POSE PUZZLE, TREASURER SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Investigators combing through state financial records
amid a growing scandal at the treasurer's office have found that as
much as $60 million in uncashed state checks, dating back to 1986,
have never been advertised as abandoned property as required by
law.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, according to new Treasurer Shannon P. O'Brien, the
state may never be able to match the rightful owners to the checks
because of poor or incomplete computer data.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have stated repeatedly that there are problems with the
quality of data and it's a problem we're committed to fixing if we
can,'' said O'Brien spokesman Dwight Robson.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien's investigation into the procedures at the state's
Unpaid Check Fund was spurred by the arrests last week of two men
involved in the alleged theft of $6.5 million from the account.
Investigators say they don't know if the sloppy bookkeeping at the
fund is directly linked to the alleged fraud or whether the lack of
controls and oversight allowed the fraud to flourish.
</P>
<P>
   A New Hampshire man, Martin Robbins, is being held on bail,
charged with larceny, after moving the $6.5 million to a BankBoston
escrow account and trying to withdraw the money this month.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins is charged along with 47 year-old John Trischitta, a
20-year treasury employee who controlled the Unpaid Check Fund.
Trischitta has been released from jail on $10,000 cash bail.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say it appears Trischitta, of Stoneham, was not
transferring unpaid checks to the Abandoned Property Division.
After a year, unpaid state checks are supposed to be transferred to
abandoned property and be advertised in newspapers and on the
state's Internet site.
</P>
<P>
   But records show that since 1990 only three large-sum payments
have been transferred between the two accounts.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, $25.2 million in unpaid checks _ dating to 1990 _ was
transferred from the Unpaid Check Fund to the Abandoned Property
Division. Further, none of that unclaimed money was ever
advertised.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, only other types of abandoned property, such as real
estate or dormant passbook savings accounts, were published in
newspapers and on the state's Web site, records show.
</P>
<P>
   It took three years before any more unpaid checks were
transferred into abandoned property. On June 25, 1998, more than
$17 million was sent to abandoned property. And on Jan. 29, $15.7
million in unpaid checks were transferred to that account.
</P>
<P>
   The identities of who that money belonged to were never
published and treasury officials say it would be exceedingly
difficult to match people with their funds now, especially for the
older claims.
</P>
<P>
   After remaining for three years in the Abandoned Property Fund,
assets are transferred into the state's general fund, the main
account from which everything from local aid to highway repairs are
paid.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, a computer company known as ICAL Systems pitched
its services to the state, offering to update the data processing
so that when an unpaid check was transferred to abandoned property,
an owner record would automatically be generated.
</P>
<P>
   But that never happened.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to the increasingly political investigation say
former treasurer Joseph D. Malone, obsessed with cutting the office
budget, did not want to spend $6,500 to hire the company.
</P>
<P>
   No one at ICAL, based in Framingham, could be reached for
comment Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Malone regularly touted his ability to generate money for the
state by turning over abandoned property to the general fund. Those
who worked under Malone defended the system and his repeated
transfers of money to the general fund, saying unpaid checks, like
abandoned property, often don't really belong to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if the state takes land by eminent domain, a check
may be made out to the address, rather than a person. And nearly 40
percent of abandoned property has no name attached to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why it's abandoned,'' quipped one former Malone aide.
``Under Joe, not only did the amount of abandoned property
collections soar but so did the amount of money returned to owners.
. . And we did it spending less money on operating costs than had
ever been done before.''
</P>
<P>
   The aide could not explain why the transfers between the Unpaid
Check Fund and the Abandoned Property Division rarely happened and
never on time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mess, let's face it,'' Attorney General Thomas F.
Reilly said Wednesday. ``We're trying to get to the bottom of this.
. . . Every day we learn more and more.''
</P>
<P>
   He would not say whether other individuals associated with the
Unpaid Check Fund are under investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
