<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8331 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-TREASURY-FUND-BOS &LR;      02-24 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TREASURY-FUND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSIDE TIPS ALLEGEDLY LED ACCUSED TO LARGEST CHECKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHEN KURKJIAN AND DAVID ARMSTRONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The man charged with stealing $6.5 million from a state
unpaid checks fund received a list of individuals and companies
owed more than $5,000 from the state last year so he could sell his
services as an ``heir finder,'' according to officials and
individuals familiar with the fund.
</P>
<P>
   The sources said that Martin Robbins of Peabody and Lincoln,
N.H., received far more extensive lists than were provided to
competing firms from John P. Trischitta, the head of the
treasurer's Unpaid Check Fund, who has also been charged in the
theft.
</P>
<P>
   While Robbins' lists included those owed as much as $100,000,
other competing heir finders were only given lists that showed the
names of companies and individuals owed less than $5,000 from the
state, according to the sources.
</P>
<P>
   An executive of one heir finder firm, who asked not to be
identified, confronted Trischitta last summer about his having
allegedly given Robbins the more complete list. The executive said
Trischitta confirmed he had done so and said that Robbins was a
``good guy.'' In a separate conversation, Robbins told the rival
executive that he had ``political'' friends who had helped his
business.
</P>
<P>
   After years of pressing Trischitta and higher-ups in former
state treasurer Joseph D. Malone's office for all the names, the
executive last summer suddenly received a list of people owed more
than $50,000. The executive began soliciting the larger targets.
But with call after call, the company was told that Robbins or
someone else from his firm, Robbins Associates, had already made
contact and they had either retained him or were considering doing
so.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robbins had gotten the only advantage that exists in this
business _ time,'' said another heir finder, who also was told of
Robbins' earlier calls. ``I don't know whether it was weeks or
months, but he had a leg up on the rest of us the entire time he
had the list alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Trischitta and Robbins declined comment on the
allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators for Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly are trying
to pin down the dimensions of the relationship between Robbins, 51,
whose checkered career includes a personal and business bankruptcy,
and Trischitta, 47, of Stoneham, a 20-year employee of the
treasurer's office and the sole manager of the multi-million dollar
Unpaid Check Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, a state prosecutor alleged in Boston Municipal
Court that Trischitta had received a $50,000 bribe from Robbins in
exchange for what was only referred to as ``services and
information.'' At a later press conference, Reilly and state
Treasurer Shannon O'Brien described Trischitta as ``Mr. Inside'' in
the criminal scheme, helping ``Mr. Outside,'' Robbins, to secure
through fraudulent means several checks totaling $6.5 million that
were untouched in the Unpaid Check Fund for several years.
</P>
<P>
   However, according to sources, investigators are also pursuing
the allegation that Trischitta provided Robbins a far more complete
list of names of people owed money from the Unpaid Check Fund than
routinely provided to other heir finders.
</P>
<P>
   About a dozen companies in Massachusetts compete as heir
finders, offering their services to the thousands of individuals
and companies who have never picked up the checks they were owed by
the state _ and which ultimately wound up in the Unpaid Check Fund
of the state treasurer's office.
</P>
<P>
   Heir finders interviewed recently said the only way they were
able to secure the names was by filing Freedom of Information Act
requests, and once they arrived, they invariably showed no names of
individuals or companies owed more than $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   One heir finder, who asked not to be identified, questioned
Trischitta on the cutoff and was told that the fund never received
checks of more than $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   The heir finder learned differently last summer when Trischitta,
responding to a Freedom of Information request, sent her a list
that consisted, as usual, of hundreds of pages of firms and
individuals owed $5,000 or less. But also on the list, for the
first time, were the names of firms and individuals that were owed
far more than $5,000, including about 50 that were owed between
$50,000 and $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   The heir finder's company immediately started calling those who
were due the larger checks to determine if they were willing to
contract for the firm's services. The pitch was the same: the
finder knew that a company was due a sizable amount of money and if
it was willing to pay a percentage _ from between 10 to 30 percent
_ the finder could secure the money.
</P>
<P>
   Invariably, the heir finder says, she was told that the firms
had already been contacted by Robbins Associates and were dealing
directly with them. A second heir finder, who secured a similar
list, said he also was told the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   Although Robbins incorporated his firm in 1994, other heir
finders said they had not heard of his competing in the business
until early 1998. By last summer, however, he had contracted with
at least two people to help him scour the lists for potential
clients.
</P>
<P>
   One woman who worked for Robbins for several weeks in the late
summer and fall, and asked not to be identified, said that he gave
her lists of companies and individuals owed about $1,000. The names
of those owed much larger amounts Robbins kept to himself, the
person said. Although she was successful in her work, signing about
30 of the companies and individuals to contracts with Robbins, the
woman said she quit the job because of frustration about Robbins'
work habits.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was totally disorganized and was unable to keep track of
anything or anyone that he was trying to solicit as clients,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Such disparate work habits may have been the cause of Robbins'
prior failings in business. In 1993, he was operating Associated
Cash &AMP; Carry, Inc. in Malden, which he described as being in the
surplus food brokerage business. He reported no income from the
company, however, and filed for personal bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   At the time he reported assets of $867,555, but a debt of $2.4
million.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, a company owned by Robbins filed for bankruptcy. The
company, Associated Salvage Inc., bought and sold salvaged and
distressed goods. The company listed debts of $1.814 million and
assets of $904,000. Among the debts listed was $50,000 owed on a
lease for a high-end Mercedes sedan.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, Robbins was sued by a business partner alleging Robbins
artificially created debt in a company they owned, Bay State Job
Lot Inc., by charging increased rent, utility charges, and
warehouse fees. Robbins then transferred all of the company's
inventory to satisfy the debt he created, the lawsuit charges.
Robbins denied the charge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
