<DOCNO> NYT19990224.0497 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8332 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-POUND-2TAKES-NYT &LR;      02-24 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-POUND-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EYE OF THE HURRICANE: IOC'S MAN IS BUFFETED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Utah, Canada)  (mk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Late last year, when scandal forced the International
Olympic Committee to investigate improper payments and gifts to
some of its members by Salt Lake City's Olympic organizers, the
organization turned to one of its own, Richard Pound, to run the
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Pound, a Montreal lawyer and former Canadian Olympic athlete,
had for years been the Olympic committee's chief negotiator of
television and sponsorship deals, and over two decades he had
earned the trust of committee members as well as that of many of
the corporate sponsors who finance the Olympic Games. Indeed,
Pound, whose efforts in the mid-1980s to reform the
television-rights bidding process had won him respect, has in
recent years been among a handful of people considered to be
possible successors to the IOC's president, Juan Antonio Samaranch.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, Pound conceded that his role of investigating
his colleagues was an awkward one. But within five weeks, Pound's
investigation, conducted against a tight, self-imposed deadline,
produced a report that led to the resignation of three Olympic
committee members and called for the expulsion of six more. At a
news conference late last month, Samaranch cited the investigation
as evidence of the IOC's determination to examine and reform
itself.
</P>
<P>
   The report, which accused the implicated IOC members of having
stained the good name of the Olympics, put Pound center stage in
what has become a global scandal. And, numerous committee members
have said, it enhanced the 56-year-old Canadian's stature as a
potential successor to Samaranch.
</P>
<P>
   But soon after its release, the report, as well as Pound's
attempts to investigate similar wrongdoing in other cities, was
criticized as inadequate. Some corporate sponsors, concerned about
the value of their investments, called for fuller investigations
and more stringent reforms. And certain officials in Salt Lake City
cited Pound's efforts as evidence that the IOC was incapable of
vigorously investigating itself.
</P>
<P>
   Pound spent only two days in Salt Lake City, hired no
independent investigators and conducted just a handful of
interviews, explaining that he had worked quickly in order to be
able to take some action at a January general meeting of the
committee in Switzerland. His investigation of possible misconduct
in previous Olympic site selections involved sending letters to
officials of bidding cities and asking them to turn over any
incriminating information. Only 11 of 28 cities even responded, and
two said they had uncovered minor infractions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pound has a great amount of integrity, but the IOC cannot
investigate itself,'' said Ken Bullock, a member of the board of
trustees of the Salt Lake Organizing Committee for the 2002 Winter
Games. ``They are Pound's peers. You can't help but be attached to
these folks.''
</P>
<P>
   Pound strongly defends the quality of his investigation, saying
he was working with limited time and with the confidence that other
investigations of the Salt Lake scandal, including an internal
ethics investigation by the city's organizing committee, would be
more thorough. Earlier this month, a report by that ethics panel
uncovered financial abuses by another 10 IOC members, and Pound has
pledged to hold them accountable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often the legal profession disciplines itself, the medical
profession. CPAs discipline themselves,'' Pound said in a recent
interview in Montreal. ``We are capable of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pound said he never asked for the job of investigator, but had
done it out of a sense of duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no fun,'' he said. ``In my case, 30-odd years of
pretty decent and capable sports administration is being turned
into pond scum because of the action of a small percentage of our
numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   However Pound's report and the additional federal and state
investigations wind up being regarded, and however much his work
affects his chances of succeeding Samaranch, it is clear that for
nearly 16 years, Pound, as a member of the IOC executive board, was
at the center of an organization that functioned like an elite and
insular club.
</P>
<P>
   It was a club dealing with billions of dollars, but subject to
little accountability from inside or out. It was an organization,
Pound acknowledges, that for years had hints that its members might
be abusing their positions and endangering the public image of the
Olympics, but that never vigorously policed itself.
</P>
<P>
   If the IOC failed in that regard, and there are plenty of
critics and supporters alike who say it did, Pound does not appear
to deserve more blame than any of the organization's other senior
members. But others insist he deserves no less, either.
</P>
<P>
   Pound swam for Canada during the 1960 Rome Olympics. In addition
to serving as chancellor of McGill University in Montreal, he has
long been regarded as a candid, accessible member of the often
secretive Olympic committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no diplomatic spin with Dick,'' said Dick Ebersol, the
chairman of NBC Sports.
</P>
<P>
   Pound was elected to the IOC in 1978, and moved onto the IOC's
11-member executive board five years later. Soon after, Samaranch
put him in charge of the major TV deals and the lucrative corporate
sponsorships the committee regularly negotiated.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately, Pound said he became aware of the sometimes
tangled world of money and loyalties and problems of appearances.
In 1984 or 1985, Pound said, he was approached by Horst Dassler,
then the chairman of Adidas, the international sporting goods
giant, which owned the marketing firm under contract with the IOC
to broker corporate sponsorship deals.
</P>
<P>
   Dassler, Pound said, wanted him to represent Adidas in its
corporate negotiations with American distributors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said I didn't mind doing it, but said he'd have to
understand that in light of the relationship he had with the
Olympic movement, this is not going to look good in hindsight,''
Pound said. ``So, I said, `If I do this, you have to understand
you'll pay my firm, but I won't participate financially.'''
</P>
<P>
   Pound did work for Adidas, but he said that as a partner in his
firm, he made sure he did not share directly in the revenue from
the deal.
</P>
<P>
   At roughly the same time, Pound said, he was offered a $1
million bribe from someone representing the Seoul Olympics to fix a
deal for European TV rights. Pound said he rebuffed the offer and
reported the bribe to Samaranch, but that neither he nor Samaranch
pursued the matter further.
</P>
<P>
   Pound, who bore no specific responsibility for investigating
wrongdoing, said he felt there was little more he could do, and
that he merely wrote a note for his files to keep as an official
record.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Gee, my first bribe offer,'' Pound said he wrote to himself.
To Samaranch, he said, ``You'll never guess, but ... '' Pound,
however, did soon reform the way television networks were awarded
the rights to the Games, opting to enforce a sealed bid process to
insure the appearance of fairness.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, with the Olympic organizing committees making their
own deals with the networks, nine of 14 Olympics from 1960 to 1984
went to ABC. ``It was unfair,'' said Neal Pilson, a former CBS
Sports president. ``We felt ABC had inside information.''
</P>
<P>
   To help with its Olympic negotiations at the time, ABC employed
a French executive in Europe, Georges Croses, who was close to
Monique Berlioux, a former IOC executive director.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Spence, a former ABC Sports senior vice president, said the
frequent choice of ABC was due to its quality production and the
fees it paid.
</P>
<P>
   Pound, starting in 1984, required networks to negotiate directly
with the IOC and submit sealed bids. As a result, NBC carried three
straight Summer Games (Seoul, South Korea; Barcelona, Spain; and
Atlanta) and CBS got three Winter Games (Albertville, France;
Lillehammer, Norway; and Nagano, Japan).
</P>
<P>
   But Pound's commitment to the sealed bid process and the sense
of fairer play it fostered was abandoned in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   That summer NBC made a bold, $1.27 billion, pre-emptive bid to
secure the rights to the 2000 Summer Games in Sydney, Australia,
and the 2002 Winter Games in Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   Impressed, Pound decided to shut out ABC, Fox Sports and CBS.
There is no questioning, television executives say, that Pound got
a great deal for the IOC. But they also say there is no way of
saying whether he could have done better had he brought the other
networks into the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was done to CBS was unconscionable,'' said Barry Frank,
senior corporate vice president of the International Management
Group, who served as a consultant to the Sydney committee.
</P>
<P>
   NBC ultimately also got the rights to the 2004, 2006 and 2008
Olympics for a total price tag of $2.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Pound acknowledged that he upended the even playing field he
nurtured, but said the NBC deals brought future financial
stability.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Pound, along with three other members of the IOC's
executive committee, was given a 32-page report by organizers of
Toronto's failed bid for the 1996 Games. The report detailed
financial abuses by several IOC members that may have cost the
organizers $800,000.
</P>
<P>
   No formal IOC inquiry, however, was ever launched, and Pound
said he did not demand one himself. Pound said the Toronto report
did not contain names of the accused members, and that the
organizers never provided them when asked. Pound said the executive
committee decided to turn the information over to one of its senior
members, Marc Hodler of Switzerland, who was in charge of dealing
with bid cities. Three years later, the IOC, at least in part
because of the Toronto allegations, did amend its gift-giving
policy to limit the value of gifts members could accept to $150.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked for names and they didn't give them,'' said Pound.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto officials insist that while their report did not contain
names, they were ready to provide them, but that no one at the IOC
pursued their charges aggressively.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't blame Dick directly,'' said Norm Seagram, a Toronto
organizer. ``We raised the warning flag to the entire executive
board. The guy in charge was Samaranch.'' Seagram added: ``You
didn't need names to institute rules and enforcement measures. You
had the actions.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Salt Lake City misconduct became public last fall,
Pound said, there was no hesitation to investigate. He said he
never gave serious thought to hiring outside investigators and did
not consider his decision to impose his own tight deadline to be
mistaken.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, when the U.S. Olympic Committee in 1991 was faced
with investigating whether its executive director, Robert Helmick,
had violated conflict of interest policies, it hired an outside
investigator who spent 10 weeks conducting an inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   For his investigation, Pound relied primarily on bid committee
summaries of the program of financial payments and gift-giving
carried out by the Salt Lake committee's former chairman and
executive vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were dealing ASAP with IOC members in the first flush of
information,'' Pound said.
</P>
<P>
   At least two people interviewed by Pound said his focus was
narrow. Max Wheeler, a lawyer for David Johnson, the executive vice
president who resigned in January, said: ``Pound seemed
disinterested in gifts given to Samaranch, because he's not a
voting member on Olympic bidding. But that's a distinction without
a difference, because if you want to influence anyone, it would be
Samaranch.''
</P>
<P>
   Pound dismissed Wheeler's observations, saying Samaranch
regularly received ``protocol'' gifts. ``As IOC president, you have
to encourage candidate cities to think about putting out the best
possible bids,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pound said he was always sure the Salt Lake committee's ethics
inquiry would yield more evidence of wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have access to everything the ethics panel had,''
Pound said. ``I don't know how they would have reacted if I said,
`Hi, we're from Switzerland, give us access to everything.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Pound, who was once behind an effort to force Samaranch to
retire at 75, now says the 78-year-old Samaranch must stay through
next month's voting on the proposed reforms and expulsions.
</P>
<P>
   As for whether he still desires the presidency after wading
through the alleged corruption of his colleagues, he said, ``It's a
position you consider and you think if I were president for a day,
what would I do?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
