<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI PLANS EASIER ACCESS TO CITY HALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Giuliani administration said Wednesday that it
would ease the security crackdown that has blocked public access to
City Hall since August, allowing demonstrators to gather in front
of the building starting this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Michael D. Hess, the city's corporation counsel, said he had
proposed new rules that would allow groups of 50 people or fewer to
demonstrate, protest or hold news conferences in the parking area
in front of City Hall. The groups could also gather on the
building's steps under the proposed rules, Hess said, but only if
they were accompanied by members of the City Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have given this very careful consideration, and we think
it's fair and constitutional and proper,'' Hess said in an
interview Wednesday night. ``Hopefully, this will end all of the
controversy.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposals, which Hess said would become law after a public
hearing in April, came six months after the Giuliani administration
began Operation Bravo, a plan to tighten security in lower
Manhattan to thwart possible terrorist attacks after the bombings
of two U.S. embassies in East Africa. Police cruisers have blocked
access to the building ever since, and only people who can prove
they have business inside are allowed past the barricades.
</P>
<P>
   As part of Operation Bravo, Giuliani banned news conferences and
demonstrations from the steps of City Hall, which had long been a
popular spot for such gatherings. But the policy drew heavy
criticism, and it ran into trouble last fall, when a federal
appeals court ordered the mayor to allow an AIDS service
organization called Housing Works to hold a rally in the parking
area in front of City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Judge Harold Baer of U.S. District Court in
Manhattan urged the administration to develop rules allowing more
gatherings on the building's steps. Giuliani loosened the security
policy shortly thereafter, but only to allow members of the City
Council to hold news conferences on the steps.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Siegel, the executive director of the New York Civil
Liberties Union, which challenged the policy in court on behalf of
Housing Works, said Wednesday that he was encouraged by the new
proposals but that they did not go far enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a significant first step, but it is not a complete
victory,'' Siegel said. ``We still want more access. Anyone should
be allowed onto those steps.''
</P>
<P>
   Siegel said that his organization filed papers with Baer last
week asking him to declare the city's policy unconstitutional, a
move that he said prompted the Giuliani administration to propose
the new rules. The Civil Liberties Union will probably challenge
the new rules in court unless they are modified to allow gatherings
of more than 50 people, and to allow groups to demonstrate on the
steps without Council members.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
