<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 22:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8338 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NUKE-WASTE-NYT &LR;      02-24 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUKE-WASTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGENCY PLANS TO PAY STORAGE COSTS OF NUCLEAR WASTE UNTIL REPOSITORY
IS READY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Nev. )   By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Energy Department, which says it will be unable
to begin accepting utilities' nuclear waste until at least 2010,
will announce on Thursday that it is now willing to take ownership
of the waste and pay temporary storage costs with money the
utilities have paid to develop a permanent repository.
</P>
<P>
   The department has been collecting money from the utilities
since 1982 on the promise that it would take their nuclear waste by
January 1998. But it is unable to do so until it opens a permanent
repository at Yucca Mountain, Nev., near Las Vegas. The anticipated
date for that opening is 2010, but so far the department has not
determined what standards such a storage site must have.
</P>
<P>
   Some reactors already are running out of space in their spent
fuel storage pools, and others no longer sell power but cannot be
decommissioned because there is no place for the spent fuel. The
department is being sued for breach of contract by more than 20
utilities, which are seeking tens of billions of dollars in
damages.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Richardson, the energy secretary, said Wednesday in a
telephone interview that he would propose in testimony before a
Senate committee on Thursday that the department ``take title'' to
the wastes it was scheduled to have received under the 1998
deadline. The wastes would stay where they currently reside, in
scores of spent fuel pools and hundreds of storage casks, and the
department would pay the storage costs, in exchange for the
utilities' dropping their suits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to address an immediate crisis,'' Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson described his proposal as a starting point for
negotiations with the utilities, members of Congress who want the
federal government to establish a centralized temporary repository
and environmentalists, many of whom want the wastes to stay where
they are.
</P>
<P>
   There is strong sentiment in Congress for construction of an
above-ground, interim storage site, probably near Yucca Mountain,
but the Clinton administration has held off legislation by
threatening a veto. The administration's argument is that there is
no point in shipping thousands of tons of highly radioactive
material around the country before anyone knows for certain where
it will be buried.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson's proposal seems unlikely to satisfy the utilities.
``The industry foremost is looking for movement of fuel,'' said
Scott Peterson, a spokesman for the Nuclear Energy Institute, a
trade association here. He said that several retired reactors could
have been converted to ``green fields'' for redevelopment if a
permanent storage site was in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the event that there is not movement of fuel, the industry
is looking for compensation for continued storage on site, but
movement of fuel is the priority,'' Peterson said.
</P>
<P>
   The industry previously has resisted any effort by the Energy
Department to use the waste fund to pay damages. The fund was
collected from utilities at the rate of one-tenth of a cent per
kilowatt-hour made in reactors under contracts signed under the
Nuclear Waste Policy Act of 1982. About $15 billion has been
raised, including interest on deposits, with about $6 billion
having been spent.
</P>
<P>
   The industry says the fund is for development of a permanent
repository, or at least a centralized repository, not for expenses
at reactors around the country.
</P>
<P>
   But the settlement would offer immediate relief to the
utilities, in contrast to construction of an interim, above-ground
repository, which could not be licensed and put in service until
2004, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   It also offers the utilities the advantage of being end their
ownership of the wastes, perhaps enabling them to sell small plots
of land to the federal government for waste storage casks.
</P>
<P>
   This is especially important to utilities in Minnesota and
Wisconsin, which have limited the construction of casks, in effect
saying that if the waste problem is not solved, the reactors must
close. If the casks were federally owned the states could not limit
them.
</P>
<P>
   A congressional aide on a committee with jurisdiction over the
Energy Department, speaking on the condition that he not be further
identified, said Wednesday night that if there was no settlement,
the Court of Claims might award vast sums to utilities whose wastes
the department already was scheduled to have accepted, which could
drain the trust fund before Yucca could be built.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a little more rational approach to the problem than a
random walk through the courts,'' he said. ``The Energy Department
can exercize some cost control over it, as opposed to people
getting checks from the court.''
</P>
<P>
   By contract, the Energy Department was supposed to accept 400
metric tons of fuel in 1998, 600 tons this year, and 900 tons a
year beginning in 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
