<SLUG> BC-NY-PIRRO-INDICT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE BID UNLIKELY FOR PROSECUTOR AFTER SPOUSE'S INDICTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JOSEPH BERGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. _ In the wake of her husband's indictment on
tax fraud charges, Jeanine Pirro, the Westchester County district
attorney, is unlikely to run for the U.S. Senate, a top aide and
two leading county Republicans said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is far less likely now that she would look to that
as a serious possibility than it was last week,'' said the aide,
speaking on condition of anonymity. ``Instead of tangling with the
issues, she's going to be asked questions about her husband. That
has changed the complexion of the race and the message.''
</P>
<P>
   The aide said Ms. Pirro had been mulling a run ever since Sen.
Daniel Patrick Moynihan announced in November that he would not
seek re-election. Her thinking, the aide said, began to solidify in
the ensuing weeks as top state Republicans, including many close to
Gov. George Pataki, encouraged her to make such a run and several
newspaper articles fed what the aide called `` a wave'' of
enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   But on Tuesday, her husband, Albert J. Pirro Jr., was indicted
by a federal grand jury in White Plains on charges that he evaded
taxes on more than $1 million in income by deducting such personal
items as a $123,000 Ferrari sports car, a leased Mercedes for his
mother-in-law, domestic servants and artwork as business expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ms. Pirro has not been charged, the indictment was
regarded by some politicians as a political setback for her because
many of the deductions taken by her husband benefited Ms. Pirro _
one involved a second leased Mercedes, which Ms. Pirro drove _ and
some of the charges stemmed from their joint tax returns from 1992
to 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Several top county Republicans, speaking on condition that they
not be named, agreed that Ms. Pirro would most likely skip the
Senate race and perhaps bide her time waiting for the race for
governor in 2002, should Pataki not seek re-election to a third
term. They also suggested that she could run for attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Pirro, her husband has always been part benefactor and
part burden. As the county's most successful and well-connected
land use lawyer, he has been able to raise money for her campaigns
as judge and district attorney, and he has introduced her to the
politicians who helped smooth her path to victory. But at many
points, his presence at her side has also been a hindrance and a
distraction.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, she withdrew as the Republican candidate for lieutenant
governor rather than provide information about her husband's
business interests, which included a Connecticut garbage carting
company that Republicans worried was part of an industry tainted by
organized crime. In 1993, when she ran for district attorney, her
opponent, Michael Cherkasky, questioned whether Ms. Pirro could
impartially investigate contracts for garages at the county airport
and hospital, which were built by developers represented by Pirro.
</P>
<P>
   While she has been the county's chief law-enforcement officer,
she has seen her husband withstand one state and two federal
criminal investigations as well as a paternity suit brought by an
Indiana woman who eventually proved through DNA tests that Pirro
had fathered her daughter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
