<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UDALL FAMILY, SOUTHERN ARIZONA DEMOCRATS LURE CLINTON
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
WASHINGTON _ President Clinton is coming to Arizona Thursday for a
blend of reasons both political and personal, including a desire to
mark in private the passing of Arizona congressional legend Mor ris
K. Udall.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clinton, who arrives in Tucson Thursday aboard Air Force One, is
hoping to regain momentum for his beleaguered Social Security
rescue plan by addressing Arizona senior citizens, who gave him sur
prising support in the 1996 election.
</P>
<P>
   The trip also presents an opportu nity to thank Pima County
voters, who campaign officials considered the key to Clinton's
becoming the first Democrat to win Arizona since Harry Truman in
1948.
</P>
<P>
   Polls showed that Arizona seniors responded favorably to
Clinton's 1996 message of protecting Social Security, and that many
feared that plans by the GOP Congress would shrink the growth of
Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The seniors' support, White House officials said this week, is a
big reason why Clinton chose Ari zona as a site to pump up his
recently announced Social Security preservation plan, which has
come under attack in Congress. What better place, White House
officials asked, to resurrect the plan than the scene of one of his
most unexpected electoral victories?
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will share a stage at the Tucson Convention Center with
Rep. Jim Kolbe, R-Ariz., who has said that Clinton's Social
Security plan ``does nothing to save Social Security'' and is
merely ``a cynical shell game.''
</P>
<P>
   Kolbe, who will travel with Clinton to Tucson, said in an
interview that he will not emphasize his criticisms but rather will
stress the need ``to find a compromise that works for both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's visit also has a personal dimension not appearing on
his official schedule, which includes the Tucson speech and a visit
to the Arizona Diamondbacks spring train ing baseball facility.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton ``felt badly that he was unable to speak at the Udall
serv ices in Tucson'' last month, a senior White House official
told The Arizona Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mo's passing has been very much on peoples' minds, and it gave
us another reason (for the trip) that seemed to make sense,'' said
the official, requesting anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was expected to meet privately during the day with
family members of the late Democratic congressman, who was beloved
for his environmental stewardship, his grace and his wit.
</P>
<P>
   Udall died in December at a hospital in Washington, D.C. Mem
bers of Congress are holding their own memorial service for Udall
at a House office building next week.
</P>
<P>
   Notwithstanding Udall's 30-year tenure in office, Arizona was
long considered a solidly Republican state until Clinton captured
its eight electoral votes in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   National Democrats, who ignored Arizona for years during
presiden tial campaigns, are eager not to let it slip back into the
Republican fold.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton traveled to Arizona three times during the presidential
cam paign, including two visits to the Valley and one to the Grand
Canyon. Clinton could afford to spend so much time in a relatively
small state because he had virtually wrapped up his election
against Republican Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   For this visit, Rep. Ed Pastor, D-Ariz., lobbied for Clinton to
come to Tucson instead of the Valley. The White House was eager to
send Clinton to Arizona, and to accommodate Pastor, who has been a
staunch supporter of Clinton and the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president took a great interest in what happened in Ari
zona,'' said Doug Wilson, coor dinator of Clinton's '96 Arizona
campaign. Wilson said Pima County had been one of the keys to the
state victory, along with a successful speech Clinton made earlier
to senior citizens in Sun City.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kind of margins that would be necessary to overturn almost
50 years of history, we knew were not going to be huge. So every
vote counted. The voter turnout and the breadth of support in Pima
County was not only a critical factor, it may have been the
critical factor,'' Wil son said.
</P>
<P>
   Kolbe disputed the notion, ad vanced by Democrats, that Clinton
had captured the hearts of senior citizens on Social Security and
Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got a larger proportion (of seniors) than Democrats have
gotten in past elections, but that's because Clinton got a larger
proportion of all the voters last time, and he carried the state,''
Kolbe said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's Social Security plan would devote most of the future
budget surpluses to shoring up Social Security's trust fund.
</P>
<P>
   Kolbe has questioned Clinton's accounting methods, saying the
trust fund would ``be stuffed with IOU's'' instead of dollars.
Kolbe has proposed his own rescue plan. It would permit workers to
redirect 2 percentage points of their Social Security taxes into a
personal ac count, which could then be invested.
</P>
<P>
   Later Thursday, Clinton will deliver a foreign-policy speech in
San Fran cisco and attend a Democratic reception in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   He then will go to Utah for a skiing trip with his daughter,
Chel sea, to celebrate her 19th birthday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
