<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELTRE STARTS WITH A (PINKY) BANG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ Adrian Beltre's first big-league camp as the
Dodgers starting third baseman had an inauspicious beginning.
Before he even got to the clubhouse for Wednesday's first
full-squad workout, he was injured. Beltre slammed his right pinky
finger in his car door. He needed two stitches near his fingernail
to close the wound.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better it happens now than at the beginning of the
season,'' said Beltre, who worked on conditioning on Wednesday.
``They took X-rays and told me to take a couple of days off.''
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Charlie Strasser said X-rays were negative. Beltre,
wearing a gauze bandage, was listed as day-to-day.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre, 20, was bummed. He wants to get training camp underway
so he can begin working toward this season and dismiss the memories
of a year ago. The highly touted prospect was promoted to the
Dodgers on June 4 but hit .215 and made 13 errors in 77 games after
making the jump from Double-A San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the nerves . . . when they called me up last year, I
was not ready for it,'' Beltre said. ``They told me I was going to
be up two or three weeks. When I started to play, I wanted to do
better so I could stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Beltre's hitting nor fielding overwhelmed anyone, but
his talent is enough for manager Dave Johnson to downplay any talk
of Beltre not being at third base on opening day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him I don't expect great things out of him,'' Johnson
said. ``I didn't want him to put to much pressure on himself. I
said it would be OK if he hit .250, and he said no. With the
surrounding (players), there shouldn't be any pressure on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite a rough time after his jump to the Dodgers, Beltre said
he feels better about his position after playing winter ball in his
native Dominican Republic. Beltre was the Most Valuable Player in
the Dominican winter league, batting .301 with 10 homers, 37 RBI
and 17 stolen bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I can play here and that helped me because (other
major-leaguers) and I played good (in the Dominican),'' said
Beltre, a lifetime .305 hitter in the minors. ``I feel I can do the
job. I feel confident and I feel relaxed. I'm positive. I think
I'll be the third baseman all year.''
</P>
<P>
   __ 'Nuff seen, 'nuff said: The first full-squad workout brought
an opportunity for a few of the pitchers to throw against hitters,
and the first one to take the mound was right-hander Kevin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Brown looked sharp during his 10-minute session, and upon
throwing his first pitch _ a strike on the outside corner _ Johnson
quipped, ``I've seen enough. He's ready.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Turning over the reigns: Prior to the workout, general
manager Kevin Malone addressed the Dodgers in the outfield of one
of the practice fields. To Malone and Johnson, it served as a
symbolic passing of the torch from general manager to manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just to say things about the team concept,'' Malone
said. ``I told them it's amazing what you can accomplish as a team
when you don't care about who gets the credit. They know where I'm
coming from. When you do something like that, you hope they see the
energy level and recognize the commitment and dedication.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
