<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAWLINGS-SUSPECT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE RELEASE SKETCH OF SUSPECT IN FATAL KIDNAPPING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY LISA VAN PROYEN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Two days after Chris Rawlings' kidnappers crashed
his Bentley with him in the trunk, one returned to the scene to
search for the victim's wallet, police said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   That same man is believed to have waved $1,000 at motorists in
hopes of buying his escape, and when that didn't work, carjacked a
Mazda sports car, police said.
</P>
<P>
   A motorist saw him rooting around some bushes two days after the
Feb. 8 attack and has helped police confirm a composite sketch,
which was released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives said these new details bolster their suspicion that
the attack was a robbery gone awry and was not tied to an FBI
investigation into Rawlings' multimillion-dollar telemarketing
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would tend to take us away from the direction of
kidnapping for ransom or murder,'' said Los Angeles police
Detective Rick Swanston of the West Valley Division. ``There is no
evidence to connect it. But we haven't discounted it.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the possibilities that police are considering is that
Rawlings' business associates might have told someone else about
Rawlings' wealth, leading to the robbery, Swanston said.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives also theorize that the attackers stuffed Rawlings in
the Bentley's trunk not to kidnap him but rather to hold him while
they searched his house. However, when they heard on a radio
scanner that the police were en route, they may have panicked and
fled with him in the trunk, crashing the car several miles away,
Swanston said.
</P>
<P>
   Based on witness descriptions, police said one suspect is an
African-American man in his 20s, between 5 feet 10 inches and 6
feet tall and weighing about 160 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   While searching for the wallet near the crash scene in the
suburban Los Angeles community of Tarzana, the suspect was seen in
a 1994 to 1998 tan over emerald green convertible Ford Mustang,
police said. He failed to find the wallet, but police later located
it.
</P>
<P>
   The man may limp because of injuries suffered in the fiery crash
that ejected Rawlings from the trunk, fatally injuring him.
</P>
<P>
   The second suspect fled on foot and is described as an
African-American man in his 20s, between 5 feet 10 inches and 6
feet tall, weighing about 200 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Both men wore dark clothing, gloves and a mask and were carrying
handguns, police said. They may also be in possession of two Rolex
watches stolen from Rawlings, including one with diamonds on the
face, bevel and band.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators believe a third man might have driven the two
gunmen to Rawlings' house that night, Swanston said.
</P>
<P>
   In another development, the Los Angeles City Council will
consider next week offering a $25,000 reward for information
leading to the arrest and conviction of the kidnappers.
</P>
<P>
   Swanston said the pair may be connected to other crimes in the
West San Fernando Valley. They fit the descriptions of two home
invasion robbers who brutally attacked film producer Daniel Blatt
on Jan. 31 at his suburban Sherman Oaks home before fleeing with
his belongings.
</P>
<P>
   While Los Angeles police search for Rawlings' attackers, the FBI
continued its investigation into allegations that he ran a
fraudulent telemarketing scheme, said Laura Bosley, an FBI
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   One of two men arrested on suspicion of being involved in the
scam, Timothy Carlnell Griffieth, has been released on his own
recognizance. The other suspect, John Darris Dickens, had bail set
at $15,000. His arraignment is scheduled for March 8.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
