<HEADER>
A8497 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-HANOVER-PROFILE-NY     02-24 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HANOVER-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CITY'S FIRST LADY SPEAKS FOR HERSELF, BUT WON'T TALK ABOUT
HUSBAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York _ Donna Hanover is the first to say that her life as
first lady of New York City didn't turn out as she had planned, and
that she hasn't been involved in politics the way she expected. She
also says that she has changed since moving into Gracie Mansion in
1994 with Mayor Rudolph. Giuliani, the husband rarely seen with her
in public the last two and a half years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've become stronger,'' Ms. Hanover said. ``As you
grow through life, you figure out what you're capable of, maybe
things that you didn't imagine before. And you do them.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a recent hourlong interview that ranged from her
professional ambitions to her children to her role as first lady,
Ms. Hanover refused to talk about Giuliani. When asked if she was
committed to her marriage, Ms. Hanover replied, swiftly and
pointedly, ``I'm committed to my family.''
</P>
<P>
   As Giuliani considers a possible run for the U.S. Senate after
his term as mayor is up in 2001, Ms. Hanover is beginning to plan
for her own future post-Gracie Mansion. Since 1996, when the
Giulianis began leading separate public lives, the state of their
marriage has been a subject of discussion in New York's political
circles, and could become an issue in a campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hanover, who said she planned to stay in New York after her
husband left office, did not make it clear in the interview that
her future necessarily included Giuliani. Even now, she has come to
define her role as first lady as a community service position
wholly separate from the mayor, whom she did not mention in a
recent week of public appearances.
</P>
<P>
   But she reacted to speculation in the city about her living
arrangements with a bright, ``Oh, I never moved out of Gracie
Mansion.''
</P>
<P>
   She would not say whether Giuliani would run for the Senate,
whether she would like him to run for Senate, or whether she would
campaign for him if he did. But she did say in the interview, which
was conducted before the recent frenzy of speculation about Hillary
Rodham Clinton's interest in the same New York Senate seat, that
Mrs. Clinton is a ``very interesting'' person.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she's dynamic, and I think she's very smart, and she's
an amazing speaker,'' Ms. Hanover said. Ms. Hanover's press
secretary, Joannie Danielides, said this week that Ms. Hanover had
no comment on Mrs. Clinton's potential Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hanover, 49, spoke over morning coffee at Bouterin, a
favorite French restaurant on East 59th Street. She was warm when
the subject was her career and her children, icy when the questions
turned to her husband. She wore a magenta blazer, and looked
younger than she did when she became first lady. In the last two
and a half years, she has grown out her pixie haircut and lost 20
pounds _ the result of 4 a.m. exercise sessions on her treadmill at
Gracie Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   `And like many women,'' she said, laughing, ``that battle is
never won.''
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of women's magazines, Ms. Hanover has
repeatedly declined requests for interviews in New York. She spoke
to The New York Times soon after becoming first lady in 1994,
describing herself as a ``sounding board'' who is ``always there''
for her husband. She spoke to The Times again for 10 minutes on the
telephone in 1996 about her decision to move away from attending
political events with her husband.
</P>
<P>
   But she recently decided that the time was right for a longer
session in person, apparently to direct attention to a career as a
television reporter and occasional film actress that in two years
will no longer be helped, or hampered, by her role as first lady.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased that I've been able to have my own career,'' she
said. ``And it would never have happened any other way. That's the
kind of person that I am. Work is extremely important to my
self-image and my sense that I've contributed to the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hanover said she was looking for a job as a broadcast
financial reporter, after taking a finance and accounting course
last year at New York University. ``People are much more interested
in business across the board nowadays,'' she said. ``And New York
is the center of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hanover appears as a correspondent up to four mornings a
week on WNYW-TV's ``Good Day New York,'' the 7 to 9 a.m. local news
program on Channel 5, and is co-host of a program on ``In Food
Today'' on the national cable Television Food Network.
</P>
<P>
   She also goes to a weekly acting class, and spent two days last
week in California taping a guest appearance as a psychiatrist on
the ABC series ``The Practice,'' to be broadcast March 14. In 1996,
she had a sizable part as Ruth Carter Stapleton in ``The People vs.
Larry Flynt.'' Last year she earned $304,613; the Mayor's salary is
$165,000.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hanover's ``first lady service,'' as she calls it, includes
the Cool School program, which recognizes outstanding New York City
public schools. She is on the board of St. Mary's Hospital for
Children in Queens and is active with groups raising money for
amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, the fatal illness known as Lou
Gehrig's disease.
</P>
<P>
   She also gives what she calls ``professional women's dinners''
at Gracie Mansion, with guests like Cynthia Rowley, the designer,
and Jane Alexander, the actress who headed the National Endowment
for the Arts. Ms. Hanover said she has ``a wonderful group of
friends'' in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been very lucky to find support,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
