<SLUG> BC-SKI-ROOKIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKE A BEGINNER ALONG AND IT GET A FREE TICKET  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By LOIS FRIEDLAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The skiing industry has developed several ``bring a friend and
ski free'' and ``recruit a rookie'' snowboarding programs, which
offer a free lift ticket, valid on the same day that a friend is
signed up for a learn-to-ski/ride program.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the beginner package varies with the ski area, but
it will include a lesson, rental equipment and a lift ticket.
Reservations are suggested at many of the areas, so call ahead to
verify details.
</P>
<P>
   The programs vary, but here are a few of the choices:
</P>
<P>
   _ Eleven eastern areas have adopted a program that rewards
skiers with a free lift ticket for signing up a new friend through
the ``Now It's Your Turn'' guaranteed learn-to-ski program,
available during nonholiday midweeks all season long.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mountain Creek, 47 miles from the Lincoln Tunnel in Sussex
County, N.J., offers this deal, plus others for New York-area
skiers. Mountain Creek has placed coupons for a beginner package at
half price, with the purchase of another lesson at full price,
inside copies of the magazine, Fresh Tracks: The Newcomer's Ski &AMP;
Ride Guide. The resort is distributing the guide around the New
York City metropolitan area in health clubs, ski shops and other
places where potential skiers may congregate. This new magazine is
a lively bible for never-evers, full of tips for easing one's way
into these winter sports. For details about the programs or a copy
of the magazine, call (917-827-2000) or go on line
(www.mountaincreek.com).
</P>
<P>
   _ Ten other resorts have adopted the basic premise of bringing a
non-skiing friend to the slopes for a guaranteed first-time-on-skis
program in return for a free lift ticket. These include Okemo and
Stratton in Vermont, Wachusett and Jiminy Peak in Massachusetts,
Ski Windham and Holiday Valley in New York, Ski Liberty and Ski
Roundtop in Pennsylvania, Snowshoe in West Virginia, and Tremblant
and Mt. Ste. Marie in Quebec.
</P>
<P>
   _ New York's Hunter Mountain ``Bring a Beginner'' program is a
bit different. Skiers and snowboarders who bring a friend who
purchases a $45 learn-to-ski/ride package will receive a half-price
lift ticket valid Monday through Friday, nonholidays. (A beginner
lesson and lift package is $28 without equipment rental.) For more
details, call Hunter at (518) 263-4223 or go on line
(www.HunterMtn.com).
</P>
<P>
   _ Ski New Hampshire will reward skiers and snowboarders who
introduce a friend to snow sports with a free lift ticket for
downhill skiing, or a free trail pass for cross-country skiing from
Feb. 22 to the end of the season. Reservations are advised for this
``Take a Friend'' program, which has been adopted by most of New
Hampshire's ski areas. Never-evers must be at least 13 years old.
For details on Ski New Hampshire's program, call (800) 88S-KINH, or
the member areas directly. On-line surfers should visit
www.skinh.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ The American Skiing Co.'s nine resorts _ which stretch from
Maine to California and include Killington and Mount Snow in
Vermont _ offer a free day on the slopes to anyone who brings a
friend who enrolls in the Learn to Ski or Learn to Ride program.
For details, call (800) 245-SNOW for Mount Snow, (800) 621-MTNS for
Killington or go to www.peaks.com for a complete list of resorts.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Recruit a Rookie'' is a program designed to introduce
teen-agers and young adults to skiing and riding, but to use
www.snowblast.com for the details and voucher. The web site, which
targets this age group both in design and content, also lists the
Levi's Sno-Core concerts which stop at many resorts around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
