<SLUG> BC-NY-PRISON-BEATING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRISON GUARD ACCUSED IN BEATING CLAIMS NO MEMORY OF INMATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A Nassau County, N.Y., jail guard accused of beating
a retarded inmate with a frying pan or a pot in 1993 testified
Wednesday in the former prisoner's civil lawsuit that he had no
memory of either the man or the night of the attack.
</P>
<P>
   But the prosecutor who investigated the case at the time
testified that the inmate's identification of the guard, Salvatore
Gemelli, as the man who savagely assaulted him, was ``as strong an
ID as you get in a criminal case.''
</P>
<P>
   The former inmate, Thomas Donovan Jr., 39, is suing Gemelli,
Nassau County and its jail in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn on
civil rights charges, and is seeking $100 million in damages.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is proceeding amid a widening federal investigation
into possible civil rights violations at the Long Island jail,
where, many current and former inmates say, beatings are an
everyday occurrence. The inquiry began after the Jan. 13 death of
Thomas Pizzuto, 38, whose family says he was beaten by guards and
then left untreated for days. His death, which was ruled a
homicide, is being investigated by the U.S. attorney's office in
Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Gemelli, a vice president of the correction officers' union,
remained calm through several hours of questioning Wednesday, even
when peppered with accusations by Donovan's lawyer, Stephen
Civardi. After Civardi established from jail records that Gemelli,
who handled Donovan's admission into the jail, had taken an
unusually long time to do so, Gemelli said the length of time
necessary depends on a number of factors. ``It also depends on
whether you're busy beating somebody between bookings, doesn't
it?'' Civardi asked. Judge Allyne Ross ruled that Gemelli did not
have to answer the question.
</P>
<P>
   Gemelli testified that he interviewed arriving inmates in his
own way, deviating from approved scripts used to screen possible
suicides, for example. When he was supposed to ask if an inmate was
in treatment with a psychologist or psychiatrist, he said, ``I'd
ask, `Do you think you're nuts?'''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Civardi closed his interrogation by asking Gemelli: ``Is
there anything Donovan could have done to justify the beating he
received at the Nassau County jail?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Gemelli responded. `` Donovan should never have gotten
beaten.''
</P>
<P>
   The other key witness Wednesday was Paul Delle, a former
prosecutor in the Nassau County district attorney's office who
initially handled the investigation of Donovan's allegation against
Gemelli. He told jurors that Donovan's ``horrific'' injuries
``appeared to be inflicted with tremendous force.'' He added: ``I'd
never seen injuries like this in my history as a prosecutor.''
</P>
<P>
   Cross-examined by Gemelli's lawyer, Chris Termini, Delle
conceded that the district attorney's office had declined to
prosecute Gemelli. ``So far,'' Delle added.
</P>
<P>
   In a setback for Donovan, Delle, who is now in private practice,
said Donovan had originally been arrested on sex-crime charges.
Jurors up to that time had not been told why he was in jail.
Donovan eventually pleaded guilty to a misdemeanor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
