<HEADLINE>
GREGORY ANDREWS, 47, COMPANY PRESIDENT
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Ga.)  (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gregory J. Andrews, the president and chief executive of Carson
Inc., which makes hair and beauty products for African-Americans,
died on Sunday in Johannesburg, South Africa, during a business
trip. Andrews, a resident of Savannah, Ga., was 47.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of death has not been determined, said Leonea Andrews,
his mother.
</P>
<P>
   Before joining Carson in July, Andrews worked for several health
care and consumer products companies.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Andrews was named marketing director for
Colgate-Palmolive Puerto Rico. He was promoted to general manager,
the top position at the subsidiary, in 1994, and in 1997, he was
named general manager of Colgate-Palmolive Argentina in Buenos
Aires.
</P>
<P>
   Andrews graduated from the University of Connecticut with a
bachelor's degree in industrial management in 1974, and he received
an MBA from the University of Wisconsin in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his mother, who lives in Washington Parish, La.,
Andrews is survived by a daughter, Azania, of Palo Alto, Calif.,
and two sons, Jovar, of New York, and Gregory Jr., of Miami. He and
his wife, Denise, of Miami, were divorced in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
