A8509 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-PIRRO-NYT &LR;      02-24 0381
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PIRRO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE PIRRO QUANDARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Feb. 25:
</P>
<P>
   The indictment of an influential Republican lobbyist,
fund-raiser and friend of Gov. George Pataki would by itself be
news. But because the man indicted, Albert Pirro, is married to
Jeanine F. Pirro, the Westchester County district attorney and a
rising star in New York politics, it delivers a doubly significant
jolt. Ms. Pirro will probably have to forgo whatever plans she had
to run for the Senate or other higher office until her husband's
legal problems are resolved. Since the indictment alleges fraud on
tax returns, some of which were signed by Ms. Pirro, she may have
to provide a fuller explanation of her own claims of ignorance of
any improprieties.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Pirro is a talented and telegenic prosecutor. In this era of
working couples, moreover, voters are often ready to distinguish
between the performance of someone in public life and that of a
spouse. Ms. Pirro's office says she was not involved in, or
knowledgeable about, her husband's business activities. But the
66-count federal indictment alleges many improper deductions for
home furnishings, baby sitters, vehicles, vacations and other items
shared by and Ms. Pirro. Her apparent lack of curiosity about the
family's finances is a legitimate subject that she needs to address
further.
</P>
<P>
   Pirro is, of course, entitled to a presumption of innocence. But
it was offensive and inappropriate for Ms. Pirro to attack the U.S.
attorney's office for conducting an ``invasive and hostile''
prosecution of her husband. As a prosecutor, she should not have
criticized the integrity of another prosecutorial office that she
is supposed to cooperate with in criminal investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Ms. Pirro has a bright future in politics, as many
experts felt until this week, will be determined by the outcome of
the case against her husband and her role in his activities. Her
supporters had been promoting her as a possible candidate for
Senate, and some of allies of New York City's mayor, Rudolph
Giuliani, believe Pataki was pushing her to run for Senate to block
the mayor's own ambitions. Any such plans are probably stalled, at
least for now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-02-24-99 2337EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
