<DATE_TIME> 1999-02-24 23:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8513 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXCLUSIVE-YANKS-NETS-     02-24 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXCLUSIVE-YANKS-NETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS AND NETS TO MERGE BUSINESS OPERATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Yankees and the New Jersey Nets are
expected to announce a joint ownership agreement Thursday that
would merge their business operations _ including television
rights, marketing, sponsorships and advertising _ and unite two
disparate ownership groups, four persons with knowledge of the
talks, including a league executive, said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The teams are expected to establish a 50-50 ownership
arrangement, in which they will exchange some stock and the Nets
will pay some cash. What is still unclear is whether the current
Yankees and Nets executives would maintain separate day-to-day
control of the two teams' on-the-field moves.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees-Nets merger will bring together tough, blustery
George Steinbrenner, the majority owner of the Yankees since 1973,
and the Nets' owners, whose lead investors, Raymond Chambers and
Lewis Katz, have pledged 38 percent of the team's profits to help
revitalize New Jersey's inner cities.
</P>
<P>
   While the storied Yankee franchise has won two World Series in
the past three years, the Nets have been something of a hapless,
even cursed, team. They have not won a league championship since
1976, when they belonged to the American Basketball Association. In
fact, before being merged into the National Basketball Association,
the Nets sold Julius Erving, their nonpareil star, to the
Philadelphia 76ers, in order to afford to join the league. As such,
the Nets will benefit enormously by being connected to the Yankees,
especially in the area of joint TV and sponsorship negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the greatest potential in combining the Yankees and Nets
is the impact on upcoming cable TV negotiations. The Yankees are
entering the 11th year of a 12-year, $486 million contract with
MSG, while the Nets' contract with another Cablevision Systems
entity, Fox Sports New York, concludes after the 2001-02 season.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees already present a formidable presence in TV
negotiations, but having the Nets as their partner could create
unprecedented leverage in renewal talks with Cablevision. On one
level, both teams are important to Cablevision's local sports
strategy, which features carrying the Yankees, Knicks, Rangers,
Nets, Mets, Islanders, and Devils on MSG and FSNY.
</P>
<P>
   But by forging a united front, the Yankees-Nets entity would
hold out the possibility that it could launch its own local sports
channel to compete with Cablevision's. A new local cable sports
channel requires at least two teams as anchor programming whose
respective seasons span a 12-month calendar.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees alone were responsible for huge subscriber and
advertiser growth for MSG when they moved there in 1989 from
SportsChannel New York. A two-team combination could create its own
channel by negotiating directly with cable systems, or it could
make a deal with such companies as Time Warner or ESPN, a unit of
the Walt Disney Co., which has sought opportunities to add local
sports channels to its national sports services.
</P>
<P>
   ``The TV play is where the upside is,'' said Marc Ganis,
president of SportsCorp. Ltd., a sports consulting firm in Chicago.
``And maybe there could be some more at some point with a public
offering.''
</P>
<P>
   Ganis noted that Steinbrenner's skills as a hard-nosed
negotiator for sponsorships for the Yankees _ including one for $95
million with Adidas that provoked a federal lawsuit from Major
League Baseball _ can only help the Nets.
</P>
<P>
   The merging of the Nets and Yankees also ends speculation that
the Yankees would be acquired by Cablevision. The two sides had
negotiated for more than a year to conclude a deal that might have
cost Cablevision at least $500 million, but talks collapsed late
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Outside of the business factors, one reason that the Nets have
apparently decided to merge with the Yankees is to broaden their
charitable platform to New York City, including the South Bronx
neighborhood where Yankee Stadium is located. The Nets' focus is
now on the New Jersey cities of Newark, Paterson, Jersey City,
Trenton and Camden.
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen as to whether the Yankees-Nets combination
will affect where the two teams will play. The Nets want to move
from the Meadowlands Sports Complex in East Rutherford, N.J., and
build their own arena in Newark as part of their emphasis on
community involvement.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees continue to wait to decide about staying at Yankee
Stadium in a new or renovated stadium, move to a proposed ballpark
over railyards on the West Side of Manhattan, or jump the Hudson
River for New Jersey. Gov. Christie Whitman has said the state will
not use public money to lure the Yankees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
