<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-BLAZERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS FALL APART IN FOURTH, LOSE TO BLAZERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ In a disturbing yet familiar sight, the
Nets collapsed in the fourth quarter of Wednesday night's game
against Portland, enabling the Trail Blazers to leave Continental
Arena with a 94-85 victory.
</P>
<P>
   After leading for most of the first three quarters, New Jersey
was outscored by 30-18 in the final period. After Eric Murdock
scored the opening basket of the quarter, Portland went on a 26-8
run to win its fifth straight game and improve to 7-2.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Williams led the charge, scoring 9 of his season-high 22
points during the critical spurt. Rasheed Wallace scored 7 of his 9
points during the late run.
</P>
<P>
   The loss was the Nets' fifth straight, dropped them to 2-9 and
spoiled a bright performance by Murdock, who started in place of
the injured Sam Cassell. In his best game of the season by far,
Murdock had 23 points and 6 assists.
</P>
<P>
   Jayson Williams rebounded from a horrible performance against
the Knicks' Patrick Ewing on Tuesday, recording 15 points and 15
rebounds. And Kendall Gill (16 points), Keith Van Horn (15) and
Kerry Kittles (12) scored in double figures.
</P>
<P>
   In the crushing loss in New York, the Nets defended well and
shot 29 percent from the floor; Wednesday, they played a nice
offensive game but crumbled down the stretch defensively.
</P>
<P>
   Cassell was not in uniform after playing 33 minutes against the
Knicks. It was the second time the Nets' starting point guard had
exhausted his sprained right ankle in one game, only to sit out the
next. If the pattern continues, Cassell's injury will hamper him
throughout the season. Coach John Calipari admitted that it might
be time to rest him for a while so his ankle heals completely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to make that decision right now,'' Calipari said.
``The only problem is that if we sit him out a couple of weeks,
you're talking 10 games. Then you wonder if you're just better off
trying to play him 20 minutes a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Murdock got the club going immediately. In an about-face from
Tuesday's debacle, the Nets' shooters caught fire in the first
half. New Jersey made 64 percent of its shots to take a 32-22 lead
after the first quarter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
