<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PIRRO-BOYLE-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIRRO'S INDICTMENT BRINGS ATTENTION TO PATAKI ASSOCIATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The bright spotlight created by the federal
indictment handed up Tuesday against Albert J. Pirro Jr., the
powerful real estate developer and lobbyist, also turned attention
to Robert E. Boyle, the executive director of the Port Authority of
New York and New Jersey and a longtime friend of Gov. George E.
Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   Boyle rose to prominence in a tight network of Westchester
County political and business figures with connections to the
Hudson Valley Hospital Center in Peekskill, which he served as
chairman. That circle includes Pirro, the husband of District
Attorney Jeanine F. Pirro, and the governor.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment says that in 1991, the chairman of the hospital _
it was Boyle, though he is not named in the document _ ``brought to
Albert J. Pirro Jr.'s attention the availability of a commercial
office building for sale in Croton, New York.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the indictment, days after the hospital corporation
agreed to lease space in the Croton building, a corporation owned
largely by Pirro entered a contract to buy the building. Two months
later, the indictment says, about the same time as the building's
purchase was closed, Boyle acquired 45 percent of the corporation
that had bought the building.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment said that Boyle failed to tell the hospital's
board of his personal financial interest in the complex real estate
deal, ``in violation of his fiduciary duties.'' It also says that
Pirro's companies paid Boyle or companies owned by him $292,299,
and did not disclose those payments to the board.
</P>
<P>
   Boyle is not charged in the indictment. He would not talk with
reporters about the allegations, but he released a statement saying
that, contrary to the indictment, he ``had no equity interest'' in
the real estate deal between the hospital and Pirro. ``I believe my
conduct has been appropriate at all times,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Levander, Boyle's lawyer, said some of the payments
made by Pirro's companies to Boyle were for a separate real estate
transaction, but he would not say what piece of property was
involved. He also would not say what the rest of the money was for,
or whether the hospital board was aware of Boyle's business
relationship with Pirro.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital's board at the time included Pataki, then a state
assemblyman, and others, like Boyle, who would later serve in the
Pataki administration. Calls to several people who were members of
the hospital board at that time were not returned Wednesday. Aides
to Pataki said the real estate deal involving Boyle that the
indictment describes never went before the hospital board for a
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Boyle, a former concrete company owner and real estate
developer, has been close to Pataki since the early 1980s. Boyle
was his campaign treasurer in his races for State Senate in 1992
and for governor in 1994. He was also treasurer of the governor's
1994-95 inaugural and transition committees, which have been
criticized for concealing information about their finances. Boyle
and his companies have donated at least $5,850 to Pataki's
campaigns since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki served with Boyle on the hospital board from 1986 to
1992. In 1991, Boyle made a personal loan of $10,000 to Pataki. The
same year, Pataki borrowed $60,000 from Paul Guillaro, a real
estate developer who was a sometime partner of Boyle.
</P>
<P>
   Zenia Mucha, Pataki's communications director, refused to
discuss Boyle or his relationship with the governor.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Hudson Valley hospital was, apparently, a tangle of
relationships. On one development project, hospital contracts went
to building companies, an architecture firm and a law firm that
were owned or partly owned by board members. When Pataki and his
future counsel as governor, Michael Finnegan, were lawyers in
private practice in Peekskill, both their firms represented Boyle
in real estate deals, and Finnegan later served on the hospital
board.
</P>
<P>
   Boyle is widely credited with greatly improving the financial
condition of the Hudson Valley hospital. He still sits on its
board, but is no longer chairman.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Pataki entrusted Boyle with the job of cleaning up the
Jacob K. Javits Convention Center in Manhattan, making him chief
executive of the center, which had been plagued by high costs and
mob ties. By most accounts, Boyle did very well there.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the governor appointed him executive director of the
Port Authority of New York and New Jersey. The same year, Pataki
named Boyle to the board of the Westchester County Medical Center,
which has had business ties to Pirro.
</P>
</TEXT>
