<SLUG> BC-BKC-CLIPNOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POND WILL BE FILLED FOR L.A. `SHOWDOWN'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Like two ships that crash in the night, the Los
Angeles Clippers and Los Angeles Lakers will meet at the Pond in
Anaheim tonight.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers, who have gone from first place last season to
``Melrose Place'' this season, have lost three road games in a row.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers have not recorded a victory in 331 days; their last
triumph was an 83-77 decision over Sacramento on April 18, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   For tonight's, ahem, showdown _ which is to rivalries as Hyundai
is to Rolls-Royce _ a capacity crowd is expected in Anaheim, where
fans will take their last look at the Lakers before they come down
with a case of Dennis Rodman.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers simply would like to take one last look before
terminating their losing streak at nine games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to go out and try to improve,'' said first-year
Clippers coach Chris Ford, the day after Tuesday's frustrating
94-89 loss to Golden State. ``We can't miss foul shots at the end
of games. We can't keep making the same defensive mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   In losing to the Warriors, the Clippers managed to commit the
same unwitting acts of treason Ford mentioned while giving up a
four-point lead with less than three minutes to play.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Lamond Murray scored a season-high 30 points and
collected eight rebounds in loss No. 9, and sidekick Maurice Taylor
added 23 and 11, respectively. But Ford would like to see Taylor's
board performance become more the standard than the exception. The
second-year power forward pulled down 20 rebounds in a
double-overtime loss to Vancouver last week in Anaheim, then
grabbed only four in each of the next two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mo has to continue to rebound,'' Ford said. ``He should be a
double-figure rebounder every game.''
</P>
<P>
   __ More power to them: Rookie Brian Skinner, who had the lateral
meniscus ligament in his left knee repaired three weeks ago,
scrimmaged with the team during Wednesday's workout at the Sports
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Skinner, a power forward from Baylor selected with the 22nd pick
in the 1998 NBA draft, is eligible to come off the injury list as
soon as his aerobic fitness matches his weight-room success.
</P>
<P>
   ``He still needs conditioning,'' Ford said. ``And, judging from
the scrimmage, he forgot most of the plays.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Talking a good game: Veteran guard Scott Brooks, who was
waived by the Clippers last Friday, will join rising play-by-play
star Michael Smith on tonight's and Friday's radio broadcasts on
1150-AM.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks played for six NBA teams in his 10-year career. He became
available for radio thanks, in part, to a knee injury suffered
during an exhibition game against the Lakers last month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
