<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAMMYS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAURYN HILL WALKS AWAY AS BIG WINNER AT GRAMMYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Updates, rewrites throughout)  (rk) 
 By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Though Grammy voters are well-known for their
erratic, unpredictable and often outlandish choices, there were no
surprises at this year's awards ceremony at the Shrine Auditorium.
The top popular music categories were overwhelmed by female
winners, including Celine Dion, Shania Twain, the Dixie Chicks,
Alanis Morissette, Madonna, Sheryl Crow and especially Lauryn Hill,
who gathered five Grammys, including best new artist and the
prestigious album of the year award.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hill, the member of the rap group the Fugees, who released
her first solo album to rave reviews and millions of sales last
year, even beat herself. In the best rhythm-and-blues song and the
best female rhythm-and-blues vocal performance categories, her own
song telling women to respect themselves, ``Doo Wop (That Thing),''
won Grammys at the expense of Aretha Franklin's ``A Rose Is a
Rose,'' which was written by Ms. Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was excited about Lauryn Hill the day I heard that record,''
said Michael Greene, the president of the National Academy of
Recording Arts and Sciences, which presents the Grammys, in an
interview before the show. ``I sweated bullets because I wondered
if the academy membership would get it. But they got it. They got
it big time.'' Ms. Hill received 10 Grammy nominations, more than
any other artist this year.
</P>
<P>
   Though some have called this year's Grammy celebration the year
of the woman, the awards show could also be called Madonna's
revenge. Despite a decade and a half of recording, she had only
previously received one award, for best long-form video in 1991.
Now, in her latest guise as a raven-haired spiritualist, Madonna,
who opened the show with a Japanese-flavored performance of
``Nothing Really Matters,'' has three more Grammys to her name:
best pop album, best short-form video and best dance recording.
</P>
<P>
   Among other women dominating this year's Grammys were the Dixie
Chicks, a new trio who pulled an upset by winning the best country
album award over Shania Twain as well as best country vocal
performance by a duo or group.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know what to expect with these things,'' Ms. Twain,
who has won two other awards so far, responded with wounded pride
backstage when asked about losing to the Dixie Chicks. ``I'm the
biggest seller.''
</P>
<P>
   The rapper Jay-Z learned Wednesday night that snubbing the
Grammys doesn't lose a musician any points. The gangsta rapper had
announced that he was boycotting the Grammys for overlooking
rappers and asked that his name be withdrawn from the running. He
was specifically upset with Grammy voters for not nominating his
fellow rapper DMX for best new artist and at the music industry in
general for paying more attention to violence in rap than his
forthcoming tour.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, his ``Vol. II ... Hard Knock Life,'' won the award
for best rap album. True to his word, Jay-Z was not here to accept
the award.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In a year of major changes for the music business, particularly
the sale of Polygram to Seagram and the industry's resistance the
distribution of music via the Internet, Sheryl Crow was the first
award-winner to acknowledge the upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   During her speech for best rock album (for ``The Globe
Sessions'') she delivered a eulogy for her record label, A&AMP;M, which
was shut down by Seagram, and the executives who lost their jobs
there.
</P>
<P>
   Past winners of top awards remained favorites this year,
particularly Celine Dion, who won the album of the year award in
1996. Her ``My Heart Will Go On,'' from the seemingly unsinkable
``Titanic'' soundtrack, won one of the top awards, Song of the
Year, which was presented to the songwriters James Horner and Will
Jennings. ``You all need to write me something, man,'' rapper and
actor Will Smith told them when presenting the award.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Heart Will Go On'' also won an award for best female pop
vocal performance. Eric Clapton, the big winner in 1993, won best
male pop vocal performance for ``My Father's Eyes'' and Alanis
Morissette, who swept up in 1996, won best rock song for
``Uninvited.'' However, one Grammy favorite, Tony Bennett, lost
this year: to Elmo of Sesame Street for best children's musical
album.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, previously neglected artists received long
overdue Grammys. In her acceptance speech for best traditional pop
vocal performance for her live at Carnegie Hall album, Patti Page
said that when her grandchildren asked what name to call her, ``I
said Grammy because I'll never get one. Now they have to call me
granny.''
</P>
<P>
   Prior to this ceremony, Ms. Page, whose career predates the
Grammys by 10 years, had never been nominated before. And Shirley
Horn, after six previous nominations, won her first Grammy for best
jazz vocal performance for ``I Remember Miles.''
</P>
<P>
   Grammy critics who've complained after watching Elvis Costello
get snubbed year after year were temporarily quelled. Costello
finally won a Grammy by collaborating with a four-time winner, Burt
Bacharach, on an album, a song from which (``I Still Have That
Other Girl'') won best pop vocal collaboration.
</P>
<P>
   Backstage, Costello said that he hadn't given much credence to
the Grammy Award in the past, but maybe now he will. And Lou Reed,
another Grammy oversight, won his first one for best long-form
music video for ``American Masters: Rock-and-Roll Heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Over half a century since its heyday, swing is officially pop
music again. The Brian Setzer Orchestra, led by the former member
of the rockabilly revivalists the Stray Cats, won best pop
instrumental performance for ``Sleepwalk'' and best pop vocal
performance by a duo or group for ``Jump Jive an' Wail.''
</P>
<P>
   On and off stage, the Grammys provided further evidence of the
invasion of pocket electronics into the theater and concert world.
Not only did cell phones ring intermittently during the
performance, but in order to keep from forgetting anyone in his
list of thank yous, Herbie Hancock pulled out an electronic
organizer during his acceptance speech for best jazz instrumental
performance for ``Gershwin's World,'' an album that actually has
vocals.
</P>
<P>
   In the classical field, the conductor Pierre Boulez won, adding
to his 20 awards, for best opera recording (``Bluebeard's
Castle''), and best orchestral performance (``Mahler: Symphony No.
9''). And in a new category added this year, best classical
crossover album, an old Grammy hand, 12-time winner Yo-Yo Ma, won
with the conductor Jorge Calandrelli for their album of Astor
Piazzolla compositions, ``Soul of the Tango.''
</P>
<P>
   Recordings released between Oct. 1, 1997, and Sept. 30, 1998,
were eligible for an award. The winners were selected by the 10,000
voting members _ from musicians to producers to industry executives
to liner note writers _ of the recording academy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
