<HEADER>
A8532 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-ANDERSEN-HNS &LR;      02-24 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSEN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARLSBAD, Calif. _ There were a few surprises in Southern
California on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Several marquee golfers _ five of the top seven in the world, to
be exact _ won't be playing in today's second round of the Andersen
Consulting Match Play Championship at the La Costa Resort.
</P>
<P>
   Mark O'Meara, Ernie Els, Davis Love III, Colin Montgomerie and
Lee Westwood lost on the opening day, but they did walk away with
$25,000 for their one day of work.
</P>
<P>
   The winners, from Tiger Woods and David Duval to Fred Couples
and Nick Price, came as no surprise.
</P>
<P>
   But there were upsets. And if nothing else, first-round results
in the $5 million match-play event proved that this really isn't
tennis and that the gap between Nos. 1 and 64 is perhaps even
narrower than the players thought. And they were convinced it was
no more than a sliver even before Wednesday's action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when you put the No. 64 next to a player and compare
it to a No. 1 next to another player, it kind of visually creates a
wider gap than there actually is,'' said Duval, who is No. 2 but
nudged No. 63 Stephen Leaney 2 and 1 to advance. ``A perfect
illustration is my match. I was 5 or 6 under par. And I still had a
tough match.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this type of format, you only have to beat six people to
win the golf tournament. But at the same time, you can very easily
get ousted.''
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Els, who was only three days removed from winning the
Nissan Open in Los Angeles. His match with Paul Azinger was one of
the few on the first day that made it to No. 18. Els responded with
a bogey when his drive missed the fairway, and he never recovered,
missing a 15-foot par putt from the back fringe and losing 1-down
to Azinger, who admitted he didn't exactly play a terrific round of
golf but caught Els on a bad day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither one of us played that great,'' Azinger said. ``Ernie's
probably suffering from some post-victory letdown. He wasn't that
sharp. Both of us were pretty sloppy. And even though I might not
have performed that great, it feels good to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Which, as the No. 1-ranked Woods said, is the beauty of match
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an ebb and flow,'' he said. ``When a guy looks like he
has momentum, you have to take it away from him.''
</P>
<P>
   And there was a lot of ebbing and flowing at La Costa on the
first day of the first event in the World Golf Championship series.
</P>
<P>
   First, fans had to get used to hearing those five traditionally
unsaid words on the PGA Tour _ ``Pick it up; it's good.'' But it
wasn't long before they realized they weren't at a Ryder Cup,
because there actually were some Americans winning matches.
</P>
<P>
   Woods led the charge as he cruised to a 4-and-3 win over Nick
Faldo, never trailing in the match. Woods was asked whether he had
any compassion for Faldo, who has been struggling with every aspect
of his game for the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``No'' was Woods' short answer. He had no intention of letting a
beleaguered opponent off the mat.
</P>
<P>
   The most impressive upset of the day probably belonged to Craig
Stadler, who knocked out Montgomerie 5 and 3, building a 4-up lead
after seven holes and never looking back. But Montgomerie, who
admitted he simply wasn't playing his best golf or anything close
to it, was fighting more than just Stadler, as it turned out.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie is one of golf's best players but also comes across
as a stern, gruff individual on the course. The smallish gallery
did not take to Montgomerie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monty didn't play that well,'' Stadler said. ``But there were
a couple times when the fans played a part.
</P>
<P>
   ``On No. 13, he missed a short putt, about six feet. And some
guy started clapping up in the stands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then, on the 15th, a guy yelled something like, `You got one
shot left,' which was not real sporting. In fact, I probably gave
him a longer, deeper glare than Monty did.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, Stadler did his part to keep Montgomerie in a
grouchy mood, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got a little perturbed on No. 13 when I didn't give him a
putt,'' Stadler said. ``I was 5-up with six holes to play. I had
about an eight-footer, and he had a six-footer. I missed mine high,
about six inches. He gave it to me. He rolled his by about 3{,
almost four feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing you want to do is give it to him and then he
birdies the last five holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no love lost in match play.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Montgomerie: ``He deserved to win. And he would have beaten
most people the way he played.''
</P>
<P>
   Stadler's romp helped give the foreign players a losing record
on day one of the match play. Non-Americans were 11-13 on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   But Americans weren't immune to problems. O'Meara fell three
holes behind after just six holes. He ended up losing 4 and 2 to
Michael Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I countered every time he did something,'' Bradley said.
``Mark O'Meara was not Mark O'Meara today. He wasn't the Mark
O'Meara everyone knows.''
</P>
<P>
   There were a lot of higher-seeded players who weren't
themselves. Of the 32 matches, 18 were won by the lower-seeded
player. The third, fourth, fifth, sixth and seventh seeds all were
losers.
</P>
<P>
   Said O'Meara, at No. 3 the highest-ranked player to lose: ``He
(Bradley) made no mistakes, and that's the key to match play.
Anyone _ any one of these guys _ can beat the other guy. That's
just the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   And most of the losers headed home feeling roughly the same way
as Rocco Mediate, who was pummeled 5 and 3 by Vijay Singh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got my butt kicked,'' Mediate said. ``That's about the size
of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
